<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUTHIER ASSUMES GM SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The National Hockey League's most dsyfunctional front
office family aired its latest, and hopefully last, load of dirty
laundry on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New Mighty Ducks president Pierre Gauthier announced he will
assume the duties of general manager, replacing his former boss
Jack Ferreira, who has been offered the position of vice-president
of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year, since Ron (Wilson) left there has been a lot
of ups and downs, a lot of question marks ... I don't like to use
the word turmoil, but a lot of indecision,'' said Gauthier of a
period during which the Ducks have fired two coaches (Wilson,
Pierre Page), hired another (Craig Hartsburg) and brought aboard
the team's former assistant GM (Gauthier) as president, replacing
Tony Tavares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe this is the way to end all this,'' said
Gauthier. ``Now (we) make things very clear, within the
organization and for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a slow, painful restructuring of the Anaheim front
office this summer since the Ducks completed a very disappointing
26-43-13 season one year after the team went to the second round of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, who worked 2 1/2 years under Ferreira after the Ducks
were formed in 1993 said ``I won't say anything negative about Jack
Ferreira, I have too much respect for him,'' but he also made it
clear it was time for a change and the centralization of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people in the league who are president and
(general) managers,'' he said. ``And in a way it says that there is
one philosophy, one direction, one person in charge. Things become
very clear for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get the right leadership and philosophy of what you
want to do, it filters down to the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira and Disney have been criticized for their lack of
action on the free agent front this summer, but Gauthier admitted
he's not likely to make any major roster changes either. Gauthier
wants to take a good look at the Ducks' young talent in training
camp. He doesn't feel free agency is a cure all, and said that
Disney is not a penny-pinching organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of different ways to improve a club
without spending a lot of stupid money on retirement contracts (to
free agents 32-35 years old),'' said Gauthier, who built the Ottawa
Senators into a playoff team via the draft. ``Money isn't issue,
it's how you spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira was fired by the expansion San Jose Sharks in 1992 was
not available for comment. But Gauthier said he will give the
former GM plenty of time to decide if he wants a position that will
involve player evaluation, and serving as a sounding board for
Gauthier on player personal decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, who said he ``did not plan to let go of one of my best
friends'' when he was hired on July 16, insisted it wasn't any real
sense of dissatisfaction with Ferreira that resulted in the
decision to take over the GM duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't because he didn't do this or should have done
this,'' Gauthier explained. ``It's more the total picture,
clarifying roles and in a way turning the page. Expansion teams are
tough, you build slowly, then expectations grow ... it's obvious
what everybody wants. We've got to take a step up, we've got to get
to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
