</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-PREGNANCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SEX, HONOR AND GRADE-POINT AVERAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Somer Chipman and Chasity Glass have achieved the kind of
academic success in high school that is often a passport to
membership in the National Honor Society. Yet neither of these
17-year-olds made the cut at Grant County High in Williamstown, Ky.
Both are teen-age mothers, apparently a disqualifying factor for
the selection panel. Its decision was misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Grant County school system has been circumspect
about the precise reasons for the exclusion. But fragmentary
remarks on the public record suggest the admissions panel decided
that sexually active teen-agers cannot be role models. By that
standard one wonders what tests the committee would devise in the
future to verify which candidates for induction into the honor
society had perfect records of abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   What the panel and the school system should do is abide by the
requirements of Title IX, which bans schools that receive federal
funds from engaging in any form of sex discrimination. One of Title
IX's regulations specifically prohibits discrimination against a
student who is pregnant or a teen-age parent, married or not.
</P>
<P>
   Since its enactment in 1972, Title IX has been primarily used as
a wedge to address the imbalance in money and other resources for
high school and college athletics for women. With a lawsuit that
was filed by the American Civil Liberties Union on Thursday, these
two young women seek to test the federal courts' willingness to
enforce a ban on discriminating against students who are pregnant
or mothers. To date, decisions by lower courts in similar cases
have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chipman's and Ms. Glass' achievements _ doing well in school
in spite of their parental responsibilities _ prove that an
unplanned pregnancy does not have to derail a student's academic
career and aspirations. Any honor society chapter should be proud
to count them as members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
