<HEADLINE>
GAUTHIER ASSUMES DUCKS GM POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The National Hockey League's most dysfunctional front
office aired its latest load of dirty laundry on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New Mighty Ducks president Pierre Gauthier announced he will
assume the duties of general manager, replacing former boss Jack
Ferreira, who has been offered the position of vice president of
hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year, since Ron (Wilson) left, there has been a
lot of ups and downs, a lot of question marks.... I don't like to
use the word turmoil, but a lot of indecision,'' said Gauthier of a
period during which the Ducks have fired two coaches (Wilson,
Pierre Page), hired another (Craig Hartsburg) and made Gauthier
president, replacing Tony Tavares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe this is the way to end all this,'' said
Gauthier. ``Now (we) make things very clear, within the
organization and for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a slow, painful restructuring of the Anaheim front
office this summer since the Ducks completed a disappointing
26-43-13 season, one year after reaching the second round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, who worked 2{ years under Ferreira after the Ducks
were formed in 1993, said, ``I won't say anything negative about
Jack Ferreira, I have too much respect for him.'' But he also made
it clear it was time for a change and the centralization of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people in the league who are president and
(general) managers,'' he said. ``And in a way, it says that there
is one philosophy, one direction, one person in charge. Things
become very clear for the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira and The Walt Disney Co., the Ducks' parent corporation,
have been criticized for their lack of action on the free-agent
front this summer, but Gauthier admitted he's not likely to make
any major roster changes, either. Gauthier wants to take a good
look at the Ducks' young talent in training camp. He doesn't
believe free agency is a cure-all, and said that Disney is not a
penny-pinching organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
