<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SHAYS-MEEHAN-NYT     08-07 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SHAYS-MEEHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A VICTORY FOR SHAYS-MEEHAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   When the votes were in, the Shays-Meehan campaign finance reform
bill sailed through the House with numbers so overwhelming as to
belie how hard the battle had been. In the end, 61 Republicans,
more than a quarter of the party's members in the House, joined
with most Democrats to pass the bill, 252-179. Yes, it now faces a
daunting challenge in the Senate. We will have more to say on that
in due course. Now, however, it seems appropriate to pay tribute to
the bill's supporters in the House, and to draw lessons from their
extraordinary perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public revulsion over the fund-raising abuses in the
1996 election, House leaders on both sides of the aisle were
anything but enthusiastic about cleaning up the campaign
fund-raising system last year. But two independent-minded New
Englanders demanded that their fellow lawmakers do more than
deplore the excesses for partisan advantage. Reps. Christopher
Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., challenged the
ingrained habits of colleagues and the conventional wisdom of
Washington's chattering class. Their task was generally deemed
hopeless when campaign reform was killed in the Senate in February.
</P>
<P>
   To their great credit, Dick Gephardt, David Bonior and other
Democratic leaders embraced campaign reform shortly thereafter. But
their endorsement made Shays' job more complicated as Newt Gingrich
and GOP leaders tried to portray it as a partisan issue. Shays was
courageous in facing parliamentary trickery and threats of revenge
from the leaders of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments, too, when Shays and Meehan wondered about
each other's motives and promises. They tried to forge a bipartisan
coalition in a Congress riven with the most bitter partisan
resentments. But they stuck together and rebutted the devious
argument that a ban on unlimited ``soft money'' donations and other
curbs on fund raising were a violation of free speech. They shamed
their colleagues into not letting their bill get strangled by
wealthy special interests.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of campaign reform profited from the clumsiness of its
foes. Gingrich's broken promises, phony substitutes, killer
amendments and attempts to run out the clock all played into the
reformers' hands. But the most important lesson is an old one.
Standing up for principles can mobilize public opinion and change
the accepted rules of the game. We dwell on this not to gloat but
to point the way to the Senate, where Trent Lott and Mitch
McConnell have declared this legislation dead on arrival and where
Sens. John McCain and Russell Feingold, sponsors of the Senate
version of Shays-Meehan, now face their time of testing. It has a
familiar ring, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
