<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-KANELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANELL EXPECTS HEFTY RAISE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Danny Kanell said he is confident as he prepares
for the New York Giants' preseason opener Saturday against the
Cincinnati Bengals. The Giants will make a statement about their
confidence in Kanell next week when they plan to begin serious
negotiations that should yield Kanell a new, and far more
lucrative, contract.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell, who is in the last year of a three-year contract that
will pay him the league minimum of $216,000, has been expecting a
new deal since last season ended. Kanell was 7-2-1 as a starter,
helping the team to a division title and its first playoff
appearance since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been preliminary contract discussions, Giants
General Manager Ernie Accorsi will fly to California next week to
begin talks with Kanell's agent, Marvin Demoff. Accorsi will also
re-open talks next week with Ken Staninger, the agent for offensive
tackle Scott Gragg. Gragg can become an unrestricted free agent
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, like everybody else, I want to get a raise,''
Kanell, 24, said Thursday between practices at training camp. ``I'm
happy they're going to talk, but I just don't want it to become a
distraction to the team. I want to take care of it as soon as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi did not want to comment on the extent of the
negotiations or the contract terms that Kanell or Gragg are
seeking. But Kent Graham, who was signed this winter as Kanell's
backup, received a three-year deal worth $3.6 million. So Kanell
can expect a hefty raise, even if salary cap considerations require
that the contract be structured to deliver the bulk of Kanell's pay
in succeeding years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to be out on the field again,'' Kanell said of
Saturday night's game at Giants Stadium. ``The last time we were
out there, things didn't work out like we planned. Playing another
game, even a preseason game, will be a start to putting that
Minnesota game behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants lost a 9-point lead in the final 90 seconds of a
23-22 first-round playoff loss to the Minnesota Vikings last Dec.
27. It was one of Kanell's more productive games of the season, as
he completed 16 of 32 passes for 199 yards, including a touchdown
pass to tight end Aaron Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel said Kanell would not play much more than one
quarter of Saturday's game, but Kanell said he would use the
playing time wisely. ``Right from the start, it's important for us
to establish our offense,'' Kanell said. ``We did have a good
running game last year but the passing struggled sometimes. People
are going to be watching us _ to see if we've improved there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kanell replaced the embattled Dave Brown last year, he was
a fan favorite, something that happens to most backup quarterbacks.
But now Kanell is the starter and he knows expectations will be
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were happy to see me play last year. I hope
they're still happy to see me. I know that people won't be
satisfied with us just winning some games. We have to defend our
division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're looking forward to that,'' he said. ``I'm even
looking forward to being back in the action. It might almost be
good to wake up the morning after the game a little sore.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel said he found a newspaper picture depicting the
discolored grass at Giants Stadium disquieting. ``I'm looking
forward to playing on the grass, I've liked the idea all along,''
Fassel said. ``But if it's not a good track I won't be too happy
with it.'' Portions of the Giants Stadium grass have turned yellow
and brown in the aftermath of a concert at the stadium last
weekend. ... Fassel said he will hold safety Sam Garnes (sore
shoulder) and tight end Al Pupunu (sprained knee) out of Saturday's
game rather than risk aggravating their injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
