<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PAYDAYS BEFORE SUN SETS ON HOLMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Larry Holmes has a saying that traces back
to growing up in poverty with 11 siblings in Cuthbert, Ga.: The
shade of a toothpick is better than the boiling hot sun.
</P>
<P>
   So, the 48-year-old Holmes is not bitter when people say the
only reason he continues to fight is the pursuit of money. He is
unconcerned about his place in boxing history, and he even puts a
positive spin on almost anything that happens to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm dead, I'm dead,'' he said Thursday, waving off talk
of his ranking among heavyweight champions. ``I ain't going to
remember nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes will be 49 on Nov. 3, yet he is still in training. He has
a fight scheduled for Jan. 23 at an undetermined site against
George Foreman, who will turn 50 that day.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes' wife, Diane, is not fond of her husband's accepting
second billing to Foreman for the fight, even if Holmes is to get
$4 million. She complained that Foreman would get $10 million and
that the fight was being promoted as his birthday bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was on me pretty good,'' Holmes said Thursday, as he
waited to participate in a cigar company's promotion. ``She said:
`How come he's getting more than you? You were the champ longer
than he was the champ. And you're just as important.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Honey, that's not the point.'''
</P>
<P>
   The point, Holmes said, is he will pick up $4 million and, in
the process, hand Foreman a whipping.
</P>
<P>
   To those who regard this fight as farcical, Holmes says he does
not see anyone in the heavyweight division who impresses him much.
He was reminded that less than six years ago, he was able to go the
distance against Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of shape, and I lost a contact lens in the fight,''
he said. ``I had gone in with a detached retina and the contact
lens allowed me to see. Even with all that, I was able to go the
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes (66-6) held the heavyweight title from 1978 until
September 1985. His victims included Muhammad Ali and Leon Spinks,
and he made 20 straight title defenses, which is second to Joe
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes once cared that he was underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get very angry,'' he said. ``I used to say things
like Marciano couldn't carry my jockstrap, when they were comparing
me with him, saying I couldn't break his record. But I was young. I
didn't understand what I understand now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I am the greatest fighter of all time. To me. To
somebody else, Joe Louis was. To someone else, it was Jack Dempsey.
To someone else, it was Marciano or Ali. It goes on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes won his first 48 fights _ one short of Rocky Marciano's
record _ before losing a controversial decision to Michael Spinks
in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
