<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TNT-DEBUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TNT PREPARES A SMASHING DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the top three fighters on the six-bout card do
what they are supposed to do, then TNT's inaugural boxing show on
Sept. 22 at the Theater in Madison Square Garden will be dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   The card will feature three world-title bouts, headlined by
Shane Mosley, the International Boxing Federation lightweight
champion and arguably one of the top five fighters in the game.
Mosley (28-0), making his Madison Square Garden debut, faces
Eduardo Morales (26-0) of Argentina. Angel Manfredy (24-2-1) meets
John Brown (18-4) for the World Boxing Union superfeatherweight
title. And Shannon Briggs (30-2), the heavyweight from Brooklyn,
fights an opponent to be named later. Briggs gets a chance to
display what he has learned since he started working with the
trainer Emanuel Steward, who has worked with Evander Holyfield and
who is also training Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden is offering about 800 $18 tickets in the
5,200-seat arena. Ringside seats will cost $100.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin O'Malley, senior vice president of Turner Sports, said TNT
was not looking to step into the void that will be left after the
USA Network abandons its ``Tuesday Night Fights'' series. O'Malley
said the network is treating this as a special sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all indications are that Evander Holyfield's next
bout will be against Vaughn Bean, the IBF's No. 1 contender, on
Sept. 19 in Atlanta at the Georgia Dome. A deal was imminent as of
Thursday. Bean stepped into the picture because Henry Akinwande,
the World Boxing Association's No. 1 contender, still had not
sufficiently recovered from hepatitis last June.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Holyfield backed off his asking price of $10 million
so that the fight could take place in Atlanta. There is talk that
the Georgia Dome is coming up with a $3 million site fee for the
bout.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, Don King walked into U.S. District Court in
Manhattan for the hearing on the lawsuit against him filed by the
welterweight Felix Trinidad and saw a familiar face on the bench.
Judge Lawrence McKenna presided over King's recent trial on wire
fraud charges. The promoter was acquitted on nine counts of wire
fraud in that case, and the jury deadlocked on acquitting King's
company.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna was also the judge in the first trial on the same
charges in 1995. That trial ended in a mistrial. After hearing
arguments over whether King's contract with Trinidad is valid,
McKenna said he would make a ruling next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
