</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JIM-DANDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIMMEL IS HOPING PATIENCE PAYS OFF WITH SCATMANDU
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A year ago at Saratoga, John Kimmel
tied with the soon-to-be-Hall of Famer Bill Mott for the most
victories by a trainer at the six-week meeting. But this year, with
many of his top fillies retired, Kimmel will apparently be counting
on allowance horses and untested 2-year-olds to stay at the top of
the trainer standing.
</P>
<P>
   With one exception.
</P>
<P>
   The colt's name is Scatmandu, he is 3 years old, he cost a
record $1.1 million, and for a solid year, everyone, including
Kimmel, has been waiting for him to do something special, besides
act stupidly before each of his races.
</P>
<P>
   Scatmandu will get his first chance here Sunday in the $250,000
Jim Dandy, and his second, perhaps, in the $750,000 Travers on Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's as good as the best 3-year-olds out there, but
I think he did everything he could to comprise his chances in the
Dwyer,'' Kimmel said of the colt's performance July 12 at Belmont.
In that race, Scatmandu smashed his head against the starting gate
with such force that he wound up leaving a trail of blood around
the track as he finished third to Coronado's Quest. ``That beat him
more than anything,'' Kimmel said.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the case all along with the Storm Cat-Princess
Alydar colt, a $275,000 yearling purchase who was then bought by
Robert Waxman, who paid a record price for a 2-year-old in
training.
</P>
<P>
   Amid high hopes in his first start at Saratoga last year _ he
was sent off at odds of 4-5 _ he acted up the second he stepped on
the track, forcing Richard Migliore, his regular jockey, to
dismount in the gate. He finished second, but was disqualified to
sixth for interference. He won his first race on Aug. 24 and then
was third to the streaking Coronado's Quest last October in the
Cowdin, his last start of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year, treated with Lasix, he has won three in a row,
including the Leonard Richard at Delaware. His performance in the
Dwyer notwithstanding, Kimmel hopes Scatmandu will rebound in the
Jim Dandy on the way to the Travers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been our goal all along,'' said the 44-year-old Kimmel,
who has trained stars like last year's Eclipse Award-winning filly
Hidden Lake, Flat Fleet Feet, Twist Afleet and Golden Bri.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel, a onetime veterinarian, has been patiently working with
Scatmandu in his secluded corner of Saratoga's backstretch. This
week, Kimmel planned to school the eye-catching chestnut in the
paddock, and, depending on the results, will consider sending him
by van to the stakes barn and saddle him there instead of having
him make the long walk through the crowd on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked beautifully Sunday morning,'' said Kimmel, who
finished two races behind Mott at Saratoga in 1996 after a
controversial disqualification. ``I caught him going five furlongs
in :59 and change. A horse broke off 15 lengths in front of him and
he caught him at the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of horses, among them Wajima, Kelso and
Buckpasser, have won the 3-year-old championship without having run
in a Triple Crown race. And while the highly regarded Coronado's
Quest has a huge jump on Scatmandu when it comes to catching Real
Quiet or Victory Gallop in the race for end-of-the-year honors,
Kimmel is hoping his patience will pay off with the colt as it has
in his rise in the trainer standing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
