<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MGM-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MGM'S ONCE-MIGHTY LEO MAY BE PROWLING FOR MATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc., which has gone from
Hollywood's most powerful player to its most consistent
money-loser, announced that its days as a stand-alone studio may be
over.
</P>
<P>
   The once-majestic operation, symbolized by its Leo the lion logo
and its links to ``Gone With the Wind'' and ``The Wizard of Oz,''
continues to bleed so much red ink that it may be forced to
surrender its independence after more than seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate MGM could be bought for around $2 billion, but
believe a more likely scenario is a merger with a larger studio or
a TV network.
</P>
<P>
   MGM, controlled by billionaire Kirk Kerkorian for most of the
past three decades, disclosed Thursday that it has been discussing
``business combinations with complementary strengths'' and
acquisitions of smaller niche companies as part of its goal of
becoming an ``integrated global entertainment company.''
</P>
<P>
   MGM gave no further details. The Hollywood Reporter, citing
unnamed sources, said preliminary talks had been held with News
Corp. and Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The move may mean Kerkorian, regarded as a savvy businessman
with a fortune estimated at $3.7 billion, has decided MGM can no
longer afford to compete head-on with the Big Six studios: Disney,
Paramount, Sony, 20th Century Fox, Universal and Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Kerkorian owns 65 percent of MGM, which has movie, TV and home
video operations but no actual production facilities. It has one
valuable franchise -- James Bond -- and has suffered the indignity
of seeing one-time chief John Calley try to start a rival Bond
series at Sony, leading to lawsuits from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been bleeding red ink. MGM has not turned a profit
for a decade, losing $128 million last year and another $73.6
million in the first six months of this year, despite a certifiable
hit in ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' and a solid performance by ``The Man
in the Iron Mask,'' released at the height of public fascination
with Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   Its three most recent films -- ``Species II,'' ``Dirty Work''
and ``Disturbing Behavior'' -- have been duds. Its coming slate,
including ``The Extreme Adventures of Super Dave'' and Robert De
Niro's political thriller ``Ronin,'' contains no obvious hit
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in financial difficulty like this and a film
performs poorly, you can't shrug it off the way they do at the
other studios,'' said Drake &AMP; Co. entertainment analyst Arthur
Rockwell, a former MGM executive.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of the studio's problems was underscored in a report
filed this week with the Securities and Exchange Commission as part
of MGM's description of its recently announced plans to raise $250
million, possibly through a rights offering to current
shareholders. It indicated that only $132 million remains in a $1.3
billion revolving credit account opened in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   MGM also announced this week it will halt development of new TV
programs, cut two films from the dozen it planned to make next
year, and seek partners to co-produce some movies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pull the plug on new TV underscores the rough
financial conditions faced by MGM, which re-entered the business 18
months ago after a six-year absence. It has 10 series ordered for
next season, including ``The Magnificent Seven,'' ``The Outer
Limits'' and ``Stargate SG-1,'' but it will be several years before
it can recoup costs due to the intricacies of TV revenue flows.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old Kerkorian, who made his fortune in the airline
and casino businesses, has bought the studio on three occasions --
1969, 1986 and 1996 -- and sold it twice. Thursday's announcement
is the fastest way to stop the red ink, Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kirk has become a bit impatient at the progress so far
and it looks as if there may have been a miscalculation internally
on revenue flows,'' he said. He noted that the studio's results may
suffer as it boosted production earlier this year because officials
feared a strike by film industry unions. The strike never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the financial outlook should improve by 2000, when
MGM regains rights to parts of its film library and revenues from
increases in TV production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no predicting how this will turn out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerkorian last sold MGM in 1990 for $1.4 billion to Italian
financier Giancarlo Parretti, who defaulted on loans, leading to
French bank Credit Lyonnais owning the studio. Kerkorian and
Australian broadcasting group Seven Network Ltd. won an auction in
1996 with a $1.3 billion bid, then added the Goldwyn and Orion film
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   MGM sold 14 percent of itself to the public in November 1997
with a $180 million offering at $20 a share after warning investors
in a prospectus that the company did not expect to turn a profit
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares had fallen from a high of $26 in May and closed at a
post-offering low of $17.125 Wednesday before rising 69.75 cents to
$17.9375 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MGM has a library of 4,000 films and owns the legendary United
Artists Pictures studio, which Kerkorian bought in the early 1980s
from Transamerica after UA's huge losses on ``Heaven's Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     08-07 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson aside, staff &QL; 
needs to step it up
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BASED on the questions I'm getting, there are three things people
in Houston must know about Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Thing No. 1: Can he pitch the Astros to the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   Thing No. 2: Can the Astros retain his services beyond what
remains of this season?
</P>
<P>
   Thing No. 3: Why is he called the Big Unit?
</P>
<P>
   Credit Tim Raines, the former Expo and current Yankee, with
hanging that odd nickname on Johnson. When they were Montreal
teammates, Raines accidentally collided with the young Johnson as
he was leaving the batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up, way up, at the beanpole kid, Raines said: ``Man, you
are a big unit.''
</P>
<P>
   There. Now on to the important stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson can help pitch the Astros to the World Series. But he,
in turn, must get lots of help from his new friends. If Mike
Hampton doesn't turn his season around in a hurry, acquiring
Johnson will be little more than a wash, except on the excitement
meter.
</P>
<P>
   They probably can win the division without Hampy shaping up, but
the postseason figures to be more problematic. And it's the
postseason for which Johnson was acquired. Fact: The Astros never
have gotten a playoff victory from a lefty starter.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's superb finish a year ago _ he went 12-3 with a 2.75
ERA after July 1 _ was a most essential component of the Astros'
first division title in 11 years. For the Astros to get full value
from Johnson, Shane Reynolds and Hampton must pitch as well as they
are capable.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton must regain form
</P>
<P>
   Either that or Jose Lima and Sean Bergman must pitch better than
they have, and they have topped our expectations by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds appears to be bouncing back from a brief slump.
Hampton, unfortunately, has gone from bad to worse since a strained
left groin landed him on the DL. After a 7-2 start (2.52 ERA), he
has reverted to his dreadful form of early last season, when he was
3-7 with a 5.29 ERA through 17 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   With Hampton, it's feast or famine, a pattern he must break if
he is to become anything more than a journeyman. It's almost to the
point where Lima and Bergman, who wasn't a lock to make the team in
spring training, deserve consideration as the third and fourth
starters, respectively, with Hampy being dropped into the five
spot.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Astros don't have another day off until Aug. 27,
juggling the pitching order is easier contemplated than
accomplished. From a competitive and financial standpoint, though,
it's something Larry Dierker is being forced to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's entry into the rotation broke badly. Assuming he
pitches every fifth day through the end of the season, a safe
assumption unless he gets hurt, he'll go against the Cubs only
once, and his presence figures to significantly impact Astrodome
attendance no more than twice after his Houston debut tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Because Drayton McLane Jr. is on the hook for an additional $2
million-plus for his ``rental,'' that's an issue. Why do you think
the Astros took their sweet time in ``deciding'' whether to unveil
him tonight or Saturday night? Because they wanted to sell tickets
for both games.
</P>
<P>
   After the Phillies, Johnson has nine starts left _ but only four
of them at home: Milwaukee on Wednesday, Pittsburgh to open a
Domestand on Aug. 28, Cincinnati to launch another Sept. 7, and
then St. Louis on Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty will have limited impact
</P>
<P>
   The last is a Saturday night, and because of Mark McGwire's huge
Roger Maris-chasing presence, that game had an excellent chance of
selling out anyway, Unit or no Unit. Also, his Pittsburgh start
hits on a Friday night, usually a good gate night regardless of the
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's presence should significantly pad the turnstile count
for the Brewers and Reds. The Cincinnati game falls on Labor Day
afternoon, so his impact will be diminished there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern, baseball-wise, anyway, is his limited
exposure to the Cubs, whom he'll face only Aug. 22 in Chicago. As
the rotation stands, he wouldn't pitch against them in the
season-ending three-game series that could decide the division. But
Johnson, coming off a five-day break, would then be as fresh as a
daisy for the playoff opener.
</P>
<P>
   Which is terrific, as long as the Astros are in it.
</P>
<P>
   For McLane to make a serious pitch to keep Johnson, he'll have
to have seen concrete, crunched-number evidence that he can to a
large extent pay for himself. The only way for that to happen is
for the Astros to go deep into the postseason, deeper than they
have gone in 36 previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order, even for a Big Unit, if the Astros' other
pitchers don't cooperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
