<SLUG> BC-RAC-HAMBLETONIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER'S DREAM: SWEEP IN HAMBLETONIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chuck Sylvester, a horseman for 30 years, has been living in a
dream world since last Saturday, when all four horses he entered in
the eliminations qualified for Saturday's $1 million Hambletonian,
the first leg of trotting's triple crown.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester, who was inducted into the Harness Racing Hall of Fame
this year, has a chance to sweep the most prestigious event in
harness racing. His threesome of Muscles Yankee, Silver Pine and
David Raymond finished one-two-three in the $400,000 Beacon, the
final prep heading into the Hambletonian.
</P>
<P>
   Proving he can do little wrong, the 48-year-old Sylvester put
Armbro Rotary into the Hambletonian eliminations last Saturday and
the horse finished second in his heat behind Muscles Yankee, who
has been made the even-money favorite to capture Saturday's event
at the Meadowlands in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew last fall that I had a chance with three or four of
them if they stayed healthy and sound,'' said Sylvester, a native
of Toledo, Ohio, who has been training horses full-time for 31
years. ``To have four in a race like this is something you rarely
dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   With four horses in the field of 10, Sylvester has a chance to
become the first trainer of trotters to bankroll $1 million in day.
He also has a chance to duplicate the record of Walter Cox, who
trained the first four finishers in the 1929 Hambletonian. ``I just
hope they don't run each other down, or have a speed duel down the
backstretch,'' Sylvester said. ``I hope we don't run into any bad
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   His choice for the Hambletonian is Muscles Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's stronger and has made no mistakes this year, but in a
race like this everything has to go right on the day,'' Sylvester
said. ``It's a total package of luck and ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Muscles Yankee certainly has the ability, having won four of his
last five starts, including his last three, and finishing second in
the other. Another advantage Muscles Yankee has is that he will be
driven by John Campbell, seeking a record fifth Hambletonian title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's faster than last year,'' Campbell said about Muscles
Yankee, who won six of nine starts in 1997. ``He's very versatile,
more mature and lighter on his feet. I also like our starting
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Muscles Yankee will leave from the sixth hole, while Sylvester's
other three horses _ Armbro Rotary, Silver Pine and David Raymond _
will leave from the first three inside posts, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester's first Hambletonian winner came in 1987 with Mack
Lobell, a horse he purchased for $17,000 that earned nearly $4
million. His other title came in 1989 with Park Avenue Joe in a
dead-heat finish with Probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some good ones,'' Sylvester said, ``but this is the
first time I've had a good all-around bunch like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
