<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICEA RESCUES RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers learned Thursday that reserve
Luis Alicea will become more significant in the season's seven
remaining weeks.
</P>
<P>
   No member of the organization, though, will question the
significance of the 5-foot-9 infielder thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea replaced sore-kneed second baseman Mark McLemore in the
starting lineup Thursday night and was 2-for-3 with two runs batted
in as the Rangers defeated the Boston Red Sox, 7-4, last night at
The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lead the American League West by two games against
Anaheim, which did not play last night.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Burkett (7-11) gave the Rangers a quality
start, allowing three runs in a 6 1/3-inning appearance, and right
fielder Juan Gonzalez produced the most awe-inspiring event of the
evening with a seventh-inning, solo home run.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Alicea emerged as the most significant figure with two-out,
run-scoring base hits in the second and fourth innings and a
seventh-inning sacrifice bunt that led to the Rangers' sixth run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way our bench has played all year. We've talked all
year about `The Fab Five II,' '' Oates said of infielders Alicea
and Domingo Cedeno, outfielders Roberto Kelly and Mike Simms, and
catcher Bill Haselman. ``I've got to where I expect it from them.
Where would we be without our bench?''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who underwent arthroscopic surgery on both knees in
September, continues to be hampered by soreness. McLemore will be
monitored closely the rest of the season and will play as pain
allows.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Alicea, who made his 23rd start at second base
and 44th this season, will likely spell McLemore on a more regular
basis the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to play every day, whether it's off the bench or
starting,'' Alicea said. ``I knew the infield was set when I came
here, so I prepared myself for any role.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea starred in his role as a two-out delivery man against Red
Sox right-hander Bret Saberhagen (11-6).
</P>
<P>
   His two-out, second-inning single, which scored designated
hitter Lee Stevens, gave the Rangers a 3-1 advantage, and his
two-out, fourth-inning triple again scored Stevens and gave Burkett
a three-run lead to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being in pressure situations and having a chance to be
the hero,'' Alicea said. ``You're going to be the goat most of the
time because that's the way baseball is, but I like being in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea's seventh-inning sacrifice bunt led to another run, and
Gonzalez later deposited a 3-2 pitch from left-hander Greg Swindell
into the club-level seats in left field for a 429-foot home run
that gave the Rangers a 7-3 lead. It was the fifth home run and
third by Gonzalez to be hit into the club-level seats in The
Ballpark's five-year existence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the eighth inning with that lead intact, but
slumping left-hander Eric Gunderson jeopardized that lead by
failing to retire any of the three batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn, who earlier hit his 28th home
run this season against Burkett, greeted Gunderson with a leadoff
home run. Oates replaced Gunderson with right-hander Xavier
Hernandez after consecutive singles by shortstop Nomar Garciaparra
and left fielder Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez induced two ground balls, and the Rangers escaped the
jam with a three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers closer John Wetteland, who surrendered a walk and a
single in the ninth inning, retired Vaughn for the game's final
out. Vaughn, the potential tying run, swung at and missed
Wetteland's 3-2 fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The save was the 30th for Wetteland, who pitched for the third
consecutive night and fourth time in five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a guy like Wetteland sitting around for a
guy like Vaughn,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Burkett said of the diminutive infielder.
``He's been a real key for us. I think our bench has been
unbelievable. Those guys have won a lot of ballgames for us this
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
