<HEADLINE>
`CONSERVATIVE' COWBOYS DON'T PLAY MCIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Guard Everett McIver, who sustained a deep cut
on his neck in a training-camp dormitory incident July 29, was with
the Cowboys on Thursday night but did not play in the scrimmage
against the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the team decided it was not worth
the risk to have McIver play in the scrimmage. Jones said McIver
will practice with the team today at training camp in Wichita
Falls, but added that his status for tomorrow's preseason game
against the Raiders at Texas Stadium is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll practice him the next couple of days and take a look,''
Jones said. ``We are just being very conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey said, ``I think we've got a shot at . I'm
anxious to see him on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver, who returned to training camp Wednesday, was in street
clothes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McIver missed Friday's preseason game with the Seattle Seahawks
and did not return to training camp at Midwestern State University
for three days.
</P>
<P>
   McIver entered the Sun Bowl yesterday surrounded by security
personnel and did not talk to reporters. However, he did talk to
Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin. The two shook hands and chatted
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   A source said last week that Irvin was involved in the dorm
incident and that the wound was inflicted by scissors.
</P>
</TEXT>
