<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' TOP OFFENSE MARCHES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ The Cowboys' first-team offense and ``backup''
running back Chris Warren picked up in Thursday night's Sun Bowl
scrimmage against the Oakland Raiders where they left off in last
week's preseason game against the Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   On their first drive against the Raiders, the Cowboys marched 65
yards in eight plays for a touchdown. Highlights of the drive were
two pass completions from Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman to
Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was for 15 yards, as Irvin toasted Raiders defensive
back and 1997 Heisman Trophy winner Charles Woodson, setting up a
first down at the Raiders' 14-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Warren took it the rest of the way with a powerful touchdown run
behind the right side of the Cowboys' offense line. Warren scored
in the first quarter against Seattle on the same play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the same thing the fans saw,'' Gailey said. ``The ball
went down the field and into the end zone. But until I watch the
tape, I really can't evaluate how we played.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made two third-down conversions on the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm looking for from our offense is consistency and the
ability to convert third downs,'' Aikman said. ``I thought we had a
little bit of both of those tonight.''
Lett sparks defense
Defensive tackle Leon Lett had a strong game. Lett had a tackle for
a loss and a sack on the Raiders' first 20-play offensive
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not letting the Raiders score, the Cowboys might have
growing concerns on defense because of the lack of a consistent
pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive ends Kavika Pittman and Greg Ellis didn't get close to
the Raiders quarterbacks during the scrimmage. The only pressure
came from Lett or from blitzes from the secondary.
</P>
</TEXT>
