<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RANGERS-ZEILE-TEX     08-07 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-ZEILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' ZEILE HAS MADE LOTS OF STOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Todd Zeile seemed destined to play for the
Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile was born in the Los Angeles suburb of Newhall on Sept. 9,
1965, the same day Sandy Koufax threw his perfect game against the
Chicago Cubs. He grew up a Dodgers fan and was a big star at UCLA.
He married UCLA classmate Julianne McNamara, a gold medal gymnast
at the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He ran a charity golf tournament benefiting a local junior
college and raised funds for the Special Olympics. He has those
Southern California surfer-boy good looks that went over well
during his appearances on ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``The Tonight
Show with Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Zeile signed a three-year, $9.6 million contract with
the Dodgers on Dec. 8, 1996, his destiny seemed to be fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been the grand design, but it also might not
have been realistic,'' Zeile said. ``I know that nothing is certain
in this game, unless you have a no-trade clause in your contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile did not and never has. Instead, he has been stamped with a
``Have Bat, Will Travel'' label, a vagabond now with his seventh
team in four seasons. That would seem an inexplicable number for a
player who may not be the superstar the St. Louis Cardinals once
expected but still has the 28th most runs batted in by any
major-leaguer since the start of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   So the obvious question ... clubhouse lawyer? Malcontent?
Doesn't hustle? Beanie Baby thief?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with him,'' said Rangers coach Bucky
Dent, who was Zeile's infield coach for four years with the
Cardinals. ``He's a great guy, a super guy. He's what I call a true
professional, a quiet guy who plays hard and does his job. He's
been perfect every time I've been around him. It's just that
different teams have different needs and go after different guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers needed a third baseman, so Texas has become the
third stop for Zeile in a season that began with World Series
aspirations in Los Angeles, followed by 10 weeks of uncertainty
with the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   It's been an unusual season, even by his wandering standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously been unique,'' Zeile said. ``With the Dodgers,
I finally had a feeling like I had the opportunity to be in one
place for a period of time and maybe even be on a winner there. We
had more talent there than our record showed, but it's hard to put
a finger on what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tried to correct the problem on May 16, when they
traded Zeile and catcher Mike Piazza to the Marlins for Gary
Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich. The
history-making trade brought Zeile's heartwarming homecoming to a
sudden end. He also knew the Marlins would dump his salary at the
first opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to react to that,'' Zeile said. ``I was
thrown into a situation that had never been seen before in baseball
and probably will never be duplicated again. It was a big shock but
I had to adjust to it. It would have been self-defeating to let
circumstances affect my performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Symmetry brought Zeile to Texas. The Rangers needed a third
baseman because the Cardinals wanted Fernando Tatis included in the
Todd Stottlemyre-Royce Clayton deal. Tatis is the Cardinals' third
baseman of the future. Zeile was once that with the Cardinals and a
whole lot more.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals took him as a catcher in the second round of the
1986 draft and three years later, he was named 1989 Minor League
Player of the Year by ``USA Today.'' The Cardinals, who went to
three World Series in the 1980s, expected much from him.
</P>
<P>
   But 1990 was a bad year for everybody in St. Louis. The
Cardinals went 70-92, their second-worst record since World War I.
Manager Whitey Herzog bailed out halfway through the season, Willie
McGee was traded, Pedro Guerrero slumped and Terry Pendleton left.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile hit .244 with 15 homers and 57 RBI. He was only a rookie
but still labeled a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were such high expectations and when the team really
struggled, a lot of that was reflected on me,'' Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre asked Zeile to move to third base the next
year to make room for Tom Pagnozzi. Torre had once made the same
move as a player, but Zeile had misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was against it at first,'' Zeile said. ``But they said it
was good for the team and, at that point, I wasn't in a position to
question what was good for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   He may not have been the superstar the Cardinals expected, but
the bat did come around. He hit .277 with 17 homers and 103 RBI in
1993 and had 19 homers and 75 RBI the following strike-shortened
season.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile thought he was going to be with the Cardinals for a long
time, a belief seemingly confirmed on the eve of the 1995 season
when he agreed to a three-year, $12 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, that turned out to be the event that began his nomadic
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals reneged on the deal,'' Zeile said, still visibly
irritated four years later. ``I was going to miss the first five
games of the season \Rbecause of a thumb injury\S and they wanted
to wait. Then \Rowner\S August Busch was out of town. Then the club
president was out of town. They kept making excuses. The bottom
line was three weeks later they came and said I needed to take a
one-year deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile refused and went to arbitration, which was being done
during the season because of the strike. He also filed a grievance
with the Players Association. He asked for $4.1 million in
arbitration and was so annoyed with the Cardinals he refused to
settle at $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They traded me to the \RChicago\S Cubs on two conditions,''
Zeile said. ``No. 1, I had to settle for $3.6 million, the midpoint
in the arbitration case, and I had to drop my grievance. It took me
10 seconds to say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent the rest of that season with the Cubs, then signed a
one-year deal with the Philadelphia Phillies in 1996. He was traded
to the Baltimore Orioles on Aug. 29, 1996, hit .364 with three home
runs in the League Championship Series, then got the call from the
Dodgers to come home.
</P>
<P>
   Now it turns out, with another year left on his contract, he
could be with the Rangers longer than he was with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the possibility of coming here \Rarose\S, I thought it
was everything I wanted,'' Zeile said. ``It's a great lineup, a
great ballpark and a chance to win. That's what I'm looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
