<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING ALVAREZ-SOSA CATASTROPHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Minnesota manager Tom Kelly was generous in
his praise of the Rangers' trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas did a pretty good job,'' Kelly said. ``\RRafael\S
Palmeiro, \RJulio\S Franco, \RRuben\S Sierra and Harold Baines
batting together sounds pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly wasn't alone in that thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lineup with Baines in the middle is awfully
attractive,'' Milwaukee manager Tom Trebelhorn said. `They're going
to be a tough team to contain offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   And Oakland manager Tony La Russa said, ``Any time you get
Harold Baines, it's a good trade. No matter who else is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sammy Sosa and Wilson Alvarez were involved, and opinions
changed. Tom Grieve did not receive the Executive of the Year
award, as Skip Bayless suggested he should have been in the
``Dallas Times-Herald.'' Instead, Grieve was later crucified. Nine
years later, the worst trade in franchise history has not been
forgotten, not when Sosa is among those threatening to break Roger
Maris' single-season home-run record.
</P>
<P>
   However, just as Doug Melvin was lauded last week when he
acquired Todd Stottlemyre, Todd Zeile and Royce Clayton, Grieve
initially was widely praised in 1989 when he traded Sosa, Alvarez
and infielder Scott Fletcher to the Chicago White Sox for Baines
and infielder Fred Manrique.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the 1989 trade was announced, Jim Reeves wrote in
the ``Star-Telegram'': ``By making the trade, the Rangers showed
their fans, and more importantly, their players that they're
willing to do what it takes to keep the team in the pennant race
down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star-Telegram'' also ran a ``You Make the Call'' in the
paper the next day, inviting fans to phone in their opinion.
Eighteen responses were published with a variety of opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Six people praised the trade and two said the Rangers made a
mistake in trading Sosa and Alvarez. Four were upset that Fletcher
was traded. Three said the Rangers should have traded Pete
Incaviglia instead of Sosa. Two said the Rangers needed to trade
for pitching. One person said, ``We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Baines welcomed the trade, saying, ``I'm not happy getting out
of a place I've been for ten years. But I was tired of losing. Now
I'm with a team going in the right direction. I'm glad to be a part
of it. My goal all along has been to get a World Series ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Baines didn't get one and was never happy in Texas. He was
supposed to be the Rangers' designated hitter for many years but
was traded the next season.
</P>
<P>
   It turned ugly in 1991 when Alvarez threw a no-hitter for the
White Sox and people started wondering what Grieve was thinking
when he made the trade. The furor will never subside. A disgruntled
limited partner made a point of asking Grieve about it every year
at ownership meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Most people forget that the Rangers traded Sosa because they
thought they had Juan Gonzalez and Donald Harris coming soon.
Alvarez was forgotten because the team had Brian Bohanon, John
Barfield and Darren Oliver in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who the White Sox also wanted, was considered
untouchable. And manager Bobby Valentine, a few weeks before the
trade was made, projected Sosa as a player who would hit .280 with
20 homers and 80 runs batted in. There was no talk about Maris.
</P>
<P>
   The trade actually would never have been made if White Sox
general manager Larry Himes had been able to trade Dave Gallagher
to Detroit for center fielder Gary Pettis. But Pettis was eligible
for free agency and the trade was held up because he wouldn't agree
to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   So Grieve pulled the trigger. He also signed Pettis as a free
agent in the off-season, another move that was praised at first but
questioned two years later when Pettis was released in spring
training. An outfield of Sosa, Gonzalez and Ruben Sierra would have
looked much better.
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball trades receive spur-of-the-moment praise. It's
only later, after reality sets in, that gains and losses can truly
be assessed.  &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
