<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLEMORE MISSES GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers' lineup Thursday night did not
include second baseman Mark McLemore. That will not be uncommon
during the season's remaining seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who underwent arthroscopic surgery on both knees in
September, will be monitored closely and play as pain allows.
</P>
<P>
   ``His knees are not 100 percent,'' said manager Johnny Oates,
who indicated that McLemore likely will miss a second consecutive
start Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielder Luis Alicea, who started Thursday night's
game, likely will spell McLemore on a more regular basis the
remainder of the season. Oates consulted Wednesday with Dr. John
Conway, who recommended rest for McLemore's knees. McLemore, who
entered last night's game hitting .178 (19-for-107) in his past 30
games, has seen his average fall from .312 to .268 and his range
decrease during that span.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore started only three of the six games at the Metrodome
and SkyDome during the Rangers' most recent road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the turf did him any good,'' Oates said. His
knees ``just haven't bounced back.''
Search for a lefty
The acquisition of a left-handed reliever ranks among the top
priorities for Rangers general manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bailes (bursitis, left shoulder) remains on the 15-day
disabled list, and Eric Gunderson continues to struggle. The
Rangers, though, likely will not turn to left-hander Tony Fossas,
whom the Chicago Cubs released recently. Jim Bronner, who
represents Fossas, called Melvin yesterday and left a message in an
attempt to gauge the Rangers' interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk to our people about him,'' Melvin said. ``My
gut feeling, though, is he's not somebody we'll be interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to meet during the next couple of weeks and see if
there's anybody in the system that can help us,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handers Jeff Granger (3-6, 4.37) and Mike Venafro of
Triple-A Oklahoma likely would be the top candidates. Venafro, whom
the Rangers promoted this week from Double-A Tulsa, recorded three
strikeouts and allowed only one hit during three innings Wednesday
in his first appearance at the Triple-A level.
</P>
<P>
   However, Melvin said any minor-league pitcher likely would not
be promoted until September.
Searching for Angels
Angels right-hander Ken Hill, who went on the 15-day disabled list
June 11, reported no discomfort after pitching three innings during
a simulated game Wednesday in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Hill underwent arthroscopic surgery June 15 to remove bone spurs
from his right elbow. The Angels scheduled a bullpen session today
in Chicago for Hill (8-5, 5.15), and the right-hander likley will
begin a medical rehabilitation assignment Sunday with Class-A Cedar
Rapids of the Midwest League.
Briefly
The Red Sox yesterday acquired left-hander Pete Schourek from the
Astros for cash considerations and reinstated right-hander Jim
Corsi from the 15-day disabled list. The Red Sox also placed
right-hander Rich Garces (bone chips, right elbow) on the 15-day
disabled list (retroactive to Monday).
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre is scheduled to participate in the
Texas Rangers' ``Star-Telegram'' Chat Room from 3:30-3:50 p.m.
Friday on the Rangers' official site (www.texasrangers.com).
Farm report
Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): Shortstop Scott Sheldon
went 2-for-4 with two runs scored, a double and his 28th home run,
but the RedHawks (59-53) lost to Vancouver, 7-4, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): Right-hander Rodney Pedraza
recorded eight strikeouts and surrendered only two runs during his
seven-inning appearance, but the Drillers (62-55) lost to Arkansas,
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): Right-hander Chris
Tynan (4-6, 4.52) recorded a season-high 10 strikeouts and pitched
seven scoreless innings as the Sand Gnats (57-61) defeated
Columbus, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pulaski (Appalachian League, rookie): Left fielder Kevin Harris
hit his seventh home run of the season during the top of the ninth
inning to propel the Rangers (18-28) to a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Coast (Gulf Coast League, rookie): The Rangers (22-19)
split a double-header of seven-inning games with the Royals, who
won the first game, 1-0. Second baseman Pedro Guerrero went 2-for-4
and drove in three runs during the Rangers' 6-2 victory in the
second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
