<SLUG> BC-BACKHOE-GUN-CHASE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN USES BACKHOE TO CHASE TEEN WHO FIRED GUN IN HIS DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANCASTER, Calif. -- A man accused of driving a backhoe through
a neighbor's fence after an argument, injuring the woman and her
son, was released from custody pending further investigation,
sheriff's officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clutter, 38, was arrested shortly after the 10:30 p.m.
Wednesday incident, in suburban Antelope Acres, which injured
neighbor Cassandra Davenport, 32, and her 14-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need for more investigation,'' said Lt. Tom Pigott,
in charge of the Lancaster sheriff's station detective bureau. ``We
need to talk to witnesses and determine what took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutter told officials that he became angered with the
14-year-old after the teen-ager began firing an unknown type of
weapon, possibly a BB gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighbor indicated the rounds were coming in his
direction,'' Pigott said. ``He confronted the juvenile and a verbal
argument ensued.''
</P>
<P>
   During the argument, Clutter climbed on his backhoe and drove it
through a chain-link fence that separates the two properties,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clutter drove the machine, the youth allegedly pointed a
.38-caliber handgun in his direction. The gun went off, wounding
the teen in his leg, when Davenport forced her son's hand down to
try to prevent a shooting, deputies said.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Clutter drove his backhoe into a car behind which
Davenport and her son were standing, pinning them between the car
and their mobile home, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager was airlifted to Providence Holy Cross Hospital in
Mission Hills, a Los Angeles suburb, for his gunshot wound and a
dislocated hip.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport was taken to Antelope Valley Hospital in Lancaster,
where she was treated for a broken right leg and cuts to her lower
abdomen and upper body.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they are investigating to see if the incident is
part of a continuing neighborhood dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if this is an isolated incident,'' Pigott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster is about 60 miles north of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
