<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-2ND     08-07 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SAID TO DETAIL CLINTON AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for inserts, grafs 9 and 18 are new; graf 16 has been
restored. Refinements throughout and some trims.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending months of anticipation with a resigned
shrug, Monica Lewinsky walked into a federal courthouse here
Thursday, and, a lawyer familiar with her account said, testified
that she and President Clinton had carried on a sexual affair
inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony before a federal grand jury, which contradicted a
previous sworn statement, tightened the legal and political vise
around Clinton. The president denied under oath in the Paula Jones
sexual misconduct lawsuit that he had had a sexual relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky, and he has denied it as well to the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky testified to having had several sexual encounters
with Clinton in his small, private study down a short hallway from
the Oval Office, the lawyer said. As expected, she also testified
that she and the president had talked about ways to conceal their
relationship, the lawyer said, but she also said he never directly
told her to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor, is investigating
accusations that Clinton lied under oath and obstructed justice by
trying to conceal the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   More than six months of waiting for Ms. Lewinsky to tell her
story ended just before 8:30 a.m., when she stepped from a dark
green Toyota Land Cruiser, embraced a lawyer, shrugged and vanished
inside. As portable generators rumbled in the background and one
cameraman swept the scene from a cherrypicker 50 feet over Third
Street, about 20 satellite trucks beamed images of Ms. Lewinsky _
once an unpaid, anonymous sorter of White House mail _ around the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, 25, answered questions in exchange for immunity
from prosecution for any wrongdoing she describes. She is
vulnerable to prosecution only if she lies in her testimony, in a
deal worked out with prosecutors nine days ago. In an affidavit on
Jan. 7 in the Jones case, Ms. Lewinsky swore that she had not had a
sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Ms. Lewinsky's described her six and a half
hours before the grand jury as grueling. ``She was asked very
specific questions about very private matters which are very hard
to discuss in public,'' the associate said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Lewinsky has agonized for months over the prospect
of damaging Clinton's presidency, friends have said. One of her
friends described Ms. Lewinsky as saying Wednesday night, as she
prepared for her testimony: ``What I'm doing tomorrow is something
I never ever wanted to do. It breaks my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 27, the 23 grand jurors have listened to the
testimony of more than 70 witnesses and hours of surreptitiously
taped conversations between Ms. Lewinsky and her former friend
Linda Tripp. Thursday was the grand jurors' first opportunity to
look Starr's prized witness in the eyes, question her and judge her
credibility for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Before another media scrum after Ms. Lewinsky completed her
testimony, her spokeswoman, Judy Smith, said she had answered
questions from prosecutors and urors ``truthfully, completely and
honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and her family are relieved that this ordeal finally
appears to be coming to an end,'' Ms. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never publicly described his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky in any detail, beyond defiantly declaring that it was not
sexual.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a capital whipsawed between disclosure and denial, starkly
different days unspooled at the federal courthouse and the White
House. Summoning the authority and trappings of his office, as well
as his own storied political resilience, President Clinton went
about his official duties Thursday without betraying a hint of
interest in the former intern's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked forward to this day for quite a long time,''
Clinton said in one speech at a Washington hotel, referring to his
opportunity to address a White House conference on building
economic self-improvement in Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, the president appeared before a row of
uniformed police officers in the sun-gilded Rose Garden to call for
a permanent five-day waiting period for people seeking to buy
handguns. With a quick left-handed salute after the official
remarks, the president cued a brassy Marine band to strike up
``Stars and Stripes Forever.'' Reporters waiting to shout questions
about Ms. Lewinsky were stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Some White House advisers gave vent to frustration over the
spectacle at the courthouse and the unremitting pressure of the
Lewinsky investigation. ``I hate the whole thing,'' said one. ``I
hate you, I hate us.'' Then, in his disgust, words failed him.
``Ugh,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, provided the official
reaction to the testimony. ``The president has not expressed any
views to us on this,'' he said in a contentious and sometimes
raucous briefing Thursday, ``except we know that he does agree with
us _ and probably all Americans _ that if this means that we're
coming to the end of this four-year, over $40 million
investigation, then that would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official said the White House had no interest in drawing
attention Thursday. ``We're showing wise restraint,'' he said.
``Nobody's going to criticize Ms. Lewinsky, and we're not going to
get in the story. It's a big enough story without us.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their restraint, White House advisers telephoned
reporters late Thursday evening to ask what they had learned about
Ms. Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Ms. Lewinsky's version of her relationship with
the president was still in doubt. But Starr's investigation has
rushed forward since then, with her immunity agreement and
Clinton's own promise to testify at the White House on Aug. 17. In
striking the deal with Starr, Ms. Lewinsky also turned over a navy
blue dress that prosecutors have sent to the Federal Bureau of
Investigation crime laboratory. Technicians there are trying to
determine if the dress contained physical evidence of a sexual
encounter with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky was asked a series of questions about the dress
Thursday. Prosecutors have left open the possibility of recalling
Ms. Lewinsky before the grand jury, perhaps after the president
testifies.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from across the country and around the world converged
on the courthouse Thursday, clucking over the spectacle and
contributing to it at the same time. Some reporters began claiming
choice spots as early as Wednesday evening for a glimpse of Ms.
Lewinsky _ only to be flummoxed Thursday morning as she took an
unexpected route through the courthouse, up to the third floor in
an elevator reserved for judges.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, as passers-by stopped to take in the scene, scores of
photographers lined up for a shot of her. When George Hancock, a
supporter of Ms. Lewinsky's from Bowling Green, Ky., tried to raise
his yellow hand-lettered sign wishing her luck, he cut off their
line of sight. ``You wave that sign again,'' screamed one
cameraman, ``I'll kill you!''
</P>
<P>
   Ducking out of view, Hancock was surrounded moments later by
reporters and photographers, some of whom berated him while others
tried to interview him. ``How's it make you feel, buddy?'' Dominic
Mumeka, 33, murmured as if to himself as he stood off to one side.
``This is your 15 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumeka, who cleans a taxi depot, said he had dropped by to watch
history be made. ``There hasn't been anything like this since
Watergate, and before that since Andrew Johnson, 1869,'' he said.
But, he asked, ``Can a guy really get impeached for going to bed
with someone?''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has resolutely refused to question Ms.
Lewinsky's credibility publicly. But fragmentary accounts have
emerged that White House officials were concerned that she had a
crush on the president.
</P>
<P>
   An Indianapolis lawyer who has worked as a Democratic operative
said in an interview Thursday that he had been asked to keep an eye
on Ms. Lewinsky at an Oct. 23, 1996 fund-raiser here to ensure that
she did not ``embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sullivan, a lobbyist and lawyer from Indianapolis, said
that he had been asked by a friend in the administration to watch
Ms. Lewinsky because she had recently left the White House and
there were concerns she was ``disgruntled.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan recalled his friend as saying about Ms. Lewinsky: ```We
don't know if she has fantasized a relationship with the president.
But she keeps showing up at these events.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he had watched Ms. Lewinsky reach out with both
hands to hug the president. ``And he hugged her back,'' he said.
``Then he said to her, `How are you doing?' She said, `Fine.' He
said, `How's your new job?' And she said, `Great.' He said, `I wish
you the best of luck,' and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he spoke on Monday with a television station in
Indianapolis. In a sign that the White House is following up any
lead to bolster Clinton's story, Sullivan said that on Wednesday
David Kendall, the president's personal lawyer, called him to ask a
number of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he felt no pressure to tell his story publicly.
</P>
</TEXT>
