<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR PLAY HAS SUDDEN LACK OF SUBSTANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A landmark passing took place in the world of sports two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest U.S. women's athlete of all time,
heptathlete Jackie Joyner-Kersee, quietly competed in her final
track-and-field meet.
</P>
<P>
   Tears flowed. Spontaneous ovations were the order of the day.
But large headlines were hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Bolder, sexier news items keep barging onto the sports pages. In
Joyner-Kersee's own sport, she was upstaged by news last week that
Texas A&AMP;M gold-medal Olympic shot putter Randy Barnes had tested
positive for a banned substance and faces a lifetime suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, yesterday in Switzerland, the International Swimming
Federation (FINA) announced that three-time Olympic gold-medal
swimmer Michelle Smith of Ireland _ and the University of Houston _
has been banned for tampering with her urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   At the 95-year-old Tour de France, one team was kicked out,
others withdrew, and at least six more teams were under suspicion
for using banned substances as the venerable bike race chugged into
its final leg along the Champs-Elysee.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there is Joyner-Kersee, who leaves her sport
untainted by innuendo or a checkered past.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, alas, is a sporting world that can't seem to
play fair or pass a urine test.
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's case, suspicions lapped at her heels as far back as
the Atlanta Olympics. She was 26 and had surfaced from a career of
consolation heats to suddenly win gold medals in the 400-meter
freestyle and the 200- and 400-meter individual medleys.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptical swimming world peered at her performances and her
choice of husbands _ Dutch discus thrower and shot putter Erik de
Bruin _ and assumed the worst. de Bruin himself had been banned
from track and field for four years for testing positive for high
levels of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's haughty stance amid the rumors didn't win her many
disciples. The world swimming body surprised her with a random test
in her hometown of Dublin in January. And when the results showed
she had spiked the sample with something that smelled like Irish
whiskey _ it could have disguised banned substances in the sample _
FINA moved to suspend Smith for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Spare the Irish jokes, please.
</P>
<P>
   The greater thought here is, doesn't anybody want to play fair
anymore?
</P>
<P>
   In Barnes' case, this would be his second suspension and,
therefore, prompt a lifetime suspension. It also would taint one of
the fond memories of the 1996 Olympics, when Barnes threw to the
gold medal on his final attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The word is ``would,'' because Barnes says he's innocent.
(Insert sighs here.)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he took the stuff, Barnes says. But the substance,
androstenedione, is an over-the-counter dietary supplement Barnes
claims he wasn't informed was banned.
</P>
<P>
   His claim isn't likely to be upheld, history tells us. But it
unsnaps the lid on a fermenting problem in 1990s sports _ athletes,
looking for an edge, taking over-the-counter supplements.
</P>
<P>
   If your son is a high school football player and he is taking
creatine, you might want to read the label. They all have labels.
They all promise increased strength or energy. They're all legal.
</P>
<P>
   And no one has a clue what the long-term effects really will be.
Since 1994, the U.S. government does not regulate the dietary
supplement industry.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want a scare, log on to the Internet and find
something called The Grey Market Underground Web-Mall
(www.Samson-1.com). Behind the gray curtain, the site sells
Renewtrient, which is supposed to be a legal, ``safe'' alternative
to GHB (Gamma Hydroxy Butyric Acid).
</P>
<P>
   In its normal form, GHB can be used as a surgical anesthetic. It
has been found to cause comas, seizures and respiratory arrest. The
makers of Renewtrient claim its product promotes increased
strength, bedroom vigor and ``reversal of male pattern baldness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site does add one disclaimer: ``This product ... is so
powerful you might acquire mild acne from its use.'' It also warns
against driving or operating machinery.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the market abounds for products like Renewtrient.
Creatine is not a GHB alternative, but its claim to help tired
muscles recover more quickly and to help build strength has made it
the supplement of choice among college and professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire has praised creatine. Dave Ellis,
whose title at the University of Nebraska is ``Coordinator of
Performance Nutrition,'' dispenses creatine and other legal dietary
supplements to the school's football players.
</P>
<P>
   The market is there. But so are the questions.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to be bigger, stronger, faster has never been more
gray.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic heroine Jackie Joyner-Kersee deserved bigger headlines
as she retired two weeks ago. We'd offer a toast, instead, but
somebody took the Irish whiskey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
