<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL CLOSES RANKS AGAINST BAGHDAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for inserts and reorganization)  
(lh) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council closed ranks Thursday to
berate Iraq for ending cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors, but
took no action other than to demand that Baghdad reverse its
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Iraq was isolated in the Security Council, the
government got mixed signals from Secretary General Kofi Annan, who
suggested that the Iraqis, ``desperate'' for some movement toward
ending sanctions, needed to be brought more closely into
deliberations here.
</P>
<P>
   But in a written statement in Washington, President Clinton
said, ``Far from hastening the day the international community
lifts sanctions,'' Iraq's failure to permit inspections ``will
perpetuate those sanctions and keep the Iraqi economy under tight
international control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council members, united in shock and a touch of
weariness at having to work their way through another unexpected
crisis created by Baghdad, called Iraq's decision to freeze
cooperation with inspectors ``totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Moscow and Paris, the capitals most sympathetic to
the Iraqis, governments distanced themselves from Baghdad in
statements. In Russia and China, there were expressions of concern
about the consequences of continued Iraqi defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now extremely important not to stoke tensions over
Iraq,'' the Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman, Vladimir Rakhmanin,
told a news briefing in Moscow. A Chinese spokesman, Tang Guoqiang,
said his government would do what it could ``to avoid a worsening
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton said the Iraqi move ``once again will
backfire,'' his statement emphasized sanctions as the wedge to
force Iraq to comply with inspections. Administration officials
said there was no immediate consideration of military force, saying
that the situation so far seemed to be less serious than last
October, when the Iraqis expelled U.S. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that the administration would consider the use of
force if the situation deteriorated. ``We'll take our time _ we're
not going to let Saddam call the shots,'' one administration
official said Thursday night, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance went on as usual in Baghdad Thursday, though no
actual site inspections were attempted because Iraq barred them on
Wednesday, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq decided this week that it would end cooperation with
arms inspections and allow only passive monitoring by surveillance
cameras, the Iraqis were aware that they were actually close to
meeting disarmament requirements in some areas, Richard Butler, the
chief arms inspector told the Security Council Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM,
said Thursday that the Iraqis also knew that problems in accounting
for biological and some chemical compounds were serious and
growing. Right up to the present, Iraq has continued to change
figures and alter other information earlier presented as ``full,
final and complete'' declarations.
</P>
<P>
   At times the Iraqis have been forced to revise a story when
confronted with evidence by inspectors _ as in the recent case of
the discovery of traces of VX nerve gas on shell casings after
Iraqis denied that they had used it. At other times, they volunteer
new information _ but that only raises more troubling questions
about why an account has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent examinations of old warhead remnants, for example,
weapons experts found more traces of anthrax than they could
explain, UNSCOM officials said Thursday. When the Iraqis were
pressed, they revised earlier ``final figures'' to say that they
had actually filled three times as many warheads with anthrax _ 16
_ as with botulism _ 5. Until then, Iraq said it had filled weapons
with more than three times more botulism than anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   This admission has revived speculation among inspectors that
Iraq produced not only more anthrax, but also two kinds of it, one
in a dry form that is easier to spray and has a longer shelf life.
Officials insisted Thursday, however, that this is only speculation
at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Iraq changes the figures, it has a ripple effect
throughout their entire declaration,'' said Charles Duelfer, deputy
chairman of UNSCOM. ``That is a very complicated procedure because
a declaration is built and substantiated to support one set of
numbers and to change that becomes very difficult.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
