<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2340 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1STLD-WRITE     08-07 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNITED NATIONS: very difficult.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister and chief
negotiator on weapons issues, gave a new explanation of how VX
nerve gas could have been found on the shells. In a letter to the
Security Council on Wednesday, he said the traces could have been
created from the ``decomposition of other chemical substances or
from the use of equipment which had already been used to produce
the VX agent.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's lengthy Council meeting, a Western diplomat
said that nobody relished having to take strong action to make Iraq
conform to its agreements. Until the arms inspectors are satisfied
that Iraq has provided answers to outstanding questions about
biological, chemical, nuclear and missile programs, Saddam cannot
hope to see the end of sanctions, which were imposed in 1990 after
the invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was weary, everyone was annoyed and everyone was
concerned that this not turn into a crisis that would force the
United States to act as it had to act last year,'' the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   The council action came after Butler briefed members on his
aborted trip to Iraq, which ended when talks broke down earlier
this week. He also spoke on the Iraqi leadership's refusal to turn
over documents, including one discovered in July that shed light on
the amount of ``nonconventional munitions'' used during the 1980-87
war with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that the document could prove that there are
larger quantities of chemical _ and possibly biological _ agents
unaccounted for in Iraq than inspectors were told about last year.
Iraqis said that they had filled 101,080 warheads with chemical
weapons in the 1980s, but the new document reveals that fewer than
that were actually deployed. The inspectors want to know what
happened to the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also spoke to the council about his assessment of Iraq's
position after talking Thursday morning with Aziz. Annan told the
council that Iraq was ``clearly in violation of the resolutions of
the Security Council and the memorandum of understanding I
concluded in Baghdad in February.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is well understood by the government of Iraq,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan added that he thought Iraq's position was ``not a
closed one,'' that Baghdad had acted out of frustration and even
desperation, and that it might be the right time ``to stand back
and make a comprehensive reassessment of where we are, where we are
going and how to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In undertaking this comprehensive review,'' he said, ``it
might be helpful to engage the Iraqis much more closely than we
have hitherto.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Iraq has persistently and successfully
managed to broaden its diplomatic contacts with United Nations
officials, skirting the Security Council when it could. Iraqi has
complained repeatedly that the Council and the disarmament
commission are dominated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Arab League Thursday, Aziz appealed for
support against what he called the ``injustice'' of UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   Arms inspectors see this as an Iraqi tactic to bring
international politics into what is essentially a technical
operation to disarm Iraq and destroy its capacity to make new
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Butler also provided the Security Council Thursday with results
of a technical evaluation in July of Iraq's ``full, final and
complete disclosure'' on biological weapons, a document the Iraqis
say closes the file on that issue. This was the third such
technical evaluation demanded by Iraq over the last year, and its
findings were no different from earlier ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new material was presented by Iraq at this meeting,''
Butler wrote in his report of the July technical evaluation. The
international experts again concluded that Iraq's latest disclosure
``was not adequate to allow for credible verification.''
</P>
<P>
   The biological experts found problems with Iraqi accounts of
what they had done with bombs, warheads, spraying devices or
quantities of the agents themselves, including botulinum toxin,
anthrax bacillus and aflatoxin.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Bill Richardson, the U.S. representative to the
United Nations called the Iraqi demand ``disarmament by
ultimatum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
