<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A SHUDDER OF DISGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert missing word in graf 12)  
 (JT)  
 By RUSSELL BAKER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a picture of the White House lawyer Lanny Breuer leaving
the courthouse Tuesday with his lawyer Mark Lynch. But where is
Lynch's lawyer?
</P>
<P>
   The editor must have cropped him out of the picture. It's hard
to conceive that a lawyer for a White House lawyer would show up at
a courthouse these days without a lawyer of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Law is on a hair-raising tear this summer. Make a move without a
lawyer, and you can end up on TV looking guiltier than Count
Dracula.
</P>
<P>
   The law is now engaged in a prodigious power grab. Unless it is
stopped people without lawyers may soon find themselves under
subpoena to explain why they refuse to salute the billable hour.
</P>
<P>
   A coup by the law itself? Quite possibly. It started at the
White House when everybody not anointed by Blackstone was put out
of the scandal loop, including the press secretary, whose task is
to keep the seething masses up to date on the democratic saga.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers _ advised no doubt by their own lawyers _
have raised the infamous old White House stone wall against
universal public enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   This naturally maddens the federal judiciary. Off and on through
history, federal judges have assumed they are better qualified than
presidents and Congress to steer the Republic. We are apparently in
such an era right now.
</P>
<P>
   When the courts finish authorizing Kenneth Starr to strip
Clinton down to his bones and then to his DNA, the supremacy of the
courts will be so well established that none but saints and fools
will want to be president again.
</P>
<P>
   And who will ever again want to become a journalist? Imagine,
mother: Do you want that lovely little child of yours to grow up
and spend a long malodorous life writing stories that make you
shudder with disgust?
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate journalists Woodward and Bernstein inspired a
whole generation of young people to think of journalism as an
honorable way to spend a life. That is the generation that's now
trying to look solemn instead of leering and winking as it issues
the daily bulletins on ladies' dirty linen.
</P>
<P>
   These wretched media people know it's filthy work, but somebody,
they say, has to do it, just as somebody has to clean septic tanks.
</P>
<P>
   What pious baloney. Sanitary engineering is a noble career
because it's vital to world health; taste-free journalism makes you
wince with shame for what ought to be an honorable calling. If
you'd be embarrassed to have your children read what you write or
watch you say it on the tube, you'd urge them not to follow in the
parental footsteps, wouldn't you?
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing about this endless business is that there is
absolutely nobody to root for. Polls show the public is sympathetic
to the president, but thinks him a liar.
</P>
<P>
   The softest judgment about him might be that he is a foolish
philanderer and incurable finagler who needs counseling rather than
impeaching.
</P>
<P>
   The absurd conduct of Monica Lewinsky can be put down to the
callowness of youth and a hopeless ignorance of the hazards of
Washington, but her famous photo with Old Glory disclosed a
stunning insensitivity to life's exigencies.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp. It's tempting to call her ``poor Linda Tripp.''
Poor because her betrayal of Lewinsky's trust was despicable, and
because she wants to believe it wasn't, and because satirists make
fun of her physical appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The old folks used to explain why such people deserved no tears
by saying, ``She made her bed, let her lie in it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kenneth Starr, even those who root for him wish he were
more like Spencer Tracy than Charles Laughton. The White House
counterattack has damaged him by comparing him to Inspector Javert
(played by Charles Laughton) in ``Les Miserables.''
</P>
<P>
   I once heard a woman sum up the plot of this immense novel in 14
words: ``A man steals a loaf of bread and never hears the end of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With slight changes the line could be applied to the Starr
attempt to get something on the president that will justify his
years of investigation. You'd have to hate Clinton with a fury to
root for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Some people probably do. Sensitive people will be content to
loathe them all quietly for what they have done to the country, for
how they have debased our culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
