<HEADER>
A2381 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      08-07 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCE ENDS AS MARINER FANS WAKE TO REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since September 1995, the Mariner fan base has been an
almost complete contradiction to the rest of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere else, many fans, vibrating with contempt for owners
and players who ushered in the 1994 strike that cost the World
Series and bled into 1995, abandoned the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not here. After the Mariners pulled off a preposterous
regular-season comeback loaded with late-inning dramatics to make
their first postseason, they played what was arguably the most
electric series ever. The engaging players and their
success-starved fans fell into an affectionate clinch rare in pro
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Fans didn't have to be told to love these guys. They beat the
marketers to the slogan.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. The point now, driven home in the week since the
trade of Randy Johnson: The affair is over.
</P>
<P>
   The rage provoked by the deal has gone beyond any event in
Mariner history, and rivals the Sonics' 1972 trade of Lenny Wilkens
for the capacity to sour.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that there was no virtue to the trade; the early
reports from Tacoma on the youngsters acquired have been promising.
Nor is it likely that many fans here are going to quit cold turkey
on the Mariners. Ken Griffey Jr. still has 21 homers to hit.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed is the feeling. The way Johnson's Seattle career
devolved and collapsed made liars, fools and hypocrites of almost
everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need Dear Abby to deduce that such results are deadly
for romance.
</P>
<P>
   The shy tycoons who own the club _ call them the ShyTys _ looked
bad for bailing on Johnson in November, then bailing on his trade
to the Dodgers in May, then lying about the fact he would be in
Seattle for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball boss Woody Woodward looked foolish, for the second
trading deadline in a row, for appearing fleeced, especially after
it became clear the Yankees had strung him along to keep Johnson
from going to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella, unable to effect change in a highly
underachieving team, looked foolish for toeing the party line when
he knows well the deal all but abandons the chance for a run in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson looked bad because his selfish behavior contradicted his
words enough times that he lost clubhouse and management support
and inevitably diminished his market value.
</P>
<P>
   The players looked like hypocrites for criticizing a deal that
probably wouldn't have happened if they had done their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The media looked bad because none of the spray of rumors _ not
only this time around, but in May when the Dodgers' attempt to
acquire Johnson came to naught _ ended up forecasting what
happened, and added to the heightened expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a number of GMs are looking foolish, because they have to
explain to their bosses and fans why they couldn't have topped the
deal by Houston that tonight, for Johnson's home debut, is giving
the Astros their first sellout in history.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that shocked all of baseball savaged the Mariners
because its appearance is a blatant step backward in the middle of
a season. It shoots to hell the credibility that was built in the
1995 run and led to the creation of a $500 million stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For the foreseeable, there is little reason for the average fan
to believe the ShyTys, Woodward or Piniella, which would seem to be
a dangerous development considering the club is desperate to sell
out all of its expensive perches in the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But the park masterminds are convinced that green grass and blue
sky will overcome any damage. Knowing the naive forgiveness of most
fans, they are probably right, which makes the seasonal write-off
easier to rationalize for them.
</P>
<P>
   Harder to rationalize for the newer, more casual fans to
baseball is the loss of a figure who literally and figuratively
towered over the local sports landscape.
</P>
<P>
   His negatives, more apparent to bosses and teammates, were not
meaningful to the average fan, who paid to see an event every time
Johnson pitched. Until this season, he delivered nearly all the
time. While no one expected Johnson to last forever, there was no
evidence to suggest he was beyond his prime except for his
regrettable season-long pout over money.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, along with Griffey, Edgar Martinez and Jay Buhner, have
been here nearly a decade together through bad times and good,
making a rare bond with the community. Joey Cora, though with fewer
seasons, struck a similar chord. It's hardly coincidence that Cora
and Martinez _ who, like Griffey and Johnson, married Seattle-area
women _ have said they would rather retire than move to another
team.
</P>
<P>
   That may be an emotional reaction to an impending dislocation,
which can change when they realize in the offseason they may be
walking away from millions.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they and their families never will be more
graciously received anywhere than the place where they made sports
magic.
</P>
<P>
   As the fans were bid to do, and did like nowhere else in
baseball, they hadda love these guys. So when these guys are ripped
away under dubious circumstances, the ShyTys, Woodward and Piniella
become the callous adulterers ending the romance.
</P>
<P>
   Stay low, gentlemen. Stay low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
