<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S SUFFER A LOSS IN MIDST OF RAINOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Mariner first baseman David Segui, having the best
season of his career, suffered a bizarre knee injury Thursday night
about 15 minutes before the series opener against the Detroit
Tigers was supposed to start.
</P>
<P>
   The game eventually was rained out and rescheduled for 4 p.m.
EDT Friday as part of a doubleheader. Segui probably won't play
either game and could be sidelined for many more.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella said Segui's right knee locked as he rose
from a chair in the visiting clubhouse at Tiger Stadium. Segui was
taken to a local hospital for a magnetic resonance imaging test to
determine the damage and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Results are expected Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just stood up and the knee locked,'' trainer Rick Griffin
said. ``Usually when that happens, you suspect torn cartilage. But
we won't know until we get the MRI results.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin wouldn't project how much time Segui could miss if the
cartilage is damaged. Segui missed 16 games after cartilage surgery
on his left knee last season while playing for Montreal. The
Mariners will promote a player, possibly first baseman/designated
hitter Dan Rohrmeier, from the Class AAA Tacoma Rainiers. The
player is expected to be in uniform for Friday's twinbill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Griffin said of Segui's injury. ``I can't think
of a weirder one this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui, signed as a free agent during the offseason, has been one
of the most productive all-around players for the M's this season.
He is batting .333 with 16 homers and 71 RBIs and has been
especially hot since the All-Star break, batting .368.
</P>
<P>
   He also is having a Gold Glove-caliber season, leading all major
league first basemen with a .999 (one error in 897 total chances)
fielding percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be terrible to lose him,'' third baseman Russ Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he juggled his lineup for Thursday night's game,
which was called after a 1{-hour rain delay. ``I put Edgar
(Martinez) at first, (Rob) Ducey in center and Junior (Ken Griffey
Jr.) at DH.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the same lineup in the first game Friday against
Tigers right-hander Seth Greisinger.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero, scheduled to start Thursday night, will pitch
Friday's opener with left-hander Jamie Moyer starting the nightcap.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the inclement weather is supposed to stick around
at least through Friday night. A postponement Friday likely would
force doubleheaders Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
