<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2GOOD-TEETH08-COX     08-07 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2GOOD-TEETH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bright teeth take bite out of film realism
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 1944 in the acclaimed film Saving Private Ryan, and Tom
Hanks and his Army squad have risked their lives trudging across
Europe in search of one woebegone GI. When they meet Pvt. James
Ryan, he flashes such a gleaming, toothy grin that the audience
starts reaching for its sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the moment is about actor Matt Damon and his Hollywood
cosmetic dentist, not the story Steven Spielberg wants to tell.
</P>
<P>
   It happens time and again in the movies. Think of Anthony
Hopkins in The Mask of Zorro, released from a squalid prison after
two decades but sporting perfect white choppers. Think of Leonardo
DiCaprio, with anachronistically bleached teeth as the man behind
that Iron Mask. And didn't anyone in Les Miserables' revolutionary
France have miserable molars?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly when dentists go to the movies they notice these
things. West Palm Beach, Florida, cosmetic and general dentist
Vincent Dolce says World War II soldiers would never have sparkling
teeth, ``even though they're young. But obviously when you're on
the screen, they make them whiter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you can see when they're a little too phony,'' agrees Dr.
Peter Ciporkin of West Palm Beach, a member of the American Academy
of Cosmetic Dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is a mistake, Ciporkin sees it as a plus for
dentists. ``It does make people much more aware. It's almost as if
the smile is a stage, where the lips are the curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   It has only been about a decade since such blinding white teeth
have been readily available, notes Palm Beach Gardens dental
hygienist Beverly Meares, so those are probably cinema boo-boos
borne of actor vanity. There is actually a tooth color known in the
trade as Hollywood White, but Meares adds, ``We discourage that,
because we don't think it looks natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone in Los Angeles, Saving Private Ryan make-up
artist Lois Burwell, an Academy Award winner, was a little startled
by the subject, but she nevertheless defends Damon's dental look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he should be the archetypal home-spun boy,'' she
says. ``I think people would notice more if he didn't have bright
white teeth. And after all, he is the youngest brother, only 19, so
he could well have such good teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Diaz, who designed the make-up for The Mask of Zorro, says
that teeth color is just one consideration. ``It depends on what
kind of character it is. When we shot the prison scene, all the
slaves and all the prisoners we tried to put coloring on their
teeth to make them gray and yellow and brown.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about Hopkins' teeth? ``Oh, he had his own make-up
artist,'' answers Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if there aren't ways to dull and discolor teeth for
dramatic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically drinking coffee and Coke will darken them,'' says
West Palm dentist Dolce. ``And there are stains you could put on if
you were doing a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could create a customized look over someone's natural
teeth,'' adds Ciporkin. ``They could have the simulation of
discoloration, broken down teeth, cavities, gum disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Meares has a less expensive suggestion. ``They could suck on a
tea bag,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1038EDT &QL; 
