 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
August 8, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   FLAMURDER-TALE _ HOBE SOUND, Fla. _ Thirty years have now passed
and officials have long since concluded ``Trapper'' Nelson's death
was a suicide. Some still swear it was murder. (Houck, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NET-COPS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The next arrest of a family violence
suspect may be just a mouse click away. The Austin, Texas, Police
Department is posting the names and descriptions of hundreds of
suspects charged with family violence on its Web page, hoping that
neighbors, friends or co-workers of victims of abuse may turn in a
suspect who has eluded the police. (Copelin, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-DEED-DR _ This story is rated G. It contains no violence or
sex scandals or gut-wrenching tragedy. It is just the tale of a
good deed, one of many that usually go unnoticed _ and certainly
don't make headlines _ while we go about our busy, private lives.
Denis Samson, 69, is getting a hip replacement. (Fuchs, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KID-SLEEP _ Let's face it. Bedtime is relaxed during summer
vacation. Kids stay up late; kids sleep late. Parents of teen-agers
know this better than anyone. To avoid the knock-down, drag-out
fights, start today to get children back into a routine that will
head off the early morning struggles to get them out of bed and to
school on time. (Gandara, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ When it was first announced we would
be getting HOV lanes on the freeways in metro Atlanta, I was less
than impressed. I have since changed my opinion. When I have had
the opportunity, I have found them to be not only efficient, but
stress-reducing. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) l, f. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-DRIVE _ ATLANTA -- Less than 10 years after it was
introduced as a 1990 model, the midsize Chevrolet Lumina sedan is
one of the vehicles reportedly headed for the ax if General Motors
carries out the talked-about thinning of its product line. Here are
four reasons it's been tagged a ``blue light'' special, a ``best
buy'' and a car that ``does most things adequately, but
unexceptionally.'' (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) l, f.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC _ ATLANTA -- For the past couple of weeks I have been
addressing the issue of fuel octane as it relates to engine
requirements. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) l, f. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ Lee May gardening column. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   YES _ While Jon Anderson said he doesn't look for pop hits, Yes
is no stranger to them. The group estimates its sales at 30 million
albums in 30 years, a figure Anderson finds staggering. At its most
mainstream, the group's 1983 album 90125 sold more than 3 million
copies, spurred by the hit Owner of a Lonely Heart. (Engelhardt,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   2GOOD-TEETH _ When dentists go to the movies they notice these
things. West Palm Beach, Florida, cosmetic and general dentist
Vincent Dolce says World War II soldiers would never have sparkling
teeth, ``even though they're young. But obviously when you're on
the screen, they make them whiter.'' (Erstein, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   SWAMP-FIRES _ The wildfires that roared through Georgia's famed
Okefenokee National Wildlife Refuge a few weeks ago scorched 5,100
acres of swampland. What a shame, some people said. But fire is one
of Mother Nature's major tools for maintaining the health of many
ecosystems such as the Okefenokee, which needr an occasional burn.
``If fires burned every inch of the Okefenokee, it would be good
for it,'' says Ron Phernetton, a fire management officer there.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   VACATION-CHURCH _ While churches cut back services for summer,
combine Sunday School classes and take a break from mid-week
activities, at the resorts and lakes from the mountains to the
coast, people are finding ways to worship. An example: a boat
church with a pulpit on a pier so that people can come in their
boats. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOXWORTHY-FAITH _ We all know comedian Jeff Foxworthy is funny
and a redneck. But now he wants people to also know he's a son of
the South coming back to his roots and a child of God coming back
to his faith. (Hannigan, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DCTALK _ Most music fans know DC Talk through their music. Their
last album, ``Jesus Freak,'' went platinum and netted the trio a
Grammy Award for best rock gospel album. Yet few people know about
the group's public campaign to promote racial unity. This
interracial trio created the ERACE (Eliminating Racism and Creating
Equality) Foundation last year to promote what they call ``living
integration.'' I talk to DC Talk member Toby McKeehan about their
campaign. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
