<SLUG> BC-GOOD-DEED-DR08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE KINDNESS OF STRANGERS: A host of folks helps man who needs
hip replacement
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This story is rated G.
</P>
<P>
   It contains no violence or sex scandals or gut-wrenching
tragedy. It is just the tale of a good deed, one of many that
usually go unnoticed _ and certainly don't make headlines _ while
we go about our busy, private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Samson, 69, is getting a hip replacement.
</P>
<P>
   This might not sound like a big deal, but to Samson, a man from
Haiti who has spent the past 35 years working odd jobs in the
Bahamas so he could send money home to his family, it is a small
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Samson is in pain. The bone in his left hip is covered with
cysts, and the joint isn't doing its job. He walks slowly, jerking
his left leg into step with his right. He is too poor to pay for
surgery, and he doesn't have insurance.
</P>
<P>
   So Dr. Andrew Seltzer, one of many local doctors and surgeons
who routinely donate their services, is going to operate on his hip
for free. The hip replacement usually costs $3,500 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   With a word from Seltzer, Palms West Hospital in Loxahatchee is
also going to waive the $8,770 cost of his stay. And the families
Samson worked for in the Bahamas are taking up a collection to pay
for his prosthesis, which will cost another $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now, how did this Haitian man living on the island of Eleuthera
come to meet the American surgeon?
</P>
<P>
   Ask 85-year-old Jim Griffin of West Palm Beach. He's the one who
brought the two together; he's fond of doing good deeds of the
international variety.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Griffin embarked on a two-year letter-writing campaign
to help a former South Vietnamese army colonel emigrate to America.
The colonel had spent the previous 12 years as a political prisoner
in a hard-labor camp after the North Vietnamese took over his
country.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin sponsored the colonel's whole family and helped them
settle in Florida. He is, after all, a retired car salesman and
retired U.S. Army major: When it comes to helping a friend, he can
be very resourceful _ and he usually gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   One of Griffin's best friends was a British businessman named
George Elcock, who lived with his beautiful wife in a big,
five-bedroom house in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Elcock was a tall, elegant man. He always wore an ascot around
his neck, and he partied with the few socialites who lived on rural
Eleuthera until he died _ land rich but cash poor _ at the age of
94.
</P>
<P>
   He was a character. Legend has it that he once owned a castle
and lived next-door to the British queen. He pinched his pennies
but somehow lived ``royally,'' says Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   And he thought Denis Samson ``was God's gift to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Haitian man with the shy smile worked for Elcock
for 36 years. Samson had come to the Bahamas at age 33 to earn
enough money to feed his family _ a wife and four children _ when
the rope factory he worked for in Haiti closed.
</P>
<P>
   Find work he did. He was so handy, recalls Griffin, that the
landowners in the Bahamas were ``always fussing over him, trying to
get him to work for them.'' He could build things, tend the garden,
fix the plumbing and electricity _ always with a twinkling eye and
that modest smile.
</P>
<P>
   But Samson was most loyal to Elcock. He followed the British
businessman from Nassau to Eleuthera in '63. And three decades
later, when a car accident had crippled Samson, leaving him unfit
for vigorous manual labor, Elcock invited him to move in. Elcock's
wife had died, and the elderly man needed companionship and help
around the house. He was nearly 90 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Samson was grateful. In exchange for room and board, he did
chores, cooked and drove Elcock to the parties he loved so much. He
was also known for fixing a good, stiff gin and tonic, Elcock's
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, George Elcock died. He left his many
properties to his wife's nephews (the couple had no children) and
$2,000 to Samson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I miss him plenty,'' Samson says. ``He was very nice to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Elcock's death, the executor of his estate sent a
letter to Elcock's friends. ``At this point in time,'' the letter
read, ``Denis (Samson) is employed as a caretaker of George's
house. ... However, when the house is sold, it will be difficult to
find employment for him. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Please join me in making a donation to Denis as a memorial to
George. I am sure George would approve. Who knows _ we may get a
good start toward that operation!''
</P>
<P>
   So the old Eleuthera social circle sent some food and money to
Denis Samson. A friend with a plane even flew him to Nassau to see
a doctor. But after almost two years, the estate's executor, David
Salter, managed to collect only $1,000. Salter tried to find a
doctor who would do the surgery for free or at a reduced price but
had no luck.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few months ago, he got a call from old can-do Jim
Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of his longtime friend, Griffin asked the surgeon who
replaced his own ailing hips to help. He came to the right place.
The surgeon, Dr. Andrew Seltzer, says he takes care of an indigent
patient without insurance every day. Two years ago, Seltzer and his
partners won a Legal Aid Society award for their charity work.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent examination, Seltzer determined that Denis Samson
indeed needed a new hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all abnormal, it's just bone on bone here,'' Seltzer
explains, pointing to Samson's x-ray.
</P>
<P>
   Samson has a slight build and appears frail next to the burly
doctor. He listens quietly and doesn't ask any questions. No, he
isn't afraid of the operation _ he's been through enough already:
two months in traction after the car accident, his leg broken in
three places.
</P>
<P>
   He grins at the mention of no more pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you sit up, sir,'' says the doctor, ``and let me
show you what we're going to do ...''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all there is to this good-deed story, for now. Samson
still awaits a happy ending: a new hip and a new life, with a grown
daughter and three grandchildren, who now live in Boca Raton. (That
is, if his application ever winds through immigration.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, when this lifelong worker gets his strength back, he'll
look for a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
