<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Theoretically it shouldn't be that hard to carve out a
half-hour to take a walk or go to the gym. '
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breaking free from the chains . . . for at least a half-hour
</P>
<P>
   My friend Janet doesn't ask for much in life. No Club Med
vacations, no diamond tiaras. On this particular morning, all she
wants is a little time for herself. Maybe a morning exercise class.
``That wouldn't make me a bad mom, would it?''
</P>
<P>
   She works part time and knows she's lucky to spend as much time
as she does with her boys, ages almost 3 and 11 months, but still
she worries. ``This is one more place I'm going to leave them, if I
take them to the nursery.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically it shouldn't be that hard to carve out a half-hour
to take a walk or go to the gym. Yet despite countless resolutions,
my son was 6 before I started exercising regularly again.
</P>
<P>
   You can find me among the non-spandex crowd at a morning
aerobics class at the downtown YMCA. You can see it in our faces,
in the guilty glee with which we grab weights and mats. This is
more than a workout. It's an oasis.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than the sweat equity, we need an hour in which we can
say, ``This is for me. My health, my well-being matter, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody says that, of course. We keep up with each others' kids,
jobs, sprained ankles. We trust our instructor, Kathleen Aughe,
never to ask, ``Can you feel that burn?'' Like all good social
clubs, our class has a secret language, in which phrases like ``bow
pulls'' and ``farmers'' and ``monkeys'' have a precise and logical
meaning. We even have what I've decided is our theme song. We
perform a fast-moving routine that feels like flying as Trisha
Yearwood croons:
</P>
<P>
   I'm the one they all depend on, Sensible, predictable, and
strong But every now and then, I feel like I've played that role
too long.
</P>
<P>
   You sing it, sister!
</P>
<P>
   I need to rock the boat,
</P>
<P>
   I need to speak my mind
</P>
<P>
   Just this once let it all unwind.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, I'm so revved up I turn the wrong way and almost
bump into the woman next to me.
</P>
<P>
   I wanna go too far, I wanna go too fast
</P>
<P>
   Somebody draw the line so I can blow right past
</P>
<P>
   I wanna spend too much, I wanna stay too late
</P>
<P>
   I'm gonna roar too loud, I'm gonna be that way
</P>
<P>
   I wanna play too hard, I wanna go too far.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the song ends, I'm ready to save the world or go on
a shopping spree, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, reality intrudes. When we start our floor exercises, our
kids creep out from the nursery, making tents out of mats, showing
off with dumbbells like undernourished Popeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back to work, or back home with the kids, back to the
world where everybody's timetable is more important than our own.
We're grownups, after all, and that's the way it's supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Janet hasn't started working out yet, but she has bought her
running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   They're a symbol, and a promise. One day, she'll take the time
to exercise, to go inside herself and think. ``It's putting
priority on yourself. I'm always taking care of the kids, taking
care of the house, spending time with my husband _ which is a
delight, of course _ but time for yourself always comes last. Even
the 15 minutes at night when I read a book are so precious.''
</P>
<P>
   The more stressed out you are, the more you need the outlet, the
harder it is to find the time. But just you wait. One of these
days, we'll break free. We wanna spend too much, we wanna stay too
late, we wanna roar too loud, we wanna go too far.
</P>
<P>
   At least for that one hour in aerobics class.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty is a staff writer for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail her at mary_mccartycoxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
