<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walk to school? No way, not nowadays!
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I did not have to walk to school barefoot six miles in the snow,
uphill both ways but during the first few years of my education,
unless it was raining, I hoofed it about six blocks to Marlin
Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   School starts for two of my children this week, and I regret
that they and their older sister have not had that same experience
and the camaraderie that went with it.
</P>
<P>
   Since the neighborhood I grew up in was alive with youngsters, I
always had lots of company going to and from school. Big sisters in
junior high, older cousins in high school and bratty younger
neighbor kids. We'd all tromp off down Earl Street, through the
parking lot of the Safeway and then across Live Oak Street. Live
Oak was part of Texas 7, the highway that separated Marlin into the
predominantly white northern half and the rest of us on the south
side.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'd cross a vacant lot by the lumber yard, go down the
sidewalk (remember sidewalks?) by the First Methodist Church, past
the office of the doctor who delivered me (good guy!), then a
couple more blocks and we were in the school yard.
</P>
<P>
   We were a lively bunch: the Pecina kids, sprinkled with the
Duartes, Palacios, Melendez and Garcias. Our overprotective mothers
felt quite comfortable letting their chicks out of their sight as
long as we stuck together.
</P>
<P>
   My older sister abandoned us when she got to high school to ride
with our older cousins in their souped-up cars. However, she was
forgiven when she turned 16 and began hauling us in our family's
station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Then she graduated, and we were afoot again. Sometime during my
seventh grade year, the school district decided to stop fighting
full integration so the next year the younger kids and I attended
what had been the Booker T. Washington campus. It was a couple of
miles from our house and too long a walk, our parents determined.
</P>
<P>
   My aunt took on driving duties. I remember sitting in the back
seat giggling with my cousins because Aunt Elvira didn't take too
well to backing up. Her method was to place one foot firmly on the
gas pedal and the other just as firmly on the brake, put the car in
reverse and maintain the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the gas pedal would win and _ with a jolt _ we would
be on our way.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the mode of transportation, the company was good and
loud and the bonds formed in the barrio still hold. In fact,
there's talk of a reunion of the neighbor kids.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that my own children have had such boring trips to
and from school, parents hauling them in a car one way and then
back again.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's something I miss doing for them.
</P>
<P>
   I also miss the days when I was allowed, on the first day of
school, to actually accompany them to their classrooms. Last year,
my then sixth grade son directed my husband and me to ``just drop
me off at the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Than last week, I was politely told by my 16-year-old daughter
that I didn't have to go to registration with her. ``Can you just
write the checks?'' And our college student will fly solo back to
Massachusetts for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Do I feel rejected? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good mother, I'm plotting revenge but I may have to
wait a few years. The only thing I can come up with is making them
drop me off a block away from the nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
