A2667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YES08-COX     08-07 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yes still saying no to being pigeonholed after 30 years
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jon Anderson, whose lyrics for the rock group Yes offer up
dreamy love scenes full of fantasy, has a feisty side.
</P>
<P>
   At least when the record company demands more commercial hits
from the band known for intricate, drawn-out works.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to call me Napoleon,'' Anderson said last week from
an Austin, Texas, hotel room. ``They still do sometimes. I get
feisty about being penned in. I'm into more things than trying to
become a commercial star.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, with lead singer Anderson and mainstays Chris Squire on
bass and Steve Howe on lead guitar, plays Saturday at the Coral Sky
Amphitheater, the final stop on the group's U.S. tour.
</P>
<P>
   While Anderson said he doesn't look for pop hits, Yes is no
stranger to them. The group estimates its sales at 30 million
albums in 30 years, a figure Anderson finds staggering.
</P>
<P>
   At its most mainstream, the group's 1983 album 90125 sold more
than 3 million copies, spurred by the hit Owner of a Lonely Heart.
But the group has mostly thrived on a hard-driving, artistic sound
that grew out of the electric rock of the 1960s. From 1971 to 1974,
Yes made four 1-million selling albums, with Fragile, featuring the
group's trademark hit Roundabout, selling 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to become more than just a popular band,'' Anderson
said. ``When you get a success, you start thinking, `I don't want
to waste this. I want to invest in it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since 90125, the group has shifted personnel often,
as it continued to cut albums, none reaching the audience of its
earlier days. The group's current makeup includes 1970s drummer
Alan White; new member Billy Sherwood, doing vocals, guitar and
keyboards; and Moscow's Igor Khoroshev on keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   While the group prides itself on musicianship, always at its
center is Anderson's voice, a hypnotic blend of soothing pitch and
revealing clarity.
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson, 53, music comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never remember a day going by when I wasn't singing when
I was a little nipper,'' he said. Growing up in the English
countryside he mimicked the Everly Brothers and Bobby Vee. He
remembers first holding a microphone at age 11, and liking it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't turn back. At 16, he played in a band, the Warriors.
In 1963, as the Beatles made it big in London, the Warriors
followed their path, hitting the hard-edged German club circuit.
Anderson returned to London in 1967 and a year later met Squire.
They formed Yes with Peter Banks, Tony Kaye and Bill Bruford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would get past 1974,'' Anderson said.
``People would say Close to the Edge (a million-selling 1972
release) will be remembered in 10 years' time. I would say, `I
don't think so.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's 1998, and the album's 18-minute title song still remains on
the group's play list, featuring Anderson's favorite lyric.
</P>
<P>
   ``And space between the focus shape ascend knowledge of love.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a reference, he said, to the spaces between things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that we don't see anything as we should. What we see
are the spaces between, which is the most wonderful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
