<P>
   SWAMP-FIRES _ The wildfires that roared through Georgia's famed
Okefenokee National Wildlife Refuge a few weeks ago scorched 5,100
acres of swampland. What a shame, some people said. But fire is one
of Mother Nature's major tools for maintaining the health of many
ecosystems such as the Okefenokee, which needs an occasional burn.
``If fires burned every inch of the Okefenokee, it would be good
for it,'' says Ron Phernetton, a fire management officer there.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
