<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAMURDER-TALE08-COX     08-07 1837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMURDER-TALE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trapper Nelson: Wild man of Loxahatchee
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOBE SOUND, Fla. _ The scene was gruesome by the time John
DuBois found his friend's body on July 30, 1968. Adjacent to the
serene Loxahatchee River and under a hammock that swung in the
shade of a Seminole-style chickee hut, DuBois arrived to see Victor
Nelson face down on the sandy ground.
</P>
<P>
   His ribcage was torn open by a shotgun blast at close range, and
raccoons, insects and guinea hens had picked at Nelson's corpse for
about a week. The stench was so fierce, his autopsy was conducted
outdoors instead of at Martin Memorial Hospital. His ashes were
later scattered on the river.
</P>
<P>
   Dying at the end of a loaded gun, his remains devoured by
animals, was an ironic end for a man who made his living harvesting
the thousands of pelts and hides of the rabbits, raccoons, possums
and alligators he shot and trapped.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years have now passed and officials have long since
concluded ``Trapper'' Nelson's death was a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Some still swear it was murder.
</P>
<P>
   His mysterious death at age 59 only added to the intrigue of
Trapper Nelson. This, according to historians, newspaper accounts,
friends and family, is his story:
</P>
<P>
   Born Victor Nostokovich in Trenton, N.J., in 1908, Nelson was
the son of Polish immigrants. He left home after his mother died
and his father remarried. The boy hopped a freight train heading
west, taking with him money he had earned trapping muskrats in the
New Jersey marshes.
</P>
<P>
   Nostokovich went to Colorado first, then to Mexico, where he was
arrested for gunrunning. Released from jail, he caught a freight
train east and eventually wound up in the Jupiter area in the late
1920s. Along the way, he adopted the name Nelson as a way of
building a new identity.
</P>
<P>
   The legend holds that from the train, he saw schools of mullet
jumping in the Jupiter Inlet and decided to stay because he'd never
go hungry with all that food in the water, said Robert Schuh,
ranger at Jonathan Dickinson State Park, which now encompasses
Nelson's homestead.
</P>
<P>
   With his stepbrother, Charles, and a friend named James Dykas,
Nelson set up a camp near Jupiter Inlet and began trapping. But the
three partners didn't get along. One morning in December 1931,
Charles shot Dykas in the head as the man made breakfast while
Nelson _ who had now acquired the nickname ``Trapper'' _ was away
from camp tending to a trap line.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Victor were jailed, but Victor chose to testify
against his stepbrother. The testimony helped convict Charles and
send him away for a life term at Raiford prison in North Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Disillusioned with partnerships, people and civilization in
general, Nelson set up a camp deep in a wooded area along the
Loxahatchee River, about 5 miles west of U.S. 1. in what is now
Jonathan Dickinson State Park. _ _ The place was a paradise for
him. Mostly he lived off the land, skinning raccoons and cooking
the carcasses. Gopher tortoises were chopped into stew, Schuch
said.
</P>
<P>
   A strapping man at 6-feet-2-inches and about 240 pounds, he
thrived on hard work, planting fruit trees and pineapples and
chopping cords of wood routinely for exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson would get up at about 6:30 each morning to check the trap
lines behind his house and farther north in Kitchen Creek. He'd
spend the morning hunting and working and then take it easy in the
early afternoon before resuming work again later. Trips to town in
his trucks were infrequent, but he'd use the occasion to stock up
on supplies and pick up copies of The Wall Street Journal, which
he'd devour, line by line.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Celmer III, Nelson's great-nephew, thinks of him as a
``gentle giant'' who worked hard and liked to have his own space.
Celmer, 53, now lives in Waretown, N.J., but spent summers as a
teen working at Nelson's homestead. He remembers ``Uncle Nelson''
as someone who was as content to sit and listen to the sounds of
nature as he was to tell stories of his travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a hermit; he liked people,'' Celmer said. ``But he
liked them to go, too, when it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard work was a given, but discipline was at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For big thrills, we'd take his Jeep into town and go get a
pint of ice cream _ a pint for each of us,'' he said. ``When you're
13, and you get to eat a whole pint of ice cream, you're a pretty
happy kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The normal diet around camp consisted of gruel _ usually, a
combination of oatmeal and turtle, with rice and pepper. Sometimes
there would be fried fish. Pancakes were a mixed blessing, since
weevils infested the flour, making for some crunchy flapjacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he'd bring back a burlap bag filled with doughnuts
that were covered with ants,'' he said. ``He'd tell us to just
shake them off. He wasn't too fussy about what he ate.'' _ _ Nelson
spent money made from his skins and pelts buying more land,
according to the book ``The Life of the Loxahatchee River'' by
Bessie Wilson DuBois, wife of John DuBois, a longtime friend of
Nelson's who owned a fish camp near Jupiter Inlet. After the
Depression, many land owners were unable to pay their taxes, and
Nelson was eager to scoop their properties up for a song at the tax
sales. By buying land _ sometimes for only a few dollars an acre _
Nelson built his property into an 858-acre oasis.
</P>
<P>
   To support himself and pay the taxes on his land holdings,
Nelson set up a zoo in the early 1950s near the river, with
handmade buildings hewn from the hard core of the slash pine. He
arranged for boat captains from West Palm Beach to bring tourists 7
miles up river to have lunch in the wild and view the bobcats,
raccoons, possums, alligators and snakes. On some days, hundreds
would tour the property and buy a souvenir orchid or handmade
trinket.
</P>
<P>
   Always the survivor, Nelson knew how to con his way into a free
lunch. Occasionally, he'd scout out the ritziest picnic table and
go hang a harmless indigo snake around the necks of a diner or two.
Appetites ruined, he'd help himself to their food.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also liked to go scoop up a tortoise, cut off its head,
pour the blood into a cup and drink it,'' Schuh said. ``He made out
real good foodwise that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Socialites from Palm Beach _ the Kennedys included, Celmer said
_ would visit by boat for a taste of wild Florida. Heavyweight
boxing champion Gene Tunney once remarked that Nelson's burly hands
made his own look feminine by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the Army took a huge hunk of his land to
create Camp Murphy. Nelson was drafted into service, first
stationed in Texas and then at Camp Murphy. He married briefly as a
ploy to avoid service but later divorced. He never had children.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the war, his zoo was in shambles. He tried to
rebuild, but by the late '50s, life began to unravel. He spent much
of his time fending off property taxes and worrying about lawsuits
from the visitors who would take a plunge into the river from his
rope swing or try to walk across the top of the alligator cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``About one drunk every year would fall into the gator cage,''
Celmer said.
</P>
<P>
   After a state health agency closed his zoo _ citing unsanitary
conditions and safety hazards from the snakes _ Nelson's demeanor
changed. He locked the gate on the dirt road that led to his
compound. He posted signs that read, ``Danger. Land mines. No
trespassing.'' He felled trees across the river to block pleasure
boaters from reaching his docks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he closed the zoo permanently. Visitors first had to
write for permission to enter his property, and not all were
allowed. His mood soured further as he saw friends become ill with
cancer. He obsessed that he, too, would be riddled with the
disease, since he had a touchy stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Debilitating sickness was the last thing on Earth he would
endure, he told his friends and relatives in a matter-of-fact tone.
``He told people that if he couldn't take care of himself, he'd do
himself in,'' Schuh said. _ _ In August 1968, it took an hour of
deliberation for a six-man Martin County coroner's jury to declare
Nelson's death a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The jury listened as John DuBois testified that Nelson
complained of ill health prior to his death. Others said he
suffered from stomach pains and expressed distrust of doctors,
telling friends that he would never be operated on. Problems with
his prostate gland forced him to use a catheter.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County Deputy Sheriff Slater Grose, who investigated the
death, told the jury Nelson apparently put the butt of the shotgun
in the sand, placed the gun barrel to his chest and pulled the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   But some things didn't make sense. Nelson had always said that
if he decided to kill himself, he'd pull in his lines so no animals
would die in unattended traps. The day he was found, his traps were
still set. Also, most people who use guns to commit suicide shoot
themselves in the head or mouth with a handgun, not in the torso
with a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fact he was due to arrive at DuBois' fish
camp near the inlet to meet a friend he hadn't seen in 30 years.
When his body was found, Nelson was dressed as if he was going to a
social occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Could it have been accidental? Possibly. Nelson kept a gun at
his side at all times, even hiding it in a rack behind the
headboard of a bed in a guest cabin he built. Maybe, Schuh
surmises, Nelson stumbled out of his hammock at the chickee hut and
fell awkwardly on the trigger. It would explain those reports that
said the gun was found dozens of feet away, not next to the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had just shot yourself and knew how far away help was,
wouldn't you be frustrated enough to take the gun and just fling it
in anger?'' Schuh said. ``Maybe so.''
</P>
<P>
   But some suspected murder, Schuh said. Trapper Nelson made a lot
of people angry.
</P>
<P>
   There was the neighbor whose goats Nelson was accused of killing
with explosives in a fit of revenge. There were the many land
owners who forfeited their property, only to see Nelson buy it for
a pittance. There were the people he chased off his land in later
years with gunshots fired into the air. There were the husbands of
the Palm Beach socialites who sometimes took refuge at his property
for days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was his stepbrother, Charles. His life sentence
was believed to be a 35-year term, but no records have been found
indicating whether he died in prison or was paroled. Thirty-five
years, Schuh said. If he was paroled, it would have put it right at
about the year 1968. Interesting coincidence, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   But Celmer says he has no doubts that his Uncle Nelson took his
own life. It's just what he would have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really miss the guy,'' he said. ``To this day, I still get
emotional about him . . . He was sort of a hero to me . . . very
intelligent . . . He just made a lot of sense about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
