<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KID-SLEEP08-COX     08-07 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-SLEEP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get kids on schedule before school starts
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Let the battles begin.
</P>
<P>
   The start of school is a few days away and parental dread is
setting in. Hint: It's not the part about shooing children out the
door; it's getting them up on time so they leave the house fed,
clothed, materials in hand and with a smile. Actually, maybe the
smiling part is pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. Bedtime is relaxed during summer vacation. Kids
stay up late; kids sleep late. Parents of teen-agers know this
better than anyone. When school rolls around and routines are out
of whack, parents get impatient and kids become irritable. It's
fertile ground for disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Brown knows what's at stake. The Leander woman says she
has a ``hellacious'' time with her children, 6, 9 and 11. ``I
reeeeally don't look forward to getting them back on schedule,''
she says. ``It's always such a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the knock-down, drag-out fights, start today to get
children back into a routine that will head off the early morning
struggles to get them out of bed and to school on time.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's family is the sign of the times. The kids have a
different bedtime at her ex-husband's house where they stay every
other weekend. She works late and the sitter can't always get her
children to bed on time. There is a lot of inconsistency. ``That's
what I'm up against and every year it takes us at least a month to
settle in. I reeeeally dread it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not always external forces that disrupt kids' sleeping
patterns during the summer. Parents are to blame, too. Go to a
restaurant, bowling alley, movie theater or mall, and you see kids
staying up late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see that all the time,'' says Brown. ``But you know what? If
I'm seeing it, I'm doing it, too. I guess with busy schedules we
try to fit so much stuff in.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Morton, who teaches first grade at Anderson Mill
Elementary School, says she can count on some children coming to
school sleepy at the start of the school year. What's worse,
parents don't fully understand what that means.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of sleep and lack of a routine affects their behavior
and concentration,'' she says. ``They daydream, get cranky and
don't perform. Their tempers flare.''
</P>
<P>
   When children doze off in her class, she says, she allows them
to sleep. `To wake them wouldn't accomplish much. Sleepy kids
complain about tummy and headaches. When I send them to the nurse's
office I get a note back that they slept for 30 minutes. They are
just exhausted,'' Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   It only takes one or two kids to affect the entire classroom.
She ends up going over lessons more than once, which slows down the
other children.
</P>
<P>
   So what can be done about it? Start establishing a routine today
so everyone is ready for Day One.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Kvols, author of ``Redirecting Children's Behavior,''
suggests reeling in children, teens included, at least a week
before school starts. ``With little ones, wake them up 5 to 10
minutes earlier each day. You should reach your target time at
least two days before school starts. This means that on the other
end, the kids need to go to bed a little earlier each night,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests giving teen-agers more say. ``You need to ask them
what they need to get ready for school. The answers will come from
them. They will be less rebellious and more cooperative if they
have a say,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kvols tells parents to approach a bedtime routine by looking at
it from a child's point of view. ``Imagine if you were in the
middle of a good book and your spouse says that it's time for bed.
In spite of your response that you're not ready, you are helped
unwillingly up the stairs, your clothes are removed and you are
forced into taking a bath. Consider how you are feeling. Are you
feeling disrespected, violated, angry or controlled?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's her advice for parents of young children. Some aspects
can be applied to older ones.
</P>
<P>
   Respect your own needs. ``Take care of yourself during the day
so you are not feeling hassled or frazzled at your child's
bedtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Start one hour before the child's actual bedtime to avoid
unnecessary stress and struggle. ``This is winding-down time.
Eliminate roughhousing, tickling or stimulating TV programs. This
just gets them more excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Offer choices instead of orders. ``Your child will have a
feeling of control over what happens to him when given choices. For
example, 'Do you want your Dad to help you with your bath or me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Create a bedtime ritual with your child's help. ``Read a story,
snuggle and give them stuffed animals to kiss. Then, give them a
hug and two kisses and leave the room singing a song.''
</P>
<P>
   Create closeness. ``Say three things that you love about each
other. Start each statement with 'What I love about you is...'
Listen to your child's feelings about the day. Ask questions which
allow your child to share more about himself, such as, 'What was
the best happy thing that happened to you today?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Kvols says bedtime needs to be a time of nurturing, closeness,
shared communication and fun. ``By involving your children in the
decision-making process and spending this special time with them,
they will feel valued and respected,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
