<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heed owner's manual suggestion on gas
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For the past couple of weeks I have been addressing
the issue of fuel octane as it relates to engine requirements. This
discussion was prompted by Dave Grosmann's question:
</P>
<P>
   ``I purchased a 1998 Buick Regal GS, which has a GM 3800 series
II, supercharged V-6 engine. The manual calls for premium gas. The
same engine without a supercharger uses regular. The salesperson
told me that I could use regular if I didn't have any pinging or
run-on, which I don't. Am I doing the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, no, not if you want the maximum performance from
that engine. If you're not concerned about the power this engine
configuration was designed to deliver, why in the world did you
fork out the extra cash for a supercharger?
</P>
<P>
   The reason your owner's manual specifies high-octane fuel is
because the supercharger raises the compression pressure, which
results in more power from the engine. The higher the compression
pressure, the more heat produced and the greater the octane needed.
Premium fuel is formulated to meet this demand. Regular fuel is
not. You might not hear your engine pinging when you mash the
accelerator, but your engine's knock sensor does.
</P>
<P>
   Engine knock (ping) occurs when the air/fuel mixture ignites
prematurely in the combustion chamber. This condition occurs when
the heat of compression starts the combustion process before the
timed ignition of the spark plug. What follows is a collision of
the two flame fronts inside the combustion chamber, resulting in an
uncontrolled ``explosion.'' Performance diminishes, emissions
increase and piston damage begins.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, automobile manufacturers have incorporated
a device into their computer-controlled engine management systems
to alleviate pinging. The ``knock sensor'' senses the sound
frequency produced by this engine condition before it is audible to
the driver. The computer cannot control the spontaneous ignition
caused by the compression heat, but it can eliminate the colliding
flame front produced by the spark plug. It accomplishes this by
delaying the spark, referred to as retarding the spark timing.
Although power is sacrificed, emissions and engine damage are
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The knock sensor normally functions during the onset of
acceleration when ping would be most prevalent; however, I suspect
in your case, it is working overtime. To complicate the situation,
many late-model computers use an adaptive learning strategy
technology that actually ``adapts'' the computer's engine commands
to a driver's individual driving technique. Your use of regular
fuel could have caused your car's computer to permanently
compensate for the continual power loss, and it may need to be
evaluated and possibly reset by your dealer's service department.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is start running a good quality premium fuel.
Don't cheap out and buy the bargain gasoline, or you'll end up with
a whole load of other problems. Read and believe your owner's
manual. If you're not prepared to follow the manufacturer's
prescription for fuel and maintenance for that vehicle, trade it
for a more conservative model. Both you and the car will be
happier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-06-98 1621E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
