really intended for motor homes pulling boats at 45 mph? Or, if you
aren't going to keep up with the flow of traffic in the adjoining
lanes, should you be allowed to create a roadblock in the HOV lane?
</P>
<P>
   One morning, I observed an officer ticketing a young woman for
traveling illegally in the HOV lane. As he wrote, she was putting
on her mascara. Sadly, it is a commentary on how a lot of drivers
perceive the HOV lanes and their regulations. No big deal.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, they ask other motorists to report offenders. I'm
not yet ready for the HOV militia. Rather, I would welcome a
substantial fine for violators and make it progressive. Each repeat
offense doubles the fine. Sooner or later, you will either get
these drivers' attention or they won't have any money left for gas.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, if we are going to have HOV lanes, then they need
to be enforced. Or we should do away with them and have an extra
lane for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-06-98 1623E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
