r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-HNS &LR;      08-07 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMICS 101: THE LESSON BEGINS WITH BACK-TO-SCHOOL SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY GALLES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Parenthood brings with it some inevitable
conflicts with children, a fact now particularly vivid to those
whose kids have been home from school for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you think nothing could get worse than your
end-of-the-summer cabin fever, things get worse. Yes, that's right.
It's time for back to school shopping, that annual pinnacle of
parent-child conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope that understanding will keep some stressed parents
from being pushed ``over the edge'' by the back to school shopping
crisis, consider its economics.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, economics reduces to the proposition that incentives
matter. Either larger benefits or lower costs associated with a
good causes decision-makers to want more of it, even when those
decision-makers are your children whose rationality you currently
question.
</P>
<P>
   This also means that whenever there are large differences in the
costs and/or benefits facing different parties who must jointly
decide on a purchase, disagreements will arise. But that is exactly
the situation in back-to-school shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Consider first who will pick up the tab. A parent paying the
bill for back-to-school clothes, supplies, etc., will weigh the
value they perceive in a good against its entire dollar cost. But
the children are paying none of the bill, so they will be weighing
the value they place on the good against the zero dollar price they
will pay (the relevant price they pay is the cost to them of
wheedling, whining, complaining, blackmailing or arguing their
parents into it, which raises the costs to the parents even more).
</P>
<P>
   Because there are lots of back-to-school things worth less than
their cost to parents but worth more than zero to children,
children want to spend more than their parents do. They want more,
higher quality, and ``cooler'' things, not to mention replacements
sooner. And parents trying to teach their child ``the value of a
dollar'' will have little luck convincing them otherwise, because
it is the parent's, not the child's, money on the line.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a big difference between parents and children on
the benefit side. Parents regard clothing, shoes, backpacks, etc.,
largely for their utilitarian value. But children see those same
things through the lens of where they think those items will put
them in the school pecking order. The result is that parents, who
see many good alternatives to a particular purchase, often end up
fighting with children who, under the enhanced peer pressure of
returning to classes, insist there is no substitute for it, in a
conversation frequently punctuated with, ``You don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-school shopping crisis is often one of the year's
most strident confrontations because of the large gaps between the
values parents and children place on the items in question and the
larger-than-usual amount of money involved. But it does not signify
that your children have suddenly become more ``evil,'' on a
slippery slope to a horrendous future. Rather, it is different in
scale, but not in kind, from many other conflicts that arise out of
the different incentives facing parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   Why are young children more likely to misbehave in a grocery
store checkout line than at home? Because the benefits (candy, gum,
etc.) are higher and the costs are lower (They are less likely to
be punished in public). Why are older children so eager to find an
excuse to borrow Dad's car? Because they get the benefits of
mobility without the costs of paying for it (Do your kids ever put
gas in?).
</P>
<P>
   Why do kids always want to go out to eat, despite the fact that
it costs more? Because it's not their money. Why do they want you
to wash their favorite clothes almost daily? Because it's not their
time and effort. In contrast, why are they so resistant to doing
chores or cleaning their rooms or dishes after dinner? And why do
their parents want them to study more than they want to study?
Because it's their time and effort.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding that the back-to-school shopping crisis is just a
temporary, annual peak in parent-child conflicts will not make them
go away. But it can help parents think about ways to minimize such
conflicts (such as giving children a fixed budget for new clothes
in the fall, which means they are spending their own money, rather
than nagging you to spend yours). And it can help maintain parental
sanity and reduce their despair about what has happened to their
formerly ``good'' children.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gary Galles is a professor of economics at Pepperdine
University in Malibu, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
