r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-SAFE-HNS &LR;      08-07 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SAFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAFE MEN' IS FULL OF GEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the many great things that the amusing ``Safe Men'' has
going for it is that it prominently features my new favorite young
actor, Paul Giamatti.
</P>
<P>
   He played the unpalatable network executive who harassed Howard
Stern in ``Private Parts,'' and he's been terrific in ``The
Negotiator'' and ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' In ``Safe Men,'' he
plays Veal Chop, the hilarious chief henchperson of Big Fat Bernie
Gayle (Michael Lerner), a well known Jewish gangster in Providence,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, Big Fat (whose son is known as Little Big Fat)
sends his less-than-completely competent sub-thug, Veal Chop (it
will give you a hint of this movie's humor to know that Veal Chop
is referred to as Big Fat's ``intern''), to find the best safe
crackers in Providence. But Chop blows the job and brings him what
turn out to be Providence's two worst, and possibly stupidest,
musicians, Eddie (Steve Zahn of ``That Thing You Do'' and
``Suburbia'') and Sam (Sam Rockwell of ``Lawn Dogs'' and ``Box of
Moonlight'').
</P>
<P>
   It's an honest mistake if you're incredibly dumb, which Veal
Chop defiantly is. The real safe crackers are no more impressive
than the dopey musicians. So, dragged to the home of Big Fat, when
Sam and Eddie realize that trying to explain they aren't safe men
will do no good, they give up. Big Fat has a job for them they
can't refuse. Either they become safe men or they die.
</P>
<P>
   The assignment is to crack three safes for Big Fat. The comedy
of errors continues as Sam and Eddie go after the first safe,
belonging to Leo (Harvey Fierstein), a well-to-do fence with a
daughter named Hannah (Christina Kirk) who goes for shady fellows.
When she happens on Sam and Eddie fooling with dad's safe, she
falls immediately for Sam, and politely escorts the burglars out
the door. Soon Hannah and Sam are dating.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is just about perfect. In addition to an inspired
performance by Giamatti, there are gems by Rockwell, Zahn and
Fierstein, and by Lerner, who was so memorable as the studio
executive in ``Barton Fink.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director John Hamburg has a gift for comedy. He also has
a gift for making even the goofiest people seem dignified. Unlike
so many movies that derive their humor from taking a superior
attitude to the characters and their stupidity, Hamburg is a
sympathizer. He never places himself above the people in his movie.
He seems to be right alongside them, rooting for them to triumph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-DEPALMA-     08-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-DEPALMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE CAST, `SNAKE EYES' IS A SLEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian De Palma is a big blustery filmmaker who likes to take his
audience by the lapels and shake it. That can be a good thing, as
when he sends us, via jazzy camera work, on a giddy, 360-degree
park ride.
</P>
<P>
   But it can also be a bad thing, as when he clunkily points the
camera up for unnecessary low angle shots and hangs it from the
ceiling for superfluous high angles, then moves it side to side too
quickly to focus, for no particular reason at all.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he wants to be viewed as an artist of the cinema,
someone with Martin Scorsese's visual grace, but the truth is that
De Palma is less a persuasive artist than he is a simple and vulgar
bully. And as far as I'm concerned, he wins. Based on ``Bonfire of
the Vanities,'' ``Carlito's Way'' and now ``Snake Eyes,'' I am
willing to never see another Brian De Palma movie.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of wonderful actors, Nicolas Cage and Gary Sinise,
and work by a young actress named Carla Gugino, makes ``Snake
Eyes'' watchable, but the movie fails in purely directorial terms.
De Palma ruins a terrific premise by making the kind of elementary
mistake students make in Film 101. He starts at high frenzy. After
a bravura opening 10 minutes, the movie has no place to go but
haywire.
</P>
<P>
   Those opening minutes give us Rick Santoro (Cage), a swaggering
Atlantic City cop with a loud mouth and an iridescent suit. He
wears too much jewelry, he clicks his cigarette lighter a little
too loudly, and he is prone to express himself at the top of his
adrenalin-fueled voice, mostly out of sheer exuberance, but with an
uncontrollable anger bubbling just beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Cage is performing at a ``Leaving Las Vegas'' energy level here,
but as good as he is, you sense a strain. I had a feeling that De
Palma pushed him further than good directing called for. What we
get is a manic portrait of a cop who could never sustain such
behavior in life, and a movie that can not sustain such energy for
98 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is an Atlantic City casino where a heavyweight bout
is scheduled to take place. Fourteen thousand people will cram the
arena to watch the famed Lincoln Tyler (Stan Shaw) fight. In the
minutes before the first round, Rick is strutting through the
stadium screaming his good feelings for all to hear like someone
suffering spasms.
</P>
<P>
   It's all just a show of high spirits, we're supposed to believe.
But when Rick wants to place a bet and the bookmaker demands a cash
outlay, Rick beats up a local perp and relieves him of several
thousand. The money he takes actually has blood on it. Talk about
symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   So that's the setup. Rick is your average, friendly, out-of-his
mind homicide detective with a wife, kid and expensive girlfriend
on the side, and political aspirations. He's on the take and, it
seems, doesn't care who knows it. It seems a bit unlikely, but
cramming this kind of unlikeliness down our throats is what a bully
like De Palma loves to do.
</P>
<P>
   Rick's best buddy is Navy Cmdr. Kevin Dunn, heading a security
detail to protect the secretary of Defense, who is attending the
fight. When the secretary is killed by a sniper, Rick and Kevin
seal off the arena and try to figure out who did it.
</P>
<P>
   Like De Palma's much better movie, ``Blow Out,'' ``Snake Eyes''
is about unraveling a mystery, with ``Blow Out'' using sound
technology as a detection tool and ``Snake Eyes'' using video. But
the truth is that ``Snake Eyes'' reveals its secret so early in the
movie that all tension is drained from the action long before the
supposedly climactic moment arrives.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plot convolutions, perhaps a close reading of the
script would make everything clear, but the explanations sounded
like a lot of mumbo jumbo from where I sat.
</P>
<P>
   Cliches abound. Rick's corrupt nature is meant to determine the
outcome of events, but of course, they merely provide an
opportunity for him to reform. The movie's coda is completely
ridiculous and, worse yet, boring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
