<HEADLINE>
`BILLY' OFFERS QUIRKY SCREEN ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BILLY'S HOLLYWOOD SCREEN TEST 
Written and directed by: Tommy O' Haver 
Starring: Sean P. Hayes, Brad Rowe, Richard Ganoung, Meredith Scott
Lynn, Paul Bartel 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated R (adult situations) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies always make love look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Two sets of eyes meet across a crowded room, and hearts forever
interlock. Couples meet cute in car accidents, exchanging insurance
information and telephone numbers. Between the opening and closing
credits, true romance, no matter how absurd and haphazard, always
finds a way to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who has ever been a soldier in the love wars
knows nothing about affairs of the heart is ever easy _ and that's
what makes Tommy O'Haver's ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' such a
refreshing and smart romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Billy of the title is a young photographer (an ingratiating
Sean P. Hayes) looking for personal and professional stability in
LA. Billy occasionally fools around with hunky Fernando (Armando
Valdes-Kennedy), but Fernando is in a relationship, and Billy's
looking for something _ and someone _ more meaningful. At a local
coffee shop, he first sees Gabriel (the impossibly handsome Brad
Rowe), who has both the name and the face of an angel.
</P>
<P>
   The two immediately click, and Billy invites Gabriel to become a
model for his pet project _ gay recreations of great Hollywood love
scenes such as the famous sand-and-crashing-waves kiss between Burt
Lancaster and Deborah Kerr in ``From Here to Eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy is infatuated to the point of obsession with Gabriel, but
there's one small problem: He's not sure whether Gabriel is gay. He
claims to have a girlfriend back in San Francisco, but how then
does one explain Gabriel's love of ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy hashes out his dilemma with his galpal, George, (Meredith
Scott Lynn), and Perry (Richard Ganoung), both of whom know that
Gabriel, with his easy but genuine charm and good looks, really
isn't good enough for Billy.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is perfect, from Hayes's sweet, lovelorn Billy, to Lynn
as his best girlfriend with more than a few of her own romantic
problems, such as the stoner (a hilarious Carmine Giovinazzo) who
tries to win her heart. Paul Bartel has a couple of slyly funny
scenes as a photographer as famous for his lasciviousness as his
artwork. Rowe makes for an ideal object of affection and creates a
real character from what could have been nothing more than a Colt
magazine pin-up. Rowe looks so much like Brad Pitt that Pitt
practically could sue for copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' never compromises its gay
sensibility _ a trio of drag queens serve as a Greek chorus
throughout the film _ but its astute observations on the unruly
laws of love and attraction are questionably universal. At the
beginning of the film, a card flashes by with the words ``A Tommy
O'Haver Trifle,'' but his debut film is anything but. It's quirky
and funny, but also succeeds as a knowing take on modern romance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
