<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-BOS &LR;      08-07 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LILITH'S FAIR LADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  There is one constant to Lilith Fair _ and her name is Sarah
McLachlan. As the founder and queen of Lilith, she is the only
artist who will perform at all 57 shows this summer. The rest of
the women come and go in a rotating cast, but McLachlan stays and
sets the tone. She jams with many of the acts, she fends off any
media criticism, and she presents charity checks at the daily press
conference. She does everything, it seems, but fix the toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tour director that worries about that,'' she says
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is more of a social one,'' adds McLachlan. ``I'm
singing with people, meeting with people, hanging out. It's a lot
of work, but I've got one of the easier jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lilith tour was hailed as last year's surprisingly hot event
_ and it's done even better this year, expanding to two dates in
many markets. ``The lineup is way stronger this year,'' McLachlan,
30, says with a mixture of pride and authority from a recent tour
stop in Austin, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the bill includes McLachlan, Natalie Merchant, Emmylou
Harris, Lauryn Hill (of the Fugees), Luscious Jackson, Abra Moore,
Syd Straw, and Boston representatives Melissa Ferrick and Laurie
Geltman. (Other tour stops have featured Bonnie Raitt, Indigo
Girls, Erkykah Badu, and Paula Cole.)
</P>
<P>
   At every Lilith date, there are 11 acts in all, spread over
three stages. ``There's a village stage, a B stage, and a main
stage. The village stage is predominantly acoustic and local
performers,'' says McLachlan, a Canadian who now lives in Vancouver
.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, there's been more of an edge to the Lilith lineups
this year; witness a rise in progressive rock acts and rappers
(Queen Latifah and Missy Elliott have been on some bills). All of
which has made this a more expansive festival, versus the
singer-songwriter slant of last year's debut tour. But don't assume
the change comes from any radical philosophical shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to believe it, but we asked all the same people
last year, but many of them didn't know who we were. It's a lot
easier getting artists after we had a successful year,'' says
McLachlan. ``People are coming to us now.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's tour also will double the proceeds to charity causes
_ many of them women's shelters and various outreach programs.
``We'll hopefully give away $1.4 million,'' says McLachlan. ``One
of the fun parts of my day is giving the local charities the check.
It might be like $17,000 from that day. It's a good chunk of money.
A woman Wednesday started bawling. She was saying, `This is my
salary for the year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Lilith grossed $16.4 million, according to Pollstar
magazine, making it more lucrative than the established H.O.R.D.E.
and Lollapalooza festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McLachlan found herself defending the all-female premise
of the tour _ something that she's had to do less of this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is a little easier to deal with, because Lilith is
not so new any more. I mean, I had to justify it every bloody step
of the way last time. I got beaten down by the `why isn't it more
like this?' and `why isn't it more like that?' questions. I just
felt like saying, `Why don't you (expletive) try and do it
yourself. Good luck, it's a lot of work. Hey, we did the best we
could. Like I said, we really tried to get tons of different kinds
of musicians, but we got who we could.''
</P>
<P>
   And forget about published reports that say Lilith may add male
acts to the mix. ``That was was one of those early moments of
weakness from being beaten down by the media,'' says McLachlan. ``I
thought, God, maybe I should make this more equal. ... But no,
definitely not. Lilith is what it is. It's a beautiful thing, so
why change it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're going to do it for three years and then we're
not going to do it anymore,'' she adds. ``We're going to stop and
we're going to reassess things. I don't know what we'll do. We
don't have anything planned at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   She has said that she doesn't want Lilith to be
institutionalized like other summer festivals. She's keeping that
promise so far, but isn't certain of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given it a thought yet,'' she says. ``I can't think
of what I'm doing next week, let alone two years from now. I know I
want to have kids _ and I'm not going to come out on the road when
I have kids.'' (McLachlan is married to her drummer, Ashwin Sood.)
</P>
<P>
   For next year, she plans to cut back from 57 shows to 37, same
as the inaugural summer. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``For sanity,'' she says. ``It's just too much. People last year
at 37 shows were almost at the end of their rope. We're there now
and have got a month left to go. We have 160 people out here who
are working 14-hour days in sometimes 100-plus- degree heat. You
can only push them so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morale is still high and everybody is having a good time,''
she says, ``but there's so much to deal with every day. And there's
a lot of people working seven months beforehand to organize the
whole thing as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite initial reports that Lilith would also travel to Europe,
it now looks as if it will be a strictly American experience. ``We
don't have any expertise in Europe,'' says McLachlan. ``We couldn't
get any headliners. I'm not a headliner there. I don't have any
following whatsoever, so that's a very different world.''
</P>
<P>
   This season's Lilith will end Aug. 31. McLachan has plans this
fall to mix a live album of her own and to work on another Lilith
Fair compilation. (Last year's initial release grossed $4 million.)
</P>
<P>
   But first, McLachlan has other ideas. ``I'm going to go home and
fix our house and relax,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
