<HEADLINE>
`GOVERNESS' GIVES DRIVER A LOT OF LICENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GOVERNESS 
Written and directed by: Sandra Goldbacher 
Starring: Minnie Driver, Tom Wilkinson, Harriet Walter, Florence
Hoath, Jonathan Rhys Meyers, Arlene Cockburn, Bruce Myers 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality and nudity) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandra Goldbacher's ``The Governess'' plunges Minnie Driver into
a richly textured lode of Victoriana. But it's a vehicle that
doesn't quite drive her far enough. It's a bit too diffuse for that
as it develops promising avenues, then abandons them to keep
darting off in new directions. But if it has the messiness of a
Victorian novel hastily and episodically written in serial form to
appear in newspapers, it also taps a few sufficiently intriguing
veins of eccentricity and perversity while enabling Driver to keep
us watching a character who never is quite captured as completely
as we wish she had been.
</P>
<P>
   As Rosina Da Silva, Driver is a young Jewish woman who might as
well be living on a different planet than merely in London's East
End in her segregated community, rendered in warm, rich earth tones
that half suggest a subterranean life. Then, when her merchant
father dies, she finds herself all but living on another planet.
Realizing she can't get a job worth having in gentile London if
she's recognized as a Jew, and not wanting to marry from
expediency, she reinvents herself as a WASP. Assuming the name of
Mary Blackchurch, she takes a job as a governess for a rich family
on a misty Scottish island.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes bleak, sometimes hazy atmosphere of her new
location is a metaphor for that family's dysfunction and isolation.
Rosina/Mary, assigned to look after a brat bored into horrible
misbehavior, tames the little girl readily enough, then expands her
scope by developing an interest in the scientific research of the
lord of the manor, played by Tom Wilkinson. His wife, played with
wry bite by Harriet Walter, is corroding from within and Wilkinson
contributes to the overall dreariness by dropping out and holing up
in his lab, where he dabbles in the infant science of photography.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how to capture the image, but doesn't know how to keep
it from fading away almost instantly. Yielding to the cliche of the
exotic and intellectual Jewess, the film has Driver's governess
promptly show the befuddled aristocrat how to develop the pictures
and add salt to the emulsifying solution to make them last. From
there, it's a short step to her doubling as his lab assistant, and
an even shorter one to embarking on a love affair with him. In no
time, he's exchanging cliches furiously, moving from ``Jane Eyre''
to ``Salome,'' tormenting himself with guilt over the few moments
of sensual pleasure he shares with Rosina, needing psychologically
to cast her as the sex-crazed, hysterical Jewess he fears is about
to consume him.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina likes sex better than her employer and is more prepared
to accept its consequences. But the mix is complicated by the
expulsion from Oxford of the family's tubercular young opium-addict
son, who predictably falls for the governess, too. As she becomes
too much for the emotionally stormy but repressed family to handle,
things move toward a melodramatic climax. As a director, Goldbacher
drenches the film in lush, heavily symbolic imagery _ including the
ones involving the capturing and fixing of an image. As a writer,
she's scattershot, losing sight of the ethnic themes for a less
fully realized playing out of warped sexuality than ``Angels and
Insects'' gave us. The ending, while logically acceptable, is
anticlimactic. Still, the sheer intelligence and independence of
spirit in Driver's busy eyes almost carry ``The Governess'' past
its structural limitations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
