<HEADLINE>
AMOS HOSTETTER IS SET FOR HIS NEXT CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amos Hostetter is the man to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked the end of a one-year noncompete agreement
Hostetter signed when he quit MediaOne Group in a furor over the
Colorado-based Baby Bell's decision to move Hostetter's Continental
Cablevision operation from Boston to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, Hostetter is an icon in the cable television industry. He
was a pioneer in the business when he and a fraternity brother
fresh out of Amherst College took a chance on an upstart technology
and launched Continental with two Ohio cable systems in 1963. Over
the next 30 years, he built Continental into the third-largest
cable operator in the country, with more than 4 million
subscribers, before selling it to US West (now MediaOne) for $11.8
billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The question now: What's his next move?
</P>
<P>
   There has been no shortage of potential deals crossing his desk
as he has worked this past year in his nearly deserted offices at
Pilot House on the Boston waterfront's Lewis Wharf. And the cable
industry has &UR;  &LR; been atwitter for months that Hostetter and his
former top lieutenants might avail themselves of that most Boston
of satisfactions _ revenge! _ by launching a hostile takeover bid
against the MediaOne executives who they say flat out lied to them.
</P>
<P>
   While there is little doubt that Hostetter would enjoy having
MediaOne chief executive Charles Lillis spend the next year
nervously looking over his shoulder, he is quick to throw cold
water on this kind of speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think so,'' said Hostetter, looking tanned and
relaxed after returning from Nantucket with two of his three young
children Thursday morning. ``Revenge is a pretty negative feeling,
and I don't want to be consumed by that for the next few years of
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is just as quick to add: ``I really believe in business,
you get back a fair measure of what you give. I think the way the
current management is doing business will ultimately bring its own
demise without any help from me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no love lost between Hostetter and Lillis.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter sold his company because he thought US West had the
kind of deep pockets that it would take to make the company a
player in the consolidating world of cable. The deal created 80
millionaires at Continental Cablevision, but it also created a deep
well of bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   US West had said it was buying the business, in no small
measure, to get Continental's management, considered one of the
deepest in the industry. Lillis had made ``an unqualified
commitment'' to leave Hostetter and his operation in Boston. By
last summer he had changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter went to Denver to argue his case to the board. He got
nowhere, and angrily quit. About 15 of 160 people in Boston went to
Denver, and less than 10 are left today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cross-eyed I was so angry,'' Hostetter said. ``I was
totally duped, used.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter says he felt so betrayed because he had recruited a
number of executives to Boston for the planned expansion under US
West, and these people had bought houses and put their children in
schools only to be told to uproot them and move to Denver on a few
week's notice. In addition, he says, he spent 2 1/2 years on the
permitting process with the city to more than double the size of
Pilot House, only to be told by US West ``to shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No chance,'' he told Lillis. Instead, he bought Pilot House
back from US West and finished it himself. It now stands nearly
completed and empty _ ready for whatever Hostetter has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter says he is looking across the communications field
into ``possibly cable but not necessarily.'' He ticks off
broadcast, Internet services, and telephony; he says he would not
rule out a start-up, but makes it clear he is more interested in
buying an established business he can grow rather than starting
from scratch again.
</P>
<P>
   If he has a timetable, he is not saying. But whatever way he
goes, he will have no shortage of resources and connections to make
it happen.
</P>
<P>
   He remains, after all, the largest single shareholder in
MediaOne, where his 8.5 percent stake is worth about $2.5 billion.
And there is little doubt that the financial backers who bankrolled
Continental will be ready to step up again when he is ready.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he has a management-team-in-waiting that is
considered one of the savviest in the business. A dozen or so of
them continue to work out of Pilot House on various consulting
projects, including former president Tim Neher; Bill Schleyer,
another former president; general counsel Robert Sachs; and Rob
Stengel, former head of programming. Their own noncompete &UR;  &LR; deals
are scheduled to expire this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter does not mince words about what he thinks is going on
at MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has more than doubled since the acquisition of
Continental Cablevision was announced, but that rise has still
lagged its peers in a hot industry, he says. Lillis is running it
like a telephone company, not a media company, with too much
bureaucracy, too many people, and private jets for the bosses,
Hostetter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They replaced 160 people in Boston with 1,200 in Denver. It's
frightening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he wanted to do a major cable takeover, this would be the
company, he says. Management owns little stock, and MediaOne does
not have the kind of dual-class of stock that makes a takeover
difficult at other cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making a run at this company, but it would not
surprise me at all if someone does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We called Lillis for his side of the story; he did not call us
back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not so bad being an insurance executive.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Benson, now the chief executive of New England
Financial, made a whopping $11.6 million in 1997, his last year as
president of Equitable Life Assurance Society, according to the
annual compensation rankings by the Insurance Forum, a newsletter.
That huge payday includes Benson's deferred compensation package,
stock options, and severance pay.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Brien, chief executive of Allmerica Financial in
Worcester, Mass., made $3.6 million last year. Massachusetts
Mutual's boss, Thomas Wheeler, made $3.5 million; John Hancock CEO
Stephen Brown made $3 million; and Liberty Mutual's Gary Countryman
got $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
