<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     08-07 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKEWED, TWISTED ROOF MAY NEED REBUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 09, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am redoing my roof that is only 10 years old. A friend told
me the roof looks as if it is twisting and is skewed a little. It
is a raised ranch, and a quarter of the space below has a cathedral
ceiling. Can I straighten it out?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE O'DONNELL, Attleboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ranch houses usually have shallow roofs, which means that the
rafters are flatter than in a steeper roof, are taking more strain,
and could move under that strain. There might also not be collar
beams in the attic connecting the rafters (the rafters form an
upside down ``V'' and the collar beams turn that upside down ``V''
into a ``A.'' Collar beams are designed to keep the rafters from
spreading. Also, the cathedral ceiling section, without collar
beams, may be contributing to the movement of the rafters. The
movement of the rafters may be causing the ridge board to go out of
level.
</P>
<P>
   To correct it, I think the whole roof should be rebuilt. There
could be some adjustments to keep it from skewing any further.
</P>
<P>
   Your next step is to consult an architect or an engineer to tell
you what happened and what has to be done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house was stained with a yellow stain that lasted 12
years. Recently I had a gray latex solid stain applied over the
yellow, and now I am getting cedar bleed, those brown stains on the
gray finish. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   BOB FITZGERALD, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Hmm, it seems strange that no cedar bleed showed through the
yellow but did through the gray. You should be able to wash off the
brown stains with detergent and water, and gentle pressure-washing,
but be careful that the pressure-washing doesn't knock off the
gray.
</P>
<P>
   A more permanent cure, and somwhat iffy, is to sand the finish
thoroughly, apply an oil-based primer that will stop the cedar
bleed, and apply two coats of the gray stain.
</P>
<P>
   I say iffy because while most paint companies make a primer
designed specifically to stop that cedar bleed, the primer is a
paint, and therefore can peel. That is a chance you have to take,
unless you strip to the bare wood and apply a semitransparent stain
of a color dark enough not to show cedar bleed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The cherry cabinets in my kitchen are 25 years old and they
look OK, but they are sticky. How can I get rid of that stickiness?
</P>
<P>
   CALLER, from Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Stickiness sometimes happens on old finishes, and no one that
I know of has a real answer. The handyman would like to know if
anyone has an answer, and how to correct it.
</P>
<P>
   The stickiness might be worse in humid weather, but it might not
go completely away in winter with the heat on. So, wash the
cabinets with paint thinner; put it on liberally, let it sit there
a few sconds, then wipe, and dry with a dry cloth. If that doesn't
work, try alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick is to wipe the cabinets with talcum powder, as
little as possible so it won't show but enough to take the curse
off the stickiness.
</P>
<P>
   If any of those treatments fails, it means the cabinets might
require refinishing. Or, sand the cabinets lightly but not enough
to take off the stain, and apply one coat of an oil-based
polyurethane varnish. Before you refinish, wipe rubbing alcohol on
the finish; if it softens the finish, it is shellac, and sticky
shellac must be refinished. If the alcohol does not soften the
finish, it is varnish or lacquer, which can be sanded and varnished
as described above.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My nephew is shingling my walls with red cedar shingles. You
mentioned once not to use power nailing on a roof, but to hand
nail. Does this apply to wood siding shingles?
</P>
<P>
   MARY PEN, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No. You can use power nailing on siding shingles, but make
sure the nailer is used correctly; that is, the nails are driven
straight, not at an angle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My boiler leaked rusty water on the concrete basement floor.
The leak has been fixed; how can I clean the rust spots on the
floor?
</P>
<P>
   BILL WEEMS, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Mix 4 ounces oxalic acid in a quart of hot water. Apply this
to the spots and let dry. Oxalic acid is a crystaline bleach sold
in hardware and building stores. When it dries, the crystals may
reappear; sweep them up and throw them away; the rust stains should
be gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some power steering fluid spilled on my driveway, and not
only stained it, but softened it and deteriorated some of the
asphalt. How can I stop that deterioration? The fluid is oily.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY POWELL, Kingston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If the fluid is still liquidy, sprinkle an absorbant clay
such as Speedy Dry or cat litter, even baking soda on the spot,
letting it mound up an inch. Leave it for an hour, then sweep it up
and throw it away. If it is not liquidy, apply paint thinner and
then put on the absorbant material. Repeat as necessary. If the
deterioration is not too deep, you can then seal the surfce
(probably the whole driveway) with a driveway sealer. If that
doesn't work, you may have to cut out that section of asphalt and
put in a cold patch of new asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-07 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE MIKE DUFFY: YOUNG, AMBITIOUS, CATHOLIC, AND GAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Duffy is smart, articulate, ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   He has considerable political experience for a 34-year-old. He
has an Irish name in a state where that never hurts a candidate. He
is a practicing Catholic, which hasn't hurt a candidate hereabouts
since the first half of this century.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a Republican, which has not been an advantage in
Massachusetts since Jack Kennedy was a pup. Duffy has set himself
the sizeable challenge of toppling a popular, long-term, low-key
and affable constitutional officer, state auditor Joe DeNucci, the
Democrat in a bottom-of-the-statewide-ballot slot that has not gone
Republican in living memory.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy is also gay, an upfront, noncloseted,
here-I-am-it's-no-big-deal homosexual, in a state which has in two
different instances re-elected congressmen initially elected by
voters unaware of their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   As perhaps the first credible statewide candidate of a major
party to run as an acknowledged gay, Duffy thinks that will neither
help nor harm his candidacy, which is an interesting take on the
public mood hereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there'll be as many people who'll vote for me because
I'm gay as will vote against me because I'm gay _ basically a
wash,'' Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bigger handicap is that I'm running as a Republican. When I
meet people, I say, ``I'm a Bill Weld Republican, and not a Jesse
Helms Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy's goal is to become ``the first openly gay elected
statewide official.'' He blithely puts his chances at 50-50, though
wise heads would give him the short end of odds in the 3-1, 4-1,
5-1 range. Off a recent conversation, I get the impression Duffy
has three reasons for running for auditor:
</P>
<P>
   _He thinks he can do a good job. Having been former Governor
Weld's choice for two terms as chairman of the Massachusetts
Commission Against Discrimination, and then director of consumer
affairs, Duffy got experience, exposure, and enough media attention
to fuel his ambition. He knows which end of the microphone is
which, and he pulled off several minor publicity coups in his Weld
administration service.
</P>
<P>
   _He wants to break a trail for other gay candidates to run with
less attention paid to their sexuality. ``I think I'd be great at
the job, but that has nothing to do with sexual orientation. I have
the desire to achieve. I'm conscious of the extent to which I'm a
role model, because there are so few prominent outwardly gay
people.'' Which leads to reason No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   _``I'd like to reclaim the Republican Party nationally from the
extremists who have taken it over.'' In Masachusetts, during the
Weld era, gays were ushered into state appointive posts after
Weld's eyelash-thin first election was strongly supported by gay
activists and contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a striking difference between my experience at the
Republican state convention here, and some of the noises coming out
of Washington ... as the rhetoric gets increasingly intolerant, it
is important to give a human face to the debate, a real live
person, who can talk about what it is to be gay.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the recent 214-212 vote in the US House that
restricted the use of some federal housing money in San Francisco,
as an example of the way conservative elements in politics
counter-attack against gay-supported causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the extreme antigay rhetoric coming out of Washington
is a concerted effort by the extreme right within the Republican
Party to try to score some political points. As to the short term,
maybe that works. But long term, it's like George Wallace standing
in the schoolhouse door.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy is optimistic. ``The culture is moving to the point of
accepting gays and lesbians. I don't think extremists can hold back
that tide. It's like the South in the '60s. Opposing those kinds of
(civil rights) things, in the long term, leaves you nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy acknowledges that some gay activists can be their own
cause's worst enemy. He discussed the notorious episode in Boston
where some gay demonstrators tried to disrupt the ordination of
seven Cathloic priests at the Cathedral of the Holy Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a practicing Catholic. Some of the things done by extreme
elements in the gay community are deeply offensive to me, not only
the throwing of condoms at priests being ordained, but in upsetting
a sacred function. There is no political agenda that justifies
those kinds of political intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy grew up outside of Fort Lauderdale, and went to school at
Trinity College in Hartford and the Kennedy School at Harvard. He
has been a Republican since age 18, he said, and worked for US
Representative Chris Shays of Connecticut, who has spearheaded
campaign finance reform among House Republicans. Duffy joined the
Weld campaign in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's never even met DeNucci, but enjoys the campaign
grind. ``The reaction from folks has been terrific. People really
like it when you extend yourself. It's as basic as Tip O'Neill
said: `People like to be asked.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
