<HEADER>
A2901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-CHAPLIN-BOS &LR;      08-07 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CHAPLIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPLIN'S TRAMP IS FIT FOR THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a few decades of downslide, Charlie Chaplin's reputation
is on the upswing again. Chaplin's way of mixing pathos with his
comedy worked against him in a post-modern age more attuned to the
deadpan existentialism of Buster Keaton. But as the Museum of Fine
Arts' admirable Chaplin retro is reminding us, the world of
Chaplin's comedy found ample room for life's matter-of-fact
brutality, which the Little Tramp negotiated with delicacy and
unsinkable optimism. Chaplin wasn't the first bowler-hatted
baggy-pants tramp comedian. But he was the one who turned the
archetype into a scrappy yet balletic figure, at home in his own
solitariness, with whom millions identified.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA's Chaplin series concludes with a handful of
lesser-known Chaplin films that fascinatingly show the Chaplin
persona being formed and perfected. The weekend's most notable
offering is ``The Circus'' (1928), the final shot of which depicts
perhaps the most quintessential image in the entire Chaplin oeuvre,
the one that turned Chaplin into his own logo. It shows Chaplin
walking away from us, having just shrugged gamely at losing the
love of the circus owner's daughter to a high-wire walker. Chipper
as ever, he toddles off toward the horizon, ready for the next hand
life deals him, as the camera irises shut.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that by ``The Circus,'' Chaplin had added the
last piece of the tramp persona _ the little bamboo cane, a prop
the importance of which Chaplin never underestimated. Its
resilience symbolized his, it gave him something to do with his
hands, and it reinforced his gentlemanliness, suggesting as
strongly as the frequent tipping of the hat that he had known
better days. The film also contains some of the funniest business
Chaplin ever choreographed for himself. Chased into the big tent by
cops, he brings the house down with his desperate and unknowingly
funny attempts to elude them.
</P>
<P>
   He's hired as a prop man by the brutal circus owner, who
routinely beats his daughter and tells his employees to never let
the tramp know that he's the star of the show lest he demand more
money. The consternation that makes him a star peaks when he finds
himself subbing for the tightrope walker. Was there ever a more
perfect physical expression of the precariousness built into the
Little Tramp's life? Here Chaplin's painstaking way of building his
sight gags reaches its apotheosis when, barely convinced he's got
tightrope-walking mastered, monkeys scamper onto the rope to keep
him company _ to his terror and the audience's glee.
</P>
<P>
   There's more comedy than pathos in ``The Circus,'' which is what
keeps it delicious. It's preceded by ``A Day's Pleasure'' (1919),
the shortest film in the series at 20 minutes, in which a pre-tramp
Chaplin plays a paterfamilias who goes through a lot to take his
family on an outing. He has trouble cranking up the car, barely
makes the steamship excursion with family in tow, dodges a beating
by a bully, then turns on him and kicks him ferociously when the
bully gets seasick, and finally must cope with being mired in tar
with two irate traffic cops. Note that one of his sons is played by
Jackie Coogan, who was to become an international star when Chaplin
filmed ``The Kid'' a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin was fearless about acting with children and animals.
Unlike W.C. Fields, whose view of domesticity was genuinely
subversive, Chaplin regarded his film family as benign, finding all
the hostility he needed in the outside world. Similarly, in ``A
Dog's Life,'' he and the mongrel he meets as a homeless man trying
to catch a nap behind a far from sheltering fence are soulmates.
The dog he names Scraps is his alter ego, hanging in there, not to
be deterred by nightstick-wielding cops or other natural enemies.
The food vendor whose pushcart draws Chaplin's tramp like a magnet,
by the way, is played by his half-brother, Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The droopy Sydney is Charlie's foil as well in ``Shoulder Arms''
(1918), quite possibly the first service comedy. Rushed to
completion and distribution before the end of World War I, it stars
Charlie as a resourceful doughboy for whom all is not quiet on the
Western Front. First, he heroically captures a trenchful of
Germans. Then he tops himself by going after the Kaiser in order to
rescue his sad-eyed buddy (Sydney again) and a French damsel played
by Edna Purviance. She was his favorite silent leading lady,
through 1923 at least, but whom he kept on his payroll for years
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pilgrim'' (1923), rounding out tomorrow's triple bill,
stars Charlie as an escaped prisoner who steals a parson's clothes
and shows up in a Texas backwater town posing as the cleric. If he
was tempted to skewer religious hypocrisy, he held his fire, taking
it easy on the parched, pious congregation and limiting himself to
desperate fraudulence. In doing so, he allows ``The Pilgrim'' to be
stolen by big Mack Swain, the prospector with whom he shared the
old boot dinner in ``The Gold Rush.'' Swain, fingertips touching as
he seems to be plowing his way into heaven like an icebreaker, eyes
rolling skyward, suggests a bilious eggplant, even when his pint
bottle of Prohibition-era booze slips from his pocket and smashes
on the sidewalk. It's Chaplin's cleric who looks disconcerted while
the bloated sanctimoniousness of Swain's deacon remains intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
