<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ZYDECO-BOS &LR;      08-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ZYDECO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THOROUGH ZYDECO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE KINGDOM OF ZYDECO 
By Michael Tisserand 
Arcade, 382 pp., illustrated, $29.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame ``The Big Easy'' or Cambridge's own Rounder Records, but
zydeco is everywhere. The Louisiana music's wheezing accordion, the
syncopated rhythms scraped along a metal washboard, sell everything
from hot sauce to autos, relying on the lively music's connotations
of good times _ and simpler ones. The real story, as revealed by
Michael Tisserand in his enjoyable and authoritative ``The Kingdom
of Zydeco,'' is both darker and more complicated, much like the
history of the state that spawned it.
</P>
<P>
   Zydeco is the music of the black Creole population of rural
Louisiana, a French-speaking group that has shared much with, but
still holds itself distinct from, the better-known white Cajun
people. Like the Cajuns, descendents of French-Canadian emigres,
these Francophone African-Americans built their own society in the
state's southwestern bayous and plains. And their isolation and
poverty kept their culture more or less intact until the last few
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Tisserand, who writes a column on zydeco for the magazine Living
Blues, explores the music through that culture, detailing the
Saturday-night house dances that let poor farmers and sharecroppers
cut loose. He traces this homemade entertainment from the first a
cappella jure (testifying) songs to the arrival of that Viennese
invention, the accordion, soon after it was patented in 1829. With
the help of Cajun music scholars such as Ann Allen Savoy (author of
the comprehensive ``Cajun Music''), he charts the frequent
cross-pollinations between the area's parallel populations. And
then, as country music and rhythm 'n' blues crept into the culture
and Louisiana musicians working in nearby Houston became more
cosmopolitan, he begins to pick up the stories of recorded
musicians, from Amede Ardoin and Canray Fontenot through Clifton
Chenier, who arguably invented contemporary zydeco. Ultimately, as
electric instruments, funk, and even hip-hop captured the
imagination of the younger generation, he follows the latest
incarnations of zydeco into recordings as recent as last year's.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans-based author loves zydeco with a passion that
becomes obvious as he traces trends _ such as the tradition of
barking like a dog in songs _ through time. He even spends pages on
the etymology of the music's name. Most critics accept the widely
disseminated story that traces the name to ``les haricots'' (snap
beans), which appear in a song made famous by Chenier, ``Les
Haricots Sont Pas Sale'' (``The Snap Beans Aren't Salty'') _ a
joyful number about times so hard that no salt meat can be afforded
to flavor the snap-bean pot. But Tisserand looks back further,
finding phrases in West African languages that suggest the music's
title, such as ``a zare'' (``I dance''), and tracing these older
sources in both lyrics and rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   While this may sound scholarly, Tisserand fleshes out the
theories with a folk-tale approach, weaving anecdotes together with
juicy quotes from elder musicians, such as Alphonse ``Bois Sec''
Ardoin and Boozoo Chavis. The results are colorful, and sometimes
the stories he uncovers are contradictory. Was the great
accordionist Ardoin beaten senseless because he accepted a
handkerchief from a white woman at one sweaty dance? Or was he
conducting an affair with such a woman, the handkerchief of legend
serving as modest metaphor? Even as various retellings deliver
alternate versions, they paint a vivid portrait of a harshly
segregated society, where black musicians could be admired for
their talent _ as long as they knew their place. Zydeco is
good-time music, he makes clear, but it grew out of very hard
lives.
</P>
<P>
   While Tisserand's own writing is clear and enjoyable, his
ability to translate the riding rhythms into prose agile, it is the
interviews he includes that make this book truly special. These
strings of quotes _ presented uncorrected and full of colorful
colloquialisms _ are treasures, bits of living history grabbed just
in time, in several cases, to preserve firsthand accounts of
customs and people now gone. The late Fontenot, for example, was
arguably the greatest fiddler of his day; to have his accounts of
Amede Ardoin or his own father, who never recorded because of his
religious beliefs, is priceless. Although the filmmaker Les Blank
has made documentaries about many of these musicians and magazines
have begun chronicling this musical subculture, there have been no
studies of zydeco as comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the dearth of historical material may account for
Tisserand's one slight failing. Roughly the last quarter of the
book is focused on contemporary musicians who have not yet proved
themselves as influential as their forebears. True, the author ties
such performers as Beau Jocque and Chris Ardoin and his band Double
Clutchin' in with their rich history: Ardoin, after all, is the
grandson of ``Bois Sec,'' and Beau Jocque's feud with Keith Frank
brings up the long-standing question of authorship in this
communally produced music. But do they merit a chapter apiece?
Perhaps Tisserand hears what the rest of us do not yet; the
knowledge and passion displayed here urge the reader to trust him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
