<HEADER>
A2910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-COLLEGE-CORRECTNES     08-07 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COLLEGE-CORRECTNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEATH LEAVES A COLLEGE IN TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ The obituary did not say what killed him.
But friends of the Rev. Kenneth A. Childs, who collapsed in his
home here last week, believe he fell victim to an academic poison:
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   After 26 years as a campus minister at Springfield College,
Childs, 56, was fired on July 22 for his ``outspoken and caustic
criticism'' of the school administration and what he called its
increasingly corporate style. Despite his popularity among the
3,000 or so students, Childs was asked to pack his things and leave
by Aug. 1. Within a week, he was dead of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   But glimmers of his moral indignation seem to have survived.
Even as students wandered teary-eyed into his empty office, faculty
members began seeking answers about his dismissal _ and demanded
the resignation of the school president, Randoph Bromery, a former
chancellor of the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Bromery did, announcing his imminent departure this week,
although he had planned to leave his post anyway and maintained
that the timing of his announcement was a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole campus just went into shock at the horror of this,''
said Fernando Gonzalez de Leon, 38, an associate professor of
history and friend of Childs. ``The only thing Childs cared about
was academic freedom. He was in perfect health. Ten days ago, this
man was like you or me.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials refused to discuss the minister's firing.
William B. Marsh, the chairman of the board of trustees, said only
that the school is ``very saddened by his death.'' David Shrair, an
attorney for the college, said simply, ``I understand he had a
heart attack. There could be thousands of reasons why anybody could
die of a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrair said it is within school policy to ``terminate any
non-faculty employee at will for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   But the confidential dismissal letter that Bromery wrote to
Childs two weeks ago _ along with what some professors perceive as
a long-running plan to silence the outspoken minister _ has sent
rumors flying across this urban campus, and raised questions among
some faculty members about whether freedom of speech truly exists
here.
</P>
<P>
   In the three-paragraph termination notice, which was saved by
Childs and obtained by the Globe, Bromery accused Childs of a
``lack of support of administration,'' as well as the ``fostering
of dissention among College constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bromery declined to reveal the nature of Childs's dissent, but
friends insisted it was hardly a revolutionary threat: The only
``evidence'' friends could imagine was Childs's occasional columns
in monthly campus newsletters, as well as his critiques of
administrative decisions at campus meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Rising from his seat to address a faculty meeting, his large
frame towering over the rest of the faculty, Childs would often
direct barbed remarks at the administration, said Tom Shea, a
professor of economics who was Childs's friend for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would stand up and say, `Don't you think we've had enough
spenditure in this area, and not enough on the students?''' Shea
recalled. ``People always called him the `conscience of the
college.' And that's what he was.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a role Childs assumed three decades earlier. After
growing up in Ripon, Wisc., he moved east to study divinity and
theology at Yale University, graduating in 1968. He was ordained
the same year and moved to Wilbraham, then to Springfield in 1973,
according to his July 31 obituary in the Springfield Union-News.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the staff at Springfield College and over the course
of three administrations became a thorn in the side of each
successive president, writing columns and helping publish an
independent faculty newsletter, the Faculty Voice. He rarely feared
the reaction of top officials, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   When Bromery became president in October 1993, his decisions,
too, came under criticism from Childs. After the name of the
college's sports teams was changed in 1993 from the Chiefs to the
Pride, in order not to insult American Indians, Childs attacked the
move as a simplistic concession toward the political correctness
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly trivial issues sparked equal outrage: After an
announcement earlier this year that Bromery hoped to close off
Alden Street, the main drag on the urban campus, Childs criticized
him in print, calling the proposal an ``arrogant initiative'' and a
``daily public embarrassment'' in a column in the Jan. 28, 1998
edition of the campus paper, the Student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt it was part of the role of the campus ministry
to speak out,'' said John J. Doyle, chair of the department of
Management and Economics, who knew Childs for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   As his criticism continued, Childs began to feel marginalized by
the administration in recent years, his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Childs had his views, and those views were not necessarily
the views of the college,'' said Shrair. ``My understanding is that
his views became even more outspoken after his first wife passed
away,'' in 1986. ``But what he was all about, I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Childs was summoned to Bromery's office and informed of
his dismissal. He received the letter on July 22. He was
despondent, Doyle said. And within days, he began feeling chest
pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tense. I think he felt discarded after a long period of
service to the college,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Childs was told to remove his belongings from the first-floor
office of the Beveridge Student Center by Aug. 1. But when he
arrived at the campus ministry center on July 28, he found the
locks had already been changed to keep him out. ``He was very
flustered, very upset,'' Gonzalez de Leon recalled.
</P>
<P>
   After a security guard opened the office door, Childs and his
wife, Donna, began filling boxes full of files, pulling down
posters, clearing shelves. When they went home, Childs was an
emotional wreck, his friends said. He collapsed that day with a
heart attack, and died.
</P>
<P>
   In the week after his death, appalled by what they perceived as
a ``chilling attack on freedom of speech,'' Childs's supporters met
to discuss their plans. On Monday, they drafted a letter requesting
Bromery resign, according to Gonzalez de Leon. On Tuesday, in a
meeting of the executive council, Bromery did.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, attention seemed to have turned toward the memorial
service, scheduled to take place at 1 p.m. today. Fliers were
tacked up around campus, featuring Childs's photo from the school
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A sign on the door of the campus ministry office said: ``We Love
U Ken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
