<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHBOX20: AN ALTERNATIVE APPROACH TO FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Normal guys. That's how a lot of musicians describe
themselves, but it really holds true for Matchbox 20. They're not
known visually and don't have any compelling idiosyncrasies that
land them in the gossip columns. All they do is sell records _ 7
million copies, in fact, of their debut album, ``Yourself or
Someone Like You,'' which has outsold the latest discs by Puff
Daddy, the Dave Matthews Band, and just about anyone else this side
of Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just normal guys playing normal music,'' says singer Rob
Thomas, whose Orlando-based band has risen quickly. ``We're
confident, but we never make any claims about how great we are.
There are a lot of bands that we like more than we like us,'' says
Thomas, 26.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether Matchbox 20 will try to blow away Soul Asylum and
Semisonic, Thomas sticks to his populist mode by saying, ``It's not
about competition. A lot of people are just coming to see a show.
For them it's just a night away from everything, a night away from
work. It's going out and having some beers with friends. I think
that's how you have to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Matchbox 20 has adroitly straddled the line between mainstream
rock and alternative rock. The band's lyrically driven guitar pop
has resulted in such smash hits as ``Real World'' (``I want the
real world to stop hassling me!'' Thomas sings), ``3 A.M.,'' ``Long
Day,'' and ``Push.'' All the while, the band has kept its humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's hip,'' says Thomas. ``So we're just going
to stick with what we do _ and hopefully we'll pull a Tom Petty and
manage to continuously make good records, fanfare or no fanfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas almost takes pride in declaring that he and his bandmates
are not known visually, despite extensive play on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we have these forgettable faces,'' he says. ``I
went to Universal Studios with my girlfriend recently and we went
through all these lines, and not once did we have any hassles. And
I think that's great. I don't think it's good when everywhere you
go, you have people who think they know you. I think we're better
off this way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Halen returns: The new Van Halen, with Boston-bred Gary
Cherone on vocals, has taken some pummeling in the press but has
not been deterred. What does Cherone have to say? ``I'd rather be
quiet and let the music talk. I'm not much of a hype machine, but
really, I don't think the band has ever sounded better _ not
because of me, but because of the whole sound. And I think we can
still convert the old guard,'' says Cherone.
</P>
<P>
   Cherone made his point loud and clear last spring at the
FleetCenter in Boston, where Van Halen ruled once again. You might
cite previous VH singers David Lee Roth or Sammy Hagar as still
being your choice, but if you caught the Fleet show you'd have to
admit that the band has never been more pumped in concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie (Van Halen) was more nervous than I was for the Boston
show,'' says Cherone, who has lived in Malden and Melrose. ``It was
like this was Eddie's hometown gig in Boston. I said to him, `Hey,
I'm the one who's supposed to be nervous, not you.' But we had a
great week. We played Boston, New York, and Philadelphia _ and each
show got better.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Fleet gig, Cherone was deluged with ticket requests. ``I
had a whole loge full of people _ everybody from the guys I play
basketball with to cousins I never knew I had. And my brothers
would keep calling me up, adding people to the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherone knows that he's been on the spot this tour, but it's
been a challenge he has relished. ``You've got to prove it every
night. You can't have a bad night,'' he says. ``But the general
consensus is that the fans are going home happy. There's a good
spirit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherone will look to rekindle that spirit at a Great Woods
appearance, where he hopes to sing a couple more VH chestnuts from
the Roth days _ namely, the newly added ``Hot for Teacher'' and
``Jamie's Crying.'' Where he once said he would avoid such
signature Roth tunes, Cherone now declares, ``I was just being
paranoid. I think I can handle them.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Halen has kept on going despite an accident to drummer Alex
Van Halen while the band was in Hamburg, Ga., not long ago. A piece
of ceiling tile fell on him, bruising his arm to the point where
the band had to cancel eight shows. ``He's OK now,'' says Cherone.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the band is in it for the long haul, Cherone adds
that VH will finish its tour Nov. 2 in Japan, then knuckle down and
write more music. ``Ideally, we'll have a new record out next
summer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock lives: The 29th anniversary of the Woodstock Festival
is next weekend, at which time the original site of the event will
come alive for the ``Day in the Garden'' series. Yes, Max Yasgur's
farm, which was purchased by cable entrepreneur Alan Gerry two
years ago, is being ``rededicated'' as a concert site, says
producer Danny Socolof. The lineup has star power. Next Friday: Don
Henley, Stevie Nicks, Ziggy Marley &AMP; the Melody Makers, and
original Woodstock act Ten Years After. For Saturday: Joni Mitchell
(who wrote the song ``Woodstock''), Pete Townshend, Lou Reed,
Richie Havens, Donovan, and Melanie. And for Sunday, there's a
younger, alt-rock-tilted show with Dishwalla, Joan Osborne, Goo Goo
Dolls, Marcy Playground, Third Eye Blind, and the Flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Woodstock '98,'' says Socolof. ``This is a
rededication of the site, though we respect what happened here 29
years ago.'' The site is now being transformed with tents for food,
crafts, and beer, plus a large sculpture garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you step on this property, there's a real good buzz,''
says Socolof, who produced the ``Surreal Field'' area at Woodstock
'94. He and his team are taking the 37 acres that comprise the
Woodstock site in Bethel, N.Y., and setting up the same stage that
Garth Brooks used in his Central Park show last year. And they're
selling a maximum of 30,000 tickets per day, in an attempt to
create a laid-back vibe. (If all goes well, they'll do more shows
there next year.)
</P>
<P>
   The music runs from 11:30 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. each day (no
late-night heroics this time) and will be broadcast live on the
festival's Web site at infoseek.com. Other information can be
procured there as well. And while there's no camping on site, there
are many campsites nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
