<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SNAKE-EYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPALMA'S STYLISH `SNAKE' ENTICES,THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SNAKE EYES 
Directed by: Brian De Palma 
Screenplay by: David Koepp 
Starring: Nicolas Cage, Gary Sinise, John Heard, Carla Gugino, Stan
Shaw, Kevin Dunn 
Running time: 99 minutes 
Rated: R (some violence) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian De Palma's ``Snake Eyes'' is a throwback to his earlier
high-tension thrillers _ ``Blow Out,'' ``Dressed to Kill,''
``Obsession,'' and ``Body Double.'' It's stylish and entertainingly
feverish as it keeps shifting the point of view in a hothouse
atmosphere _ an indoor arena where an assassin guns down a Cabinet
member during a heavyweight championship fight. During the panic
that ensues, and while they've still got a chance to keep the exits
blocked, Atlantic City cop Nicholas Cage and his boyhood buddy,
naval commander and security expert Gary Sinise, join forces to try
and nail the killer.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma has fun throwing the loud, hectic boxing match scene at
us, then replaying it from different characters' points of view,
enticing us to examine the pieces of the labyrinthine puzzle in
each retelling so we can find the details that will tell us who set
up whom. The Atlantic City setting allows the arena stuff to spill
into the surrounding environment, a hideous money-extracting casino
and hotel run by John Heard's mogul and designed to give greed and
ugliness a bad name. A sort of cross between Howard Hughes and
Donald Trump, living off defense contracts and gambling glitz,
Heard's kingpin is a vulgarian. The question is whether he's a
lethal one.
</P>
<P>
   The film derives its energy from the way De Palma's camera
hurtles through the cavelike spaces of the arena and casino and
from the contrasting styles of Cage and Sinise. De Palma's
camerawork has always tended toward showing off, but here the speed
of it takes the sting out of its self-advertisement. The camera
never upstages Cage's over-the-top cop. With his shiny brown rayon
jacket and saffron-patterned Hawaiian sportshirt, he suggests an
oven-fresh cheese-filled glazed meatloaf as he careens around the
arena, strong-arming payoffs out of the petty crooks who hang
around the action like pilot fish.
</P>
<P>
   He both feeds off the crass action and contributes to it. While
the film stays on the surface of things and scarcely bothers to
convince us of any real tie between the cop and the career naval
officer, his spillover contrasts vividly with the air of steely
containment projected by Sinise's security chief worried about a
sudden end to his credibility and career. If Cage's cop lets it all
hang out, right down to his gold-plated cell phone, Sinise's
equally tense crimefighter keeps it all inside. If Cage's
flamboyance keeps you watching the cop, it's Sinise's fierce
concentration that glues you to his taut Defense Department
staffer.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Gugino's mystery woman is the figure who invokes the De
Palma of ``Body Double'' and ``Obsession'' in her platinum blond
wig that's knocked from her head in the stampede following the
gunshots as she flees the killer while blood from an arm wound
reddens her white silk suit. De Palma has a few piquant points to
make about the claustrophobic world of the gambler and uses its
darkness and feeling of the walls closing in to reinforce the
melodramatic pressure. ``Snake Eyes'' is claptrap, but De Palma's
slickness makes the Cage-Sinise duet fun to watch. It's probably
the kiss of death to call ``Snake Eyes'' the most intelligent dumb
thriller of the summer, but that's what it is as De Palma finally
stops trying to top Hitchcock and just rolls with the film's
connection to lurid '90s excess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
