<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SAFE-MEN-BOS &LR;      08-07 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SAFE-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAFE MEN' WALKS ON THE MILD SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SAFE MEN 
Written and directed by: John Hamburg 
Starring: Sam Rockwell, Steve Zahn, Mark Ruffalo, Josh Pais, Paul
Giamatti, Christine Kirk, Harvey Fierstein, Michael Lerner, Michael
Schmidt 
Running time: 89 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Hamburg's ``Safe Men'' plays like Coen Brothers Lite. Very
Lite. It wants to trade on quirky eccentricity, but it's neither
dark enough nor brilliant enough to conceal its overextended
softness. It's at best mildly agreeable as it takes a couple of
woebegone young musicians and throws them into a few forced
safecracking assignments for which they are, to put it gently,
ill-suited. The comedy comes in when they keep bumping up against a
pair of really good safecrackers. But the idea of setting their
botched capers in the circumscribed netherworld of the Jewish mafia
in Providence, R.I., is dulled when that criminal element consists
of two far-from-menacing guys.
</P>
<P>
   The shady rivals played by Michael Lerner and Harvey Fierstein
seem to have gained their criminal backgrounds solely by watching
movies, and the wrong ones at that. Still, their respective
tough-guy acts scare Sam Rockwell's aspiring musician and his
sidekick, Steve Zahn. So, having been set up by the henchman of the
schemer played by Lerner, they gulp, take a timeout from playing
the Polish social events that are the only gigs they can get, and
head into the night, driven by the memory of the shouted threats
from Lerner's workout-suited goniff, who suggests an angry knish,
waving a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the limited scope of what's going on, it takes an
awfully long time to get there. The only real diversion comes from
the half-calculating, half-impulsive gleam in the eye of Christina
Kirk, as the daughter of the larcenous retailer played by
Fierstein. She should know better than to get interested in
thieves, her eyes tell us, especially since she just dumped one of
the really talented safecrackers. Still, Rockwell's hangdog
sincerity gets to her, and besides, she can tell he's no thief at
heart. The problem with ``Safe Men'' is that it's all too obviously
safe, except when you're wondering which way Kirk's character is
going to go. Hamburg's next comedy, the press notes tell us, will
be for Disney. It seems a logical development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
