<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-CASTRO-$ADV09-CO     08-07 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CASTRO-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A FIT FIDEL QUASHES RUMORS OF ILL HEALTH AS 72ND BIRTHDAY
APPROACHES
 &HT;    With CASTRO-BOX-$ADV09.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Cuba's septuagenarian leader Fidel Castro ``died'' four
years ago, supposedly from a stroke. It was lung cancer that killed
him two years ago. Most recently, he suffered from a potentially
fatal disorder that turns the brain to mush.
</P>
<P>
   But the irrepressible Castro, who turns 72 on Thursday(Aug. 13),
has more lives than a cat.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, Castro's birthday unleashes a fresh round of
feverish speculation concerning the health of the Communist
dictator, much of it kindled by wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   And this birthday's no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Miami newspaper quoted a Cuban defector claiming
to be a surgeon as saying Castro had received treatment in October
for a brain malady known as hypertensive encephalopathy.
</P>
<P>
   Hope that the Castro regime's days were numbered spread like
wildfire through the exile community here.
</P>
<P>
   But the claims of the defector, Elizabeth Trujillo, collapsed
when the Vatican's chief spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Vals, reported
that he had met with Castro for six hours in October, on a day when
Castro was supposed to be seriously ill, to plan January's visit by
Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Castro ridiculed reports of his illness, saying he'd never even
heard of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, they kill me off,'' Castro said. ``The
day I die, no one will believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no different last summer, when all sorts of ill-health
stories made the rounds -- some even announcing his death -- after
Castro wasn't seen in public for several weeks. But Castro easily
quashed those rumors by delivering a rousing, marathon seven-hour
speech at the opening of the Fifth Communist Party Congress.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a robust and seemingly healthy Castro basked in
warm receptions during a six-day swing through the Caribbean
following the reports of Trujillo's claims. He visited Jamaica,
Barbados and -- most significantly -- the only place where Cuban
and American troops ever did battle: Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   He will visit the Dominican Republic in late August -- his first
trip there since his 1959 Communist revolution -- and South Africa
and Portugal later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy reportedly dies every two years or so, but in reality
the man's 72 years old and still giving six-hour speeches, and he's
traveling all over the place, so he can't be doing all that bad,''
said Max Castro, an expert on Cuba at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But, to many Castro foes, the dictator ``just doesn't look
well,'' although they admit their perceptions could be borne of
fertile imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look like a healthy 72-year-old man should look.
His color's not good. He's thin. Maybe it's just wishful
thinking,'' said Ninoska Perez, spokeswoman for the Cuban American
National Foundation, the most powerful anti-Castro exile group.
</P>
<P>
   One reason ill-health rumors swirl so freely around Castro is
the general secretiveness of Communist regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Leonid Brezhnev, for example, wasn't seen for weeks before
Soviet authorities acknowledged his death.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, the government rarely publishes meeting agendas or
economic statistics, let alone details concerning Castro's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, where there's an open society, if the
president gets sick, everybody knows about it, but in Cuba this
kind of thing is treated like a state secret,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   Also fueling a growing number of rumors has been the increased
visibility over the past year of Castro's brother, Raul, who is
five years Fidel's junior.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Raul Castro was formally designated his
brother's successor as Communist Party leader at the party congress
held in October.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Raul Castro, the head of the Armed Forces, has
enjoyed a more public role in running Cuba's government. Late last
year, he represented Cuba both in Beijing and at the Vatican in
advance of the pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Fidel is clearly worried about his health and is
clearly trying to pass on the mantle,'' said Jaime Suchliki, an
expert on Cuba at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``His voice is certainly not as clear as it once was and it's
obvious he's lost weight,'' he said. ``I've heard that he only
works four hours a day so it's clear that he has slowed down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban Foreign Ministry has repeatedly said that Fidel Castro
is in good health.
</P>
<P>
   And, if anything, Castro himself has made it abundantly clear in
recent months that he retains a firm grip on his country of 11
million people.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed at a Communist Party congress in March that he would
take no steps toward capitalism. He reaffirmed his belief that,
despite the trends toward worldwide capitalism, his socialist
vision of the world would eventually prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have to perfect it, to become stronger, more cultured,
more prepared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's also scored a number of diplomatic victories over the
past year, particularly since the pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien -- the dismay of the
United States -- traveled to Cuba in April to announce increased
bilateral cooperation. Earlier this year, Guatemala and the
Dominican Republic restored diplomatic relations with the island.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite decades of efforts by the U.S. government to
isolate Cuba, more than 2,000 U.S. executives are expected to visit
Havana this year, according to the New York-based U.S.-Cuba
Economic Trade Council.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Cuban government hailed Castro's whirlwind
Caribbean tour as a triumph of Third World solidarity and a
rejection of U.S. moves to force political changes on the communist
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro seems to be secure in his power and has become
something of an icon by standing up to the United States,'' said
Ernest Preeg, who follows Cuba at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a right-of-center think tank in Washington.
``This plays well throughout the Caribbean, so it's no wonder
relations are being strengthened.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also no indication that a popular uprising might remove
Fidel Castro any time soon, despite worsening economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A devastating low 1997-98 sugar harvest and reports of a severe
drought in eastern Cuba have raised serious doubts about the
island's economic recovery prospects this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few human rights groups in Cuba, but they are not
a powerful force, so there is no real organized resistance,'' Preeg
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that may be why Castro's critics are so eager to believe
stories of ill health: it could be the only way to get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to Castro, people are always grasping at
straws,'' said Shawn Malone, an expert on Cuba at Georgetown
University in Washington. ``Speculation over Castro's poor health
is typically overblown.''
</P>
<P>
   So, as Castro approaches the 40th anniversary of the revolution
he led, there's every reason to believe the leader will be around
for awhile longer.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Balaguer, for example, ruled the Dominican Republic well
into his 80s, even when he was physically frail and blind. At age
92, he still has a hand in Dominican politics.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
