<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PIAZZA-HNS &LR;      08-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PIAZZA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS ARE SINGING THE BOOS OVER MIKE PIAZZA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Piazza undoubtedly will be hurt and confused to learn there
are no plans in the works for a telethon on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, the best hitting-catcher in baseball history doesn't
need much provocation to take offense. Trapped inside a 6-foot-3,
215-pound catcher's body are feelings that bruise as easily as
Chuck Wepner used to bleed in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers offered Piazza $84 million this past
spring _ on top of the $8 million he is pulling down this year _ to
grace their lineup with his presence through the 2005 season. After
careful consultation with his agent, Piazza decided that such an
offer constituted an insult. Piazza wanted $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Well, who doesn't want $100 million? But Piazza managed to
convince himself he was entitled to the sort of money that would
embarrass Mark McGwire. In more ways than one, Mike Piazza is no
Mark McGwire. Which is how it came to be that a 29-year-old catcher
who has played in the All-Star game six years in a row is playing
for his third team this season. Less than three months after they
gave Piazza a hero's welcome, New York Mets fans are singing the
boos. They've rehearsed the tune so often at Shea Stadium, they can
spit out their hot dogs in mid-bite and not miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza pops out weakly with a runner in scoring position.
Boooooo! Piazza grounds out with a runner in scoring position.
Boooooo!! Piazza strikes out with a runner in scoring position.
Boooooo!!! By Piazza's admission, he is hitting a ``soft'' .307
this season.
</P>
<P>
   His batting average with runners in scoring position is plunging
like necklines on ``Baywatch.'' Even though the Mets are in
contention for a wild-card playoff berth, Piazza mopes around with
the wounded look of a puppy who can't figure out why he keeps
getting whacked on the head by a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza deserves as much sympathy as the next guy who takes a
$12-million-a-year offer to stay in a city where the fans worship
him as an affront. How soon people on the top forget what it was
like in the real world. Just a decade ago, Piazza went in the 62nd
round (No. 1,390 overall) of the free-agent draft. The Dodgers took
Piazza only because his godfather, then-manager Tom Lasorda, begged
them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It was a match made in, well, Hollywood. Piazza started his
career with a series of bangs that would humble any right-handed
hitter this side of Joe DiMaggio. Even with the strike taking a
chunk out of 1994, Piazza averaged .337 with 33 homers and 105 runs
batted in over his first five seasons. Those are the numbers
befitting a perennial All-Star outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Or a first-ballot Hall of Fame catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Bench averaged .267 with 34 homers and 113 RBI during his
best five-year run. Roy Campanella averaged .296 with 30 homers and
104 RBI during his best five-year run. Yogi Berra averaged .299
with 27 homers and 109 RBI during his best five-year run. Dodgers
fans loved Piazza unconditionally, right up to the moment they
realized he didn't love them back.
</P>
<P>
   That rude awakening came when the season began, and Piazza was
complaining about what a toll that not knowing if he'd get his $100
million from the Dodgers was taking on him. The Dodgers offered
Piazza the biggest contract in major-league history, and that
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   He revealed himself to be just another mercenary, which is his
prerogative.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a price to pay for following the almighty dollar:
Employers and paying customers expect nothing less than the best.
Before Piazza burned bridges in Los Angeles, fans could have
forgiven Piazza _ even suffered with him _ for his struggles this
season. He'd produced for them in the past. He was one of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   New York fans, on the other hand, have precious few memories of
Piazza doing anything but letting them down in the clutch. They see
a hired gun who isn't earning his $8 million keep this year. They
see somebody who is likely to leave them after the season, so they
don't even realize that _ struggles and all _ Piazza is on pace to
finish the season with 27 homers and 91 RBI. One hot streak and
Piazza could be on his way to another 30-homer, 100-RBI finish. One
hot streak and Piazza could carry the Mets into the playoffs, at
which point anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Power hitters by nature are streaky _ capable of going boom or
bust without a moment's warning. Clearly, Piazza is pressing at the
plate, pressing like never in his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tough year mentally,'' Piazza calls it, and whether he
brought it on himself should be immaterial to Mets fans at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   The more they boo him, the less likely he is to go off on the
sort of rampages that Mets management envisioned when they made the
May 22 trade. The more they boo him, the less likely Piazza is to
spend one New York minute considering signing with the Mets after
the season. The more they boo him, the less likely it is that the
Mets will regret giving up three prospects to rent a player whose
presence caused catcher Todd Hundley the embarrassment of trying to
play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza is going to be a tremendous force in this town,''
Mets co-owner Fred Wilpon was saying in May, when Piazza was still
a conquering hero. ``This is a guy who could become the kind of
player people talked about who played in New York 30, 40, 50 years
ago. We're talking (Mickey) Mantle, (Willie) Mays, DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans have every right to boo Piazza, boo him out of town,
boo him all the way to the Hall of Fame. Still, it seems a peculiar
and self-destructive way to go about making the best of the
situation. Having the right to boo doesn't make it right,
especially if Mets fans hope to have any sort of meaningful
relationship with Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Mets and Mike Piazza have had the most
dysfunctional courtship since Michael Douglas and Glenn Close got
together for a couple of drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a fatal attraction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
