<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDER UPGRADING APPLICATIONS IN LIEU OF USING NEW, OLD WINDOWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Windows 98 is out, but I want to keep Windows 3.1 on my
system as well. I know you can install both Windows 95 and 98 and
still keep Windows 3.1, but can I go ahead and use my Windows 3.1
applications with the Windows 98 installation? Or will I have to
reinstall them all over again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately, if you decide to have both operating systems
on your computer, you will have to reinstall your applications.
</P>
<P>
   When you install Windows 95 or 98 in a folder other than your
system's current Windows folder, it doesn't pick up settings from
your Windows 3.1 setup. If you try to launch your applications from
Windows 98, they become confused and are likely to crash.
</P>
<P>
   If you reinstall them and point them to your Windows 98 setup,
you might render them useless in your Windows 3.1 configuration.
You may have to have two separate installations of your favorite
applications, which would take up lots of hard drive space.
</P>
<P>
   It might be worth it to begin upgrading to Windows 95/98
versions of your favorite applications, rather than try to
reinstall your old Windows 3.1 programs with Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am having a problem with my modem and America Online. I can
connect once to AOL, but unless I turn my computer on and off, I
cannot connect again. I get a message saying that COM2 is being
used by another device.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have an external modem, you can usually turn it on and
off to fix this problem. But with an internal model, there's a
nifty little way to reset it using the Control Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Open the Windows 95/98 Control Panel and launch the Modems
module. Click on the Diagnostics tab and you'll get a box that
shows you the communications ports and modems on your computer.
Click on the modem listing, then click the More Info button.
</P>
<P>
   This will cause the modem to dump its internal information.
You'll get a snapshot of the current settings, and, as a happy
byproduct, your modem will be reset.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one other thing to check. Make sure you don't have any
software that ``listens'' for incoming phone line activity, such as
a voice-mail or fax program. Disable these _ they also can cause
this kind of problem.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's also possible that your modem could be defective.
Have it checked by a qualified technician.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some friends and I heard on TV news recently about a virus
that would affect Windows 95 and 98. We have not heard anything
else since. You were not to turn on your computer Sunday for any
reason or you would be infected. Can you tell us what is going on
with this new virus, and should we be concerned with it?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a very nasty virus called W95.CIH. Fortunately, it's
rare, and it's not that new. The scare you heard Saturday, July 25,
was a bit of an overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   W95.CIH is a virus that harms a computer in two ways. First, it
erases a system's hard drive. Second, if the system has a flash
BIOS _ a BIOS that can be reprogrammed _ it will scramble that
BIOS, rendering the PC unusable.
</P>
<P>
   It plants itself into EXE files on Windows 95 and 98 systems,
and when those programs are run, moves into memory and infects
other files. The most common strain activates on the 26th of every
month, not just July 26. There are strains that activate April 26
and June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Popular virus scanners, such as McAfee VirusScan and Norton
AntiVirus, can detect and remove it. But as I said, it is rare. If
you regularly scan your system, you should be fine. There's no need
to keep your computer off on the 26th of each month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
