<HEADLINE>
PERFECT PORTABLE COMPUTER REMAINS ELUSIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building the perfect small computer seems easy. Make it tiny,
fast, powerful, easy to use and with long battery life. And, oh
yeah _ make it cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this so hard?
</P>
<P>
   I've spent the last few weeks looking at smaller-than-usual
portable computers, ranging from a Windows 98 sub-notebook system
to a ``palmtop.'' While they all fall into the category of
Generally Cool, each has at least one drawback that keeps me from
moving it under the still-empty category headed: Perfect Portable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vaio 505GX, $2,700, Sony: The 505 line is one of the hottest
notebooks in the world right now, and at first glance it's easy to
see why. On the surface, this looks like the ultimate portable PC.
</P>
<P>
   It's incredibly light, at just under 3 pounds. It's thin, at
less than an inch thick. And it's a got a small footprint, 11-by-7
inches. If you're a road warrior, you'll barely notice its presence
in your briefcase as you dash between appointments.
</P>
<P>
   The 505GX has a 266-megahertz Pentium MMX chip, 32 megabytes of
memory and a 2.1-gigabyte hard drive. It comes with a brilliant
10.1-inch active matrix screen that can display in resolutions up
to 800-by-600 pixels in 24-bit color.
</P>
<P>
   Its pointing device is a touchpad that also doubles as a writing
tablet. You can use a built-in stylus on the pad to sign documents
or draw simple pictures.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a 33.6K modem, a single PC-card slot, a Universal
Serial Bus port and a IEEE 1394 connection, also known as iLink or
Firewire. Sony added this so you can attach a camcorder and edit
videos on the Vaio.
</P>
<P>
   What's been left out to make this so slim and light? There are
no removable drives _ the CD and floppy drives are external (and
the CD-ROM drive is an extra-cost option). Sony also has placed the
traditional ports _ monitor, parallel, serial mouse and keyboard _
on a small external unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a dream machine, right? Well, there are a few
problems. First, if you've got big fingers, the
not-quite-full-sized keyboard will drive you nuts. I've got
average-sized hands, and while typing answers to e-mail was
tolerable, typing a lengthy document was not.
</P>
<P>
   And the touchpad leaves a lot to be desired. It was impossible
to set the sensitivity just right. It was either too sluggish or
too jumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the battery life was poor _ I was lucky if I could get
two hours out of the slim cell that's stored in the 505GX's hinge.
Also, power management on the system slows everything down, making
performance abysmal _ it felt like a 486 system. When plugged into
AC power, though, the 505GX was plenty zippy.
</P>
<P>
   If Sony can work out some of these flaws _ particularly making
the keyboard a tad bigger and stabilizing the touchpad _ this could
easily be a home-run product.
</P>
<P>
   _ C-Series 2010C, $900, Compaq Computer Corp.: Compaq's first
system using Microsoft's Windows CE operating system was a bomb,
largely due to a Chiclet-style keyboard and a horrible
black-and-white display that was hard to see in almost any kind of
light.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq learned many lessons from that first product, dubbed the
PC Companion, and fixed them nicely with its C-Series.
</P>
<P>
   The 2010C is packed into a case that's about the size of a
checkbook on steroids and weighs just under a pound. It comes with
20 megabytes of memory, a 640-by-240-pixel passive matrix color
screen and a built-in 33.6K modem, which operates at relatively low
power. In earlier Windows CE units, a modem could drain a battery
in minutes _ this one does much better.
</P>
<P>
   The C-Series 2010C also comes with a feature that lets you
record quick memos to yourself. However, this will drain your
batteries quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The 256-color screen makes all the difference in the world. I've
always liked the Windows CE operating system _ it's great if you
are familiar with Windows 95/98 _ and version 2.0 is even better.
It comes with improved versions of Word, Excel, Internet Explorer
and an e-mail client that works a lot like Outlook and Outlook
Express.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great e-mail machine and organizer, but don't expect
it to do much more than that. The keyboard, while improved, is
useless for longer documents.
</P>
<P>
   _ PalmIII, $400, 3Com.: The PalmIII is the latest incarnation of
3Com's hand-held line previously known as the PalmPilot. These
6-ounce devices, which can fit in a dress-shirt pocket, have
developed a cult following that rivals that of the now-discontinued
Apple Newton.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no wonder. The PalmIII is a nifty device, though
extremely limited in its capabilities. However, that's by design;
it doesn't try to be all things.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmIII comes with two megabytes of memory (enough to hold
up to 6,000 contacts), an infrared port for wireless connections, a
docking station for connecting to your PC and a handful of built-in
software programs. Searching and retrieving information is
lightning-fast, which makes this hand-held device perfect for
storing information you need to get quickly.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy add-ons that extend the Palm's capabilities, turning
it into a pager or e-mail retriever. However, the latter is
something of a kludge _ you must dial up the PC where you get your
e-mail, and then download from there. You can't connect directly to
an e-mail server.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm's built-in software is simple and very intuitive.
Transferring data is foolproof _ you just push a button on the
Palm's docking station to synchronize everything.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to use it, though, is to rely on entering
information via your PC, then dumping it into the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Palm's main flaw is its reliance on
handwriting recognition. It uses Graffiti, a program that converts
specially designed letters into standard text. Unfortunately, you
must train yourself to use stylized characters, which, with my
notoriously nasty handwriting, I found quite tedious. You can fall
back to using an onscreen keyboard, but it's very slow going.
</P>
<P>
   I really like the Palm, even if it falls short of perfection.
But then, don't they all?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
