<HEADLINE>
CYRK TIES FUTURE TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a company that mostly made promotional T-shirts for the
likes of Reebok and Pepsi, Cyrk Inc. sees a big part of its future
in the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Its relationship with Yahoo Inc., the Internet search service,
is an example of how Cyrk hopes to expand its business beyond just
supplying Happy Meal toys for McDonald's and Marlboro Gear to
cigarette smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 12 years ago, Cyrk initially had a simple mission: It
made caps, shirts, and gym bags that big companies use to advertise
themselves and reward their most loyal customers. But now with help
of several acquisitions, the Gloucester, Mass. company is looking
to become something more as it begins to heavily promote a Yahoo
gear cyberstore it helped launch earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossing loyalty programs with electronic commerce is just one
of the new ways in which Cyrk is building brand value for its
clients,'' Cyrk notes hopefully in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks know how loyalty programs work. Save enough Pepsi
bottlecaps, and the bottlecaps can be redeemed for Pepsi-branded
merchandise that's featured in a special catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that consumers will have an incentive to load up on
Pepsi and that they won't be tempted to drink something else.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cyrk is experimenting with similar incentives for Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   On one front, Cyrk is assisting Yahoo with its branded credit
card. Those who sign up for a Yahoo Visa card qualify for the
equivalent of frequent flyer miles. As consumers pay for goods and
services with the credit card, Cyrk helps to electronically track
how many points an individual consumer has earned.
</P>
<P>
   In a traditional loyalty program, consumers have limited choices
for redeeming their coupons. For example, hoarded Marlboro coupons
can be swapped only for Marlboro Gear.
</P>
<P>
   But with an electronic loyalty progam, points can be used at any
number of cyberstores. In Yahoo's case, that includes on-line
bookstore Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   For Yahoo, the advantage of such a program is that it not only
provides Yahoo with an ``incremental revenue opportunity,'' but it
also encourages more on-line shopping over the Yahoo network, says
Laurel Rossi, Cyrk's chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the credit-card program, Cyrk operates a separate
cyberstore that sells Yahoo-branded gear such as shirts, clocks,
and slinky toys.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the goal here is to establish ``Yahoo as a household
name, a fun pop-culture brand,'' says Karen V. Edwards, Yahoo's
vice president of brand marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Cyrk envisions its Yahoo relationships evolving into something
far more than T-shirt sales. One possibility is awarding points to
subscribers of Yahoo's electronic mail service; points could be
redeemed for discounts on Yahoo gear.
</P>
<P>
   The more e-mail a person sends, the more discounts he or she
might qualify for. The discounts would come in the form of an
e-mail coupon. And, of course, the more subscribers use Yahoo
e-mail, the more likely they will be exposed to the banner
advertising that Yahoo includes on its Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   For Cyrk, the Internet has the potential for shoring up a
weakness that has long dogged the company, a weakness that was one
reason it had to lay off nearly a third of its worldwide work force
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, Cyrk has had to rely heavily on a few
giant clients such as McDonald's and Marlboro because only such
``mega-brands'' have the resources to mount big loyalty rewards
programs, Rossi says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, nearly 90 percent of its revenues came from Philip
Morris Inc., and in Cyrk's last fiscal year, McDonald's Corp.
accounted for about a third of its $559 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rossi, the Internet helps make loyalty programs
affordable to smaller companies, partly by squeezing out the hassle
and high expense of paper coupons and paper catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   And so for Cyrk, the Internet may be an opportunity to lessen
its dependency on a few big customers and to establish ongoing
relationships with a wide range of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be the leading promotional resource for the
world's best brands,'' says Dave Wilson, Cyrk's managing director
of client services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
