<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-TUMULT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAR MARKET'S INFLUENCE ON FUNDS WATCHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Having buckled their seat belts to sit tight through
Wall Street's tumultuous ride, mutual fund investors have displayed
steady-headed reason in holding onto their stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   But asset management firms and investment specialists were
divided Thursday over whether investors would show such
resoluteness and avoid panic-selling should a market correction
turn into an extended bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major fund groups have been preaching for some time that the
market's gains cannot be sustained,'' said Burton J. Greenwald, an
investment consultant in Philadelphia. ``But the real test will
come if the market drops to 8000.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors aren't thinking about what happens if things really
go down,'' added David Masters of MicropalInc., a fund consulting
firm. ``They're just waiting for it all to go back up again.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Americans have fallen for mutual funds this decade, funnelling
billions of dollars into stock funds and playing a major role in
stoking the bull market's run.
</P>
<P>
   But fund firms said Thursday that shareholders had shown once
again that they had learned to ride out market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that investors are in the market for the long
haul and have been very calm,'' said Anne Crowley, a spokeswoman
for Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest fund firm.
``Thursday,'' she added, ``was a very typical day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, becalmed after two days of
gyrations and heavy trading, nudged up 30.90, or 0.4 percent, to
close at 8577.68 Thursday. It was still down 3.4 percent for the
week. The break came two days after the Dow sank nearly 300 points,
or 3.4 percent, to 8487.31 on Tuesday _ its worst one-day drop of
1998 and more than 9 percent below its record high of 9367.84 on
July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Other indexes also rose Thursday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index climbed 8.21, or 0.8 percent, to 1089.64. The Nasdaq
Composite index, dominated by computer companies, saored 41.31, or
2.3 percent, to 1829.51, its biggest gain in five months.
</P>
<P>
   The US market has been pressured by disappointing US corporate
earnings due to Asia's financial crisis, and, more recently,
President Clinton's political woes .
</P>
<P>
   To reassure worried fund investors, Fidelity had trotted out
investment icon Peter M. Lynch, posting a question-and-answer page
with the legendary stockpicker on its Web &UR;  &LR; site. But the firm also
reported positive net cash flows over the past three days, meaning
that investors put more money into mutual funds than they pulled
out. By Thursday, a standby reserve guard to man the telephones and
take incoming calls from investors was no longer needed, Crowley
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Putnam Investments, spokesman Matthew Keenan said the volume
of calls from fund shareholders fell 7 percent Thursday after
spiking 15 to 20 percent in previous days. ``People have stayed the
course,'' he said, adding that customers bought more Putnam funds
Thursday than they sold.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may have held onto stock funds, but they have not been
putting new money into such funds. Money-market funds, a safe haven
in times of volatility, had attracted $7.3 billion in new
investments so far this week, double the amount of last October,
when the market suffered a 7.2 percent drop, according to IBC
Financial Data Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Individual fund investors own 20 percent of all US corporate
equity, according to the Investment Company Institute, a fact that
makes them crucial players in any market swings.
</P>
<P>
   Investment planners have been preaching for years about the
necessity of not rashly pulling long-term retirement money out of
the market. Retirement assets accounted for 35 percent of all
mutual fund assets at the end of 1996. Financial advisers have also
been telling investors to expect average annual gains of 10 to 12
percent, and not the high double-digit returns of recent years.
Some industry players say the advice is sinking in.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Group, which sells highly popular index funds, said
Thursday that investors had not abandoned index funds despite a
drop in returns. ``Investors have reaffirmed their belief that
staying the course is the best course in times of volatility,''
said Vanguard spokesman Brian Mattes. He said ``very few''
shareholders of the Vanguard Index 500 fund and other index funds
had sold their holdings. Vanguard had not needed to call out its
``Swiss Army'' of 1,000 executives to man telephones, and that
calls from shareholders had subsided.
</P>
<P>
   But industry watchers outside the fund firms detect storm clouds
in the lull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three days is hardly a test of the pudding,'' said James E.
Wilson, a financial planner in Columbia, S.C. ``I don't know if
over a three month fall, people would stay put.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTOCROSS-FAMILY-2TAK     08-07 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOCROSS-FAMILY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY OUTRACE MISFORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LEMPSTER, N.H. _ ``Can we race now?''
</P>
<P>
   Morning had made its way through the southwestern New Hampshire
woods, casting a bright, cloudless daybreak over a motocross theme
park that took up 132 acres of the middle of nowhere. Amid smoking
campfire coals and sleepy-eyed folks who walked along rows of
recreational vehicles and hundreds of motorcycles, the 5-year-old
boy in the racing suit sat on his dirt bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we race now?'' Jacob Robinson of Nashua said again with a
sigh, tired of waiting after 2 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline and David Robinson did not grow weary of their son's
persistent imploring. They knew how much he had anticipated this
morning since they promised him he could join his brothers Joshua
and Jeremiah in motocross competition three weeks before. For them,
it also was a time of anticipation. And of mixed emotions and
silent prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Jacob suffered a seizure and was subsequently
diagnosed with Arnold-Chiari Syndrome, a rare brain malformation in
which part of the cerebellum pushes down against the spinal canal.
He underwent surgery to correct the problem at Children's Hospital
in Boston, yet he must have an MRI every six months to make certain
the surgery hasn't generated too much pressure against his brain.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason the Robinsons forbade the buoyant youngster
from competing in motocross. Yet undoubtedly, they knew they
couldn't hold him back for long, not with 6-year-old brother
Jeremiah making such exceptional strides in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah was born with one nostril and bilateral club feet so
severe that his feet were turned almost completely backward. He
wore a cast from the hips down from the time he was 10 days old
until he was 3. When he was 2, he underwent reconstructive surgery,
during which doctors cut every bone in his feet below the arch into
smaller pieces, then inserted pins to make them face forward.
</P>
<P>
   After being in braces and wheelchairs until he was 4, Jeremiah
took up sports with varying success. But after his father _ himself
a motocross racer _ bought the three boys dirt bikes for Christmas
last year, Jeremiah was hooked. Pauline and David stifled their
fears to allow him to race, and he has become a hit at Jolly Roger
Moto-Sports Park, placing second in the New Hampshire Challenge
Motocross Series' 50-cc A-class (age 4-6) standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Robinsons tried to get Jacob to take part in his brother's
races by being one of the flag officials, but it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   So once again, the former high school sweethearts from
Billerica, Mass., led their family along a course of hope and fear
and courage and uncertainty, bolstered by two boyish smiles as
bright as a New Hampshire morning, haunted by voices of family and
friends who question whether they're doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
They don't give up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Can we race now?'' Jacob Robinson asked again. Soon the young
racers were summoned for the two-lap practice run along the
one-eighth-of-a-mile track of steep hills and uneven curves.
Pauline and David took up stations at various points, she along
three consecutive humps, he at the top of the final incline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacob and I walked the track last night so he would know where
to go,'' Pauline said. ``I say my prayers before each race. I get
so nervous. But I guess I wouldn't be normal if I didn't get
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   It is often said that we are never burdened with more than we
can bear. How agitating it must be for the Creator to witness those
who buckle under the weight of mere milligrams of hardship _ folks
who confuse steppingstones for stumbling blocks and mourn losses
rather than count blessings _ and how perplexing it must be to see
the Robinson family coexisting among such whiners.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Joshua and Jeremiah Robinson are more courageous and
resilient than most adults _ particularly those who would chide
their parents for allowing them to be thrill seekers. They have a
will and tenacity that are perfect for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fearless, especially Jeremiah,'' said Gerald
Renillard, Pauline's father. ``When they were giving him stitches
in the hospital, doctors couldn't get over him. He was laying there
and then he said, `Aren't you done yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   With all they've been through in such a short time, the two boys
seem unfazed by steep hills and high-banked turns. Meanwhile, both
parents show them strength in the face of apprehension with support
and encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same time, Pauline Robinson endures her own medical
battles.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she was diagnosed with Sjogren's Syndrome, an
autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system reacts against
itself, destroying exocrine glands, including those that secrete
saliva and tears. Women are nine times likelier to be affected than
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like having the flu every day of your life,'' said
Barbara Henry, president of the National Sjogren's Syndrome
Association. She added that if the condition is not detected and
treated early, it can lead to lymphoma, which can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to put Pauline's disease into remission have failed thus
far. ``I know what my kids are going through, because of my
disease,'' she said. ``We don't know what tomorrow is going to
bring. At least we all know, if I pass away, I enjoyed watching my
kids ride. Know what I'm saying?
</P>
<P>
   ``People criticize us for allowing them to race in motocross.
Some are friends, some family. We always tell people not to
prejudge us, because we love our sons more than anything. We
realize how short life is, all the surgeries they've had. I just
want them to be happy and support whatever they want. If we keep
teaching them the right way, they should be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cheers and fears
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the practice run began, a sound similar to the buzzing of
angry wasps could be heard in the distance. Then over the first
hill they came, youngsters storming along the track in multicolored
suits, revving their engines along each turn. Bike No. 5 scaled its
first hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Jeremiah. I don't see Jake,'' Pauline Robinson
muttered. Then Jacob Robinson's bike, No. 5X, headed downhill.
Pauline could hardly control her emotions. As her sons whizzed by
her, she gave the thumbs-up sign, then followed their progress up a
hill, watching until they were both out of sight, pumping her fist
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The first race, however, wasn't without mishap. On the first
table-top jump, a hill that was completely flat at the top,
Jeremiah careened off his bike and tumbled down the slope. ``Oh,
Jeremiah fell,'' yelled Pauline, scaling the wall between the hill
and her son with the dexterity of a mountain climber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
