<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIGHAM PROVIDES FIGHTING SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ It was a little too quiet for Larry Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there had been hitting and shoving at various times during
training camp. Emotions had run high. But it was never sustained
emotion, like the Patriots display when they're going well.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing this, Whigham, the All-Pro special-teams player,
came to practice Thursday ``with a little something on my
shoulder.'' He meant, of course, that he had a chip on his
shoulder. He wanted to make a point. Stir the masses.
</P>
<P>
   So on a goal line-line stand, usually emotional in nature,
Whigham hit second-year tackle Ed Ellis a little harder than a
safety normally would hit an offensive lineman. Ellis, who is 340
pounds, decided he wasn't going to take it from a 200-pound
defensive back. So they exchanged shoves and then punches. From
there, smaller skirmishes broke out, with offensive tackle Zefross
Moss also going after Whigham while defensive end Willie McGinest
was seen taking a swing at the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Whigham had accomplished his goal. Of course, there can
sometimes be excess. On the next play, the emotion didn't stop. Ty
Law got into a shoving match with Lovett Purnell. Shawn Jefferson
then got shoved around a circle of players. Lastly, second-year
linebacker Bernard Russ exchanged words and then blows with Rod
Rutledge. The rookie tight end shoved Russ, then knocked his helmet
off after Russ threw an overhand right to Rutledge's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing jumping in there?'' defensive coordinator
Steve Sidwell screamed at Russ, who had come on to the field while
Law and Purnell were shoving. ``Get your ass off the field!''
</P>
<P>
   The series of confrontations broke up the monotony. Precisely
what Whigham was getting sick of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not me ... as far as fighting,'' Whigham said. ``This
team needs spunk. Pete Carroll's philosophy is a laid-back
philosophy. It's great for a football team. My philosophy is guys
need to get revved up and get ready to play football. If it takes
getting a little fired up in practice, that's what needs to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But taking on a 340-pound lineman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred, 400, 500 pounds _ it doesn't matter,'' said
Whigham. ``I didn't even know who I was fighting. Some guys knew I
was coming to practice looking for some contact after Thursday. It
wasn't anything that happened. It's what didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team needed that today. Everybody is going around here
nice and easy. Training camp isn't that hard. Nobody's bitching at
anybody. Guys were just trying to make their assignments. This team
is known for a little more than that. This team has a spunk about
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight was just a part of the frustrations of the camp, but
it was positive. I spoke to the rookie defensive backs the entire
night and I told them that I made this football team on effort. I
told them after this week, they're going to make a cut: `I'm not
gonna say this, but one of you guys is gonna make it on effort. The
least you can do is play each time like it's your last.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whigham's self-assessment was correct. He won over Bill Parcells
because he was a little more hyper than most. He wanted Parcells to
notice him and he made his mark on special teams, causing moments
of pure chaos for the opposition. Meanwhile, he learned to play
strong safety and has gradually improved. At 6 feet 2 inches, 205
pounds, he's very similar in size to Tebucky Jones, leading some of
his teammates to wonder why he wasn't tried at the right cornerback
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have tried it, but they drafted the kid
No. 1 and he's very talented, very fast, and very tough,'' siad
Whigham. ``If he can learn to play corner right away in this
league, that's a real plus. If not, last year's No. 1 (Chris Canty)
has played well and maybe he can do the job there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Whigham earned recognition for his efforts on special
teams, being voted to the Pro Bowl. But it was a frustrating season
for Whigham, who was often double- and triple-teamed. Even more
frustrating was that no one else took charge and made the big hit
or the big play. This year he sees younger, faster, more aggressive
players who might take the pressure off him and he's excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's there, but it has to come out,'' said Whigham. ``We
didn't show that intensity against San Francisco and we have to
from here on out. There are four games left before the season
starts, but that creeps up on you quickly. We have to be ready,
completely ready to play Denver. The last two years we played them,
we haven't been at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Whigham believes every camp, every season has a turning point.
He thought that occurred Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we stepped up our game to another level,'' he said. ``We
knew we could do it. As a veteran team that's experienced, we know
when it's time to do that. Our team took a giant step today.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll appreciated what Whigham was trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a real spirit for the game,'' said the coach. ``He
works hard. He's a very effective special-teams guy. His ability to
get people jacked up is very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll credited his players with excellent intensity and
aggressiveness in the morning practice but thought they might have
been irresponsible with the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we crossed that line a couple of times when a couple of
guys lost their poise,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Russ's episode, he said, ``There was a battle going
on in seven-on-sevens where a guy not even in the drill came in and
got involved, and that was a tremendous teaching opportunity.
Things like that are looked down upon by the league office. There
are fines for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whigham didn't cross the line. He just danced on the chalk a
bit. He is the poster boy for intensity. Special-teams coach Dante
Scarnecchia recently cited him as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach was talking about intensity, and a couple of plays he
showed were plays involving me being effective,'' said Whigham.
``It was good for my confidence to show guys that this was the
intensity we need. I thought to myself, `I wasn't even going all
out. If he thought this was good and if I can take it up another
level, then maybe I can make my dreams come true.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was making his teammates dizzy Thursday. He exchanged barbs
with Vincent Brisby. He gave rookie fullback Chris Floyd a shot
from behind on a special-teams play.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was all too quiet, almost church-like, for Whigham, who
added a little noise and made sure he will never be mistaken for an
altar boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
