<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMJANOVICH PERFECT FOR US COACHING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOULIAGMENI, Greece _ Arrogant. Pompous. Vain. Self-absorbed.
Pretentious. Imperial.
</P>
<P>
   What a pleasure it is to report that two-time NBA championship
coach Rudy Tomjanovich is none of these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always told my assistants,'' he says, ``that if I ever
change, they have my permission to take a running start and kick me
in the ass.''
</P>
<P>
   He is known universally throughout the NBA as Rudy T; nothing
more, nothing less. He doesn't have a ``guy'' hanging around to
say, ``Yes, Rudy.'' He's the same low-key individual he was when he
came into the NBA 28 years ago as a rookie forward with the San
Diego Rockets, except that he has a couple of rings and a lot more
money.
</P>
<P>
   For which, by the way, he's very grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin Murphy was my next-door neighbor when we played
together in Houston,'' Rudy reminisces, ``and we used to have these
little talks while we were leaning on the mailboxes. They were
talks people in the league should have a lot more often. They were
about how lucky we are to be getting paid to be playing a game we
love.''
</P>
<P>
   He's played it (11 years) and scouted it (two years) and
assistant-coached it (nine years and change) and head-coached it
(the past six-plus years), and now he is sitting in a luxury hotel
gazing out at the azure Aegean as the man in charge of a mystery
team with the letters ``USA'' on its chest. Rudy, Rudy, a partly
confused and partly ignorant nation now turns its lonely eyes to
you. They have asked you, Rudy Tomjanovich, the pride of Hamtramck,
Mich., to take this collection of Off-Broadway basketball players
into battle at the world championships in Athens. They have asked
you, Rudy Tomjanovich, to bring home the gold medal in order that
(a) we won't have to go through some sort of messy qualifying for
the Sydney Olympics two years hence, and (b) we don't lose our
international bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   They are asking you, Rudy Tomjanovich, to do this, and now what
is this you are saying, something about not even feeling like a
coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always amazing for me to be addressed that way,'' he
says. ``A lot of people in the beginning, knowing that I wasn't a
confrontational-type person, doubted that I could coach. Now, even
after all this time, someone will start off, `Coach,' and it'll hit
me: `They're calling me `Coach'?''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T has never been part of any NBA loop. Some guys go all
over the world every summer giving clinics, with junkets here and
there for either the league or a shoe company. Rudy stays home in
Houston and hopes his air conditioning doesn't break. ``I never
even heard of any of that stuff,'' he shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   So this was going to be a nice ceremonial job, Rudy T's reward
for winning the non-Michael NBA titles in 1994 and '95. He was
getting the keys to the Porsche as sort of a Good Guy Lifetime
Achievement Award. He and his family would get free trips to Monte
Carlo, Rome, and Athens, and the best part was going to be that he
wouldn't even have to coach. The NBA stars would walk through this
tournament, and in years to come, people wouldn't even remember who
coached them in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   That fantasy died with The Lockout. Rudy T is now being forced
into some serious, stay-up-all-night coaching. Hyperbole? Uh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up till 5 a.m. after losing to Lithuania,'' he
reports. ``We had to put stuff together to show them what they did
wrong against Lithuania (an 84-82 loss) and then we had to get
ready for a completely different team in South Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   Be assured that if Chuck Daly stayed up until 5 a.m. in
Barcelona or Don Nelson stayed up until 5 a.m. in Toronto at the
1994 worlds, it was voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy doesn't pine for a team he never had. Anyway, this job is
sure a lot more interesting than one in which your only concern is
keeping already pampered stars happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could only lose in the other situation,'' he points out.
``You'd be critiqued for winning by 15 instead of 25.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Rudy, a.k.a. Mr. Understatement. How about being blasted
for not winning by 40?
</P>
<P>
   Rudy and assistants Del Harris and Lon Kruger had about two
weeks to whittle an original list of 30 players to 15 before
heading out for three exhibitions en route to Athens. That 15
became 12, and here they are, getting ready for this evening's
quarterfinal match against up-and-down Italy. Rudy's team is good
enough to win, and it's also fragile enough to lose. The
international pundits don't believe in it. Yugoslavia remains the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The players are lucky to have him, but of course, all except the
older members of the team (like, say, 34-year-old Wendell Alexis)
are clueless when it comes to their history. They don't know they
are being prepped by a man who averaged as many as 24.5 points per
game for a full season and was a career 50 percent shooter. ``Jason
Sasser says to me the other day, `Coach, did you play?''' Rudy
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they know that he played, they have absolutely no
idea how he played. They don't know that in the entire history of
basketball, no man has ever come close to Rudy T as the master of
the long-distance bank shot. This information is not going to win
them today's game, but just the same, they should know exactly who
this man is.
</P>
<P>
   This job is broadening Rudy because it's so radically different
from anything he has known. ``During the playoffs, I pride myself
on being able to make adjustments in time for the next game,'' he
says, ``but here you make your adjustments on the fly. And then you
play a team the following day that presents a completely different
set of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The junket has turned into pure hard work, but it will be worth
it if Rudy gets to see his team mount the top step of the podium
Sunday. ``It would be a very big thing,'' he says, ``not so much
for me but for them. I would really get emotional for them if we
can pull this off. This is a great story. You have this group of
strangers who've come here from all over the world, from different
levels of basketball, and who have come together in such a short
period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   This Off-Broadway team didn't need a genius or an author as
coach. It needed a sincere guy with a lot of experience and just
the right human touch. The plain truth is that the Off-Broadway
team has gotten the coach who suits it to a, yes, T.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
