<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BILLY-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BILLY'S HOLLYWOOD SCREEN KISS' IS CHARMING, BITTERSWEET COMEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' is a disarming romantic comedy
that is long on charm, sharply observed and bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   It opens with a Polaroid snapshot of Billy, waving at the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a homosexual,'' says Billy. ``I am also a fan of old
Hollywood movies, especially bad women's melodramas. I am a
photographer specializing in Polaroids. And an all-around nice
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy has come from his home in the Midwest, where, he says,
there are lots of heterosexuals but not many gays, to Los Angeles,
where he figures he finally has a lot better chance to find someone
of his own sexual persuasion to love. He also hopes he will have a
better chance of finding a market for his photos.
</P>
<P>
   Billy, played winningly and without any affectation by Sean P.
Hayes, is in the midst of an affair with a guy who keeps telling
him he's ``so special,'' but who has another boyfriend. Billy wants
romance, not just sex.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a coffee shop with his friend Georgiana, who has
appointed herself Billy's romantic adviser, Billy meets the man of
his dreams, Gabriel. Gabriel, played by Brad Rowe, a dead ringer
for Brad Pitt, responds in a friendly way to Billy, accepting
invitations to a party and later to a movie.
</P>
<P>
   But Gabriel also keeps talking about his girlfriend in San
Francisco. And he rejects Billy's tentative overtures to romance.
Is he straight? Is he gay? Gabriel's conflicting signals drive
Billy to distraction. He decides Gabriel is straight, but hopes he
might be open to new experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel agrees to model for a series of Polaroids that Billy is
shooting parodying romantic scenes in Hollywood movies such as
``From Here to Eternity.'' But when a famous photographer (played
by the ever eccentric Paul Bartel) asks Gabriel to pose for him in
Catalina, Billy is beside himself with worry. Billy grabs Georgiana
and they rush off to Catalina. Billy still hopes to win Gabriel's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Tommy O'Haver enlivens the simple story with
amusing frills. When troubled, Billy's dreams turn into versions of
famous movies, with himself and Gabriel in the lead roles. A couple
of these are amusing; a couple are undeveloped and fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   When Billy tells Gabriel the story of how he learned as a child
that he was gay, the memory is told in Polaroid snapshots, the
self-pity cut by the amusing photos.
</P>
<P>
   There are also several subplots, such as Georgiana and her
boyfriends. Georgiana is one of those smart people whose brain
seems to turn off completely when someone of the opposite sex shows
an interest.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Greek chorus, three transvestites who pop
up at parties lip-syncing torch songs. Personally, I could have
done with a lot less of them, but they are amusingly awful.
</P>
<P>
   The real appeal of the story is Billy. Whether Gabriel turns out
to be straight or gay, in love with Billy or just a friend, we
don't want Billy to be unhappy. Like he said, he's an ``all-around
nice guy'' and overdue for a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first feature film for writer-director Tommy
O'Haver, though he has a lot of experience on short films. (He's
currently writing a feature film of the comic ``Archie'' for
Universal.) His strong point seems to be in writing little scenes
of dialogue and in gentle satire of people's hang-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about as slight as they come. It certainly doesn't
break any new ground, either as a gay film or romance, except for
the fact of treating the whole subject as a nonissue. Anyone who
feels all gay films should address issues such as AIDS or emotional
torment will find none of that here.
</P>
<P>
   The romance and sex _ there's not much of the latter _ is
handled with a very light touch, as you would expect in any
romantic comedy. There's more kissing than in ``In and Out,'' but
not much more.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Billy's feelings and situation are universal, whatever
the sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, as Billy, plays it low-key but he has a sure comic touch.
In September he will turn up on television in a new TV series,
``Will and Grace,'' again playing a gay character.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first film for Rowe, who played the boyfriend of
James Brolin's daughter on TV's ``Pensacola.'' He will next be seen
in ``Stonebrook'' with Sam Shephard. Rowe displays a shy sex-appeal
screen presence perfect for this role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss,'' which is rated R, was
nominated for the Grand Jury Prize at this year's Sundance Film
Festival. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
