<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KETEYIAN GETS IT STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armen Keteyian is not the typical sideline reporter.
He is a news guy, capable of being fair, accurate, and tough.
</P>
<P>
   His selection, then, by CBS to join its top NFL broadcast team
of Greg Gumbel and Phil Simms signals a transformation in the job
usually limited to injury reports, weather updates, and occasional
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   How this plays out during the season remains to be seen, but
it's clear Keteyian wants to broaden the job's scope.
</P>
<P>
   Sports is news, after all, and the off-field behavior of
athletes has become a never-ending source of front-page stories and
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though CBS is an NFL partner, spending $500 million a year
to secure the broadcast rights after a five-year absence, Keteyian
said his hiring signals the network's ``willingness to dig deep''
and cover ``the NFL as a news story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a reporter first,'' Keteyian said. ``I'm proud of the fact
that I try to be as accurate and fair and provide for viewers
(news) as unfiltered as I can make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keteyian learned the sports-as-news approach during his
eight-year stint with Dick Schaap at ABC. Of the 400 or so stories
he reported, almsot 75 percent involved legal, social, or ethical
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost as if I was a cult of one,'' Keteyian said.
Gradually, more and more newspapers and television networks have
assigned reporters to cover sports as a business.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly or wrongly, athletes have become role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an obligation factor,'' Keteyian said. ``Given this
society's emphasis on sports, professional athletes have almost by
default become role models. Some are incapable of handling that
responsibility and would perform a public service if they stayed
out of the press. Instead of being role mdoels, some have become
poster boys for the FBI Most Wanted List.''
</P>
<P>
   Keteyian, 45, bounced around newspapers for a while, then landed
at Sports Illustrated. In addition to CBS, he reports for HBO's
``Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel'' and ``Inside the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his best-known recent reports was on the point-shaving
scandal at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meet the CBS lineup
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, CBS unveiled its talent and production crews
assigned to the NFL. They range from Marcus Allen, a superstar
running back, to Beasley Reese, a former defensive back for the New
York Giants. There also are some veterans, like Verne Lundquist,
Don Criqui, and Jim Nantz. Mark May, Randy Cross, Simms, and Sam
Wyche have both NFL and broadcast experience ... HBO Sports'
``Inside the NFL'' debuts Sept. 3 for its 22d season. Len Dawson
and Nick Buoniconti are joined by Cris Collinsworth ... Fox Sports
has until next Friday to decide whether to pay the NHL as much as a
reported $600 million for exclusive US broadcasting rights.
According to the Wall Street Journal and Associated Press, the Walt
Disney Company, which owns ESPN and ABC, offered the NHL that
amount despite hockey's dismal television ratings. Fox had a 1.4
rating last season, down from 2.0 in 1996-97. Fox is entering the
last year of its $155 million, five-year deal. ESPN's $100 million,
seven-year deal also expires after next season ... One-on-One
Sports (1510) has former Notre Dame football coach Lou Holtz on
Monday to talk about the upcoming college season and his new book,
``Winning Every Day.'' The call-in show starts at 2 p.m. ... On
Aug. 22, HBO airs two fights: Arturo Gatti vs. Ivan Robinson and
Fernando Vargas vs. Darren Maciunski. TNT airs three title fights
Sept. 22: Shane Mosley vs. Eduardo Morales, Angel Manfredy vs. Jeff
Mason, and Masibulele Makepula vs. an opponent still to be named
... CNN/SI's Vince Cellini joins Fred Hickman as co-anchor for
CNN's ``Sports Tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
