<SLUG> BC-CAR-NENGLAND-SPEEDWAYS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AROUND THE OVALS OF NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARRE, Vt. _ Drivers who have mastered speedways at Daytona,
Indianapolis, and Talladega are loaded with unmitigated gall. They
dart around mile-long tracks for 500 laps, often passing each other
on straightaways a mobile home could get through, then the winning
team stages a raucous celebration in Victory Lane, as if they've
done something exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Such drivers should spend Sept. 27 racing at Thunder Road
International Speedbowl. They would discover that exceptional is
when you're among 24 cars running in a three-stage, 150-mile race
around a quarter-mile, high-banked oval that narrows from three car
widths to two in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   They would discover that if you win the first of the three
50-lap stages, you must go to the rear for the second beacuse the
field starts in the inverse order of finish. The process is
repeated for the third stage. Points are given for each finish (one
for first, two for second, and so on), and the driver with the
fewest points claims a one-payoff prize.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, many drivers on the Winston Cup circuit have already
heard of the Milk Bowl, one of the most popular and challenging
short-track races in the sport. The 35th running of the event will
feature qualifying (which determines the order of the first stage)
Sept 26.
</P>
<P>
   First prize is $3,000. The race is also the final event in the
Texaco/Havoline Late Model Racing Series. The winner receives 80
series points.
</P>
<P>
   The Milk Bowl was created by Thunder Road founder and president
Ken Squier, a Vermont resident who does commentary on NASCAR races
for CBS. The name is derived from Vermont's dairy industry. The
three-stage format, he said, was adapted from hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the major races today on TV are from the era of the
500-mile race which began in Indianapolis,'' he said. ``All of a
sudden, we're not a `War and Peace' reading society, we're a
Reader's Digest reading society. We wanted to try to create a race
that fit the tempo of what people expected today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most exciting thing the race has is its start. Once you
got them started, outside those moments of stark terror, a race is
a race. If you were to take hockey, which has three periods to
carry the action, put that into a race, then you have three starts,
four different potential winners.''
</P>
<P>
   But only one payoff, because as Squier found out in the early
years, ``everyone wants to beat the system.'' Thunder Road used to
award prizes to segment winners but discovered drivers would drop
out of the first race, complaining of mechanical problems, thereby
putting them at the front for the second.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 22 Milk Bowl winners (seven drivers have won the race at
least twice, with Robbie Crouch winning it a record four times),
only three have captured all three segments. Ten drivers have
claimed the championship without winning a segment. Three have won
two segments without winning the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a phenomenal race because you can have the best day of
your career and still finish seventh,'' said Thunder Road announcer
Dave Moody.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you get past 24 cars driving at speeds of up to 75
miles an hour around a narrow, quarter-mile course? ``You have to
be patient while being aggressive at the same time,'' said Phil
Scott of Montpelier, who won the race last year, finishing third in
the first stage, first in the second, and second in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we like to do in a 50-lap event, we may run 18th for 25
laps until things get cleared out, until there's a lane you can go
in so you can pass cars. Then you have to make a mad dash for the
last 25, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Thunder Road drivers are accustomed to such a
format: All weekly events are handicapped so the best drivers start
from the rear. ``When you've got a racetrack in New England that's
doing well, you'll see they've got good car counts and good
handicapping, where they start the best guys out back and they make
them race to the front,'' said general manager Tom Curley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lot of whining and a lot of the best drivers wishing
they could start up front. That's obviously the easy way, but it's
lousy for the race fans.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the Milk Bowl. Fans come with pen and pad in hand to
tabulate scores, knowing what each racer must do in the final
segment to win. Some stay long after the race to check their count
against the official tally.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all they stay for. There's one more wrinkle to the
Milk Bowl you won't see on the Winston Cup circuit: The winner must
kiss a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``After winning the Milk Bowl, it's wonderful (to kiss a cow),''
said Scott.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AGAWAM, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You go to a racetrack every day and work on the pit crew of an
accomplished driver, and invariably, you're left with one thought
that spins around in your head like a fine-tuned racer around a
slick asphalt oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After working on her brother's pit crew for six years, Kris
Valerio put that conviction to the test in 1995. The Bristol,
Conn., resident purchased Rob Valerio's Strictly Stock Division car
after the former two-time Strictly Stock champion moved up a
division. It didn't take Kris long to prove she had a knack for the
sport, too: She earned rookie of the year honors in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Now the siblings race alongside each other in the Teddy Bear
Pools Truck Division. They are among the more competitive drivers
at Riverside Park Speedway, a quarter-mile, high-banked oval that
features as many as seven racing divisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
