<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-MONEY-HNS &LR;      08-07 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MORE MONEY AND POWER, WOMEN SEEK FINANCIAL SAVVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After Princess Diana was killed in a Paris car
crash last year, people recalled her fairy-tale rise to fortune.
But few realized that she shared a common trait with many women:
financial dependency.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a sheltered financial life, Diana went straight from her
father's home to the realm of Prince Charles. She left a job paying
an hourly wage in her hometown for life with royalty. Other people
paid her bills. She never handled her own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very financially naive,'' said Victoria Collins, an
author and financial adviser at Keller, Coad, Collins, Hakopian &AMP;
Leisure Investment Counsel Inc. in Irvine, Calif. ``She did share
things in common with women going through divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins spoke Thursday on the investment styles of women at The
Money Show, a popular financial conference that draws thousands of
small investors each year to San Francisco, Las Vegas, Seattle,
Chicago and Orlando. The conference was organized by InterShow of
Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In a session called ``A Smart Woman's Guide to Life and Money,''
investment advisers warned the audience that some women still are
enslaved to out-of-date attitudes about money and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Older women grew up in a time when their fathers controlled the
family money. Women weren't allowed to talk about finance. And if
their Depression-era fathers gambled on Wall Street, they'd buy
only the safest blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women lack a certain confidence on this topic,'' said Gail
Seneca, founder of Seneca Capital Management, a San Francisco
investment firm that manages $4 billion in assets. ``It is truly
agonizing for women to make decisions on their investment
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Women and men tend to have different investment values, Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Women tend to move cautiously, weighing the lifelong impact of
their investments. In planning their finances, they anticipate
worst-case scenarios, such as poverty or natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, men invest more aggressively. They focus on the
short-term gains or losses of individual stocks. They also tend to
move quickly and impulsively, often after hearing tips at the
office or on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men assume they know it all _ even when they don't,'' Collins
said, ``while women assume they don't know it _ even when they do.
But finance today is so complex that no one individual _ man or
woman _ can know it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Even rich or successful women have financial troubles. Marcia
Clark, the famed prosecutor in the O.J. Simpson case, earned
$96,000 a year with the Los Angeles district attorney's office, but
owed $37,000 in credit-card debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``While she was up there at the trial every day, she was
worrying about her finances,'' said Collins, who is Clark's
financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that millions of women today are savvy and well
educated about finance. Working women have tremendous economic
clout. And more women _ especially those under 40 _ take part in
key money decisions with their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   All investors should explore their psychological motives for
investing, Collins said. What does money mean to them? Power and
status? Long-term security? Personal freedom? A way to enhance
family ties and relationships?
</P>
<P>
   Seneca said that women plunging into investments for the first
time should focus on the basics: Long-term financial goals. Asset
allocation among stocks, bonds and other investments. Yearly tax
planning. Assessing one's comfort and risk levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the big pieces right first,'' Seneca said. ``What does it
take to feel OK about your investments, not just today, but over
your long lifetime? That's more important than investing in Latin
American stocks or the hottest fund.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unwise to chase the unpredictable markets, according to
Janet Brown, president of DAL Investment Co. in San Francisco. No
one knows when hot fund managers and their investment sectors _
large or small companies, domestic or foreign stocks, growth or
value stocks _ will fall in and out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Brown advised that women patiently watch for the
top-performing funds and investment managers, then invest
accordingly with these ``market leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in forecasting the market's direction, but we
can follow the top-performing funds,'' Brown said. ``Performance is
the bottom line. Stay aware of who's beating the market, and adjust
your portfolio gradually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
