<HEADER>
A2985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NENGLAND-SPEEDWAY     08-07 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NENGLAND-SPEEDWAYS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BARRE, Vt.: ... racing divisions.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When I first started out, I would race in the ladies' races,
which were called the Powder Puff Division,'' said Kris Valerio,
29, a customer service representative at FleetBank who has two
feature race wins this year. ``But this is a lot more
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   She had three Strictly Stock (now Sportsmen's) Division wins in
1997 and is currently ninth in the Truck Division standings.
</P>
<P>
   Rob, 30, currently 13th in the Truck Division, began racing in
1980. He won the Strictly Stock Division in 1992 and '93.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to deliver newspapers, and one day I saw a race car in
the driveway of someone's house,'' said the auto body mechanic, who
won his first feature race of the year last weekend at Riverside.
``I got to know the owner of the car, and he helped me get involved
in racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob and Kris say they were never involved in the same activities
growing up, and it's one reason they don't consider what they're
doing competition.
</P>
<P>
   Their pit crews work alongside each other at Riverside. We're
not out there against each other,'' said Rob, who lives in New
Britain, Conn. ``We're here to help one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob said that when he discovered his sister wanted to enter the
sport, he was encouraged yet concerned about how she would handle
the agitation of male drivers who aren't accustomed to racing
against _ and being beaten by _ a female. But in addition to her
on-track success, she was voted the Strictly Stock's most popular
driver last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, whenever she stepped up to the trucks, I was
impressed,'' Rob said. ``Whenever you change like that, there is
usually an adjustment period, but she made a smooth transition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
STAFFORD SPRINGS, Conn. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a young racing fan, Mike Stefanik discovered early that
Stafford Motor Speedway was the preferred track for modified
drivers. So when the Springfield, Mass., resident decided to take
up the sport, there was little doubt about which track he would
call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can win here, you can win anywhere,'' he said. ``That's
how this place's reputation has always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning to race at the half-mile, semi-banked oval helped him
earn a reputation as one of the best modified drivers on the
circuit. That reputation was solidified this year when he was
chosen as one of the top 50 modified racers of all time in a poll
conducted by Stafford Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The selectees are honored at each racing event at the
53-year-old track, which is owned by Jack Arute Sr., whose son Jack
Jr. is a college football analyst for ABC. Track officials came up
with the idea as a way to participate in the celebration of
NASCAR's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   After sending out thousands of ballots (each with 130 entries
and write-in space) to car owners, drivers, and trade shows, among
others, and tallying votes on the racetrack's website, Stafford
officials were startled at the response: 29,700 ballots, including
some from Canada, Italy, China, and Sweden. Two-fifths of the
responses came from the website.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 drivers are honored on two canvas billboards leading into
the track. ``The program's been a huge success for us,'' said Cory
Posocco, Stafford's marketing and special events director. ``A lot
of the celebration with NASCAR's 50th anniversary has been Winston
Cup-related, but we chose to honor modifieds because it is the most
popular racing series in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Posocco added that Stafford officials chose the modified cars _
open-wheeled, high-horsepower machines designed specifically for
speed _ because they constituted the original first division of
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Those who made the list include Brett and Geoff Bodine and Jimmy
Spencer and Ron Bouchard, drivers who eventually made it to the
Winston Cup series.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always raced at Stafford; they would come from
North Carolina, New Jersey, and the rest of the East Coast,'' said
Stefanik, who last season became only the second driver in the
50-year history of NASCAR to win two division titles in the same
year _ the Feather Lite Modified and the Busch Grand National
North.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ran a modified, you needed a win at Stafford to be
good,'' he added. ``This is where the big races were, where the big
payoffs were, where all the big guys hung out. Now to be one of the
big guys is pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCARBOROUGH, Maine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James McConnell said it began as a kindhearted gesture. The man
who founded Beech Ridge Motor Speedway in 1949 allowed the winner
of the first official race to keep the checkered flag as a
souvenir. The response to the gesture was so overwhelming that
McConnell allowed the second winner to keep his. Then the third.
Then the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A tradition was born. The one-third-of-a-mile track, which
celebrates its 50th anniversary this season, has given away every
checkered flag to feature race winners since its inception. That
has meant a lot of work for local seamstresses, since every flag
has been made by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother made all the flags for many years,'' said McConnell,
86, of Raymond. A former sawmill owner and race car driver, he
bought the land on which the track sits for its lumber. After
clearing it, he built the track. He sold it in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The flags are 3 1/2-inch cotton squares (black and white, of
course), which are quilted together: two separate pieces of squares
consisting of six rows across, five rows down, for a total of 30
squares on each side. Those who have made the flags have become
popular as well.
</P>
<P>
   Marie-Jean Janson, 92, of Biddeford made the flags for 20 years
before retiring three years ago. ``In her last season, she made 300
of them,'' said Carmen Janson, her daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The current flagmaker is Sandra Jones, a Kennebunk seamstress
who got the job after making a souvenir signature flag for a friend
that became so popular in the area, she eventually sold 100. ``My
mother had Alzheimer's Disease at the time, so I needed something
to do while I spent time with her,'' she said. ``I make 200 a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing at Beech Ridge has always been competitive, so the list
of those who have won flags is impressive, including Robbie Crouch
and Jeff Fuller. ``They'd always try to give them back to us
because they didn't think they were supposed to keep them,'' said
Bonnie Coffin, former promotions director.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants a checkered flag made by Jones need not bother
to ask. ``I have an agreement with (Beech Ridge) that I will not
sell checkered flags,'' she said. ``Plus, that wouldn't be fun. You
have to earn them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
