<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAREJA THE MAN IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ The Revolution have won once in their last
nine home matches. But their 3-0 victory over San Jose Wednesday
not only removed their stigma of having the worst record in Major
League Soccer but also rekindled their playoff hopes going into
tomorrow's visit to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Their all-out commitment was exemplified by Paul Keegan, who
expended an incredible amount of energy starting as a left-side
midfielder and also covering central defense as the Revolution
protected their lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the most encouraging component of the Revolution game was
Oscar Pareja's ability to control the pace in midfield. Pareja's
playmaking skills set the tone and gave them something to rely on
other than physicality.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the Revolution reverted to frenetic kicking and
running did they seem vulnerable. But goalkeeper Ian Feuer, who
regained his starting position after more than two weeks on the
bench, prevented the Clash from capitalizing.
</P>
<P>
   And Joe-Max Moore, who had been on the verge of being traded two
days previously, combined with Raul Diaz Arce to provide a threat
at striker. Moore helped set up the first goal, by Ivan McKinley,
with a bold dribble into the penalty area, then scored the second
with an opportunistic follow against the run of play.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore recognized the Revolution's potentially fatal lack of
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our possession in the middle of the midfield wasn't what it
should be,'' Moore said Thursday. ``We got stretched out and we
have to be more compact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling everyone to try to keep possession, hold the
ball, make them run. I don't always say that. I want to go forward
and get the third or fourth goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Often when a team is protecting a lead in soccer, the best
defense is a good offense. But only if that offensive mentality is
displayed selectively. The Revolution lose their effectiveness by
attacking with little variation. Their predictability makes them an
easy mark for the better teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, at times we have given up late goals,'' Moore
said. ``And a lot of games that we should have won, we've thrown
away. Right now we need to win games, and it doesn't matter how
pretty or ugly it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Revolution are in a similar position to their first
two seasons, when they were scrambling to avoid last place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still trying to find an identity,'' coach Thomas Rongen
said. ``Against San Jose, we had that `over my dead body'
mentality. We had a combination of blue-collar and technical
players. And we are going to step it up a notch in the next game.
We are going to be tested for our guts, our fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But they still must occasionally maintain possession and play
through midfield, which means Pareja will be a key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar has a free role, and it is going to be important for us
to find him,'' Rongen said. ``He has an innate ability to fight off
pressure, he is very strong, and he got stronger as the game went
on. He shields the ball, keeps possession, which buys you time and
draws fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, he has been willing to do a lot of the dirty work as
well as the playmaking. He covers a lot of ground. The amount of
running he did was amazing for an international player, who could
easily let the others do most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have been seeking a midfield choreographer since
Edwin Gorter moved to sweeper and Jair broke his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar has been given the role and the title,'' Rongen said.
``That should help give us an identity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
