effort to force the closing of sex shops. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrials were up 97
points, or 1.1 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 33 points, or
1.8 percent. Earlier, shares fell 0.3 percent in Tokyo and 3.3
percent in Hong Kong. They were up 1.3 percent in Frankfurt and 1
percent in London. The long bond was up 4/32, with the yield at
5.66 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   Other market stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Hindered by the GM strike and the Asian
recession, the economy added jobs in July at the slowest pace in
more than two years. Payrolls grew by 66,000, in line with
analysts' forecasts and below June's employment gain. The GM strike
cost the economy almost 160,000 jobs in July. The jobless rate in
July was unchanged at 4.5 percent. Workers' average hourly
earnings, a gauge of business costs, rose 0.2 percent, or 3 cents,
in July, matching June's increase. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
repeats his determination to spur economic growth and prevent
Japan's troubles from spreading to the rest of the world, but he is
short on specifics. Delivering his first policy statement to
Parliament, he says permanent tax cuts will ``considerably exceed''
6 trillion yen, or $41 billion. He also repeats his pledges to push
through another spending package, of 10 trillion yen, and close
troubled banks. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-LOANS (Tokyo) _ American investment banks and private
investors are trying to turn Japan's bad debt quagmire into an
investment opportunity. They are buying packages of the bad loans
held by Japanese banks for about 10 cents on the dollar. They then
try to sell the real estate that backed the loans. As a result, a
measure of liquidity is trickling into Japan's real estate market
after eight years of economic malaise, and local banks are finally
finding buyers for their bad loans. But there are many risks. By
Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
