<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SNAKE-REVIEW-HNS     08-07 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SNAKE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAGE ON A ROLL IN `SNAKE EYES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes'' runs counter to most recent Hollywood thrillers.
Rather than slick and mechanically paced (action every 12 minutes!)
with predictable plot and characters, ``Snake Eyes'' runs at its
own odd speed, draws attention to its glitzy style and features an
erratic, screwball hero.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Brian De Palma film, and De Palma is working in the
intense, eccentric personal manner that established him with films
such as ``Dressed to Kill,'' ``Scarface'' and ``Body Double.'' It
is more idiosyncratic than, for example, his films ``The
Untouchables'' or the mainstream ``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   At times its strangeness gets in the way of allowing the
audience to simply enjoy it as a thriller.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is unusual, too. ``Snake Eyes'' stays from start to
finish (except for a short epilogue) in an Atlantic City casino
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 14,000 folks have come for a heavyweight championship
fight in the casino arena. Among them is the controversial U.S.
secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Guarding the secretary is naval Cmdr. Kevin Dunne (Gary Sinise).
Dunne is old friends with an Atlantic City police detective, Rick
Santoro (Nicolas Cage) and has brought him in on the guard detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cage and De Palma quickly establish that Santoro is a flamboyant
good ol' boy, cocky and tastelessly loud, right down to his
Hawaiian shirt. When offered a bribe, he accepts it so casually
that we realize he's forgotten it's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne is his exact opposite. Ramrod straight-arrow, he is
pristine, neat, intense and conscientious.
</P>
<P>
   The movie hardly starts before De Palma's close-ups and
off-speed editing alert us to pay attention; something is about to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro and Dunne are sitting near the secretary of defense. The
fight starts. Dunne spots a woman on another aisle and walks away.
Santoro sees Dunne and the woman talk, then she runs off, and Dunne
runs after her. Like a person on drugs, Santoro begins focusing in
on various people around the arena.
</P>
<P>
   A shot is heard, and the defense secretary is killed. A woman
standing nearby is also shot but promptly disappears.
</P>
<P>
   In the slowed-down reality of the moment, De Palma gives us all
kinds of hints, clues and red herrings to think about. The clues
include why the heavyweight champ, who has just been knocked out,
pops his eyes open instantly at the sound of the gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   The whole assassination scene is a showcase for De Palma. His
shots and his editing of visuals and sound bombard us with details
and impressions. Events seem to be both speeding up and slowing
down at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   We will see the assassination scene again and again throughout
the movie. Each time it will be from a different perspective,
sometimes from eyewitness accounts, at other times from video
cameras taping the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro has the hotel sealed before anyone can leave so he can
conduct an investigation. He sees this as his steppingstone to
becoming mayor if he can crack the case quickly for national
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes'' is plotted like a traditional mystery thriller,
but De Palma is not interested in who done it, but in how he, De
Palma, presents it. Though the movie is packed with twists and
turns, most of them don't come as much of a surprise because De
Palma is more into showing off than in plot or logic.
</P>
<P>
   What normally would be the movie's big revelation _ you probably
will suspect it already _ is revealed early.
</P>
<P>
   But much of ``Snake Eyes'' is fascinating, thanks to those two
major showboats, De Palma and Cage.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma has all sorts of fun distracting us from the slight
story. In perhaps the most eye-catching shot, he tracks his camera
across the ceilings of several hotel rooms _ some of them with
activity irrelevant to the story _ as he moves from one group of
characters to another.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cage has, for the time at least, all but abandoned
serious drama to concentrate on his action-hero career, he has
continued to create some of the most peculiar and watchable
characters in the genre. Here he plays Santoro as both magnetic and
repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro is a guy you wouldn't trust with your wallet or your
wife, unless you were already friends. Then he would be as loyal as
a bulldog. (Which becomes an important plot point.)
</P>
<P>
   Cage has several memorable moments, including a bravura scene in
which he comes across like a good cop-bad cop while questioning the
boxing champ, who may or may not be involved in the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, while Santoro and a material witness he is
protecting are hiding in a stairway, she tells him some information
he really doesn't want to find out. His reaction is priceless, both
funny and weird, but at the same time much more realistic than you
would get from most actors in most movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sinise, in a much less flamboyant part, is his usual rock-solid
self.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``feels'' strange in some ways that aren't intended.
An advertising point has been that the 14,000 potential suspects
are sealed into the building, and that all of the movie takes place
in a few hours. That's true, but it does not feel true.
</P>
<P>
   We never get the impression that guests are being detained or
that time is essential. The hotel casino is big, with many areas,
and it seems like nothing unusual has happened. People wander
around, play games and pick up dates. There's no sense of crisis or
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   While we are in the vague-complaint department, here's another.
The movie seems oddly short, and not just because, at 99 minutes,
it is shorter than most. Granted, most movies are too long, but
this one just seems to be hitting stride when all of a sudden
things wrap up abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   It feels truncated, like parts have been cut. There is a
hurricane outside the hotel during the investigation, but almost
nothing is made of it. Near the end of the movie, Cage refers to
something that happened underwater. But nothing happened
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the movie's underwater scenes, Sinise said the
hurricane originally played a much larger role in the action. ``But
they decided it was just not right for the movie,'' he said.
Apparently, it was too late to fix some of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is rated R, mainly for violence. De Palma, who has
often had trouble getting an R because his movies were so violent,
was contracted to bring this film in as a PG-13. He re-edited
several times to get the milder rating, but in the end had to
settle for the R.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
