<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-$ADV08-     08-07 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEARCH FOR INFORMATION A KEY TASK FOR CLINTON LEGAL TEAM
 &HT;    860&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his battery of in-house lawyers all but
sidelined in the most critical legal challenge of his career,
President Clinton is relying on three private attorneys skillful in
the ways of politics and scandal to prep him for grand jury
questioning Aug. 17_ and possibly save his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The three _ David Kendall, Nicole Seligman and former cabinet
member Mickey Kantor _ bring a formidable set of instincts, skills
and experience to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Each one plays a unique role:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kendall, the bookish but street-smart senior problem solver
who heads the team.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seligman, the glamorous Harvard-trained font of strategy and
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kantor, the calculating Clinton confidant valued as much for
his sensitive political antennae as for his steel-toothed
negotiating style.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the White House has refrained from labeling the trio a
dream team.
</P>
<P>
   The key to their performance could be how well they perform the
daunting task of ferreting out exactly what Monica Lewinsky and
dozens of other witnesses have already told the grand jurors behind
closed doors, and what independent counsel Kenneth Starr has
learned from his seven-month probe into Clinton's Oval Office
relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ''A defendant entering into a grand jury investigation would
like to know everything the grand jury and the prosecutors know,
because they don't want to state anything that would be
inconsistent with things that were stated before,'' said Bruce
Fein, a former deputy associate attorney general. ''But that's
going to be pretty hard to get.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been made no easier by recent court rulings suggesting
that White House counsel Charles Ruff and the nearly three dozen
lawyers in his office have no assurance of confidentiality in their
work for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to overrule a U.S.
appellate court's decision that White House deputy counsel Bruce
Lindsey _ and perhaps by extension, anyone else on the White House
legal staff _ could be forced to testify in the Lewinsky case. As
government employees, the lower court ruled, White House attorneys
are public servants, not presidential confidants.
</P>
<P>
   Anything those attorneys might discuss with Clinton, in other
words, could quickly become the subject of a grand jury probe.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Clinton able to confide and confer only with his
wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who cannot be forced to testify
against him, and his private attorneys, whose conversations with
Clinton are protected by the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   It will ultimately be the Clintons, both of whom have legal as
well as political expertise, who will frame the president's Aug. 17
testimony, hone its fine points and perhaps develop a companion
statement for the public.
</P>
<P>
   But the president is counting on Kendall, Seligman and Kantor to
give him a strong hand, and to do that they need to learn something
about the cards held by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to prevent Clinton's legal team from talking
directly with lawyers for other witnesses, or even to witnesses
themselves, in their search for investigatory intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Throughout this investigation, as any lawyers would, attorneys
do speak with other attorneys and their clients on a regular basis
as the investigation has proceeded,'' acknowledged White House
counsel spokesman Jim Kennedy. ''That's just the normal process of
gathering information.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has denied that he had an affair with Lewinsky and
coached her to cover it up, has pledged to testify completely and
truthfully on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   If he sticks with his story, Clinton could find portions of his
testimony at odds with Lewinsky's version of events.
</P>
<P>
   In grand jury testimony on Thursday, Lewinsky, who has received
blanket immunity from Starr, reportedly contradicted earlier claims
by herself and the president by saying that she and Clinton had an
Oval Office affair lasting more than a year and that they discussed
possible cover-up schemes.
</P>
<P>
   If she did change her story, and if Starr has other witnesses
and perhaps even physical evidence to back up her reversal,
Clinton's attorneys would like to know about it before he
testifies, not after.
</P>
<P>
   Their problem is that grand jury proceedings _ in which jurors
hear testimony and weigh evidence to decide whether prosecutors
have sufficient reason to formally charge, or indict, someone _ are
held behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to protect people who are under investigation, so
they aren't publicly maligned in case no charges are brought.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses are free to speak publicly, however, about what they
tell a grand jury, and there are no prohibitions against lawyers
for one witness conferring with lawyers for another.
</P>
<P>
   However, such practices are far from an exact science.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're not guaranteed cooperation,'' said Fein. ''They don't
have to tell you anything. Moreover, they can lie to you, or omit
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in other words, could end up flying partly blind into
his testimony, something his legal team hopes to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Clinton's lawyers are doing to get a peek at Starr's
playbook, they're not making their strategy public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't talk about it,'' said one of Clinton's three private
attorneys, who declined to be quoted by name even to refuse
comment. The other two did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   What is known about Clinton's team is that it provides him with
a balance of expert legal advice from Kendall and Seligman _ both
partners with the Washington firm Williams &AMP; Connolly _ and the
comfort of tested loyalty and political acumen from Kantor, with
the Washington office of the Chicago-based firm Mayer, Brown &AMP;
Platt.
</P>
<P>
   Team leader Kendall, like Clinton and his wife, graduated from
Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Also like Clinton, Kendall quickly turned his training toward
the American South, where he spent the better part of five years
challenging death sentences as part of the legal defense team of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall later toiled under the tutelage of Edward Bennett
Williams, a master trial lawyer and Washington power broker
extraordinaire. Williams helped build his partnership, Williams &AMP;
Connolly, into what many regard as the pre-eminent Washington
superfirm before he died 10 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues call Kendall, 54, a father of three and a compulsive
movie-watcher, a lawyer's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a brilliant fellow who has sort of a renaissance sort of
knowledge,'' said Robert Barnett, a Williams &AMP; Connolly partner.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is widely read, extremely intellectual, but he also has a
street fighter's toughness,'' said Barnett, who represented Clinton
in the investigation into the Whitewater real estate deal before
turning it over to Kendall four years ago. ''He is just a decent
man. Smart, funny, and a hell of a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York native turned Baltimore Orioles fan, Seligman, 41,
graduated from Harvard University in 1978 and moved immediately to
Hong Kong, where she was an editor with the Asian Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Two years of journalism, she decided, was enough. She returned
to Harvard to study law, graduated in 1983, and soon took on one of
the highest-profile cases of the decade: the defense of former
National Security Council official Oliver North in independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh's inquiry into the Iran-contra case.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has fought the independent counsel over a five-year legal
battle in the Oliver North case and has seen everything close-hand,
from congressional testimony, an indictment, a trial, an
acquittal,'' said Brendan Sullivan, who led North's defense.
''She's about as expert as you can get in these kinds of matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, also of Williams &AMP; Connolly, said Seligman can be a
bedeviling adversary in depositions.
</P>
<P>
   ''She can be tough on one hand and yet, on another, she can turn
very charming and feminine, which takes a witness by surprise,''
said Sullivan. ''So, if she doesn't get them one way, she'll get
them another. I'd have her on my team any day.''
</P>
<P>
   And, one way or another, Kantor has long been on Clinton's team.
The Nashville native has been a political compatriot of the
Clintons' for more than a decade, played a key role in the '92
presidential campaign and served in two important economic slots in
Clinton's first term, as U.S. Trade Representative and later, after
the death of Ron Brown, as Secretary of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Kantor, 59, was among a close circle of friends contacted by the
Clintons last January, in the tumultuous days after the Lewinsky
allegations first surfaced. He reportedly worked closely with Mrs.
Clinton during a period when, for several days, the president
virtually disappeared from sight in preparation for a State of the
Union address clouded by controversy.
</P>
<P>
   As he once did during high-profile trade negotiations, however,
Kantor has kept his cards close to the vest, saying little publicly
about the Lewinsky matter and providing behind-the-scenes advice
and counsel to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a relationship as an attorney to the president,'' White
House spokesman Barry Toiv told reporters last week. ''I honestly
don't know how often they talk, but I am sure they talk fairly
often.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
