<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRS-GREENTHUMBS-$ADV0     08-07 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS-GREENTHUMBS-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. GREENTHUMBS, THE GARDENING EXPERT, IS A FREE SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 9.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. _ Birds are chirping outside on the vine-covered
porch, as the music of opera singer Andrea Bocelli wafts through
the screened door and kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the small kitchen of her renovated 1851 Gothic house,
Cassandra Danz tells a visitor that ``when I go into the garden, I
never wear floral prints because the bees will come to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Danz could be a fictional character in a children's book or a
character on ``Sesame Street.'' But many know her as Mrs.
Greenthumbs, through her offbeat gardening books, newspaper and
magazine columns, and as a regular on ``Live with Regis &AMP; Kathie
Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   What you see on TV is what you get in person. Mrs. Greenthumbs,
a.k.a. Cassandra Danz, 48, is a free spirit with a gentle, Auntie
Mame sort of personality and wry sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Danz is a former member of the comedy troupe Women in High
Heels, which she helped form in 1977. Her stand-up comedy stints
have included appearances at Second City in Chicago, Catch a Rising
Star in New York City and the Improv in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her flair for comedy, Danz has long held a passion
for organic gardening. So it seemed natural to the Brooklyn native
to combine stand-up comedy with gardening.
</P>
<P>
   Danz's character of Mrs. Greenthumbs was noticed in 1994 by
Michael Gelman, producing director of the Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee show.
Her career was boosted the following year when she made the first
of many appearances on the popular morning show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first saw her at an off-off-Broadway one-woman comedy
gardeners show,'' Gelman said in a phone interview. ``I'm a lover
of offbeat comedy, and she lit up the stage with her funny sense of
humor. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a natural. She interacts well with Regis and Kathie
Lee because they too are themselves on camera. Cassandra has a fun
bawdy side. `She's an earthy one,' as Regis would say. He's a
Catholic-school type who gets embarrassed by her silly, risque
antics. Kathie Lee gets a good chuckle out of Cassandra and how she
views and enjoys life and the world around her.''
</P>
<P>
   Danz said working on the TV show is ``like being part of a
family. A dysfunctional family, but a family. ... They are all so
supportive of anything you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Danz was recently offered her own gardening television show in
Canada. ``I just came back from Halifax, where I completed filming
26 episodes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a variety gardening show where we dance, sing and
do other silly things. We have a piano, musical director and my
announcer is a tenor. People from the audience come in with their
sick plants. They sit on a couch and I analyze them, like a
psychiatrist. Other times I play Greenah (like Xena Warrior
Princess), the Garden Warrior. We also have guests, like a tree
surgeon, a vegetable expert and a very high-camp floral designer
with lots of attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   She also had a bit part in the movie ``Tootsie'' with Dustin
Hoffman. ``I think I got my part because I looked like Dustin
Hoffman in drag,'' she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Danz lives with her husband, Walter, who works for a commuter
train line. They have a 19-year-old son. Their house is filled with
an eclectic blend of bargain finds that they have collected over
the years from yard sales, flea markets and auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Her approach to gardening appeals to a broad range of people who
love gardening or reading about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gives you courage to do gardening,'' said Hudson neighbor
Meg Mundy, an actress and former model and magazine editor.
``Cassandra is a delight to be around _ very witty and smart.''
Pulitzer Prize-winning poet and Hudson resident John Ashbury took a
gardening class offered by Danz.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's extremely good-natured and witty to work with, and if
you're into gardening, she makes it fun,'' Ashbury said. ``She's
quick to tell you that you shouldn't worry about damaging anything,
as `plants are very forgiving.'''
</P>
<P>
   To help people with their gardening, Danz has penned a couple of
humorous gardening books. Her latest tome is titled ``Mrs.
Greenthumbs Plows Ahead: Five Steps to the Drop-Dead Gorgeous
Garden of Your Dreams'' (Crown, $25). Her first book was titled
``Mrs. Greenthumbs: How I Turned a Boring Yard into a Glorious
Garden and How You Can, Too'' (Crown, $12 paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Danz's own garden is a compilation of floral beds placed
perpendicular to the house with just enough lawn to divide the
segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the flower gardens perpendicular to the house, so you
can see and enjoy them,'' Danz said. ``People tend to plant their
flowers alongside the house, where only the neighbors can see them
and you can't.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around at the various flowers, trees and plants in her
yard, Danz said, ``I love it here in my garden. It's like living in
heaven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
