<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-ADDITIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP SUES OVER ADDITIVE IN GASOLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco-based environmental organization
is suing the major oil companies, seeking to ban them from using
the gasoline additive MTBE and force manufacturers to pay for
cleaning up toxic residue in California ground water.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed Thursday in San Francisco Superior Court,
alleges that the oil companies knew that MTBE (methyl tertiary
butyl ether) was toxic and a hazard to human health when they began
blending it into their gasoline under a 1990 federal law requiring
oil companies to add air-cleaning chemicals to gasoline to reduce
carbon monoxide in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE is an oxygenate that, when added to gasoline, reduces
carbon monoxide emissions from motor vehicles. It is colorless but
causes a foul taste in water. MTBE has been in wide use in
California since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says the additive can cause
cancer in animals. MTBE is soluble in water and has leaked out of
storage tanks and into the domestic water supplies in several
areas.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by scientists at the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory concluded that more than 10,000 sites have been
contaminated by MTBE since the additive was introduced in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil companies have been running the same kind of scam the
tobacco companies did for years, only it was with MTBE instead of
nicotine,'' said Donald Brown, executive director of Communities
for a Better Environment, which filed the complaint. ``They must
clean up their mess and pay back big time for profiting from
poisoning California's water supply.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two major oil companies named as defendants, Chevron
and Tosco, both based in the San Francisco area, are testing
gasoline additives other than MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   Tosco spokesman David Kory said the company was aware of
customer complaints and that ``we want to demonstrate that
solutions to the problem of reducing or eliminating MTBE from the
gasoline are possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosco has replaced MTBE with ethanol, which is made from corn
and rice hulls, in its gasoline in several California counties.
</P>
<P>
   The East Bay Municipal Utility District, the Santa Clara County
Water District and several other jurisdictions in Los Angeles,
Orange and Kern counties, and the San Francisco area, have note
MTBE pollution in water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara County Board of Supervisors passed a resolution
calling for a ban on MTBE after 168 ground water sites, three
reservoirs and three water treatment sites were found to have
traces of MTBE. The Tahoe Regional Planning Authority banned the
use of two-stroke outboard motors in the lake, and the East Bay
Municipal Utility District enacted a similar ban for its reservoirs
for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tosco and Chevron, major oil companies named in
the lawsuit were Mobil, Arco, Texaco, Shell, Exxon and Unocal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
