<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATALOG-SHOPPING-SPI &LR;      08-07 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATALOG-SHOPPING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALOGS HAVE FIRM GRIP ON BUYERS, JOIN FORCES WITH ONLINE
MERCHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who gets mail knows catalogs accumulate faster than dryer
lint, and they're a lot heavier. So it's no surprise to hear from
the Direct Marketing Association that there are at least 8,000
catalogs generating an expected $87 billion in business this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the statistics Amy Blankenship spews as
director of the DMA's shop-at-home information center.
</P>
<P>
   Today's catalogs may be less hefty and more specialized than
their weighty ancestors, but they're not being eclipsed by online
shopping services.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they're joining up, making catalogs like JCPenney,
LLBean and Lands' End available in hand or on-screen.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship was in Seattle last week for a DMA-sponsored
marketing conference, telling anyone who would listen how to shop
the Net and/or catalogs successfully, while sharing online and
catalog shopping trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know you could have a complete clambake _ lobsters and
all _ sent by Clambakes to Go catalog via Federal Express? Or how
about a bright red British phone booth from Design Toscano _ a
catalog that also offers suits of armor.
</P>
<P>
   While food and gifts are popular with at-home shoppers, they
can't compare with clothing.
</P>
<P>
   According to DMA research, clothing accounts for about 33
percent of all catalog purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies even offer personal shoppers who can pull
together a wardrobe for a customer.
</P>
<P>
   Online shoppers, on the other hand, focus on computers and
peripherals, as well as books and music.
</P>
<P>
   Online shopping is a growing category _ especially now that some
catalogs allow shoppers to mix and match wares on screen.
</P>
<P>
   But Net-shopping is still way behind catalogs in dollar volume.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship says catalog shoppers will spend about $87 billion
this year, while online shoppers will spend about $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship has a knack for putting a positive spin on what some
consider the negative side of at-home shopping.
</P>
<P>
   She worked as a congressman's press secretary in Washington,
D.C., before moving to New York and taking the DMA job a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's not aware that at-home shoppers sometimes find
that clothing that looks glamorous on the screen or page will be of
poor quality when it arrives, or that shipping costs can send the
price of an item into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the order form before placing an order,'' Blankenship
said. ``Companies use different services to get orders to
consumers. Ask about different shipping options.''
</P>
<P>
   Home shoppers don't have to pay local taxes if the catalog
doesn't have a physical presence or nexus in their state, according
to Blankenship.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 30,000 taxing jurisdictions in the United States,''
she said. ``It would be extremely hard for companies to keep track
of them all.''
</P>
<P>
   What isn't a hot seller on the Net or in catalogs? Blankenship
hesitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, there haven't been a lot of cosmetics sold, but
the Body Shop is doing direct business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to DMA research, only about 5 percent of all shipments
are returned, and some companies make it easier than others to
return merchandise _ with an enclosed return label and free return
postage, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship encouraged shoppers to always read the customer
service section of a catalog or Web site for return/exchange
policies. Computer software and recorded music that can be
duplicated are sometimes not returnable, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for successful catalog shopping:
</P>
<P>
   Amy Blankenship, director of the shop-at-home information center
for the Direct Marketing Association has dozens of helpful hints to
make shopping at home successful. Here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   _When you find a catalog with good merchandise and service, tell
others.
</P>
<P>
   _Ask questions. Service representatives who answer phones are
usually trained to help with your purchasing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   _Keep records. Even when ordering by phone, fill in the order
blank, date it and file it away. Once merchandise arrives, save the
receipt, packaging and literature until you are certain you are
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   _Never give personal information such as bank account or Social
Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _If it's a ``special offer'' or involves a ``trial period,''
read the fine print and know your obligations before you join or
purchase. These offers are often linked to book, music and
collectibles ``clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   _Never send cash through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   _When shoping online, make sure you are on a secure site. If the
URL on the ``checkout'' page starts with https:// it means the
document is from a secure server.
</P>
<P>
   _When a shipping date cannot be met (30 days maximum unless
otherwise specified), the supplier must notify you of a new date.
</P>
<P>
   _Need more catalogs in your mailbox? The DMA publishes the Great
Catalog Guide featuring more than 270 different catalog companies
listed according to products and/or services. Send $3 check or
money order to: Consumer Services Department, Direct Marketing
Association, P.O. Box 33033, Washington, DC 20033-0033.
</P>
<P>
   _Problems? Home shoppers have options when a catalog company has
not resolved a complaint in an acceptable, timely manner. The DMA's
Mail Order Action Line is a free service, but requests for help
must be in writing, sent to: Mail Order Action Line, Direct
Marketing Association, 1111 19th St. N.W., Suite 1100, Washington,
DC 20036-3603. Include details about your order, the catalog
company, explanation of the problem, photocopies of documents,
copies of canceled checks and correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   _If an offer seems too good to be true, it probably is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
