<P>
   BOMBING-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton quickly
condemns fatal bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania as
terrorist acts and sends over medical aid. Federal investigators
and military support are also on the way from Washington and U.S.
bases in Germany. How will this affect security at U.S. embassies
around the world? What terrorist groups are being mentioned as
responsible? Wrapping up the developments from Washington. (Deans,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-ANALYSIS _ WASHINGTON _ The fatal bombings of U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania are another sign that the United
States has to be ready to both reap the benefits as well as suffer
the consequences of being the world's last remaining superpower.
Namely, if you're going to make a statement, then do it by taking
on the biggest kid on the block. Moreover, the presence of U.S.
facilities around the world that are ``public'' buildings _ such as
the embassies _ makes for numerous vulnerable targets. (Glass, Cox
News Service). ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-SECURITY _ Security levels vary at U.S. embassies around
the world, depending on conditions in the countries. A look at
security at the two embassies hit by bombs Friday. (Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-REACT _ ATLANTA _ For Emma Mwangi, a Kenyan who has been
visiting friends in Atlanta, news of blast at the U.S. embassy in
Nairobi came as a shock. Afterwards, she frantically tried to reach
her father, a businessman who works in the same block. (Kurylo,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-PRESIDENT _ MIAMI _ Spouting a message of peace, Andres
Pastrana takes office as Colombia's new president Friday in the
face of some of the worst political violence to hit this South
American country in years. A nationwide rebel offensive by Marxist
rebels has killed more than 130 people this week. In the most
devastating action, rebels overran an important southern
anti-narcotics base, killing or dragging away dozens of soldiers
and police as possible bargaining chips. (Emling, Cox News
Service). ETA: 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BANKBAILOUT _ MEXICO CITY _ Angry opponents have strapped
themselves to crosses to symbolize the ``crucifixion'' of Mexico's
poor. Headlines scream allegations that the rich are, once again,
getting a free break thanks to pals in the government. The dispute
is over a $65 billion bank bail out stemming from Mexico's 1994
economic crisis. What's different now is that Mexico has a stubborn
opposition Congress that isn't ready to rubber stamp a Zedillo
Administration request to publicly absorb the debt, which is 14
percent of Mexico's GDP. Earlier this week, in defiance of Mexico's
bank secrecy laws, the country's left-center opposition released a
list of names of bank debtors that include some of Mexico's
wealthiest. Also on the list are suspected white-collar thieves who
abused the bail out, and, opponents say, big-time campaign finance
supporters of the country's ruling party. Arguing that most debtors
are actually Mexicans of modest means is Treasury Secretary Jose
Angel Gurria, who briefed foreign reporters this week and is in
charge of negotiating with Mexico's now vigorous opposition.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO from Austin. ETA: 3 p.m. (i
and f categories)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CASTRO _ MIAMI _ Summer is always the time for feverish
speculation about the health of aging Cuban President Fidel Castro,
who turns 72 on Aug. 13, and this summer is no exception. Just a
few weeks ago, a Cuban doctor-turned-defector living in Costa Rica
claimed that Castro suffers from a fatal brain disorder. There was
a barrage of similar ill-health rumors last summer, some even
announcing Castro's death. But, if anything, Castro appears more
robust than ever. He appears to be traveling more these days than
at any time in his 39 years in power. He continues his commitment
to communism, even as he's been striking a conciliatory tone
towards President Clinton. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO-TRAVEL _ MIAMI _ An itinerary of Fidel Castro's travels
over the last few months. (Emling, Cox News Service). MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ISRAEL _ JERUSALEM _ Go to the movies, and guards will
check your hand bag for bombs and ask if you have any weapons.
Leave a shopping bag unattended, and it could be blown up by the
``Sappers'' who patrol city streets in their high-tech vans. After
a while, you get so used to it and nearly forget about the
counter-terrorism security measures in every day Israel that would
be considered intrusive in the United States. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). WEDNESDAY IN i and k CATEGORIES.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-BRITAIN _ WEST HORSLEY, England _ In late June, I stood
on the front porch of my mom and dad's place an hour south of
Dallas and marveled at the old plastic thermometer. It reported the
temperature to be 112 degrees. So imagine the relief of arriving to
this place, where a cool spell is caressing an already mild
climate. The grass is thick, soft and green. My apple trees are
heavy with fruit and the berries are making the birds crazy.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). MOVED WEDNESDAY IN i and k
CATEGORIES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ WASHINGTON _ An interview with House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga. (Sherman/Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WORKFORCE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday signs the
Workforce Investment Act, which will convert most federal job funds
for states into block grants. (Harlan/Joyce, Cox News Service 400).
</P>
<P>
   DEWINE _ Good week for U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine of Ohio: President
Clinton signs his major job-training bill today, and a bill he
sponsored with Pat Moynihan that would force the U.S. to release
all files on Nazi war criminals is on its way to Clinton for
signing. DeWine hopes this bill would spur other countries to do
the same. (Joyce/Montgomery, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LAWYERS _ WASHINGTON _ With his battery of in-house
lawyers all but sidelined in the most critical legal challenge of
his career, President Clinton is relying on three private attorneys
skillful in the ways of politics and scandal to prep him for grand
jury questioning _ and possibly save his presidency. The three _
David Kendall, Nicole Seligman and former cabinet member Mickey
Kantor _ bring an imposing set of instincts, skills and experience
to the field. But the key to their performance could be how well
they do at the daunting task of ferreting out exactly what Monica
Lewinsky and dozens of other witnesses have already told the grand
jurors behind closed doors and what independent counsel Kenneth
Starr has learned from his six-month probe. (Deans, Cox News
Service 900).
</P>
<P>
   DECADE _ WASHINGTON _ Let's take a stroll through the graveyard
of decades. There's the gaudy 1920s marker, with its epitaph of
``Roaring.'' Keep on marching past the ``swinging'' '60s headstone
and the human-shaped ``Me Decade'' of the '70s. The monstrous
tombstone for the '80s can't be missed _ it denotes the ``Greed
Decade.'' But now is a particularly grave time in pop culture land.
Just 17 months shy of 2000, there's no consensus among trend
trackers, pop culture mavens and futurists on a catch phrase for
the '90s. (Abulhassan, Cox News Service 650). MOVED WEDNESDAY in w
and l CATEGORIES.
</P>
<P>
   TITANIC _ WASHINGTON _ In a search for relics and ratings, the
Discovery Channel will send remote-control camera vehicles to the
floor of the North Atlantic next Sunday (Aug. 16) and telecast a
``live,'' two-hour visit to the sunken luxury liner Titanic.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service 680&AMP;add). MOVED THURSDAY IN w and e
CATEGORIES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLA-GORE _ DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore,
Federal Emergency Management Agency Director James Lee Witt and Lt.
Gov. Buddy MacKay hold roundtable discussion on hurricane
prevention measures at Deerfield Beach High School. Later, Gore
meets with Democratic officials and might swing an endorsement of
MacKay from U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings, who is miffed at the party
for snubbing black lawmakers. (Crowley/Belkin, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-DROUGHT_ AUSTIN, Texas _ Senate Finance and House
Appropriations committees meet jointly to gather info re drought
impact on state. (Herman, Austin American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-HEAT-DEATHS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Convicts' families are set
to protest overheated conditions inside prisons at a Friday press
conference in Austin. Expected to highlight the early July death of
a Death Row convict named Duhamel. Will wrap in with pending
lawsuit from '95 heat-related death. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-POLITICS _ Miami's long-running saga of political scandal
is under the spotlight again as ex-City Commissioner Humberto
Hernandez goes on trial for vote fraud stemming from last fall's
tainted city elections. The charismatic Cuban politician seems to
sum up what many feel is the heart of the city's problems: a
byzantine system built on cronyism and corruption, centered around
the unquestionable clout of the Cuban community. American-born but
the son of a Bay of Pigs veteran, Hernandez has repeatedly thumbed
his nose at prosecutors and media critics, claiming his unstoppable
Latin power base will protect him. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YAGER-HEARING _ ATLANTA _ Hearing continues on a motion for a
temporary restraining order to stop Faye and Howard Yager, accused
in a lawsuit of running a misguided underground network to protect
allegedly abused kids, from continuing to hide a Connecticut man's
son. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
