<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3032 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SPICE-GIRLS-SPI     08-07 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SPICE-GIRLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL DOLLED-UP SPICE GIRLS SASHY INTO THE NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop-music history is littered with the memories of slickly
packaged, teen-oriented acts that sold millions of records before
disappearing into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to New Kids on the Block, anyway? And Menudo?
Vanilla Ice? Word has it he's still trying to make a comeback, if
only he would show up when he's supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   A few of them, like the Monkees and Duran Duran, actually had
talent. Fewer still had true greatness. Take the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Spice (a k a Geri Halliwell) got out while the gettin'
was good. But she was a bit premature, quitting as she did just
before the start of the group's much-publicized U.S. tour. There
are still millions to be made pushing bubble-gum feminism and
peddling records, toys, dolls and all sorts of consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Spice, who abruptly quit in May, missed her chance at
becoming a real doll.
</P>
<P>
   Her former Spicemates _ Scary (Melanie Brown), Sporty (Melanie
Chisholm), Posh (Victoria Adams) and Baby (Emma Bunton) _ are being
immortalized in a series of products manufactured by Toymax
International Inc., the company that brought you Creepy Crawlers.
</P>
<P>
   Though doomed to turn up on the swap-meet circuit, these dolls
and other toys will be treasured by young fans eager to cuddle with
something other than a poster, video or CD.
</P>
<P>
   When the Spice Girls' U.S. tour rolls into the Northwest for a
concert Saturday night, the big video screens will be pushin'
product _ from T-shirts and programs to cosmetics and soft drinks.
Hey, if The Artist (formerly known as Prince) can shamelessly fill
his concerts with product pitches, why not the Spice Girls?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from commercials, the show should be pretty soundly
entertaining for fans. The four Spice Girls perform with a live
backup band, six male dancers, prerecorded background vocals and
enough costumes to stock a fashion boutique.
</P>
<P>
   It's a flashy, giddy, high-flying show that attracts legions of
young, screaming girls. Parents who accompany their kids to the
Tacoma Dome will be absolutely dumbstruck by the sound of thousands
of high-pitched voices at full volume. It's enough to make you
queasy.
</P>
<P>
   The song list, which is heavily weighted with material from the
Spice Girls' two albums, ``Spice'' (1996) and ``Spiceworld''
(1997), encompasses various styles of pop music _ disco, reggae,
hip-hop, neo-swing and hard rock.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a slight feminist tone to the show are such songs as ``We
Are Family'' and ``Sisters Are Doin' It for Themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Spice Girls' own songs, you can bet they'll perform such
tunes as ``The Lady Is a Vamp,'' ``Spice Up Your Life,'' ``Saturday
Night Divas,'' ``Move Over,'' ``Two Become One'' and ``Naked,''
which is done bare-shouldered with some teasing, suggestive props.
</P>
<P>
   Members also live up to their names with special costumes and
hair-dos. Baby sports ponytails and baby-doll dresses, Sporty wears
a soccer jersey and Scary favors a leopard-skin outfit. Posh simply
strives to look stylish and demure.
</P>
<P>
   When the show recently played in New York, many of the videos
hadn't yet been revamped to reflect Ginger's departure. Indeed,
life must be moving so fast for the group that precious little time
is available for a post-Ginger makeover. Even the the group's new
video, ``Spice World,'' which hit stores in June, features Ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Fans might have expected Ginger to come up with an interesting
solo gig. But thus far, only Scary has taken on an extracurricular
project, cutting a track with rapper Missy Elliot for the Frankie
Lymon biopic ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?''
</P>
<P>
   The surviving Spice Girls haven't been terribly forthright
regarding Ginger's hasty exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was a shock,'' Baby recently told Entertainment
Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she just had different ideas about what she wanted to do.
And we've always been behind each other a hundred percent.
Fundamentally, the Spice Girls are about friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Scary: ``She just wanted to move on and do her own thing.
... We support her and say good luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BANKBAILOUT-08     08-07 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANKBAILOUT-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ME
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICANS FIGHT HUGE BANK BAILOUT, CHARGING THAT THE CORRUPT
BENEFIT
 &HT;    EDs: With photo to be placed in the International folder on the
Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Angry opponents have strapped themselves to
crosses and marched in public to symbolize the ``crucifixion'' of
Mexico's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines scream allegations that the corrupt and rich have,
once again, hopped on a free ride from their pals in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   These are scenes from Mexico's latest emotionally-charged
national dispute, which center on a $65 billion bank bail-out --
the result of the country's 1994 peso crash and subsequent economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents in this corruption-weary country say the rescue plan,
already equal to 14 percent of Mexico's Gross Domestic Product
(GDP), has benefited too many rich businesses and individuals who
recklessly helped themselves to money before the crash and now
expect the public to foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would the government pay for my personal needs, just the same
as it's done for its friends?'' asked an indignant Lourdes Flores,
a school teacher. ``I guess being a rich criminal is a guarantee of
privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores' remarks sum up widespread disgust over reports that some
high-flying bail-out beneficiaries were bankers who committed
fraud, while others were loyal contributors to electoral campaigns
of Mexico's dominant political entity, the Revolutionary
Institutional Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   One such person who may have been a crook and a contributor is
Angel Isidoro Rodriguez Saez, a jet-setter nicknamed ``The Divine
One,'' who Mexican officials say loaned himself $400 million from
his own bank. The government bailed the bank out during the crisis,
but Rodriguez Saez has also been charged with fraud. Many Mexicans
still struggling with the impact of the crisis are angry that
pending charges, ``The Divine One'' remains free -- and rich --
following extradition from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent a financial meltdown after economic disaster struck
Mexico in 1994, the government bailed out banks, like ``The Divine
One's,'' that were in trouble. Many banks had been privatized
during Mexico's rush to loosen state control in the early 1990s. As
a result, banks began making billions of dollars in speculative
loans that eventually went sour.
</P>
<P>
   A federal deposit-insurance agency here known as FOBAPROA bought
$65 billion worth of the bad debts with government bonds payable in
10 years. But now President Ernesto Zedillo's administration wants
congressional approval to convert the burden to public debt, by
turning the bonds into securities banks can cash sooner at better
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Congress, for the first time in 70 years, is no longer
controlled by the PRI and no longer willing to rubber stamp
executive proposals. The left-center opposition, the Democratic
Revolution Party (PRD) is leading a charge to modify Zedillo's
proposal, and this week made great political mileage by divulging
the names of extremely wealthy FOBAPROA beneficiaries it gleaned
from documents it was given.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD violated Mexico's bank secrecy laws by releasing
specific names, according to the administration, which is offering
documents to Congress -- in confidence -- as a way of smoothing
negotiations with opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But newspapers here gobbled up the information with glee.
Mexico's Congress had no subpoena power to obtain the names, and
the PRD's defiant act was met by many disgruntled Mexicans with
hearty approval.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the names on the list ``are among the world's richest
people, and FOBAPROA took on their bad loans,'' said PRD federal
deputy Dolores Padierna, who serves in Mexico's lower house.
``These multi-millionaires can pay their own debts. The Mexican
people shouldn't be paying them.''
</P>
<P>
   Padierna told reporters that the PRD's aim is to reduce the
bail-out's cost to the public by declining to back criminal debts.
She said the PRD estimates that as much as 70 percent of FOBAPROA's
$65 billion burden shouldn't be backed by the public because it
resulted from corruption.
</P>
<P>
   As much as half of FOBAPROA's debt originated from huge, often
dubious, loans made to the rich, including ``The Divine One,''
according to documents released to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Treasury Secretary Jose Angel Gurria, who is in charge
of negotiating with skeptical political opponents, agrees that
public opinion seems to be running against the administration.
</P>
<P>
   However, he argues, more than 90 percent of the 600,000 debtors
on FOBAPROA's lists are regular business people, farmers and other
Mexicans of modest means who took out relatively small loans they
failed to repay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no International Red Cross for helping debtors,''
Gurria said, explaining that Mexico can't afford to abandon its
rescue proposal -- which also includes important reforms to help
tighten bank-lending practices.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bail-out, he said, the government hopes to create an
agency like the United States' Resolution Trust Corporation, which
would sell debtors' property to raise money to repay the bad
credit.
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, it's unlikely that the debt will be
fully recouped. Many analysts predict that FOBAPROA will end up
collecting only 30 percent of the total -- if it's lucky.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Gurria, who discussed the FOBAPROA stalemate with foreign
reporters this week, admitted that the government will have
difficulty collecting debts from wealthy individuals who obtained
credit -- sometimes from cronies -- with ``signature loans'' based
on estimated assets but not guaranteed by them.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even if many of these individuals still own vast
properties, they may be untouchable unless fraud is proved.
</P>
<P>
   Gurria said the administration wants to punish abusers of
Mexico's banking system as much as anyone. And analysts say it
would help the administration in the court of public opinion if a
few white-collar crooks were soon prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Diaz, an economist with the Mexico City Center of
Research for Development, said both sides of the FOBAPROA debate
have reasonable arguments that will have to be considered as
negotiations proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to pay a large amount of the debt because it is
attributed to corruption is risky, Diaz said, because it could
provoke a run on banks and capital flight. But the PRD, he said,
has correctly warned that the bail-out could actually be much
greater than the $65 billion estimate, and it could require
increasing taxes and cutting social spending.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound good to many Mexicans. So a refusal by
Zedillo's administration to compromise, Diaz said, could mean
``political disaster'' for his party in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0153 </DOCNO>
