<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHEDULED-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH-ROW INMATE SEEKS TO HALT EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Condemned double-murderer Bill Bradford was so
overcome by recent visits from family members and an old friend
that he decided to try to stop his date with death, his lawyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly 15 years on death row, Bradford was visited only
by his lawyers, said his current attorney, Jack Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, 52, had told the court he did not wish to continue
appeals challenging his death sentence. An execution date of Aug.
18 was set.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened, Leavitt said: The news media reported
on the condemned inmate who was eager to die. People read about
Bradford and visited him at San Quentin. People, his lawyer said,
he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention which the press was giving to Bradford's
imminent execution ... produced an unexpected result,'' Leavitt
wrote in a formal request for a stay of execution, which he sent to
the U.S. District Court in Los Angeles on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration states Bradford's intent to continue his legal
appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family and friends whom he had not seen for nearly 15 years _
and in some cases, blood relatives he had never known _ learned
about his death-row existence. They wrote to him, talked to him by
telephone and visited him, providing a supportive setting which had
long been denied him. He found a reason to continue living _ if
only to allow him to reconcile himself with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, an amateur photographer, was sentenced to die for
strangling two aspiring models _ Shari Miller, 21, and Tracey
Campbell, 15 _ in 1984 after luring them to the Southern California
desert with promises of modeling jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court upheld the death sentence last year.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt said Bradford told him Thursday morning that he had
changed his mind, and that he wanted to seek a stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have walked into Bradford's life in recent weeks
were a 23-year-old daughter whom he had not seen in 14 years, a
half-sister whom he had never met and an old friend who is like a
brother to Bradford, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In his legal filing, the lawyer wrote that ``Bradford has
decided to avail himself of his right to exhaust his federal
procedures before the state is permitted to levy a final,
irrevocable judgment against him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Bradford has changed his mind about
dying. He filed papers to halt his execution in the middle of July,
though he withdrew that request almost immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
