<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Holocaust Debate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How should the Holocaust be taught? Today, a specialized field
of study has grown up around it. While some thinkers believe the
Holocaust is getting the attention it deserves, others are uneasy
about focusing scholarship on an attempt to wipe out the Jewish
people instead of on the whole of Jewish history. The New York
Times asked Ruth R. Wisse, a professor of Yiddish literature and
comparative literature at Harvard University, and Steven T. Katz,
director of the Center for Judaic Studies at Boston University and
the author of ``The Holocaust in Historical Context,'' to lay out
their views on the purpose and meaning of teaching the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The story will be in two parts:
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-KATZ (Undated) _ Steven T. Katz argues that the
Holocaust is a singular event, perhaps the most significant
occurrence in 2,000 years of Jewish history, and that it therefore
deserves to be treated as such.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-WISSE (Undated) _ Ruth R. Wisse counters that turning
the Holocaust into the defining event in Jewish history is a
terrible mistake, that it distorts the rich and long history of the
Jews, allows Hitler to define the Jews and obscures the political
nature of what happened in Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-SITTERS (Undated) _ The image and the reality of the baby
sitter as clues to the culture's deep-seated attitudes toward
adolescent girls. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   TRILLIN-HUMOR (New York) _ At Lunch With: the humorist Calvin
Trillin, whose latest book is ``Family Man.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MAGIC (Undated) _ Magic Johnson's TV show on Fox is canceled.
</P>
</TEXT>
