<HEADLINE>
GETTING AN EYEFUL WITH GLASSTRON 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ah, sitting in a hammock in the back yard, rocking
back and forth in the shade, ice-cold lemonade in hand, watching
``L.A. Confidential'' projected in digital glory across the insides
of my sunglasses. This is summer living.
</P>
<P>
   And you can do it with the Glasstron, which looks like a pair of
sunglasses, but in fact has high-quality digital television screens
behind each silvered lens, and earplugs at each temple to shoot
stereo sound straight into your brain.
</P>
<P>
   Sony representatives said the device probably will debut at
Christmas at a price of $700 to $800. During demos at the recent Hi
Fi '98 show, Sony paired the Glasstron with its paperback-size
portable DVD player for mobile movie heaven in high definition.
</P>
<P>
   And there'll be competition for your secret movie supershades.
Samsung reportedly has a similar set readying for release, price
and availability still undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   The Glasstron isn't the only gizmo Sony's been showing off
lately either. Lots of oohs and ahs at the Herring on Hollywood
conference were directed at cheap new notebook computers from Sony
that are thin enough to make Kate Moss diet.
</P>
<P>
   The VAIO 505 SuperSlim is less than an inch thick, sheathed in
brushed magnesium alloy, with a built-in 33.6-Kbps modem, 10.4-inch
screen, and external floppy-disk drive and docking port. An
external CD-ROM drive is extra, as are detachable speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-pound computer sports an equally thin price: about $2,000
for a machine with a 200-Mhz Pentium II MMX chip, and about $2,700
for one with a 266-Mhz chip. This is cool.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD, BUT LIVELY: Paul is dead. No, not that Paul. Paul Lomo.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Paul, don't you? Lead singer of the seminal, and
troubled, rock band Miasma back in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Miasma put out some great music on Conquest Records. Then Paul's
supermodel squeeze turned up dead. Followed two weeks later by
Paul, face down in a swimming pool, breathing a little too much
agua for the good of his lungs, and his longevity. You do remember,
don't you, all these years later?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you don't remember Paul. Or Miasma. Or Conquest
Records. Because they didn't really exist anywhere until John
Sanborn and Michael Kaplan created them, for ``Paul Is Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderfully dense and entertaining ``interactive rock 'n'
roll mystery'' centering on Lomo's bizarre life and death, that
just debuted on the Internet at www.paulisdead.com.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Paul Is Dead,'' Sanborn and Kaplan wove together 96
streamed-video shorts that will be released on the Internet a
couple of times a week through March, slowly unveiling the Lomo
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   They also wrote 16 songs that represent the Miasma ``oeuvre,''
(with each song containing clues), as well as a dozen alternate
takes and demos of the songs that also provide information.
</P>
<P>
   And they strung together another 300 pieces of what Sanborn
calls ``rock 'n' roll detritus,'' things like audio recordings and
documents, and 300 Web pages, many of them fake fanzines about the
band that flesh in more detail.
</P>
<P>
   Further adding to the experience is Lenny Pochnik, an obsessive
Miasma ``fan'' whose responses actually are generated by a complex
computer program called a ``chatbot.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 'bot's erratic behavior and feud with rock
critic/protagonist Elly Clyde, viewers/players of ``Paul Is Dead''
need to work with Lenny, or they'll never get in to see his trove
of Miasma material, Sanborn said.
</P>
<P>
   That interplay is part of what makes the twisty plot so fun. The
Web show is targeted for a broad-ranging audience that tends to be
more passive in its play, Sanborn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made for a mass-entertainment audience,'' Sanborn said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Paul Is Dead'' also has enough depth to satisfy people who
have a gamer's mentality, or who just like pawing through a
fictional world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, you can just watch it, or if you want, you can root
around,'' Sanborn said. ``There's puzzles, there's locked rooms,
there's Q-and-As, but they're not essential to the piece. ``Paul Is
Dead' is an attempt to create a world that people can get highly
involved with.''
</P>
<P>
   As involved as the plot may be, the Web show's financial history
may be even more confusing and mysterious. It originally was
commissioned by Microsoft Network, then was handed off to partner
MGM Interactive before finally ending up back with Kaplan and
Sanborn.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, the show survived, making ``Paul Is Dead'' is
a lively addition to the online world.
</P>
<P>
   ALL PLAY FOR THIS `BOY': After surviving online quite nicely the
past few years on the strength of its own brand of fun, Playboy has
decided to beef up its Internet site, signing partnerships with
three quirky Web sites, none of which has much to do with naked
women, martinis or Alex Haley interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best-known is Hecklers Online, which has been the
top humor site on America Online the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The Hecklers bill themselves more as humor editors than humor
writers, depending on daily submissions by thousands of readers for
the raw material of their constantly changing site. Reader potshots
become, for instance, an Interactive Top 10 of jokes each day, said
Barry Patterson, the company's business development director.
</P>
<P>
   The Hecklers said they will stay on AOL, but will be able to run
other edgier, more adult humor with their Playboy site that could
never appear on the squeaky clean AOL.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Patterson said, AOL has spiked comedy bits such as
a mock science story of a giant body part enveloping the galaxy,
and a reader-generated list of words that sound dirty but aren't.
Those are the sorts of things that will appear on the Hecklers'
Playboy site.
</P>
<P>
   The Hecklers also will routinely attend Playboy Mansion parties
and other events, digital cameras in hand, and create humor based
on what they see.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy also has become the online entry point to Monk, the
electronic version of the offbeat 13-year-old magazine of life on
the road, published by Michael Lane and Jim Crotty.
</P>
<P>
   The two travel the country in a pink motor home, theming each
issue around a specific city, and writing about its distinctive
places and people. With Playboy, the Monk boys will be focusing on
such things as the 40 gotta-see places in each town they visit,
Crotty said.
</P>
<P>
   The other new site is the Smoking Gun, which has long qualified
as noir weird. The site specializes in publishing official
documents from notorious cases, big and small, with appropriate
annotation and explanation.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone with an interest in the sometimes bizarre verite of
judicial and government documents, the Gun site has long been worth
a bookmark.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the deals, Playboy Enterprises CEO Christie Hefner
said the company decided a year ago that it needed to treat its Web
site, which is among the Internet's busiest, as more than just a
stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   That meant more partnerships and content, such as with Hecklers,
Monk and the Smoking Gun, and just-announced deals with seven
electronic-commerce sites for such things as compact disc sales.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy's biggest addition, online gambling, remains a ways off
in the future, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the political environment will change, and so
will the ability for government to (collect) its taxes, which is
the precursor to legitimizing online gambling,'' Hefner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
