<SLUG> BC-DORM-DESIGN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A CRASH COURSE IN COZY 101
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ask any college kid _ er, young adult _ heading
off to school in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating a dorm room ranks high on the list of things to do in
the first few days of the fall semester, right up there with
running to the bookstore before all the used copies sell out and
getting into classes that don't start before midmorning.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, dorm rooms are more than merely a place to crash.
They're a home away from home, the first place students can truly
call their own, where parents can't censor their choice of posters
or force them to pick up their dirty socks.
</P>
<P>
   Dorm-room decorating has become serious business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dorm room is a reflection of myself,'' said Juan Venegas, a
senior at California State University, Northridge. ``It's my
sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   In Torrey Pine residence hall, Venegas' theme is fraternity
paraphernalia and family photos. Down the hall, Tierney Sams, a
junior from Los Angeles, expresses her taste in music by hanging
posters of jazz and hip-hop performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a creative person, so I like a dorm room to describe who I
am,'' Sams said. ``It gives me a cozy, home type of feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tierney prowls the aisles of Pic N Save, finding bargains on
colorful containers she uses for storage, candle holders and vases.
</P>
<P>
   To give students some additional ideas, home-decorating experts
create their vision of the perfect dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sunyog, home trend manager for Mervyn's California,
created a room bursting with color by using fabrics in bright red,
yellow, blue and green.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Dean, owner of Dean Interior Design in Studio City, put
together a room ``that a couple of guys would actually live in,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And a team from IKEA in Burbank _ Monica Lovkvist, an interior
designer, and Chrissy Bates, a visual merchandiser _ went for a
unisex look that was both utilitarian and stylish.
</P>
<P>
   Each decorator began with the basics: two twin beds, two brown
Formica dressers, two desks, off-white walls and a purplish-blue
carpet in CSUN's Building 6.
</P>
<P>
   In just under two hours apiece, they transformed the rooms into
dorm sweet dorm.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Dean accomplished a truly authentic male look _ minus
the dirty clothes strewn on the floor _ by keeping accessories to a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Dean chose comforters in washable denim blue ($69.99 at Strouds)
and blue and gray stripes ($79.99 at Strouds), with a single throw
pillow ($12.99 at Strouds) on each.
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed Pamela Anderson pin-ups and Dodgers pennants from
his 12-year-old son's room and surfing posters (ranging in price
from free to $5.95 at Val Surf) to make this a room any guy could
feel comfortable not making his bed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a small room and put a lot of items in it,
aesthetically placed, the room has a tendency to look bigger,'' he
said. ``It's the optical illusion of design.''
</P>
<P>
   (And, Dean reminds, no dorm room is complete without a framed
photo of Mom and Dad to help remind students who's paying the
bills.)
</P>
<P>
   Ever see those television commercials where IKEA worker bees
transform an operating room and subway car into cozy living areas?
</P>
<P>
   IKEA's Monica Lovkvist and Chrissy Bates accomplished no less a
feat at CSUN. Keeping in mind the tight budgets of most college
students, they chose some of the store's lower-priced items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dorm rooms can be cold and impersonal,'' Lovkvist said.
``Students should have some cozy things around them to make them
feel at home. It's the first step of starting their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BEDS: Most dorm rooms come with those awful white
hospital-style sheets that won't do much for making you feel at
home. In their place, the pair chose cotton sheets in black, white,
blue and red ($9.95 for a set of two pillow cases, $6.95 each for
flat and fitted sheets) with a coordinating duvet ($29.95) and
throw pillows ($5.95 to $12.95). For added color, they folded a
lightweight cotton blanket ($29.95) over the duvet.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid having to dig around in the bottom of a closet to find
the match to your favorite pair of platform shoes, put
space-saving, galvanized steel shoe racks ($5.95) under the bed,
said the IKEA team.
</P>
<P>
   THE SHELVES: Unfinished pine boxes in assorted styles and sizes
(ranging from $9.95 to $19.95) can help maximize space and avoid
clutter. Put them on a desktop to hold papers, under beds for
storage and on shelves for style. For a personal touch, students
can add handles (IKEA sells hundreds of varieties ranging from 95
cents to $6.95 for a set of two). For added flair, stain or paint
the wood, or simply use marking pens to draw whatever you'd like.
</P>
<P>
   THE DESK: Good lighting is essential for studying. Halogen desk
lamps ($29.95) provide a softer light than the overhead fluorescent
fixtures. Keep your papers organized with three-level paper trays
($24.95).
</P>
<P>
   An X-shaped magnetic board ($4.95) is an alternative to a
bulletin board for posting notes, and a wooden figurine ($12.95) is
a funky knick-knack. Empty, frosted glass bottles ($3.95 to $9.95)
can make simple accessories or vases.
</P>
<P>
   The white swivel desk chairs ($79 each) might not be the most
comfortable for long hours of hitting the books, but they do look
stylish.
</P>
<P>
   THE WALLS: On the left side, the IKEA decorators hung three
prints of scenes from New York ($7.95 each) in matted frames
($12.95 each). (The frames are also a perfect fit for old album
covers.)
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite wall, Bates searched the children's section of
IKEA and found ``fun-house'' mirrors ($4.95 each) to ``add some
dimension to the room,'' she said. Another option is hanging a
bright light in front of the mirrors, for a disco-ball effect.
</P>
<P>
   On the floors, Bates and Lovkvist laid two rugs ($19.95 each) in
complementary geometric patterns.
</P>
<P>
   They used an extra dresser between the beds to double as a
nightstand. No college student can expect to graduate without a
reliable _ and loud _ alarm clock. Rather than the standard black
digital kind, they chose retro-looking blue and yellow clocks
($14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Tabletop lamps ($24.95) with paper shades can provide ambient
light. Since students might not remember to water their plants, the
decorating duo chose a hearty ficus plant ($6.95) in a galvanized
steel pot ($7.95) to add warmth to the room.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important items in a dorm room is the bed _ not
only for a good night's sleep after staying up all night cramming
for finals but to serve as a couch for entertaining friends.
</P>
<P>
   A sure way to make your bed both luxurious for sleeping and
comfy for sitting is lot of pillows, whether they are the sleeping
kind encased in colorful pillowcases ($14.99 for a set of two),
fabric throw pillows ($14.99) or plastic, inflatable pillows
($9.99), said Steve Sunyog.
</P>
<P>
   No college dorm room is complete without plastic milk crates
($4.99 each). Stack them to make a night stand, a table for a
microwave or extra storage area for books and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A fitted sheet ($7.99) secured to the wall with a staple gun to
make a pouffy valance can work as an inexpensive alternative to
curtains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a nice little pop of color to your walls,'' Sunyog
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other homey accessories include: trash can ($14.99), plates
($3.99 each), bowls ($3.99 each), tumblers ($3.99 each), bath
towels ($7.99).
</P>
<P>
   A dorm room staple for decades, a beanbag chair ($39.99) is
still a great place to flop with a book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
