<HEADLINE>
LOW RATINGS SINK MAGIC JOHNSON AFTER ONLY TWO MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final stunt for ``The Magic Hour'' will be a vanishing act.
The late-night talk show, featuring the basketball legend Earvin
``Magic'' Johnson as its host, has been canceled by its syndicator,
20th Television, after only two months because of low ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the hourlong show appears on Fox at 11:30 on
weeknights. Reruns will continue until early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were improving with each day,'' Johnson said in a
statement, ``but this is television, and shows are canceled all the
time for one reason or another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magic Hour'' had an average Nielsen rating of 1.6, or a
little more than 2 million viewers each night, since its June 8
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the show was gaining in popularity, the economics of
such a major enterprise make it impossible to continue beyond its
initial commitment without gaining higher ratings in a very short
time,'' said the announcement by 20th Television, which is owned by
Fox's parent, the News Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
