<HEADLINE>
JENNA'S LAW MAY DEFANG GOP ATTACKS ON DEMOCRATS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACEY TULLY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The name ``Jenna'' took on a sad,
larger-than-life quality over the last year in the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that Russell Sage College nursing students mourned
the death of their friend and classmate, Jenna Grieshaber, 22.
</P>
<P>
   On Interstate 787, a billboard _ an advertisement for a law firm
_ screams ``JUSTICE FOR JENNA'' in red ink.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, lawyers are preparing to defend the Albany Police
Department against a lawsuit that, in part, alleges that the police
let Jenna's suspected killer escape from the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   A memory. An ad. A lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, a law. On the steps of the state Capitol,
Jenna's name became permanently linked to legislation eliminating
parole for violent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gov. George Pataki signed the bill, another potential
legacy of the death began to melt away.
</P>
<P>
   Because Republicans can no longer claim that Assembly Democrats
blocked the legislation, her name suddenly lost much of its power
as campaign ammunition in November's elections, according to
pundits and pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be a campaign issue,'' said Joseph
Crangle, a Buffalo lawyer who has served as past chairman of the
Democratic State Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly takes some of the wind out of the Republicans'
sails,'' Marist College pollster Lee Miringoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Majority Leader Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, had
initially blocked the lower house from voting on the bill, arguing
that the law should also include increased drug treatment and
education programs. Republicans responded by mounting an intense
campaign to portray Assembly Democrats as being soft on crime.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, bowing to the fierce political pressure, Silver
called the Assembly back into session and the law passed with
strong bipartisan support. It requires first-time violent offenders
to serve at least six-sevenths of their maximum term and extends
the post-release supervision period.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Sheinkopf, a Democratic political consultant, agreed that
Assembly Democrats _ especially those upstate who face tight races
_ can certainly breathe easier. But this relief came at a high
price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, Sheinkopf said, has ``disarmed the Republicans'' in
districts with equal numbers of enrolled Democrats and Republicans,
where incumbents will face the toughest challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he paid a very big price. And Pataki's the big winner,''
Sheinkopf said. Pataki, a Republican, will now be able to
concentrate on criminal justice issues and downplay the struggling
upstate economy as he campaigns for re-election, Sheinkopf
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be the man who made you safer and the economic
villain at the same time,'' Sheinkopf said. ``Would you rather be
safe or would you rather be employed?''
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga County Republican Chairman John ``Jasper'' Nolan agreed
that Silver's decision to allow the bill to the floor for a vote
``nullified'' a potentially powerful campaign issue. But he said
Silver's initial reluctance helps the Republicans draw a clear
distinction between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years, no one could really grasp what the Republicans
where trying to say. And then tragically, this young woman's death
gave it a personality,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   The law remains a powerful symbol of discord between the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jenna's law is a striking example of the kind of issues that
they (Republicans) are using to separate themselves from the
Democratic leadership in the Assembly,'' said Thomas Slater, a
Clifton Park political consultant who is working on several
Republican campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Green, an Albany prison-rights activist and Green Party
candidate for lieutenant governor, said she believed the political
attacks leveled by Republicans have been successful. Green staged a
36-hour hunger strike last week in opposition to Jenna's Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've hammered away enough at it. They've said: `We're the
people who want to protect you. They've completely dehumanized the
suspect,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, pollster John Zogby maintains that there is too much time
before the November election for the issue to have any real effect.
And he expects that low voter turnout in September and November
will benefit incumbents, whether Republican or Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not a year when you're going to be able to generate
any sense of passion in people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
