<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRILLIN-HUMOR-ART-775     08-07 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRILLIN-HUMOR-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LUNCH WITH CALVIN TRILLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As an author and deadpan humorist, Calvin Trillin
often recycles his life into his essays and stories and then
recycles them into books. In ``Family Man,'' his latest and his
20th book, he says that for a writer nothing is off the record. He
gave an early warning to that effect to his wife, Alice, and their
two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Although as adults, each daughter has shown signs of literary
talent, he does not fear filial reciprocity: ``When they were about
5 and 8, I asked them to sign a standard nondisclosure agreement.
Nothing fancy. When they didn't understand why they were doing it,
I said, `Trust your daddy.'''
</P>
<P>
   After he finished writing his book _ wry tales and home truths
about life with the Trillins _ he asked them to vet it for moments
that might make them uncomfortable. His older daughter was peeved
because she had wanted to tell some of the stories herself. His
response: ``You should have gotten there first, kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled. He loves his family and is having a happy life
_ and he is a little embarrassed about that fact. There is no Dark
Secret in his past, and he knows that Dark Secrets sell books.
</P>
<P>
   Trillin was having lunch at one of his favorite restaurants, the
Union Square Cafe, but the ground rules for the meeting were that
he would not talk about food. He often talks and writes about food,
as in his ``tummy trilogy'' about eating in America. The
conversational aim was to furrow new Trillinesque territory, but
feinschmecker that he is, his appetite kept intruding, as in his
opening gambit to the waitress: ``I would like the only martini
ordered here this afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Family Man,'' he says that a writer's obligation to his art
and to his family depends on the quality of the art. He offers the
Dostoyevsky Test: ``If you have reason to believe that you're
another Dostoyevsky, you can say anything you need to say.'' And if
you don't, you can't.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know if you're another Dostoyevsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``A rational human being would realize he's not another
Dostoyevsky around the time of the first piece he writes,'' Trillin
said. ``I can't remember whether Dostoyevsky was a late bloomer or
not. I do remember when there was a question about the dental plan
at The New Yorker, I was told that writers were basically artists
and didn't have to worry about such mundane, bourgeois things as
dental plans, and that Dosteyevsky didn't have a dental plan. I
said, did you ever get a load of his teeth? Dostoyevsky belonged to
the wrong HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the question, he said: ``I just thought of an
answer. If there's a comparison to Dostoyevsky in the review of
your first book, then at least you have a shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it's a negative comparison?
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean like, `the notion of this guy writing on the same
planet with Dostoyevsky is laughable?' Let me think about that for
a minute. I thought about it. No.''
</P>
<P>
   The food arrived at the table, ``spicy deluxe chicken salad.''
``It looks more deluxe than spicy,'' he commented, then admitted,
``Spicy's hard to see, unless it has those big red things.''
</P>
<P>
   As a working journalist, he has said that the ``principal side
benefit'' of his profession is a ``decent-size death notice.'' He
imagined that in his own obituary, the subhead would read
``Monolingual Reporter Succumbs.'' He was asked what should come
after the comma, a writer who ...? Would it be Calvin Trillin, ``a
writer who never forgot Rule 6: Enough is enough.'' Or ``a would-be
Dostoyevsky who settled for a life of rhyme,'' or the ``funniest
man named Calvin?''
</P>
<P>
   Sifting possibilities, he said, ``My problem with that is that
I've never known exactly which hat I was wearing: the reporter
fedora with the little press badge in the hatband, or the jester
with the pompom bouncing in my eyes. If I had called in a
professional career consultant, he would have said you have to
figure out what's going to be after the comma in your obituary.
Then, you'll know how to get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Trillin said that recently he had been talking to a friend who
shared his birth date, Dec. 5. ``We were talking about famous
people who were born Dec. 5. I, of course, brought up Walt Disney.
Kansas City guy, Walt Disney. And either Somoza or Trujillo, one of
the big dictators. My friend said, `And Calvin Coolidge,' of
course. I said, `Calvin Coolidge was born on Dec. 5?' Does that
explain it? Could it be that my parents were going to name me
Grover or Millard, and then it turned out I was born on Dec. 5, so
they named me Calvin? I rather doubt it, since I looked up Calvin
Coolidge and he was born in July.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Then he explained that he once thought about interfering with an
advance obituary. ``The wily and parsimonious Victor Navasky called
me and up and said, `This joke of yours about how cheap I am has
gone too far.''' Trillin has often said that when he writes pieces
for Navasky at The Nation, he is paid ``in the high two figures.''
Confronted with the editor's protest, he said he would be willing
to join in a letter to ask that in his advance obit ``the
chintziness should be moved further down in the story.''
</P>
<P>
   He thereupon confessed that he had been offered the high two
figures but that his agent had ``got him up to $100,'' in other
words, the lowest three figures, and that is what he is paid for
his poems in The Nation. ``Poets are normally paid by the line,''
he said. ``The highest payment, the last time I checked, was $10 a
line at The New Yorker. I'm paid $100 no matter how long the poem
is. That's absolute top dollar in that field. I write a two-line
poem, that's $50 a line.''
</P>
<P>
   Trillin then revealed the key to his poetry: ``I usually set the
shower to iambic pentameter on Sunday night. My shower has an
iambic pentameter setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot, cold and iambic pentameter?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, ``and why do you think I'm so grateful to
Kenneth Starr?''
</P>
<P>
   Because his name is easy to rhyme?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but it's not as good as Ross Perot. Ross Perot was the
versifier's dream candidate for president _ an iambic pentameter
with an o rhyme.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Bush? ``It was hard because tush was not considered
respectful to the president,'' he said. ``In my farewell poem to
Bush, I only used his other names: `Farewell to you George Herbert
Walker.'''
</P>
<P>
   Among his more public ventures, Trillin has appeared in a
one-man show in the American Humorist series at the American Place
Theater, and he has acted in movies directed by Nora Ephron. ``We
prefer not to identify the director,'' he said. ``Then you think,
this man has been in a number of movies. Two. By chance by Nora
Ephron. Both of them were big successes. I'm sort of a talisman. I
was pretty good in `Sleepless in Seattle.' I didn't quite carry the
movie, although the Varsity Theater near the university in Seattle
had on its marquee, `Meg Ryan and Calvin Trillin in ``Sleepless in
Seattle.''' Tom Hanks did not make it.''
</P>
<P>
   How did he explain that? ``Talent. Name recognition.'' He said
that he and his wife and Ms. Ephron were together for Trillin's
60th birthday, and the director said she was about to start
shooting another movie. Out of the blue he asked her if there was a
role in it for a sheriff. As a matter of fact there was and, months
later, he was offered the role. He assumed the character with great
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by chance, I had the creed of the Texas Rangers on my
bulletin board: `No man in the wrong can stand up against a man
that's in the right and keeps on a-comin'. When I got into my
sheriff's costume and walked onto the set, Nora actually thought
maybe one of the movie vans had been parked in a no-parking zone
and some law enforcement officer had come in. I exuded Law
Enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been offered several non-Ephron films, including
one in which his character was described as ``a geeky-looking guy
in plaid pants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `That's not me. You're talking Tom Hanks.'''
</P>
<P>
   The waitress brought over a platter of cookies. He ate one, eyed
another and remembered Rule 6. Returning to an earlier subject, he
said, `` `Funniest person named Calvin' is very tempting. Can I put
a request in?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
