<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-SITTERS-NYT &LR;      08-07 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-SITTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOLESCENT GIRLS AS BABY SITTERS: IMAGE AND REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The baby sitter is downstairs, the children are asleep. The
phone rings. A maniac is calling _ from the upstairs extension.
</P>
<P>
   Baby sitters in jeopardy are a classic theme of the horror
genre, from the baby-sitter novels by R.L. Stine to movies like
``When a Stranger Calls.''
</P>
<P>
   To Miriam Formanek-Brunell, a professor of history at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City and the director of the Women's
and Gender Studies program there, the image of the baby sitter also
offers clues to deep-seated attitudes toward adolescent girls.
``Adolescent girls are either victims, villains or vixens in
popular culture,'' said Ms. Formanek-Brunell, who is writing a
history of baby-sitting in America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Formanek-Brunell's study is part of a new realm of scholarly
inquiry called ``girls' culture,'' which looks at girls and their
clubs, secret languages, games and books. This month, a new
anthology on girls culture, ``Delinquents and Debutantes:
Twentieth-Century American Girls' Cultures,'' edited by Sherrie A.
Inness, will be published by New York University Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls' lives have been overlooked until recently by
historians,'' said Ms. Formanek-Brunell, author of ``Made to Play
House: Dolls and the Commercialization of American Girlhood,
1830-1930'' (Yale University Press, 1993) and editor of ``The Story
of Rose O'Neill: An Autobiography'' (University of Missouri Press,
1997). ``Girls' lives tend to be trivialized and dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But baby-sitting has been the leading form of part-time
employment for adolescent girls since World War II,'' Ms.
Formanek-Brunell said. ``By 1948, it was a $750 million
industry.'''' It is also, she said, one of an adolescent girl's
``first steps toward independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Formanek-Brunell combed child-care manuals, baby-sitter
handbooks, periodicals and newspaper articles. ``Until 1941, I
couldn't find any mentions of baby sitters in popular culture,''
she said. ``Teen-age girls were not singled out as baby sitters.
They were one among many caretakers `minding' the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The professionalization of baby-sitting started right after
World War II, she said. During the war, adolescent girls had
factory jobs as part of the war effort. But at the end of the war,
they were pushed out to make way for returning soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of a new ``youth culture'' aimed at girls, she
said, they began working to earn money so they could buy newly
available consumer goods, like records and clothing. At the same
time, as couples began moving to the suburbs, away from their
extended families, there were were fewer relatives to care for
small children. Parents became dependent on sitters. ``Now girls
could charge for it,'' said Ms. Formanek-Brunell. ``They feel brash
and brazen. And they make parents' lives hellish.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast and the Midwest, they tried to form unions.
``They were perceived as militant radicals,'' Ms. Formanek-Brunell
said. The unions didn't catch on, but adolescent girls began
developing a culture of rebellion. Suburban houses had been built
with young children in mind and they provided little private space
for adolescents to gather. The girls began inviting their
girlfriends _ and boys _ over for parties. Girls were seen as a
destabilizing force. The YWCA responded to the tension created by
these newly assertive adolescents by developing courses on
baby-sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults are thinking that girls should baby-sit and not get
paid for it,'' Formanek-Brunell's said, ``The idea is that it is
their obligation as daughters and as young females. They should
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, parents felt guilty about hiring someone to
care for their children, said Ms. Formanek-Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   By the '50s, the baby sitter began to be seen as a sexual threat
to marital stability. ``She becomes an icon,'' said Ms.
Formanek-Brunell, ``She is dangerous. She represents social and
sexual disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Bother to Knock'' (1952), in which Marilyn Monroe plays
a young, disturbed woman hired to baby-sit, was an early example of
the baby sitter as villainous temptress. Later, in ``The
Babysitter,'' a story by Robert Coover, a husband has erotic
fantasies about the baby sitter. The story was made into a 1995
movie starring Alicia Silverstone.
</P>
<P>
   In movies like ``Fright'' (1971) and ``Halloween'' (1978) the
baby sitter is in for big trouble. ``Halloween'' actually has two
baby sitters who are attacked. Like Jamie Lee Curtis, the star of
``Halloween,'' many major female stars played baby sitters early in
their career. In the Stine novels, written in the late '80s and
early '90s, ``She is the victim of a crazed man who is beating up
baby sitters, and she becomes crazy herself,'' said Ms.
Formanek-Brunell
</P>
<P>
   She notes that on the covers of Stine's baby sitter books and in
``Baby Sitters Beware,'' one of The Baby-Sitters Club books: ``We
see the girl through the window. We become voyeurs, stalking and
watching her too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Formanek-Brunell points out the frequency of the image of
the telephone in the baby sitter horror genre. ``The phone is an
instrument of liberation for adolescent girls,'' she said. ``But it
is transformed into something extremely threatening that engenders
an undesirable intimacy with the maniac, and therefore brings about
her submission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular culture both mirrors and shapes the fears and
anxieties of adults about female adolescents,'' Ms.
Formanek-Brunell said. ``The girls are taking their first steps
toward independence, they're beginning to earn money, and they're
being hounded, stalked and frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   (And you were complaining about paying $7 an hour.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3213 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-DIVERSE-CHRIST     08-07 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-DIVERSE-CHRISTIANITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANITY ISN'T THE WHITE MAN'S RELIGION ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Repent of your sin! You have no inheritance in the Kingdom of
God! You are going to hell. You have made yourself homosexual
because of your carnality.''
 &HT;    Not intoned by some street-corner evangelist, this warning came
from the Rt. Rev. Emmanuel Chukwumu, an Anglican bishop from
Nigeria, outside the hall at the Lambeth Conference this week in
Canterbury.
 &HT;    Inside, Anglican bishops from around the world debated
homosexuality. Meeting in their once-a-decade convocation, bishops
from the Anglican Communion (the Episcopal Church in the United
States) soundly defeated any liberalization of Christian ethics
regarding sexual orientation.
 &HT;    Bishop Chukwumu continued preaching to gay activists: ``That is
why your Church is dying in Europe -- because it is condoning
immorality. You are killing the Church. This is the voice of God
talking. Yes, I am violent against sin. Sodom and Gomorrah were
destroyed.''
 &HT;    This encounter epitomizes the triumphs and tensions of
Christianity as it ends its second millennium.
 &HT;    Unbeknownst to most western Christians, the missionary
enterprise conducted by their forebears over the last three
centuries was successful. As
 &HT;    the world prepares to celebrate the 2,000th birthday of
Christianity's founder, the faith has undergone a remarkable
transformation.
 &HT;    The ``typical'' Christian is neither white nor of European
descent. Now, a Christian is more likely to be black, brown, yellow
or red. The world's largest religion has become the world's most
globally diverse faith.
 &HT;    Christianity's triumph confounds many liberal westerners.
Beginning early this century, many theologically liberal Europeans
and North Americans abandoned missions because of their
imperialistic assumptions.
 &HT;    However, when mainline Protestants stopped spreading the faith,
indigenous peoples began to evangelize their neighbors. Ironically,
liberal withdrawal created effective localized Christian missions
-- missions that transformed western Christianity into forms shaped
by native cultures.
 &HT;    Liberals were replaced not only by native missionaries -- often
theologically and biblically naive -- but also by the largest
evangelical mission force fielded in history. Following World War
II, evangelicals transformed the historically mainline mission
endeavor into a juggernaut of biblical literalism, traditional
values and conservative politics.
 &HT;    The views of these new missionaries meshed well with many
aspects of indigenous cultures. Armed with surprising cultural
sensitivity and advanced technologies, these missionaries and their
national partners converted millions previously outside the reach
of Christian churches. Through their efforts, and building on the
older missions, Christianity became the faith of sub-Saharan
Africa, South America, and large parts of Asia. Christianity isn't
the white man's religion anymore.
 &HT;    At Lambeth, Anglicans experienced the globalization of their
church. For the first time in their history, African and Asian
Anglican bishops outnumbered North Americans and Europeans.
 &HT;    From one perspective, this change delighted bishops from
traditionally British-based churches. Anglicanism is, indeed, a
lively, global, diverse and
 &HT;    growing faith. However, the change has also startled many. For
the most part, old-line Anglicans are socially and theologically
liberal; the new Anglicans -- influenced by cultural traditions and
theological literalism imparted by the evangelical mission force --
from the Two-Thirds World are not. Therefore, when sexual issues
came to a vote, the conservative Africa-Asian coalition demolished
any prospect of gay/lesbian ordination or same-sex union.
 &HT;    Many liberal Episcopalians, like myself, who take the Bible
seriously and favor liberalizing the church's teaching sexual
orientation, were distressed by the vote. We are rethinking
biblical theology regarding same-sex unions, and gay and lesbian
ordination. We are trying, in good conscience and fidelity, to
preach the gospel to our culture in a loving, grace-filled, and
meaningful way.
 &HT;    We believe that God's word lives as a powerful, healing force in
the church, our lives and our society. God calls each generation to
discern and speak that word and in the midst of the world's
turmoil.
 &HT;    Following Lambeth, many Episcopalians will blame the vote on
African and Asian homophobia or a vast right-wing conspiracy to
overturn theological liberalism in the church.
 &HT;    While Africans and Asians probably are homophobic and a
right-wing Episcopal conspiracy probably exists, that's not the
problem. The problem is that liberal Christians-- Episcopalians
included - have been too shy and slow to proclaim the good news as
we understand it. We abandoned the mission field, thus allowing
biblical literalism and ignorance to shape new churches and
theological education.
 &HT;    We were so afraid of our colonial sins that we silenced
ourselves, withholding our faith experience from our brothers and
sisters. We ignored Africa and Asia unless they fit with a liberal
political agenda. We neglected Jesus' command to go and teach the
nations. We failed.
 &HT;    We liberal chickens have finally come home to roost. For a
century, while Christianity has exploded across the globe with new
vitality, mainline Christians have sat puzzled on the sidelines.
 &HT;    No, Bishop Chukwumu, our churches are not dying because of
immorality. We are dying of timidity.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
