A3264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PULPIT-$ADV9-     08-07 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PULPIT-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION PUTS CRACKS ON PILLARS OF CLINTON'S LEGACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 9) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This was to be President Clinton's year for big
ideas, a time to cement his legacy as the first two-term Democratic
president since Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months ago, the president spent his 1997 vacation
reviewing a binder filled with projects that would form the pillars
of his place in history. This week, he is preparing to testify Aug.
17 before a grand jury investigating allegations he had an affair
with a White House intern and urged her to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the scandal, the pillars of his legacy are cracking.
And the projects _ race relations, anti-tobacco legislation,
climate change initiatives and Social Security reform _ are
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidents in their second term always face the reality of
dwindling influence but this particular scandal has just perhaps
accelerated that process,'' said Earl Black, a political science
professor at Rice University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Added a top Republican congressional aide: ``He's destroyed his
bully pulpit and no one trusts him. His whole agenda has suffered
as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide recalled that in January Republicans braced for a major
State of the Union address by Clinton who then was riding high in
the polls and on a roll politically.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was being balanced for the first time in 30 years,
the economy was thriving, unemployment was at its lowest rates in a
generation, inflation was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of concerned about that, but all the momentum
just died as soon as the Monica Lewinsky story broke, and he has
not been able to regain that momentum,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton has learned with a Republican-controlled Congress,
his greatest asset is his ability to use his office and his moral
authority, the bully pulpit of the presidency, to persuade the
public and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the president repeatedly has told people, this is the
time to solve the nation's big challenges.
</P>
<P>
   But his initiative to spark a dialogue on race relations has
been deemed lackluster by critics who complained the debate never
got off the ground. Tobacco legislation, patient bill of rights
legislation, campaign finance reform all foundered in Congress as
emboldened Republicans kept on eye on the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of specific legislative issues, I think the president
finds it difficult to be influential at critical moments,'' said
Robert Holsworth, a political science professor at Virginia
Commonwealth University in Richmond, Va. ``He certainly seems to
have lost his moral authority and his political clout has
dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that at a critical moment in the life of
the historic tobacco legislation, Clinton was unable to step into
the debate and control it. The legislation would have raised
cigarette prices by $1.10 per pack to discourage use by youths and
to reimburse states for the medical costs caused by ailing smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really bizarre political situation where you have a
president with an extraordinary high level of job approval who
can't seem to use it as leverage with the Congress,'' Holsworth
said.
</P>
<P>
   Holsworth also harkened back to Clinton's 1997 inaugural address
in which he pledged to help heal the wounds of the nation, to help
end rampant cynicism, to help revitalize the political center
against the extremes of the left and right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is that going nowhere, but he has to appeal to the
very elements of the culture that he wants to change in order to
fend off these attacks. So my feeling is this grand rhetoric about
articulating a third way and developing a new vital center is just
completely off the table at the moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Congress has passed few pieces of legislation as the
Republican leaders have battled among themselves over the direction
their party should take. Neither party has much incentive to
compromise on major issues, preferring instead to turn them into
major political issues for the fall campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and Democrats on Capitol Hill maintain the
president has pressed his agenda just as hard as possible and blame
Republicans for stalled legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried really hard not to let this affect the president's
public schedule,'' said Paul Begala, a senior Clinton adviser. In
an odd way, Begala said, the president was able to present his
agenda to the public more easily because networks so often
broadcast his speeches live.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways to manipulate this media obsession to the
advantage of policy,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has been on message. He hasn't deviated,'' said
Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas. ``There has been a concerted effort to
distract him from the issues, and I don't see that ending when this
investigation is over. Still, the president stays focused and
pushes our message.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, said, ``As far as I can tell, the
president is out front and center talking about issues people care
about.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has since January, Clinton worked hard this week to
present a picture of a president going about his business, although
he studiously ignores reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around here are doing there jobs,'' said spokesman
Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   And, Clinton, attending a $1.2 million fund-raiser for Democrats
last week, told the crowd of contributors, ``When I was re-elected,
the vice president and I sat down one day and I told our people, I
said, `Look, I want us to drive the agenda of this country until
the last hour of the last day of my term in January of 2001. That
is what we signed on for; that is what we owe the American people;
that is the right thing to do.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
