<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN     08-07 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY ISSUE DIVIDES ANGLICAN COMMUNION, MANY U.S. BISHOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the significant messages coming out of the Lambeth
Conference in Canterbury, England, is the clear confirmation that
the Episcopal Church in the United States is much more liberal than
many other provinces of the worldwide Anglican Communion.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Episcopalians from the United States _ including
Bishops Jack Iker of Fort Worth and James Stanton of Dallas _ are
usually in the minority when they speak out against gays in their
home country.
</P>
<P>
   But they were in the majority at the Lambeth meeting, held every
10 years. They joined with bishops from Africa and other parts of
the globe to push through a resolution strongly stating that
homosexuality is incompatible with Christian teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Iker, one of the few American bishops still refusing to ordain
women, also was buoyed by another resolution that said bishops
``should not be compelled to ordain and license women.'' It called
for establishing special provinces for bishops who oppose women's
ordination.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, though he opposes ordaining gays and conducting
same-sex unions, favors ordaining women.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops voted 526-70 for the resolution on homosexuality.
Forty-five bishops, including Presiding Bishop Frank Griswold of
the United States, abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution rejected the practice of ordaining gays and
lesbians and conducting marriage ceremonies for gay couples. An
amendment explicitly condemned homosexual practice.
</P>
<P>
   After the homosexuality vote, members of the Episcopal Synod of
America, a conservative coalition based in Fort Worth, walked out
of the meeting room chanting ``V-I-C-T-O-R-Y,'' according to Katie
Sherrod of Fort Worth, who was a part of the Episcopal News Service
team of reporters covering Lambeth.
</P>
<P>
   Iker and Stanton have been saying all along that the American
church is more liberal than the rest of the Anglican Communion on
the subject of homosexuality. And the Lambeth Conference proved
their point.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Eustace Kamanyire of Uganda was quoted by Religious News
Service as saying that acceptance of homosexual practices by
Anglican clergy is undermining the church in many parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This false teaching emanating from part of the Anglican
Communion, when exported to Africa and other parts of the world, is
causing serious damage and scandal to Christ and his church,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the resolution won't change the deep divisions over gay
ordinations and blessing of same-sex unions that exist among
Episcopal bishops in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop John Spong of Newark, N.J., one of the bishops who has
ordained gays, circulated a statement signed by other bishops from
the United States, England, Canada, Australia, Ireland, New
Zealand, South Africa and Wales vowing to continue seeking ``full
inclusion'' of gays in the life of the church.
</P>
<P>
   One of the signers, Bishop Catherine Waynick of Indianopolis,
was quoted by Religious News Service as saying, ``I want to suggest
that our call is not to correctness but to love.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-week-long Lambeth Conference, although influential, is
not a legislative body, as Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey
emphasized repeatedly. Decisions made at the conference are not
binding on any of the churches.
</P>
<P>
   Carey, at the end of the conference, urged his fellow church
members to engage in friendly dialogue on the controversial issues
facing the church.
</P>
<P>
   While rejecting ordination of gays and same-sex unions, the
resolution spoke out on the need to minister to many gays in
Anglican churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many ... are seeking the pastoral care and moral direction of
the church and God's transforming power,'' the resolution said.
``We commit ourselves to listen to the experience of homosexual
people. We wish to assure them that they are loved by God and that
all baptized, believing and faithful persons, regardless of sexual
orientation, are full members in the body of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the statement on homosexuality is not binding, Iker,
Stanton and other American conservatives will be energized anew to
carry on their fight against more liberal practices in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
