<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRIVILEGE-$AD     08-07 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRIVILEGE-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S BATTLE WITH STARR MAY DISCOURAGE FUTURE PRESIDENTIAL
CANDIDATES, EXPERTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whether President Clinton's failed efforts to keep
private conversations from a grand jury will affect the authority
of future chief executives is uncertain. But the allegations of
extramarital sex, obstruction of justice and perjury plaguing
Clinton will be a warning to his successors and may even discourage
qualified applicants from seeking the office, presidential scholars
say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's epic battle with independent counsel Kenneth Starr
over whether the president tried to cover up an alleged sexual
relationship has led to judicial decisions compelling the grand
jury testimony of White House attorneys and Secret Service agents.
The courtroom defeats might not have eroded the ability of future
presidents to be effective, but they have altered the course of
Clinton's presidency, the power of independent counsels and perhaps
the caliber of future chief executives, said Eastern Michigan
University professor Edward Sidlow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current situation is really in some ways real particular
to this president and this really aggressive special counsel,''
said Sidlow, who heads the university's political science
department. ``I think as much as one might sit back and question
how future presidents might be affected you also have to question
what sort of latitude future special counsels are going to have.``
</P>
<P>
   Sidlow said Starr's zeal in investigating Clinton's relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky might dissuade
qualified people from running for office. ``Who's going to want to
serve as president ... if this is the kind of tawdry business
they're going to get involved with?'' the professor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a former federal judge and U.S. solicitor general, has
not been afraid to test the boundaries of the sacrosanct
attorney-client privilege in seeking the testimony of White House
attorneys, including long-term Clinton confidant Bruce Lindsey.
Starr, a renowned appellate advocate, also showed no fear in
seeking testimony from Secret Service agents regarding what they
saw or heard from the president during their efforts to guard his
life.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington, D.C., has ruled
against the president in both cases, delivering crushing defeats to
Clinton's efforts to keep the content of his conversations with
White House attorneys from the grand jury as well as the
president's attempt to keep his security detail from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has appealed the decisions to the Supreme Court. But, in
the meantime, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist has cleared the
way for the White House lawyers and Secret Service agents to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's losses in the circuit court, if upheld, might give
comfort to his Republican detractors in Congress and undermine
efforts of future presidents to advance their national agendas,
said Rice University professor Paul Brace. As an extreme example,
Brace said, presidents would be unable to conduct private treaty
negotiations if opponents of such an international agreement were
privy to the confidential discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never good to have a precedent on the books that can
serve to reduce presidential prerogatives in the future,'' Brace
said. ``The presidency should be protected from that sort of
partisan meddling.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Brace said, future presidents can take some solace
in Clinton's poll numbers. Clinton continues to be immensely
popular with the electorate, as its misgivings regarding his
behavior and truthfulness have been superseded by the credit it
gives him for the U.S. economic well being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the right economic conditions, the public is willing to
disconnect the president's moral behavior,'' Brace said. ``You can
probably get away with a great deal'' as president if the nation's
fiscal health is good, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another legal setback for Clinton, a unanimous Supreme Court
ruled last year that a sitting president may be sued. That decision
cleared the way for Paula Jones to pursue her allegation that
Clinton, while Arkansas governor, sexually harassed her by making
unwelcome sexual advances toward her in a Little Rock, Ark., hotel
room.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the high court's decision, Clinton was compelled
to sit for a deposition in that case. The president's testimony in
that litigation has led to Starr's investigation as to whether
Clinton committed perjury when he told Jones' lawyers under oath
that he did not have a sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones case, dismissed by a federal judge, has been appealed
to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The legal defeats, while dramatic, will have no effect on
presidents' ability to lead effectively, provided their poll
numbers are high, said Roderick Hart, a professor at the University
of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of 10 politics trumps law in the life of the
presidency,'' Hart said. ``The presidency rests more on political
pedestals than legal ones and always has.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's judicial losses, Hart said, will merely remind future
presidents of something they should already know: Be very careful
of what you say and to whom you say it. ``Presidents today assume
that most of the people they talk to are looking for a book
contract,'' Hart said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
