<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCISCANPRIEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A LONG WAY FROM THE HEART OF TEXAS TO THE BASILICA FOR THIS
PRIEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Rev. Robert Sisk is 65. But he hustles up four
flights of stairs without huffing and puffing to show off his
favorite spot in an ancient basilica in the heart of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists never see this,'' said the buoyant priest,
pointing from a rooftop patio to a commanding view of the famous
ruins of the Roman Forum, the government center of early Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance is the Mamertine prison, where early Christian
martyrs were confined before being executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inspiring,'' he said. ``Every day I can look out from the
patio and also from my office window and see the place where Peter
and Paul were in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Sisk, who was pastor of St. Maria Goretti Catholic Church in
Arlington, Texas, for four years before moving to Rome three years
ago, now is secretary-general and first counsel of the Third Order
Regular Franciscans, a worldwide order of missionary priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still write to some of my great friends in Arlington,'' he
said. ``They are beautiful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he lives and works amid history, helping supervise more than
300 missionary priests who work mostly among the poor around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Franciscan order, organized in 1447, was created by
followers of St. Francis of Assisi, the revered Italian monk who
led followers to take vows of poverty, chastity and obedience, and
then travel to many places spreading the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk is a true Franciscan.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 17 years in a 100,000-square-mile Amazon region, often
living in the jungle in primitive conditions. He traveled up and
down the river, creating hospitals, schools and mission churches.
Later, he was in South Africa during the time of apartheid, uniting
two branches of Fransiscans during a troubled period from 1979 to
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love getting out where the action is,'' he said. ``Since
I've been secretary-general here, I've visited all the missions,
except the Philippines, Sri Lanka, South Africa and a new mission
in Eastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been to India three times, Bangladesh twice, and Peru and
Paraguay once. He will travel to South Africa in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in India, I celebrated Mass at Mother Teresa's
tomb,'' he said. ``Some of the Franciscans in India helped Mother
Teresa when she was first starting her work.''
</P>
<P>
   People don't realize how many Christians there are in India,
Sisk said. In Bangladesh, only 3 percent are Christian, but
Franciscans do significant work with tribal people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission in Bangladesh is among the poorest of the poor,''
he said. ``The toughest mission to visit is in Peru. It is high in
the mountains. You have to have a good heart to move around up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sisk's headquarters are in the Basilica of Sts. Cosma and
Damian, itself a shrine and place of pilgrimage. The basilica's
Christian history dates back to the time of Constantine.
</P>
<P>
   It is built over structures once a part of the Roman Forum.
Close by are what remains of the Temple of Julius Caesar, and down
the street is the restored Arch of Constantine, honoring the Roman
emperor who converted to Christianity. A little farther is the
massive Colosseum, where early Christians became martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting being in the midst of all this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During a noon meal at the basilica, the friars, sitting at dark
wooden tables, partook of a four-course meal of salad, pasta, meat
and dessert along with red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk gave a prayer of thanks, sampled the pasta, and told the
meal's preparers, ``This is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Branches of the Third Order Regular Franciscans also work in
urban areas, including the Catholic Diocese of Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 17 of our priests are in the Fort Worth diocese,'' Sisk
noted. One of them, the Rev. James Gigliotto, now is pastor of the
St. Maria Goretti church in Arlington. Another, the Rev. Raymond
Nedimyer, is an associate there.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries of all Franciscan missionary priests _ including those
in the Fort Worth Diocese _ go into a fund that finances the
international work of the order, Sisk said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is stimulating living among sites of early
Christianity, Sisk said his favorite part of the job is traveling
to the remote mission fields.
</P>
<P>
   His most nostalgic journey has been revisiting the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the young men I knew while in the Amazon now are
ordained priests working among their own people,'' he said. ``It
was my biggest joy to hear people say they are good priests.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
