<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-NISSAN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN GIVES A GLIMPSE OF ITS PLAN FOR RECOVERY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its advertising slogan notwithstanding, Nissan has not been
enjoying the ride. Now, it is counting on some new models to get it
down a very bumpy road.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where the company has historically been No. 2 to
Toyota, sales have fallen in a slumping economy while its debt has
soared to $30 billion. Nissan posted a net loss of more than $100
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, sales plunged 28 percent in the first half
of 1998. Sweet leasing deals of years past have produced a glut of
used cars, overvalued on the books, that haunts new-car sales
today. With 215,000 new vehicles unsold at midyear _ despite
discounts of up to $2,500 _ Nissan cut output at its plant in
Smyrna, Tenn., by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as sort of a Japanese BMW, thanks to durable,
fun-to-drive cars like the Datsun 510, Sentra SE-R and Maxima,
Nissan took chances on innovative designs, like the 240Z that
created a new market for moderately priced sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   But many recent Nissans have lacked flair, though the vehicles'
quality ratings remain high and their performance is competitive.
</P>
<P>
   With the axing of the 300ZX sports car two years ago, dealers
were left without an image-builder to lure shoppers. And Nissan's
Japan-centered decision-making showed a failure to understand
changing American tastes: The company still lacks a small sport
utility, and it is trying to sell a revamped Frontier pickup with
four cylinders, two doors and a cramped cabin to Americans who want
big engines, multiple doors and lots of space.
</P>
<P>
   With dealers anxious and the financial community suggesting that
Nissan might become a takeover target _ possibly for a newly merged
DaimlerChrysler _ the company gathered its top executives last
month for an American tour before dealers, financial analysts and
automotive journalists. In an unusual move, it also offered a peak
at future products and prototypes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the business front, Nissan reiterated its plan to reduce its
debt by 25 percent within three years and to consolidate its two
North American units to streamline decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to reduce the number of platforms _ the costly basic
building blocks of cars and trucks _ from 25 currently to 10 by
2003 and to slash $1,000 a car from its production costs, which are
now higher than Toyota's or Honda's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the company's design studio in California is
getting more responsibility to develop models for North America. In
the past, American designs were often pushed aside in favor of more
conservative vehicles from Japan that failed to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that while Nissan's coming products would
help, they did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Nissan to really change the image of the brand, they need
the coupes and convertibles and fun-centered concepts,'' said Susan
G. Jacobs, an automotive analyst in Rutherford, N.J. ``Most of its
competitors will be coming out with fun cars, while Nissan will be
focused on sedans, wagons and trucks. It's very hard to change a
brand with sedans and wagons.''
</P>
<P>
   Nissan executives say they're building a base for the future.
``There's nothing like a good jolt of fear to release the creative
juices,'' Jerry Hirshberg, president of Nissan Design
International, said in New York as he took the wraps off these
vehicles: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000 SENTRA More expensive-looking than the current model, the
next Sentra has a stylish rear end evocative of the Audi A4.
Hirshberg called it an entry-level car ``people don't have to
apologize for.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000 MAXIMA In a bid to revive the Maxima's sporting image after
the last redesign produced a more mainstream family sedan, the
prototype of the next Maxima appears larger and jazzier, with
styling that emphasizes the wheels. Prominent, round taillights are
set into a tapered, Jaguar-like tail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRONTIER FOUR-DOOR Nissan's slow-selling pickup will get a V6
this fall; next fall, it will be available with four full-size
doors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SMALLER SPORT UTILITY Based on the Frontier, this yet-unnamed
truck is likely to be priced around $20,000. But in contrast to the
car-based Toyota RAV4 and Honda CR-V, the Nissan will be defiantly
rugged, with body-on-frame construction, a two-step roof like the
Land Rover Discovery's and higher ``theater seating'' in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at young buyers _ ``people who need places for lots of
stuff,'' Hirshberg said _ the vehicle will have many nooks,
crannies and cubbyholes, including a ``backpack'' built into the
inside of the tailgate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPORT UTILITY TRUCK Also based on the Frontier, the ``SUT'' has
the look of a miniature Hummer. Hirshberg cited surveys showing
that truck owners use the cargo bed less than 70 percent of the
time, and even then, they use only 20 percent of the space.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan would substitute a small bed for a utility vehicle's
usual cargo area, with a twist _ to accommodate objects too large
for the truck bed, the back seats could be folded and the rear of
the cabin opened.
</P>
<P>
   Initially viewed as a design exercise, the utility truck now
seems likely to be built, since it would cost little to produce. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LATTER-DAY `Z' CAR To come up with an image-lifting car for the
future, Nissan designers turned to the past, producing an updated
concept version of the Datsun 240Z of 1970 that meets modern safety
standards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
