r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     08-07 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT E-MAIL OR EEK-MAIL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I read about the latest so-called e-mail virus
scare. This sounds like just another hoax to me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Skeptical
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SKEP: Maybe. You really want to take that chance?
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks back, some four-eyes with a lot of free time on his
hands discovered a potential problem with Outlook Express 4.x,
Outlook 98 and Netscape Communicator mail. Other mail programs may
be at risk, too. File attachments with very long names _ no, I'm
not going to tell you how long because my mailbox has already been
jam-packed with malicious missives _ can crash the e-mail programs.
</P>
<P>
   Skilled hackers could conceivably execute nasty little programs
as the program halts. Although no reports of dirty tricks have
surfaced, now that the story has made the news, you can bet some
pinheaded hacker wannabe is out there losing sleep trying to invent
a way to wipe out your hard drive before you know what hit you.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has a partial fix at www.microsoft.com/ie/security,
but it's still grinding away on a complete patch. Netscape is
supposed to be hard at work, too. Check in frequently at
home.netscape.com/products/security/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just love hackers? This is starting to cut into
efforts to catalog every Carmen Electra-worship page on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I normally leave my computer running in order
to receive faxes. We have a lot of power failures in my area, which
has not been a problem as I am running Win95-early on a 486. The
computer restarts without all the Scandisk gobbledygook and
everything works fine. I have just ordered a new 400-mHz screamer
that will come with Win98, and I am sure I'll get the gobbledygook.
Is there a way to get Windows 98 to restart on an unscheduled
shutdown without Scandisk?
</P>
<P>
   _ Stormy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR STORMY: ``You buy them books,'' a trusted mentor once told
me, ``and they eat the covers.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bill and his pals didn't put Scandisk in there to irritate
you. They were trying to save people from themselves. Every time
you close down Windows without going through the shutdown routine,
you run the risk of corrupting your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Stormy, I realize you're not doing the bad shutdowns
intentionally, but please think about getting an uninterruptable
power supply. Those power failures aren't doing your hardware any
good.
</P>
<P>
   The early versions of Win95 didn't run Scandisk to repair disk
problems after an improper shutdown. Why? Beats me, but most likely
because the guys at Microsoft underestimated how few people would
or could follow directions.
</P>
<P>
   New versions of Win95 and 98 automatically run Scandisk if a bad
shutdown is detected. Win 95 makes you click to get things started,
but 98 runs it on its own. I really hesitate to tell you the next
part, because this is one time when I'd prefer that you ignore me
even more than usual. You can change Scandisk's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   You should know that there's the very real potential of mucking
things up, but here goes: Use a text editor such as Notepad to open
Msdos.sys, which is in your root directory. Look for a line that
reads ``Autoscan(Equals)1.'' Change the 1 to 0 if you want to turn
off Scandisk. Change it to a 2 if you want Scandisk to run without
any intervention. Please don't touch anything else. You don't know
what you're doing, and you'll wind up blaming me.
</P>
<P>
   And if you turn Scandisk off, don't come crying to me when you
start getting ``illegal operation'' error messages out the wazoo. I
warned you.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
