<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM'S PERFORMANCE EXPLAINS LACK OF TESTIMONY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we know why David Graham didn't testify last month in his
murder trial: Nobody would have believed a word he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's lawyer, Dan Cogdell, was obviously well aware of this.
Shortly after Graham was convicted of murdering 16-year-old
Adrianne Jones, Cogdell told one of Court TV's legal eagles that he
figured Graham would not have been a good witness in his own
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he believed that he could be a better witness for
Graham than Graham could be. Cogdell said that his client simply
wasn't articulate enough or personable enough to persuade the
jurors of his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was that the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Graham turned up in an exclusive interview on NBC's ``Dateline''
the other night, serving up the story that his lawyer told in
court: Diane Zamora murdered Jones _ and Graham had nothing to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not there,'' Graham told interviewer Stone Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   So if he wasn't there, Phillips wanted to know, where the heck
was he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whereabouts that night?'' Phillips asked.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's reply was precisely what most people who followed his
trial would have expected:
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh ...''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Graham looked at Cogdell, who was seated nearby,
and Phillips' recorded narration informed viewers that the lawyer
had advised his client not to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   Good advice, seeing as how any alibi Graham might have offered
would have been preposterous. Graham couldn't tell Phillips where
he was when Jones was killed because he was right there with her,
firing two bullets into her head.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts criticized Cogdell's decision to keep Graham
off the stand, but the 20-year-old killer's ``Dateline'' appearance
made it clear that Cogdell's reasoning was sound.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine Graham on the witness stand, trying to convince
jurors that he was somewhere else when Jones was murdered and the
prosecutor asks:
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were you?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham replies:
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh ...''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the jury convicted him in less than 10 hours. If
they'd heard him say, ``Uh,'' when asked for his alibi, they might
have convicted him in less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham's problem on ``Dateline'' _ and his likely problem if
he had testified in court _ went far beyond his unconvincing
version of the murder. Graham simply came off as a smirking,
arrogant jerk.
</P>
<P>
   He came off, in fact, as exactly the sort of person who could
murder an innocent girl and leave her battered and bloodied body
along a deserted road, who could stand by silent and unrepentant
when an innocent man was mistakenly arrested for this heinous
crime.
</P>
<P>
   He came off as exactly the sort of coldblooded sociopath who
could commit murder for no reason except to please his psychotic
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, Graham's tale of noninvolvement failed to account for
the detailed confession that he provided to police when they
finally connected him to Jones' murder. Graham told Phillips that
the confession was fiction, that his slavish devotion to Zamora led
him to implicate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Which was the same story _ from the other side of the looking
glass _ that Zamora told when she testified in her murder trial.
Zamora said that Graham alone was responsible for the killing _
although she did admit to being on the scene when the murder took
place _ and claimed that she confessed to participating in the
crime because she loved Graham and wanted to share the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora's yarn was unbelievable, and the jury promptly convicted
her of capital murder. But she at least tried to show some emotion.
When Graham told his story on NBC, he could have been talking about
some teen-age prank that got him suspended from high school.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham wasn't talking about a prank. He was talking about a
vicious, senseless murder for which he and Zamora are now serving
life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Graham in action, it's easy to understand why
Cogdell didn't let him testify. And hard to understand why
prosecutors didn't ask for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
