A3364 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HENRYFOOL-TEX     08-07 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HENRYFOOL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD, UNPREDICTABLE POETRY FROM A `FOOL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hal Hartley became an indie-film hero not so much by breaking
the rules of filmmaking, but by ignoring them. In his early films,
Hartley's characters often spoke in a clipped, deadpan style, as if
they were rehearsing for a postmodern ``Dragnet.'' Hartley
preferred simple compositions, sometimes with such static camera
work that you could hang the scenes on a wall. So when people start
calling his latest film, ``Henry Fool,'' his most ``accessible,''
it's a relative term. It may be the most mainstream thing Hartley
has ever done, but nobody's going to confuse it with ``Dr.
Dolittle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Fool'' could just as easily have been called ``Simon
Grim,'' so much does it focus on Simon (James Urbaniak), a tall,
sad-sack garbage man who seems to weigh less than his coveralls.
Simon looks like a wounded sparrow, and he greets the world with
similar levels of vulnerability and surprise. Like many of
Hartley's characters, Simon doesn't have a happy home life; sister
Fay (indie-film princess Parker Posey) brings home a different
stranger every night, and Mom (Maria Porter, like Posey a Hartley
regular) is so depressed that she wanders the house in her bathrobe
and listens in on Fay's latest conquests.
</P>
<P>
   Things change for the Grims when Henry (Thomas Jay Ryan) rents
out their basement room; he's a Hartley standard, the Man With a
Past. Henry puts on a show of cynical, world-weary intelligence,
looking as if he can barely be bothered to shampoo or shave. He's
not prepared for what he reads, though, when he hands Simon a pen
and a notebook and tells him to write down his thoughts. Simon
turns out to be a poetic prodigy, and the epic work he produces has
a profound _ and not always positive _ effect on everyone who reads
it.
</P>
<P>
   You can never quite tell where a Hartley film is going; even
``Flirt,'' which used the same dialogue to tell three separate
stories, was wildly unpredictable. For Hartley, though, the
destination isn't as important as the journey. He's a rare
filmmaker who's truly in love with the rhythms and idiosyncrasies
of the English language, and with ``Henry,'' he almost wallows in
them. He uses Henry and Simon's unlikely friendship to address the
nature of art and criticism. When Henry complains that a prophet
isn't honored in his own country or that what's considered junk now
might be a masterpiece 10 years later, you know he's airing
grievances about the response to his own films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry'' is one of Hartley's longest films, and it unravels in
its last half-hour, which feels so tacked-on that it's almost as
though Hartley decided to make another movie. This is the most
conventional material he's ever presented; one shot even vaguely
echoes ``Casablanca's'' airport scene. It doesn't help that it
resolves an unnecessary subplot that features Kevin Corrigan, maybe
the most irritating actor in indie movies.
</P>
<P>
   That ``accessible'' tag shouldn't put you off; Hartley's films
are out of the mainstream, but they're never impenetrably bizarre.
For Tarrant movie buffs, ``Henry'' may prove to be his most
accessible film in another way; it's the first Hartley film to get
a Tarrant play date in at least five years. They'll still have to
wait at least a week for its UA Hulen date; for now, impatient
Hartley fans will have to make the trek to Dallas' Inwood theater.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Henry Fool''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Hal Hartley
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Thomas Jay Ryan, James Urbaniak, Parker Posey
</P>
<P>
   Length: 137 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, violence, sexual situations
(including a nearly NC-17 scene) and a couple of gross moments
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
