<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE STORY ABOUT CUSTOMER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This isn't a column about my hard drive going belly-up. It's a
column how things should work after something quits working.
</P>
<P>
   And its moral doesn't apply to just the computer industry, but
to all businesses centered on customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The week before last, the hard drive in a computer I use
basically for software testing informed me it had a problem. A
diagnostic program indicated part of the storage area had gone bad.
The cause could have been anything, including the ever-possible
explanation: These things happen.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Maxtor drive. It's several years old, and although it
had a massive storage capacity when I bought it, it is small by
today's Godzillabyte standards.
</P>
<P>
   I called Maxtor, this time as a customer with a problem, not a
computer writer. It may be an old model, they said, but it was
still in warranty. The technician said I'd have to do a low-level
format on it, which would correct all but the most serious of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   If it didn't, the formatting program would send back an error
code. If that happened, write it down and call back. I went home;
did a low-level format; wrote down the number; called back that
evening.
</P>
<P>
   A different technician, able to track my problem because the
first technician had entered the information into the computer
system, gave me an authorization number for a replacement and
handed me off to customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The customer-service rep asked for the serial number of the
drive. After confirming it was still in warranty, she said I could
send it back and they would send a replacement by return mail. Or,
they would send out a new drive, and I could send the old one back
within 30 days in the same shipping container. Otherwise, my credit
card would be billed for failing to return the defective drive.
</P>
<P>
   Could I speed things up by paying for overnight freight? No
problem, that's $10. The drive arrived the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Maxtor no longer makes a 1.6 gigabyte drive (I told you it was
rather long in the tooth). The smallest replacement, which they had
sent, was 2.1 gigabytes. For an additional charge, I could have
upgraded to a larger drive, but for the chores this computer does,
a small drive is more than adequate.
</P>
<P>
   At no time was I ever asked for a receipt, or told that I hadn't
sent in my warranty card, or quibbled with about whether the drive
could have had a virus, or told I would have to send the drive back
in the original packaging to obtain an exchange. (Yes, computer
companies sometimes make customers jump through these hoops.)
</P>
<P>
   They did not make excuses. They did not try to pass me around in
an endless telephone circle. They apologized for the failure and
for any inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   From the time I discovered I had a problem until the time the
replacement was installed: Less than 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another figure that's just as impressive. Time spent
on hold during three telephone calls waiting for a technician or
customer representative: Less than five minutes. (While on hold, a
recording lists various tips for trouble-shooting problems or ticks
off information about the drive and computer system the technician
might need to know to help with the problem.)
</P>
<P>
   I was not surprised. More than five years ago, I also had a
Maxtor drive that developed a problem. The outcome was the same
then as it was last week: quick, no hassle, friendly help.
</P>
<P>
   Even since that first replacement go-round, every hard drive
I've ever had in a computer has been a Maxtor. When I was putting
one together from scratch about a year ago, the store listed a
Western Digital as the hard drive going in the machine. ``I want a
Maxtor,'' I said, and told them why. It's not that I don't like
Western Digital or Seagate or any of the other companies. They make
fine products. It's that I've had very good experience with Maxtor.
</P>
<P>
   And even though two of the drives out of the many Maxtors I have
used over the years failed, I did not lose one byte of information
in those failures. (You DO make regular backups of your hard drive,
don't you?)
</P>
<P>
   Lyn, the last Maxtor customer representative I spoke with, said
sometimes people aren't happy when their hard drives fail. ``Some
of them say they'll never buy our product again,'' she said. ``The
fact is, hard drives sometimes fail. But we stand behind our
product and currently have the lowest failure rate in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the president of Lexmark International Inc.
told a group of computer writers that his company's motto was:
Customers for life. He shared with us a letter from a customer who
had an ancient IBM laser printer (Lexmark is a spin-off from that
company), and was unable to find drivers for it to work with
today's operating system. Lexmark's customer representative had
worked with him, finally giving him a partial credit for a new
color ink-jet printer that was faster and had better resolution
than his old laser. The customer was delighted. Not only did he
have laser quality, but he had color capability as well.
</P>
<P>
   He was, said the Lexmark president, ``a customer for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexmark and Maxtor are two computer-industry companies that have
already learned it's much easier to keep customers than it is to
advertise to go out and find new ones. They know that word-of-mouth
is highly effective advertising that can't be bought.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be earned.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have had some not-so-good experiences with
computer-related companies. I, too, have had my share. But every so
often, some of them do things very well.
</P>
<P>
   When they do, be sure and reward them with your loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
