<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-NISSAN-QUEST-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 NISSAN QUEST: GROWTH SPURT FOR A MINI MINI-VAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Fifteen years ago, as millions of baby boomers were
settling down to raise families, Lee A. Iacocca played midwife to
the Chrysler Corp.'s own promising, strapping newborn, driving the
company's first boxy mini-van off the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   It was the right product at the right time, and it virtually
supplanted the station wagon as family transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler still holds 40 percent of the 1.2 million mini-van
market, even as every major manufacturer has crowded in. But the
next wave of competition is sweeping in, with an all-new, bigger
Honda Odyssey arriving in October and redesigned vans from Ford,
Mazda, Nissan and Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the Nissan Quest and Mercury Villager are getting
their first substantial makeover since they were introduced as 1993
models. As before, they are nearly identical, and they are still
produced through a joint venture of Nissan and Ford: the engine,
transaxle and body stampings come from Nissan's nonunion operations
in Smyrna, Tenn., and the vans are assembled by United Automobile
Workers members at a Ford plant in Avon Lake, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The Quest and Villager are on the small side among mini-vans,
with a wheelbase 7 inches shorter than the Dodge Grand Caravan's.
They are thus more nimble and carlike than most of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the mini-vans had received only minor tweaks and
fell behind in competitive features like a fourth door. The
redesigned Quest keeps its old body structure and retains its
relatively agile handling, but it gains another door and adds
horsepower and cargo capacity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the Quest's wheelbase is unchanged at 112.2 inches,
but the body has been stretched nearly 5 inches and it is about an
inch wider. The interior capacity has grown by about 10 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Styled at Nissan's American design center in California, the
Quest has a fresher appearance. Every body panel is new, but the
most noticeable change is up front, where a prominent oval grille
protrudes like a snout. Other than that, the appearance is
mainstream, a plus with mini-van buyers who seem to like blending
into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For owners, functionality is all-important, and a second sliding
door, this one on the driver's side, is now seen as essential. The
extra door is standard on the Quest, and it comes in handy for
unloading children away from traffic or loading shopping bags
without having to walk to the passenger side.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important as the extra inside space are features that
allow more versatility. The second-row seats can be easily removed.
The third row slides forward or back on rails. You could, for
instance, remove the second-row seats and slide the third row all
the way back to provide maximum room for long-legged teen-agers or
to carry adults limousine-style.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the third row, Nissan has added a cargo shelf that can be
set at one of two levels, or removed entirely. The shelf is useful
for lining up two rows of grocery bags, for instance _ one on the
floor and one on the shelf above _ and nothing gets crushed. Or,
you could load a stroller, golf bags or luggage underneath, and
line the shelf with shopping bags.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extra space and added versatility, cargo capacity
still falls far short of larger vans'. With my two children
strapped in, I drove a '98 Quest to a rented cottage in northern
Michigan, loaded with paraphernalia for a week's vacation. Space
was tight, so I couldn't imagine how the van would accommodate a
larger family on such an outing, unless they pack more
economically.
</P>
<P>
   On my return, I picked up the '99 model. Although it is not
vastly larger inside, space is used better and storage compartments
are more plentiful. Other ergonomic features have been improved.
The audio controls, for instance, are now situated above the
heating and air-conditioning controls that are used less often.
</P>
<P>
   My children most appreciated the improvements in the cup
holders. In front, they pull out of the center dash and are
sturdier than the wobbly gadgets that folded down from the side of
the seat in the '98 model.
</P>
<P>
   Options include an integrated transmitter that opens garage
doors and security gates, and driver's seats that memorize
preferred positions. New is a sportier SE model with 16-inch wheels
and a stiffer suspension. The Quest also comes with a standard
security system, less forceful dual air bags and four-wheel
anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Quest's most significant improvement is under the hood,
where a 3.3-liter V6 producing 170 horsepower has replaced a
3-liter V6 with 151 horsepower. While a difference of 19 horsepower
may not sound like much, back-to-back comparisons of the old and
new versions showed the '99 to be much livelier.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Quest, albeit loaded with gear, had chugged up hills
out of breath. Even empty, it gave me pause when passing. In
contrast, the '99 stepped smartly away from traffic lights and
confidently passed other vehicles on two-lane roads.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have not been announced, but they are expected to remain
in the range of the current model, from $23,589 to $29,087. The
Villager is priced about the same, and differs mainly in its front
styling, available colors and optional trim.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A van for families that know when to stop
packing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
