<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3382 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     08-07 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY'S LAW IS ONLY THE BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday Aug 10)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people think that the world is controlled by Murphy's laws
(Nothing is as easy as it looks. Anything that can go wrong will go
wrong. Left to themselves, things tend to go from bad to worse.
Etc., etc.), but the truth of the matter is that Murphy told only
part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Conrad Schneiker, Ed Logg, Gregg Townshend and a book
by Arthur Bloch called ``The Complete Murphy's Laws,'' I now know
that there are a lot of corollaries, axioms, maxims and dictums
that fill in the gaps in ol' Murphy's cynical _ if all too accurate
_ laws.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   Acheson's Rule of the Bureaucracy: A memorandum is written not
to inform the reader but to protect the writer.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's Byroad: When you are over the hill, you pick up speed.
</P>
<P>
   Berra's Law: You can observe a lot just by watching.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard's Newspaper Obituary Law: If you want your name
spelled wrong, die.
</P>
<P>
   Boozer's Revision: A bird in the hand is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Borstelman's Rule: If everything seems to be coming your way,
you're probably in the wrong lane.
</P>
<P>
   Calkin's Law of Menu Language: The number of adjectives and
verbs that are added to the description of a menu item is in
inverse proportion to the quality of the resulting dish.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon's Cogent Comment: The leak in the roof is never in the
same location as the drip.
</P>
<P>
   Checkbook Balancer's Law: In matters of dispute, the bank's
balance is always smaller than yours.
</P>
<P>
   First Maxim of Computers: To err is human, but to really screw
things up requires a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's Rule: There are three ways to get something done: Do it
yourself, hire someone, or forbid your kids from doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Deitz' Law of Ego: The fury engendered by the misspelling of a
name in a column is in direct ratio to the obscurity of the
mentionee.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's Law: Anything worth doing is worth doing for money.
</P>
<P>
   Finagle's Fourth Law: Once a job is fouled up, anything done to
improve it only makes it worse.
</P>
<P>
   Getty's Reminder: The meek shall inherit the earth, but NOT its
mineral rights.
</P>
<P>
   Glatum's Law of Materialistic Acquisitiveness: The perceived
usefulness of an article is inversely proportional to its actual
usefulness once its bought and paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Gumperson's Law: The probability of anything happening is in
inverse ratio to its desirability.
</P>
<P>
   Gumperson's Corollaries:
</P>
<P>
   1) After a salary raise, you will have less money at the end of
the month than you had before.
</P>
<P>
   2) Children have more energy after a hard day of play than they
do after a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   3) The person who buys the most raffle tickets has the least
chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman's Automotive Law: Nothing minor ever happens to a car on
a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Herblock's Law: If it's good, they'll stop making it.
</P>
<P>
   Issawi's Law of Committo-Dynamics: The less you enjoy serving on
committees, the more likely you are to be pressed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Second Law: If, during the course of several months,
only three worthwhile social events take place, they will all fall
on the same evening.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland's Law: The usefulness of any meeting is in inverse
proportion to the attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Langin's Law: If things were left to chance, they'd be better.
</P>
<P>
   Occam's Electric Razor: The most difficult light bulb to replace
burns out first and most frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo's Postulate: Anything good is either illegal, immoral or
fattening.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll's Law of Media Accuracy: Everything you read in the
newspapers is absolutely true except for that rare story of which
you happen to have first-hand knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
