<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SCREENKISS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCREEN KISS': JUST YOUR AVERAGE SMOOCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The arrival of ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' means that
someone out there is finally starting to listen.
</P>
<P>
   For years, critics whined about gay independent cinema's
infatuation with self-important AIDS melodramas and in-your-face
sexuality. For years, we griped about mainstream Hollywood's
preference for mincing effeminates or gay guys who just need to
meet the right girl.
</P>
<P>
   Can't we just have a gay romantic comedy where the characters
are just plain, excuse the word, normal? Is that too much to ask?
Pictures like ``I Think I Do, Kiss Me, Guido'' and now ``Screen
Kiss'' reply confidently, ``No, it isn't.'' In fact, the indies and
the majors alike are discovering that they attract a far bigger
audience with realistic gay characters than they ever did with
low-budget trash like ``The Living End'' or big-budget stereotyping
trash like ``Mannequin.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Tommy O'Haver's ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss''
follows the romantic shenanigans of Billy Collier (Sean P. Hayes),
a Polaroid photographer with a habit for falling for the wrong guy:
His part-ime lover is involved with someone else. He has reduced
the one guy who really loves him (Richard Ganoung) to ``just
friends'' status. When he finally meets his Prince Charming at a
party, he's not even sure if the guy's gay.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned Prince is Gabriel (Brad Rowe), a handsome
model type whom Billy persuades to pose in his new series of photos
depicting famous Hollywood screen kisses. So begins Billy's
emotional ``Is-he-or-isn't-he?'' roller coaster ride that reaches
its crest when Gabriel gets a little too tipsy one night and asks
to sleep over.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's most brilliant scene, Gabriel strips his shirt off
and curls up next to the wide-eyed Billy, who spends the next
excruciating five minutes trying to find a way to make his hand
casually fall against Gabriel's back. O'Haver never cuts _ the
scene is one long, unbearable shot that should make any viewer
squirm. As Ganoung says in the press notes, ``I don't care if
you're gay, straight, whatever. We have all been in that bed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's moments like that that elevate ``Screen Kiss'' from
mediocrity, because despite its ground-breaking averageness, it's
almost a little too average to be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Give it points for not ending the way you might think. No fair
telling whether Billy will get the guy. Suffice it to say that no
one goes home empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes and Rowe have a believable chemistry. Ganoung (remembered,
but almost unrecognizable, from his starring role in ``Parting
Glances)'' is just right as Billy's concerned but selfish friend.
And Paul Bartel puts in a hilarious cameo as a lascivious big shot
who wants to make Gabriel a star.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tommy O'Haver
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Sean P. Hayes, Brad Rowe, Paul Bartel
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity, brief nudity, adult situations and subject
matter
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
