<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-FIDELITY-ART-     08-07 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-FIDELITY-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MAGELLAN AND CONTRAFUND, THINNER PORTFOLIOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By NOELLE KNOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a lesson from the School of Focused Investing, two of
Fidelity Investments' three biggest funds have drastically pared
the number of companies in their portfolios over the last six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stansky, who runs the $74.6 billion Magellan fund,
reduced the number of stocks in its portfolio to 438 as of June 30
from 523 last year. William Danoff, who steers the $35.4 billion
Contrafund, cut back his portfolio even more over that period, to
336 from 654.
</P>
<P>
   The two also increased moderately the percentage of their funds'
assets in their top 10 holdings. Magellan lifted that percentage to
17.8, from 15.7. Contrafund raised its share to 20.4 percent, from
13.7.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally or not, both Magellan and Contrafund are beating
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index so far this year, a feat
managed by just 14.9 percent of United States diversified equity
funds. Through July 31, Magellan and Contrafund returned 17.2
percent and 17.7 percent, respectively, compared with 16.5 percent
for the S&AMP;P 500, according to Morningstar Inc., the financial
publisher in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The average large blend fund, which invests in
large-capitalization stocks with both growth and value
characteristics, returned just 12.9 percent, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing this market fairly wisely,'' said Jim Lowell,
editor of the Fidelity Investor newsletter. The new tactics, he
said, are more ``saleable and defensible'' to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Danoff ``wanted to make larger commitments to stocks he likes,''
said Anne Crowley, a spokeswoman for Fidelity. ``He's been
concentrating the fund on his very best ideas.'' Neither Stanksy
nor Danoff was available for comment, Ms. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Danoff, however, has changed his mind on some big positions.
Among his top 10 stocks, Schlumberger, Alcatel Alsthom, U.S.
Bancorp and AT&AMP;T have fallen off the list; they have been replaced
by Gillette, American Express, America Online and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Contrafund, which closed to new investors in April, still posts
an aggressive 144 percent turnover rate, down from 165 percent last
year. Many investors frown on frequent stock trading within a fund
because it often produces higher taxable capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan, under Stansky, holds far fewer stocks than it did
under some of his predecessors, especially Peter Lynch, who was
known for buying small positions in many small companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Lynch would have 1,100 stocks in the portfolio at times,
and that was when it was a $2 billion to $3 billion fund,'' said
Eric Kobren, executive editor of Fidelity Insight, an investment
newsletter published in Boston. ``He was very quick to put a lot of
things on the farm team, which are stocks they want to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Magellan was closed to new investors last September. Among the
fund's top 10 stocks, Philip Morris, Cendant and Fannie Mae have
fallenl off the list, replaced by Lucent Technologies, Cisco
Systems and American International Group. The fund's turnover has
increased to 34 percent from 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The second-largest Fidelity fund, Growth and Income, has not
joined the stock-shedding party. Under its manager, Steven Kaye,
the $45.3 billion fund already had far fewer stocks in its
portfolio, compared with its siblings'. As of June 30, it held 246
stocks, one fewer than it did at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Growth and Income has returned 15.3 percent through July 31,
behind the S&AMP;P 500 but ahead of the average large-cap blend fund,
according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's turnover has tapered off to 30 percent from 38
percent. Its top three holdings as of June 30 _ General Electric,
Merck and American Express _ were all in the fund's top 10 at
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Magellan fell 3.5 percent, while both Contrafund and
Growth and Income fell 3.3 percent. The average United States
diversified stock fund fell 3.2 percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
