<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-INTRO-NYT &LR;      08-07 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INTRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEBATE ABOUT TEACHING THE HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, this brief introduction may be used to accompany
BC-HOLOCAUST-KATZ and BC-HOLOCAUST-WISSE.)  
(gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How should the Holocaust be taught? Today, a specialized field
of study has grown up around it. There are undergraduate and
graduate courses, academic centers and conferences, fellowships and
endowed chairs. There are libraries devoted to it, along with
museums, films, docudramas, Internet sites and novels.
</P>
<P>
   While some thinkers believe the Holocaust is getting the
attention it deserves, others are uneasy about focusing scholarship
on an attempt to wipe out the Jewish people instead of on the whole
of Jewish history.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times asked Ruth R. Wisse, a professor of Yiddish
literature and comparative literature at Harvard University, and
Steven T. Katz, director of the Center for Judaic Studies at Boston
University and the author of ``The Holocaust in Historical
Context,'' to lay out their views on the purpose and meaning of
teaching the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Katz argues that the Holocaust is a singular event, perhaps the
most significant occurrence in 2,000 years of Jewish history, and
that it therefore deserves to be treated as such.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wisse counters that turning the Holocaust into the defining
event in Jewish history is a terrible mistake, that it distorts the
rich and long history of the Jews, allows Hitler to define the Jews
and obscures the political nature of what happened in Nazi Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-WISSE-NYT &LR;      08-07 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-WISSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING JEWS AS VICTIMS SAID TO INVITE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BC-HOLOCAUST-KATZ and BC-HOLOCAUST-INTRO)  
(js) 
 By RUTH WISSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The destruction of the Jews of Europe was all but ignored when
it was happening. The impulse to document it now and to fix it in
memory is quite natural, commendable and necessary. But insuring
that this genocide will not be forgotten is not the same as
teaching Judaism or making the world a safer place. Although some
well-intentioned folk evidently believe that advertising the
victimization of the Jews will discourage aggression against them,
they might as well believe that dying is good for your health.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine an American child who knows nothing about the Jews being
introduced to them first as the objects of genocide! Of the Hebrew
Bible he knows nothing. Nothing of the Jews' reception of the Law
at Sinai, and their self-disciplined attempt to interpret and
maintain it through thousands of years. Nothing of the Jewish
yearning for God, the Ten Commandments, the Sabbath, the liturgy.
No information about Jewish history, about Jewish sovereignty in
the land of Israel or the concept of exile outside it; about Jewish
migrations and the development of multiple Jewish languages. No
awareness of Jewish philosophy and literature, folkways and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The child is expected to learn tolerance from the Holocaust, but
tolerance of what? How will he be prepared for the quirky tribe of
real Jews when he has discovered the Jews as perfect victims in
their death throes and martyrdom? The more he thinks of Jews as
victims of the Nazis, the less he will be able to appreciate the
stiff-necked, highly particularistic people who observe different
rituals and rites of passage, and who want to remain as distinctive
as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Mass murder is neither the defining moment of Judaism nor the
sound basis of a moral education. A Jewish college sophomore who
was educated in Hebrew school on a steady diet of
``Holocaustology'' said to me recently, ``The Jews of Europe may
have been killed for what they believed in, but I was never told
what they believed in.'' She knows she was cheated of a proper
education. If the slaughter of the European Jews dare not be
forgotten, neither should it overshadow the way of life it tried to
destroy. Jewish education and American education ought to have much
more to teach about the creative energy of the Jews than the
destructive energy of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characteristics of Nazism was its reduction of the
Jews to an abstraction of evil, a symbol of corruption. Teaching
the Holocaust separately from teaching about the Jews as a whole
runs the risk of abstracting them and diminishing them to the same
degree. The Jews of Europe did not seek to be martyrs, and were in
the process of emancipating themselves politically so that they
should be better able to determine their own destiny. Treating the
Holocaust as a secular crucifixion cuts off Jewish tragedy from the
historical continuum, and distorts the rich reality of Jewish
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Jews of Israel, in particular, are learning how to
re-fashion their own sovereignty after too many centuries of being
imagined as dead. Homage to the murdered Jews is morally
reprehensible when it takes precedence over, or becomes a
substitute for, education about the flourishing Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a second danger in focusing on the Jews as victims
of the Holocaust: it obscures the nature of aggression committed
against them. The murder of the European Jews was a political act,
a war within a war. The Germans were able to win their war against
the Jews even as they failed to impose the Thousand-Year Reich in
Europe. This was because in his war against the Jews, Hitler had
the support of most of the populations he overran. By the time he
conceived his Final Solution, anti-Semitism had become the most
powerful ideology on the Continent, a force that united the
conquerors with many of the conquered.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism, which is the organization of politics around
antipathy to the Jews, battened on the longstanding image of the
Jews as victims, although the Jews had done everything possible to
resist this fate. Following an earlier catastrophe _ the Romans'
destruction of the Second Temple in Jerusalem in A.D. 70 _ the Jews
postponed indefinitely the recovery of their national sovereignty,
and determined to uphold their religious civilization among other
peoples. They learned to survive without land, without autonomous
political authority and without independent means of self-defense,
attempting to compensate for their political weakness through
economic and intellectual strength.
</P>
<P>
   Although this strategy of accommodation yielded certain
advantages, the temptation it offered the surrounding peoples
usually proved even greater. Jews often accumulated visible status
and wealth. But prosperity without the ability to protect their
assets made them the ideal target of rulers and mobs. Demagogues
inflated their power by attacking this small people with the very
large image. The reputation of the Jews as a no-fail enemy grew
with each successive expulsion, massacre and pogrom.
</P>
<P>
   Those who exploit the Holocaust as a moral fable make no
connection between it and the political predicament of the Jews:
being perceived as victims and targets. In fact, Hitler's
victorious war against the Jews inspires as much imitation as
regret.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Jews have reclaimed their sovereignty since their
destruction in Europe, and in Israel they now command their own
self-defense. But as long as the demographic and political
imbalance between the Jews and those who wish to dislodge them
remains as lop-sided as it was in Europe, the precedent of the
Holocaust still tempts the aggressor. Far from regarding the German
genocide as morally abhorrent, Arab anti-Semitism recycles the same
accusations, and keeps its eye on the same prize.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever had trouble sympathizing with the dead Jews. But
the protection of the living _ and especially protection for the
Jewish political community that remains under siege _ requires the
opposite set of moral reflexes. Of course, it is imperative to
document, to study, to analyze and to commemorate the greatest
moral failure in Western civilization, which coincides with the
tragedy of the Jewish people. Preventing its recurrence requires
something else, and something more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-KATZ-NYT &LR;      08-07 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-KATZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS KILLINGS SEEN AS A DEFINING EVENT OF THE MODERN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BC-HOLOCAUST-WISSE and BC-HOLOCAUST-INTRO)  
(gm) 
 By STEVEN T. KATZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VORONOVO, Russia _ This city is 30 miles from Moscow, at what
was once Trofim Lysenko's Agrarian Research Center. I am here under
auspices of the Holocaust Educational Foundation to lecture for two
weeks on the Holocaust to 23 professors, Jewish and non-Jewish,
from all over the former Soviet Union. They have come from as close
as Moscow and as far away as Birobidzhan, the ``Jewish republic''
created by Stalin in the 1930s in the Far East of Russia near
Manchuria. Each of the students has agreed, as the basis of their
participation in the seminar, to introduce or to continue teaching
a course on the Holocaust at their universities.
</P>
<P>
   I begin with this geographical backdrop because from here it
seems clear that those who argue that the Holocaust should not be
taught as a specialized field of study in university programs are
out of touch with the feelings of scholars, Jewish and non-Jewish,
around the world. Still, more important, they misunderstand the
Holocaust's significance not only for Jewish history but also for
the modern era in its totality.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust, along with the creation of the State of Israel,
is the defining event of Jewish history in the 20th century, if not
of the last two millenniums of Jewish existence. It is also one of
the defining events of the 20th century more generally, hence the
massive effort to relativize and de-Judaize it.
</P>
<P>
   For here the distinctive features of modernity _ nationalism,
the decline of religious authority, an innovative political
ideology, bureaucracy, technology, the secular state, racial
theory, and intentional state-sponsored genocide _ come together in
a unique way.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, given the inversion of all moral and metaphysical
values that Nazism represented, all the classical Western doctrines
of ethics, philosophy and theology are challenged to their core. As
such, anyone concerned to understand the modern world _ its
unprecedented capacity for altering the human condition, and its
immense potential for good and evil _ must confront, with all
seriousness, the events that together make up the whole of we call
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the teaching of the Holocaust has to be done
correctly. This means properly placing the event within the
narrative of European history and the dismal tradition of Christian
anti-Semitism, as well as within the contours of modern Jewish
history. In the latter context it means, in particular,
understanding the complex and difficult issue of Jewish
emancipation, which, in turn, gave rise to ``the Jewish Question''
(die Judenfrage) _ what to do about the Jews now that they had been
liberated from their medieval status.
</P>
<P>
   For the Holocaust, as Hitler described it, was intended as ``
die Endlosung der Judenfrage'' (``the Final Solution to the Jewish
Question.'' According to this logic, all of the earlier attempted
solutions that had dominated the 19th and early 20th centuries _
efforts aimed at religious conversion, assimilation, socialism and
religious reform _ were considered manifest failures. And they
failed because they were not rooted in the racial theory that alone
properly diagnoses the nature of the ``Jewish Problem'': that the
Jews, each and every Jewish man, woman and child, are literally
less than human. They, the Jews, incarnate negative principles of
being that necessarily cause them to be aggressive, destructive,
parasitical, ``Untermenschen'' (subhumans) in the grand scheme of
history. In consequence, the Aryan people must, in putative
``self-defense,'' act to protect themselves and their civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The whole of World War II is, in a fundamental sense, the
application and playing out of this racial-metaphysical theory.
This is especially true vis-a-vis the brutal war on the eastern
front, and the continent-wide unrestrained effort to gather up all
Jews from all quarters of Europe and to deport them to Auschwitz
and Treblinka, Sobibor and Chelmno, to be immolated, their ashes
used to fill swamps and to fertilize the Polish landscape.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, emotionally, psychologically, intellectually
and academically difficult material to decipher and comprehend.
How, for example, could the ``ordinary men'' who comprised the
Einsatzgruppen (the Nazi killing squads created as an integral part
of the Nazi war machine in Russia) _ who were not preselected
sadists, not professional killers, not volunteers, and who were led
by individuals possessing Ph.D.'s and other advanced degrees _ kill
1.5 million to 1.8 million men, women and children ``face to
face''?
</P>
<P>
   To ask such an elemental question, to confront such far-reaching
matters in all their complexity, should not lead to denying the
Holocaust a special place in the university curriculum, but rather
requires that it receive one. Given its monumental significance,
the Holocaust must be front and center, taught by experts to
students of all ethnic and religious backgrounds whose world has
been, in large measure, created by it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to teach this pivotal subject without either a
sufficient knowledge of its larger historical circumstance,
including the makeup and character of the Nazi state, or of Jewish
history is to tell less than the whole story and thus, by design or
ignorance, to distort it. One must know, among other things, the
remarkable character of that Jewish civilization that was
destroyed, the nature of the cultural, social, political and
religious life that was carried on in the Polish and Lithuanian
ghettos, the details of the impossible and unprecedented position
of the Jewish Councils, and the story of Jewish resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the shared methodological and pedagogical
circumstance of any academic subject taught in the university or
elsewhere. That is, proper academic (or other) instruction always
requires the necessary expertise. In this particular case, this
entails mastery of Jewish and non-Jewish historical and other
materials. Certainly this makes large scholarly demands on those
who would teach the subject, and assuredly much of the teaching of
the Holocaust falls short of this standard.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean that Holocaust studies shouldn't exist as
an independent field of study. Indeed, it is all the more reason to
support the creation of first-rate programs that will train
competent scholars and that will help devise appropriate
pedagogical models for conveying the lessons and legacies of this
most overwhelming and consequential event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
