<HEADLINE>
GIVE YOUNG DRIVERS TIME TO LEARN THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Maine, now Massachusetts has adopted restrictions for
young, newly-licensed drivers. Maine requires adult copilots for a
time and the Bay State is putting a curfew into effect. The
legislation recognizes that we license young _ entirely too young,
perhaps _ and that experience informs judgment. The neophyte driver
needs some apprentice time.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes into account that we license youngsters when they
are going through extreme changes, when the judgment is clouded by
raging hormones. While the respective legislatures should be
applauded for the good intentions and the institution of
(itals)something(unitals) to reduce teenage carnage on the
highways, they should also get dope slaps for not attacking the
root of the problem: driver ed. It is not enough merely to curtail
the newly-licensed until a some experience is gained; we've got to
make certain the newly-licensed can actually drive before handing
them the keys.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the problem of teenage auto carnage is more likely
to be found in quality driver education than in enforcement of new
rules. In fact, real driver ed would likely make restrictions
easier for teens to swallow, thus easier to enforce. Of course,
improved education is much more expensive than legislating rules
changes. But Massachusetts and Maine are both boasting budget
surpluses currently _ what better way to spend the money than by
making a quantum leap in the quality and efficacy of driver ed?
</P>
<P>
   The improvement would not be simple; the issue of driver ed is
complicated by the same thing that makes improvement in the
Massachusetts educational structure difficult: the quality of the
teachers. Additionally, there is a small investment in equipment
and probably a large investment in insurance premiums, given the
current litigation-oriented mindset in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of concentrating on parallel parking, driver education
should concentrate on the real world of (itals)driving(unitals).
Young candidates for driving privileges should not just be preached
at to avoid the occasion of sin but given the skills to cope with
the perils of temptation. ``Don't drink'' and ``don't speed'' are
worthwhile admonitions but offer no knowledge of how to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   What should be taught? Classroom work should begin with the
physics of the car _ how it behaves, steering geometry, weight
transfer. The student should be taught how weight transfers in
braking, how that affects the contact with the road, how that
affects the possibility of skids.
</P>
<P>
   The driving exercises should begin with throttle steering
exercises, advance to the skid pad exercises in losing, then
regaining, control of the car. Correcting for a skid is a bit more
complicated than just ``steer in the direction of the skid,'' the
standard short lesson in driver ed _ sans practice, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Exercises should follow to demonstrate what happens in braking,
how to maintain steering control while braking. And there should be
a thorough grounding in antlock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, slalom exercises to demonstrate control, finesse. Then the
motocross exercises, actually driving a closed course. In winter,
the exercises take advantage of snow and ice to teach winter
driving skills. None of this takes place on a public road; all of
this should take place before a youngster is given a learning
permit and allowed behind the wheel in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   So, does the state spend billions building training arenas for
drivers to accomplish this? No, Bunky, the state already has;
virtually every high school in New England already has a skid pad _
they call it a ``parking lot.'' A motocross course or slaloms are
easily assembled with traffic cones.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are automotive technologies out there to help
_ so-called ``skid cars'' that vary traction and induce skids _
safely _ and autos that can simulate loss of reaction time and
skills in an alcohol-impaired driver _ safely and without the
booze.
</P>
<P>
   The result of such a program instills a new respect for the car,
exposes the limitations of the driver, and offers worthy avenues of
practice to sharpen skills. More important, knowledge and skill
reinforce good judgment, erect barriers to hormone poisoning on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   So what makes me an expert on the subject? For 20 years while
writing these weekly offerings, I've been going to schools that
offer just such curricula as I've outlined above. And taking course
_ Skip Barber's advanced driving, lessons here and there with Bob
Bondurant, track time with Jackie Stewart, winter driving schools
with Jean Paul Luc, Audi, and Saab. I remember my son's tales of
driver ed in high school and saw the difference a day with Skip
Barber's instructors made in his driving attitude and his skill.
And I remember being in a class with an instructor of driving
instructors for public schools, an offensive oaf who argued with
Barber's instructors until he had convinced everyone in the room
that he was an arrant ass teaching children to court disaster. Then
he proved it on the skid pad.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are a fact of life in America. We should be doing as much
as possible to prevent them from becoming a fact of death for our
children. It is not enough to tell them what not to do; we must
reinforce postive driving habits and real driving skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
