<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BWM RAGTOP SHINES IN `EXHAUSTIVE STUDY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, August 09, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday is usually devoted solely to deadline duties at the
Globe; last Friday was different. Very different. The deadline
duties had to be dealt with, to be sure, but the bulk of the day
was given over to an exhaustive study of convertibles by the New
England Motor Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   Exhaustive. Comprehensive. A fleet of rag-roofed vehicles had
been amassed for the project, and the vehicles and the NEMPA
Exhaustive Study Committee _ a committee of the whole _ would
assemble at the Globe early Friday morning. For me, the Exhaustive
Study commenced Thursday afternoon when the bright blue BMW Z3 M
Roadster was delivered _ my specimen for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was given over to the regular writing routine and some
of the Friday work; the remaining Friday work would be tackled in
the early morn prior to beginning the Exhaustive Study. This meant
staying in town, in a modest-priced motel close to the office. I
love my job.
</P>
<P>
   Friday dawned gray _ and wet. Pouring rain. Not a great day for
an Exhaustive Study of convertibles. Thursday night I had nosed the
Z3 into a space at the end of the empty cul de sac that serves as a
parking lot. Friday morning, the cul de sac was no longer empty but
full of vehicles filling every marked parking spot and some
unmarked places adapted for parking, serving to make me painfully
aware of a drawback peculiar to convertibles: visibility. Or to be
more specific, lack of visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Z3 top is low, almost claustrophobic, and the backlight
(technobabble for the rear window) is plastic _ no defroster here _
and small. Rain has rendered the plastic opaque; there is no
visibility through the canvas to either rear quarter, and the
outside mirrors are rain-spotted and not much use _ especially the
passenger side in which objects appear farther away than they
actually are. So, it is exit (bumping my head on the low overhead),
reconnoiter, reenter (bumping again _ I just can't bend low enough
to avoid it), creep along in reverse until I forget locations,
repeat all of the above. Finally, I have effected a turn and can
drive out frontwards _ narrowly missing a pedestrian trying to get
across the lot.
</P>
<P>
   I hit the Globe at 7 a.m. plus a few minutes and meet no one I
know _ but then I haven't been to the Globe at this hour in years.
At 9 a.m. with deadlines dutifuly met, the real labor of the day
begins as the convertibles _ Mustangs, BMWs, a Jaguar XK8, Mazda
Miata, Chrysler Sebring, a couple of Mercedes-Benz cars, Acura NSX,
even a Toyota RAV4 with a canvas top, not exactly a convertible but
so what! I offer up my Z3 to another for ``familiarization on the
first leg'' trading for a much roomier 225-horsepower Mustang GT
with glass backlight. The Exhaustive Study Committee rolls out onto
Morrissey Boulevard and sets a course for Maine. At the New
Hampshire border, the committee pauses to swap specimens; I hang
onto the GT. The sky brightens, tops come down; in Maine, the sun
is shining, the GT top comes down.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first NEMPA Ragtop Rumble _ it was supposed to be
Ramble but a typo in the stationery caused a change in title to
avoid more paperwork and expense. It takes us into Ogunquit, along
the coast and a stop for lunch, then a run along the ocean and up
to Wells to the Wells Antique Auto Museum where notes are compared,
tires kicked, and the museum's eclectic collection of old cars,
music-producing machines, and automotive paraphernalia are assessed
(a story for another day _ wonderful place). With the sun long past
its zenith, I reclaim the Z and set out across Maine and home.
Exhausting work, this, but I love this job.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is given to more exhaustive studies of the Z3; Sunday,
I enlist the aid of son of auto writer, and we set out for the
seacoast again _ Orchard Beach, Saco, thence westerly along Route 9
into Kennebunk, back across Maine into Somersworth, N.H., over a
short stretch of 236, and north, more or less, along the country
lanes of the Granite State. Son Chris is driving; I am ...
studying. Exhaustively.
</P>
<P>
   With the ragtop folded, the Z3 offers no visibility problems,
naturally. Well, almost none; the rear-view mirror blocks a big
chunk of windshield and really gets in the way, especially when
making right turns, no matter where the top is.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to roll up the windows, fasten the net windscreen
in place behind the seats and carry on a normal conversation on a
65 m.p.h. interstate. This M version is not only a pretty little
roadster but also a dynamite driving machine. It flies. It is
elastic, too; the Z will accelerate nicely in any gear _ did I
mention it's a five-speed manual? Perhaps I've neglected to
mention, too, the 240-horsepower 3.152-liter I-6 in this mighty
mite, the same engine that powers the M3 performance models.
</P>
<P>
   It is a very comfortable two-seater, this, but it does have some
flaws. Although the gauge cluster on the dash is clear, a set of
meters on the mid-dash console becomes invisible at times due to
reflections. The motor that powers the rag roof is wimpy; one must
unlatch the roof and push it up a foot or so before the motor will
grab it and pull it down. There is a boot to cover it when folded,
and it's not all that bad to attach _ tabs slip under the body, and
two snaps lock it in place. But it almost fills the small trunk;
it's better left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is quick, precise, the Z sticks to the corners like
kittens to couch covers. The shifter is smooth and there is some
resistance to the reverse position _ at least on the test model _
which made fouling up a shift much less likely. The ride is firm,
didn't seem harsh.
</P>
<P>
   The air-conditioning/heater controls are big knobs, easy to use
_ the AC will chill meat even with the top down in the sun. The
radio controls are not as user friendly but not bad _ on/off/volume
knob, large presets, and tuning rockers that are almost big enough
for gloved hands (in case you drive this in winter). There are two
cupholders, but behind your elbows between the seats, hardly
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel mileage wasn't bad; the Z3 delivered 22.6 miles per gallon
during the Exhaustive Study, over a variety of roads covering some
400 miles measured. The bad news is price. The Z3 M Roadster lists
for $42,770 delivered, albeit very well equipped; if I had it, I'd
pay it. Despite its flaws and idiosyncrasies, this little car is a
big bag of fun and a machine of ecstacy on a winding country road.
The kid and I give thumbs up _ that's six thumbs if you include the
guy who swapped the GT. He loved it even in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
