<HEADLINE>
CHOKING OFF THE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 09, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real change doesn't come down from up high. It bubbles up from
below.
</P>
<P>
   The lava theory of political change was ratified yet again with
the passage last week in the US House of a campaign finance reform
package that makes Newt Gingrich swoon, and Trent Lott gag. The two
Sun Belters who run the Congress have had no thornier issue than
the soft-money ban that would choke off the cash flow upon which
the GOP's thin edge in the House, and slightly-thicker edge in the
Senate, is predicated.
</P>
<P>
   Without its traditional edge in money-raising, the GOP would
very likely lose control of both branches of Congress. And it had
been 40 years in the minority wilderness before Gingrich and a
claque of right-wing millionaires wrested the House from a
dispirited and tired Democratic crew in '94.
</P>
<P>
   You can do marvelous things when you own the gavel. Bob Dole
would never have been his party's presidential nominee without the
deals he forged as Senate majority leader. Bill Clinton would not
be facing the Ken-and-Monica show, the Democrats' fund-raising
excesses would not be so visible, there would not have been seven
different independent counsels harassing Clinton cabinet figures,
if the Democrats were still running both branches of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Muttering about Monica knocked US Reps. Chris Shays (R-Conn.)
and Marty Meehan (D-Mass.) off more than one network talk show,
making sexual innuendo more valuable to the TV talk industry than
campaign finance reform. Since the TV industry winds up as the
chief profiteer off the soft money scam, in the form of payment for
TV spots, it's no wonder TV execs are cool to reform.
</P>
<P>
   It's the prerogative of leadership to try to change the subject,
which is why Gingrich, always a scorched-earth politician, and
Lott, who owes oily allegiance to oil, tobacco and other
anti-consumer forces, tend to rant about manufactured ``wedge''
issues like partial birth abortion, or cracking down on gays or
flag-burners. The Republican leaders mimic the current Israeli
government: a hard-line, abrasive regime kept in power by a
precarious balance of conservative party regulars and radical
religious fringe elements.
</P>
<P>
   When the country is unchallenged abroad, and enjoys unrivalled
prosperity at home, as at the present moment, it means that
so-called national leaders can indulge in the kind of frat-house
horesplay that allows Lott to rant about gays, or Gingrich to
bluster about his pet peeves, which are numerous.
</P>
<P>
   What happened last week in the House was of earthquake
proportions: the followship commandeered the agenda, and insisted
on passing toothy campaign reform. The vote was 252 to 179, but the
key number was 61. That's the number of House Republicans who
sucked it up and tucked it to Speaker Gingrich. Over his violent
objections, enough of his own troops deserted the leadership to
shove a meaningful reform bill past the House and over to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It's fate there is problematic. But reform has a way of
garnering momentum even in the face of implacable opposition. The
package erected by Shays and Meehan would ban the corrupt influence
of ``soft money,'' the unregulated sums, hundreds of thousands of
dollars, which flow directly from special interests.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also make it harder for shadowy
special-interest groups to buy attack advertising TV spots in the
run-up to an election, that could tip the outcome, without
disclosing just who is paying for the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and Meehan pulled off a remarkable triumph. While Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.) made it easier for Meehan to line up
Democrats, Shays had to contend with the vociferous criticism of
his fellow Republicans. He was called traitor, sellout and worse;
his longterm prospects in the House may not be healthy, so long as
Gingrich's motorcycle gang holds the reins.
</P>
<P>
   But Shays and Meehan have crowbarred their way to the national
stage with this victory. Lott's machinations may yet stall the
reform in the Senate, where a different version, McCain-Feingold,
died despite having 52 senators in favor. Because of Lott's desire
to keep corrupt soft money circulating through his own paws, he
decreed 60 votes would be needed to choke off debate, and reformers
fell short. Meehan said late Friday he has hopes that Sen. Alphonse
D'Amato (R-NY) can be knuckled to switching to the reformers' side.
D'Amato is up for re-election this fall, and the New York Times
will hammer him relentlessly on this.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible switcher is Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, in
Meehan's upbeat calculations. ``Nobody ever expected the House to
move the bill,'' said Meehan. ``We came from nowhere in just four
months.'' Every New Englander in both branches is for the reforms,
save three from New Hampshire: Sens. Gregg and Smith, and US Rep.
Sununu.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Sens. Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe of Maine, Rhode
Island's John Chafee and Vermont's Jim Jeffords are all aboard.
``We need eight Republican senators'' in all, said Meehan, and a
D'Amato switch would make five.
</P>
<P>
   If it were not for the Monica Lewinsky circus, the public
pressure would be enormous for Republican senators to relent and
accept the soft money ban. But as long as television owners have
Monica video to play with, and Monica-talk to peddle, they can
forestall public presentation of dry old campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the obstructionist efforts of Gingrich, Lott, the
special interests, and the TV profiteers, reform passed the House.
Anyway you slice it, the people won one for a change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
