<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW HORIZON FOR THE DIXIE CHICKS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Familiarity breeds, well, if not contempt, certainly apathy.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with Dallas' own Dixie Chicks, who nabbed two major
Country Music Association nominations (best vocal group and the
Horizon Award) last week.
</P>
<P>
   The former would be nice enough, but it's the Horizon nod that
really counts. (After all, LeAnn Rimes won it last year.) It means,
basically, that Nashville has anointed the Chicks as newcomers to
watch. Even if they don't win the award (and we'll find out Sept.
23), the nomination alone gives them a big boost in country music
circles, a cachet that plenty of up-and-coming acts would kill for.
</P>
<P>
   This is both perfectly sensible, as their major-label debut CD,
``Wide Open Spaces,'' has sold more than 500,000 copies in six
months _ and pretty darned funny.
</P>
<P>
   Martie Seidel and Emily Erwin, after all, began playing street
corners in the West End nearly a decade ago. Adapting their name
from Little Feat's ``Dixie Chicken,'' the Chicks graduated to
birthday parties, club gigs and conventions, gaining a rep as a
cutesy/kitschy little country/bluegrass act, happy to twirl the
skirts and wear the boots and hats and play the role of Uber-Texans
to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   And that, really, is where a lot of us left them. The Chicks
became synonymous with cute, with nice little songs and reliably
winsome club shows. They were always a big draw in Big D and Fort
Worth, but after a while the shtick got a little old. Unless you
were a huge fan (and, to be sure, there are those who have stuck
with 'em from Day One) they became old news. Oh, yeah, the Dixie
Chicks. Great. Pretty girls. Saw 'em at Poor David's once.
Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   We could be forgiven for this, to an extent, because for a long
time, cute and bubbly and pleasant is about all the Chicks were.
They didn't break out nationally, and they didn't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the apathy set in. It's the oldest story in the
book: If you're big doin's in your hometown, you either go to the
next level or a lot of the homies move on to something else.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was like Stevie Ray Vaughan. Between going solo in
the late '70s and breaking out nationally in 1983, Stevie played
around here a lot. A LOT. I loved going to hear him; seeing Stevie
Ray Vaughan in a bar was kind of like coming home and finding
Michael Jordan shooting hoops in your driveway. But after a while
it became a case of, ``Oh yeah _ Stevie Ray. Incredible player.
Does the Hendrix thing real good. I think I'll catch him NEXT
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   But while we weren't paying much attention, the Chicks changed.
In 1995, following the departures of a couple of members, Natalie
Maines, daughter of legendary musician Lloyd Maines, came aboard.
She added a whole lot of fire, and the band, collectively, took on
a new persona _ cute for cute's sake was out. Suddenly they were
spokeswomen for young women leaving home (or getting a job after
college, or getting their heart seriously broken) for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The chorus to the hit ``Wide Open Spaces'' says it all: ``She
needs wide-open spaces/Room to make her big mistakes/She needs new
faces/She knows the high stakes.'' Rarely has a country song
detailed the hopes and fears and giddy excitement and terror of
being in one's early 20s and realizing you have your whole life _
good AND bad _ before you.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's metaphors we're looking for, we couldn't find a
better one. After all these years, and all that trial and error,
the Dixie Chicks have become a band to really take notice of. For
the second time, and for better.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
