<SLUG> BC-PARALYZEDBYPAINT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOMEOWNER ABANDONS THE SAFETY OF WHITE WALLS FOR ROOMS WITH A
HUE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by PAINT-CUES ON HUES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was a woman living in fear.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, I was afraid to paint the white walls in my
all-too-vanilla home. It was our first house, and I clung to renter
mentality. We would have to sell the home someday, and experts say
buyers prefer plain walls that allow them to visualize their own
decorating tastes.
</P>
<P>
   But what about my decorating tastes?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I didn't know whether I had any and was too cheap
to pay someone who did. I wanted to be bolder, but I was drowning
in doubts.
</P>
<P>
   What if the paint color clashed with the fireplace? What if it
looked stupid? What if it was too light? Too dark? Too trendy? My
fears kept me paralyzed, clutching paintbrushes only in my dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis: color commitment anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that is actually a term bandied about by color experts such
as Leslie Harrington, director of color and design by Benjamin
Moore paints.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington reassured me that the condition is perfectly normal.
</P>
<P>
   I could be cured once I realized that painting is really the
easiest and cheapest way to add instant personality to a room (and
hide the fact that I don't have much furniture).
</P>
<P>
   My fears gave way to obsession as I began scoping out paint
chips. Soon I had more than 100 stuffed in my purse. I needed a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to the growing ranks of interior design celebs. Lynette
Jennings, star of ``HouseSmart'' on The Discovery Channel,
suggested starting with a favorite piece of fabric and, from it,
building a color palette for the whole house.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the pastel floral pattern of my family room sofa and
love seat, so I started with that.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lowell, design guru of ``Interior Motives'' on The
Discovery Channel, urged looking through the clothes closet because
you tend to wear the colors you like best. If you wear purple, why
not paint your walls purple? he reasons.
</P>
<P>
   I was making progress, narrowing the possible palette down to
light blues and greens (the colors that filled my closet). It was
then that I realized just how many thousands of shades of aqua are
out there.
</P>
<P>
   Dazed and confused yet again, I turned to the diva of home
decor. Martha Stewart offers a line of paint in Kmart stores that
ranges from Aquatic Green to Yellow Rose. Her plethora of blues and
greens mesmerized me _ I debated the virtues of Hooked Rug Green
vs. Tree Swing Green.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, anyone contemplating a trendy wall color
these days has to pay a visit to Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   The high priest of preppie style sells his line of paints at
Home Depot. Although he doesn't offer coordinated color cards a la
Martha, he does divide his colors by lifestyle. There's a Sport
collection for those who favor brawny colors to highlight their
buff furniture. The Desert collection spotlights Southwestern
style, and the more traditional Country collection featured my
favorite color, Montauk Gray.
</P>
<P>
   After several months, I had narrowed the choices down to three
bluish, grayish-green colors _ Martha Stewart's Atlantic, Ralph
Lauren's Montauk Gray and Benjamin Moore's Gray Sage.
</P>
<P>
   Still in doubt, I invited a friend over who had painted the
white walls in her house years ago. Before we got around to the
chicken salad, I popped out the paint chips and asked her opinion.
She told me Gray Sage was strong, but given the Southern exposure
of the room, ``The walls could handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked at the color, but somehow it seemed a bit too drab.
Emboldened to let my own tastes take control, I opted for the
slightly bluer Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   It was a breakthrough to buy the paint, but the real point of no
return came when I stroked on that first brush of color. A few
hours later, one wall was transformed.
</P>
<P>
   Following the experts' advice, I waited a couple of days to see
how the color evolved through the day and night. A few days later,
the whole room was awash in Atlantic, which gave new punch to my
old white moldings.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington told me the measure of a successful wall color is
really how well it showcases the contents of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people walk in and say `Wow, look at those red walls, you
haven't succeeded,' '' she said. ``It has to show off the furniture
and accessories. Then it becomes a neutral and looks like a
magazine, and they say, `Wow, I wish I had to guts to do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
