<SLUG> BC-FILM-HALLOWEEMH20-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED SLASHER FAILS THE SCREAM TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of ``Halloween H20'' as ``The Slasher Movie That Cried
Wolf.'' It's so intent on false alarms that it begins to look like
a practical joke on genre fans, a horror movie with no real horror.
Once the bodies do start falling, you're too bored to care.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis, returning for the first time since ``Halloween
II,'' wastes no time getting back into the thick of things. Even
before she's on camera, she's screaming that scream that made her
famous. It's 20 years later (H-2-0, get it?), and Curtis' Laurie
Strode character is living under an assumed name in one of those
anonymous California small towns, where she's the alcoholic,
pill-popping headmistress of a prestigious private school. Just
what you want when you've faked your death _ a high-profile
position.
</P>
<P>
   She's also a single mother, with a son named John (newcomer Josh
Hartnett _ first tip, Josh: Fire your hairstylist). John is 17, the
very age Laurie was in the first film. Understandably, she's
overprotective and reluctant to let John join his classmates on a
camping trip.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie still sees her brother, Michael Meyers, the ``Halloween''
series' demented killer, everywhere she goes _ she's literally
afraid of her shadow. WE know, of course, that he's really on the
loose, and he's coming to get her _ and John. But Michael's older
now, of course, and he moves a little slow _ kind of like this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, by now we know all of ``Halloween's'' tricks.
The ``Scream'' movies ratcheted (or hatcheted) up the slasher genre
with their wit and pop-culture savvy; the closest this movie can
come to them is showing a ``Scream 2'' video on a TV screen.
``(Scream'' screenwriter Kevin Williamson reportedly did a
script-polish; maybe the video was his contribution.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Halloween H20: Twenty Years Later''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Steve Miner
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jamie Lee Curtis, Josh Hartnett
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, strong language and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   Length: 81 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
