<HEADLINE>
SEEING JEWS AS VICTIMS SAID TO INVITE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add picture note)   (With BC-HOLOCAUST-KATZ and BC-HOLOCAUST-INTRO)  
 (ART ADV: Photo of the writer is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(js) 
 By RUTH WISSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The destruction of the Jews of Europe was all but ignored when
it was happening. The impulse to document it now and to fix it in
memory is quite natural, commendable and necessary. But insuring
that this genocide will not be forgotten is not the same as
teaching Judaism or making the world a safer place. Although some
well-intentioned folk evidently believe that advertising the
victimization of the Jews will discourage aggression against them,
they might as well believe that dying is good for your health.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine an American child who knows nothing about the Jews being
introduced to them first as the objects of genocide! Of the Hebrew
Bible he knows nothing. Nothing of the Jews' reception of the Law
at Sinai, and their self-disciplined attempt to interpret and
maintain it through thousands of years. Nothing of the Jewish
yearning for God, the Ten Commandments, the Sabbath, the liturgy.
No information about Jewish history, about Jewish sovereignty in
the land of Israel or the concept of exile outside it; about Jewish
migrations and the development of multiple Jewish languages. No
awareness of Jewish philosophy and literature, folkways and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The child is expected to learn tolerance from the Holocaust, but
tolerance of what? How will he be prepared for the quirky tribe of
real Jews when he has discovered the Jews as perfect victims in
their death throes and martyrdom? The more he thinks of Jews as
victims of the Nazis, the less he will be able to appreciate the
stiff-necked, highly particularistic people who observe different
rituals and rites of passage, and who want to remain as distinctive
as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Mass murder is neither the defining moment of Judaism nor the
sound basis of a moral education. A Jewish college sophomore who
was educated in Hebrew school on a steady diet of
``Holocaustology'' said to me recently, ``The Jews of Europe may
have been killed for what they believed in, but I was never told
what they believed in.'' She knows she was cheated of a proper
education. If the slaughter of the European Jews dare not be
forgotten, neither should it overshadow the way of life it tried to
destroy. Jewish education and American education ought to have much
more to teach about the creative energy of the Jews than the
destructive energy of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characteristics of Nazism was its reduction of the
Jews to an abstraction of evil, a symbol of corruption. Teaching
the Holocaust separately from teaching about the Jews as a whole
runs the risk of abstracting them and diminishing them to the same
degree. The Jews of Europe did not seek to be martyrs, and were in
the process of emancipating themselves politically so that they
should be better able to determine their own destiny. Treating the
Holocaust as a secular crucifixion cuts off Jewish tragedy from the
historical continuum, and distorts the rich reality of Jewish
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Jews of Israel, in particular, are learning how to
re-fashion their own sovereignty after too many centuries of being
imagined as dead. Homage to the murdered Jews is morally
reprehensible when it takes precedence over, or becomes a
substitute for, education about the flourishing Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a second danger in focusing on the Jews as victims
of the Holocaust: it obscures the nature of aggression committed
against them. The murder of the European Jews was a political act,
a war within a war. The Germans were able to win their war against
the Jews even as they failed to impose the Thousand-Year Reich in
Europe. This was because in his war against the Jews, Hitler had
the support of most of the populations he overran. By the time he
conceived his Final Solution, anti-Semitism had become the most
powerful ideology on the Continent, a force that united the
conquerors with many of the conquered.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism, which is the organization of politics around
antipathy to the Jews, battened on the longstanding image of the
Jews as victims, although the Jews had done everything possible to
resist this fate. Following an earlier catastrophe _ the Romans'
destruction of the Second Temple in Jerusalem in A.D. 70 _ the Jews
postponed indefinitely the recovery of their national sovereignty,
and determined to uphold their religious civilization among other
peoples. They learned to survive without land, without autonomous
political authority and without independent means of self-defense,
attempting to compensate for their political weakness through
economic and intellectual strength.
</P>
<P>
   Although this strategy of accommodation yielded certain
advantages, the temptation it offered the surrounding peoples
usually proved even greater. Jews often accumulated visible status
and wealth. But prosperity without the ability to protect their
assets made them the ideal target of rulers and mobs. Demagogues
inflated their power by attacking this small people with the very
large image. The reputation of the Jews as a no-fail enemy grew
with each successive expulsion, massacre and pogrom.
</P>
<P>
   Those who exploit the Holocaust as a moral fable make no
connection between it and the political predicament of the Jews:
being perceived as victims and targets. In fact, Hitler's
victorious war against the Jews inspires as much imitation as
regret.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Jews have reclaimed their sovereignty since their
destruction in Europe, and in Israel they now command their own
self-defense. But as long as the demographic and political
imbalance between the Jews and those who wish to dislodge them
remains as lop-sided as it was in Europe, the precedent of the
Holocaust still tempts the aggressor. Far from regarding the German
genocide as morally abhorrent, Arab anti-Semitism recycles the same
accusations, and keeps its eye on the same prize.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever had trouble sympathizing with the dead Jews. But
the protection of the living _ and especially protection for the
Jewish political community that remains under siege _ requires the
opposite set of moral reflexes. Of course, it is imperative to
document, to study, to analyze and to commemorate the greatest
moral failure in Western civilization, which coincides with the
tragedy of the Jewish people. Preventing its recurrence requires
something else, and something more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
