<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the third day in a row, scattered thundershowers will
surround a decaying trough of low pressure moving slowly through
the Mississippi Valley and western Great Lakes on Saturday.
Rainfall throughout this corridor will be less than in recent days,
though isolated thunderstorms could still produce an inch or two of
additional rain.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the low, residual moisture in the lowest few
thousand feet of the atmosphere will cause low stratus clouds to
linger over sections of eastern Minnesota and Iowa. Farther south,
burgeoning cumulus clouds will replace clear skies over the
southeast Plains and east Texas as rising currents of warm, moist
air ascend into a pocket of cool air at 20,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A boundary between humid and drier air will provide the focus
for clouds and spotty showers in central New England on Saturday.
Farther north, abundant sun and very warm air will cover northern
Maine. Meanwhile, ample sunshine and increasingly sultry air will
affect the Middle Atlantic States as high pressure along the
Eastern Seaboard draws humid air northward.
</P>
<P>
   Intervals of sunshine and puffy cumulus clouds will prevail from
Virginia to Florida on Saturday. A few of these clouds will produce
thunderstorms, especially during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Winds from the southeast will transport increasingly humid air
into the Southwest. As the intense sun heats the moist air,
isolated thunderstorms will develop in the afternoon and evening,
possibly leading to local flooding. Elsewhere, mainly sunny skies
and seasonably warm weather will cover the Pacific states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Cold Funnels
</P>
<P>
   Ominous but harmless cold-air funnels dipped below cumulus
clouds over northwest Missouri on Friday. These funnel clouds earn
their ``cold'' moniker because, when they occur, they form in the
cool air aloft that follows a cold front between late spring and
mid-autumn. As the sun breaks through clouds and warms the ground,
cold-air funnels can develop as cumulus clouds build to modest
altitudes up to 25,000 feet. In contrast, funnel clouds associated
with destructive tornadoes form in very warm, humid and unstable
air masses in which parent thunderstorms can mushroom to 50,000
feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
