<HEADLINE>
HOT CONSUMER ITEMS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The only handwritten letters I get these days are
from stores,'' said Barry Cooper, a real estate developer who is an
avid shopper. Thank-you notes have become de rigueur, from Madison
Avenue boutiques to Pottery Barn and J. Crew. In their retail sales
programs, Paul Stuart, Bergdorf Goodman, Lord &AMP; Taylor and other
stores require classes in the art of writing thank-you notes to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, expressing gratitude is becoming more competitive. After
buying Volkswagen's New Beetle, Cooper received a note of thanks
with a tiny silver copy of the car.
</P>
<P>
   And for Edward Hunter, who has worked at Sulkha, the men's
clothing store on Park Avenue, for 12 years, a mere thank-you note
is too prosaic. He prefers to woo his clientele with verse:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics) Allow searchings for paths unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Wish us wisdom's weight of all clouds passing.
</P>
<P>
   Realize dreams hugging rainbow rays.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hunter doesn't reserve his poetry for big spenders. ``I give it
away with great energy,'' he said. ``I'm a great believer in
spreading the written word.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Stevens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Roller Girl when I wear them,'' Tia Williams, 22,
said of her 1981 Sergio Valente jeans. ``The old 80s jeans are more
fun and a lot sexier than the ones today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams was in diapers when nothing came between Brooke
Shields and her Calvins. But after the success of ``Boogie Nights''
(with Heather Graham as Roller Girl) and ``The Last Days of
Disco,'' a new generation is snapping up circulation-restricting
jeans in secondhand stores like Antique Boutique on lower Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Disco-era designers have reissued their classics: Jordache
($40), Sergio Valente's V jeans ($70) and Calvin Klein's Original
Calvins ($52). But not everyone is pining for the days you had to
pull up your zipper with a pair of pliers. Jimmy Hanrahan, a
stylist at MTV, cautioned against banking on the trend.
``Individual style has conquered the designer label dictatorship,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lola Ogunnaike &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent video, an ode to materialism, the hip-hop idol Sean
(Puffy) Combs mentions Matsuda sunglasses, but he's wearing Barry
Kieselstein-Cords. BKCs, as they're called, are the latest from the
animal-loving designer whose handbags and jewelry are home to a
menagerie of frogs, alligators and other beasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has developed a cult following that started way back with
his jewelry,'' said Rise Gerber, the fashion director for
accessories at Bergdorf Goodman, where the sunglasses are a top
seller. ``This is a way for a woman who may not be able to afford a
handbag to have something of his.''
</P>
<P>
   With the shades' introduction in January, men joined the BKC
cult. Eddy Veder and Robin Williams have also bought the
sunglasses, which cost $395 to $18,000, the price of a
limited-edition pair bought by Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Stevens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Naomi Campbell, Parker Posey, Donna Karan and Kirsty Hume
wanted hand-dyed dresses made from vintage lingerie, they all
sought out Momo Falana, a line sold at the 26th Street flea market
and by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo DiCaprio is also a customer. ``I went into great detail
telling him about the shimmer in the fabric and the dying
process,'' said Maureen (Momo) Roberts, one of the two creators.
``He was quick to remind me that the dress wasn't for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Designs range from a beaded 1920s dressing gown ($1,000) to
boldly dyed chiffon slips ($30). ``People seem to want that
timeless romantic feeling, no matter what the trends are,'' said
Michael Lublin, Ms. Roberts' husband and partner. Appointments:
(212) 979-9595.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Stevens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fear of germs from all sorts of contact once thought to be
innocuous is growing. There are now antibacterial ballpoint pens
designed by C&AMP;K Manufacturing, Nike ACG sneakers with an
antibacterial foot bed and a new line of germ-free Clean Use
calculators from Casio.
</P>
<P>
   And these are not being marketed exclusively to the Howard
Hughes fan club, either. Products from dishwashing liquids to body
lotions have seen sales rise with the addition of ``antibacterial''
to their labels.
</P>
<P>
   No-rinse hand sanitizing lotions like Purell are even being
dispensed in public restrooms, left. And new competition for Purell
is Jao, which also offers aromatherapy benefits (available at
Bigelow Pharmacy).
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors believe that eliminating too many bacteria can have
health risks of its own. For the anti-anti-bacterial camp, there's
the High Performance Hygiene System, a collection of soaps ($8) and
facial dips ($12) available at Ricky's drugstores and Healthy
Pleasures markets, and coming to Bloomingdale's this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our products emulsify germs; they don't kill them,'' said
Steven Blaushield, the president of High Performance (orders from
888-262-5700). But this is no simple soap-and-water solution. You
immerse your hands in a tub of fatty acids and oils that feel like
Vaseline. And for germ-sensitive nasal and eye membranes, plunge
your face in a basin of water dosed with the hydrogen peroxide and
iodine dip and blink.
</P>
<P>
   Dany Levy
</P>
</TEXT>
