<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-BOX-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLOMBIA, US: STRAINED, BUT SIGNIFICANT RELATIONSHIP
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-PRESIDENT-0808.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FACTS ABOUT PRESIDENT-ELECT ANDRES PASTRANA:
</P>
<P>
   Age: 43
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Married to Norha Puyana; three children.
</P>
<P>
   Party: Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Born in Bogota, Pastrana is the son of the late
former President Misael Pastrana. He was once the mayor of Bogota,
a senator, and a television journalist. He narrowly lost a bid for
president in 1994 against Ernesto Samper.
</P>
<P>
   THE U.S.-COLOMBIA CONNECTION:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. exports to Colombia, dominated by chemicals, were $5.2
billion in 1997 compared to $4.6 billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. imports from Colombia -- mostly petroleum, coffee and cut
flowers -- were $4.7 billion in 1997, up from $3.7 billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The United States will give the Colombian military about $100
million in aid this year. The United States has about 200 military
advisers in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trade between Florida and Colombia totaled $4.09 billion in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An estimated 1 million Colombians live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   --About 50,000 Colombians live in the states of Georgia,
Tennessee, Kentucky, North and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   --About 15,000 Colombians live in the metro Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   --About 300,000 Colombians live in Florida, with some 200,000 in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   --About 2,000 businesses in South Florida are owned by
Colombians.
</P>
<P>
   --About 60,000 Colombians live in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some of the U.S. companies operating in Colombia include
American Airlines, the Coca-Cola Co., General Motors Corp.,
Gillette, IBM, Microsoft, Mobil, and Xerox Corp.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL FACTS &AMP; FIGURES ABOUT COLOMBIA:
</P>
<P>
   The land: About the size of Texas and New Mexico combined at
439,735 square miles, Colombia is in the northwestern corner of
South America, bordered by Panama, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, and
Venezuela. It is the fourth largest country in South America with
coast lines on both the Caribbean and Pacific. The capital, Bogota,
has a population of 6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The people: Colombia has a population of 36 million, of whom
about 58 percent are Mestizo, 20 percent are Caucasian, and 14
percent are Mulatto. At least 95 percent of the population is Roman
Catholic. The language is Spanish and the literacy rate is 87
percent. Education is free and supposed to be compulsory, but many
children in rural areas don't go to school.
</P>
<P>
   The government: The Senate has 102 members and the Chamber of
Representatives has 161. The president, who appoints his 13
ministers, is elected by popular vote for a term of four years. The
president-elect is Andres Pastrana, who will replace Ernesto Samper
when he takes office Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The history: Almost from its inception, Colombia has been a
scene of strife. Leftist rebels, that number about 15,000 today,
have fought the government for 34 years. One leftist group, the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), is Latin America's
largest and oldest guerrilla force. About 35,000 people have been
killed in the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The economy: Chief crops are coffee, rice, tobacco, cotton,
sugar, and bananas. As well as oil and gas, Colombia has the
largest coal reserves in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
