<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PRESIDENT-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLOMBIA SWEARS IN NEW PRESIDENT FOLLOWING WEEK OF BLOODY
VIOLENCE
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-BOX-0808.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Harvard-educated Andres Pastrana was sworn in Friday as
Colombia's new president following a week of unexpected political
violence, a bloody reminder of just how virulent the Marxist
guerrillas have become and how difficult it will be to forge peace
in this war-weary country.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful guerrilla offensive that began Monday and tapered off
by Wednesday left more than 140 soldiers and police officers dead.
At least 100 more were missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most dramatically, the rebels overtook an important
anti-narcotics base in Miraflores, in southern Colombia, killing or
dragging away scores of security officers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a grim welcome for Pastrana, 43, who just last month
trudged through the jungle to meet face-to-face with leaders of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), Latin America's
oldest and largest rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   Following that historic meeting, Pastrana and rebel leaders
announced that peace talks would begin by November.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC -- and the smaller Cuban-inspired National Liberation
Army (ELN) -- number nearly 20,000 fighters. Demanding a
more-responsive government and increased social spending, they've
tried to topple the Colombian government in a civil war that has
spanned three decades and killed some 35,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's 147,000-member military has been ineffective against
an increasingly bold and influential guerrilla force that's
believed to be gaining wealth and firepower through fees collected
from drug traffickers in exchange for the protection of cultivation
fields and processing centers.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, a television journalist and former mayor of Bogota,
Colombia's capital, replaced outgoing President Ernesto Samper and
will serve a four-year term. The June 21 election of the
independent candidate, who had the backing of the opposition
Conservative Party, ended the ruling Liberal Party's 12-year lock
on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel groups had refused to negotiate peace with Samper's
administration, which they branded illegitimate following reports
that Samper's 1994 campaign was bankrolled by $6 million in drug
money.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, it appeared the rebels had ended their offensive in
an effort to underscore their desire to work with Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday, the FARC said that its rash of
attacks was a final protest aimed at Samper's government.
</P>
<P>
   Colombians hope Pastrana will restore authority to an office
whose reputation eroded under the scandal-plagued administration of
Samper, who even had his tourist visa revoked by the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the rebel onslaught, there was reason to be
optimistic as Pastrana took office.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana met with President Clinton in Washington on Monday, a
clear indication that U.S.-Colombia relations have improved.
</P>
<P>
   And leaders of right-wing paramilitary groups behind much of the
nation's bloodshed agreed to participate in peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Both guerrilla and civilian groups have agreed to hold a
national convention before Oct. 12 to discuss economic and social
reforms that could pave the way for a permanent peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still some question over how fast and how far the
new president can go in a nation so mired in political and economic
crises.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is still the cocaine capital of the world, where up to
80 percent of the cocaine sold in the United States -- and a
growing amount of heroin -- is produced.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment, inflation, interest rates, and the government
deficit have soared to 20-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, supporters say Pastrana, who comes from a long line of
politicians, and is the son of a former president, may have the
background and the determination to turn the tide in his
strife-torn homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pastrana was kidnapped by the Medellin drug cartel
during his mayoral campaign, then freed a week later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to be well-meaning in his pursuit of a serious peace
process,'' said Coletta Youngers, an expert on Colombia at the
Washington Office on Latin America, a liberal think tank.
``Although he faces pressing concerns, people are cautiously
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
