<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, Aug. 8. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Ledeall: Two massive bombs
devastated the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on Wednesday
morning, killing several American officials and more than 80 other
people, in what appeared to be simultaneous terrorist attacks. In
Washington, President Clinton condemned the attacks as abhorrent
and inhuman acts of cowardice. He vowed to bring those responsible
to justice ``no matter what or how long it takes.'' By James C.
McKinley Jr. (6-column lede, with photo-layout and map.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton denounces the
attacks; other American reaction. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SECURITY (Washington) _ A look at security measures at
other U.S. embassies worldwide. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of President Clinton. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Hindered by the GM strike and the Asian
recession, the economy added jobs in July at the slowest pace in
more than two years. Payrolls grew by 66,000, in line with
analysts' forecasts and below June's employment gain. The GM strike
cost the economy almost 160,000 jobs in July. The jobless rate in
July was unchanged at 4.5 percent. Workers' average hourly
earnings, a gauge of business costs, rose 0.2 percent, or 3 cents,
in July, matching June's increase. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
repeats his determination to spur economic growth and prevent
Japan's troubles from spreading to the rest of the world, but he is
short on specifics. Delivering his first policy statement to
Parliament, he says permanent tax cuts will ``considerably exceed''
6 trillion yen, or $41 billion. He also repeats his pledges to push
through another spending package, of 10 trillion yen, and close
troubled banks. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-KATZ (Undated) _ Steven T. Katz argues that the
Holocaust is a singular event, perhaps the most significant
occurrence in 2,000 years of Jewish history, and that it therefore
deserves to be treated as such.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-WISSE (Undated) _ Ruth R. Wisse counters that turning
the Holocaust into the defining event in Jewish history is a
terrible mistake, that it distorts the rich and long history of the
Jews, allows Hitler to define the Jews and obscures the political
nature of what happened in Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   SWIM-SMITH (Undated) _ Michelle Smith de Bruin, the Irish
swimmer who was banned in a drug scandal, says she will appeal the
penalty and sue the world swimming federation for damages. By Frank
Litsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
