<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-TRANSCRIPT08     08-07 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-TRANSCRIPT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARTIAL TRANSCRIPT OF INTERVIEW WITH HOUSE SPEAKER GINGRICH
 &HT;    With GINGRICH.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a remarkable week in Congress. A House
committee recommended that that House cite Attorney General Janet
Reno in contempt of Congress. A former White House intern told a
federal grand jury about sexual liaisons with the president.
Despite Republican leadership opposition, the House passed a bill
to overhaul the way money is raised in campaigns. And bombs burst
in two U.S. embassies. House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., sat down
with the Atlanta Journal-Constitution to address the week's
activities before departing for Ireland. Below is a partial
transcript:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Yesterday, a house panel found the Attorney General Janet
Reno in contempt of Congress. What do you think about that?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the attorney general now has until we return in
September to either A, appoint an independent counsel as the FBI
director and her own senior lawyer have recommended, or B, turn
over to the House the documents which prove and explain why her
legal advisers believe there should be an independent counsel. ...
I think we have now served notice ...that we are tired of being
stonewalled by the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Monica Lewinsky (reportedly) said yesterday that she had
several sexual liaisons with the president. You have said in the
past, that if the president has obstructed justice ...he should be
brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's draw the distinction between whatever the rumors are
and what the principles are. ...First, no one is above the law. If
a crime, notice not a scandal, but if a crime has been committed,
the American people have the right to know. And third, the
president, as the chief law enforcement officer of the United
States, has an absolute duty, as does his staff, to cooperate with
a legitimate executive branch investigator. ...(But) until we get
the Starr report, until Henry Hyde and the Judiciary Committee have
a chance to to review it, we don't know anything. And so there is
more than enough gossip on television without us.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would you like to see hearings as soon as possible?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think it's very simple. If the report is overwhelming,
people will move in one direction. If the report is powerful, but
not overwhelming, people will move in another direction. Until we
see the report, any comment is prejudgment.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think the president has lied?
</P>
<P>
   A. What I personally think is irrelevant. I personally think we
should wait until we get the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have said in the past that you wanted anti-teen smoking
bill. Has that thought changed?
</P>
<P>
   A. When you only have an 11-vote margin, life stays permanently
interesting. Those members who represent tobacco-growing areas
legitimately want to vote no. I don't blame them. They are
representing their constituents. ...The Democrats have adopted a
deliberate strategy, which I think is understandable, but not very
helpful, where they want to stop anything because they would like
to claim that we are a do-nothing Congress. ...I am going to make
one more effort in September to see if we can find the votes to
pass an anti-teen smoking bill.
</P>
<P>
   Q. (Following public comments about the embassy bombings in
Africa,) what are you thinking about right now?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm an Army brat. My first reaction is always personal. It
reminds me of ... being in Europe as a child when we'd go on alert
in order to avoid theoretical Russian attacks. We lived with a
footlocker for three years so we could go to Switzerland if the war
started.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it slightly surreal to go from partisan squabbling to
bonding with the president over national security?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a natural constitutional tension between the
Congress and the president. ... And it has been this way since 1789
with George Washington. And so, what makes this a remarkable system
is we take the most human of behaviors on the one hand, and we are
able somehow to rise above them to create this most idealistic of
self-governing systems on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are you most proud of? What do you look at as your best
accomplishments?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have profoundly begun to move the agenda and language of
this country _welfare is the best example, balanced budget is the
second _ from the assumptions of the liberal welfare state to an
opportunity society that is very different. ...It will be more
obvious three years from now. 2001 will be the period when we
really get the real payoff. All this is an investment for when we
have a Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will you be that president?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think so. You can never tell. This is a strange
country. Never thought I'd be speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Q. On campaign finance and what happened this week, were you
disappointed that Republicans broke with you?
</P>
<P>
   A. Republicans and Democrats alike voted for a bill that's
essentially hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is it hopeless?
</P>
<P>
   A. The bill is basically deluded about the nature of the
information age. It is expensive to reach people. It's getting more
expensive to reach people in the information age. ...Wisconsin has
very strict reform laws, which they have now found every possible
loophole in an attempt to get around. What you do is you make
politics more convoluted and more Byzantine and less honest and
less open.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Fact that you had members go over ... was that an act of
defiance?
</P>
<P>
   A. In the case of some members, they really believed it. In the
case of other members, they decided it was a politically expedient
vote. ...I lose less than 10 percent of the votes that matter in
this House with the narrowest majority since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
