<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH08-COX     08-07 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH BACKS PRESIDENT ON TERRORISM, ATTACKS HIM ON ETHICS
 &HT;    With GINGRICH-TRANSCRIPT
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN and REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the end of an eventful week in Washington, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich on Friday in one breath expressed solidarity
with President Clinton in condemning ghastly terrorist attacks and,
in another, ruminated about his possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In a week in which Attorney General Janet Reno was under the
threat of being held in contempt of Congress, a former White House
intern reportedly told a grand jury that she had an affair with the
president and bombs ripped apart two U.S. embassies, the Georgia
Republican covered a range of issues in an interview squeezed in
around public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing whether the House Judiciary Committee would hold
impeachment hearings before the fall elections, Gingrich said it
depended upon the strength of independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the report is overwhelming, people will move in one
direction. If the report is powerful, but not overwhelming, people
will move in another direction,'' Gingrich said. ``Until we see the
report, any comment is prejudgment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker made clear his annoyance with, in his view, the
continuing reluctance and outright refusal by Clinton and his
administration to cooperate with Starr and congressional
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``To invoke totally phony and repudiated claims of privilege is,
I think, very distressing and a failure to do his job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, addressing reporters about bombings at the U.S. embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania, Gingrich said no one should mistake ``family
arguments'' between Democrats and Republicans for U.S. weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are challenged, we unite as one country without any
questions,'' the speaker said, a few hours before he led a
congressional delegation on a weeklong trip to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The House left town for its summer vacation without tackling
nettlesome legislative issues such as a tobacco bill, and without
an agreement on how to go about cutting taxes, which the speaker
intends to make the centerpiece of the GOP's re-election campaign.
No more than two dozen work days remain before Congress hopes to
adjourn in early October.
</P>
<P>
   On passing a bill aimed at cutting down on the number of
teenagers who smoke, Gingrich said he planned to push for a bill
when Congress reconvenes after Labor Day. His biggest obstacle, he
said, is persuading Republicans from tobacco-growing states to
support any tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying right now to figure out how to get the votes to do
that,'' Gingrich said. ``When you only have an 11-vote margin, life
stays permanently interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the criticism that the GOP has been more interested
in attacking Democrats and holding onto their majority than passing
key public policy initiatives, Gingrich tried to turn the tables on
his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, he said, only want a tobacco bill that generates
taxes for new social programs. Failing that, they would prefer
using tobacco as a campaign issue rather than compromising on
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who used to serve in the minority in the Congress
with a Republican president, I know exactly the pain that they are
living through,'' he said. ``The conceptual challenge of the
Democratic Party today is that its ideology is obsolete and its
interest groups refuse to allow it to rethink what it's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But just this week, Gingrich faced a major disappointment when
61 members of his party defied the GOP leadership and supported a
bill that would ban unlimited, unregulated donations to political
parties known as soft money and regulate campaign advertising by
third parties.
</P>
<P>
   But addressing the uphill fight it faces in the Senate, where
Majority Leader Trent Lott killed a similar bill this year,
Gingrich called the legislation ``hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
