<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKFORCE08-COX     08-07 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKFORCE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SIGNS BILL TO SHIFT JOB TRAINING PROGRAMS TO STATES
 &HT;    By SHANNON JOYCE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed a major overhaul of the
nation's job training programs into law Friday, giving states,
local governments and individuals the ability to tailor training
programs to fit their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we celebrate a big step forward in making sure every
adult can keep on learning for a lifetime,'' Clinton said at a
White House Rose Garden ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The Workforce Investment Act of 1998, sponsored by Sen. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio, will consolidate job training resources, link and
monitor training programs, and make one-stop job centers the
gateway to training.
</P>
<P>
   ``To invest in our people, we have to give all of our people
access to world-class education and training,'' Clinton said. ``We
have to do more than we are already doing.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWine has called the bill a necessary companion to the 1996
welfare reform, giving welfare recipients the training they need to
find good jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, everyone must be given the competitive skills that
are necessary to prosper in the new global economy,'' DeWine said
at the ceremony. ``This is the crucial second stage of welfare
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, communities and local businesses will
develop a three-year job training strategy. Local governments have
the freedom to pick programs that train workers for jobs in local
industries and businesses, and use local resources, such as a
community college or vocational school, to provide the training.
</P>
<P>
   Once the state governor reviews the plan, it will be sent to the
U.S. secretary of labor for final approval. States will receive a
block grant to pay for their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the new process ``a model of what we should be
doing.'' In addition to allowing communities to choose what is best
for their local economy, the new law lets workers decide which
training program they want to use.
</P>
<P>
   Programs will now have to be accredited by the U.S. Labor
Department, and allow prospective students access to statistics
showing how many of the program's graduates have jobs and how much
they earn.
</P>
<P>
   Job training programs will be linked with courses that provide
training for people with disabilities, allowing students to
transfer between the two programs.
</P>
<P>
   Each trainee will have an individual training account to use for
training programs. After the trainee and a job counselor decide on
a training program, the trainee will receive a voucher to pay for
it.
</P>
<P>
   The new voucher system would replace the old practice of states
and counties buying slots in training programs and then finding
students to fill them, a move DeWine says will eliminate pushing
people into training programs they may not want to use.
</P>
<P>
   The new law will also boost Job Corps, a job training program
for youth, and give financially depressed areas more money for
youth training.
</P>
<P>
   Job Corps students will be sent to the center closest to their
homes and monitored six and 12 months after they graduate from the
program.
</P>
<P>
   High-poverty areas designated as Empowerment Zones or Enterprise
Communities will be eligible for $1.25 billion in grant money for
youth programs. Included in that grant program is $250 million to
help the children of migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
