<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3587 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-PLAN-RESENDING     08-07 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PLAN-RESENDING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD FROM BOEING DUE NEXT WEEK ON 737 PLANS  
 ATTN: WICHITA, ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST and JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. plans to announce next week whether it will
establish a next-generation 737 production line at its under-used
factory in Long Beach, Calif., and several people familiar with the
plans said Thursday it is all but certain the work will be done
there.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary report recommending the new assembly operations in
California has been prepared but has not been given the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Last-minute issues are still being worked out, including
negotiations with leaders of Boeing's largest union, which strongly
opposes the plan.
</P>
<P>
   California government officials ``have bent over backwards'' to
provide Boeing with economic incentives to add a 737 assembly line
at Long Beach, The Post-Intelligencer was told.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing senior vice president Fred Mitchell warned a team of
managers working on the 737 study Thursday to disregard ``media
speculation'' and emphasized ``we have not yet completed our
business case and we have not yet made a decision on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo, Mitchell, Boeing's executive vice president for
airplane production, wrote: ``We are still testing logistics,
working with the unions who represent employees in the Puget Sound
and Long Beach areas, and working with government officials as part
of our study. Those open items are complex, and we have to work
through them before the business case, either way, is confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the 737 study will be completed and a decision announced
within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But people familiar with the plans said the company is scheduled
to announce next Thursday its decision to set up the Long Beach
line. In addition, the company will announce a consolidation of
facilities - primarily defense and space - throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several days Boeing will truck 737 wings from its
Renton factory to Long Beach to determine how costly the trip would
be, how long the journey would take and to pinpoint the best route.
</P>
<P>
   The company conducted a similar experiment a few weeks ago, when
it sent by train a mock-up fuselage of its longest 737 aircraft
from its Wichita, Kan., factory to Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already makes fuselages in Wichita and ships them to
Renton for final assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also is preparing a production bay in Long Beach
previously used to build McDonnell Douglas MD-11 jets to
accommodate assembly of next-generation 737s.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-ton crane is being installed to help move 737 aircraft
assemblies, and a three-story mezzanine structure is being built in
the the assembly area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are setting up an assembly line that will be identical to
the Renton 737 assembly line,'' said Boeing spokesman John Thom in
Long Beach. ``It's prudent to be ready for a 737 line but
everything is contingent upon a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He said 737 assembly operations could begin in California as
early as October.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced in May that it is sending some 737-model
aircraft to its Douglas Products Division for finishing work to
ease its overburdened Renton aircraft factory.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said that the Long Beach plant ``can provide
some relief, because we don't have enough people or space for all
the work'' in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle-based union has argued that establishing an
assembly line in California would be the equivalent of
subcontracting work to non-Machinist members.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnson, president of District Lodge 751 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers in
Seattle, was not available for comment Thursday but a union
spokesman said talks with the company are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Another meeting between the union and Boeing officials is set
for next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If a 737 assembly line were established in California, it would
focus on final assembly of airplanes such as the Boeing Business
Jet and the cargo version of the jet, which have significantly
different configurations from the next-generation 737s ordered by
airline customers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing would consider doing assembly work on the
737-900 model in Long Beach and possibly other versions of the
next-generation airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the decision, Boeing officials have said the
Renton factory will still be used as the primary final assembly
location for 737 and 757 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   If the company goes ahead with a new production line in Long
Beach, it would be the first time Boeing has established commercial
aircraft final-assembly operations outside the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited the Long Beach factory when it acquired
McDonnell Douglas last year.
</P>
<P>
   California politicians, including Gov. Pete Wilson, have been
lobbying hard for Boeing to save aerospace jobs in that state after
the company announced earlier this year that it would consolidate
its space operations in Southern California and end production of
three McDonnell Douglas jets now made at the Long Beach plant.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 Boeing jobs in Southern California could be lost
as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The California Trade and Commerce Agency has been quietly
working behind the scenes with Boeing on a multimillion-dollar
package of economic incentives to encourage the Seattle-based
aerospace giant to permanently shift some 737 work from Renton to
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the agency declined to discuss details of the
package.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Mayor Beverly O'Neill said her city, Boeing and the
state are still discussing the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to find every incentive we are qualified for to
make sure we have a package they (Boeing) like. But it's still be
discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she could not comment on details of the package.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Beach plant is located in one of the state's so-called
``enterprise zones,'' and Boeing would be eligible for significant
tax breaks if it established a new assembly line there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, our enterprise zone program is one of our most
powerful economic tools,'' said Jerry Miller, deputy city manager
in Long Beach who until recently headed the city's Economic
Development Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been part of the on-going discussions between Boeing
and the state over the package of economic incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at liberty to say much about the package,'' he said
Thursday. ``It's fair to say, though, that Long Beach has been very
much involved, as has the state of California.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic incentive package would be in addition to the tax
breaks now available to Boeing in the enterprise zone. Boeing is
the largest of some 10,000 companies located within the zone. They
are all eligible for state tax credits on purchases of eligible
manufacturing equipment, as well as tax credits for hiring new
workers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Boeing can get a state tax credit on 100 percent of
the 8.5 percent California sales tax paid on up to $20 million of
the eligible manufacturing equipment purchased each year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said it could cost Boeing as much as $1 billion in
tooling to start a 737 production line in Long Beach. Boeing has
refused to say what those tooling costs might be.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also gets a tax credit in the enterprise zone of $26,910
over a five-year period for every new worker its hires at its Long
Beach plant. The workers must be full-time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how many workers would be needed for the 737 work
in Long Beach, but Boeing spokesman Thom estimated 400 to 500.
</P>
<P>
   Kedrick Legg, president of the local unit of the United
Aerospace Workers, said be believes a new 737 line would save most
of the union jobs Boeing plans to eliminate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
