r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-07 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEMORY OF A MAN YOU NEVER MET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The pallbearers rolled the deep blue casket in slowly.
Every sniffle in the Lincoln Ward building, every sob, was muted by
the sound of one softly squeaking wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Allred's survivors followed a step behind, shuffling two
abreast, holding hands, wringing tissues. They passed by so
closely, you could breathe in the women's perfume, hear the
slap-slap of a little boy's new black shoes. Allred's wife, his
seven sons and daughters, took their seats in the center pews.
</P>
<P>
   The organ music quit. Every sound on Earth seemed to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Allred died at age 38 Monday morning, an hour before
sunrise. He was headed south on the Loop 101, approaching the
Southern Avenue overpass. His Ford van swerved hard left; he hit
the concrete median at freeway speed.
</P>
<P>
   Police, kin, friends all share the same theory as to the
accident's cause: Allred, they agree, fell asleep at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   To all who knew him, this does not surprise. At 4:30 a.m., the
Scoutmaster and Sunday school teacher died delivering the
``Tribune`` newspaper. Just one job out of Allred's four.
</P>
<P>
   Accountant in the family firm and for a cousin's construction
business. Distributor of spray vitamins. Paper carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really didn't like delivering the newspaper,'' said Steve's
uncle, CharlesAllred, during the eulogy. ``He liked driving around
in the quiet of the morning. He liked watching the sunrise.''
</P>
<P>
   There, seated in a metal folding chair, in a hushed room washed
by a jelly of light, you can identify totally with a man you never
once met.
</P>
<P>
   In part at least, Steve Allred wanted to get away from the gray
noise.
</P>
<P>
   It surrounds us, this constant buzz. Clinton and Lewinsky. Road
rage. The NBA lockout. MTV. Talk radio. Whitewater. White House.
White vs. Black.
</P>
<P>
   The gray noise never relents, only distracts. The gray noise
comes with its own gravity, a powerful grip. But, on this day, it
can't reach this room full of those who loved Steve Allred.
</P>
<P>
   Their remembrances revolve around the same adjectives:
Hard-working, honest, soft-spoken, stoic, protective, private.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Roberts, Steve's little sister, a small woman in a pink
dress, recalled a brother who would take her along on his dates, to
Big Surf and Sonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve said he was a simple person. But sometimes he was the
most complicated man I ever knew, especially when it came to
reading his mind. You never knew what he was thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   His Uncle Carl spoke of Steve the boy, ordered to go outside and
play: ``He looked at his mother and said, `Then you'll be all
alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not as alone as the two teenagers from his first marriage, Chad
and Lindsey. And not as alone as his wife of 13 years, Elizabeth,
left to mother five kids without the benefit of a life insurance
payoff _ her husband had none.
</P>
<P>
   She purses her lips at the thought of the future, manages the
hint of a smile. She is an Allred; no complaining allowed. Instead,
conversation moves back to Steve.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, I'd just have to say, `Go to bed, it's 9
o'clock.' He had to wake up so early for the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth glances down at Connor, the five-month-old asleep in
her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kind of did it,'' says the new widow of her husband.
``He just did it, never complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us have the knack, the will. Those few find the
importance through the gray noise, find what matters among all that
does not.
</P>
<P>
   Those few pass unnoticed, mostly, because all that doesn't
matter to them still manages to drown them out.
</P>
<P>
   In the cemetery, the pallbearers pulled the casket from a hearse
the white of bone. Music played softly, a prayer was spoken. You
could hear the sniffles, a little's boy's anxious whine.
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Allred's funeral ended, three dozen cars started. An
airplane whooshed overheard. A few radios blared the news. You were
back in the world. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
