<HEADER>
A3607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-785(2TAK     08-07 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-785(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBUCHI PROPOSES TAX CUTS TO SPUR JAPAN'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In his first major policy speech since taking over as
prime minister a week ago, Keizo Obuchi on Friday proposed cuts in
individual and corporate taxes, steps toward deregulating the
economy, cuts in government spending and new public spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am determined to make my utmost effort, at the risk of the
Cabinet's life, to bring the Japanese economy to a recovery path
within a year or two,'' he told Parliament, alluding to newspaper
reports that have described his Cabinet as standing on the edge of
a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   While he spoke forcefully, though, he was mainly just trying to
speed up changes his predecessors had been proposing for some time;
he offered little in the way of shock therapy for Japan's ailing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi plans to serve up a quick cocktail of tax cuts and public
spending to spur the economy. For the long term, his menu is far
less detailed, though he did reiterate an often-heard bias for
Western methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using as a guide the process by which the United States and
some European countries have rebuilt their economies since the
1980s,'' he said, ``I will promote measures for deregulation,
administrative reform, privatization of the public sector and
tax-system reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi may not have much time. ``It seems he wants to engineer a
soft landing of the Japanese economy,'' said Heizo Takenaka, a
professor at Keio University, ``and the basic question is: Is that
possible? I personally feel that some kind of shock therapy is
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   It may well be. When Obuchi took office, the unemployment rate
had just hit yet another high, domestic auto sales were down for
the 16th straight month and the yen had sunk against the dollar.
Manufacturers are cutting production, and even in the midst of
sweltering heat, air conditioner sales are off.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was most specific about taxes. He promised 6 trillion
yen, or roughly $41 billion, in overall tax cuts next year,
effectively making permanent the 4 trillion yen in temporary cuts
that his predecessor, Ryutaro Hashimoto, extended this year.
</P>
<P>
   The individual tax cut is less generous than it seems, since
Hashimoto had already promised an additional 2 trillion yen in
temporary cuts, and those will be superseded.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi pledged to lower the maximum combined local and national
income-tax rate to 50 percent from 65 percent, the first step
toward what he hopes will be a comprehensive overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would lower the corporate tax rate to 40 percent
from 46.3 percent starting in April, bringing it roughly in line
with Western levels.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have long criticized Japan's high taxes for
inhibiting entrepreneurs and forcing dynamic individuals to move to
other countries. ``I paid 200 million yen in taxes last year,''
Takuya Okada, chairman and chief executive of Jusco Ltd., one of
Japan's largest retailers, fumed recently.
</P>
<P>
   And the temporary cuts, which returned just 18,000 yen to him,
``did not really inspire me to spend,'' he said. ``Now, if they cut
my income tax to 50 percent, then I might think about spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Few economists, though, say a tax cut will put the economy on a
path to lasting recovery. ``Tax cuts are necessary because
bankruptcies are increasing and unemployment is spiraling up,''
said Andrew Shipley, an economist at Schroders, but they are ``not
going to start a consumer-led recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   And corporate tax cuts will not necessarily stimulate capital
investment. Only 35 percent to 40 percent of Japanese corporations
pay taxes, and the low cost of capital _ companies can borrow at
around 1 percent _ offsets the tax burden for those companies doing
well enough to have to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   While economists welcome a corporate cut, many say the tax
structure itself is in need of a fix. ``Companies now get tax
breaks for certain types of investment that made sense a long time
ago but, given changes in technology and the economy, now make no
sense,'' said Jeffrey Young, chief economist at Salomon Smith
Barney in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   And voters want something that makes sense. The ruling Liberal
Democratic Party lost control of the Upper House of Parliament when
voters turned out in unexpected droves on June 12 to vent their
anger.
</P>
<P>
   That loss threatens to stall the passage of legislation to
revamp the debt-ridden banking system, and foreign investors will
continue to punish the stock market and the yen until they see
evidence of real change.
</P>
<P>
   Popularity ratings for Obuchi and his Cabinet are so low that
commentators see a bright side: They probably can't get any worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best we can hope for even in a year's time is that he can
stabilize the situation,'' Young said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though his words left lingering doubts about any eye-catching
banking overhaul, Obuchi was at his most eloquent when speaking
about the financial sector, likening it to the heart that is
responsible for circulating blood _ or, in this case, money _ to
the rest of the body, or society.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference after the speech, Akitaka Saiki, Obuchi's
deputy press secretary, was asked about whether the prime minister
would allow insolvent banks to fail. Foreign investors are all but
baying for a bank failure as a sign that the government is serious
about cleaning up the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to save bad banks,'' Saiki said. ``They need
to take responsibility for their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi offered few specifics, but he did say he would try to
push through measures that would cut the government payroll by 20
percent over the next decade and cut government costs by 30
percent, both ideas that have been pushed for years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the tax cuts, he plans to pay for them by issuing deficit
bonds, a financing technique all but prohibited by last year's
Fiscal Structural Reform Act. That law severely limited Hashimoto's
ability to maneuver when the economy started sliding toward
recession late last fall, and the prime minister said Friday that
he would submit legislation in the fall to suspend that law.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed a supplemental spending budget of 10 trillion
yen, or about $69 billion. That will come on top of a 16 trillion
yen package put together in the spring by Hashimoto, meaning that
Japan will spend more than 4 percent of its gross domestic product
this year trying to get its economy going again with public works
projects. ``This is an amazingly big set of packages by any
standards,'' Takenaka said.
</P>
<P>
   Saiki, the prime minister's spokesman, said Obuchi intends to
spend this money somewhat differently from the way such budgets
have been spent in the past, when they largely went to building
bridges, transportation facilities and roadways that kept the
politically loyal and labor-intensive construction industry afloat
when the bubble economy started losing air.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, he added, wants a bigger portion of the new supplemental
budget spent on ``industries of the future,'' like medicine and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Those industries are considered the best hope for putting a plug
in rising unemployment _ a source of continuing discomfort for
politicians, who consider it a ticking time bomb that could blast
them out of office.
</P>
<P>
   But economists see higher unemployment as painful but necessary,
for it means companies are trying to increase productivity and
profitability, which makes them more competitive globally.
</P>
<P>
   And even Saiki said that if deregulation proceeds, Japan may
face more unemployment in the short term. ``The structure of the
economy has to be changed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
