<HEADER>
A3631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-GINZBURG-NYT &LR;      08-07 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-GINZBURG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE JOURNAL: A DISSIDENT IN THE `FREE' WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Communist bureaucracy made Alexander Ginzburg stateless
during the Cold War. French bureaucracy would have left him
stateless now if he had not raised his voice in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg knows something about protest. As a poet and outspoken
supporter of human rights in the Soviet Union, he was in prison for
much of the 1960s and 1970s. He was freed and flown to the United
States with four other imprisoned dissidents in 1979 in an exchange
for two convicted Soviet spies.
</P>
<P>
   The swap left him with freedom but ``indeterminate
nationality,'' as the French travel document he must use instead of
a passport describes it.
</P>
<P>
   Since he has lived and worked in France for most of the last two
decades, he finally applied for French citizenship three years ago.
But when the decision finally came, in a letter dated June 17, it
was, as he puts it, ``a resounding `nyet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand and speak French only indifferently and can
neither read nor write it,'' said the letter, signed by the
subdirector for naturalization in the Directorate of Population and
Migration of the Ministry of Employment and Solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   That title might have come from Gogol's satire on the Russian
bureaucracy, ``The government inspector,'' prominently displayed in
Ginzburg's library, but the subdirector's letter was no joke.
``Under these circumstances, you cannot be considered assimilated
into the French community,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ginzburg, 62 and short of breath after a bout with cancer
that left him with only one lung, has not lost his combativeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact that I don't speak French well at all,'' he said,
in Russian, in his sixth-floor apartment near the Gare de Lyons.
``But it's also a fact that nobody ever gave me an examination that
would justify such a finding.''
</P>
<P>
   France, like the United States, prides itself on two centuries
of devotion to republican ideals of freedom, equality and human
rights. After the Russian Revolution in 1917, it gave shelter to
thousands of ``white Russian'' refugees who opposed the Bolsheviks.
Some survivors of that immigration still cannot speak fluent
French, but they hold French passports.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, though, and it is harder in these days of
double-digit unemployment rates and mass clandestine immigration to
qualify for naturalization in France or anywhere else in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   So, as things stood in June, Ginzburg would not qualify, though
his wife, Irina, and their older son, Alexandre, 25, were granted
citizenship. Alexandre's younger brother, Alexis, 23, grew up in
Paris with him, but he was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have in fact attracted the attention of the police, in
1995, for willful damage to private property (graffiti),'' the
letter to Alexis, also dated June 17, informed him. But it said he
could apply again for citizenship in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paris is one of the world capitals of graffiti art,'' his
father said in exasperation. ``There are art galleries devoted to
it, and four art journals. There are exhibitions from time to time,
and the newspapers treat the artists as celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is offended when the newspapers write about him and
don't reproduce his art. He was painting on his own building when
the police came by, and all they did was ask him to show his papers
_ he never heard another word from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg came to France in 1980, after his release, to take a
job working for the European office of the AFL-CIO, so he could not
apply here for immigration status as a refugee. ``I came here from
New York City, so I wasn't fleeing persecution,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in France to work for a Russian emigre journal,
Russkaya Mysl, or Russian Thought, but he clashed with the editors,
he said, and was dismissed last year. His dismissal, he is
persuaded, was not unconnected to the refusal of his naturalization
request, since the editors are well connected to the French
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But so is Ginzburg, who says he has known President Jacques
Chirac for years. He proudly displayed an invitation to the July 14
Bastille Day garden party at Elysee Palace this year, though he was
not feeling well that day and did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   After news of his plight appeared in the daily Le Figaro and
other French newspapers, he received a handwritten note from the
culture minister, Catherine Trautmann, assuring him that his case
would be rapidly cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleague Martine Aubry,'' the minister of employment and
solidarity, Mrs. Trautmann wrote, ``is personally taking charge of
your difficulty, which we sincerely deplore.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ginzburg said, the police in the precinct where he
had applied for naturalization called and told his wife that he
would soon have his citizenship papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can finally get rid of this green snake,'' he said,
unfolding the accordion-like travel document. ``But they said they
knew nothing about Alexis' application. Me, an old man, they'll
accept, but they turn down a healthy young man who grew up in
France and considers himself French.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes, he said, that the authorities will soon relent and
grant Alexis, too, the citizenship of his adopted country.
</P>
</TEXT>
