<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-07 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ADVANCES TO SEMIFINALS ON A CLOSE CALL AGAINST ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ OK, Rudy T, how satisfying was this one?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were still drinking,'' said Rudy Tomjanovich, who has
been in an alcohol abstention mode for a while now, ``I'd have a
couple of beers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate foreign basketball adventure nightmare. Here
was Rudy's plucky US national team being slapped around by a 15-3
Italy run, unable to get a call and perilously close to being sent
home without even the opportunity to get a medal in the World
Basketball Championships. The indignity of a US team playing for
fifth instead of sixth, or perhaps even seventh instead of eighth,
was unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   But sing no sad songs. If Rudy T wasn't hoisting them at an
Athenian tavern, be assured some American was. For after falling
behind by a 7-point margin that felt at the time like 27, the US
finished off the game with a dramatic 14-4 run in 4:57 to defeat
Italy, 80-77, and move into a semifinal matchup Saturday against
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The story gets better every day. It is almost impossible to
exaggerate the magnitude of what Rudy and his staff are trying to
do against professional teams that know each other intimately. ``If
the USA wins this,'' said Lithuiania assistant Donn Nelson, ``it
will be a minor miracle. Rudy would have to be Coach of the
Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of basketball to be played before that happens,
but at least the Americans will be playing in games that really
matter, and there were many people both here and back where all you
fine folks are who doubted they'd even get this far.''
</P>
<P>
   I know this much: Not many people ever dreamed that one of the
key players on the team would be Kiwane Garris.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: If this kid had missed the bus or gotten food
poisoning, the US would now be looking at a morning consolation
game against Lithuania. Garris, the 6-foot-1-inch guard from
Illinois who spent most of last season in the CBA, played the final
seven minutes as a shooting guard alongside starting point Michael
Hawkins (himself a huge contributor) and made some big plays.
Really big.
</P>
<P>
   Included among them was a 3-pointer that got the aforementioned
7-point deficit to 4 at 73-69 (4:44); a 12-foot banker (75-71); two
free throws (75-75 at 3:10); a key defensive rebound at 2.9
seconds; and finally, a free throw to create the final score.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T is a fearless coach who will make any adjustment he feels
is necessary, and he is having fun _ when he isn't courting a heart
attack. He was a totally animated sideline presence in the second
half. You'd almost swear he was back in the Summit for a Rockets
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotions are the same,'' he admitted. ``I'm attached to
these guys. I was really into the game, running around, jumping all
over the place. But you have to love 'em. They're a bunch of
hardworking guys, although there were times we didn't look very
good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T knew his team was in trouble when it got off to an 11-2
lead. You want a good start, but you don't want too good a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too easy,'' he pointed out. ``Then they start thinking
it's another Australia (against which the US was up by 30), and you
know the other guys are going to come roaring back.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy had played the US tough in an exhibition two weeks ago and
clearly had no respect for Rudy's Off-Broadway team. The most
athletically disrespectful player of them all was 6-2 Jamaican-born
guard Carlton Myers, who showed any Americans who didn't already
know why he is a star for Teamsystem Bologna in the Italian League.
Myers tortured the US for 32 points and was particularly adept at
worming his way to the foul line, where he was a gaudy 15 for 15.
</P>
<P>
   After going to the hoop for what turned out to be Italy's final
basket at 7:21, Myers went to the line five more times, once for
three shots on an ill-advised Garris foul (did anyone say the kid
was perfect?). He was a European maestro playing the European game
in a European arena in a European atmosphere, and for a long while,
it appeared he would be good enough to defeat the Americans all by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of Myers repeatedly stepping to the line for a pair of
swishes was starting to aggravate Rudy T, so much so that during
each stoppage of play, he kept yelling one thing at his players:
``Let's see if the guy can make a shot! Stop putting him on the
line!.''
</P>
<P>
   He did miss a couple in crunch time, but one was enough to age
Rudy by a couple of years. That would be a heart-stopping
in-and-out 3-pointer with the US leading, 79-77. Myers launched it
from a good 5 feet behind the arc, and it looked awfully good
before it finally popped out and Garris grabbed the rebound with
2.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The US needed both stops and points to pull this out, and it got
the latter from such reliables as Hawkins, who crammed all 16 of
his points into the second half and gave the US the lead (77-75)
with a banked runner at the 41.4-second juncture, and from the icy
veteran Wendell Alexis, whose two free throws broke the last tie
with 25.7 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, Rudy &AMP; Co. would have at least a full day to recover
and perpare. Not here. It's off to the videotape, because the only
Russians Rudy knows are the Black ones, and as you've already been
informed, Rudy isn't drinking _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBINGS-CLINTON-0808     08-07 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBINGS-CLINTON-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON VOWS TO CATCH BOMBERS 'NO MATTER HOW LONG IT TAKES'
 &HT;    With BOMBINGS-ANALYSIS-0808.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Assailing the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in
eastern Africa on Friday as ''cowardly attacks,'' President Clinton
sent emergency medical and disaster teams to the region and vowed
to cast a global dragnet to try to bring the perpetrators to
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the difficulty of countering anti-American
terrorists, however, Clinton also ordered heightened security at
the 260 U.S. embassies and missions around the world and sought to
reassure the thousands of foreign service officers who are
stationed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''These acts of terrorist violence are abhorrent. They are
inhuman,'' a solemn Clinton said during a Rose Garden event marking
a worker education initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will use all the means at our disposal to bring those
responsible to justice, no matter what or how long it takes,''
Clinton pledged. ''We are determined to get answers and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   American flags were lowered to half-mast around the capital --
and at U.S. facilities around the world -- to mourn the eight
Americans confirmed killed by a powerful bomb at the embassy in
Nairobi, Kenya, and the State Department said six more U.S. foreign
service officers were missing and 14 were hospitalized by late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A second bomb exploded at the American embassy in the Tanzanian
capital of Dar es Salaam within minutes of the Nairobi attack. No
Americans were confirmed killed in that attack, though at least
five Tanzanians, including three guards and two embassy employees,
were reported dead by late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, officials said the terrorist bombs killed at least
81 people, injuring more than 1,700 and turning buildings into
mountains of shattered concrete where crowds crawled over looking
for victims, calling out and waving their arms for help to pull
bodies from the wreckage and free trapped people crying for help.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon moved quickly to mobilize emergency assistance,
flying a C-141 cargo plane loaded with medical supplies, personnel
and other gear to the region from a U.S. Air Force Base in Germany.
A second C-141 took off from Andrews Air Force Base, outside of
Washington, ferrying additional supplies and staff; while still
more aircraft were scheduled too fly into the region from elsewhere
in Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright cut short a vacation
in Italy to return for an immediate meeting with Clinton on the
matter and to help manage a State Department task force set up to
help deal with the fallout from the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of yet there has been no claim of responsibility for these
dastardly and cowardly acts of apparent terrorism,'' Albright said
before leaving Rome, vowing that ''the United States will spare no
effort, and use all means at our disposal, to track down and punish
the perpetrators of these outrageous acts.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city that has been consumed this week by midsummer partisan
bickering and distracted by escalating developments in the
investigation of Clinton's relationship with former intern Monica
Lewinsky, the president's political foes set those matters aside to
rally around themes of national unity amid shared trauma.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a week that has seen Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
renege on a U.N.-brokered weapons control regime that averted U.S.
airstrikes earlier this year, House Speaker Newt Gingrich warned
that the nation stands as one against attacks on the country or
threats against American interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one anywhere in the world should doubt that when you
challenge the United States of America and you kill those who serve
the American people, that there is no partisan argument, there is
no scandal, there is no distraction, there is nothing which
prevents us from coming together as a people and doing what we have
to do to protect our own,'' said Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one anywhere should think that the United States is weak
because it is free, should think the United States is timid because
it occasionally has family arguments,'' Gingrich told reporters at
a Capitol press conference. ''When we are challenged, we unite as
one country, without any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday, there were more questions than answers in
Washington about the shocking strikes against American missions
half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   Although no group immediately came forth with a credible claim
of responsibility for the bombings, Undersecretary of State Thomas
Pickering told reporters that investigators presume they were
linked.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time that we have had two such coordinated
explosions,'' the career diplomat said. ''It obviously required
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   House International Relations Committee Chairman Benjamin
Gilman, whose position conveys access to classified intelligence,
said he knew of no organization indigenous to eastern Africa
regarded as a serious terrorist threat -- adding that he suspects
the bombers represented some non-African group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both of those nations do not have any history of political
terrorism or even dissent, so it appears highly unlikely that these
outrages were perpetrated by any local organization,'' said Gilman,
R-N.Y. ''So we have to look further, apparently, than the local
people. We don't know yet who is truly responsible for these
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering declined to specify the measures ordered to shore up
security at U.S. missions abroad in the wake of Friday's attacks.
He said, though, that the bombings were a tragic reminder of the
danger American diplomats face day-in and day-out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get some 30,000 threats a year,'' against U.S. diplomatic
facilities around the world, Pickering said. ''We treat them all as
extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
