<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$A     08-07 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An August Storm &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was as though a gale hit Wall Street on Tuesday, blowing
stocks loose from their moorings. The Dow Jones industrial average
plunged 299.43 points, or 3.41 percent, to 8,487.31, and other
market gauges were down even more sharply.
</P>
<P>
   No one factor caused the havoc that left traders like one on the
floor of the New York Stock Exchange, left, in despair. The Asian
economic crisis was cited, as were stunted growth in corporate
earnings and even the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, a little calm had returned as some of the
most-damaged sectors _ small-capitalization stocks and technology _
helped lead the market higher. The Dow industrials ended the week
at 8,598.29, still down 285.27 for the week. One sector that
appears thoroughly battered is new issues; the year is shaping up
as the worst since 1990 for initial public offerings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Longer Sizzling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Economic indicators painted a far less robust picture than they
had earlier in the year. The Conference Board reported that its
Index of Leading Economic Indicators slipped in June, as it had in
May. It stood at 105, down 0.2 percent from May. ``It doesn't mean
bad times for the U.S. economy, but we've seen the best,'' said
Allen Sinai, chief global economist at Primark Decision Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Federal Reserve said in releasing its beige book
that although the economy was healthy, growth showed signs of
slowing as exports to Asia slumped. Personal incomes rose a scant
0.2 percent in June. The nation's unemployment rate held steady at
4.5 percent and wage growth eased in July. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH CARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hemorrhaging Red Ink &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Managed care, manage thyself, investors might well say. United
Healthcare, one of the nation's largest health maintenance
organizations, said it would take a $900 million charge in its
second quarter, in part to abandon unprofitable Medicare plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to forget that Medicare was created because
private insurers could not make money on the elderly population,''
said Diane Archer, executive director of the Medicare Rights
Center, a consumer organization in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Following the debacle at Oxford Health Plans, another managed
care concern, the move sparked an investor stampede out of health
care stocks and possibly jeopardized United Healthcare's proposed
$5.5 billion merger with its rival, Humana Inc., which would create
the nation's largest HMO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Streamlining GM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, the world's largest auto maker, said it would
build a new generation of highly efficient assembly plants in North
America. To the dismay of the United Automobile Workers, which
effectively shut down GM with eight-week strikes against two parts
facilities, the new plants could use as little as half the number
of workers currently employed at GM assembly plants, like the one
in Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   Outside suppliers, many with nonunion workers, would do much of
the work. GM, which reported that sales fell 38 percent in July,
also announced a sweeping reorganization of its internal
distribution structure that is expected to save $200 million to
$300 million a year and eliminate as many as 1,000 white-collar
jobs, and said it would spin off Delphi Automotive Systems, its
parts unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reported a 4.3 percent slide in domestic car and truck
sales for July, and Chrysler registered a 3 percent gain. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less Than Sunny &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, the appliance maker, said it would restate last year's
financial statements, resulting in a ``material adjustment,'' and
possibly the results for 1996 and the first quarter of this year,
too, because of possible accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst estimated that the adjustment would be $25 million
to $50 million. The stock slid $1, to a new low of $7 on Thursday.
The disclosure followed an announcement that Sunbeam and Albert J.
Dunlap, the former chairman and chief executive ousted by the board
in June, had signed a ``joint cooperation agreement'' to share
various documents related to lawsuits and an investigation into the
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides quickly began bickering about what they had
agreed on. Still, one thing went right for the company: the
American Medical Association agreed to pay Sunbeam $9.9 million for
backing out of a deal to endorse the company's humidifiers, blood
pressure monitors and other products. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNET &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Frontier for Business &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A century and a half ago, when Americans pushed back the Western
frontier, they panned for gold. Well, so far, this century's
frontier, the Internet, has not proved itself a gold mine. But
business is trying. Amazon.com, showing that its aspirations extend
to selling far more than books over the Internet, bought the
Junglee Corp., which operates a service that lets people shop on
line for everything from clothing to computers, and Planet All,
which operates a vast Internet address service.
</P>
<P>
   And Agency.com agreed to acquire Eagle River Interactive. The
Omnicom Group will own just under half the combined company, which
will be the Internet's largest ad agency. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEALS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal's Bid &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal, a maker of aerospace and automotive products,
announced a $9.8 billion unsolicited offer for AMP Inc., which said
it would review the offer. ... Albertson's Inc. said it would
acquire American Stores for $8.3 billion in stock, in a deal that
would create the nation's largest supermarket chain. ... Eastman
Kodak agreed to buy the Imation Corp.'s medical imaging business
for $520 million in cash. The move shows that Kodak, after
shrinking operations and its work force earlier this year, is now
rebuilding.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Setback for Microsoft &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered Microsoft to turn over to the government
the source code for its operating systems, Windows 95 and Windows
98, and to make its chairman, William H. Gates, and 16 other
executives available for pretrial depositions taking as long as the
Justice Department deemed necessary to prepare for a Sept. 8 trial
in the government's antitrust suit against the company. ... A
vulnerability was discovered in Eudora, the most widely used e-mail
software, just days after a serious security flaw was found in two
rival electronic-mail programs.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws would permit an attacker to destroy or steal data or
tamper with a personal computer, although no incidents have been
reported.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT UNIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victory From Defeat &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bankers were cheering five months ago when the Supreme Court
ruled that the nation's laws did not permit credit unions to
include more than one occupational group in their memberships. But
credit unions had the last laugh. Congress passed a measure to
permit them to expand their memberships, and President Clinton said
that he would sign it, even though it does not require credit
unions to abide by fair-lending rules that banks must follow.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonse M. D'Amato, the New York Republican who heads the Senate
Banking Committee &UR; , &LR;  said of the credit unions, ``We need them in
these days of consolidation and mega-mergers to serve the little
guys.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARCHER DANIELS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Secret Videotape &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after government raids disclosed the
existence of a huge investigation, prosecutors played a secret
videotape to a federal jury in Chicago that is hearing a criminal
price-fixing case against former executives of Archer Daniels
Midland.
</P>
<P>
   In one episode, Michael D. Andreas, of Archer Daniels met with
Ikeda Hirokazu, of the Ajinimoto Co. of Japan, with which the
government contends Archer Daniels conspired to fix prices of a
feed additive, and Mark Whitacre, an Archer executive and secret
government informer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3649 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-watch-PA     08-07 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, Aug. 7 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the
last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, July 31, the Senate approved, 97-2, a $252 billion
defense spending bill. The bill allows $1.9 billion for U.S. forces
in Bosnia. The Senate rejected a measure to pressure the
administration into withdrawing the troops. Supporters said the
funds will provide resources and flexibility for soldiers in Bosnia
to meet the challenges of living conditions and family separation.
Nobody took the Senate floor to oppose the bill. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: LEGAL
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday voted, 255-170, to provide $250 million for
legal aid next year. The Legal Services Corp., which provides this
service for the poor, received $283 million in funding this year.
Supporters said legal aid is an essential service for those who
could not otherwise afford legal counseling. Opponents said the
organization pursues an activist, ideological agenda. A ``yes''
vote would approve the funding.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: CENSUS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday rejected, 201-227, an amendment to the
Commerce, State, Justice and judiciary spending bill that would
have allotted full funding for the Census Bureau for next year.
Supporters of the amendment said the bureau needs the full funding
to fulfill the Clinton Administration's plan to combine statistical
sampling with the traditional head count in order to account for
people, mostly minorities, that are often overlooked. Opponents
argued that sampling could distort counts and it could enable
politicians to fix numbers to meet their own political needs. A
``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: PROSECUTE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday rejected, 82-345, an amendment to strike
a provision in the Commerce, State, Justice and judiciary spending
bill designed to protect citizens from unfair prosecutions by
setting up a Misconduct Review board for unethical prosecutors.
Supporters said the provision was too restrictive on prosecutors
and not an integral part of the spending bill. Opponents said
Americans need a method for fighting back when treated unfairly by
prosecutors. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: GAYRIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday rejected, 176-252, an amendment to the
Commerce, State, Justice and judiciary spending bill that would
have revoked President Clinton's ability to prohibit discrimination
against gays in the federal workplace. Supporters said it was
unfair for Clinton to be able to give special breaks to special
interests. Opponents said taking away Clinton's ability would have
legitimized government-sponsored discrimination. A ``yes'' vote
favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 252-179, a bill that would reform
the campaign finance system. The measure would ban the unlimited,
unregulated ``soft money'' contributions to political parties,
impose restrictions on issue advertisements mentioning a
candidate's name and increase disclosure requirements. Supporters
said the campaign finance problems stemming from 1996 show that the
system is corrupt and needs an overhaul. Opponents said the bill
infringed on free speech rights guaranteed under the First
Amendment. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- --- ---
