<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX     08-07 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug.
8, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Lou
Hudson, Carmelita Bevill or Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's
National/Foreign Desk at (817) 390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARALYZED BY PAINT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I was a woman living in fear. For five years, I was
afraid to paint the white walls in my all-too-vanilla home. It was
our first house, and I clung to renter mentality. We would have to
sell the home someday, and experts say buyers prefer plain walls
that allow them to better visualize their own decorating tastes.
But what about my decorating tastes? The truth is, I didn't know
whether I had any and was too cheap to pay someone who did. I
wanted to be bolder, but I was drowning in doubts. By KATHRYN
HOPPER. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. (Accompanied
by PAINT-CUES ON HUES.) &QL; 
