early films, Hartley's characters often spoke in a clipped, deadpan
style, as if they were rehearsing for a postmodern ``Dragnet.'' So
when people start calling his latest film, ``Henry Fool,'' his most
``accessible,'' it's a relative term. It may be the most mainstream
thing Hartley has ever done, but nobody's going to confuse it with
