<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBLESS-RATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY SHRUGS OFF GM STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate held firm at 4.5 percent in July
despite a strike by workers at General Motors Corp. which cost the
nation its biggest monthly job loss in nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Labor reported Friday that the US economy,
which has slowed dramatically in recent months, created only 66,000
new jobs in July. Although that is well below the pace of job
growth in the three prior months, enough new jobs were created to
leave the jobless rate unchanged from a seasonally adjusted June
rate of 4.5 percent and just above the 28-year low of 4.3 percent
reached in May.
</P>
<P>
   The job losses were made up especially in the booming retail and
housing industries.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs report is ``very encouraging,'' said Lawrence Horwitz,
an economist with Primark Decision Economics, a Boston consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Economists had braced for much worse news in the labor market
amid lower corporate profits and sporadic layoffs, a meltdown by
Asian trading partners, and a new government estimate that economic
growth slowed dramatically in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the pace of job growth was about right for easing fears
on Wall Street that a tighter labor market could cause inflation to
rear its head and force the Federal Reserve Board to react by
raising interest rates. Wages, a key concern at the Fed, also rose
at a slower pace last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is still locked on hold,'' William Dudley, chief US
economist for Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York. ``This report isn't
strong enough or weak to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street remained settled Friday after a riotous week. The
Dow Jones stock market index closed up 20.34 points at 8,598.02.
For the week, the blue chip average finished down 285 points and
failed to recover from Tuesday's 299-point slide.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's small gain hid broad market strength. Advancing issues
outnumbered declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange by
about a 2-1 margin on volume of about 760 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nation's ability to withstand the damaging effects
of a 54-day strike at the country's biggest automotive company, the
jobs report contained troubling news.
</P>
<P>
   Most obvious was the fact that the strike cost the nation
111,000 of a steep 176,000 decline in manufacturing jobs last month
_ that is the largest job loss in one month since October 1982. The
company quickly followed up a strike settlement last week with the
United Autoworkers by announcing that there would be plant closings
and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Asia's economic contraction can be seen in the
manufacturing sector. When General Motors is taken out of the
picture, the nation lost 42,000 manufacturing jobs in July,
according to Primark. That accelerated the pace of job losses in
manufacturing in May and in June, which averaged about 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic components, which relies heavily on Asian export
markets, lost jobs, as did the food industry and textile mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really seeing the Asia impact taking a bite out of
manufacturing,'' said Primark's Horwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in manufacturing ``does reflect slower exports and the
struggles that firms are having to keep earnings strong and finding
they have to cut back their labor force in order to save costs,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings were rose 3 cents for the third
consecutive month, to $12.79. That's smaller than the average
monthly increase of 5 cents during the first four months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   There were other positive notes. To handle high summer spending
by consumers, retailers increased employment by 125,000 last month,
including 69,000 jobs at restaurants and bars. Amid high housing
starts and sales, the construction industry added 18,000 jobs last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of 66,000 jobs last month pushed total employment
in the non-farm sector to 125.8 million. Though the jobless rate
was unchanged, the rate for black men jumped from 6.9 percent to
8.9 percent and from a record low of 20.2 percent to 28.6 percent
for black teen-agers of both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment among Hispanics fell from 7.6 percent to 7.2
percent, and for whites, from 4 percent to 3.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
