u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-$ADV9-     08-07 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSSEIN'S ILLNESS HAS JORDANIANS JITTERY ABOUT FUTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 9) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ For days following news that King Hussein had
been diagnosed with cancer, anxious Jordanians flooded downtown
money changers in a rush to trade their country's dinars for more
stable U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, the frantic activity had begun to subside due to a
speech the 62-year-old monarch gave via satellite from the Mayo
Clinic in Rochester, Minn., where he has been receiving treatment
for lymph cancer since July 14. Doctors, he told his jittery
public, were optimistic that they would be able to bring the cancer
under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not over and done with yet,'' he said. ``My cancer is a
new battle I am determined to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the king's speech helped bring calm, many Jordanians
admit they remain worried about the future of one of the Middle
East's most enduring monarchies. The king's illness has rekindled
uncomfortable questions of succession to the Hashemite Crown and
concerns that a close U.S. ally who has been Israel's staunchest
friend in the Middle East may not be able to rule much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jordanians say the idea seems almost unfathomable. For 46
years, King Hussein, born Prince Sharif Hussein and descended from
a family that traces its ancestors to the Prophet Mohammed, has
ruled them with a mixture of benevolence and brutality that has
brought deep respect and left him unquestionably in control.
Three-fourths of his subjects have never lived under another ruler.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is King Hussein,'' said Bassam, a 37-year-old
grocer in the middle-class neighborhood of Medinet al-Riyada. ``We
got used to him. If he's gone, we don't know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments echo from the impoverished Palestinian refugee
camp of Baqa, at the edge of Amman, to the upscale neighborhood of
Abdoun. With a reputation for balancing his impoverished country's
interests with the often conflicting ones of the mightier countries
around him, Jordanians wonder whether anyone else possesses the
finesse to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``People associate Jordan's stability with the personality of
the king, his charisma, his ability to lead,'' said Radwan
Abdallah, a Jordanian political consultant affiliated with Middle
East Consulting, Research and Analysis, a think-tank based in
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think his illness might lead to instability,'' said
Abdallah. ``There are some unknowns that lead people to be a bit
anxious about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts, Jordanian and Israeli alike, say that the kingdom
is stable enough. The king's likeliest successor is his brother,
Crown Prince Hassan, an affable, Oxford-educated intellectual who
has been Hussein's political adviser for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   But some palace watchers predict a struggle between Prince
Hassan and the king's sons. Prince Abdallah, an army general in
charge of the Royal Guards, elite units of paratroopers and
military intelligence, and Prince Hamzah, 18, who will attend a
British military academy in the fall, are the two likeliest
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jordanians worry whether their country, which borders
Syria, Iraq and the Israeli-occupied West Bank and which is filled
with Palestinians, would be able to hold on to its territory, its
Hashemite identity, or its current form of government. The glue
that kept those elements in place is the king himself, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great shock for Jordan to lose King Hussein,''
said Abdallah Hassanant,'' editor and political commentator for the
English-language Jordan Times. ``They have great trust in him that
after each crisis, he will come out with the fewest loses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassanat, like most analysts here, says Jordanians favor a
continuation of the monarchy. Despite a prolonged downturn in the
economy and the king's decision to make peace with Israel, a move
initially welcomed but increasingly unpopular, they think it is the
best way to maintain security and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Palestinians, who by some estimates make up 70
percent of the population, do not enjoy all the rights of native
Jordanians, most also want the monarchy to continue, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Successive waves of Palestinian refugees, granted citizenship
and allowed to integrate, now dominate Jordan's thriving business
class. The wealthy Abdoun neighborhood, for instance, is
overwhelmingly Palestinian, some government ministers are
Palestinians and one segment of the royal family is Palestinian:
King Hussein's third wife _ he divorced the first two and she died
in a plane crash _ was a Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any change in the system will have to come from Jordanians,
not Palestinians,'' said Sari Nasir, a sociologist at the
University of Jordan whose Palestinian family fled from a village
near Tel Aviv during the 1948 war that created the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinians can vote but they are not interested in changing
Jordan into a Palestinian entity,'' he said. ``That will never
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts say it is unlikely Jordanians will press for change
either, even though much of the loyalty coming from both
Palestinians and Jordanian Bedouin tribes is to the king himself.
Crown Prince Hassan, they say, has not built such close ties with
these groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the Islamists are very much loyal to the king,'' said the
University of Jordan's Abdallah. ``They are not very radical. They
are affiliated with the political system.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge is likely to come from within the royal
family itself. Already, dynastic rivalries have surfaced, pitting
Prince Hassan against the king's sons, say palace watchers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jordan's constitution, the crown should go to the
king's first-born son, Abdallah, 36. But he was born to an
Englishwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, that idea did not sit well with the
anti-colonial sentiment rife among Jordanians still shaking off bad
memories of British rule here. Bowing to public sentiment, Hussein
agreed to amend the constitution and named Prince Hassan as his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that that 1965 constitutional amendment might
lead to royal friction came in 1992, when Hussein was first
diagnosed with cancer. Then, he suggested creating a Hashemite
council responsible for electing his successor _ either his brother
or one of his sons. After intense lobbying by Prince Hassan, the
idea was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the king battling his second bout of cancer, the idea
has resurfaced. So has a compromise: Prince Hassan would take the
helm next, but the dynasty would then revert back to Abdallah _
rather than going to Hassan's eldest son, Rashid.
</P>
<P>
   And speculation that the king might name his youngest son,
Hamzah, born to fourth and current wife, Queen Noor, the
American-born Lisa Hallaby, started after the king sent him a
letter on his 18th birthday reminding him that Hussein was king
when he was Hamzah's age. ``It was taken to mean that he is
eligible to sit on the thrown,'' said one Jordanian observer.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli observers worry that whoever does take the helm may
not have the personal charm that has helped Hussein maneuver
through some tough times, both at home and in Jordan's relations
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The king's warmth has endeared him to most Israelis, first when
he spoke at the funeral of slain Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and then when he knelt in from of the grieving family members
of Israeli schoolgirls who were killed by a Jordanian soldier.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts agree that whoever does succeed Hussein will
follow the king's path of peace with Israel, despite its current
impasse with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace with Israel is in the interest of Jordan at this
moment,'' said the Jordan Times' Hassanat. ``Anybody who comes
after the king will follow the same policy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
based in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
