</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-TRAINING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B-2 TRAINING MISSIONS CANCELED BECAUSE OF EJECTION SYSTEM
TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Air Force has suspended the B-2 stealth
bomber's training missions at Whiteman Air Force Base because of
problems with the aircraft's ejection system, the Air Force
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 of the active bombers are based with the 509th Bomb Wing
at Whiteman, 60 miles southeast of Kansas City near Knob Noster,
Mo. The Air Force said the grounding would not hurt the 509th Bomb
Wing's combat capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a real-world conflict, we could put them right
back into service,'' said Maj. Art Haubold, an Air Force spokesman
at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also suspended training for about a week in 1997
when an engine shaft assembly on a bomber broke in a test flight.
</P>
<P>
   The first B-2 entered service at Whiteman in 1993. The warplane
is covered with a special ``skin'' that enables it to absorb or
deflect radar signals and avoid detection.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, regulators have questioned the aircraft's
effectiveness. A report from the General Accounting Office in June
raised doubts about the bomber's ability to detect radar and avoid
detection. An earlier report questioned the aircraft's
effectiveness in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's manufacturer, Northrop Grumman, discovered the
problems with the ejection system in testing at its B-2 plant in
Palmdale, Calif. Haubold said the problem was with the initiators,
which control when the plane's hatch opens and when the crew is
ejected.
</P>
<P>
   The eight initiators on each aircraft will be replaced at
Whiteman and in California. Each aircraft will resume peacetime
training as soon as replacement parts are installed and inspections
are complete. Air Force officials offered no timetable for the
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they consider this to be a long-term process,''
Haubold said. ``This won't be a hard fix to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The huge warplane can drop either nuclear or conventional bombs.
Eleven bombers are under construction, in addition to the 10
already at Whiteman.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of the bombers has flown on a combat mission. But
in April, two of the bat-winged aircraft flew to Guam on a training
exercise, the first long-term overseas deployment of the warplane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
