<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-STITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW US ENVOY TO TANZANIA STILL ON TRACK TO ASSUME POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three weeks ago, Boston's Rev. Charles Stith, the newly
named US ambassador to Tanzania, left with his family for their
annual 21-day vacation to the Caribbean island of Sint Maarten. He
gave his wife, two teenaged children and mother-in-law ``Team
Tanzania'' family briefing books and tapes of Swahili to study
between rounds of golf and romps in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the day before the family was to return to Boston and a
month before they expect to move to Africa, the Stiths awoke to the
news that the US embassy in the Tanzanian port city of Dar es
Salaam had been the target of a terrorist bomb. Stith gathered the
family to pray for the victims of the attacks in Dar es Salaam and
Nairobi, and he made plans to fly to Washington Sunday morning to
meet with State Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I were there right now,'' Stith, 48, said in a
telephone interview. ``That's the post I've been selected to lead.
In a time of crisis a leader wants to be present. That's not to say
folks aren't handling this in a professional and competent manner.
I wish I were there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith got a call from the State Deparment around 6:30 Friday
morning. Half an hour later, Stith's nephew from Atlanta called and
the rest of the family arose and followed events in Africa on Cable
News Network for the rest of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just shocking that something this devastating and brutal
and cowardly would happen in any context,'' Stith said. ``Obviously
we're concerned'' for the family's safety. They give you training
around security issues. Something like this brings home the fact
that this stuff is serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith did not believe the bombings would change the family's
plan to leave for Tanzania around September 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little devastated about what's happened,'' said his
wife, Dr. Deborah Prothrow-Stith, an associate dean at Harvard's
School of Public Health, who plans to travel between Boston and Dar
es Salaam. ``It raises some concerns obviously about issues of
safety. We haven't talked a lot about that. In light of what
happened at the Capitol and Oklahoma City, they are not issues that
would keep us from going but it's concerning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very excited about going and understand this as an
isolated event that's not reflective of the relationship between
the United States and Tanzania.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, the family has relaxed on Sint
Maarten. &UR;  &LR; Sith also spent time concluding business with the
Organization for a New Equality, the civil and economic rights
group he founded and from which he is resigning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The family shopped for lightweight clothes to bring to Africa,
and 16-year-old Mimi, who'll wear a uniform at the international
school in Dar es Salaam, looked for outfits with navy blue bottoms
and white shirts. They read their briefing books. They listened to
Swahili tapes in the car and on the beach and in their two-bedroom
time share condominium. Prothrow-Stith, 44, counted her leg lifts
in Swahili during her aqua aerobics. They laughed when they
discovered that the set of four language tapes came mistakenly
packaged with two in Swedish.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Friday's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, my sister and I looked at each other and said, `Man,
are we going to still be going?' But it almost makes me want to go
more now,'' said 19-year-old Percy, who will take a leave of
absence from Bates College to serve as an assistant to his father.
``Maybe my first natural instinct is to stay away from harm's way,
but when I thought about it, I thought this is a freak thing. It's
tragic, but it definitely doesn't change my feelings about wanting
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at a picture (on television) now,'' he said. ``It
hurts a lot to see something like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
