<HEADLINE>
POSTAL SERVICE TO OPEN TELEPHONE INFORMATION CENTER IN MALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ The U.S. Postal Service will create about
1,100 new jobs in Kansas City, Kan., by opening a telephone
information center inside the beleaguered Indian Springs
Marketplace, which has been losing tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Postal officials on Thursday announced a nearly $68 million
contract with a Denver company to operate the second of six planned
National Service Centers. The Kansas City, Kan., one should be in
the former Dillard's department store space by December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said Rene Brunetti, who manages his father's
Italian Delight restaurant, which has seen good times and bad over
22 years at the mall entrance. ``Oh gosh, this will help
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Unified Government of Wyandotte County and
Kansas City, Kan., also were elated at the announcement, which they
have hoped was coming for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only a great opportunity for our citizens but also a
shot in the arm for the Indian Springs Marketplace,'' said Mayor
Carol Marinovich. ``Hopefully, this will be the attraction for new
retail opportunities at Indian Springs.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jobs are expected to pay in the range of $8 an hour
plus benefits with on-site child care, said Don Denney, spokesman
for the Unified Government.
</P>
<P>
   The service center will be operated by TeleTech Facilities
Management Inc., which also operates a service center in Denver.
Company officials could not be reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Unified Government Commissioner Tom Bruns, whose district
includes Indian Springs, said Kansas City, Kan., had been competing
with another area city for the service center. He would not name
the other city.
</P>
<P>
   Bruns said Kansas City, Kan., did not offer a financial package
to entice TeleTech. But the Kansas Department of Commerce and
Housing will provide funds for job training as well as tax credits
for the new center, said department spokesman Matt Brisch. Details
will be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the service center will answer postal-related
questions around the clock on toll-free lines for customers in 13
central states, from Minnesota to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   People who call will be able to speak to actual human beings.
</P>
<P>
   They will provide information on postal rates, ZIP codes, post
office locations and mailing restrictions. If necessary, the
service center can transfer callers to a local post office.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Postal Service will urge all Americans to call
the same toll-free number with postal questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to provide consistent information,'' said
postal spokesman Don Smeraldi. ``When people from time to time call
post offices, the employees there are concentrating on getting the
mail moving and sometimes the questions may not be answered as
quickly as we would like.''
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of people into Indian Springs Marketplace, which is
more than half empty, comes as Stein Mart clothing store prepares
to open an outlet in the former J.C. Penney space. Other tenants at
Indian Springs include Montgomery Ward, Radio Shack and Harold
Pener.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited for the surviving businesses at Indian
Springs,'' said Denney. ``This is certainly a reward for their
patience, and hopefully it will benefit them more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
