A3678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY08-COX     08-07 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMN: Nurturing rain draws audience in celebration
</P>
<P>
   By Lee Mayc. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. -- It had been such a long time. Weeks that
seemed like months had drifted by on waves of punishing heat. With
no rain that I had seen. Such a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   A toll had been taken, of course. Here in the mountains, some of
the less hardy new plants had bitten the dust, literally, joining
it after withering and shriveling. A tiny anise was the most recent
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Atlanta the list was growing, including several ferns, a
new beautyberry, wintergreen, a corkscrew willow. There was no
escape from the heat, the drought. Day after day, night after
night, I sweated and watered, knowing even as I held the hose that
nothing would satisfy like water from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain's the only thing that'll keep 'em alive,'' an elder man
here had agreed as we struck up the inevitable weather
conversation. ``Rain's got minerals in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But we hadn't seen any in such a long time. Even on days and
nights when thunder rolled. Nothing. Dry heaves.
</P>
<P>
   Until that Saturday. I woke up early, hearing, for the first
time in McCaysville, a rooster crowing for day. Through the bedroom
window, looking southwest, I could see the usual, stunningly
beautiful morning mist hanging over the distant ridge, gray-blue.
</P>
<P>
   Toward noon, skies darkened. Clouds sank and, along with a
breeze, drifted toward Fightingtown Creek, toward my ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 2 p.m. I went from the creek side of the cabin to
the road side, where herbs, the rock garden and Big Momma's garden
grow near the door. I knew rain was on the way, and I wanted to see
the plants feel it. I wanted to feel it.
</P>
<P>
   It came. First in a light mist. Then drops, so few that I could
count them as they pattered onto the hydrangea leaves, splattering
in the dust around the four-o'clocks.
</P>
<P>
   The pace quickened, and soon there had been enough drops to
clean the dust from everything _ plants, rocks, the car. Enough
drops to turn the driveway's gravel a slick charcoal tone
everywhere except a car-sized rectangle that remained artemisia
gray.
</P>
<P>
   I had to go out there. As I did, I recalled another rain,
decades earlier, when as a boy soldier in Germany I grabbed a bar
of soap and dashed into a downpour along with other GIs, stripped
naked and lathering happily.
</P>
<P>
   On this day I remained fully clothed, welcoming wet pants,
shirt, shoes. Turning my face into the rain, I let it shower my
forehead, trickle down my chin, through my beard, onto my chest and
back. It was good.
</P>
<P>
   As was the smell of wet red clay and black humus _ sweet, rich,
fecund.
</P>
<P>
   Among the plants, I could feel them embracing the rain,
responding to it as eagerly as I was. The liatris, suffering heat
prostration, stood a bit taller, as did the bee balm and the
rhododendron.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, all the plants seemed to especially enjoy the rain.
On the creek side, I stood face to face with oaks whose suddenly
vibrant leaves held diamond raindrops glittering against creek and
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Butterflies, too, loved this shower. They never stopped dancing,
dashing from buddleia to zinnia, then soaring across treetops,
toward the giving clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon, it was over _ leaving all of us to dry and wonder how
long it would be until next time.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
