<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER OF EMINENT DOMAIN GOES AWRY IN MERRIAM, KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIAM, Kan. _ Merriam's decision to oust a longtime business
owner from his property to make way for a BMW dealership expansion
is a stark reminder of the downside of eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   While this practice is traditionally perceived as government's
power to take private property for public use, it has been many
years since this was strictly the case. There was a time when
government's condemnation powers were used almost exclusively to
expropriate property for a genuinely ``public'' good such as a
roadway or a school. As such, eminent domain was perceived by most
Americans as a sometimes bothersome but nevertheless acceptable
exercise of government power as long as owners were justly
compensated.
</P>
<P>
   As the go-go economy of the postwar era gained momentum,
however, governments increasingly broadened the concept in the name
of promoting economic development. What evolved is a process by
which government now routinely uses its condemnation power to take
private property for private use if public benefit can be credibly
assumed in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more controversial recent uses of eminent domain
locally has been by Kansas City, Kan., and Wyandotte County, Kan.,
to create a site for a proposed speedway. The justification is that
the area badly needs the economic boost a development of this size
could give it.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone buys that claim, of course, but the reason the
initiative has gained enough public acceptance to proceed is
because it's at least a credible claim. While there are no
guarantees the raceway's promise will be fulfilled, the magnitude
of the potential reward is considered big enough to merit the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Merriam's most recent use of eminent domain is quite a different
situation, though, for a couple of reasons. The City Council's
decision seems to turn on the expectation of the car dealership's
capacity to generate substantially more sales tax revenue than
current use generates.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the same thing as using condemnation powers to
encourage a comprehensive development. Rather, it would seem, it's
simply a matter of government using its power to favor one
business's interests over another.
</P>
<P>
   What was missing in the discussion preceding the council's
decision, however, was an adequate explication of how the
additional sales tax revenue would benefit the public. It seems
reasonable to assume a positive trade-off, but such things
shouldn't be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Another troubling aspect of Merriam's move in this regard is how
it offends the sense of community. This isn't a big city where
eco-devo wheeling and dealing is likely to be a more impersonal
affair. It's a relatively small town that should be at least as
concerned with maintaining an atmosphere of neighborliness and
community as it is with economic dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   This is, in fact, a primary reason many Americans prefer small
towns to big cities. Merriam's move, though, overrode the interests
of somebody who's been part of the local business scene and
community for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   While the desire of city leaders to promote Merriam's economic
vitality is understandable, even laudable, there's more to consider
in this case. Government's only legitimate role is as steward of
the broad public interest. While promoting a healthy economic
climate is in the public interest, no business's right to exist
should depend on its ability to generate taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
