<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS08-     08-07 2646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    (EDITORS: MAFIA! IS REVIEWED BY KNIGHT RIDDER. DO NOT USE IF YOU
ARE NOT OWNED OR SUBSCRIBE TO KNIGHT RIDDER)
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel, Steve Murray, and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Reviewer's initials appear at end of review). Grades range from
A to F.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon PG-13
</P>
<P>
   The world, interpreted as a video game. While ``Deep Impact''
treated a similar let's-save-Earth story with sobriety,
``Armageddon'' never lets the threat of global annihilation get in
the way of fun. It's a space-cowboy movie, with Bruce Willis and
Ben Affleck saving the world for Liv Tyler. As a summer popcorn
movie, it's more enjoyable than that big-lizard flick ``Godzilla.''
And you'll see the reported $165 million budget onscreen in the
impressive effects and mammoth sets. But is the movie good for you?
Probably not. Rated PG-13 for sci-fi disaster action, implied sex
and profanity. 2 hours, 24 minutes. (SM) Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   BASEketball R
</P>
<P>
   Thank heaven for the rude boys of summer. In the wake of the
Farrelly Brothers and ``There's Something About Mary,'' here come
``South Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone in another
zesty, disgusting, laugh-out-loud comedy. Parker and Stone play two
slackers who invent a hybrid of baseball and basketball that
becomes a national sport. The movie manages to be racist, sexist,
homophobic and just about everything else. But it does so in a way
that kiddingly tweaks the very notion of political correctness.
Rated R for profanity, gross-out humor. 1 hour, 43 minutes. (SM)
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo 66 NR
</P>
<P>
   Don't shuffle off to this ``Buffalo.'' Former Calvin Klein
underwear model Vincent Gallo wrote, directed and stars in this
uneven fable about an ex-con who kidnaps a voluptuous teen
(Christina Ricci) to pose as his wife while he visits his parents
(Ben Gazzara and Anjelica Huston). The first half is amusingly
bonkers, thanks to the cast, but overall, the film is all over the
place _ self-pitying and sardonic, arty and maudlin. Not rated but
includes strong language, graphic violence and nudity. 1 hour, 46
minutes. (ER) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Can't Hardly Wait PG-13
</P>
<P>
   You won't want to wait . . . for the movie to end. This teen
comedy about an end-of-the-school-year all-night party shirks
subtlety whenever a broad stroke will get us there faster. Jennifer
Love Hewitt plays Amanda, the goddess of the just-graduated senior
class. Ethan Embry is the sweet, sensitive guy who, the movie tries
to convince us, deserves to be her boyfriend. Rated PG-13 for
profanity, simulated sex, drug and alcohol use. 1 hour, 38 minutes.
(SM) Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Clockwatchers PG-13
</P>
<P>
   In this wicked take on workplace hell, four temps (Toni
Collette, Lisa Kudrow, Alanna Ubach, Parker Posey) bond over Happy
Hour wings and shared grievances about working in a place rife with
petty politics and ubiquitous Muzak. Fledgling filmmaker Jill
Sprecher has some plot problems, but when she sticks to the subtle
nuances of the typical dysfunctional corporate ``family,'' she's
dead-on. So's her cast, especially Posey as a born rebel who keeps
herself sane by minor acts of sabotage. Rated PG-13 for language. 1
hour, 36 minutes. (ER)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Deep Impact PG-13
</P>
<P>
   The impact here is human, which is pretty gutsy since, going in,
we all know this is about a giant comet hurtling toward Earth.
Directr Mimi Leder harks back to 1959's ``On the Beach'' in her
determination to show that worldwide catastrophes can be measured
one human life at a time. Her strong cast is headed by Tea Leoni,
Morgan Freeman, Elijah Wood and Robert Duvall. Rated PG-13 for
violence, language and end-of-the-world jitters. 2 hours, 3
minutes. (ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Disturbing Behavior R
</P>
<P>
   Disturbingly lame. This teens-in-peril flick is a high-concept
pitch with zero follow-through _ it's ``The Stepford Teens'' with a
touch of ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers.'' James Marsden plays a
newcomer to a small-town high school who encounters a band of
frighteningly clean-cut students. With the help of the school
psychiatrist (Bruce Greenwood), these fascist Archies ``recruit'' a
new classmate into their group every few days. Rated R for
profanity, violence and sex. 1 hour, 23 minutes. (SM) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dolittle PG-13
</P>
<P>
   This raucous but uninspired Eddie Murphy vehicle has almost
nothing to do with the old Rex Harrison musical. Murphy is John
Dolittle, a busy doctor who has neglected his wife (Kristen Wilson)
and his two daughters. One day, all kinds of animals start
pestering him vocally. Despite the zing of some nuttier moments,
the lame plot keeps dragging the movie to the ground. Rated PG-13
for crude humor and language. 1 hour, 30 minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Ever After PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this ``Ever After'' proves you can teach an old doll
new tricks. Re-inventing the Cinderella story in a way that targets
``Titanic''-loving teens more than Barney grads, the movie stars
Drew Barrymore as its spirited heroine, Anjelica Huston as her
scheming stepmother and Dougray Scott as a prince who's more than
just another trophy husband. Jeanne Moreau, doyenne of the French
New Wave, contributes a classy cameo. Rated PG-13 for emotional
situations (death of a father) and some violence. 2 hours. (ER)
Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Halloween: H20 R
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis returns in this unsurprising 20th anniversary
sequel to John Carpenter's 1978 frightfest ``Halloween.'' Now,
she's a single mom to 17-year-old John (Josh Hartnett). Also back
is Michael Myers, the maniac who stalked Curtis all those years
ago. You can easily guess who'll survive and who'll get cut out of
the picture, literally. But when Curtis pulls a Sigourney Weaver, a
la ``Aliens,'' stalking Michael instead of fleeing him, the movie
finally gets some juice. Rated R for profanity, violence, gore,
alcohol use. 1 hour, 22 minutes. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fool R
</P>
<P>
   More challenging but irritatingly oblique foolishness from Hal
Hartley. A nerdy, withdrawn garbageman (James Urbaniak) is
befriended by a grandiose, overbearing stranger (Thomas Jay Ryan)
with literary pretensions and a secret past. Encouraged to write
himself, the protege surpasses his mentor. Hartley has wit and an
eccentric vision. But his trademark monotone style is emotionally
deadening. The movie just goes on and on and on. Rated R for sex,
nudity, language and graphic scatological humor. 2 hours, 18
minutes. (ER) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   High Art R
</P>
<P>
   Former Brat Packer Ally Sheedy gives us a stunning lesson in the
high art of acting as a once-famous photographer who becomes
involved, both personally and professionally, with an ambitious
young editor (Radha Mitchell) at a chi-chi manhattan magazine. In
the film's pivotal role, Sheedy is all wired intensity and wary
irony. Rated R for language, drug use, nudity and sex. 1 hour, 42
minutes. (ER) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Weapon 4 R
</P>
<P>
   The latest in director Richard Donner's cheerfully chaotic
blow-em-up series re-pairs Mel Gibson's hothead cop Riggs, and
Danny Glover's long-suffering partner Murtaugh. Shaggy and amiable,
Number 4 hardly bothers to get its real plot going for its first
hour. More than ever, the film is an excuse to give its crack
supporting cast, including Joe Pesci and Chris Rock, a series of
comic riffs. Rated R for violence and profanity. 2 hours, 5
minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Madeline PG
</P>
<P>
   A remarkably faithful and fun adaptation of the beloved series
of children's books about a precocious redheaded orphan living in a
girls school. Set in the relatively uncomplicated 1950s and
breathtakingly filmed in Paris, it's fast-paced enough to appeal to
kids (even little boys should take to the motor scooter-riding
rascal Pepito) and just nostalgic enough for adults. Rated PG for
comic violence. 1 hour, 29 minutes. (Jill Vejnoska) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Mafia! PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere Francis Ford Coppola is sobbing. But his masterpiece,
``The Godfather,'' isn't the only movie to take a hit in this
ridiculous spoof by writer/director Jim Abrahams, part of the trio
who brought us ``Airplane!'' and the ``Naked Gun'' series. There
are also jabs at ``Casino'' and ``Il Postino.'' Lloyd Bridges plays
the head of a crime family; Jay Mohr (``Jerry Maguire'') is his
ruthless son. Rated PG-13 for profanity, violence and drug content.
1 hour, 33 minutes. (Knight Ridder Newspapers) Grade: NR
</P>
<P>
   The Mask of Zorro PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Derring-do done right. Our men in black are Anthony Hopkins and
Antonio Banderas who double our swashbuckling pleasure and double
our fun as dual Zorros, saving California and Hopkins' beautful,
spirited daughter (stunning newcomer, Catherine Zeta-Jones) from
the evil schemes of one Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson). Rated PG-13 for
violence. 2 hours, 16 minutes. (ER) Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Mulan G
</P>
<P>
   The best Disney animated feature since ``Beauty and the Beast''
and ``The Lion King.'' Based on a 4th-century legend, it's about a
young girl who pulls a National Velvet, i.e., disguises herself as
a boy and goes to battle in her elderly father's place. This isn't
just a grand family film; it's a grand film, period. As Eddie
Murphy's little red dragon says, ``Mulan, you the man!'' 1 hour, 28
minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The Negotiator R
</P>
<P>
   In this crisply acted thriller, Samuel L. Jackson plays a
hostage negotiator for the Chicago police department who is framed
for embezzlement and murder. Desperate to clear his name, he takes
four members of the department hostage, then asks another
negotiator (Kevin Spacey) to act as a mediator between himself and
his fellow officers. The film's main kick is the engrossing duel of
bluffs and counterbluffs between Spacey and Jackson. Rated R for
violence and profanity. 2 hours, 15 minutes. (SM) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The Opposite of Sex R
</P>
<P>
   Christina Ricci's teen tart burns across the screen in this
acerbic yet strangely sweet black comedy. The convoluted plot kicks
off when Ricci visits her gay half brother (Martin Donovan) and
steals his dim-bulb lover (Ivan Sergei). The fine supporting cast
includes Lisa Kudrow and Lyle Lovett. Rated R for vulgar language,
sexual situations, some nudity and sexual references. 1 hour, 40
minutes. (ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sight R
</P>
<P>
   Another winning adaptation of a book by Elmore Leonard, the
brain that cooked up ``Get Shorty.'' George Clooney plays a courtly
bank robber, Jennifer Lopez is the federal marshal he kidnaps. In
outline, this is a screwball romantic comedy. It just happens to be
propelled by firepower, betrayal, bloodshed _ and the erotic
gravitational pull between the two leads. Rated R for language. 2
hours, 9 minutes. (SM) Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The Parent Trap PG
</P>
<P>
   Wisely deviates little from the plot of the 1961 Disney film
that made 15-year-old Hayley Mills a star. This time Lindsay Lohan
plays the dual role of separated-practically-at-birth identical
twins who meet and switch identities in the hopes of reuniting
their divorced parents. Rated PG for mild profanity and alcohol
use. 2 hours, 7 minutes. (Jill Vejnoska) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   (pi) R
</P>
<P>
   Warning to anyone whose math paranoia dates back to eighth-grade
algebra: Darren Aronovsky has your number(s). In his technically
and intellectually brilliant film, a solitary math prodigy (Sean
Gulette) stumbles onto a number that could be the key to everything
unknowable in the universe, be it the stock market or God. Named
best director at Sundance, Aronovsky is clearly a talent to be
watched. Rated R for vulgar language and grotesque violence. 1
hour, 25 minutes. (ER)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Polish Wedding PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Though it's playing the art-house circuit, this is more like a
``Moonstruck'' wannabe than anything Christina Ricci has done
lately. In Detroit, a large first-generation Polish family wrestles
with everything from adultery to teen pregnancy. Director Theresa
Connelly's debut film may be shaky and cliched, but her strong cast
(Lena Olin, Gabriel Byrne, Claire Danes) comes to her rescue. Rated
PG-13 for sex. 1 hour, 41 minutes. (ER) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan R
</P>
<P>
   Part gung-ho heroism, part in-your-face horror show, Steven
Spielberg's superb film shows us World War II as we've never seen
it before. Tom Hanks leads a courageous squad (and excellent
ensemble cast) on a mission to find a private (Matt Damon) whose
three brothers have already been killed in combat. Hanks'
performance is a miracle of decency and subtle emotion, but kudos
all around here. And the opening D-Day sequence is the most
powerful combat footage ever created on film. Rated R for extreme
violence and some vulgar language. 2 hours, 50 minutes. (ER) Grade:
A
</P>
<P>
   Smoke Signals PG-13
</P>
<P>
   A bittersweet coming-of-age comedy about two Native Americans
who leave their dilapidated reservation to go to Arizona to fetch
their father's (one biological; the other spiritual) body. Rambling
and rough around the edges, with a honed casualness that suggests
the early '70s, Chris Eyre's debut film is still definitely worth a
look. Rated PG-13 for vulgar language and alcohol abuse. 1 hour, 30
minutes. (ER) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Snake Eyes R
</P>
<P>
   Oscar winner Nicolas Cage and Brian De Palma are always worth
gambling on; while they don't come up total winners here, they're
hardly losers either. Cage plays a crooked Atlantic City, N.J., cop
who finds himself in the middle of an assassination plot during a
heavyweight boxing match. Part detective story, part
action-thriller, the picture loses steam near the end, but De
Palma's wired camera work and Cage's strutting energy help hold it
together. Rated R for violence and language. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
(ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   There's Something About Mary R
</P>
<P>
   Rude, crude and hilarious, this comedy by the ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber''
team of Peter and Bobby Farrelly definitely isn't a family film.
Ben Stiller plays Ted, a nerdy high school senior who suffers a
very particular bathroom mishap that keeps him from attending his
prom with the class golden girl (Cameron Diaz). Thirteen years
later, he hires a lower-rung gumshoe (Matt Dillon) to track her
down. Rated R for strong comic sexual content and language. 1 hour,
58 minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The Truman Show PG
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey's excellent performance is the centerpiece of this
provocative, thoroughly entertaining social satire about a cheerful
insurance salesman who slowly realizes his entire life has been a
TV show and everyone he knows are actors. Peter Weir directs this
dazzlingly executed conceit and the strong cast includes Laura
Linney and Ed Harris. Rated PG for mild language. 1 hour, 44
minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The X-Files PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Though the feature film continuation of Fox's conspiracy-mad TV
series offers more gore and profanity, it never accelerates to that
stratospheric level of action, suspense or awe that we hope for in
a summer movie. As FBI agents Mulder and Scully, David Duchovny and
Gillian Anderson take a smooth step up from television to the big
screen. Rated PG-13 for mild language, gore and violence. 2 hours,
2 minutes. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   -- LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Wrongfully Accused PG-13
</P>
<P>
   The sultan of spoof, Leslie Nielsen (``Airplane!'' ``The Naked
Gun'') stars in this gag-glutted comedy that skewers such movies as
``The Fugitive'' and ``Mission: Impossible.'' Co-starring Richard
Crenna and Kelly Le Brock.
</P>
<P>
   -- Aug. 21
</P>
<P>
   54 R
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Mark Christopher takes an unflinching look at
the notorious late '70s disco palace Studio 54. Salma Hayek
(``Fools Rush In'') vamps it up as a dance diva; Ryan Phillippe
(``I Know What You Did Last Summer'') plays an innocent from New
Jersey who becomes a Studio 54 regular.
</P>
<P>
   -- Aug. 28
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
