<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-DCTALK-COX     08-07 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DCTALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dc Talk walks the walk on racial harmony
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most music fans know dc Talk through its music.
</P>
<P>
   Its last studio album, ``Jesus Freak,'' went platinum and netted
the trio a 1996 Grammy for best rock gospel album. The group also
won a 1997 Grammy for its live album, ``Welcome to the Freak
Show,'' and a 1993 Grammy for its album ``Free at Last.''
</P>
<P>
   Fewer people know about the group's campaign to promote racial
unity. This interracial trio created the ERACE (Eliminating Racism
and Creating Equality) Foundation last year to promote what dc Talk
members call ``living integration.''
</P>
<P>
   They have promoted ERACE through public service announcements
and speaking engagements. And they now plan to build a house for
gang members in Long Beach, Calif. _ a meeting place for those who
want to use the Bible to help them leave gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   The trio opened their national ERACE tour in Atlanta in June.
Trio member Toby McKeehan talked with Cox News Service about ERACE
and dc Talk's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why did dc Talk create the ERACE Foundation?
</P>
<P>
   A:It was obvious that we had the right to say this, considering
we're an interracial group. For a long time, we spoke out through
our music and just lived integration. We've worked together for 10
years and we now have this privilege of saying, ``This can work,
not only on an artistic but a business level.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why is integration so important to dc Talk?
</P>
<P>
   A:It grew out of our friendship. We know that it can work.
People often talk about being colorblind, but I don't want to be
colorblind. I want to recognize all the colors and appreciate the
beauty that they bring to society.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's happening with dc Talk right now?
</P>
<P>
   A:We're finishing our new record. It'll come out in September.
And we'll do a big tour in January.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's the musical style for this record?
</P>
<P>
   A:It's definitely along the lines of ``Jesus Freak.'' It's a
diverse record. (Laughs.) We're the band that's ever reinventing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any radical departure in music from (``Jesus Freak'')?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'll just say that we are venturing creatively. I'll just save
it for the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
