<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-DATE-COX     08-07 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-DATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious dating services are growing as the faithful go
high-tech in finding partners.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Life looked good for Ken Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   At 40 years old, Edwards was a dentist who had built a
comfortable upper middle-class existence around his Christian faith
and his family, a wife of 19 years and three children.
</P>
<P>
   But his world collapsed in 1992 when his marriage ended in a
bitter divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to rebound, enrolling in divorce recovery classes and
joining his church's singles ministry. But life was difficult and
lonely in his new role as a middle-aged bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play the 'What if?' game,'' Edwards, 48, said. ```Could I
have done better? Why am I such a failure?'''
</P>
<P>
   Then he joined a Christian dating service, Equally Yoked, and
was introduced to a woman whose husband had died two years earlier
after 20 years of marriage. On their first date, Edwards took the
woman, Cathy Reed, to an Italian restaurant. They talked for hours,
until 2 in the morning, about their families and childhood and
about their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was so excited after this first meeting, he called Reed
on his car phone and talked to her for another hour as he drove
home.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, they were married on a beach in Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   Popular wisdom suggests church and other such houses of worship
are the best places for singles to meet potential mates. But
religious dating services are growing in popularity as the faithful
take a high-tech approach to finding soulmates.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of such services are popping up across the country and
most can be found on the Internet. Christian Meeting Point, Faith
Mates and Soul Attraction are a few of the services that can be
found on your computer. Many are aimed at specific denominations.
Some are interdenominational. Most offer photos and biographies of
singles interested in finding mates.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, there are two Christian and one Jewish dating
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear from most singles is that dating is hard and
difficult,'' said Lauren Stone, director of Impressions, the Jewish
dating service based in Midtown. ``But when you're Jewish, and you
want to meet someone who is Jewish, it's even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Single adults who have never married are one of the largest and
fastest growing groups of Americans, accounting for one in four
(about 44.2 million) people older than 18, according to the U.S.
Census Bureau. That's twice the number in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church hasn't caught up with demographics,'' said Wayne
Parker, who created Faith, Hope &AMP; Love Online, a Christian dating
service based in Sandy Springs that also offers its services on the
Internet (www.faith-hope-love.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to churches that have thousands of people, and
they'll say that they have only 12 people who show up for their
singles program,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   And since many people think religious compatibility is one of
the keys to a successful relationship, many seem to be turning to
dating services to help them meet potential mates.
</P>
<P>
   The same philosophy holds true for Jewish singles.
</P>
<P>
   Impressions offered Jan Glazer, 44, a quick way to meet a man of
her faith after her first marriage failed. A member of Impressions
introduced Glazer to Glenn Sugarman, 42, at an Impressions party.
Glazer was smitten by Sugarman's darkly handsome features.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have the same values, the same spiritual
background,'' said Glazer, who lives in east Cobb. ``My children
are Jewish. I felt like it was important for me to carry over that
Jewish identity in another marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious dating services also tend to filter out people who are
not serious about their faith. Before joining Equally Yoked, for
instance, applicants must be interviewed by the dating service's
staff and sign a ``statement of faith and conduct.'' The statement
demonstrates that the client agrees with basic doctrines of
Christianity, such as belief in the Bible and sexual abstinence
before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can say they're a Christian in a newspaper ad,'' said
Doug Cozart, who works with Equally Yoked. ``But there's really no
gatekeeper. We're the gatekeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a focus on Christian beliefs is what drew Reed, now Cathy
Edwards, to its service.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 43, said she had prayed she would meet a man who was a
strong spiritual leader. She was struck by Ken's spiritual strength
after watching him talk about the importance of his faith on a
viedotape produced by Equally Yoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew where he was, and he knew where he had been,'' she
said. ``It was his love of the Lord that drew me in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are drawn to religious dating services because there
seems to be less pressure than going out on a traditional date,
that such services in some cases are simply a means to find
religious fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep expectations manageable,'' said Cozart. ``We
tell people to meet as brothers and sisters in Christ. Don't set
the bar at 8 feet and try to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious dating services have their critics, though. Dick Dunn,
a minister of singles at Roswell United Methodist Church, has
authored six books on launching a successful singles ministry. Dunn
said many religious dating services unwittingly reinforce ``the
whole myth that you need to be coupled to be acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn also said religious compatibility is not enough for a good
marriage. He pointed out the divorce rate for Christians is just as
high as non-Christians. In fact, a study done by the
California-based Barna Research Group concluded born-again
Christians and self-described Christian fundamentalists are more
likely than non-Christians to divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith alone is not going to help,'' Dunn said. ``It's the
mundane things that can get in the way. We don't agree how to raise
children. We don't agree how to spend money. If faith goes beyond
Sunday, it may work.''
</P>
<P>
   A year into their marriage, Ken and Cathy Edwards said their
faith and marriage are still working. Cathy still gushes about Ken
like a newlywed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that first night, I knew he was special,'' she said of
their first date. ``He ended up being everything that I could
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
