<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAREHOUSE-COX     08-07 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAREHOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For one Atlanta couple, the solution to juggling work and home
is one large warehouse
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Stephen and Terry Drahos knew all the pluses of
working from home. After all, they had done that while renting for
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But deciding two years ago to buy a place big enough for both
raising a family and running two businesses proved another story.
That is, until they stumbled upon a warehouse in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't looking for a warehouse but couldn't find a house
that met our needs,'' Terry Drahos said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,500-square-foot red-brick building held tons of space for
her frame shop, Stephen's law practice and a home for them and
their two sons.
</P>
<P>
   Even their new neighbors supported their plans, which required
the typically controversial rezoning of the property for commercial
use. ``But they kept asking us, `Dutch Valley Road? You want to
live there?''' Stephen said.
</P>
<P>
   That reaction was just the beginning of it. Despite the growing
market among young, mostly single professionals for lofts in
downtown warehouses, the Drahos family faced several major hurdles:
downgrading the property's industrial zoning, securing an
affordable mortgage and insuring the mixed-use site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unheard of. It was like we were being penalized for
doing something off the wall, when it's an age-old concept in large
cities up north,'' recalled Terry, who grew up in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after unraveling all the red tape, the family has renovated
the cavernous building into a bright, urban setting ideal for the
dual-career couple struggling to spend more time with their kids.
And it even comes with a view of neighboring Piedmont Park and the
skyline to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all a battle, but a lot better than owning three
places,'' Terry observed.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had shared a similar setup in a rental house in
Buckhead. ``The other place was a test drive, so we pretty much
knew what we were doing,'' said Terry, 38. ``It all had worked so
well, we were hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1996, when the house was sold and they lost their lease,
they set out to buy. The location had to be in town, with
commercial zoning and reputable schools.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, they had difficulty finding a real estate
agent willing to devote the time necessary for finding such a
place. As a result, Terry figures that she scouted 20 to 30
properties.
</P>
<P>
   After turning to commercial properties, they discovered Dutch
Valley Road, a short dead-end street of small warehouses and
offices off Monroe Drive. Because the street was zoned industrial,
the property needed to be reclassified as commercial, which allows
residential use. ``In industrial zones, you can do anything _ put
in a junk yard, a chicken processing plant _ just not a home,''
Stephen said.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest opposition was from banks. Because the property
would house her framing business as well as his law office, the
couple could not qualify for a residential loan. At $342,500, the
price was a steal, but a commercial mortgage required them to put
20 percent down _ some four times more than they would on a house.
(They estimate they've invested another $30,000 in renovations.)
</P>
<P>
   Insurance for a building housing both a home and businesses
proved another hassle. ``They didn't know where to put us,'' Terry
said of the companies. They finally secured a commercial policy
with a rider for residential coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The final hurdle arose after the purchase. By then, the Summer
Olympics were beginning, and construction activity surrounding the
event made contractors scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the roadblocks, the move offered more positives than
negatives. Because the building formerly housed photography
studios, the warehouse offered some unexpected amenities: a
kitchen, four bathrooms, a dark room and a garage.
</P>
<P>
   A receptionist area leads on one side to her business, Odyssey
Frame Shop, and on the other, to his law office. In between, a
corridor extends to two large rooms at the rear.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is one long space with living and dining areas,
defined by furniture groupings, with a small kitchen nestled under
a storage loft. An adjoining room houses Terry's work area and the
family room, which allows her to keep an eye on sons, David, 6, and
James, 2. Above that room is a small loft where the couple created
two bedrooms, for themselves and the boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Drahoses did much of the renovations themselves, except for
the biggest project _ opening the rear brick wall to create three
large windows. ``It was like living in a cave before we did that,''
said Stephen, 43.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected perk lay just beyond the kudzu banks of Orme
Creek, which runs beneath the windows. There, surrounding a city
sewer facility bordering Piedmont Park are more than 20 acres of
designated green space. ``So nothing can ever be built behind us
and block our view,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, she and her husband maintained much of the warehouse
look by sandblasting white paint from the brick walls. They've
decorated them with contemporary paintings, family photographs and
framing displays.
</P>
<P>
   The Drahoses also took steps to make the building more energy
efficient _ especially after receiving their first electric bill.
``We said, 'Whoa, over $1,000?' '' Terry recalled. Their monthly
utilities, including gas, water and electricity, now average $500.
</P>
<P>
   Offsetting that is the $1,500 per month the couple figure they
save by not owning or renting three spaces. There's also the
savings in child care and transportation to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   With children, the Drahoses acknowledged, there is the
disadvantage of having no yard (they're planning a deck and a roof
garden) and no neighborhood for the kids to roam.
</P>
<P>
   But the warehouse has brought more solutions than challenges in
juggling careers and households.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors, once past their dismay at the amount of space, are
realizing the potential, Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everyone seems to be waking up to the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
