<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-FIDELITY-PERF     08-07 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-FIDELITY-PERFORM-ART-_$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY IS REAPING A BETTER HARVEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic showing 10 largest fund families will be sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By TIMOTHY MIDDLETON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the space of two years, it appears that Fidelity Investments
has gone from eating crow to having something to crow about.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended June 30, Fidelity's United States equity
funds, weighted by asset size, were the top performers among the
industry's 10 biggest fund companies, according to Kanon Bloch
Carre, a fund consulting firm in Boston. A year ago, the Fidelity
funds ranked third. And the year before that, they were dead last
among the 10 largest groups.
</P>
<P>
   The improved performance follows Fidelity's high-profile
reorganizations of staff and policies in the last two years. Most
publicly, Jeffrey Vinik, the manager of the Magellan fund, the
company's flagship, left Fidelity and was replaced by Robert E.
Stansky.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kanon Bloch, Fidelity's United States diversified
stock funds, which exclude global, foreign and sector funds,
delivered an average total return of 26.4 percent in the latest
period.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other large fund outfits, Vanguard Group was second,
with gains of 25.8 percent, and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter was
third, at 25.6 percent. Franklin Templeton was last of the 10
groups, at 17.5 percent. The return of the average United States
equity fund for the period was 21.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A separate Kanon Bloch study offered more good news for
Fidelity. Through the end of July, only 18 percent of domestic
growth and growth-and-income funds outperformed the Vanguard Index
500 fund, which mirrors the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. But
a fat 45 percent of the total assets of those winning funds was
managed by Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is shocking to me _ to have that large a percentage of
the assets beating the S&AMP;P to be in one family,'' said William
Dougherty, president of Kanon Bloch. ``Of course, we all know why:
It's because of Magellan and Contrafund.''
</P>
<P>
   Magellan and Contrafund are the industry's No. 1 and No. 6 funds
in assets, with $74.6 billion and $35.4 billion, respectively. They
have rebounded from below-average performance since Fidelity
installed Stansky at Magellan, overhauled Contrafund by, among
other things, refocusing it on large-capitalization stocks, and
closed both funds to new investors to limit growth.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ended June 30, Magellan and Contrafund
returned 29 percent and 29.7 percent, respectively. Fidelity Growth
and Income, the No. 5 fund with $45.3 billion in assets, was just
slightly less impressive, returning 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the average large-capitalization blend fund, which
invests in stocks with either growth or value characteristics,
returned 25.8 percent in the period, according to Morningstar Inc.,
the financial publisher in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The changes at Fidelity also included the promotion early last
year of its general counsel, Robert C. Pozen, to president of the
Fidelity Management Research Co., its asset-management arm. Pozen
began a series of changes to bolster the company's fundamental
stock research and free its portfolio managers from administrative
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone back to their roots,'' said Eric Kobren,
executive editor of Fidelity Insight, an investment newsletter
published in Boston. ``They understand that they make money by
stock-picking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozen said the turnaround was attributable not only to
Fidelity's biggest offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Magellan and Contrafund,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Cracow, Poland, where he was on vacation.
``We have a whole group of other managers who have done just a
terrific job.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other funds, he cited Dividend Growth, Emerging Growth and
the Fidelity Fund as having turned in superior one-year
performances.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? ``There's been no one magic bullet,'' Pozen
said. The staunching of Fidelity's once-frantic turnover of fund
managers has certainly been a factor, he said, as has the creation
of a senior management team that has shouldered responsibility for
trading, marketing and computer systems _ tasks that used to fall
to portfolio managers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pozen has also reorganized the research department, whose
research director, William R. Ebsworth, is now focused on domestic
fundamental research. Areas like quantitative, technical and
foreign research are now under the purview of others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vinik, the manager of Magellan when it sank to bottom-quartile
performance in 1996, made a big and unsuccessful asset-allocation
play _ an ill-timed move out of stocks and into bonds. Now, Kobren
said, ``they are concentrating more on stock-picking than on sector
or asset-allocation bets.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobren said Fidelity's fund managers had avoided troubled areas
of the market, like energy stocks, while overweighting more buoyant
sectors like financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Kanon Bloch's data are based on asset-weighted performance,
which gives more credit to funds with more assets. Dougherty said
he took this approach because more shareholders benefit when a big
fund does well than when a small one does.
</P>
<P>
   This method also helps pit giant fund complexes against one
another, instead of against smaller, nimbler firms. Fidelity and
Vanguard are the largest and second-largest groups in the industry,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer size has benefited Fidelity in another way, Kobren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large portion of their success has to do with the largeness
of some of their funds, which by dent of their size are forced to
invest in the larger-cap area of the market,'' he said.
Large-capitalization stocks have been wildly outperforming small
and midsize issues for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Kobren said that while Fidelity's recent results were
encouraging, ``I don't agree that short-term performance like this
should be read as something extremely significant.'' He said it
would take several years to judge all the changes Fidelity has
made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
