A3712 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-670&AMP;ADD-N     08-07 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS REPORT SHOWS SLOWER BUT STILL ROBUST GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The economy created jobs at a slower but still
robust pace last month and the unemployment rate held steady at 4.5
percent, the Labor Department reported Friday. Continued strong
employment growth in service industries more than offset the damage
that Asia's woes are inflicting on manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Employers added 66,000 jobs to their payrolls in July, the
lowest monthly level in two-and-half years. But the figure was
distorted by the strike against General Motors, which was settled
late in the month after idling more than 140,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said that without the temporary effects of the GM
strike the payroll increase would have been above 200,000, a slight
slowdown from the pace of job creation earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The figures provided further but by no means definitive evidence
that the economy may be gradually cooling off, reducing concerns
about an outbreak of inflation without raising any serious risk of
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after a gut-wrenching 299-point drop in stock prices on
Tuesday and several subsequent days of sweaty palms on Wall Street,
the report reassured investors that the economy remains basically
stable despite the confusing and sometimes conflicting forces, from
Asia's downturn to the buoyancy of consumer spending, that have
left the outlook unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining as much as 132 points, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell back in late trading today and closed 20 points higher
at 8598.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving towards a desirable soft landing, but we're not
quite there yet,'' said M. Cary Leahey, an economist at High
Frequency Economics, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of the year, the economy added an average
of 245,000 non-farm jobs a month, heightening concern that
employers would have to bid up wages to attract workers, setting
off an inflationary spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Leahey said that July's underlying job gain of around 207,000
was consistent with an economy growing at between 2.5 percent and 3
percent a year, still high enough at the current low unemployment
rate to make inflation a threat, at least in the view of many
Federal Reserve officials.
</P>
<P>
   A slowing of job growth to around 150,000 a month, Leahey said,
would suggest a moderation in growth to around 2.25 percent, within
the Fed's non-inflationary ``speed limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the economy slowed to a 1.4 percent growth rate in the
second quarter from 5.5 percent in the first three months of the
year, most economists see growth in the second half of the year
running at an annual pace of between 2 percent and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking aspect of the report was the wide gulf between
the strong growth in jobs in consumer-oriented service jobs,
especially retailing, and the slide in employment among
manufacturers, who are having trouble exporting to Asia and are
facing increasing competition from imports from that part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Service industries created 229,00 jobs during the month,
including 125,000 in retailing. Manufacturers, by contrast, shed
176,000 jobs during the month, including those lost temporarily to
the GM strike; even after adjusting for the effects of the strike,
the manufacturing job loss was about 20,000 jobs in July, in line
with the scale of the manufacturing downturn throughout most of
this year. Last year manufacturers added an average of 20,000 jobs
a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturing and services are in two different worlds,'' said
Cliff Waldman, an economist with the National Federation of
Independent Businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that wage gains appear to be moderating or
holding steady. Average hourly earnings in July increased 3 cents,
or 0.2 percent, to $12.79, although the gain might have been
slightly greater in the absence of the GM strike.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 12 months earnings have increased at a 4.2 percent
annual pace, matching its pace over the 12 months ended in June and
slightly lower than its annual pace in April and May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has been in a stage of heightened alert for
inflation since March, but has held off on raising interest rates,
both because there are no signs that inflation is actually taking
root and because any increase in rates in the United States could
further destabilize already shaky financial markets in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report is unlikely to lead the Fed to change its stance
at its next meeting on Aug. 18, analysts said. They said the
central bank would wait for more conclusive evidence that the
economy is slowing to a non-inflationary rate before dropping its
formal bias towards higher rates as its next most likely move.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they said, Fed officials were sure to track
closely the tug of war between those sectors of the economy that
are being hit by the combination of the strong dollar and Asia's
difficulties and those being driven by the domestic consumer's
confidence and willingness to spend. The Fed reported Friday that
consumer installment credit in June jumped $6.7 billion _ a 6.4
percent annual pace _ indicating that consumers remained willing to
borrow to continue their long spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think consumers are about to become more cautious,
reflecting the slowdown in wage growth and record-low savings. But
others see few signs of consumer moderation and think
service-sector job growth will continue to put pressure on wages
even as manufacturing contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's job report ``indicates only the most minor slowdown in
labor demand, almost exclusively in the manufacturing sector,''
said Ian Shepherdson, an economist with HSBC Securities. ``There is
nothing in this report to support the idea that a wider slowdown is
gathering pace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
