<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-LOANS-ART-2TAKE     08-07 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-LOANS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OF JAPAN'S BAD DEBTS ARE BECOMING INVESTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic showing bad debt in Japan and U.S. is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Norie Nishikawa scans the parking lot and walks into the
apartment complex, moving quickly to a mailbox. She pokes the
letters she finds there, noting the return addresses, especially
the ones from collection agencies, before a building clerk asks her
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, she snaps a roll of pictures and is off, jotting down
notes on everything from maintenance problems to hints of the
presence of gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Nishikawa and hundreds of brokers like her are working
alongside American investment banks to transform Japan's mountain
of bad debt and depressed property into an investment opportunity _
and, some experts hope, to reverse Japan's long economic slide.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, acquiring Japan's bad real-estate debt is a big
gamble even at sale prices, but, if successful, it could help shore
up the foundations of the Japanese economy and reassure markets
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Americans and other foreigners are moving in to buy
``packages'' of the bad loans held by Japanese banks, for around 10
cents on the dollar, and then trying to sell the collateral that
backed the loans. They hope to either get an immediate profit or
else hold on and enjoy big gains when the property market picks up.
</P>
<P>
   The dividends throughout the economy could be substantial: If
foreign investors help increase liquidity in the Japanese property
market, the banks could get rid of some of the nation's bad debt _
which is estimated at anywhere from $500 billion to $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   If property prices turn around, confidence in the economy could
soar, and this could put new pressures on yakuza, as Japanese
gangsters are called, who have been occupying many properties _
sometimes at the behest of property owners who want to discourage
foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole economy is frozen because everyone thinks there's a
yakuza in every garage,'' Jack Rodman, the national director for
Asia at E&AMP;Y Leventhal Real Estate, said.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, investors here and abroad hope that the infusion
of interest and cash could bolster the real-estate market and help
bring an end to eight years of paralysis in the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very active market, a very healthy market,'' Rodman
said, though he added that it is fraught with frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   The government intends to give the emerging market for bad
Japanese debts a push in the fall with a blueprint called the Total
Plan that will encourage banks to part with their loans, partly by
easing the process for them to sell collateralized properties at
the government auction.
</P>
<P>
   (On Friday, Keizo Obuchi, the new prime minister, announced a
series of measures to stimulate the economy in his first major
policy speech since he took office. He proposed tax cuts and public
spending to spur the economy in the short term, but offered few
details.)
</P>
<P>
   Already, over the last 18 months, many foreign companies have
flooded into the business of combing the bad-debt market and
bidding up prices for the depressed land. So far, however, the
profits and the number of transactions have been limited and they
seem not to have done as well as they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in thinking it was a good business and everyone had
their home office calling up and saying: Why haven't you done a
deal yet?'' said an American investment banker who is involved in
such sales but refused to be identified. ``There is no market.
These sales don't represent a market.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not the foreign companies make any money, their
activity could still help rescue Japan's troubled economy as they
create a new business: wrapping up the bad debt into a tradable
security.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is helping put the packaged transactions together,
advising Japanese banks how to take bad loans, bundle them in
groups of up to 300 loans and sell them for a bit of cash and a lot
of tax deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists like Rodman note that the method is similar to the way
the United States extricated itself from the savings and loan
debacle of the 1980s. One key difference, though, is that the U.S.
government set up Resolution Trust Corp. to clean up the crisis in
five years, which is about as long as the Japanese have taken just
to talk about the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from clear whether the plan will work as well in
Japan as it did in the United States. For starters, Japan's bad
loans are worse than the United States' bad loans were. Japan also
is dependent for buyers not on local people _ who generally have
not touched the stuff _ but on the fickle appetites of foreigners,
mostly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The bundles of bad Japanese loans have already attracted
significant interest: midsized real-estate investors, as well as
blue-chip names like Merrill Lynch; Goldman, Sachs; Morgan Stanley,
and Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   After Japan's bubble economy, which had been built on inflated
real-estate values, burst in 1990, banks and property owners hung
onto bad loans even as prices fell. The entire property market
congealed and banks became stuck with bad assets. But they often
did not demand repayment for fear of putting their longtime clients
into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a freezing situation that was comfortable to both'' the
banks and their borrowers, said Kiichi Miyazawa, who was appointed
finance minister in July and is a former prime minister. Miyazawa
added, however, that Japan was now beginning to address the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of Japan's real-estate market is central to the
restoration of health of the finance sector and the economy as a
whole. But for now, bad loans remain the fundamental source of
economic disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Properties in Japan have lost up to 90 percent of their value in
some locations, so Japanese banks have been reluctant to sell
collateral at cut-rate prices and lock in huge losses, or to turn
their backs on long-time clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing the banks,'' said Yasuhisa Shiozaki, who
resigned recently as parliamentary vice finance minister. ``There
should be a variety of ways of resolving the bad debt, and the
largest part should be through sales, bulk sales or singles sales _
straight sales to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks have been selectively selling their
collateralized properties at public auctions and private sales,
already removing billions of dollars' worth of bad loans from their
balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading economic newspaper,
estimated that the face value of the transactions might have
reached $28 billion, and bankers involved in such sales say that
estimate is reasonable. If so, the sum is equivalent to nearly
one-third of the official accounting of unrecoverable loans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A typical sale works this way: A Japanese bank assembles a giant
package of many bad loans, some backed by collateral properties,
some not. The total face value of the package may be worth as much
as a few billion dollars, but the bank sells the package to foreign
investors at a deep discount, anywhere from 5 percent to 50 percent
of the total face value.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the savvier banks first go out and sell the
collateralized properties themselves because they think they can
get a decent return through the government auction process or
private placements. Then they include these unbacked loans in the
package to foreigners free, bundling them along with the
collateralized ones, just to sweep the bad debt off the books.
</P>
<P>
   Selling loans can be a messy business because a collateralized
property may have as many as 50 liens on it, making it hard for the
bank to seize.
</P>
<P>
   And the packaging of the bad debt is a risky undertaking for
everyone involved, in part, investors and brokers say, because of
the yakuza, the Japanese gangsters who control rackets involved in
squatting in troubled properties and small-debt collection, among
other activities.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to knock on the door to collect the rent on a new
investment and find the yakuza at home. And while the police may be
able to help in pinpointing a yakuza connection to a particular
property, they sometimes cannot do much until it's too late; few
have forgotten that a Sumitomo Bank executive involved in loan
collection was murdered in 1994, and industry executives suspect
the yakuza.
</P>
<P>
   Many investment bankers say the yakuza connection is exaggerated
and illegal squatting is on the decline because courts are starting
to crack down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one of the most pressing questions on the mind of every
investor is whether a given piece of property is somehow linked to
the yakuza.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Miss Nishikawa comes in. Her company copies the
auction listings from dog-eared postings at the Tokyo courthouse,
where real-estate auctions are held, and she and her colleagues
dash off to check out the properties and draw up a report for
customers looking to buy homes or buildings on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people might have the image that this kind of property is
involved in the cleanup of unhappy problems,'' said Takami Toriya,
a board director at Tokyo Auction Forum Co., which brokers
properties sold at the government's auction. ``But there are good
properties at any auction. We opened this place in central Tokyo to
try to remove this dark, dangerous and fearsome image.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem arises because companies that own real estate with
bubble-sized loans sometimes pay for the yakuza or other gangsters
to squat on the property on the theory that they will dissuade the
bank from foreclosing and make the property impossible to sell,
according to experts in Japanese real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bank initiates a foreclosing and tries to evict a tenant
or a loan shark, sometimes trouble happens,'' said Shoichi Honda,
executive vice president at Kennedy-Wilson International, which
helps evaluate mob connections when it appraises properties for
investors. ``When we checked one portfolio, we found 15 percent of
the property contaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   One owner of a real-estate company, who bought a collateralized
property at a government auction, acknowledged that he had to call
in mob affiliates to evict squatters in a building he bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The properties put on auction are not such good quality,''
said the real-estate executive, who refused to be identified.
``They've got all kinds of dirty connections. In some cases, the
houses are built illegally.''
</P>
<P>
   That presents another impediment to investors. For example, if
buildings were constructed illegally, without access to the street,
new investors may not get a local license to demolish and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``These properties,'' the real-estate executive added, ``are
actually just trash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
