<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-PROBE     08-07 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-PROBE-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-DEFENSE MINISTER OF FRANCE A TARGET OF MONEY-LAUNDERING
INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A conservative former defense minister of France and an
aide were formally placed under investigation Friday on suspicion
of taking part in a money-laundering scheme to finance their
political party.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Francois Leotard, who considered running
for the French presidency three years ago, emerged from a session
with Investigating Magistrate Laurence Vichnievsky Friday in a
furor, yelling ``a fist in the face'' to a reporter who asked him
what had happened. Under French law, being placed under
investigation is one step short of being formally charged with a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the investigation, one of scores over the past
decade that have exposed shakedowns, phony front companies and
systematic fraud in the financing of nearly all French political
parties, was focused on 5 million francs _ $830,000 _ in small
bills deposited in a Luxembourg bank for Leotard's Republican Party
in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, lawyers familiar with the case said, the party _
later renamed Liberal Democracy _ received a loan in the same
amount from an obscure Milan bank. The money was needed to finance
the purchase of the party's Paris headquarters, Leotard's
supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Jean Veil, said that Leotard denied all the charges
of wrongdoing Friday, as did the aide placed under investigation
with him, Renaud Donnedieu de Vabres.
</P>
<P>
   After a wave of party financing investigations and indictments,
since 1995 French law has forbidden ``moral persons'' _
corporations and, presumably, the government _ from making
contributions. Allowances are openly provided to established
political parties from public funds.
</P>
<P>
   French press reports have said that Leotard told investigators
the cash had come from savings in special funds provided to the
party by the prime minister's office. The investigating judge is
understood to be pursuing charges that the Milan bank, the Fondo
Sociale di Cooperazione Europea, agreed to be used as a front for
laundering the cash.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The French government budget this year included 48 million
francs _ about $8 million _ in special funds for undisclosed
purposes and 346.7 million francs _ about $57.8 million _ in
designated special funds thought to be for secret service agencies,
Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
   Leotard, 56, was defense minister in the conservative government
of Prime Minister Edouard Balladur from 1993 to 1995. Since 1996,
he has headed the Union of French Democracy, a conservative
umbrella group that fractured earlier this year after some of its
leaders accepted support from the extreme-right National Front in
order to hold power in French regional parliaments. Leotard's own
party left the Union of French Democracy then.
</P>
<P>
   He and Philippe Seguin, the leader of President Jacques Chirac's
Gaullist Rally for the Republic party, announced in May the
formation of a new conservative umbrella group called the Alliance,
in hopes of rebuilding the French right after it lost legislative
elections last year to a leftist coalition headed by Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, a Socialist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
