<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELISABETH-AZR &LR;      08-07 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELISABETH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT ON DYING FINDS LIFE  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will move Saturday, Aug. 8 for NYTNS clients)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Elisabeth Kubler-Ross is still alive. She is
not dying, although she may have considered giving up at one point.
Death, her old friend, has instead been sent packing like an
overripe houseguest. She is doing fine now, and living in a desert
home in north Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a serious sixth stroke three years ago, and
despite national news stories about her bitter attitude toward a
rapidly approaching death, the 72-year-old woman is again walking,
and even dancing, in the desert around her home. Not bad for a
woman whose very name conjures up death to those who remember her
as the author of the landmark 1969 work ``On Death and Dying'' and
17 other death-related books.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have not forgotten, and who have quietly visited
her this past year, are Muhammad Ali, Britain's Sarah ``Fergie''
Ferguson and a few film stars. Hollywood folks recently have come
by to talk about doing a movie about her life with Susan Sarandon
hinted as the lead role. Plus, the phone rings throughout the day
and the postman brings uncounted thousands of long, interesting,
often unread letters from around the world. She only has time and
energy to read the postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Her quiet fame has been well-earned: She has faced death
squarely, up close and during the 1950s and '60s, when death was
the great unmentioned.
</P>
<P>
   She was a country doctor in Switzerland for a short time, then a
hospital psychiatrist in the United States, where she was shocked
to see dying patients isolated in rooms at the end of hallways.
</P>
<P>
   She talked to terminal patients and patted their arms as they
died, nearly following them in. She got the stories from those who
somehow came back. The stories about following the light, moving
through the tunnel, meeting the beings of light: all the repetitive
stories and images that, beginning in the 1970s, would become a new
language of death and the basis for a ``new age'' of mysticism. Her
clinical stories and her books reshaped how we think of death.
</P>
<P>
   She dared the medical establishment to start changing their
ways, to think about emotional support and pain relief for the
dying. She helped bring hospices to America.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Phoenix three and a half years ago to be closer to
her son, Kenneth Ross, after her farm burned in Virginia, possibly
by arson because neighbors didn't approve of her starting a center
there for children with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years of studying death has also given her some ideas
about the meaning of life. Life is for learning, she believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have learned all you have come to learn and taught
all the things you can teach, then you can graduate to the next
level,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry, God will give you what you need to learn. He
gave her a series of strokes that once left her a crumpled shadow
of her old self.
</P>
<P>
   Why? To master the things that she hates: ``patience, surrender,
self-love and all that crap,'' she said, chain-smoking, surveying
her desert acres from her living-room recliner-chair.
</P>
<P>
   For sending her the strokes, she said she called God every name
in the book. ``Take me!'' she says she shouted at him. ``Two years
is a long time to be sitting in a chair, 18 hours a day in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But the woman who focused her life on death is now focused on
her own survival.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point was in May of this year and the moment did not
go uncelebrated. About 30 friends and family members had a party by
the teepee and totem pole at Kubler-Ross' home. They sent balloons
up to symbolize the release of the old, negative Elisabeth. They
smoked an Indian pipe of Elisabeth's and announced the birth of the
new, positive Elisabeth.
</P>
<P>
   She never thought she would walk again. At that party, she
danced, very slowly, for the first time in three years. And with 11
different men.
</P>
<P>
   She has begun the hard work of getting her life back. She agreed
to accept a speaking engagement again this fall, her first in more
than three years. Remarkably, she participated in five 10K runs
during the past year _ in a wheelchair pushed by friends. She is
having cosmetic dental work done. A swimming pool is planned for
her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   She is still weak enough that a walk across a room wears her
out, even with a walker. Outside, she uses her wheelchair. She
spends most of her day in her easy chair, often on the phone with
people from the neighborhood or from around the world. She no
longer writes, but her friends hope that her writing, too, will
come back.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of her partial recovery, which she credits in part to a
personal healer, is unconventional, but it fits with the original
styling of her whole life. As she wrote in her 1997 memoir ``Wheel
of Life,'' ``what feels right, not what's expected'' has guided her
decisions. Some of her professional colleagues and her late
ex-husband, Manny Ross, felt that, by the late 1970s, she was
drifting too far from science and too close to mysticism. But
that's where her interests were taking her.
</P>
<P>
   In her 1991 book ``On Life After Death,'' she dismissed the idea
that death even exists, ushering in another boatload of New Age
books about afterlife experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Kubler-Ross, in her luxuriant Swiss accent, railed against the
premature reporting of her death and dying that has been
distributed in the media during the past three years. ``They made
up every story possible: I have had cancer. I am dying _ I have
died _ of everything possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am alive and well and kicking,'' she said, weakly
karate-chopping the air. She wishes she were fit enough to
karate-chop some of the interviewers who have shown up at her door.
While she welcomes many people, she also ``chases more people out
of this house than you can count.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors come seeking photographs, autographs or a glowing blurb
for any new book about to be published on the subject of dying or
the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors cross the line and get the bum's rush. She asked a
German woman to not take flash photos for fear of triggering a
seizure. The lady flashed away, and Kubler-Ross ordered her beloved
assistant, Ana Garcia, to follow her out and take her camera.
Garcia returned trembling, camera in hand, and Kubler-Ross took out
the film. ``Now you can take it back to her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some are surprised to see this feisty, grouchy side of
Elisabeth, friends say. It is, after all, her warmth and
sensitivity that are more visible in her writing.
</P>
<P>
   Among her visitors, however, are also welcome professionals from
the world of medicine and psychiatry, paying respects to one of the
great lights of our era. ``On Death and Dying'' introduced the now
well-known psychological stages of dying: denial, isolation, anger,
bargaining, depression and acceptance, setting a framework for
grief counseling.
</P>
<P>
   As a pioneer in the hospice movement in the United States, she
recounts how the first one took four years to get approved: `` `We
don't want death houses in our area,' the real-estate people would
say.'' Now they are popping up ``like Chicken Delights.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubler-Ross was a hospice patient after her stroke until it was
clear that death wasn't on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think she got tired of just sitting,'' said one of
her doctors, Gladys McGarey of Scottsdale, a U.S. pioneer in
alternative medicine who has been a friend for 30 years. ``She is
such a wonderful and dynamic person and it finally got through to
her that the world needed her and God wasn't going to take her now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there were people all over the world praying for
her couldn't have hurt, either.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarey and Kubler-Ross give credit to self-trained healer
Joseph Bortniak for getting her on a positive mental track. Twice a
month, Kubler-Ross attends a healing circle he conducts in the
Valley. On Sundays, Bortniak, who is 33 and prefers to go by his
first name only, comes out to the Kubler-Ross home for
individualized healing work.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent healing circle led by Bortniak in a north Scottsdale
New Age bookstore, Kubler-Ross looked 20 years younger than she had
earlier that same day, partly because of a purple silk pants suit,
but more from a constant smile and giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Kubler-Ross is impatient for her full recovery. She says she
would rather die than sit around much longer.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she revels in the upbeat presence in her home
of little angels, butterflies and ``E.T.'' dolls.
</P>
<P>
   She saw that movie 15 times and fell in love with the ``E.T.''
alien. ``It was a good example of unconditional love,'' she says.
Another thing to learn before going, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   A great life's work fills the bookcases. But the work is
unfinished. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maureen West can be reached by e-mail at maureen.west(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
