<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-IRA-BOMBER-60     08-07 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-IRA-BOMBER-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUNTBATTEN BOMBER IS FREED, OUTRAGING MANY IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To many Britons, the Irish Republican Army's bombing of
the Shadow V pleasure boat on Aug. 27, 1979, was the most shocking
of all the horrors inflicted during the darkest days of the Irish
Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The boat belonged to Lord Mountbatten, Queen Elizabeth's cousin,
and the explosion from the 50-pound bomb detonated from the Irish
coast killed him, his 14-year-old grandson and two other people.
The explosion, which was followed by another bomb on land that
killed 18 paratroopers, also seriously injured three other family
members and did as much as anything to harden the hearts of many
Britons against the IRA and its goal of forcing Britain to
relinquish control of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how much times have changed since then, Thomas
McMahon, the former IRA man who was convicted of preparing and
planting the bomb, on Thursday became one of the first prisoners to
be released since the signing of a peace plan for the war-torn
province in April. The plan, known as the Good Friday agreement,
provides, among other things, for prisoners belonging to terrorist
groups that continue to observe cease-fires to be released from
prison within two years.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, 50, who was one of the longest-serving prisoners in
Ireland, was the seventh inmate to be freed there this month. And
although officials from both sides of the conflict say the release
of prisoners is essential to the peace effort, it remains one of
the most controversial aspects of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible murder, as were all the other murders,''
said Joe Hendron, a member of the moderate Social Democratic and
Labor Party, who supports the Good Friday agreement. But, he added,
``for the sake of the future of the young people in Northern
Ireland, I think the agreement must be put into effect.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the release of McMahon, who for the last two years has
been allowed to leave prison for short periods to train as a
carpenter as part of a pre-release program, was met Friday with an
outpouring of anger. For many, it brought back the horrors
surrounding the killing of Mountbatten, the only member of the
British royal family ever to be killed in the 30-year Northern
Ireland conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Mountbatten, who presided over India's transition to
independence as Britain's last colonial viceroy there, was spending
the day with guests on his boat in Donegal Bay, near a quiet
fishing village off Ireland's northwest coast, when the bomb went
off. It was detonated at 11:45 a.m. in full view of the police
patrol watching the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Mountbatten _ who was the Prince of Wales'
godfather and mentor, and had introduced the young Princess
Elizabeth to her future husband, Philip, before she became queen _
shocked Britain because it struck so close to the heart of the
royal family and the British establishment. It also helped convince
the Conservative government of Margaret Thatcher to take a hardline
stance against the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Although the authorities said the bombing was the work of a
number of people, McMahon _ who said he renounced all ties to the
IRA several years ago and who had been formally regarded as a
``nonaligned'' prisoner _ was the only person ever convicted of
Mountbatten's murder.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday opponents of the peace plan said it was an outrage
that any prisoners should be released before both sides gave up
their weapons and while violence from splinter groups opposed to
the peace accord continued.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We have prisoners being released, but no decommissioning of
terrorist weapons taking place, no end to violence from
paramilitaries, punishment beatings continuing, murders continuing,
bombings continuing,'' said Jeffrey Donaldson, an outspoken critic
of the agreement and a member of parliament from the Ulster
Unionist Party, which supports Britain's continued control over
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a pretty dreadful circumstance, and I think
it's wrong that the British and Irish governments continue to make
concessions to the terrorists without requiring the terrorists to
deliver on peace,'' Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement has by no means brought total peace to the
province. Last month, three children in Ballymoney, Northern
Ireland, burned to death after someone firebombed their house. And
every week, more people are threatened, beaten up and shot in
revenge attacks, mostly by paramilitary groups. But parties to the
agreement have insisted that they have maintained cease-fires, and
that the violence is the work of breakaway factions.
</P>
<P>
   If the cease-fires continue, several hundred more prisoners
could soon be released. In the notorious Maze prison near Belfast,
prisoners began on Thursday to fill out the preliminary application
forms that could lead to their release. And the Irish government
recently freed six former IRA terrorists from a high-security
prison near Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Michael O'Brien, 38, who was sentenced to 18
years in prison in 1993 for the attempted murder of two police
officers in an incident in which a police constable, Glenn Goodman,
was killed by one of O'Brien's associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an affront to justice,'' Constable Goodman's father,
Brian, told the Press Association. ``The politicians who signed
this deal should hang their heads in shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
