<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARS-POTTER-ART-$ADV     08-07 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-POTTER-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTTERY, FROM COUTURE TO READY-TO-WEAR TO MASS MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jonathan Adler wants to be perfectly clear: he has all the
respect in the world for traditional potters who churn out pretty
glazed vases and earth-tone dinner plates. But when he approaches
the kiln, he is not thinking Mother Earth, but rather a different
sort of woman _ Coco Chanel, say.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when he was a semiotics major at Brown University
and first dabbling in pottery at the neighboring Rhode Island
School of Design, he made a very rococo Chanel-inspired pink
teapot, complete with double Cs. ``The pottery teacher said, `I
don't think you have what it takes,' '' Adler said. ``I was
crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   But his fashion-oriented approach to pottery would later bring
him a large fan club, especially among the designers he admires.
The collectors of his eclectic pieces include Geoffrey Beene,
Cynthia Rowley and John Bartlett, and his work is sold in such
stores as Barneys New York, Neiman Marcus and Amalgamated Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely go in someone's house who doesn't have his work
somewhere,'' said the men's wear designer Gene Meyer, who has
several of his pieces. ``It is amazing how much he is collected by
other designers, which is the highest compliment, I think, that can
be paid.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many influences on clothes and decor are coming
from late modernism, Adler's boldly striped black and white pots or
his all-white Jetsonesque vases with geometric reliefs look as if
they would fit well in the living room of a Pop Art collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what I love about his work is how he readjusts the
idea of pottery and uses a lot of modern references that no one has
really used for a long time,'' said John Bartlett. ``A lot of his
pieces can be mistaken for pieces from the 50s and 60s, which
bridge the gap between our modern heritage of 20 years ago and
today. A lot of people in fashion love it, because it is so urban
and cool and it doesn't shout at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Adler's approach to his work in many ways has more to do with
fashion than housewares. ``Most potters find one thing they do and
do it,'' he said. ``I could relate more to fashion ideas, like,
`This season it is all about blah blah blah.' I express all the
different parts of design that I am interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Adler's hipster locution certainly doesn't fit the potter
stereotype long ago sealed by the crunchy crowd that gathers in
Vermont to throw pots and play folk music. He is more likely to be
found in Bar Pitti in downtown Manhattan than at a food co-op, and
he favors tight Lacoste shirts and flip-flops over hand-woven
sweaters and Birkenstocks.
</P>
<P>
   His inspiration is from pop culture, skateboard graphics and
fashion, among other sources that have not traditionally informed
pottery. His 1970s-style vases in mustard and avocado tones with
rich glazes grew out of trips to flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   Taking his admiration of fashion full circle, Adler, 31, has
applied business principles to his own work that have been used by
many fashion houses in recent years: product lines at every price,
for every sort of customer.
</P>
<P>
   There is Jonathan Adler Couture, which this season consists of
hand-thrown porcelain pieces embellished with bold geometric relief
patterns. Then there is a line he calls Pot au Porter _ less
expensive items in hip 70s colors, and bright, colorful pieces.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Ralph Lauren formed Lauren, a line of inexpensive
sportswear, Adler has just developed a line for Pottery Barn _ the
first collection bearing a potter's name that the chain has
stocked. If the Pottery Barn venture is a success, Adler could go
from downtown artist to wealthy mass marketer.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that all designers seem to make, to feel that they
have arrived, Adler is opening his own store this fall in SoHo, on
Broome Street between Greene and Mercer Streets. Joint ventures are
also part of his mix; he has developed a special pottery line for
Todd Oldham's SoHo clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   Given his college pottery teacher's discouraging words, it was
never assured that Adler would make it so far. At that point, he
did what many young people have done when other dreams fail: he
went into the film business.
</P>
<P>
   He started in the mail room of a talent agency. Later, he worked
for a producer he will not name because he said he was so tortured
by the experience that it led him to abandon any hopes of becoming
the next Jeffrey Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   He said he became depressed. He leaned on his parents, Harry and
Cynthia Adler, lawyers in Bridgeton, N.J., for financial support.
He went back into the studio and made more pottery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he was discovered by Bill Sofield and Thomas O'Brien,
former partners who ran the influential home design store Aero in
SoHo. ( O'Brien runs the store now.) Soon after, a buyer for
Barneys discovered him, and his signature work at the time _ black
and white vertically striped pieces _ began winning attention from
fashion and interior designers, as well as other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very `it's time to make the doughnuts,' '' Adler
said, referring to endless days and nights of throwing, glazing and
refining pottery for his various clients. ``It was
super-manual-labor-y, and I was losing my noodle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he went to Peru through a group called Aid to Artisans,
which matches artists with residents of host countries to make
marketable products. He found a small studio on the beach outside
Lima and in early 1997 started to produce his Pot au Porter line.
</P>
<P>
   His low costs allowed him to lower his retail prices and sharply
increase his distribution _ Pot au Porter now sells for $20 to $120
at Neiman Marcus, Barneys and dozens of specialty stores around the
country. The Couture line sells for $120 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Although fashion remains a major influence, Adler still seems to
be one part semiotics major, one part child of the 70s. His Couture
pieces, for example, refer to his love of Reform synagogue
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been driven by and fantasized about moving into
those synagogues,'' Adler said. ``They have such a groovy,
brutalist, modern thing doing on. Growing up, we went to a
Conservative synagogue, and I was always jealous of those kids who
went to Reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Such personal references do not exclude fashion designers from
connecting to his work. ``I am in a major stripy phase in my
collection,'' said Cynthia Rowley, referring to Adler's early
striped pieces, which are still a staple of his collection. ``So
Jonathan's work could be the basis for a lot of fabrics maybe in my
women's business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
