<SLUG> BC-ELISABETH-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFELINE: ELISABETH KUBLER-ROSS  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED -  &QL; 
 &QL; 
1926 _ Born as a triplet to an upper middle-class family in Zurich,
Switzerland, Elisabeth weighed 2 pounds at birth and was not
expected to live. &QL; 
1945 _ Signed up to work for the International Voluntary Service
for Peace, founded after World War I and a model for the American
Peace Corps. The group of young, smart idealists from around Europe
helped ravaged communities after the war. Her greatest lesson about
the meaning of life came at Maidanek, the site of a former
concentration camp. On the walls of barracks where people spent
their final hours before dying in a gas chamber, she found
butterflies carved all over the walls. She was spellbound. For the
next 25 years she would ask herself the meaning of those
butterflies, believing they could help explain the processes of
death and dying. &QL; 
1951 _ Accepted into medical school, where she fell in love with
fellow medical student Manny Ross, of Brooklyn, N.Y. In 1958, after
finishing medical school, they married and moved to the United
States. &QL; 
1959 _ While in residency, she was shocked to learn that doctors
routinely avoided the mention of anything to do with death. Dying
patients were shunned and abused. &QL; 
1962 _ She studied psychiatry at the University of Colorado and
began lecturing on the topic of care for dying patients. &QL; 
1969 _ In Chicago, she wrote her landmark book, On Death and Dying,
that became an international best seller. Ordinary people began
talking about the five stages of dying. The only place where it did
not enjoy instant acceptance was her own hospital. &QL; 
1970s _ She left hospital work to lecture and give ``Life, Death
and Transition'' workshops around the world. She began researching
the subject of life after death. Her findings led her to the belief
that ``death did not exist _ not in its traditional definition.''
She sought mystical and spiritual experiences. Her husband objected
to the unconventional direction of her studies and they divorced.
She moved to California, but her plans to build a healing center
fell through. Kubler-Ross continued writing books, eventually 18,
in 23 languages. &QL; 
1980s _ A successful author, Kubler-Ross bought a 300-acre farm in
Virginia as a healing and workshop center. In 1985, she announced
plans to treat AIDS babies on her farm, sparking community protests
and a zoning battle she ultimately lost. When the farm burned in
1994, including all her lifelong collections, she suspected that
the animosity of the community might have been behind it. She
helped to find homes for 350 AIDS-infected children who needed
adoption and her lecturing continued worldwide. &QL; 
1995 _ Kubler-Ross' son, Kenneth Ross, persuaded her to make a
fresh start in Arizona, where she bought an adobe house on five
acres in north Scottsdale. On May 13, 1995, she suffered a major
stroke _ her sixth _ that paralyzed her left side. She since has
recovered some of her mobility. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
