<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONET-SIDE-AZR &LR;      08-07 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM MOVES PLENTY OF PEOPLE AND MERCHANDISE  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - The big Monet show in San Diego is an excellent
representative of the alimentary school of exhibit design, which is
most frequently used for blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the museumgoer enters the show like an egg entering the
maw of a great snake or lizard, and works his way through the
system, one gallery after another, and just before exiting, stops
to be drained of a last dollar by the cecum of the gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   The design discourages dawdling and is the most efficient at
moving the large crowds through the show like bamboo through a
panda. There is never any question where to move next.
</P>
<P>
   The first room contains a short video presentation, which gives
an overview of the Impressionist painter and his home in Giverny.
On the walls are enlarged black-and-white photographs of the artist
and the estate that became the subject of his most famous
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The second room includes more photographs, both black-and-white
and color, some of the restored Giverny and its current gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings begin in the third gallery, which contains mostly
paintings other than the featured works from Paris' Musee
Marmottan. These are earlier Monet paintings, either from the
museum collection or borrowed elsewhere. The central panel, though,
is the first of the late paintings.
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining and informative ``accoustiguide'' takes viewers
through these galleries and into the main one, which presents the
main course: the late, very modern-looking paintings that Monet did
at Giverny in the first quarter of this century.
</P>
<P>
   It is amusing to watch the crowds with their headphones on,
whole groups turning together like sardines in the current as their
cassette tapes move from one painting to another. Oddly, they all
seem to coagulate in the center of the galleries, leaving a
corridor of empty floor running around the room.
</P>
<P>
   The next gallery includes a couple of the Japanese woodblock
prints that influenced Monet and so many of the Impressionists, and
one of Monet's wooden palettes, crusted with daubs of dried paint.
</P>
<P>
   A last gallery shows off the many caricatures Monet drew as a
teenager, and makes the case that if he did not become a painter,
he would have had a very successful career in journalism as a
cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   But then comes the piece de resistance, the gift shop, which is
even more crowded than the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know what to make of all this merchandise. Sure,
there are the expected calendars, address books and jigsaw puzzles
_ and four completely different designs of tote bag _ but there are
also shiny silver gardening tools, watering cans and flower seeds,
playing off the Giverny garden theme.
</P>
<P>
   By the cash register, there are miniature mattocks and machetes,
although I doubt Monet would have used the tropical machete in his
temperate garden.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are Monet waterlily mouse pads, Kodak disposable
cameras with Monet designs printed on them, and brightly colored
Monet umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   There was a CD called ``Music in the Age of Monet,'' with lots
of pretty 19th-century French music, and another group of CDs in
circular tin boxes. These were outrageously priced at $18, despite
the fact they were made by the same Pilz recording company that
regularly dumps its releases in mass market stores for as little as
99 cents a disc.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's dinnerware is also available in reproduction for $110
per dinner plate. If that is too rich for you, the same yellow and
fuchsia design is available on paper plates for $5 a pack.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure why a furry little frog has anything to do with
Monet, but a refrigerator magnet in that form is a popular item.
Perhaps it's because it is wearing a tiny little T-shirt with a
tiny little Monet signature logo printed on it.
</P>
<P>
   There are videos, too. Most are respectable public television
documentary-style items. But my favorite was ``Paint Like Monet in
a Day With Oil Pastels by Sandra McFall Angelo.'' If only the tape
were available a hundred years ago, it could have saved Monet a
lifetime of effort and study. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
