<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIMATE IS RIGHT FOR `GIVE 'EM HELL' ATTACK ON CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: ADDS sentence to end of the 5th graf noting House passage of
a campaign finance measure.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 9)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ If Harry Truman returned to
Earth to commemorate the 50th anniversary of his astonishing
campaign against Thomas E. Dewey, he would find the climate
conducive to a reprise of his ``give 'em hell'' assault on a
``do-nothing'' Congress.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When lawmakers headed home over the last two weeks for their
August vacation, they created the proper atmosphere for a
Truman-style tirade by rejecting or leaving unattended a number of
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Truman's day, the issues were a post-war housing shortage,
inflation, federal aid to education and civil rights. Today the
need is to save Social Security, curb the use of tobacco by young
people, reform campaign financing, protect patients in managed
health care plans and improve educational standards while
safeguarding public schools.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most divisive matters before the Republican
leadership is whether to use an expected budget surplus to cut
taxes or save Social Security or both.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 80th Congress that Truman attacked with such vigor and
success in 1948, the 105th has bowed to the dictates of big
contributors and has failed to fulfill a number of its promises. It
has also placed the financial well-being of the Republican Party
ahead of the need to devise a more honest system of raising and
spending campaign funds. Despite a House vote for such a system
last week, the measure stands little chance in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Such a situation would have provided fertile ground for the
plain-spoken Truman, who was heading, according to Democrats and
Republicans alike, toward certain defeat at the hands of New York
Gov. Dewey, the GOP nominee, in November 1948.
</P>
<P>
   At the Democratic convention in Philadelphia that July no
speaker who appeared before Truman did talked of winning as though
he or she meant it, according to Truman biographer David
McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   But Truman meant it. He was a fighter who refused to accept
defeat as his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Striding into the convention hall at 2 o'clock on a hot, humid
morning, he ended the lethargy that until then had held delegates
captive.
</P>
<P>
   He did it first by predicting that he and his running mate,
Kentucky Sen. Alben W. Barkley, ``will win this election and make
these Republicans like it _ don't you forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he truly roused the crowd's partisan passions by announcing
that he was summoning the 80th Congress back into session on July
26 _ ``which out in Missouri, we call Turnip Day'' _ to see if the
members would pass laws to implement their platform promises.
</P>
<P>
   Furious at Truman, whom they denounced with every conceivable
epithet, the Republicans did convene on Turnip Day and, as the
president had anticipated, did nothing to fulfill the party's
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Truman then launched his nationwide whistle-stop campaign,
lambasting the 80th Congress, and won the election.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton has been critical of the 105th Congress' poor
performance but does not have Truman's political option of calling
the lawmakers back into session. Congressional leaders already have
agreed to return next month.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful, however, that much will be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But the record of Congress, while dismal, has not been a total
disaster. Working closely with Clinton, legislators already have
accomplished a goal close to Truman's heart. They have balanced the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also voted to reform and modernize the Internal
Revenue Service and approved a massive and much-needed highway
construction bill.
</P>
<P>
   They also have provided support for Clinton on important foreign
policy matters just as the 80th Congress did for Truman in
approving the Marshall Plan and other vital Cold War policies.
</P>
<P>
   How Truman would react personally to Clinton is anyone's guess.
He probably would find the current president charming and
intelligent, and as a lifelong Democrat he probably would support
him without condoning his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Since his own administration was besmirched by scandal, Truman
might possibly sympathize with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He would not, however, approve of any extra-marital adventures.
In Truman's life, there were only four women of importance _ his
mother, his sister Mary Jane, his daughter Margaret and his wife
Bess, whom he courted for many years before she agreed to marry
him.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin for his 1945 Potsdam conference with Soviet dictator
Josef Stalin and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, Truman
met a young Army public relations officer who told the president he
could get him anything he wanted, including women.
</P>
<P>
   Truman bristled. ``Listen, son, I married my sweetheart,'' he
said. ``She doesn't run around on me, and I don't run around on
her. I want that understood. Don't ever mention that kind of stuff
to me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned morality meant a lot to Truman, as did
old-fashioned politics and old-fashioned decency.
</P>
<P>
   At the commissioning of the $4.5 billion nuclear-powered
aircraft carrier USS Harry Truman on July 25, Clinton noted that 50
years ago that week Truman integrated the armed services for the
first time and that since then ``our men and women in uniform have
truly been a force for freedom and a shining example to all
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his good deeds and accomplishments, Truman also was a
tart-tongued, free-swinging politician. If he were around today, he
undoubtedly would have some pithy comments about characters and
events.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly would be able to pierce the fog of hypocrisy and
pomposity that too often envelops Capitol Hill and the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
