<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIM-SMITH-690&AMP;ADD-NY     08-07 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-SMITH-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENDED IRISH SWIMMER MAINTAINS INNOCENCE, PLANS APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelle Smith de Bruin, the Irish swimmer who was banned
Thursday for four years because her random drug test had been
manipulated, denied Friday that she had done anything wrong and
vowed to fight to clear her name.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Dublin, the 28-year-old de Bruin said
she would sue the International Swimming Federation, which assessed
the ban, for ``substantial damages.'' She said she would appeal the
ban to the Sports Arbitration Council, an independent international
body.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, de Bruin, a good swimmer but new
to the top level, won three gold medals and a bronze. She became an
instant heroine in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Such quick improvement, especially for an older swimmer, was
astonishing, and many coaches and swimmers from other nations
suspected that it came from the use of bodybuilding drugs barred in
swimming and most other Olympic sports. They pointed out that her
husband and new coach, Erik de Bruin, a former Dutch discus
thrower, had once been suspended by track and field for using
illegal bodybuilding drugs.
</P>
<P>
   No traces of such drugs have ever appeared in one of her drug
tests. But the international federation, known by its French
acronym of FINA, said a random test last January contained an
inordinate amount of alcohol, probably whisky, which served as a
masking agent.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's news conference, de Bruin read a 13-point statement
that rejected each allegation. She said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe thst there has been a concerted effort on the
part of FINA to ensure that I did not swim again and to ensure that
by whatever method available to them a ban would be imposed. I had
no motive for introducing alcohol or indeed any other masking agent
into my sample. ... We now go on to the appeal process, which I
know will prove my total innocence. I don't think you can ever
recover completely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Arbitration Council, where de Bruin's appeal is
headed, was founded in November 1994 by the International Olympic
Committee to resolve disputes emanating from the Olympic Games. Th
council quickly accepted disputes involving international
federations governing Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
   Th council is independent of the IOC. From an international
panel of 40 to 50 sports jurists, almost all lawyers, the council
appoints a panel to hear appeals of decisions by sports in the
Olympic family. While council decisions are binding on the
federations, dissatisfied athletes have sometimes appealed to a
court. The courts have generally upheld the council's findings.
</P>
<P>
   People in Rathcoole, the village outside Dublin where de Bruin
lives, continue to support her. Louis Fitzgerald, who owns and
manages Poitin Stil, the local pub that held all-night celebrations
when de Bruin won her Olympic gold medals, said he wanted to
establish a fund to help her appeal. John Hannon, a South Dublin
county councilor, said a new local park would still be named for
her.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don H. Catlin, the director of the UCLA Olympic Analytical
Laboratory, said FINA's ban of Smith ``is just another sad day for
sports.'' John Collins, who coaches Olympic swimmers at the Badger
Swim Club in New Rochelle, N.Y., called FINA's action against Smith
``somewhat gratifying because there have to be some standards you
go by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who train hard and do it for years,'' Collins said,
``it's difficult when people like Michelle Smith do this. It's good
they're catching people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Wales, a Cincinnati lawyer, 1968 Olympic bronze medalist in
swimming and vice president of FINA, said swimming was ``a very
clean sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a very small element may be using drugs,'' he said,
``and it's FINA's obligation to enforce its very strict rules.
Organizations like FINA have to conduct out-of-competition testing
to make sure that stays the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The testing of de Bruin's urine sample was done by the
laboratory in Barcelona, one of 25 in the world approved by the
IOC. There are two laboratories in the United States _ one in Los
Angeles run by Catlin and the other in Indianapolis run by Indiana
University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some drug tests are done after a competition and involve medal
winners and others selected at random. There is also random
out-of-competition testing. In each case, this is the procedure:
</P>
<P>
   One same-gender member of the testing team is present when the
sample is voided. The athlete places the sample into a collection
container, then divides the sample into two separate bottles
labeled A Sample and B Sample. The bottles are closed, caps are
screwed on tightly and a security tape is places atop each bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The bottles are placed in separate containers, typically plastic
bags with a security device. Those two bags are placed inside
another bag, which is shipped via a rapid-carrier service to an
IOC-approved laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   There are many security checks. If a tape is pulled off a
bottle, it generally leaves a mark. Other tapes are broken if the
inner or outer bags are opened. When a sample is opened at a
laboratory, a note is made of any tampering. The laboratory has no
idea which athlete it is testing because the sample is not
identified by a name, but just a number.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory tests the A sample. If it finds no banned drugs
or masking agents, the B sample is thrown away. If the A sample is
positive, the B sample is later tested in the presence of the
athlete or his or her representative.
</P>
<P>
   Several people familiar with the process said the protocol is
not always followed to the letter. They said some testing officers,
concerned with invading privacy, do not always watch the sample
being produced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
