<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRISON-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES FAN COMPLAINTS ABOUT OFFICIALS' RESPONSE TO HEAT
CONDITIONS IN TEXAS PRISONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Relatives of Texas prisoners, fuming over
sweltering conditions in state prisons, on Friday portrayed the
official response to the summer heat wave as another form of inmate
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical, mental and medical abuses have been a constant
problem. This summer's extreme heat, combined with those ongoing
abuses, have subjected prisoners to even more inhumane
conditions,'' said Lois Robison. The north Texas woman is the
mother of two inmates and chairman of Texas Citizens United for the
Rehabilitation of Errants, an inmate advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do go to prison to be punished ... but they're not
really supposed to go to prison to be killed or to have their
health permanently impaired,'' Robison of Burleson said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that department policies intended to help overheated
inmates are being ignored at individual prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials recently disclosed the heat-related deaths of
two inmates. The housing areas of Texas prisons are not
air-conditioned, and officials have said temperatures inside some
of the older units have reached triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, prison officials said they view the inmates'
health and safety as ``paramount.'' Almost all of the complaints,
they said, are unfounded rumors, ``absurd'' falsehoods and inmate
``lore.''
</P>
<P>
   A prison spokesman categorically denied claims that water has
been withheld from prisoners; that windows are kept closed
unnecessarily; and that newly acquired fans benefit only guards.
</P>
<P>
   The prison officials also denied that inmates transferred
between units endure ``torturous'' rides in hot buses. While buses
aren't air-conditioned, most transfers are done between midnight
and noon to prevent overheating of inmates _ and their guards, one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But before that change was made, one inmate suffered heat stroke
after his bus ride from Lubbock to Abilene on a hot June afternoon.
Archie White, 48, serving a sentence for burglary and drug
possession in Brazoria County, died June 29 after a bus ride that
ended around 4:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The health, welfare and safety of the prisoners is of
paramount importance all the time, particularly in times of stress
like this heat wave. We have adequate safeguards,'' said Texas
Department of Criminal Justice spokesman Glen Castlebury.
</P>
<P>
   But Robison asserted that the official response to the heat
crisis has been inadequate. As an example, she said fans sold in
commissaries are too small to be of much relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have 10- or 12-inch fans to be available to the
prisoners. We also would like indigent prisoners to be provided
with fans,'' Robison said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials confirmed that inmates who can afford fans
can't always use them because some dorms don't have electricity at
each bedside. Nor did the officials dispute the relatives'
assertion that some inmates have lost the privilege of having a
bedside fan.
</P>
<P>
   But while Robison claimed the loss of fans was punishment for
rules infractions, prison officials said inmates lost their fans
only if they were transferred to areas where they weren't allowed
for security reasons _ and that edict was withdrawn earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said the prison system, with 143,000 inmates, has
taken numerous steps to alleviate overheated conditions _ short of
abandoning the long-standing ban on air conditioning in housing
areas. Fans have been added to recreational areas, and air
conditioning is already available in classrooms and some work
areas, Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   He said water is ``never, never, never'' withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury acknowledged that some of the nearly 1,900 new fans
distributed among prison units are situated in hallways, where
guards patrol, but don't blow into cells. Robison said inmates who
complain about that arrangement are threatened with transfer to
areas ``where the gangs are and where people are being raped and
extorted and beaten repeatedly.''
</P>
<P>
   Robison said she's aware of the widespread public dislike for
``country-club'' conditions in prisons, but inmates ``have no
control over where they have to be. And it's the state's
responsibility to take care of their health and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking them to air-condition the prisons. But
they've got to find some way to give these people relief,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
