A3753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGA-ROOM-ART-$ADV09     08-07 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGA-ROOM-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONGA ROOM: WHERE NUEVO LOS ANGELES IS CONVERGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By FRANCES ANDERTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to see the future of Los Angeles at play, put on
your dancing shoes and head for the Conga Room, a recently opened
Latin music club and restaurant, whose combination of top-notch
salsa bands and sizzling interior design has brought sophisticated
Hispanic style to an ethnically mixed audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called the House of Blues for Latin entertainment, the
Conga Room is rewriting the character of traditional Hollywood
night life. Unlike the look-but-don't-touch vibe of some other
clubs, the Conga Room, which conjures up the heat of the Caribbean
and Latin America, is about emotion as expressed in touch dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Sex roles are very much in force. Men ask women to dance, and
they'd better know how to lead.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday night, as a popular local salsa band, La
Combinacion, performed for the packed audience, the dance floor
filled with novices and veterans, all swinging elbows, swiveling
hips and quick shuffling feet, as blaring, brassy horns and frantic
congas thundered away.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was dressed to the nines, some men in suits and ties,
while others favored the traditional Hispanic garb of white cotton
guayaberas _ lightweight shirts hanging free _ and slacks. Women
wore velvet, lace and frills, and daringly high hemlines and heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very sensuous,'' said Chris Gaylor, 31, a home
designer from Beverly Hills. ``You dance salsa _ it's the most
sensuous of the dances. It's the guys that manipulate the girls.
It's a very charismatic dance. It's a very masculine dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the popularity of the new club, which opened in
February, may be tied to the national revival of swing dancing, the
Conga Room is not nearly as much an exercise in nostalgia as
self-consciously retro swing clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa has had an uninterrupted place in the Hispanic night life
of Los Angeles, thriving in traditional clubs like El Floridita and
the Mayan Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic men and women predominate in the largely upscale crowd,
but the Conga Room is one of the most mixed ethnically in the city.
It is on a section of Wilshire Boulevard that Ron Meyers, its
designer, calls the ``magical dividing line'' between Los Angeles'
major ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   It is far enough west to attract the largely white residents of
the Westside, but also far enough east to lure Hispanic, Asian and
black patrons from the city's eastern and southern neighborhoods.
The club may well mirror a future Los Angeles _ ethnically mixed
but predominantly, and confidently, Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   People come from all directions and all generations _ ``anyone
with salsa in their soul,'' said Brad Gluckstein, a real estate
developer and Latin music fan who founded the club and later
brought in Martin Fleischmann, a music promoter, as an active
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither is Hispanic, their passion for the music has
apparently given them all the credibility they need to draw
Hispanic patrons. And it hasn't hurt that the Conga Room's minority
investors include Hispanic stars like the actors Jennifer Lopez and
Jimmy Smits, and Bobby Bonilla of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been used for premiere parties for ``The Magic Hour,''
the television show starring Magic Johnson, and for the new movie
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' with Angela Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   It is also something of a political clubhouse, a site for
fund-raisers for politicians like Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Calif.,
who is the chairman of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Democratic National Committee, scouting
cities for the next presidential convention, partied the night away
there in late July. There's a VIP entrance in back, which leads to
a VIP room thick with the smoke of expensive cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers, who also designed the flamboyant Atlas Bar and Grill on
Wilshire Boulevard, created an interior for the Conga Room that
evokes, but does not parody, Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The main bar _ which serves mojitos, a Cuban rum drink, and
Jennifer's martini, a recipe from Ms. Lopez (Absolut with Madeira)
_ is bright and colorful, with orange stained walls, a sky blue
ceiling and a luxuriant red Corian bar, recalling 50s Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the discreet VIP lounge, with its magenta walls and
regal gilded armchairs, is aristocratic Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   And in the huge main room, Meyers hoped to achieve the feel of a
village party on a Caribbean island. The wood and brick walls are
simply and effectively transformed by a lame curtain behind the
stage, revolving chandeliers made of bamboo and, of course, by the
spotlighted, dressed-to-impress musicians.
</P>
<P>
   On any given night you might find Celia Cruz, Tito Nieves, Jose
Feliciano, or even Sheila E playing congas, timbales, bongos and
drums with her father, Pete Escovedo, and his orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Entry isn't cheap: $20 for general admission on a Saturday
night, $45 for a table with a view of the dance floor. The more
traditional dining room, with its classic Spanish-style mirror and
picture frames, serves a $25 prix-fixe menu of nuevo Latino cuisine
like grilled Chilean sea bass and roasted garlic chicken. Congas
are ubiquitous, in oversize versions painted on the wall and in the
guise of cocktail tables.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, Manuel Lopez, 34, a machine operator from
Orange County, drew a small ring of admirers while dancing with his
friend, Valeska Cruz. Lopez said he had been taught to dance by his
parents as a young boy, and Ms. Cruz said she had been at it at
least 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been going to salsa clubs around Los Angeles for a
long while but came to the Conga Room for the first time with
friends who wanted to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   Gluckstein, the co-owner, said, ``We want to have fun with the
club. It's not a serious place, but it has to have cultural
underpinnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Silvers, a lawyer from Santa Monica, and his companion,
Holly Aaron, an accountant, braved the dance floor despite never
having taken dance lessons. ``Rhythm, sexuality, passion, touch
dancing,'' Silvers said, ticking off the attractions. ``It gets you
in touch with the person you want to be in touch with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
