<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HAMPTONS-CLINTONS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST HAMPTON HAILS THE CHIEF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BOB MORRIS 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His entourage never went past the front porch (we put
out the flag just in case), and I didn't happen by any of the
parties he was attending, the way some people did. But I finally
had a Clinton moment at the end of last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   I was jogging to the East Hampton Gym on Sunday afternoon when I
noticed a police car with a flashing red light in the middle of
Newtown Lane. Traffic was stopped. A crowd was corralled in the
street behind barricades.
</P>
<P>
   There, outside a restaurant called Babette's, where Gwenyth
Paltrow and I have eaten from time to time, although not at the
same time, I was held back with a multitude of fashionably dressed
pedestrians as a security squad in blue blazers hovered.
</P>
<P>
   The president had just left, after stopping to acknowledge a
petition circulated by the restaurant owner (she got a hug)
opposing Kenneth W. Starr's grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't actually get to see them _ the Clintons, minus Chelsea,
and their hosts, Steven Spielberg and Kate Capshaw, with their two
children _ but I was able to hear comments of those who had, and
despite recent events that have done so much to diminish this
president's presidentiality, people were smitten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a pesky creep,'' a middle-aged woman in jogging
shorts was telling a friend. ``I told the Secret Service guys they
could frisk me if they wanted to, and I was so relentless that they
let me through. And I just walked up to Hillary and thanked her for
working so hard and for supporting breast cancer research, and she
took my hand and told me, `You're so very welcome.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A man _ tan, smoking a cigar, not necessarily the look of
someone you would trust in a real estate deal or divorce _ was
babbling like a child. ``He has such a soft handshake,'' he said.
``It's not the hard handshake of a businessman at all. And he
really looks at you when he talks!''
</P>
<P>
   All around me, people were atwitter. Someone had reminded the
president about a fund-raiser in New Jersey where they met. He said
it was a wonderful party. Someone else had reminded him about
another event. He said he remembered that, too.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of cell-phone-wielding, access-wanting, Gucci-wearing
tourists and summer people, who normally don't bother to say hello
or even smile at one another in passing, had gone gleeful and
turned into neighbors instead of competitors on the gourmet food
chain of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell that the people love him,'' one man said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because he loves people,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   Every village (like every family and every Bubba) is complicated
in its own way. But just for that moment, East Hampton (which gets
more attention than other villages over its complications) had
become Everyvillage.
</P>
<P>
   Under its big old trees, in the shadows of cedar-shingled
buildings with simple signage more fiercely regulated than any in
the world, the village stood still in time, as innocent as if it
were in a Preston Sturges movie.
</P>
<P>
   When the motorcade departed, the frame unfroze: the crowd
cheered and waved and then squinted at the bunting over the Village
Hardware store, the DKNY window and the white clapboard Odd Fellows
Hall, now an Eileen Fisher store. Corny as it sounds, it was as if
everyone were seeing this place for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   I felt a burning in my throat. It was hard to know why.
Certainly, it wasn't about Anytown, U.S.A. Nor was it about
uplifting the poor or disfranchised. Somehow, this was about
community, Our Town, resort style. And for once, nobody was being
cynical. Nobody was even complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a once-in-a-lifetime inconvenience,'' I heard one
woman say as I jogged off.
</P>
<P>
   Now that a week has passed, and pedestrians in the village are
once again looking disgruntled, beleaguered or blase in the way
that only the exquisitely spoiled and high-strung can look on
vacation, I remember how, for a moment, this seen-it-all town was
transformed.
</P>
<P>
   And I wonder _ when is he coming back?
</P>
</TEXT>
