u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRELSON-BEHAVIOR-$A     08-07 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRELSON-BEHAVIOR-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR'S CONTEMPT FOR FEDERAL GOVERNMENT CROPS UP IN DENVER
COURTROOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 9) 
 
By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When a courtroom official admonished Woody Harrelson
and his two brothers for climbing over spectator benches in U.S.
District Court last week to get a front row seat in their father's
hearing, the actor tried to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just white trash,'' he said, barely concealing a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he can bankroll his father Charles Harrelson's
top-dollar bid for a new trial in the 1979 murder of a Texas
federal judge. Hollywood stardom aside, Woody Harrelson _ and
brothers Jordan and Brett _ come from modest folk.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first day of the three-day hearing, one of
the Harrelson sons casually pulled out a banana and began to peel
it before an agitated official mouthed the word, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else, however, might explain the brothers' behavior
and Woody's casual attire, which ranged from black jeans (albeit
Armani) to drawstring pants and never once included a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Like his 60-year-old father, Woody harbors a certain amount of
contempt for the federal government. At the root of his hostility
is the the fate of his dad, who Woody believes was used as a
scapegoat in the murder of Judge John Wood. So angry is Woody he
once acknowledged withholding some federal income tax payments to
protest ``the way this government does business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that there are a lot of people out there who
have experienced serious injustice,'' said the younger Harrelson
last week, arguing that his dad, for one, did not get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   As for Charles Harrelson, he spoke for himself. He portrayed
himself as a patriot fighting against a corrupt government, a
believer in the United States but not ``what it's become.'' Such
alienation brought to mind Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh,
who sat in the same courtroom only months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now Harrelson and McVeigh share the same address, a federal
maximum security prison in Florence, Colo., known as Supermax.
Among the other famous prisoners there who identify the government
as the enemy: Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to me is not important,'' said Harrelson. ``But
it matters a lot what happened in San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Harrelson received two life sentences for Wood's
murder. Federal prosecutors say the hustler and card player,
convicted in a murder-for-hire plot years before Wood's death, shot
the San Antonio judge on May 29, 1979, with a hunting rifle. They
relied on testimony from Joe Chagra, an El Paso lawyer who pleaded
guilty to conspiring to kill the judge with his brother Jimmy, a
drug lord who faced trial in Wood's court.
</P>
<P>
   The chief concern of Harrelson's legal team, a high-profile
bunch that includes defense attorneys from San Francisco,
Albuquerque, N.M., and Corpus Christi, is their client's legal
counsel. They say it was ineffective, and that he was represented
by a secondary lawyer who himself was a suspect in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson goes further. He testified that his lawyer, Thomas
Sharpe, conspired with the government to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   Woody is determined to fight on for his dad, despite the fact
that Charles Harrelson deserted his family when his son was just 7.
He cast his father looks of empathy during the proceedings. On
Monday night, Woody met with his dad briefly and found him in good
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still knows how to laugh after all these years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Harrelson has no doubt rubbed off on Woody, the goofy
bartender on the television show ``Cheers'' who has since starred
in ``Natural Born Killers'' and was nominated for a best actor
Oscar for ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody delighted in his dad's testimony, which brought the elder
Harrelson face to face with the same federal prosecutor who 16
years ago sent him to prison. For that, Charles Harrelson told the
prosecutor more than once and with feeling, ``I despise you.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance met with rave reviews from the front row, where
Woody sat with his brothers and wife, Laura Louie. Indeed, when
Charles Harrelson left the stand Wednesday, Woody flashed him a
thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
