<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE, MR. PRICE. HELLO, HIGHER FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.J., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, to say the least, a case of odd timing: Last Monday,
after Franklin Resources announced that Michael F. Price was
surrendering his chief executive title and stock-picking duties at
its Mutual Series fund unit, the company increased the front-end
loads for small investors in the six Mutual Series funds.
</P>
<P>
   The load, or initial sales charge, was raised from 4.5 percent
to 5.75 percent for those with less than $50,000 invested. So not
only are investors left without the skills of Price, the vaunted
value investor, but many will have to pay more for the privilege of
buying shares.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the higher charges go against the industry trend.
Front-end loads have dropped over the past 10 years, according to
Cerulli Associates, a consulting firm in Boston. While 8.5 percent
loads were once common, a 4 to 5 percent sales load is more the
norm today.
</P>
<P>
   A. Michael Lipper, chairman of Lipper Analytical Services in
Summit, N.J. described Franklin's move as unusual and said it ``may
be addressing the recent stock price decline in shares of
Franklin.'' The increased sales load, he added, ``may get more
brokers who are looking for a higher-loaded fund to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales charges are used to compensate brokers and other fund
sellers; raising them can serve as a powerful incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Lipper said the increased loads could be an effort to lift
Franklin's own stock price, but a spokeswoman for Franklin, Holly
Gibson, said the increased sales load had been in the works for
several months.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, however, that the mutual fund giant's
stock could use some extra juice right now.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Franklin Resources have fallen 27.6 percent, from a
high of $57.3125 on April 13 to $41.50 on Friday. That compares
with a falloff of 7.9 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's Financials
Index over the same period. But why the weakness in Franklin stock
to begin with? One reason may be that the company missed its
second-quarter earnings estimate of 54 cents a share by 2 cents on
June 23.
</P>
<P>
   But a more serious influence is likely to be the Asian economic
crisis. Some investors may be looking at Franklin's international
and emerging-markets exposure through its Templeton funds group,
which is focused on foreign stocks. Templeton funds account for 46
percent of Franklin's assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long term, having Templeton is a great asset,'' said Henry H.
McVey, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``But short
term, it won't bring in as much cash as a complex which is
domestically focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard K. Strauss, a brokerage and asset management analyst
with Goldman, Sachs, said the market had overreacted to Franklin's
exposure to Asia _ less than 5 percent of the company's total
assets. ``I think it will rebound when the market recognizes how
limited Franklin's exposure is to Asia and as overall market
conditions begin to pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   A host of smaller issues may also be contributing to the stock's
weakness, according to McVey. He said Franklin's decision to
consolidate transfer agencies had contributed to higher costs, as
had rapid account growth and year-2000 compliance issues. Another
factor, he said, was the introduction of the European Monetary
Union, which requires a major revamping of Franklin's computers.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Johnson, president of Franklin-Templeton Distributors, a
subsidiary of Franklin Resources, said the loads were raised to
consolidate pricing policies after the company's acquisitions of
the Templeton and Mutual Series funds. Templeton already charges a
5.75 percent load; Franklin's other funds, which had charged 4.5
percent, increased their loads along with those of the Mutual
Series.
</P>
<P>
   So why didn't Franklin lower the loads on the Templeton funds
instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``The representatives who sell our funds seem to favor the
schedule used by Templeton, not the schedule used by the Franklin
funds,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The higher charges apply only to people with less than $50,000
invested at the funds. Investors with $50,000 to $99,999 will keep
paying 4.5 percent and those with $100,000 to $249,999 will pay 3.5
percent, down from 3.75 percent. The charges decline to zero for
those with $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   The new sales charges apply only to the company's class I
shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
