<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OPERATING ON FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ From the start, the approach hasn't made
sense. Did the Patriots really think Tebucky Jones could be a
starting cornerback in the NFL right away when only the chosen few
(Hall of Famer Mike Haynes, for example) ever make such a quick
transition? Did they really believe Steve Israel would make a solid
return after an injury-filled 1997? And did they really believe
Chris Canty would suddenly be the prolific corner they thought they
drafted in the first round last year?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, how desperately did they want a third-round draft pick?
Desperately enough to trade their starting right corner even before
they knew the answers to the aforementioned questions?
</P>
<P>
   These questions have never been answered to anyone's
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jones will make everyone forget his predecessor, Jimmy
Hitchcock. But, like many in Patriots Nation, Hitchcock can't
fathom the decision to let him go when they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped trying to figure it out,'' said Hitchcock from
Mankato, Minn., where he's preparing for his return to Foxboro
Stadium Sunday night as a Minnesota Viking. ``I thought about it a
lot while it was happening, but I never got any answers. I never
spoke to Pete (Carroll) about it, and really, it doesn't matter. I
play for the Minnesota Vikings now. That's where my allegiance is
now. I'm trying to impress Dennis Green, not Pete or (Bill)
Parcells or anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he'd love to hear the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock won the job in training camp last year after he'd been
banished from Parcells's team in 1996. Parcells wouldn't even let
Hitchcock into the locker room following the Super Bowl loss to the
Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock never liked Parcells because of the way the coach
treated him. When Carroll gave him a second chance, he appreciated
it. But while Hitchcock proved to be a loyal soldier, always
willing to acknowledge his mistakes and shortcomings after a bad
play, he just wasn't what Carroll envisioned at right corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they expected,'' said Hitchcock. ``I thought
I played well overall. I thought I really helped to the point where
they didn't have to worry about that position.''
</P>
<P>
   True, he wasn't perfect. But on a defense that had come together
so well so fast, he seemed to be a fixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy did a good job for us,'' said safety Willie Clay. ``He
played hard all the time. You could never argue anything about
that. He came to play and he made some very good plays. He got
burned once or twice, but everyone does at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay knows that with Hitchcock back for another year, the
Patriots wouldn't have to answer questions about right cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that's been the topic around here since I got here
four years ago,'' said left cornerback Ty Law. ``That spot has been
occupied by so many people, and now we're asking someone else to
take it when we had someone who could play it. I'm not the
personnel director or the coach, so I don't know what went into the
thinking. I thought Jimmy was getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing they didn't believe,'' said Hitchcock,
the Vikings' starting right corner. ``They didn't believe I could
get better. I think I got better every year. That's one thing I
pride myself in _ picking something I can be better at and
achieving that.''
</P>
<P>
   He made himself a good run-stopper and he also had a penchant
for making the big play, like a 100-yard interception return
against the Dolphins. But when he got burned, it always seemed to
stand out like a sore thumb. Rod Smith beat him for a 40-yard
touchdown in the Patriots' 34-13 loss to Denver, and in a 26-20 win
at Jacksonville, Hitchcock surrendered the majority of Keenan
McCardell's 11 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hitchcock was the guy the opposition always picked
on. That's because nobody would dare challenge Law. At least not on
a regular basis. So Hitchcock knew he was going to be thrown at.
Parcells did it in a 24-19 Jets win over the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears that the Patriots will test him early tomorrow
because quarterback Drew Bledsoe used to go after Hitchcock in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll expect it and it should be fun,'' said Hitchcock. ``I
loved some of the battles I had in practice with Vincent (Brisby)
because he was always talking trash to you. It was fun. And Terry
(Glenn) is the ultimate challenge. When you go up against Terry and
shut him down, you've accomplished something.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of him would love to make a big play and show the Patriots
what they're missing. The other part doesn't care what they think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all I can do to come to Minnesota and get used to a new
team and a new system and a new coach,'' said Hitchcock. ``I'm
getting comfortable here. Denny Green is a great coach and he
commands so much respect. Guys would never think of missing a
meeting or not being on time. Everybody respects him. He's given me
the opportunity to be the starter, and I'm going to give it
everything I have.''
</P>
<P>
   What does he make of the Patriots' situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Hitchcock. ``I know if Steve Israel was
healthy, he'd be able to take the job because he's a very good
player. I'm sure they had a lot of faith in Tebucky Jones or they
wouldn't have drafted him. They may have to wait for him, and I
guess they're willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But why?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't drive yourself crazy trying to figure that stuff
out,'' said Hitchcock. ``It just happened. I thought I'd be with
the Patriots for a long time. I enjoyed living there. I loved the
community and the fans. I thought we had a good thing going, and
they do have a very good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
