<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FACING A FIELD OF EXPLOITATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ The field at Ohio Stadium is the smallest in
Major League Soccer. It measures 62 by 106 feet, the size of a
football field _ which is its main function at Ohio State. And it's
a field the Columbus Crew know how to take advantage of, as
evidenced by their 6-3 home record.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the Crew exploit the field's dimensions: They put the
ball in play as quickly as possible, with midfielders Jason Farrell
and Brian Maisonneuve trying long tosses to forwards Stern John and
Brian McBride, the latter of whom excels on headers.
</P>
<P>
   McBride (10 goals, 2 assists) was the Most Valuable Player in
the league's All-Star Game, picking up a goal and two assists in
the US's 6-1 win over the World team. John also has 10 goals and
two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They score a lot of quick goals,'' said forward Paul Keegan,
who with his Revolution teammates will try to solve the Crew's home
advantage tonight. ``And Columbus, a hardworking team, plays well
on the small field, with everybody close to each other. In some
ways, it's good the field is so small. It's a more technical game,
with one or two touches. This will not be a game where you can take
the ball up the wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to play over there because the field is so very
small,'' said Revolution defender Edwin Gorter. ``It's going to be
a battle for 90 minutes. With nine games remaining, we know we're
going to have to win at least six or seven.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, fresh from a 3-0 decision over the San Jose
Clash Wednesday that ended their league-record eight-game home
losing streak, are last in the Eastern Conference with 19 points,
just 2 points behind fourth-place Tampa Bay for the final playoff
spot. Third-place Columbus has 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to pick up one game after another,'' Gorter said.
``Against who or where, we don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the Revolution haven't done well against the Crew
this season, losing both meetings. Overall, the Revolution are 2-8
against Columbus. And in road games this season, New England is
3-8.
</P>
<P>
   On the brighter side for the Revolution, the Crew have lost
their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbus has had an up-and-down team, but they're getting
healthy,'' said Revolution coach Thomas Rongen, whose team will be
back in a 4-4-2 alignment. ``They're at full strength. It's always
tough playing there, regardless of what personnel they put on the
field. In our 3-2 loss there (April 11), we showed that we can have
success. If we defend well against them, we can create some
chances, and the team that converts on their chances will win this
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
