<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TEN MAY GET GIFT: ND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes poltics and college football create strange alliances.
Take the Big East, the Big Ten, and Notre Dame for example.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several months, much has been written, said, and
speculated regarding the Big Ten's courtship of Notre Dame, which
is a member of the Big East in all sports except football.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions are ongoing. But here's a new twist. Don't be
surprised if the Big East actually tries to help the Big Ten get
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. When Notre Dame joined the Big East in 1994, the
league was coming off one of its worst seasons ever in basketball.
Adding Notre Dame, the feeling went, would not only help the Irish
but it would help the Big East if ND could regain the status of
national power it had enjoyed under Digger Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for adding Notre Dame as the 13th team was that
should the Irish be happy with the basketball and nonrevenue aspect
of membership, if the time ever came to think about joining a
football conference, the Big East would be the logical choice.
</P>
<P>
   This was a plan which never really worked out. To many, Notre
Dame remains an outsider that does nothing to enhance the league in
basketball and, as the 13th team, creates a logistical and
scheduling nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the concern about the Big Ten's possible interest in
Syracuse _ a school with strong Big East ties _ and you have an
interesting scenario developing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the way it would work. The Big Ten tells the Big East it
would like to take Notre Dame as its 12th member. The Big East says
fine because that would keep the Big Ten away from Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame goes back to a more natural Midwest base, works on
some financial deals with television contracts and bowl
arrangements, and says talks with the Big Ten will continue, with
the clear understanding that it is a matter of when this merger
will happen, not if.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, when all the current contracts will have expired, the
Irish will be the newest member of a 12-school Big Ten, the Big
East will remain intact with its original core group, and both
leagues will move into the next century with optimstic outlooks.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten commissioner Jim Delany says he expects a resolution to
the Notre Dame question before this year. ``My hope is that this
fall or winter, something will come of it or something will not,''
said Delany at the Big Ten football meetings in Chicago Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Count on it happening sooner than that. Like this month. What
most people familiar with the talks seem to think is that sometime
in the next few weeks, Notre Dame and Big Ten officials will come
to this decision: Either let's say we've decided to go our separate
ways or the talks will continue. If they continue, the odds of
Notre Dame joining the Big Ten go from 50-50 to about 90-10.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the Big Ten wants Notre Dame and the Big
East wants Syracuse to stay. If the price of that arrangement is
losing Notre Dame, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Double vision
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up Sept. 5 as one of the most important days in the
history of the Big East. On the first full weekend of the 1998
season, Ohio State will travel to West Virginia and Tennessee will
travel to Syracuse. A Big East sweep of those games would give the
conference an unprecedented national boost in prestige. Conversely,
a double loss would further tarnish the league's image ... If
Boston College decides to play Northeastern, it would make sense
from this standpoint. It would help Northeastern and it would help
college football in New England. Normally, Division 1-A and 1-AA
teams should keep their distance. But a game against Southern
Methodist, which wanted out of its contract with BC, does not
really excite anyone around here, and a game against Northeastern
is a no-harm, no-foul proposition. Look for that game to be played
in the opening week of either the 1999 or 2000 season. BC should do
this on a regular basis, scheduling one game every four years
against teams like Connecticut, Massachusetts, and Harvard ... Nice
to see that coaches continue to take their role as pollsters
seriously. Purdue coach Joe Tiller said he let his college-age son,
Michael, pick his preseason Top 25. Penn State coach Joe Paterno
said associate athletic director Budd Thalman fills out his ballot.
And these guys are going to have a say in who plays for the
national championship in the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4. Please ... Tom
Osborne says he will keep a low profile this season in his first
year as Nebraska coach emeritus. Then he plans to get tapes of each
Nebraska game and analyze them _ for fun. Talk about good times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
