<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-ISRAEL-PLO-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN SNUBS ISRAELI PROTEST OVER PALESTINIAN ARCHBISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Vatican on Friday firmly rebuffed Israeli efforts to
block the appointment of a Palestinian archbishop in Galilee,
saying such nominations ``are the reserve of the pope in the
exercise of his supreme power.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first open confrontation between the Holy See and
Israel since they established diplomatic relations in 1994, a
historic step intended to end 2,000 years of hostility between
Catholics and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
complained about the appointment of the Palestinian, Archbishop
Pierre Mouallem, to lead mainly Arabic-speaking Melkite Christians
in the northern Israeli region of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu charged that Mouallem, who until his appointment was a
bishop in Brazil, had been chosen under pressure from officials of
the Palestine Liberation Organization and Palestinian supporters in
the Catholic Church. `We think there should not be any
politicization of the choices of emissaries on the part of the
church,'' Netanyahu told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican response was terse and uncompromising. ``In the
nomination of His Excellency Mouallem, the synod of the Greek
Catholic Church carried out its duties free from any external
pressures,'' a Vatican spokesman, the Rev. Ciro Benedettini, said
in a written statement. ``The fundamental accord existing between
the Holy See and the state of Israel provides for the autonomy of
church and state, each in its own sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   While the dispute was mainly the product of Israeli politics, it
could have repercussions on Israel's relations with the Vatican.
Pope John Paul II has long hoped to visit the Holy Land for the
millennium, and any serious dispute with the Israeli government
could jeopardize that.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the pope appointed Mouallem archbishop of Akko, a
diocese of 45,000 Melkite Christians in Galilee. Melkite Christians
follow an Eastern Rite liturgy of Roman Catholicism and accept the
authority of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said Mouallem, 70, an Arabic-speaker who was
born in Ailaboun near Nazareth and became a refugee during the 1948
Arab-Israeli war, harbors PLO sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said the archbishop was the choice of Farouk Kaddoumi,
a senior PLO official, and Hilarion Capucci, a former Melkite
archbishop of Jerusalem who was convicted of smuggling guns from
Lebanon to Israel in 1975 and spent two years in an Israeli prison.
Pope Paul VI won Capucci's release by promising that the prelate
would never return to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu acknowledged that he had met with leaders of the Greek
Catholic Church to discuss the appointment. Israeli newspapers
reported that he had suggested a different candidate, the Rev. Emil
Shufani, who is viewed by Israeli officials as more moderate.
Netanyahu's office confirmed that the prime minister had met with
Shufani.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Vatican had any intention of changing the
nomination to meet Israeli concerns, Benedettini replied, ``On the
contrary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pope, who in March took the unprecedented step of issuing an
``act of repentance'' for the failure of Catholics to deter the
mass deportations and killings during the Holocaust, has devoted
much of his papacy to seeking reconciliation with the Jews. He met
with Netanyahu for the first time in February 1997 and accepted his
invitation to visit Jerusalem for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But one obstacle to a papal visit to Jerusalem is the debate
over the status of the city. Israel holds it to be its ``united and
eternal capital'' while the Vatican has pressed for recognition of
its special status as a city holy to Christians, Muslims and Jews
alike.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other signs of strain between the Vatican and
the Netanyahu government. In his last Easter message, the pope said
peace in Jerusalem ``is put at risk by dangerous political
decisions,'' apparently a reference to Israel's building of Jewish
settlements in largely Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
