<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNICLE STATUS STILL UP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two days after The Boston Globe asked for Mike
Barnicle's resignation, the fate of the popular, 25-year Metro
columnist apparently remained unresolved after a meeting he had
with top Globe officials Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Following an hourlong off-site session with Barnicle, Globe
publisher Benjamin B. Taylor and Assistant to the Publisher Alfred
S. Larkin Jr. issued a short statement saying, ``We consider it a
private meeting between the parties, and have no further comment on
it at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe editor Matthew V. Storin requested Barnicle's resignation
after he acknowledged using a number of jokes in his column from
comic George Carlin's book ``BrainDroppings.'' Barnicle said he had
never read the book, but a film clip showed him recommending it on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, 54, has maintained that he will not resign. When asked
whether the Globe was still seeking his resignation after Friday's
meeting, public relations director Richard P. Gulla said, ``We
haven't said anything differently. Nothing has changed,'' other
than the fact that the meeting took place.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin and Taylor declined to comment. In a brief interview
Friday evening, Barnicle _ who had made the rounds of media outlets
pleading his case before the meeting with Globe officials _ said he
had no additional comment and was ``sticking with the statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin sought the resignation after a WCVB-TV (Channel 5) clip
showed Barnicle recommending ``BrainDroppings'' on the June 22
``Chronicle'' program. That segment aired about six weeks before
Barnicle's August 2 column, which contained eight jokes similar to
some in the book.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned about that column, Barnicle had told Globe
editors that he had never read Carlin's book and had received the
jokes from two friends. Managing Editor Thomas F. Mulvoy Jr. said
that he knows the friends cited by Barnicle, but the Globe has made
no effort to contact them.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Globe suspended Barnicle for a month without pay
for using ``poor judgment'' in writing the column. But after
learning about his televised endorsement of the book, Storin asked
for his resignation, saying Barnicle ``misrepresented himself
either to his television audience or his editors. This
contradiction is unacceptable.'' Globe editors say Barnicle did not
tell them about his endorsement of ``BrainDroppings'' when asked to
explain his Aug. 2 column.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle has said that he never read the book and that his
casual recommendation (he told viewers there was a ``yuk on every
page,'') aired for only ``four seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that, you know, maybe someone out there will
understand the mechanics of the TV business,'' he told Katie Couric
on the ``Today'' show Friday morning, adding that he promoted
``BrainDroppings'' because ``I think (Carlin's) a funny guy. ... I
would promote practically any book, as long as it got people
reading.''
</P>
<P>
   As the drama over Barnicle's status moved into its third day,
reports surfaced that the Globe was reviewing an Aug. 4 Barnicle
column in which he quoted a retired policeman discussing a series
of old murders committed by a well-known crime figure. Managing
Editor Gregory L. Moore said Friday that the paper is trying to
follow up on the column by locating the relatives of the purported
victims. ``We haven't finished the reporting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of Globe readers continued to contact the
paper Friday to weigh in on the controversy, although the volume
slowed. On Wednesday, 1,620 calls came into the Globe's city desk,
with only 100 of them supporting the paper's decision to ask
Barnicle to resign. As of late afternoon Friday, 720 more calls had
come in, with the ratio running about 5 to 1 in Barnicle's favor.
In a development that may or may not have been connected to the
furor, the Globe received a bomb threat Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Another form of pressure on the Globe surfaced Friday when
Staples chief executive and chairman Thomas G. Stemberg sent a
letter to publisher Taylor stating, ``I strongly urge you to make
every effort to resolve the differences between the Globe and Mr.
Barnicle ... As chairman and CEO of a major advertiser in The
Boston Globe, I strongly feel that Mike Barnicle's column is an
essential component of the Globe's editorial content and a key
element of the Globe's attractiveness as an advertising vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gulla, Taylor has ``responded personally by letter
to Mr. Stemberg, thanking him for his point of view.'' Gulla added
that the Stemberg letter will not affect the Globe's decision on
Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision will be made on the facts of the situation,'' he
said. When asked how much revenue the Globe derived from Staples
advertising, Gulla said simply: ``a substantial amount.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
