<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING IT OVER, WALL ST. WANTS RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The market giveth and the market taketh away.
Investors learned that much last week. The question is: What will
the market do now?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really knows, of course. But parsing the week's trading,
which left the Dow Jones industrial average down 3.2 percent, does
reveal a few clues for investors trying to figure out what to do
next.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's plunge in stocks, investors asked what had
changed to send the bull into hiding. Was it the economy? Nothing
really new there. Inflation and interest rates are still low,
consumer spending is robust and productivity is high. The wild
cards remain Asia and the strong dollar, which both roil financial
results at American corporations.
</P>
<P>
   There was one big change last week: the market's psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Investors drive stock prices, which makes the market emotional.
Sometimes investors are demanding of stocks; other times they are
not. Last week, they got a lot more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what had been an ``anything goes'' market suddenly
became a ``show me the earnings'' market. And that's what it likely
will stay for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from a period where the market could outperform
earnings growth to one where we really need earnings growth for
stocks to move appreciably higher,'' said Doug Cliggott, United
States equity strategist at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   He says corporate earnings growth for the rest of this year will
be only modestly better than the 1.2 percent in each of the first
two quarters. That's well below what many on Wall Street are
expecting. And he doesn't see a return to high single-digit
earnings growth on the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stocks until mid-1999.
For that reason, Cliggott says he thinks the averages will stall
for the next nine months.
</P>
<P>
   But some stocks can prosper even if overall earnings growth
slows. Cliggott thinks those are companies whose earnings prospects
are held to be so low by investors that exceeding them will be
relatively easy.
</P>
<P>
   These include all the regional Bell operating companies and the
big, beaten-down oil companies like Amoco, Royal Dutch Petroleum,
British Petroleum and Exxon. He also picks Ford and General Motors,
because most investors aren't expecting much earnings growth there.
All have good dividend yields.
</P>
<P>
   If this truly is a show-me market, said Michael A. Berry,
portfolio manager of the Heartland Midcap Value fund, ``investors
should buy stocks with a margin of safety and some upside
potential.'' That means shares that are cheap relative to their
earnings, book value and cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   His picks include Southdown Inc., a cement maker that is down 16
percent from its April highs. The company has long-term earnings
growth of more than 20 percent annually, yet trades at 24 times
last year's earnings. Immune from Asia fever, it should benefit
from increased spending on highway construction.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also likes the oil drillers Ranger Oil, down almost 40
percent from its 52-week high, and Precision Drilling, which trades
at 9 times earnings and has fallen 60 percent from its high within
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil is by no means over. That the Dow and the S&AMP;P could
muster only muted gains after Tuesday is a clear sign that the
bulls are not yet back in control.
</P>
<P>
   No, the stampede last week was to Treasury securities, and
investors drove yields on two-year Treasury notes down 0.18
percent. Heavy demand for two-year notes usually means that the
market is expecting either an easing of interest rates by the
Federal Reserve or a financial upset as yet unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Since an easing in rates is almost out of the question,
investors would be wise to expect more stormy weather. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
