A3797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-SMITH-BOS &LR;      08-07 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-SMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESS SPECIALIST IN THE MIDDLE OF THE LEWINSKY FRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the media horde closes in for one of its group
interviews on the Monica S. Lewinsky affair, the reporters and
cameras these days are often pressed around a woman with an unusual
history of navigating the nation's most sensitive political
controversies.
</P>
<P>
   She is Judy A. Smith, a Boston University graduate whose
unlikely journey through Washington has made her something of a
press-relations specialist on sex and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, Smith has been the spokeswoman for Lewinsky and her
mother, Marcia Lewis. After Lewinsky's grand jury testimony
Thursday, it fell to Smith to feed a statement to the press corps.
When reporters blocked Lewinsky's path to her lawyers' office last
week, it was Smith's job to cut a path to their door.
</P>
<P>
   But this is only the latest political contretemps for Smith, who
has become a noticeable figure in press photos and on TV news
reports. As a White House press aide during the Bush
administration, Smith helped guide Clarence Thomas past sexual
harassment accusations and onto the Supreme Court. She worked for
Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence Walsh and for the investigators
pursuing Washington Mayor Marion Barry, who was caught on video
smoking crack in a hotel room with a female friend.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an unusual journey through national history for
Smith, 38, whose resume also includes a stint as one of the
highest-ranking African Americans in network television.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a very poised woman who has handled some very tough
tasks,'' said James Wieghart, who worked with Smith on the
Iran-Contra team, where she was a press aide and associate counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who would not comment for this article, is a Washinton,
D.C., native who attended a local all-girls Catholic school, then
moved to Boston in 1976 to earn a communications degree from Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, she had just earned a law degree from American
University in Washington when Walsh hired her to help with the
overwhelming media attention to the Iran-Contra investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was her first job doing public relations work,'' Walsh
recalled, and it was a tough one. ``There were 25 or 30 reporters
who covered us pretty regularly.'' Much of the investigator's work
was secret, and Smith always showed good judgment in deciding what
she could reveal and what comments would land the office in
trouble, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith moved from Walsh's office to work for US Attorney Jay
Stephens, where she handled a press corps hungry for details of the
case against Barry. And when Smith joined President Bush's press
staff for the last two years of his term, she found herself in the
trenches promoting Thomas's nomination to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate grilled Thomas about Anita Hill's sexual
harassment complaint against him, the White House stationed Smith
outside the hearing room to make sure Thomas's opponents did not
have the field of TV cameras to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Her background as a lawyer and in press relations for
prosecutors proved valuable, former White House aides say, as did
her perspective as a black woman in an overwhelmingly white
administration. ``Judy was more sensitive to where different groups
opposing Judge Thomas, like the NAACP, were coming from than were
the white male Republicans at the White House,'' said Gary Foster,
another Bush press aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough political battle,'' said Andrew Card, who was
then Bush's deputy chief of staff. ``And then Judy is black, and
Clarence Thomas is a black man, and the black community was divided
in that debate. Personally, I think it was very hard for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House again tapped Smith to work on racially sensitive
matters after Los Angeles erupted in riots over the 1992 Rodney
King verdict. Smith was one of the first Bush aides dispatched to
Los Angeles to prepare for the president's eventual visit. She
helped make sure that White House comments would be seen as
sensitive both to black and white concerns, former colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush years also put Smith in the middle of other public
relations challenges, from the flap over personal travel by chief
of staff John Sununu to early dust-ups in Bush's 1992 reelection
effort. ``There is no better training ground than the White House
press office,'' Foster said. ``From 7:30 a.m. until you leave,
reporters are in your face, and you have to know what to say and
what not to say. Judy Smith evolved in her time there and learned a
tremendous amount.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years after leaving the White House, Smith was senior
vice president for communications at NBC. She left to start her own
public relations firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Through a connection to Lewinsky's mother, Smith was asked to
handle public relations for the former intern, said Wieghart.
Before taking the job, Smith checked in with Wieghart, her old
friend from the Iran-Contra days.
</P>
<P>
   Wieghart said they talked about how Lewinsky's image had been
tattered by a Vanity Fair photo spread and by the constant
newspaper pictures of Lewinsky dining in Washington's finer
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   During the discussion, Smith said she would urge Lewinsky to
take a lower profile so she would not appear to be relishing her
celebrity-status while the nation was in crisis, Wieghart said.
``Her intention _ and I think she's done this _ is to basically put
Monica Lewinsky under wraps ... and remind the press that this was
a young woman, inexperienced in life,'' Wieghart said. Smith would
emphasize to reporters that Lewinsky ``has not been talking to the
press, not trying to hurt Bill Clinton's image, and she has not
been attacking (independent counsel) Ken Starr. And that's pretty
much what her focus is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
