<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-DAY, NOW AND THEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 09, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One morning toward the end of 2002, if all goes according to
plan, automatic teller machines all over Europe will begin
dispensing crisp new euro notes with their pictures of various
bridges, instead of German marks, French francs, Dutch guilders,
and Italian lira. Already the planning is well under way.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, therefore, the last time such a currency conversion
was undertaken. That was in June 1948, half a century ago. After
nine months of top-secret planning, the Allied occupation
authorities replaced a hodgepodge barter system based on cigarettes
by issuing new deutsche marks for old reich marks at a ratio of one
to 10 _ in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   That monetary reform contributed to a decisive change in the way
we understand the nature of money. It required massive organization
and sleight of hand. Most significant, it paved the way for the
post-World War II German Wirtschaftswunder, or economic miracle.
And like the saga of D-Day itself, the story of x-day presents a
number of morals.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, German authorities held ceremonies at the barracks,
now a museum, in which the details of the plan had been hammered
out half a century before. Hans Tietermeyer, president of the
Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, said, ``June 20, 1948,
represented the economic turning point _ from misery and the
management of shortage to the `economic miracle.'''
</P>
<P>
   The bankers emphasized the story of the 11 German experts who
had been put aboard a bus, its windows taped over, and driven to a
tightly guarded compound at Rothwesten, a suburb of Kassel, not far
from Gottingen. There they worked for 16 hours a day writing rules
and regulations, buoyed by the urgency _ and the suddenly top-notch
cooking _ that was the clearest signal they were about to enter the
world of central banking.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily the monetary reform is associated these days with the
name of Ludwig Erhard. At the time he was head of the Special Unit
on Money and Credit, from which the experts were drawn. Later he
would become West Germany's longtime economics minister and
finally, for three years, its chancellor. Over the years, however,
the antecedents of the Wirtschaftswunder have blurred together.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Marshall Plan, the generous policy of US aid.
There was the liberalization, the removal of price controls and
rationing that was overseen by Erhard. And there was the monetary
reform that made it possible. This, in large part, was the work of
a nearly forgotten young genius named Edward A. Tenenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article on the monetary reform leaves little doubt that
it was the 26-year-old Tenenbaum who pushed the measure through.
Charles P. Kindleberger and F. Taylor Ostrander (a seasoned
historical economist and a well-traveled business executive
respectively, both of whom worked on European reconstruction as
young men in the years after World War II) write of Tenenbaum that
``he was not a particularily warm or outgoing man, but he was
bright, very bright, acknowledged widely to have been the leader of
the Allied team that pushed Allied monetary reform to its
completion.''
</P>
<P>
   The scion of a distinguished Polish family that fled to America
in the 1930s, Tenenbaum graduated from high school, then returned
to Europe for a time to sharpen his languages _ he spoke English,
German, and French fluently, Spanish, Italian, and some Russian. He
graduated summa cum laude from Yale in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   He moved up rapidly in the government economic and intelligence
arms, and by 1947 was the Allied military government's chief
liaison to the Special Unit on Money and Credit _ at less than half
the age of Erhard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Hitler had ordered that there be no postwar economic
planning for Germany; nevertheless various authorities (Erhard
among them) had been writing gingerly all along about how to deal
with the nation's exploding debt. The war ended and the pace
quickened in 1946 with the delivery (to military governor General
Lucius Clay) of the Colm-Dodge-Goldsmith report on the financial
rehabilitation of Germany. This was the map with which Tenenbaum
had to create his blueprint. Not surprisingly, it anticipated the
problems faced by suddenly liberalizing nations ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Of special interest in the fall of 1947, of course, were the
Russians. Would they agree to a single currency for both portions
of a divided Germany? An even larger issue than the nascent Cold
War had to do with whether the new currency had to be backed by
gold. Whether a purely paper currency would work was no more a
technological certainty than had been the atom bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later Tenenbaum wrote, ``We did nothing that would
have made it impossible for the Soviets to join us in using the new
currency. Nothing in the wording of the new currency was
inconsistent with any known attitude of the Soviets. There was no
indication of an issuing authority, no signature, nothing except
the demonination, the name `Deutsche Mark' (which had been used in
quadripartite discussion), and the word Banknote. These were
nobody's promise to pay anything, the ultimate conclusion of
Western monetary history and the final triumph of the nominalist
history of money,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There was opposition from the Germans, flak from the British
(who tried to engineer into the plan authorization for
Keynesian-style deficits,) interference from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Tenenbaum brooked none of it. ``Operation Bird Dog'' was
launched, beginning with the printing of the new currency in the
Unitted States. The Russians were told, but the rest was top
secret: 23,000 steel cases, shipped from New York marked for
``Barcelona'' via Bremen, then delivered to Frankfurt by 800 Army
trucks, pending their surprise delivery to individual banks. The
greatest logistical triumph since the Allied landing on the beaches
of Normandy, crowed Tenebaum. X-day went off almost without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it worked. The great German hyperinflation of the
1920s had led to Hitler. But the stabilization of June 20, 1948,
replaced in days the battered cigarette-based system and produced
only robust economic growth. The stability of the mark became a
symbol of the postwar German success, its stability a badge of
pride to Germans traveling abroad. Gradually the Germans who were
such successful stewards of the system began to take credit for its
design.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Kindleberger and Ostrander write, ``There is
something to be said for a form of benevolent despotism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture of young Tenebaum, pushing to currency reform
through the German experts and politicians at Rothwestern and
earlier,'' they say, is reminiscent of accounts of the US
representative, Harry Dexter White, ramrodding through the Bretton
Woods Agreements almost singlehandedly in 1944, leaving little else
to do for John Maynard Keynes, Undersecretary of State Dean
Acheson, or the hundreds of self-important representatives of
states around the world who attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
   After brief further assignments in Paris and Athens, Edward
Tenenbaum returned to the United States. He worked quietly as a
consultant on economic matters, often for the International
Monetary Fund, arguing powerfully for burden-sharing in German
economic affairs, until he was killed in an automobile accident in
1975. He left behind an unfinished manuscript called ``The German
Mark'' that has lain unpublished in the archives ever since.
(Kindleberger and Ostrander say that it is brilliant on the nature
of repressed inflation.)
</P>
<P>
   It is Tenenbaum's widow who has had the last word. In a 1980
letter to The New York Review of Books criticizing Milton and Rose
Friedman's ``Free To Choose'' for its treatment of the German
monetary reform, she wrote, ``The Friedmans' whole book is a
diatribe against government interference and bureaucracy, yet in
Germany after World War II reconstruction of the economy could not
have occurred without a sound currency and massive aid from the
Marshall Plan, both accomplishments of the US bureaucracy so
despised by the Friedmans.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Two Lucky People,'' the Friedmans' joint memoir published
this year, there is a five-page entry on the autumn in Paris in
1950 that Friedman spent consulting to the agency. It contains much
information on their hotels, schools, nanny, luncheons, and tours.
There is also an interesting little problem about bartering
cigarettes for gas upon entering Germany without any deutsche
marks. But there is nothing at all about the origins of the
Wirtschaftswunder that was then taking root.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-IMPACT-430&AMP;     08-07 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-IMPACT-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.J.)  
 GM SALES ARE STILL DAMAGED BY RECENT AUTOWORKERS' STRIKE  (js) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. _ The nearly eight-week-long strike this
summer at two General Motors parts factories will continue to hurt
the automaker's sales until October, and some customers have been
permanently lost, GM's top marketing executive said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the gloomiest assessment yet of the strike's damage, Ronald
Zarrella, the group vice president for North American sales,
service and marketing, said that GM dealerships would not be fully
restocked until mid-September. The introduction of some 1999 models
will also be delayed, he said, because GM has so many parts left
over for 1998 models that it is cheaper for the company to keep
building those models instead of discarding the parts.
</P>
<P>
   The company will run new advertisements this weekend that will
emphasize that the automaker is back in business and that 1998 cars
and trucks are available at discounts that reflect the end of the
model year, Zarrella said. But GM's market share, usually about 31
percent, will be below 25 percent in August and will not rebound
fully until October, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving a number, Zarrella said some longtime customers
had decided to buy cars and trucks from competitors and would be
hard to woo back. Each percentage point of market share is worth
150,000 cars and trucks a year, or $3 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jacobs, an automotive consultant in Rutherford, N.J., said
that General Motors' permanent loss might be as high as
one-and-a-half percentage points because the strike slowed its
introduction of several completely new car and truck models. But GM
executives may benefit from highlighting the strike's harm, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can refer to the long strike as derailing them from
staying over 30 percent, a convenient excuse for declining market
share,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's assessment of the strike's costs grew steadily
grimmer this week, and the company's share price drifted down
despite GM's announcement of several initiatives long sought by
institutional investors, including a spinoff of the autoparts
subsidiary and a consolidation of marketing operations. Shares
rebounded to $72.50 during the day Friday, from $70.25 on Thursday,
but then gave back some of the gain after Zarrella's disclosures at
a midday news conference on Friday at the University of Michigan's
annual auto industry conference here. The stock closed up 81.25
cents a share at $71.0625.
</P>
<P>
   GM announced on Wednesday that its sales dropped 37.7 percent in
July compared with July 1997. Its market share was just 21.1
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a typical year, many GM factories would be closed by now to
install new equipment for the production of the next model year's
cars and trucks. The new models would then go on sale in late
September and early October.
</P>
<P>
   But Zarrella said the company has continued to produce 1998
models since the strike ended on July 29. It still has
1998-model-year parts for 200,000 more cars and trucks, or about
two weeks of production. The company will use up these parts before
converting production to the 1999 model year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers have traditionally introduced their new models at the
same time because of a belief that laggards could lose sales to
companies that move faster. But Zarrella said it was not clear
whether GM would suffer this autumn by offering a mix of 1998 and
1999 models even as other automakers have ample supplies of 1999
models.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts estimate that the strike cost GM $12
billion in lost production and $3 billion in lost after-tax
profits. Until this week, some analysts thought GM would be able to
recover most of the lost profits by running its factories around
the clock for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But John Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief executive, said on
Wednesday that even with extra production through the rest of the
year, the automaker's permanent loss would be about $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a buzz saw in the strike,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3813 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPKIDS-MUSIC-LADN     08-07 2047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPKIDS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KIDS ARE ALL RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Frances Bean Cobain, your limo is waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old daughter of Courtney Love and late Nirvana leader
Kurt Cobain probably isn't thinking about a music career yet, but
if she ever wants one you can bet the major labels will be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Other kids of rock icons didn't wait long.
</P>
<P>
   They may not sound like their famous parents, but the offspring
of John Lennon, Bob Dylan, Pete Townshend, Loudon Wainwright III
and Stephen Stills have joined the family business.
</P>
<P>
   They've all released very different albums, but they have one
thing in common: Everyone thinks they got signed because of their
last name. This despite the fact that Jakob Dylan's band the
Wallflowers now outsells his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Songwriting, however, doesn't ordinarily run in the family.
Think about novelists, for instance. There just aren't that many
parent/offspring teams who have both been successful. It's not like
learning a skill and asking your pop to help get you into the
union. You're not only going to be judged on your creativity _ and
then your sales _ but, inevitably how you stack up to Mom or Pop.
</P>
<P>
   Then think about what's its like being the offspring of revered
figures like Leonard Cohen and Richard Thompson, whose songs are
the subject of tribute albums. Talk about intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're the son of a Beatle or Dylan, music legends, how
do you deal with their legacies? Do you ignore it? Or do you
acknowledge it up front and simply hope everyone forgets at some
point?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a roundup of the new rock brat pack. They have one other
thing in common: They all deny they got their record deals because
of their famous last names. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SEAN ONO LENNON
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22 &QL; 
Dad and mom: John Lennon and Yoko Ono _ nothing serious; dad's been
called the most influential figure in the history of pop music;
mom's an influential pop artist and experimental musician. After
Sean was born, Lennon stayed home with Ono to act as
``house-husband'' in New York's Dakota apartments until he was
killed Dec. 8, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``I was 5 when Dad died. As a kid, I was more
into my mom's music than my dad's. I know every song she ever
wrote. I'm an expert in Yoko Ono's music. Beyond her being my mom,
she's also a really good friend. The thing my mom showed me is that
all mediums are there for you to use and exploit _ from films to
visual art to music _ and that it is all really just expression. It
all boils down to creative ideas. If the concept is good, it
doesn't matter if you're making a painting, a sculpture or a pop
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: ``I feel real lucky because of the
name, but that's why I went with (Beastie Boys label) Grand Royal _
because they would never sign someone because of their last name.
To be honest, I don't think the reaction (to my last name) has been
totally good. If anyone asks me about my dad or my childhood, I'm
happy to talk about it. The shock (of his father's death) I got at
an early age created in me an intense distrust, and I reacted to
that mistrust by trying to be open with everybody. I've been really
friendly with people from a pretty early age. Now that I have all
this attention, I want to use it for a positive goal _ to get my
music out and to promote open-mindedness _ those things are
important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``Into the Sun'' (Grand Royal) _ Art-pop with fake
jazz and Beach Boys overtones. Sean has some nice instrumentation
but the songs seem half-formed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JAKOB DYLAN
</P>
<P>
   Age: 28
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Bob Dylan _ An incalculable influence on popular music; as
a songwriter, he showed pop lyrics could mean something; as a
singer, he proved you didn't have to boast a conventionally good
voice to put your songs across; as a musician, he sparked such
genres as folk-rock and country-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: Jakob was born in New York, the youngest of
five children of Bob Dylan and Sara Lowndes. He was about 3 when
the family moved to Los Angeles; his parents divorced in 1977 after
12 years of marriage. In hundreds of interviews, Jakob, whose
popular band the Wallflowers won two Grammy Awards this year, has
respected his father's three-decade insistence on privacy and never
talked about his dad except in a June 1997 Rolling Stone interview.
At the time, he said, ``I get asked all the time, `What was your
dad like as a parent?' And I say, `I'm 27 years old; I'm not a
crackhead; I don't go on afternoon talk shows and spill.' I mean,
you can probably figure out for yourself that he did a decent
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: Jakob has said the Dylan name has
worked against him. ``And I actually found some kind of power in
that. I still do. I do not mope and I do not complain. I've driven
my own path here and I'm on it and it's fine. But if people think
it must be easy ...''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``Bringing Down the Horse'' (Interscope) _ Like his
dad, Jakob is no stranger to poetically ambiguous lyrics lots of
people can relate to. The Wallflowers' Grammy-winning ``One
Headlight,'' and ``6th Avenue Heartache'' were among rock radio's
biggest hits last year. The band, currently recording its third
album, boasts a rootsy Hammond B-3-driven sound reminiscent of such
classic Bob Dylan albums as ``Highway 61 Revisited.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EMMA TOWNSHEND
</P>
<P>
   Age: 28
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Pete Townshend _ His furious guitar chords and windmill
strums powered the Who, considered one of the finest British
songwriters of his era on the basis of songs like ``The Kids Are
Alright,'' ``My Generation'' and the rock opera ``Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``My dad would never have a copy of his
records at home so I'm not familiar with much of his work,'' she
told the British music mag Mojo.
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: ``I'm quite happy to trade on the
family name because I'm proud of my dad,'' Townshend said. ``I feel
sorry for him because he's always been famous. To date there
haven't been that many people in rock 'n' roll who've had to cope
with having a famous parent so it's still a bit of a novelty. It
doesn't seem a problem in the movie industry. Look at Michael
Douglas. People appreciate Jamie Lee Curtis and Tony Curtis as
individuals. When people hear my music I think they forget about
who my dad is. My mum always kept my feet on the ground. If she
lends you a tenner. she always gets it back off you.''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``Winterland'' (Eastwest) _ Obviously influenced by
Kate Bush and Tori Amos, Emma writes lush confessionals like the
track ``Five a Side Football,'' which she says was partly inspired
by problems at home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Age: 25
</P>
<P>
   Dad and mom: Loudon Wainwright III and Kate McGarrigle _ Dad's a
singer-songwriter with a sardonic, witty confessional style that's
made him a concert favorite in the United States and England; mom
worked with sister Anna in the folk duo the McGarrigles, which
received international recognition in 1974 when Linda Ronstadt
covered their ``Heart Like a Wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``We were always the weird artists on the
block. For a long time I was resentful (of my dad) because he was
away for a long time touring and I thought he didn't love me. But
in a weird way, as I got older and realized how dedicated he was to
what he wanted to accomplish and how hard he was working, I
realized it wasn't his fault. I learned to admire his
perseverence.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: ``If the label is banking on the
Wainwright name, they're in trouble. No, they didn't sign me for my
name. (DreamWorks executive) Lenny Waronker doesn't sign anyone
because of their name. I know a lot of these children of famous
music people, and except for Teddy Thompson, I'm really at the
bottom of the barrel if you're gonna judge it on the fame of the
parents. And I'm thankful for that because I'm free of a lot of
things they have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``Rufus Wainwright'' (DreamWorks) _ Bears the
influence of opera and cabaret _ some call it popera _ Van Dyke
Parks did the string arrangements. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ADAM COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Age: 25
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Leonard Cohen _ Born nearly a decade earlier than the
Beatles or Rolling Stones and an intellectual and published
poet/novelist to boot, his classic albums _ such as ``The Songs of
Leonard Cohen,'' ``Songs From a Room'' and ``Songs of Love and
Hate'' _ are often breathtakingly perfect; he's also the subject of
two tribute albums in which his songs are covered by R.E.M. and
Bono, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``My dad has given me a very high standard by
which to live. I've definitely inherited his sensibility. He's
given me so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: ``You don't get a record deal until
the company feels it can make a buck off you. The fact that I am
who I am has definitely raised an eyebrow, but I've benefited from
that. By putting us all together (other sons and daughters of rock
icons) it almost sets up a tone of solidarity that I'm not averse
to at all. To resist is to fuel people's intrigue.''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``Adam Cohen'' (Columbia) _ Bears the influence of
dad only in terms of people behind the scenes, such as longtime
Leonard Cohen producer Steve Lindsay, who produced here;
high-profile session musicians such as Dean Parks and Jim Keltner
helped out on this collection of catchy pop tunes and ballads. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHRIS STILLS
</P>
<P>
   Age: 23
</P>
<P>
   Dad and mom: Stephen Stills and Veronique Sanson _ Dad is famed
for his work with Buffalo Springfield and Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash,
two of pop's most enduring and successful groups; mom is a French
singer, pianist and composer.
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``When I heard `For What It's Worth' for the
first time in my life, I just sat there and played it over and over
again. That's when I realized that's what it's all about. It was a
big eye-opener. It touched something that all the other (nonsense)
didn't come close to.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: ``It makes perfect sense. There's no
denying it. I got some of my dad's guitar chops, I got some of my
mom's piano chops. I got really lucky on the gene pool. Super
lucky. And I'm not denying it. When you hear me or look at me, if
you have knowledge of my parents, you go, `Wow!' Everybody jumps on
it like it's contrived, but this is all natural. We (Stills and
second-generation rock pals such as Cohen, Wainwright and Teddy
Thompson) fell into this because we love it. This wasn't imposed on
us by our parents. In fact, our parents were more, `Try and avoid
it, kid. You don't want to go there because this business sucks.'
We just happen to be the sons of guys who were part of an era where
people were doing something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The album: ``100 Year Thing'' (Atlantic) _ Multilayered
harmonies, nice melodies and poetic lyrics show this apple didn't
fall far from the tree; produced by Ethan Johns, son of famed '60s
knob-twirler Glyn Johns (Rolling Stones, the Who). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TEDDY THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22
</P>
<P>
   Dad and mom: Richard Thompson and Linda Thompson _ Before
breaking up, the couple released six albums, including the British
folk-rock masterpiece ``I Want to See the Bright Lights Tonight'';
dad is among the most admired and critically acclaimed songwriters
and guitarists in folk-rock music; he's also the subject of a
three-disc career retrospective and a tribute album in which the
likes of R.E.M., Bonnie Raitt, David Byrne and Los Lobos cover his
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Around the house: ``Me and my sister spent a lot of time in the
back of the Volvo station wagon at folk festivals and we hated folk
music,'' Thompson told Mojo. ``I'd watch my parents on stage and
cringe. Dad would close his eyes and and I thought that was so
stupid. Folk sounded horrible, droning away with no drums. I can't
describe how much I hated it. Only in the last couple of years has
that gone away and I'm listening to all the albums and furiously
trying to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it made a difference?: Teddy has a publishing deal but not a
record contract. He appeared with Richard Thompson on his British
tour last January. ``He wasn't obliged to ask me to sing with him.
He's done his fatherly duty. When I sign, I want to do a quick
record, not spend 18 months like Rufus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
