<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-KABILA-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO SEEKS TO STOP RWANDA'S AID TO REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Facing a mounting rebel threat, President
Laurent Kabila of the Congo sought Friday to persuade other African
leaders to press Rwanda to end its support of a 6-day old
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila left the capital, Kinshasa, on Friday to meet with a
senior South African delegation in the southern Congolese city of
Lubumbashi, and then flew to nearby Zimbabwe to confer Friday
evening with regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Lubumbashi meeting ended without comment from either side.
Before the South African delegation left for the Congo on Friday
morning, however, its leader, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo,
reaffirmed South Africa's support for Kabila's rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping that they will be able to normalize the
situation,'' Nzo said. ``That will be our message.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African statement comes at a time when Kabila is
facing sharply eroded diplomatic support, both regionally and
internationally, and is under siege from a well-executed rebellion
that has seized control of much of eastern Congo and is now
mounting increasingly bold attacks in the west.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa was an early and enthusiastic supporter of Kabila's
government, and although it is unlikely to provide any military
support, a strong diplomatic backing for Kabila could sway other
African countries to stand by him.
</P>
<P>
   At the Zimbabwe meeting, Kabila was expected to have his first
face-to-face encounter with leaders of Rwanda, which is widely
believed to be providing strong backing for the rebellion against
his government.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rwanda has repeatedly denied any involvement in the
recent fighting, that country, which backed Kabila's own drive to
take power two years ago, has grown openly disenchanted with
Kabila's moves to weed ethnic Tutsi, whose ancestors originated in
Rwanda, from positions of influence.
</P>
<P>
   Even more serious, from the Rwandan perspective, was Kabila's
inability to stop attacks by anti-Rwandan rebels operating from
Congolese territory.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's failure to clamp down on cross-border rebel activity
has also cost him the support of two other major African allies who
helped bring him to power, Uganda and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's diplomatic effort comes at a time when anti-government
guerrillas have dramatically broadened their campaign against him,
grabbing control of several towns in the country's southwest near
Congo's only seaport, Moanda.
</P>
<P>
   With the rebels in control of these towns, which lie only 300
miles from the capital, few experts expect Kabila's enemies to come
to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``A political settlement would entail that we keep Kabila in his
position, and we are totally opposed to that,'' Commander Sylvain
Bikelenge, the officer in charge of the rebel-held eastern city of
Goma told Reuters. ``We believe that the Congo needs new leadership
working under a broad-based government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the rebel advances of the last week have stunned Kabila,
however, the insurgents have also suffered some setbacks. Reports
from international relief and church workers in the last two days
have confirmed the Congolese government's claim to have at least
temporarily beaten back a rebel attempt to capture the strategic
river port of Kisangani, Congo's third-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   With Kabila leaving the country to meet with fellow heads of
state, there was diplomatic speculation in Kinshasa about whether
he would return there soon, or stay in the southern city of
Lubumbashi to rally fellow southerners to his government's war
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, who was born nearby, used Lubumbashi, an important
mining town, as his headquarters for the second half of his
seven-month war to unseat his predecessor, the longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said that Kabila's best chance at holding onto
power now depended upon a force long exiled in Angola, known as the
Katangese Gendarmes, who fought in Angola's long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The Katangese, southerners like Kabila, form one of the
principal components of the new national army that Kabila has been
attempting to build since defeating Mobutu's forces, but diplomats
say that many of their leaders have felt shunned by the new
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kabila's best shot at this point lies with the Katangese,''
said one Western diplomat. ``If he can get them to fight for him,
than maybe, just maybe, he'll be able to hold on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
