<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-COULTER-$ADV09-N     08-07 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-COULTER-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE THE PENSION, A GOLDEN PARACHUTE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.C.)   (af)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When is a pension plan more than just a pension plan?
</P>
<P>
   When it potentially offers a multimillion-dollar ``golden
parachute'' to a young chief executive who recently sold his
company in one of the decade's biggest merger deals.
</P>
<P>
   Read between the lines of the employment contract for David A.
Coulter, BankAmerica's chief executive, with the new company being
created from his bank's proposed $67 billion merger with
Nationsbank, and some interesting figures emerge.
</P>
<P>
   If Coulter, 50, retires from the new company, he is scheduled to
receive annual pension payments equal to 95 percent of his 1997
salary and bonus at BankAmerica. That amount is not spelled out in
the contract but can easily be tracked down using executive
salaries disclosed in BankAmerica's proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Coulter received a salary of $987,500 and a bonus of
$4.25 million _ or total compensation of about $5.24 million. His
new pension plan thus guarantees him annual payments of $4.98
million upon retirement until his death. This would be in addition
to tens of millions of dollars in stock options he could exercise
upon his departure.
</P>
<P>
   If his wife is alive upon his death, she would receive
survivor's benefits worth about $3.7 million annually until her own
death. Coulter's current pension is worth only a relatively paltry
$810,153 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Coulter may not choose to retire soon. He is going to
be president of the combined company. And when the merger was
announced in April, both boards said they intended for Coulter to
eventually succeed Nationsbank's chief executive, Hugh L. McColl
Jr., as chief of the merged bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger agreement did not guarantee Coulter the top spot.
McColl, 62, who engineered a deal that gives Nationsbank a more
prominent role than that of BankAmerica in the merged company, is
known to enjoy the perquisites and power that come with the chief
executive's job and has shown no signs that he plans to step down
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and bank advisers have speculated that when McColl
does depart, his job will go instead to a Nationsbank executive
loyal to him.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Coulter does not get the big job, he may still stay at
the combined company. Indeed, Coulter, a San Francisco resident, is
now shopping for a new home in Charlotte, N.C., where Nationsbank
is based and where the headquarters of the merged company will be
situated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Coulter's bountiful retirement package attracted the
attention of Graef Crystal, editor of the Crystal Report, a
newsletter on executive compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they artfully built it around a pension so people
wouldn't realize what was going on here,'' Crystal said. ``I find
it all very obfuscatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument in the early 1980s was that golden parachutes
were needed to create a level playing field so CEOs wouldn't get in
the way of sensible mergers,'' he added. ``But now it has tilted
too far the other way because there are untold riches to be reaped
from selling your company.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter was unavailable for comment. A BankAmerica spokesman
cited language in Coulter's employment agreement which said that
both banks determined ``it is in the best interests of their
respective shareholders to assure that'' Coulter continued to work
at the new company once the merger was completed.
</P>
<P>
   If Coulter does take advantage of his pension plan and retire
from the merged company in the near future, Crystal said, it would
be only the latest in a series of increasingly outsized payouts to
departing chief executives. He cited the $42 million payment
recently granted to William J. Catacosinos, former head of the Long
Island Lighting Co., as part of New York State's partial takeover
of the utility.
</P>
<P>
   And Robert J. Eaton, Chrysler's chairman and chief executive, is
scheduled to receive $24.4 million if he quits or is dismissed
during the two years after his company merges with Daimler-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter has had a brief tenure as BankAmerica's chief executive,
and Crystal finds it curious that he was ready to cede control so
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coulter had only been CEO for a few years, so why was he so
ready to step down?'' Crystal asked. ``He may have decided it's
time to clean up and go out and lie on the nearest beach to San
Francisco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
