<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKEN-TRUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF BOY ABUSED BY PRIEST LOOKS AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Note material in 10th graf may offend some readers.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGTON, N.H. _ When Thomas Harding enters St. Peter's Church
Sunday morning, the emotional hurt may be as great as the physical
pain that dogs his every step.
</P>
<P>
   For tomorrow, at the 10:45 a.m. Mass, Harding will worship for
the first time since the parish priest's conviction last week for
sexually abusing his teenage son. Harding has clashed with
parishioners over the years, but the friction became more intense
once he sought the prosecution of Reverend Roger Fortier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared what's going to happen when I walk into church. I
really am,'' Harding, 52, said in an interview at his cramped home.
``In my mind, I see some frantic person saying, `You put him away
for life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Harding will enter the plain brick church with his grandson,
walk toward the left-middle pew he always uses, and await the
reaction of neighbors and friends with whom he has worshipped and
socialized for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   What Harding will discover is whether the anger, the contempt,
and the telephone calls will give way to forgiveness. But despite
last week's verdict, Harding believes some people are still
unwilling to believe their pastor was a sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize you're talking about a priest, someone you
were brought up to respect,'' Harding said. ``You don't mess with
the priest, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Harding's son Joseph, a former altar boy, accused Father Fortier
last October of sexually abusing him in 1994 and 1995. Since the
priest's arrest, feelings of anguish and betrayal have wracked a
large family devoted to the church.
</P>
<P>
   Father Fortier was Harding's close friend, a man who shared
coffee with Harding, a severely disabled machinist, nearly every
morning. He celebrated Thanksgiving, Christmas and children's
birthdays with the family. He confided deep secrets to Harding,
including the fact he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Harding turned from confidant, to victim. After
another family accused the priest of sexual assaulting a teenager,
Joseph Harding took his father aside last year and confided that
Father Fortier had also abused him.
</P>
<P>
   The priest had shown the boy pornographic videos in the rectory;
he had fondled his crotch; he had performed oral sex on him.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Father Fortier was convicted of sexual abuse in both
cases. He could be sentenced to 20 years in prison on each of eight
counts and still faces trial involving a third youth. &UR;  &LR; Father
Fortier is expected to be sentenced in October.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal has tested the faith of a family whose home is filled
with religious images, and who trusted the priest to take Joseph on
the kind of outings Harding could not manage himself. For Harding,
the chance to have apriest take Joseph, the youngest of 11
children, to the mall and other destinations seemed a blessing for
a man who once thought he might never walk again. ``I felt good
that he could do that.'' said Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the feeling toward the priest is far different. ``I miss
Roger Fortier for the friend that I thought he was, but I hate
Roger Fortier today for the person he turned out to be,'' Harding
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although Harding can speak of hate for Father Fortier, that
emotion is not shared by many parishioners among the 300 families
who comprise St. Peter's Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardings' decision to press charges against the popular
priest was greeted with disdain by some friends and neighbors,
Harding said. People with whom he had worshipped for decades moved
away from him at church, and on the street, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the parish say Harding's longstanding difficulties
with churchmembers have more to do with his past involvement in
church administration than with the Father Fortier case.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, meanwhile, has stated he will not return to St. Peter's.
But his father is adamant that he will not be pushed away.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Young, whose son was the other victim of sexual abuse,
feels betrayed by Father Fortier but said the church is a
``loving'' one that will heal and become stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Harding recalls only three people who offered him encouragement
in the nine months from Father Fortier's arrest to conviction. The
priest did not apologize to the family after the verdict, said
Harding, who added that the Diocese of Manchester had not contacted
them directly.
</P>
<P>
   Harding resigned last week as grand knight of the local Knights
of Columbus, the Catholic men's group. His last official act was to
remove Father Fortier from the group.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cilley, director of religious education at the church,
said he is not aware of any hard feelings. ``I feel that the people
of St. Peter's are good people who work very hard for their parish
community as well as the community of Farmington,'' Cilley added.
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Eddy Bisson, the new pastor at St. Peter's, said he
will not have a chance to speak about the subject at Mass tomorrow
because a visiting missionary is scheduled to lead the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's just as well,'' Father Bisson said. ``This way,
we can see what people may be feeling and keep an eye out on the
church a bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding stressed that his anger is directed at Father Fortier _
and not at his religion, or the church where he served as
administrative assistant from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someday I can forgive him, but I can never forget what
he did,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to pick myself up from this and become a better
person _ one with respect. I had it before, and I'll have it
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
