<P>
   Editors, The New York Times is planning a package of stories in
connection with the terrorist attacks on the U.S. embassies in
Nairobi and Dar es Salaam:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Ledeall: Two massive bombs
exploded three minutes apart outside U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on Friday morning, killing more than 80 other people,
including several Americans (figures to come), in what officials
said were coordinated terrorist attacks. In Washington, President
Clinton condemned the attacks as abhorrent and inhuman acts of
cowardice. He vowed to bring those responsible to justice ``no
matter what or how long it takes.'' By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ Clinton administration officials said
that while no one had claimed responsibility for the bombings, the
attacks had probably been carried out by one of a small number of
terrorist groups that had taken aim at American installations in
the past. The government has sent teams of FBI agents, military
medical officers and explosives experts to Kenya and Tanzania to
aid in the investigation. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SCENE (Nairobi) _ The carnage and chaos at the site of
the Kenya bombing. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SECURITY (Washington) _ The two bombed embassies did not
meet the security standards set for the State Department's overseas
posts by an independent review panel created following terrorist
attacks against the American embassy and marine barrack in Beirut.
The embassies had never been modified because the White House and
Congress had never provided enough money, officials said. By James
Risen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS (Undated) _ What we can learn about the American
victims. 300-400 words early; possibly growing later.
</P>
