u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROWDED-CEMETERY-BOS &LR;      08-07 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWDED-CEMETERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD VETS' FUNERALS CROWD MILITARY CEMETERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURNE, Mass. _ At the Massachusetts National Cemetery here,
funeral processions queue up with military-like precision to keep
pace with a schedule that on some days dictates an interment every
15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Military honors _ the firing of rifle volleys and the playing of
``Taps'' _ are provided far more often now by tape than by buglers
and service personnel. And because graves are dug and filled in
bunches, funeral parties are not allowed to hold graveside
services.
</P>
<P>
   As the World War II generation passes away in record numbers,
the national cemetery, the only one of its kind in New England, is
struggling to keep up. Set on 750 acres adjacent to the
Massachusetts Military Reservation, the cemetery is charged with
providing an honorable burial at no cost to the nation's veterans
and their spouses. But providing a personal touch at a very
difficult time is no easy task for a cemetery that averages 9 to 10
funerals a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for some people, but the cemetery has a system that
works,'' said Robert Studley, regional partner for the Loewen chain
of funeral homes. ``If you're not there at the proper time, you're
put way back in the line, and there can be a wait.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Veterans Administration, which runs the
cemetery here and 114 others around the country, the passing of the
World War II generation will result in a steady increase in veteran
burials over the coming years, peaking at 620,000 in 2008. The
national cemetery in Bourne handles 2,100 burials a year, and the
number is expected to increase to as high as 3,000 over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   All veterans with discharges other than dishonorable, their
spouses, and their dependent children are eligible for burial in a
national cemetery. The government covers the cost of the grave, the
grave opening, the grave liner, and the grave marker, all of which
would cost at least $2,000 at many private cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt W. Rotar, director of the Massachusetts National Cemetery,
says it has plenty of room and adds that his staff, increasing from
22 to 25 full-time personnel next year, should be able to keep pace
with demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cemetery system is one of the few agencies in the Veterans
Administration that are expanding rather than consolidating,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rotar, a veteran himself, acknowledges that the
one-size-fits-all approach of the cemetery is not to everyone's
liking, although he said he does his best to accommodate everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Burials can be scheduled every 15 minutes from 9:30 a.m. to
11:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. to 3 p.m. Most funerals queue up in front
of the administration building, where they are met by cemetery
staff. They are given a map showing the location of the gravesite
and then directed to one of two partially enclosed committal
shelters. After a brief service of no more than 20 minutes, the
family departs and cemetery personnel take the casket to the
gravesite for burial.
</P>
<P>
   Graveside services are not permitted because graves are dug and
filled in batches. ``It wouldn't be a safe or a dignified
environment,'' said Rotar, noting that there are backhoes, dump
trucks, and workers at the gravesites.
</P>
<P>
   Military honors, provided at the discretion of local military
commanders, are becoming less and less common, in part because of
recent base closings. Rotar estimates military honors are provided
about twice a month, and often the military personnel have to
travel from New York near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only 500 buglers in the whole military, but we seem
to have quite a few here in New England,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Mason, an ex-Marine who serves on an advisory committee
to the cemetery that is building a memorial to prisoners of war and
soldiers missing in action, said the cemetery does a great job.
``The dignity and integrity of the service is not sacrificed at
all,'' he said. ``I don't know how they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   William Forbush, who served in the Army in New Guinea during
World War II, was at the cemetery recently checking it out with his
wife. They liked the manicured landscape, the stone walls, and the
tasteful Cape Cod-style administration building.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Why do you want to go down there, to save some
money?''' he said. ``But I feel it's an honor to be buried with my
comrades.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, however, was a bit troubled by the cemetery's policy
against graveside services. ``To me, it's final to see the casket
interred,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   William Green, a retired Marine Corps captain, said he attended
a service at the cemetery and was turned off by how sterile it was.
``You're not allowed to see the body interred, so there's no real
sense of finality,'' he said. ``They don't even play `Taps.' It's
on this scratchy recording.''
</P>
<P>
   Green also said he preferred a headstone or a cross to the
plaques used at the park-style Bourne cemetery. He said he thought
a long time about it before deciding not to be buried there.
</P>
<P>
   To ease some of the pressure on the National Cemetery,
Massachusetts, with the help of federal grants, is developing
veterans cemeteries in Agawam and Winchendon that should be open in
the next two years. An estimated 600,000 veterans live in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans who entered the service from Massachusetts, died while
a legal resident, or lived here at least five years will be
eligible for a free burial. Spouses, however, will have to pay
$300.
</P>
<P>
   Although the policies of the state veterans cemeteries will be
similar to the national one in Bourne, there are some key
differences. The state cemeteries will feature chapels instead of
committal shelters and upright white grave stones rather than
plaques. And state officials hope to enlist veterans groups to
provide military honors for nearly every burial.
</P>
<P>
   Bob McKean, director of state veterans cemeteries, said he sent
out applications for the new cemeteries just last week and has
already received 200 back. ``It's astounding, the response,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 1954EDT &QL; 
