<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS GAIN, BUT IT'S TOO EARLY TO CHEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market rallied for a third day Friday as
investors bought stocks whose prices had been pummeled during, and
even before, the headline-grabbing sell-off that began in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the three-day rally, the major market measures
still ended the week down sharply, with the Dow Jones industrial
average off 3.2 percent and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks down 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many concerns around this market,'' said
Marshall Acuff, an equity strategist with Salomon Smith Barney.
``The market is going to remain volatile until they are all worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The buying of battered stocks kept the technology-heavy Nasdaq
index and the Russell index of 2,000 smaller-company stocks well
above water, but still off their highs for the day. The Nasdaq
finished up 17.26 points, or nine-tenths of 1 percent, at 1,846.77,
while the Russell ended at 415.80, up 9.18, or 2.3 percent.
Advancing stocks outnumbered decliners 2 to 1, another positive
turn for the market.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the Dow and the S&AMP;P gave up their gains in Friday
afternoon trading was a signal of continued volatility _ and
continuing investor concern. It seemed that after a turbulent week,
in which the Dow suffered its third- worst one-day point decline
ever, investors were just tired or wanted to take what profits they
could from the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is another sign that the blue chips have further to
decline,'' said Ralph Acampora, director of technical research at
Prudential Securities, whose sudden switch to bearishness on
Tuesday helped knock the Dow down 299.43 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and the S&AMP;P index, which are dominated by the
bigger-company stocks that many investors now feel are overpriced,
sank into negative territory Friday afternoon. The Dow struggled
back to finish up 20.34 points, or two-tenths of 1 percent, at
8,598.02. It had been up 112 points. The S&AMP;P ended off 0.18 point
at 1,089.45, after hitting 1,102.54.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's early rally was helped by an apparently favorable July
employment report. Despite the distortions from the nearly
eight-week strike against General Motors, the data showed that the
domestic economy, especially the service sector, is still quite
robust.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still reminders of the worries that helped send
the Dow industrials down 9.1 percent before the end-of-the-week
rally. The drag on American exports and manufacturing from the
economic crisis in Asia was reflected in the generally weak
increase of 66,000 nonfarm jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   And as the stock market was rallying, the Japanese yen tumbled
and is now weaker than it was when the United States and Japan
intervened in the foreign exchange market to support the currency
in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed weakness in the yen is a result of the lack of
confidence in the new Japanese government's ability to turn the
nation's economy around, a necessary ingredient in any economic
rebound across Asia. The new Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's first
policy statement to Parliament Friday just added to the
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has tried to shrug off Asia, but I think the
problems there are getting worse,'' said David Jones, chief
economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. ``Japan is becoming a modern
macroeconomic policymakers' nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, was more confident about the economic outlook. ``When you
look at the core forces underlying the market they remain in good
working order,'' he said. ``So the sky is not falling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The role battered stocks have played in the market rebound that
began on Wednesday can be seen in the performance of the
semiconductor industry, oil stocks and smaller-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about demand from Asia and climbing inventories had sent
semiconductor stocks, including Advanced Micro Devices,
Motorola &UR;  &LR; and Teradyne tumbling. The Philadelphia semiconductor
index, which also includes Intel, had fallen 29.5 percent from its
February high to its low June 15. But in the last three days of the
trading week the index was up 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks had also been off sharply as the price of oil
plunged. The Philadelphia oil service index, which includes
Halliburton &UR;  &LR; and Schlumberger, dropped 48.5 percent from May 1 to
Wednesday. But on Thursday and Friday, the index jumped 7.8
percent. The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of major oil companies,
including Exxon and Chevron, rose 3.3 percent Friday after falling
16.8 percent since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, the Russell index of smaller company stocks had fallen
almost 19 percent from its high in April to a 1998 low on
Wednesday. But over the next two days it jumped 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the jobs and wage data in the July
employment report did not upset investors because it supported the
view that the Federal Reserve, whose policymaking committee meets
on Aug. 18, will leave interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 20/32, to 107 4/32, while the
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.63
percent from 5.67 percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
