<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CABLE-TV-600(     08-07 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CABLE-TV-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL IS GOOD NEWS TO ALL-NEWS NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The images hardly make for compelling television: mostly Monica
Lewinsky getting out of cars and Kenneth Starr getting into them.
The talking heads make up a largely over-exposed collection of
former prosecutors, defense attorneys and pundits. And often there
hasn't been a whole lot of hard news to headline.
</P>
<P>
   But for 24-hour cable news networks like MSNBC, CNBC, Fox News
and CNN, all that does not seem to matter. The questions that would
dominate dinner party conversation these days are apparently enough
to sustain what some have come to call ``All Monica All the Time'':
Will the dress test positive? Will the president submit his saliva?
What is Ms. Lewinsky's state of mind?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the talk show clatter, the Monica Lewinsky story is big
business, meaning more revenue and higher ratings to shows that
mostly struggle at the margins, looking for, at best, the
mysterious murder of a beauty queen.
</P>
<P>
   Where initially this kind of round-the-clock coverage, ushered
in by the Gulf War, appeared to be dictated by news developments,
now it seems largely fueled by the bottom line. All-news channels
depend on events like the O.J. Simpson trial, the death of Princess
Diana and now the trials and tribulations of President Clinton for
their very survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs live or die on issues of this sort,'' said
Marvin Kalb, director of the Shorenstein Center on the Press,
Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University. ``Because talk is
the cheapest form of entertainment, it can fill hours of air time
at the lowest possible cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable news executives say they are simply responding to the
demands of the marketplace. ``Do I think we're crisis-driven now?
No,'' said John Moody, vice president of news editorial at Fox
News. ``The nation's viewing habits are changing. There's always
someone who wants to find out what's going on. This is not a
country that's all at home at 6:30 to watch Dan or Peter or Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   But media experts say cable news networks are not yet
established enough to eat into the networks in the absence of a big
breaking story. ``The worst thing that can happen to a CNN is for
there not to be a Monica Lewinsky or an O.J. Simpson or a war,
because you don't get any of these peaks and surges in viewing,''
said Gerbrandt. ``No news is bad news for these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the cable universe is so much smaller than the broadcast
universe, media experts say _ 66 million households vs. 100
million, according to one estimate _ a little lift goes a long way.
A story like this one, for example, can boost a program's rating
from a 0.1 or 0.3 to a 0.3 or a 0.6. ``In broadcast terms, that's
nothing,'' said John P. Ellis, a marketing and advertising
consultant who has advised CNBC. ``But in cable terms, it's called
doubling your audience. To cable news people, Monica is a huge
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a story like the Lewinsky scandal not only helps
fledgling all-news cable shows build ratings and get noticed,
television experts say, it goes straight to the bottom line,
particularly because these programs have fixed costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A case like this, for cable news shows over the coming year,
is probably worth in the tens of millions of dollars,'' said Larry
Gerbrandt, a senior analyst with Paul Kagan Associates Inc. a
Carmel, Calif.-based media research and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how long it drags out, maybe even in the
hundreds,'' Gerbrandt continued, ``because future ad time is based
on historic viewing patterns. So the benefit really comes over the
next year to 18 months.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For what are called spot advertising buys _ time that has not
been purchased in advance _ for example, cable news channels can
adjust their prices upwards depending on the daily Nielsen ratings
data, Ellis explained. ``Cable news is very spot market heavy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the cable shows may reach a relatively small audience
compared with the networks, media experts say, their influence is
considerably broader. Networks and print organizations, cable news
executives note, are fueled by the constant scandal updates
available from their cable competitors. ``When the soap opera on
the news channels is better than the soap opera on the networks,
then I think it does provide a certain amount of pressure,'' Moody
said. ``Despite protestations that we're saturating America's
living rooms with tawdry detail, that same detail is exactly what's
being demanded by our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this means people like Geraldo Rivera are having a very
good time. Prime time ratings for his program, ``Rivera Live'' on
CNBC, which has devoted its hour to the Lewinsky-Clinton story
night after night, are up nearly 30 percent for the month of July
compared with the same period last year, from 438,000 households to
567,000.
</P>
<P>
   ```Rivera Live' has clearly found its niche,'' Rivera said.
``It's by seeking the nuance and promising your audience that
you'll report every significant development that you build an
expectation that, when push comes to shove, there's only one show
to turn to.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``Hardball With Chris Matthews,'' which started a
year and a half ago and appears just before Rivera's program on
CNBC, saw its prime-time ratings increase 57 percent for July
compared with last year and 147 percent in the program's midnight
time slot, when it is rebroadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cable news anchors are quite so proud. Keith Olbermann,
whose program ``White House in Crisis'' on MSNBC was started in
February in response to the Lewinsky story, has done some public
chest-thumping about his own coverage. In a May 23 speech to his
alma mater, Cornell University, he said: ``There are days now when
my line of work makes me ashamed, makes me depressed, makes me cry
... . About three weeks ago, I awakened from my stupor on this
subject and told my employers that I simply could not continue
doing this show about the endless investigation and the
investigation of the investigation, and the investigation of the
investigation of the investigation. I had to choose what I felt in
my heart was right, over what I felt in my wallet was smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Olbermann, who declined to comment, is still on the air
every night, discussing the latest Lewinsky speculation on MSNBC's
``The Big Show.'' Erik Sorensen, the executive vice president in
charge of programming at MSNBC who only started at the network last
week, said this kind of ambivalence comes with the territory.
``There is a lot about this story that a lot of us covering it
aren't particularly crazy about,'' he said. ``But that's what we do
for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable news shows have been criticized on the Lewinsky story,
along with the mainstream press, for vamping without substance and
for vague attribution. Indeed, Gerbrandt suggested that the report
about nerve gas in Vietnam, which got CNN into trouble recently,
was an example of an ill-fated effort to generate excitement in a
slow news period. ``That story on nerve gas is the result of a CNN
trying to make sure they have an ongoing series of reports that can
attract viewers,'' Gerbrandt said, ``realizing that you can't count
on a scandal or a disaster or a trial of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, correspondents say their information is no less
reliable because they have so much time to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, for example, made a point of saying on the air last week
that he stood by his report of Aug. 4 alleging that the infamous
dress had tested positive for ``human genetic material,'' which he
attributed to ``one source very close to the president.'' NBC last
week sent out a message warning its other reporters not to pick up
Rivera's report and saying the network had not confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been wrong yet,'' Rivera said. ``In that sense, I'm
still living as queen for a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is viewing newscasters like Rivera as
royalty. ``For me, I am finding _ as there is this explosion of
talk, talk, talk _ that I cannot listen to the din,'' said Kalb of
Harvard. ``I'm not learning anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton story shows few signs of receding, cable
news executives acknowledge that there will come a time when Ms.
Lewinsky will be old news. ``I'm already losing sleep over it,''
said Sorensen of MSNBC. ``Inevitably, this story is going to end
and, as an all-news channel, we rely on reality _ and we need
reality to cooperate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
