<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CURRENCY-ART-$     08-07 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CURRENCY-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH STOCKS SLUMPING, CURRENCY TRADING SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The refrain on foreign exchange trading desks these days is:
``Volatility is being very good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most currency traders don't miss what was for them the dull,
trendless and not very profitable trading that dominated the
mid-1990s. It has given way to big daily movements and strong
trends in many currencies, especially those at the heart of the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The forces that are causing the volatility have helped to
unsettle other financial markets, and the atmosphere of higher risk
played a role in Wall Street's big drop in the last few weeks. But
trends are favorable for the international bankers, traders and
investors who make part of their living from movements in
currencies, whether up or down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nice time to be a foreign exchange dealer,'' said
Robert White, the treasurer of Standard Chartered Bank. ``That
volatility provides opportunities for risk-taking and brings in
customer business'' as investors and financial managers try to
hedge against adverse moves or buy currencies to help them enter or
exit fast-moving investments around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Craig A. Puffenberger, the head of global foreign exchange
options at Credit Suisse First Boston, put it another way: ``The
volatility gives us opportunities to find things to buy cheaply and
to sell them expensively.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is good for money traders and banks, of course, is not
necessarily good for everyone. The increased volatility and sharp
strengthening of the dollar against many currencies have caused
some problems.
</P>
<P>
   For American companies, a stronger dollar makes their products
more expensive and less competitive abroad. It makes imports
cheaper and more competitive in this country. Big-name companies
like Coca-Cola, Dow Corning, Union Carbide and 3M all said the
strong dollar had contributed to the weakness in their latest
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Currency volatility increases the uncertainty for companies
doing business abroad and for investors who put their money to work
in overseas markets. This uncertainty raises their costs as they
hedges to protect themselves against unexpected plunges or
increases in a currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-rate doubts also can reach into the pocketbooks of the
average tourist, abruptly raising or lowering costs for hotels and
plane tickets from one day to the next.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the revived volatility are many, including the
collapse of economies in Asia, the inability of Japan to overcome
its economic malaise and the threat of a financial crisis in Russia
that could spread elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Fand, the senior foreign exchange strategist at
BankBoston, thinks the market has taken its eye off the economic
fundamentals that moved currencies in the past, like differences
between interest rates and inflation rates around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the market is moved by themes _ the presumed
inadequacies of the new Japanese government, for example. ``The
market attaches much more significance to these themes,'' he said,
adding that traders could fixate on one as quickly as they could
forget another.
</P>
<P>
   The gyrations in Asian and emerging-markets currencies have
helped offset the loss of profit opportunities in Europe, where
volatility has evaporated ahead of the Jan. 1, 1999 introduction of
Europe's single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   From its high to its low this year, the dollar has moved just
5.5 percent against the German mark. In contrast, the Japanese yen
has had three big moves _ 3.8 percent, 4.5 percent and 6.9 percent
_ against the dollar in just the last eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some beneficiaries of currency volatility have been the big
banks that are the major players in the foreign exchange market,
with its activity of $1.4 trillion a day.
</P>
<P>
   At Chase Manhattan Bank, for example, revenue from foreign
exchange trading jumped 70 percent in the first quarter of this
year and 58 percent in the second quarter. Foreign exchange revenue
at Citibank rose 17 percent in the first quarter and 50 percent in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While these returns are not a major source of revenue, they have
contributed to the strong performance of these banks' stocks this
year. Chase is up 26.4 percent for the year, and Citicorp, the
parent of Citibank, is up 19.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies may or may not stay volatile. A rebound in Asia or a
turnaround in the financial outlook for Russia could make them more
stable.
</P>
<P>
   But banks that trade currencies have been lifted for now, at
least, out of the doldrums of a few years ago. Back then, low
volatility, the broadening use of electronic trading and concerns
about the arrival of the single currency in Europe led to layoffs
and closures of trading desks _ as well as a decline in revenue
from currency trading.
</P>
<P>
   Donald H. Layton, vice chairman of global markets-international
at Chase Manhattan, said the higher revenue was coming from three
sources: proprietary trading, in which the bank bets its own money
on the direction of currencies; higher volumes of trading from
customers, which these days are predominantly money managers, hedge
funds and others moving money around the the world; and the bigger
spreads, or differences between the buying and selling prices of
currencies that come with higher volatility. The larger spreads add
to the revenue and profits from trading.
</P>
<P>
   Layton acknowledged that trading in more volatile markets
``means there is more risk.'' But he said the banks could handle
that partly because more of their foreign exchange revenue comes
from customer dealings than from proprietary trading.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of this, he said, is the inconsequential fallout
from the surprising intervention on June 17 by the United States
and Japan to support the yen, which moved 4.7 percent higher in one
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intervention for the market was a major event, but it was
not a major profit- and-loss event to the banks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Peabody, the bank analyst at Mitchell Securities, is
more concerned about bank reliance on currency volatility.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report to clients, Peabody said the rise in
volatility was one reason that bank activities like underwriting,
mergers and acquisitions, trading, and handling of international
capital flows have done so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reversal of a strong U.S. dollar and low long-term interest
rates should prove disruptive to market-sensitive sources of
revenues, the mainstay of the current double-digit
earnings-per-share growth in the banking industry,'' he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
