<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CWA-BELL-BOS &LR;      08-07 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CWA-BELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC, UNION, TRY TO BEAT STRIKE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bell Atlantic Corp. and a union representing 3,500 New England
telephone service employees inched closer to easing mandatory
overtime requirements and inflexible work schedules at the
bargaining table this week, but remained far apart on the use of
outside contractors, a union official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications giant the Communications Workers of
America negotiated throughout the day and into the evening in an
attempt to reach an accord before a strike deadline of midnight
Saturday. The company is also bargaining with the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which represents 15,000
telephone operators and technicians in New England, while a third
set of talks are being held with the CWA representing workers from
southern New York to Virigina.
</P>
<P>
   All three sides seemed hopeful of averting a strike, which would
affect customer, directory, and repair services to an estimated 3
million customers in Massachusetts with 4.5 million customer
telephone lines. New York-based Bell Atlantic serves about 40
million telephone lines from Maine to Virginia, and overall has
some 83,000 workers represented by the CWA and IBEW.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the company is preparing for the possibility of a
walkout, Bell Atlantic spokesman in Boston, Jack Hoey, said: ``Our
objective is to get an agreement. Therefore, we are focusing all
our efforts on the collective bargaining process.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the CWA and IBEW have authorized strikes against Bell
Atlantic, as well as against Atlanta-based BellSouth Corp., which
provides service in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut Friday, Southern New England Telecommunications
Inc. hammered out a contract with a local branch of the CWA,
averting a potentially costly strike. Under the agreement, 6,300
union workers will get wage increases of 11 percent over the next
32 months. The new contract also calls for improved health care and
pension benefits, according to the company and the Communications
Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   CWA officials dealing with Bell Atlantic, while frustrated over
the company's use of outsourcing, seemed hopeful that a new
contract would include such changes in mandatory overtime as
advanced scheduling notice and exemptions for parents with
inflexible childcare arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making some progress in terms of scheduling and the
amount of short-term leave an employee will be allowed to take for
emergencies such as taking a child to the doctor, but we are
getting down to the wire with the contracting issue,'' Kathy
McGreevey, secretary-treasurer of CWA Local 1400 in Portsmouth,
N.H., said Friday. ``There is no movement on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic said it would not comment on details of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service employees now work an average of 7.5 hours a
day, with overtime ranging from two to 15 hours per week, McGreevey
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said workers are allowed five days for personal time, but
are required to take a full day off when they need to be away from
the job for two or three hours, and they are discouraged from
taking vacations. Even so, the two sides seemed to be moving toward
language permitting more scheduling flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are at the point where they don't care about the
money,'' McGreevey said. ``The issue for them is remembering what
their family looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if agreements are reached on quality of life issues,
CWA's key demand _ that the company limit its use of outside
contractors _ is not one Bell Atlantic is likely to yield on to
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key sticking point for us is the work they want to move to
Bell Atlantic subsidiaries staffed with contractors who make $7 per
hour with no benefits,'' Melissa Morin, president of Local 1400,
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially, almost all of the work our service
representatives do would be affected. In Massachusetts, that means
1,800 service representatives could lose jobs during a gradual
moveout over a year or two. In New England, about 3,500 jobs are at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Morin added that the average customer service representative
earns $21 per hour, with full benefits. She said about 50 different
new contractors have started doing marketing work for the company
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step will be to eliminate the full-time technicians
and repair people,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
