<HEADLINE>
CHART READERS SEE LITTLE PROMISE OF A RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The steep drop in equity prices over the last two weeks may have
surprised many people, particularly those whose portfolios contain
little more than blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts known as market technicians, who use performance
charts to find price trends and cyclical movements in stocks, had
been seeing cracks for weeks, if not months.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the seemingly arcane indicators they watch _ 10-day
advance/decline ratios, upside volume versus downside volume, the
30-day moving average of the New York Stock Exchange composite
index _ were sounding alarm bells even as narrower market measures
like the Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index marched to new records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change in the market over the past 13 sessions as opposed
to the past three months is the weakening of the major stocks,''
Phil Roth, chief technical market analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said after the major indexes tumbled more than 3 percent
last Tuesday. ``Many stocks have been acting poorly for some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Mamis, publisher of the Mamis Letter, a weekly letter for
institutional clients, said: ``Tuesday's decline in the Dow, the
S&AMP;P 500 and the NASDAQ composite are the chickens coming home to
roost. My charts show that stocks I follow began to have problems
back in late February.''
</P>
<P>
   To qualify a market as healthy, technicians like to see more
stocks rising in value than declining. They like to see trading
volume in advancing issues outweigh the volume in stocks sold. In
short, they like to see breadth _ rising stocks across a wide range
of industries. They have not seen that in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a severe internal implosion,'' said Alan Shaw,
director of technical research at Salomon Smith Barney. ``Some
weeks ago, we were thinking this looked like 1994, when a lot of
stocks got severely beaten down but the major averages held up. But
then we saw that this was not only like 1994, but 1990 as well,''
when there was a broad downturn in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how stocks in the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 had been
shielded from the broader universe of equities, Roth noted that as
of Tuesday, 64 percent of the stocks that make up the Russell 2000
index, which tracks small companies, had declined more than 20
percent from their highs; 40 percent of those issues have fallen by
more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charts show that the Russell 2000 is down to levels seen last
October,'' he said. ``That would equate to a level of 860 for the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.'' That is 20.5 percent below the
current level, 1,082
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the technicians said they saw few signs that
the selloff had ended, particularly for the stocks that have long
been market leaders, like General Electric, Coca-Cola, Pfizer and
Wal-Mart. A rally is possible, they added, but is not likely to be
sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sellers are still in the market,'' Mamis said. ``We have not
yet had a selling climax, a time when everybody who wanted to sell
can't stand it any more and then sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth of Morgan Stanley disagreed, but only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market looks like it is climaxing,'' he said, noting that
4 of the 10 heaviest-trading days were in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we have seen the final low. I think it could
build a weak base, stage a recovery and then be vulnerable in the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he would like to see a slowing, and then a reversal,
of the number of declining stocks compared with the number of
rising stocks before he would be confident that the selloff was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is trying to get a grip here,'' he said. ``But that
could take a matter of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   For those seeking signs that the selloff is ending, Mamis said
several stocks could be barometers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at issues like Coke, General Electric or Wal-Mart to see
if they rally with any vigor,'' in the event of a general rise in
stock prices, he said, ``or if their rallies are mediocre or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the old leadership fails on the rallies, then I have a real
problem, because they are so vulnerable,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he advised focusing on issues that have been beaten
up in recent months _ basic commodity companies like International
Paper, Georgia Pacific and Alcoa; manufacturers like Deere, or
technology companies like Micron Technology or Motorola. ``I want
to see them not go down if the market goes down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Dow fell further and the Deeres of the world don't go
down any more, the value investor is going to start buying them,''
Mamis said. ``That is the change that has to take place. But in
order for that to happen, the big averages have to make lower
lows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
