<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURMESE ARE TENSE ON EVE OF ANNIVERSARY OF CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Ten years ago Saturday, on the auspicious
date of 8/8/88, Burma erupted in gunfire, the start of a crackdown
on pro-democracy demonstrators that over the next six weeks took
thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the country now known as Myanmar was tense Friday
in advance of the anniversary, as the pro-democracy leader, Daw
Aung San Suu Kyi, stepped up pressure on the ruling military junta.
</P>
<P>
   Following a highly publicized six-day sit-in in her car when
authorities would not allow her to travel to meet her supporters in
the countryside, her party, the National League for Democracy,
refused an invitation Friday to meet with government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a further sign of worsening relations, Mrs. Aung San Suu Kyi
demanded Friday that the military remove a guard detail that has
been stationed for years just within the gate of her compound.
</P>
<P>
   Leaflets have reportedly been distributed calling for
demonstrations on the anniversary and the military has announced
that it would meet street protests with force.
</P>
<P>
   But more than an anniversary is involved. With the economy and
political stature of the ruling junta worsening, Suu Kyi appeared
to be pushing for a confrontation. Few analysts could offer a
scenario under which the junta would willingly surrender power,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we hear suggests they are heading toward a showdown
one way or another,'' said a Bangkok-based diplomat who is an
expert on Burma. ``It's fairly clear that both sides are not giving
in. Obviously, we don't know which way it's heading, whether it's a
showdown towards dialogue or a showdown towards crackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The past decade has been a demonstration of the decisive power
of force, and of its limitations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, government offices emptied onto the streets and even
the police marching band joined jubilant pro-democracy
demonstrations. It seemed that an unfocused mass uprising had taken
over a country that for 26 years had suffered under the repressive
one-man rule of U Ne Win.
</P>
<P>
   But the army _ virtually alone in Myanmar _ remained loyal, and
was willing to shoot into crowds. The uprising was quelled and
power remained in the hands of a group of generals loyal to Ne Win,
who formally resigned just before the crackdown but who, according
to many analysts, may still remain a power behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since the uprising, though, the ruling clique can
point to few successes other than its continuing grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   Though the generals liberalized the country's closed economy and
invited foreign investment, the economy is near collapse today,
both as a result of international sanctions and government
mismanagement. Inflation is rising, commerce is stagnant and
industries dependent on foreign investment, like tourism and
garment manufacture, are moribund. The government is struggling to
prevent a second year of rice shortages _ an economic burden that
was one of the catalysts of the 1988 uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are bad in Burma, really bad,'' said Josef Silverstein,
a scholar of Myanmar at Rutgers University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Politically, the government has failed to win the hearts of the
people. Far from shunting Suu Kyi aside and ignoring her in the
state-controlled press, the junta seems obsessed with her,
attacking her regularly in vituperative and colorful prose. The
government so mistrusts its population that it has closed
universities since December 1996 for fear of a student-led uprising
like the one in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The mistrust seems to have affected the leadership itself: for
months, unconfirmed reports have emerged of splits within the
ruling group.
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, the junta has found itself increasingly isolated because
of its human-rights record and its suppression of political
dissent. Western nations led by the United States have instituted a
variety of embargoes, and Washington has barred members of the
leadership from visiting the country.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in a brief victory, Myanmar was inducted into the
influential regional grouping, the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, which turns a blind eye, on principle, on the ``internal
affairs'' of its members.
</P>
<P>
   But when this caused the European Union to cancel two meetings
with the association, and when the junta failed to modify its
behavior, even its Asian neighbors began to distance themselves
from it.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a decade of suppression, Suu Kyi and her followers
remain a potent political force. Through peaceful pressure, a
willingness to be arrested and jailed, and deft public relations,
they have kept the allegiance of many Burmese and have won wide
support abroad.
</P>
<P>
   One source of this support is the compelling personality of Suu
Kyi herself _ confident, unbending, articulate and radiating a
sense of mission and morality.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has raised the stakes, demanding that the National
Assembly convene by Aug. 21, although she has not said what she
would do if that does not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to convene Parliament is an even more potent symbol
for pro-democracy advocates than is the crackdown 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Myanmar's leaders allowed the opposition to contest free
elections in 1990, the National League for Democracy won in a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no transfer of power. The military said it had all
been a misunderstanding, that voters had elected not a government
but a constitutional assembly. Repression of the opposition was
stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can see there has been no improvement at all,''
Suu Kyi said in a recent statement. ``In fact I could say that I am
inclined think that things have even got worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2020EDT &QL; 
