<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGL-EARNINGS-COX     08-07 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGL-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGL users face higher gas bills
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Hundreds of natural gas customers have complained to
the Public Service Commission about higher bills resulting from a
new Atlanta Gas Light billing system.
</P>
<P>
   The company is using the system to prepare for more competition
this fall, when consumer prices for natural gas are no longer
regulated by the PSC and more companies will be allowed compete to
provide the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``My base bill (for July) went from $9.94 to $22.88 and we don't
even use any gas in the summer,'' said Charles Woodliff, a retiree
from Alpharetta. ``We only use it to heat in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   PSC spokesman Shawn Davis explained Atlanta Gas Light has
started annualizing the amount its residential customers pay for
its gas delivery system _ though not for the cost of the gas
itself. Previously, delivery costs rose or fell each month in
relation to the volume of gas each customer used. Now they remain
flat each month.
</P>
<P>
   Under deregulation, Atlanta Gas Light will only deliver gas to
homes and businesses, while marketing companies will be responsible
for selling the gas. AGL Resources, the parent of Atlanta Gas
Light, has created a separate marketing unit to also compete in gas
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly bills from Atlanta Gas Light will still vary depending
on how much gas a customer uses. But summer bills will now tend to
be higher than last year, while bills this winter will tend to be
lower than a year ago, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gas Light calculates its average residential customers
will pay $39.70 more each year under the new billing system. That's
a 6.76 percent increase. Davis said the PSC may take action in the
near future to reduce that increase to the 3 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   The increases are going to a universal service fund, which will
help protect the new marketing companies from uncollectable
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
