<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH08-STRIKE-CO     08-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH08-STRIKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth, union report progress
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- With the contract for most BellSouth employees set to
expire at 11:59 tonight negotiators for the union and company kept
talking, claiming progress toward a last-minute agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Bargainers aim to nail down deals on contracts for six units
that represent 48,000 union workers. The teams for BellSouth and
the Communications Workers of America met most of the night and
will likely spend most of today at the table as the clock ticks
toward the midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday, the spin from the talks at the Ramada Plaza near
Northlake was turning optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is moving fast, but it's slow progress in getting
to where we need to get to,'' said Jimmy Smith, vice president of
the CWA for the Southeast. ``Both sides are working hard at it. I
am very hopeful that we can get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith grew up in a small South Carolina town, the son of a
grocery store owner who hated unions. This is the first contract
confrontation with BellSouth he has managed since succeeding to the
top of the CWA's Southeast office. Early in the talks, he expressed
concern about the BellSouth bargaining team, which includes Tom
Posey, an executive who came from Anheuser-Busch, where labor
relations are especially rocky.
</P>
<P>
   That anxiety has eased somewhat, he said. ``We have a working
relationship,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth spokeswoman Deborah Spicer agreed the two sides have
made progress and pronounced the company pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that we can reach an agreement by the time
the current contract expires.''
</P>
<P>
   Key issues on the table include pensions and medical benefits
for retirees, BellSouth's penchant for sending work to nonunion
contractors and forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Kaufman, economics professor at Georgia State University,
said the union is virtually forced to make those issues priorities.
The union, whose average member has been with BellSouth for 22
years, is not making it a priority to compel BellSouth to bring
more positions under the union umbrella, nor is it focused on
higher pay. Instead, the CWA is using its leverage to win benefits
for its current members, especially longtime workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake are dwindling job opportunities,'' Kaufman
said. ``BellSouth is expanding some nonunion parts of the company,
and the union is feeling some organizational insecurity. And
anytime an organization feels insecure, they can be defensive and
protective.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's total work force has shrunk from a 1990 peak of
103,152 to about 86,188 now. The phone unit, which accounts for
most of the union's members, has been trimmed from 79,453 in 1992
to about 59,700, although that includes a slight uptick in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   For Atlanta and its booming economy, the impact of a strike
would be marginal _ at least if it is a short walkout. BellSouth
may be one of the region's largest employers with about 21,000
employees in Georgia, most in metro Atlanta. But that is a tiny
fraction of a vibrant and growing job market.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the company has also taken pains to prepare managers
to run the phone system, which is already highly automated, so a
strike would not likely mean more than minor nuisances to customers
_ unless it drags on.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, customers could find it hard to get a new line
installed or to even get needed repairs. And with a dozen companies
offering phone services to businesses and consumers being courted
by MediaOne and MGC Communications, BellSouth doesn't want
customers looking elsewhere for help.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks enter what could be the last lap, the union
benefits from that strong economy, since skilled workers are in
high demand. The CWA also could benefit from having a company that
is flush, that has reported quarter after quarter of record sales
and profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sustained expansion of the economy, there is the
desire of unions to catch up,'' said Robert McKersie, professor of
management at Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``We are
seeing more militancy and willingness to bring negotiations right
up to the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the union and company extended talks past the
deadline. They reached a pact several days later, and that could
happen again, McKersie said. ``They may stop the clock and keep
negotiating. But these don't sound like the kind of issues to have
a strike over.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the recent strike against General Motors, the company is
not pushing the union into a corner. Unlike last summer's bitter
walkout against United Parcel Service, the union is not bitter,
angry and ready to flex its muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In negotiations, it's never all one side or the other,'' said
Larry Michel, economist at the Economic Policy Institute. ``But
with a booming economy and the expanded need for communications, it
would be a very tough time for BellSouth to take a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Increased competition
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is moving into a new era, where it expects increased
competition with rivals. There are big players like WorldCom/MCI
and Sprint, smaller competitors like Allegiance Telecom and IGC
Communications. The only other union companies are AT&AMP;T _ which is
struggling to find a strategy _ and the other regional Bell
companies. BellSouth can argue that it is at a disadvantage because
those nonunion rivals need not consider labor agreements when they
plot business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The company can argue that a sweetened deal puts BellSouth at a
disadvantage in the market _ and any chance for a healthy union
depends on a healthy company. The union can respond that is makes
the company stronger by guaranteeing skilled labor.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two sides depend on each other, and the results
of today's last-minute talks are likely to reflect that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
