<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-COX     08-07 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM taking off its Olympic ring
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- IBM is pulling the plug on its Olympic sponsorship
after 38 years of tying its marketing efforts to the five famous
rings.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which suffered a well-publicized black eye because
of technical glitches during the 1996 Atlanta Games, is bailing out
in a dispute with Olympic officials over the high cost of the
worldwide sponsorship program.
</P>
<P>
   After spending more than $100 million to sponsor the 1998 Winter
Games in Nagano, Japan _ and providing much of the technology for
free _ Big Blue wanted future local organizing committees to bear
some of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the negotiations over a new eight-year deal broke down
because Olympic officials want to create a separate sponsorship for
the Games' Internet services and Web sites. In Atlanta and Nagano,
that was part of IBM's overall sponsorship package.
</P>
<P>
   But Olympic officials are likely to be successful in creating
this new sponsorship category _ and the money that goes along with
it _ because of the enormous growth of the Internet, sports
marketing experts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As e-commerce continues to increase, it's a category that
almost certainly justifies its own sponsorship,'' said John
Bevilaqua, an Atlanta sports marketing consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But Bevilaqua said he understands IBM's cost concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic committee can't have it both ways,'' he said.
``You can't continue to ask one company for an escalating price,
while taking away elements of their sponsorship category.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM spokeswoman Debbie Gottheimer said the International Olympic
Committee asked for a ``significant increase'' in the company's
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that was not commensurate with the marketing benefits
we would receive in return,'' Gottheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's global sponsorship will end in 2000 with the Summer Games
in Sydney, Australia. That means officials in Salt Lake City must
work quickly to find new technology sponsors and suppliers for the
2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is likely several IBM rivals will bid on pieces of
the Olympic technology pie now that Big Blue no longer wants to
swallow it whole. Among the potential replacements are computer
maker Hewlett-Packard and software company Novell Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials said they held firm in their negotiations with
IBM because of the feedback from other high-tech companies
interested in becoming sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   As companies expand to more and more markets, the Olympic rings
_ one of the most recognized symbols in the world _ can be a
valuable sales tool.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy also can be risky.
</P>
<P>
   During the Atlanta Games, IBM's image took a big hit when
computer problems were reported around the world just as the
company was pinning its marketing efforts on a flawless
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In Nagano, IBM's performance improved dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
