<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAGER-HEARING-COX     08-07 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAGER-HEARING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyer: Safe house operator doesn't know where boy is
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Faye Yager can't be forced to tell a Connecticut man
where his son is, because there is no evidence that she or her
husband know where the child is, her attorney argued in federal
court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence has been offered showing Faye Yager was with Bonnie and
Randy Rubenstein late last year, but there is no evidence the
Yagers ``have current information about the whereabouts,'' said
Brian Spears, Faye Yager's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Rubenstein, who had custody of his son, Randy, when the
boy was kidnapped by his ex-wife in September 1997, has filed an
$80 million lawsuit in U.S. District Court here against Faye and
Howard Yager.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Yager is the controversial operator of a network of safe
houses that hides children, and generally their mothers, from
allegedly abusive fathers. Rubenstein is asking the judge to force
the Yagers to provide information on the boy's whereabouts. On
Friday, Spears argued there is a risk the child would be harmed if
he were returned.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Connolly, the court-appointed guardian ad litem for Randy
Rubenstein, said there were no allegations of sexual or physical
abuse during divorce and custody proceedings in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling by U.S. District Judge Willis B. Hunt Jr. or a
resumption of hearings isn't expected for at least 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
