<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS     08-07 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudy T again gets &QL; 
most out of a team
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Italy's Carlton Myers launched his last-ditch
3-point try to win the game, and Rudy Tomjanovich was over there on
the near sideline, lifting off like a, well, rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flying,'' he said. ``Going for that rebound, man. That's
definitely the highest I've jumped in years. I think I could have
dunked if I had the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Kiwane Garris, the backup point guard, had the ball
wrapped up in his mitts tighter than a politician holding on to a
dollar, and the United States finally had another win in its grasp.
</P>
<P>
   After 39 grueling minutes and 57 hair-pulling seconds, Garris
made one of two free throws and Rudy T's Dreamers survived with an
80-77 win in the World Championship of Basketball quarterfinals
that was as fraught with significance as it was filled with drama.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Clutchopolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you,'' Tomjanovich said. ``On nights like this, I
wish I was still drinking. Because I'd love to go out and have a
couple beers.''
</P>
<P>
   There surely were celebratory toasts raised Friday night in
Athens tavernas by other members of the small U.S. contingent of
supporters after this win. Not because it was much different from
the way the Dreamers have had to tiptoe through the minefields in
the tournament. But for what it meant.
</P>
<P>
   That is, another measure of validation and vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Now a tough matchup with Russia in the semifinals, and it will
take two more improbable wins to get gold.
</P>
<P>
   Always high U.S. expectations
</P>
<P>
   But they all knew a loss to Italy in the quarterfinals would
have meant their efforts of the past month would have gone to
waste. Back at home, the boycotting Dream Teamers likely would have
chuckled at the inability of their minor-league cousins to fill
their shoes and the majority of fans would have treated their work
with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   When the letters across the front of the uniform jersey say
``USA,'' there is an unspoken expectation that you do not come to
one of these international basketball affairs _ Dream Team or no
Dream Team _ and spend the final weekend slugging it out in the
consolation round to determine whether you finish fifth, sixth,
seventh or eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went 5-1 in the early rounds, and none of that would have
meant anything,'' Rudy T said. ``We lose here, and we go back home
and have people say, `Oh, yeah, we heard you were over there
somewhere and did OK.' You lose, and everything we have
accomplished goes out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   This game had that potential to go over the edge, filled as it
was with all of the expected perils of a Chevy Chase European
vacation. The Dreamers were playing before a mostly hostile crowd,
in a game where Myers was on fire offensively and being helped down
the stretch by what we will, in an attempt not to sound parochial,
describe as generous officiating. That is, if you were Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Italy did not score a field goal in the final 7:22 of the game
but stayed in it to the end thanks to 13 free-throw attempts, all
of which were successful and all but two by Myers, who was
15-for-15 from the line en route to 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamers keep their heads
</P>
<P>
   This game appeared to be lost when the Italians took a 73-66
lead with 4:57 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only natural at that point for guys to do something
crazy, to try to get it all back at once,'' Tomjanovich said.
``Then, you miss a play and they score and a six-point hole becomes
nine or 10. It's like a boulder.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dreamers pushed the boulder back up the hill. They've
been together a month, but in that short time they have taken on
the traits of Rudy T's teams. They don't panic, and they don't
quit.
</P>
<P>
   Against Italy, Tomjanovich used the ``Pasta Plate Plan'' _ throw
it against the wall, and see what sticks. He used Garris and
Michael Hawkins, his two point guards, together down the stretch
with his tall forward Wendell Alexis.
</P>
<P>
   They got a 3-pointer, then a runner from Garris, a steal by
Hawkins and a driving banker from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel something special about this group of guys,''
Tomjanovich said. ``They have been open to our coaching and willing
to listen. They stay together and get things done. That's a sign of
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a basketball fan, that's the kind of stuff you love.
A team is down and pulls off a tough win like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is something special happening around Rudy T again.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Spain game,'' he said, ``a coach here told me a
Greek saying: It's like falling off a building and landing on your
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've landed on our feet twice now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clutchopolis. Where not everything is ruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
