<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3944 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-450(2TAKE     08-07 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHISTICATED TERRORIST GROUPS SUSPECTED IN EMBASSY ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-SCENE, AFRICA-SECURITY,
AFRICA-VICTIMS)  
(lh) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials said the attacks
on two U.S. embassies in East Africa only minutes apart Friday
probably were carried out by one of a small number of sophisticated
terrorist groups that had targeted U.S. installations in the past.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ordered teams of FBI agents, medical military
specialists and explosives experts to leave immediately for Africa
to track down the bombers and aid the victims. While few terrorism
investigations overseas have ever borne fruit, Clinton vowed to
bring the bombers to justice.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the United States, the governments of Israel
and South Africa said that they would also participate in the
rescue effort. The South African air force said it would send a
Boeing 707, capable of carrying up to 60 casualties, to transport
some of the injured from Kenya to a military hospital in Pretoria,
the South African capital.
</P>
<P>
   Israel said it was sending a search-and-rescue team to Kenya to
help free victims trapped in the rubble of the embassy building in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that Defense Secretary William Cohen had
spoken Friday with Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai of Israel,
about the bombings in East Africa and other issues. Defense
Department officials said the conversation was routine and that
Israel would play no special role in the investigation of the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. intelligence official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that based on early circumstantial evidence, the
investigators were focusing on followers of Osama bin Laden, a
multimillionaire Saudi-born financier who has sworn to wage a holy
war on the United States and its interests abroad. The U.S.
official declined to describe the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Laden and a group of extremist Muslim clerics
called on their followers to kill Americans. He is considered a
prime suspect in a 1996 terrorist bombing of an American apartment
complex in Saudi Arabia in which 19 American airmen were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said there were also suspicions
that the attacks in East Africa may have been carried out by the
Jihad, or Holy War, organization in Egypt, an Islamic extremist
group that warned earlier this week of ``reprisals'' against the
United States over its purported involvement in the extradition to
Egypt of three of its members who were arrested in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the early hours of this, and it's too early to finger
anybody,'' said another senior administration official, cautioning
against speculation about the identity of the bombers. ``We're
looking at the usual suspects. And this time, the usual suspects
may be to blame.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The United States said that within hours of the bombings Friday,
two teams of FBI agents and other government anti-terrorist experts
had been been gathered in Washington and ordered to fly from
Andrews Air Force Base to East Africa _ one team bound for Nairobi,
the Kenyan capital, the other for Dar es Salaam, the Tanzanian
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon sent a C-141 cargo plane with a surgical team and
medical supplies from the American air base in Ramstein, Germany,
to Nairobi. A separate anti-terrorism squad of 40 Marines was being
flown to Nairobi from Saudi Arabia, where they are temporarily
based.
</P>
<P>
   As the first teams of U.S. investigators were leaving for East
Africa, President Clinton, who was awakened at 5:30 Friday morning
with news of the bombings, condemned them as ``cowardly acts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These acts of terrorist violence are abhorrent, they are
inhuman,'' the president said, interrupting a bill-signing ceremony
in the Rose Garden to comment on the bombings. ``We will use all
the means at our disposal to bring those responsible to justice, no
matter what or how long it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ordered a tightening of security at U.S.
embassies and other diplomatic installations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Police hurriedly erected barricades in front of several U.S.
embassies elsewhere in Africa, out of fear that terrorists might
strike again on the continent. The Ugandan government ordered
traffic police in Kampala, the capital, to move vehicles from the
building that houses the U.S. Embassy there.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said that there was no specific threat to
the embassies in Kenya or Tanzania immediately before the bombings.
``There was no telephone call to the embassies minutes before,
saying something was going to happen, no,'' said Patrick Kennedy,
assistant secretary of state for administration.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion fell on Laden in part because of the location of
Friday's terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Laden, who has been described by the State Department as ``one
of the most significant financial sponsors of Islamic extremist
activities in the world,'' has close ties to Muslim extremists
groups in Sudan, which borders Kenya to the north. He lived in
Sudan before relocating to Afghanistan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long had strained ties with the Sudanese
government, which it has accused of harboring terrorist groups, and
has moved most of its embassy employees out of Sudan to Nairobi,
where they work out of the embassy building that was bombed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Laden sends tens of millions of dollars through Islamic banks
and charities to terrorist organizations, militant groups and
extremists political movements based in Sudan, Algeria, Egypt,
Lebanon and the Philippines, as well as providing support for
Jihad, which is also suspected of involvement in the attacks in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a newspaper in Kuwait quoted the leader of Jihad,
Ayman Zawahri, as renewing his call for a holy war against American
interests. The newspaper said that Zawahri was then living in
Afghanistan with Laden, who has been stripped of his Saudi
citizenship by the government in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
   Even if strong evidence emerged linking Laden, Jihad or any
other group to the bombings in East Africa, experience suggests
that the investigation of the case by the FBI will be long,
complicated and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   While the FBI has jurisdiction under American law for crimes
against Americans abroad, few of the major terrorism investigations
of the last decade have resulted in arrests. Terrorists responsible
for the 1983 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, the
1988 bombing of a Pan Am jumbo jet over Scotland and the 1995
murder of two American diplomats in Pakistan were never caught.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the State Department, Undersecretary
Thomas Pickering said that it was too early to single out suspects
in the bombing or to speculate about why they had chosen to carry
out the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find them, we'll ask them,'' he said. ``I don't
believe at this stage that we are reading anything special into the
choice of these until we get further down the investigative
process. I don't have an answer. Terrorists tend to be
unpredictable, and there may be some of that in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was reported to be rushing
back to Washington from Italy, where she was to have attended the
weekend wedding of her chief spokesman, James Rubin. She said in a
statement that the administration ``will spare no effort to use all
means at our disposal to track down and punish the perpetrators of
these outrageous acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
