<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-RELATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSIES BUILT BEFORE TOUGHER BUILDING CODES ENACTED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two U.S. embassies bombed by terrorists in
eastern Africa on Friday were constructed before the federal
government initiated a strict building code to protect its foreign
ambassadors from such explosions, a senior State Department
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But even the stricter construction standards might not have
protected embassy personnel from what appears to have been highly
organized terrorists with large quantities of explosives, said
Thomas Pickering, undersecretary of state for political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of U.S. investigators are scouring debris from the massive
midmorning bombings of the embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania, which were built before the 1986 Diplomatic
Security Act called for new embassies to be better fortified to
withstand an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bomb-proof is a relative term,'' Pickering said. ``Tell me
what size bomb, and I'll tell you what the proof is .... Obviously
a bigger bomb makes a bigger problem, and smaller bombs are less of
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder Newspapers, quoting U.S. intelligence sources,
reported that the blast in Tanzania was caused by a car bomb. The
source said the Kenya bomb, while yet not traced to a car,
apparently was placed next to a parked gasoline tanker truck
outside the embassy, boosting the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The Nairobi and Dar es Salaam facilities were built more than 17
years ago, before the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Beirut in 1983
led to a security review worldwide, heightened restrictions at U.S.
embassies and enactment of the 1986 law. Metal detectors and
concrete barriers are some of the more visible results of the
tighter measures at many embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Williams, director of overseas diplomatic security for
the State Department until retiring in 1995, told reporters Friday
the older U.S. embassies still are most vulnerable since they're
often located on busy city streets and lack reinforced walls.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Kenyan and Tanzanian sites did not maintain
the sizable vehicle setbacks routinely found at newer embassies in
more risky areas of the world. The Nairobi embassy is at a busy
downtown intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The only protection from a bomb blast is ``distance, not much
else,'' Williams told reporters. ``Even if our buildings are
tremendously strong, they have to be far enough from a road.''
</P>
<P>
   The massive bombs used Friday were detonated outside the
embassies but close enough to badly damage the buildings and many
nearby automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   British security expert Michael Yardley told The Associated
Press that terrorists will seek out such weaknesses. ``If you
harden one target ... terrorism merely deserts to a softer target.
That seems to be exactly what's happened here,'' he said. ``It's
almost impossible to protect yourself globally from this sort of
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the explosions in Kenya and Tanzania, Pickering
expressed confidence in the strict building code and security at
the 260 U.S. embassies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a set of standards which we believe deals with most of
the difficulties, if not all, that we could expect to face,'' he
said. ``And we have taken the whole series of steps ... putting our
embassies on alert, cautioning Americans, issuing specific notices
with respect to Kenya and Tanzania in the light of these events.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams and others told reporters Friday that there has not
been enough money spent since 1986 to upgrade a majority of U.S.
embassies to the stricter standards.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, which receives about 30,000 threats of
terrorist attacks annually, established a special task force
immediately after the bombings Friday to tighten embassy security
worldwide and to coordinate the delivery of medical supplies to the
two facilities, where a total of 804 Americans are stationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always in a state of alert,'' Pickering said.
``Terrorists tend to want to be unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said Friday the two African
embassies weren't on high alert before the blasts because there had
been no warnings of a possible terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
