<HEADLINE>
MAYOR RESPONDS TO DETECTIVE'S CLAIMS ON RAMSEY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Boulder's mayor on Friday demanded an
investigation into complaints by a city police detective that the
district attorney's office had ``effectively crippled'' the
20-month-old investigation into the killing of JonBenet Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``These charges should not be left unchallenged, Mayor Bob
Greenlee said of an explosive 8-page letter of resignation that
Steve Thomas, the police detective, tendered here on Thursday. ``It
is confusing and unacceptable to me that people are unaccountable,
or not responding.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, which would have been the little girl's eighth birthday,
found official Colorado in turmoil over the detective's farewell
blast. Calling for the nomination of a special prosecutor in the
case, Thomas wrote that Boulder police detectives view some members
of the Boulder County district attorney's office as potential
defense witnesses, adding: ``I believe the district attorney's
office is thoroughly compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Laurion, a spokeswoman for Alex Hunter, Boulder's
district attorney, said in response: ``The letter is outrageous and
is substantially false and misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Boulder police and prosecutors said
Friday: ``Our primary responsibility is to gather sufficient
evidence to prosecute the JonBenet Ramsey homicide, and to further
address these charges would only sidetrack the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer conferred with other district attorneys about the
letter's call for a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, first obtained by ABC News on Thursday night, cut
through some of the fog that has surrounded the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While officials last fall reassured residents of cooperation
between police and prosecutors, Thomas wrote that the two
institutions at times ``weren't even on speaking terms.'' He wrote
of sessions with prosecutors where ``detectives protested in
frustration, where fists hit the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never offered true prosecutorial support,'' said
Thomas, one of five lead detectives in the murder case. ``We were
trying to deliver a murder case with hands tied behind our backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the detective faulted the prosecutor's office for
failing to obtain the Ramseys' telephone and credit-card reports,
for failing to quickly call for a grand jury to compel reluctant
witnesses to testify, for failing to demand that all witnesses be
subjected to polygraph tests, for leaving evidence untested, and
for ``mistreating'' prosecution witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that the district attorney's office shared
``police reports, physical evidence and investigative information''
with the Ramseys' defense lawyers and repeatedly reminded police
detectives ``just how powerful and talented and resourceful
particular defense attorneys were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics seemed to trump justice,'' Thomas, a 13-year veteran
of the force, concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Haddon, Ramsey's lead defense lawyer, has been a major
figure in Colorado's Democratic Party. Hunter, the prosecutor, is a
Democrat. Romer is general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. Greenlee is a Republican and a House candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the detective is implying that there has been any kind of
collusion between prosecutors and defense because of political
influence _ that's patently absurd,'' Bob Grant, district attorney
for Adams County, said Friday after conferring with the governor
over the detective's resignation letter. Grant, a Democrat, said
that it was ``more likely than not'' that the Boulder prosecutor
would take the case before a grand jury this fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ten weeks after the Boulder police briefed the district attorney
on the case, regional police departments appear to be losing
patience with an investigation that has involved interviews with
590 people and investigations of 122 suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Denver and Broomfield have recalled
investigators who were on loan to Boulder prosecutors. Last week
the Boulder County sheriff lent a replacement detective only after
considerable cajoling.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter, Thomas wrote that he feared
prosecutors would doom the case by not aggressively presenting it
to a grand jury. ``District Attorney Hunter's continued reference
to a `runaway' grand jury is puzzling,'' he wrote. ``Is he afraid
that he cannot control the outcome?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Silverman, a former Denver prosecutor and a Republican,
said after reading the letter Friday: ``He has substantial fears
that the DA may tank the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys have said that they had nothing to do with the
murder of their daughter on Dec. 26, 1996. After spending $1
million, Boulder police have not declared any suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In a documentary aired here on Wednesday, Ramsey said, ``I would
have given my life for JonBenet, and I regret _ I will regret for
the rest of my life _ that I wasn't able to do that that night.
JonBenet was the spark plug of our family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
