<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BUFFETT-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A BEAR ON MR. BUFFETT`S FARM? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Iowa)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If actions speak louder than words, the person many consider the
nation's most astute stock-market investor _ and surely its most
influential _ seems, at least, to be whispering ``sell.''
</P>
<P>
   While Warren E. Buffett, the decabillionaire ``Oracle of
Omaha,'' has always argued that long-term investors should welcome
market drops as chances to scoop up bargains, his proposed
acquisition of General Re, America's biggest reinsurance company,
involves a major, largely unrecognized, portfolio shift from stocks
to bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal was announced, Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway
holding company had $40 billion of its $50 billion in assets
allocated to the stock market. But the addition of General Re,
which is laden with bonds, changes that share to $45 billion out of
$74 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one fell swoop, Berkshire reduces its stock holdings as a
percentage of investment assets from 80 percent to roughly 61
percent,'' said Daniel S. Pecaut, proprietor of a family brokerage
firm in Sioux City, Iowa, and a close student of his Corn Belt
neighbor. ``Clearly he is selling stocks, and there is something
important going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett, who has said almost nothing publicly of late, denied
when the deal was announced in June that it reflected any belief
that stocks might be peaking. ``It is not a market call
whatsoever,'' he stated.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of General Re does offer Berkshire some tax
advantages and other benefits. But it is difficult to conclude that
the purchase is anything but a reallocation of Berkshire's assets
on a scale befitting an investment behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other clues that Buffett has grown wary of
stocks. One is that Berkshire has lately been venturing outside its
traditional realm of blue-chip companies (200 million shares of
Coca-Cola being the largest position); Geico and other insurance
companies, and ownership of an assortment of small operating
subsidiaries in businesses like candy, jewelry, shoes, furniture
and vacuum cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Berkshire took a large position in oil futures,
of which contracts for 14 million barrels remained at the end of
1997. And the company stunned the metals market last year by buying
111 million ounces of silver.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of change is that Berkshire shed 5 percent of its
stock portfolio last year, trimming stalwarts like Walt Disney,
McDonald's, Wells Fargo and Freddie Mac in what Buffett in his
annual letter to shareholders called part of an effort ``aimed at
changing our bond-stock ratio moderately'' to reflect a shift in
their valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely if ever, according to Buffett watchers, has this master
of spotting undervalued, growth-oriented businesses referred to the
relative attractiveness of bonds and stocks. ``Though we don't
attempt to predict the movements of the stock market,'' Buffett
allowed in his letter, dated Feb. 27, ``we do try, in a very rough
way, to value it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even last winter, good value was getting hard to find, in
Buffett's view. ``We are not pleased with our prospects for
committing incoming funds,'' Buffett cautioned shareholders.
``Prices are high for both businesses and stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   For General Re's shares, however, Buffett offered a big, though
not outlandish, 28.5 percent premium. And he agreed to pay with
Berkshire stock even though less than four months earlier he had
put a sharp pencil to all his previous stock-only acquisitions over
the years and found that they had actually lost money.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Berkshire's spectacular performance _ a 24.1
percent average compounded annual gain since 1964 _ would have been
even better had he not done deals for stock, which in effect reduce
stockholders' stakes in all of the holding company's investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure that Charlie and I, will be very reluctant to
issue shares in the future,'' Buffett said, referring to Charles T.
Munger, his long-time sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Buffett's earlier merger discussions with General Re had come
to naught, but he wanted the company so badly that he was willing
to pay an above-market price in Berkshire common stock even though
this meant sharply shrinking his exposure to future stock profits,
at least in the foreseeable future. Conceivably, in fact, Buffett
considered his stock overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he appear particularly sanguine about prospects for the
bond market. Last week, Berkshire reported that it had sold all its
$4.6 billion in zero-coupon bonds _ another unusual holding for the
company. The sale proved a hugely profitable bet. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Zeroes, which pay no cash interest, are more sensitive to
changes in interest rates than other types of bonds. Buffett's sale
of the bonds indicated that he believed interest rates were
unlikely to fall much further and perhaps could start rising.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Berkshire has long and highly profitable experience
in the insurance business. The deal for General Re _ Buffett's
biggest &UR;  &LR; by far _ will create for the combined company a float of
$22 billion. (In insurance, float refers to the free use of money
collected as premiums but not yet paid to settle expected
claims. &UR;  &LR; In the interim, that money is available for investment.)
</P>
<P>
   Buffett has stressed the transaction's attributes as a corporate
marriage _ the two companies presumably are worth more together
than separately. But others are also impressed with its ingenuity
in diluting the stock portion of his company's portfolio. That
avoids both a horrendous tax bite from an outright sale of
immensely appreciated stock, and the likely market havoc from
``Buffett Turns Bearish!'' headlines about such a sale.
</P>
<P>
   A disruption like that, which perhaps only Alan Greenspan, the
Federal Reserve chairman, could match, is a constant concern at
Berkshire. ``They're very careful about it,'' Pecaut said,
``because they don't want people to jump off cliffs.'' (His
analysis first received attention in last week's issue of Grant's
Interest Rate Observer, a newsletter published in New York.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, little mention has been made of Buffett as a possible
contributor to the recent market swoon. The clever &UR;  &LR; deal allows him
to lighten up on stocks while enhancing a business juggernaut that
will have even more buying power when the climate for stocks
improves. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  For now, Buffett, a baseball fan and a co-owner of Omaha's
minor league team, can simply keep the bat on his shoulder because,
as he is fond of observing, there are no called strikes in
investing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pecaut, meanwhile, concluded this about the General Re deal:
``By doing a stock merger, Berkshire is trading away 18 percent of
its holdings in Coca-Cola, American Express, Gillette, etc., but
doing so in a way that Berkshire pays no taxes,'' he said. ``As my
kids would put it, `way cool.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-07 0795
