<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSIES-BOMBINGS-1S     08-07 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-BOMBINGS-1STLD-WRITETHR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
81 KILLED, 1,600 INJURED AS BLASTS RIP U.S. EMBASSIES IN KENYA,
TANZANIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct time in 9th graf to 10:40 African time, 3:40
EDT.) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Massive car bombs rocked U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania on Friday in unprecedented simultaneous attacks by
terrorists that killed at least 81 people, including eight
Americans, and injured more than 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton pledged to track down the unknown killers and
dispatched teams of medical and security personnel to the two East
African nations to help with the injured and to begin the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These acts of terrorist violence are abhorrent, they are
inhuman. We will use all means at our disposal to bring those
responsible to justice, no matter what or how long it takes,'' the
president said, addressing the attack during a Rose Garden ceremony
to sign legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to get answers and justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, located 450
miles apart, suffered extensive damage, but the loss of life and
injuries were far greater in Kenya where office and apartment
buildings around the downtown embassy bore the brunt of the
explosion. The embassy in Dar es Salaam is in a residential area.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported 74 dead and 1,643 wounded in
Nairobi and seven killed and 72 hurt in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rice, assistant secretary for African Affairs, said there
were eight Americans among the dead in Kenya, six U.S. citizens
missing and 14 Americans hospitalized. No Americans died in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The United States ordered all its embassies and government
buildings overseas on heightened alert and beefed-up security.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary of state for
administration, said the first bomb exploded in Dar es Salaam about
10:40 a.m. African time (3:40 a.m., EDT), and the second in Nairobi
three or four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said there were no warnings to either embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The AP reported that Kenyans crawled over the twisted and broken
concrete of the embassy to look for victims, laboring under studio
lights as darkness fell in Nairobi. ``We fear the worst. By the
time the rubble is cleared, we expect to find more dead,'' Red
Cross spokeswoman Nina Galbe told the wire service.
</P>
<P>
   It reported the bomb collapsed a four-story building and badly
damaged the nearby Cooperative Bank House where government and
private offices are housed. Windows were shattered as far as 10
blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in Dar es Salaam killed embassy employees, all
Tanzanians, destroyed cars and uprooted trees.
</P>
<P>
   No organization claimed responsibility for the bombings, but the
list of suspects could be lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   One suspected terrorist whose activities were being examined in
the wake of the explosions is exiled Saudi dissident Osama bin
Laden. Bin Laden has threatened a holy war against U.S. troops in
his homeland and Americans elsewhere overseas, AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   He also is suspected of backing other terrorist acts around the
world, including the 1996 Khobar Towers attack in Saudi Arabia that
claimed the lives of 19 U.S. airmen.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and White House also declined comment on
reports that Islamic Jihad called last week for attacks on U.S.
property after the United States helped engineer the arrests of
some of its members in Albania and their return to Egypt. The group
has ties to the assassins of Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   Neither African country has a history of terrorist activity, and
the United States bolstered its standing in sub-Saharan Africa
after President Clinton's 11-day visit there this spring. The
United States has cordial relations with both nations, prompting
speculations the terrorists were from outside the region. Still,
the State Department cautioned against any assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe at this stage that we are reading anything
special into the choice of these (countries) until we get further
down the investigative process,'' Undersecretary Thomas Pickering
said. ``Terrorists tend to be unpredictable, and there may be some
of that in this.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was the first dual terrorist attack against U.S.
targets in different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said a U.S. military C-141, the largest transport,
left Germany with members of a disaster response team to help
provide medical assistance. Nairobi hospitals reportedly were
overwhelmed by the injured.
</P>
<P>
   He said a second transport left Andrews Air Force Base in the
afternoon carrying medical supplies and U.S. personnel to help with
recovery efforts. A 44-member special Marine team also was
dispatched to help secure the embassy grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our immediate priority is to assist the casualties and their
families, and at the same time, we are taking steps to ensure
embassy security,'' Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said a team of federal agents will conduct the
criminal investigation in both countries. Embassies' grounds are
considered the sovereign territory of the foreign nation.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering dismissed questions of whether the United States could
bring the terrorists to justice. For instance, the Khobar Tower
attack remains unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you we will be relentless and persevering. So I
don't believe that anyone should assume that the U.S. government
will ever give up on these cases or that, in fact, the failure to
make immediate progress in some is an indication somehow that we
are not going to bring the appropriate result,'' Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Crowley, a National Security Council spokesman, said, ``We
don't forgive; we don't forget; and ultimately whoever's
responsible for the attack will be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said President Clinton was awakened about 5:30 a.m.,
EDT, and informed of the bombings by national security adviser
Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to John Lange, the charge d'affairs in Tanzania,
and to Prudence Bushnell, the U.S. ambassador to Kenya who suffered
a cut lip in the explosion. ``He expressed again, on behalf of the
American people, our thoughts and prayers to the American community
during this difficult day,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls also were placed to the presidents of Kenya and Tanzania
``to express our condolences to each country, because, while it's
clear that this attack was directed at our facilities in each city,
the death toll and the injuries have primarily been borne by the
citizens of Kenya and Tanzania,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in Italy to attend the
wedding of her spokesman, James Rubin, cut short her trip to return
to the United States. A delegation of members of Congress on its
way to Africa also was diverted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered all U.S. flags flown at half-staff. The State
Department later issued travel advisories to U.S. citizens planning
trips to either country. It also allowed all non-essential U.S.
personnel there to leave the countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
