<HEADER>
A3960 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-SECURITY-575&AMP;A     08-07 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-SECURITY-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEITHER EMBASSY MET CURRENT SECURITY GUIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-SCENE,
AFRICA-VICTIMS)  
(lh) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two U.S. embassies in East Africa that were
bombed Friday did not meet security standards that were ordered for
the State Department's overseas posts following separate terrorist
attacks against the U.S. Embassy and marine barracks in Beirut,
Lebanon, in the early 1980s, State Department officials
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
had never been modified to fully comply with the tougher security
standards called for in 1985 by a panel headed by retired Adm.
Bobby Inman, largely because the White House and Congress have
never provided enough money to fund a worldwide conversion of all
U.S. embassies, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the State Department was given less than
one-third of the money that would have been required to modify or
build new facilities to meet the standards, which were imposed to
prevent a repeat of the 1984 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Beirut,
which killed 16 people, and the 1983 bombing of the U.S. Marine
barracks in Beirut, which killed 241.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1981, before the Inman standards went into effect, the
U.S. Embassy in Nairobi was scheduled to undergo a $3 million
rehabilitation and security upgrade in January 1999, its first
major security modification since its original construction, a
State Department official said Friday. The planned alterations to
the embassy in Nairobi were to include new construction to
completely separate the embassy's business and operations areas
from the more public counselor section, the State Department
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In Dar es Salaam, the State Department spent $750,000 in 1988 to
modify the embassy, which is located in a 44-year-old, three-story
office building that previously housed a Tanzanian government
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, it was the Israeli chancellory until it was
expropriated by the Tanzanian government in 1973 after Tanzania and
Israel broke relations. In 1980, the United States leased the
building for its embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither embassy complied with the Inman standards, which,
among other things, called for 9-foot walls to be constructed
around all embassies and for the embassies to be set back at least
100 feet from streets and neighboring buildings. In Dar es Salaam,
a 9-foot wall was constructed in 1988, but it is as close as 25
feet to 75 feet to nearby streets and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy in Nairobi is only set back 30 feet from the street,
on a busy intersection in the downtown district. A large building
of over 65,000 square feet, the embassy has five stories above
ground and two below and sits on a half-acre site. It was one of
the last embassies built before the Inman standards were accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a set of standards which we believe deals with most of
the difficulties, if not all of the difficulties, that we expect to
face, and it is clear that these two buildings did not meet our
current standards,'' Thomas Pickering, under secretary of state for
political affairs, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombings Friday, the United States placed embassies
around the world on a heightened security alert. Yet Pickering also
said that no public building can ever be completely bomb-proof.
Asked about the two installations' vulnerability to attack,
Pickering said: ``Bomb-proof is a relative term. Tell me what size
bomb, and I'll tell you what the proof is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The State Department estimated in 1986 that converting or
replacing all embassies to meet the Inman standards would have cost
approximately $3.5 billion. Between 1986 and 1990, the State
Department requested $2.7 billion to upgrade its embassies, but
Congress only appropriated about $880 million during that period.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the prohibitive costs, as well as a growing belief that
compliance with the security standards directly conflicts with the
public diplomatic functions of U.S. overseas posts, have led both
Congress and the administration to quietly drop the idea of
modifying all U.S. embassies to comply with the Inman standards.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials came to believe that the security
recommendations of the Inman panel were Draconian, and would
transform many embassies into nearly inaccessible fortresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was impossible to implement the Inman standards
worldwide,'' observed Jane Loeffler, the author of a new book on
the history of embassy design. ``Both because of the cost, and
because it would have brought into question the very meaning of
American diplomacy. Every American embassy would have become a
walled compound out in isolated suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the State Department established a priority list of
embassies that most needed protection. Those in nations like
Kuwait, where the State Department believed there was a high risk
of a terrorist attack, were the first to undergo redesign or to be
moved to new and more secure buildings. But State Department
officials said that both Nairobi and Dar es Salaam were considered
low-threat posts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, gates, metal detectors and extra security personnel have
been added to embassies in every country, but not even all new
embassies comply with the Inman standards.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 through the new fiscal 1999 budget, Congress has
provided a total of $112 million to increase embassy security, said
a Republican staffer on the House appropriations subcommittee that
deals with the matter. The aide said that State Department
officials have told lawmakers that they are no longer wedded to
trying to achieve full compliance with the Inman security standards
at all U.S. embassies. ``State has told us they have been satisfied
with the level of funding on security measures,'' the aide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2100EDT &QL; 
