</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-GRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOPS TO LEAVE RESTIVE REGION OF SUMATRA AFTER ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The armed forces promised Friday to begin
removing troops from Aceh province, where the military has been
accused of killing thousands of people suspected of being
separatists in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The defense minister and armed forces commander, Gen. Wiranto,
made a half-day visit to Aceh, the country's westernmost province,
1,000 miles from the capital, in an bid to calm public outrage over
decades of military repression under the former government of
President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give one month at the latest for all troops that are not
based in the region to be withdrawn and returned to their
respective bases,'' Wiranto was quoted as saying on the state
television from the town of Lhokseumawe on the northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say how many troops were stationed in the province of
170,000 people, on the northern tip of Sumatra, Indonesia's largest
island.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto apologized on behalf of the military for the actions of
any soldiers whose ``excesses may have caused any harm to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The province was declared a ``military operational region'' in
1990 after intensified activity by rebels hoping to form a separate
country with an Islamic government. More than 85 percent of the 200
million people of Indonesia are Muslims, making it the world's
largest Muslim country, but the government is secular.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of torture and mass graves in the staunchly Muslim
province have surfaced almost daily in the local press in the last
month, prompting parliamentary and non-governmental investigations
of reports that more than 30,000 people in the province have
disappeared since 1989 at the hands of the military.
</P>
<P>
   The military's special forces unit, Kopassus, has been
implicated in many of the disappearances by widows and other
relatives who have broken their silence since the resignation of
Suharto on May 21.
</P>
<P>
   Three high-ranking Kopassus officers, including a Suharto
son-in-law, Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, were suspended this week and
are being questioned about the disappearance of dozens of
anti-Suharto activists in the capital, 14 of whom are still
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Committee for Missing Persons and Victims of
Violence, welcomed the military's apology but said it smacked of
politics more than progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too fast to judge if this attitude is anything more than
political,'' said Munir, the head of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The troop withdrawal is important, but the status of the
province as a military operational region has to be changed,''
added Munir, who like many Indonesians uses only one name. He plans
to visit the province next week, ahead of plans by human rights
groups to begin digging at the suspected burial sites.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a parliamentary fact-finding team sent to the area
earlier in the week to investigate the reports of mass graves were
moved to tears by the account of a 70-year-old man who was arrested
earlier in the year on charges of concealing arms in his home.
</P>
<P>
   A local daily reported that the man, a father of seven, said his
captors had stripped him naked, gave him electric shocks and tried
to bury him alive during three days and nights of military
interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   Under President B.J. Habibie, who replaced Suharto after 32
years of highly authortarian rule, the military has taken an
increasingly public approach to redressing the atrocities committed
by soldiers in several Indonesian provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
