<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-STAFF-BOS &LR;      08-07 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-STAFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAW STARR MEDIA LEAKS, UNSEALED RECORDS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge has ruled that independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr probably violated grand jury secrecy laws by
repeatedly leaking information to the news media about his
investigation of President Clinton, according to court documents
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing complication for Starr at a crucial stage of
his inquiry, a federal appeals court unsealed records showing that
US District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson found credible evidence in
June &UR;  &LR; that Starr and his associates breached the secrecy laws.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr and his staff are unable to disprove the allegations,
they could be cited for criminal contempt of court, and their
investigation could be severely compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was ordered by the US Court of Appeals on Monday to
further investigate the alleged violations, cited numerous news
leaks by prosecutors, including statements she said Starr was ``in
no way authorized'' to make.
</P>
<P>
   The development occurred a day after former White House intern
Monica S. Lewinsky testified before the federal grand jury about
numerous sexual encounters she saidshe had with Clinton over an
18-month period beginning in November 1995, according to a source
familiar with her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has denied under oath having a sexual relationship
with Lewinsky, is scheduled to be questioned by Starr's staff and
the grand jury on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Starr issued a statement Friday saying Johnson's ruling was
based on ``minimal'' legal standards. He denied any wrongdoing by
him or his staff. ``We welcome the opportunity to demonstrate that
fact to the district court,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   To Clinton's lawyers and White House operatives, who have
complained for months about alleged grand jury leaks, the documents
released Friday were seen as vindication. The appeals court
released the material under a public access motion filed by 11 news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The White House counsel's office said in a statement that ``for
the first time in the 20-year history of the Independent Counsel
Act, a federal court has found prima facie evidence of potential
criminal wrongdoing by an independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal lawyer, David E. Kendall, called the alleged
leaks ``highly unprofessional and utterly indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall had sought the investigation, submitting dozens of news
reports and transcripts for Johnson's review.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the material was an NBC Nightly News report, aired
on Feb. 4, that Johnson said ``directly identifies `sources in
Starr's office' and discloses information regarding a subpoenaed
witness's potential testimony before the grand jury, evaluations of
such potential testimony, and the strategy and direction'' of the
Office of Independent Counsel's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in her June 19 decision, also cited reports in the New
York Times and New York Daily News that ``identify OIC prosecutors
as the sources of the reports and improperly disclose what a
subpoenaed witness has told the OIC during investigative
interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Johnson chastised Starr for telling reporters she
had made ``a magnificent ruling'' in denying Clinton's
executive-privilege request in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comment not only confirmed for the press that the court
had indeed made a decision but also revealed that the substance of
the decision was favorable to the OIC,'' Johnson stated. ``The fact
that information about the opinion had already been leaked at time
of Mr. Starr's comment in no way authorized him to make statements
confirming or denying such leaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Johnson said Starr's ``admission'' to journalist
Steven Brill in Content magazine that he briefed reporters on
condition of anonymity ``bolstered the court's findings of prima
facie violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, after determining the reports probably violated the
secrecy laws, granted Kendall permission in June to participate in
her formal inquiry into the allegations. Starr appealed the ruling,
arguing that his investigation of Clinton could be ruined if he
were forced to reveal details of the grand jury proceedings to
Clinton's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, in its decision Monday, generally agreed,
saying Clinton's lawyers should be allowed to participate ``only in
extraordinary circumstances and as a last resort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Proceedings to ferret out violations of the grand jury secrecy
rule should not themselves present an undue risk of compromising
that very secrecy,'' the appellate court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the risks included potentially exposing ``grand
jury members, government lawyers and agents, and witnesses to
outside pressures and possible danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he was ``gratified'' by the ruling, which he said
would protect ``the integrity of the ongoing grand jury
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals judges ordered Johnson to investigate the
allegations privately, with a special investigator if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But the judges also said the burden was on Starr to prove that
he and his staff did not act illegally in their dealings with
reporters. Starr ``must now come forward with evidence in whatever
form the district court requires ... to rebut the inferences made
from the news articles,'' the appellate court stated.
</P>
<P>
   The legal proceeding is known as a ``show cause hearing,'' in
which individuals who allegedly have violated the secrecy rules are
required to show why they should not be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were released Friday as Clinton conducted business
as usual, maintaining his silence on the investigation. He
participated in a Rose Garden ceremony on job training, expressed
outrage at the fatal bombings at US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
and spent the rest of the day beyond sight of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Lewinsky, who appeared pale and drawn after the
grand jury session on Thursday, was in better spirits Friday.
``She's doing fine,'' a source close to her said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lewinsky harbored unpleasant memories of the grand jury
experience. ``It's just hard,'' the source said, referring to
testifying about private details of alleged sexual liaisons. ``It
wasn't like she was Linda Tripp, chomping at the bit to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Senator Frank Murkowski, an Alaska
Republican who is chairman of the Senate Energy Committee, asked
Clinton to delay swearing-in UN Ambassador Bill Richardson as
energy secretary amid questions involving the Lewinsky episode.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski cited a report in Friday's Washington Times that said
Richardson may have contradicted himself when he testified before
the energy committee about a job he offered Lewinsky at the US
mission in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Richardson had no openings on his staff when
he made the offer last October, contrary to his sworn testimony
during a nomination hearing last month.
</P>
<P>
   The committee unanimously recommended Richardson's confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee hired a former
ethics committee lawyer, Abbe Lowell, to head their staff if
Starr's investigation leads to an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ann Scales of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
