A3964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-POLITICS-COX     08-07 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-POLITICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ethnic issues haunt Miami fraud cases
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He is young, handsome and charming to many constituents,
some of whom are fanatically loyal to him. But that loyalty may not
save the career of Humberto Hernandez, the one-time chairman of the
Miami City Commission, now facing back-to-back trials that could
send him to prison for years.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 36, is on trial in state court on charges of election
fraud stemming from last fall's tainted city elections. This
winter, a judge found massive absentee ballot fraud, much of it
centered in Hernandez's Little Havana district, and tossed out the
returns in the mayor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Hernandez faces federal mortgage fraud charges from
his work in the real estate field. Those charges predate the ballot
fraud charges and led to Hernandez being removed from office by
Gov. Lawton Chiles last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Hernandez went to his loyal Cuban-American
constituents last fall, telling them it was all a plot by the Anglo
establishment to keep Cubans out of power.
</P>
<P>
   He won election anew to the City Commission in November's
tainted contest, despite the mortgage fraud indictment. He was
removed from office again in May when he was arrested on the voter
fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the trial is crucial to Miami's efforts to clean
up its scandal-plagued image.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trial is extremely important,'' said Marsha Silverman, a
political scientist at the University of Miami. ``The message needs
to be sent that we take voter fraud seriously here.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a veteran of the failed Bay of Pigs invasion, when
American-backed Cuban commandos tried to take the island back from
Fidel Castro, Hernandez was born in Miami and earned a law degree
from Florida State University.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as an assistant city of Miami attorney, but was fired
from that job when it was found that he was also running a private
law practice on city time.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't his only brush with questionable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Following the 1996 ValuJet crash in the Everglades, Hernandez
was accused of ``brazen misconduct'' by the Florida Bar Association
after some of his employees were caught handing out business cards
to the families of crash victims.
</P>
<P>
   But he still won election as a city commissioner from Little
Havana in 1996. Observers said he carefully cultivated the votes of
older Cuban immigrants, most of whom don't speak English and are
mistrustful of the Anglo world, holding close to their Cuban
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is someone who won't be `out-Cubaned,''' said Dario Moreno,
a Florida International University political scientist and himself
a Cuban-American. ``He has astutely played the ethnic card by
appealing to the worst aspects of our nature here in Dade County.''
</P>
<P>
   In last fall's election, investigators found hundreds of
questionable absentee ballots, most signed by Cuban immigrants. One
was signed by a dead man. Some ballots were signed by people who
lived outside the district in which they voted. One of those was
Hernandez's own secretary, Evelyn Herbello. Hernandez is charged
with helping orchestrate a cover up of the illegal ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Herbello, however, went to authorities and secretly wore a tape
recorder to help build the case against her boss. After they were
arrested and were riding to jail in a police van, Herbello's
recorder captured Hernandez making defiant, profane remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no jury that will find us guilty,'' Hernandez boasted
on the tape, which may be introduced as evidence in his trial.
Hernandez could face up to five years in prison if convicted on the
vote fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   His federal trial on mortgage fraud charges is set to begin
Sept. 8. That case centers around what prosecutors say was a
complex scheme by Hernandez and others to defraud banks of $8
million earned from the sale of luxury condos. Hernandez has
adamantly declared his innocence in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been the only politician charged with corruption in
Miami-Dade County. In the past two years, the sprawling county has
been hit by a string of such cases, most recently involving two
county commissioners and a high-ranking state senator.
</P>
<P>
   The scandals have brought embarrassment to the city and could be
hurting its efforts to attract new industry, many observers
believe. Worried Latin business leaders held an ethics summit this
summer, while the Chamber of Commerce has drawn up ethical
guidelines for public officials to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But Moreno fears those efforts will founder if prosecutors
aren't successful in jailing some of the allegedly corrupt leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes in this trial are pretty high,'' he said. ``If he
is found innocent, it will be portrayed on Cuban radio as a set-up,
an Anglo conspiracy. If he is found guilty, it will add momentum to
the idea that we need to get away from this corruption and ethnic
pandering.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
