<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-REACT-COX     08-07 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A father's voice ends a daughter frantic wait
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For several tense hours Friday morning, Emma Mwangi
paced the floor of a friend's Roswell apartment and nervously
dialed her father's office number in Nairobi. She hoped for the
best, but feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Flavian Mwangi, 69, works in an office building near the U.S.
Embassy. When his daughter saw the bomb's aftermath on TV, she knew
he had been close to ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly called his office and got no answer. Her attempts
to reach him at home were unsuccessful, too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, shortly after noon, he answered the phone at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, you're alive!'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, my darling. I'm alive,'' he replied. ``It's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 20-year-old niece, Salome Wanjiru, was injured during the
blast and is in the hospital, Emma Mwangi said: ``She was working
in my father's office. She's usually in the computer room, which is
right next to where he works. When the bomb went off, he was
talking on the phone. All this debris fell through the windows and
partitions in his office started falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Several relatives, including her brother, are missing, but she
thinks they are probably OK. They all work for her father, who owns
a coffee company.
</P>
<P>
   The blast left Mwangi with many questions and fears for her own
safety. She is visiting a friend in Roswell and plans to return to
Nairobi Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't imagine the American Embassy in Nairobi being
bombed out, because of the security,'' she said. ``It was really,
really scary for me.''
</P>
<P>
   During her vigil Friday, she was joined by several other Kenyans
who listened to radio updates, watched TV news reports and tried to
reach their own relatives in Nairobi. A few are here to visit
friends, but most are studying at metro area colleges and
universities. The students all plan to return home when they finish
college.
</P>
<P>
   All lamented the fact that terrorism had touched their homeland,
and all agreed that no Kenyan could have been responsible for such
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenyans are peace-loving people,'' said Hilary Motoku, 24, who
is studying civil engineering at DeKalb College. ``Bombs.
Terrorism. That's not the way we do it. That's an outside source
that did this.''
</P>
<P>
   He worried that Kenya's reputation would be damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really unfortunate that they would do such a thing. They
killed so many innocent bypassers, bystanders, people on buses,
ladies selling vegetables across the street, women and children,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Political demonstrations are not uncommon, they said, and some
escalate into violence once the police arrive. But it rarely goes
beyond stone-throwing. ``Bombing? That's too much,'' said James
Nguru.
</P>
<P>
   The group speculated that Islamic militants may be responsible,
but even that would be unusual for Kenya. ``There are Muslims in
Kenya, but they are not militant,'' said Emma Mwangi.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrick Thige Mwangi, who is not related to Emma Mwangi,
worried that his wife, Julia, may have gone to the U.S. Embassy to
apply for a visa to visit Atlanta. He still had not been able to
reach her by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was trying to join me here,'' said Fredrick Mwangi,
39, who studies at Beulah Heights Bible College near Grant Park.
``I don't want to imagine that she went to that place. She was
supposed to go get a visa application.''
</P>
<P>
   Motoku worried about other students who may have been standing
in line at the U.S. Embassy to get a visa. ``We all stood there on
line starting at 6 o'clock in the morning. If you're coming to
American you have to line up there,'' he said. ``Many students
might be there now getting ready to come to school here in the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wanyange described Nairobi as a modern, growing city with
skyscrapers, office buildings, banks, restaurants and hotels. He
worried, though, about whether Nairobi officials would be able to
adequately respond to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've ever had to deal with something like
this before,'' said Wanyange, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Nguru said an area across the street from the U.S. Embassy has
an open air market where women sell vegetables and other street
vendors peddle T-shirts, music and other trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she rejoiced in the news that her father was alive, Emma
Mwangi worried about what Nairobi will be like when she returns
home next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Embassy was a fortress,'' she said. `` ... After
something like this, you ask yourself, what's the next target?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
