<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-WEAPONS-U.N.-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW U.N. PUSH TO URGE IRAQ TO COOPERATE WITH INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Diplomats from Security Council member
countries said Friday that countries friendly to Iraq were being
asked to try to persuade the government of President Saddam Hussein
to cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors again in return for a new
hearing of the Iraqi case in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Iraqis and the U.N. Special Commission, charged with
disarming Iraq and destroying its means of making weapons of mass
destruction, were operating in a low key Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance of long-term monitoring equipment by the commission,
known as Unscom, continued unimpeded in Iraq. No intrusive searches
were scheduled. There were reports Friday that the International
Atomic Energy Agency, which is responsible for the nuclear weapons
file, may attempt an inspection on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Danilo Turk, representative of Slovenia and the
Security Council's president for August, told reporters that there
was no call in the council for action against Iraq as long as the
threat to end all cooperation with Unscom remained a threat. He
said a new look at sanctions was not out of the question if Iraq
reversed course and made real progress in arms inspections in
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been situations when sanctions regimes have
changed,'' he said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister and
chief arms negotiator, could be invited to meet informally with the
Security Council to present Iraq's case.
</P>
<P>
   Council members agreed, however, that for the moment Iraq is in
violation of its agreements with the council and with
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. In March the council had warned of
``the severest consequences'' if Iraq broke the pledge made to
Annan in February to cooperate fully with Unscom.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's call on Thursday for a comprehensive
review of relations with Iraq came as a surprise to Security
Council members, diplomats who were at the meeting with Annan said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the last year has been spent reviewing various aspects
of the Iraqi situation and adjusting programs in the hope that
Saddam could be persuaded to be more cooperative with inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis have provided the weapons inspectors with virtually
no new material or answers to outstanding questions in that time.
They have only repeated their contention that there are no more
requirements to meet and that sanctions should be lifted
immediately. A complete embargo on trade with Iraq was imposed
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several council members tried to elicit more information from
Annan before he left on a trip to Portugal. Diplomats said Friday
that he did not want to take the diplomatic initiative with Iraq
but hoped that the Security Council would give the Iraqis a hearing
soon .
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, who is completing his tenure as U.S.
representative to the United Nations before moving to Washington
next month as energy secretary, met with the secretary-general on
Thursday and was assured that Annan wanted to leave the Iraqi
problem in Security Council hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased that the secretary-general was so forceful in
his statement claiming that Iraq had repudiated its agreement with
the Security Council,'' Richardson said Friday in an interview.
``Our interpretation of the Security Council review that he called
for is for finding ways to make Iraq comply with the disarmament
and inspection provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis say sanctions are killing Iraqis, especially
children, by depriving people of food and medicine. That contention
is gradually becoming less easy to defend as the United Nations
steps up aid.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions fuel protests, however. Volunteers from an
American group, Voices in the Wilderness, have been on a hunger
strike for more than a week outside the U.S. Mission to the United
Nations in New York. The group argues that continuing sanctions
indefinitely amounts to an American ``weapon of mass destruction''
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In Bagdad Friday, a spokesman for the ``oil for food'' program
said that for the first time a full ration of basic food supplies
is available to every Iraqi. The spokesman, Eric Falt, also said
the program would be further expanded in September, when new money
comes in from a greatly expanded fund.
</P>
<P>
   The program began a year ago when Iraq was permitted to sell $2
billion in oil every six months to pay for urgent civilian needs.
The figure was raised to $5.2 billion by the Security Council in
February. Money to compensate victims of Iraq's invasion and
occupation of Kuwait and other deductions are made from the fund,
leaving until now about $900 million available for food, medicines
and other goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   As of August, every Iraqi is eligible for a free monthly ration
of goods that includes 20 pounds of flour, 5.5 pounds of rice, 4.4
pounds of sugar, 2.2 pounds of legumes, about 6 pounds of baby
formula, several pounds of tea, cooking oil, salt, soap and
detergent. In September, Falt said, cereal, cheese and powdered
milk will be added to raise the protein level.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam resisted Security Council offers of an ``oil for food''
program for more than five years, before agreeing to the deal late
in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-NYT &LR;      08-07 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SIDES IN CENSUS BATTLE HAVE THEIR DAY IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Pa., N.J., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROANOKE, Va. _ A federal court that is hearing a challenge to
the Clinton administration's plans to use statistical sampling in
the next census homed in less on constitutional questions during
oral arguments Friday than on interpretation of a federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   The court, a special three-judge panel of the 4th Circuit, is
considering a case brought by a Republican congressman from
Georgia, a conservative law firm in Atlanta and several suburban
counties in Pennsylvania and New Jersey. The plaintiffs say
sampling would defy both Article I of the Constitution, which
requires that the census be an ``actual enumeration,'' and the
federal statute that was debated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is similar to one brought by Speaker Newt Gingrich
before a special panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit. That case was heard on June 11, and a
decision is imminent. Lawyers on both sides of the issue say they
expect that each case will ultimately be appealed to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The political stakes are large. Sampling should result in a
larger count of minority groups, many of whose members were missed
in the 1990 census. Because the census is used to apportion House
seats, and because minorities as a whole tend to vmte Democratic,
sampling could affect the power balance in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Federal judges typically prefer to resolve cases on a statutory
rather than constitutional basis, and at the hearing Friday the
panel focused its questions on interpretation of a 1976 law
governing how the decennial census should be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that statute, federal law said that except for purposes
of apportionment, the secretary of commerce ``may'' use sampling to
help conduct the census. The 1976 law said that except for
apportionment, the secretary ``shall'' use sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and lawyers for congressional Democrats argue
that by changing sampling from an option to a mandate, Congress in
effect made it optional for apportionment purposes rather than
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say that except for federal holidays, workers must
work from 9 to 5,'' said Paul Smith, who argued on behalf of the
House Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri. ``That
doesn't mean you can't come into work on holidays if you want.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Michael Carvin, the lawyer for the
plaintiffs, said a prohibition was nothing other than a
prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say that except for the wedding dress, you may take
all the clothes in the closet to the cleaners,'' Carvin told the
court. ``If you then change it to say except for the wedding dress
you must take all the clothes to the cleaners, you still can't take
the wedding dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans say that if the courts allow the
Census Bureau to use sampling under current law, they will move to
adopt legislation limiting it or altogether prohibiting it.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the Census Bureau's proposal to count everyone in 90
percent of the households in each of the country's census tracts _
neighborhoods consisting of roughly 1,700 households each _ and
using the results of that count to determine the number and
characteristics of people living in the remaining 10 percent. The
bureau then wants to check its work, and possibly adjust its
counts, by conducting a nationwide survey of 750,000 households.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
