<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3973 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CROWN-CASTLE-A     08-07 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CROWN-CASTLE-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING THE BACKBONES OF THE WIRELESS AGE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
(af) 
By SANA SIWOLOP  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the money poured into the shares of glossy new cyberspace
ventures lately, it is easy to overlook companies that are
exploiting more down-to-earth technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the companies that build or own transmission towers for
the rapidly expanding wireless communications business.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they may lack the new-kid-in-town sizzle of an Internet
software concern. But besides building or owning wireless
transmission towers, these companies often perform valuable
maintenance services for phone, cellular, paging and data
transmission companies. Investors have taken note.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the largest tower company, American Tower, went public
at $21 a share. Even in the face of the market's big drop last
week, the company's class A stock closed at $23 on Friday after
having traded as high as $28 on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Two other tower companies, Crown Castle International and
Pinnacle Tower, are expected to go public soon. At the end of July,
Crown nearly doubled the size of its offering; if it goes through
at its expected price of $18 a share, the offering would be one of
the largest of the year, with a market value of $1.76 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to see how antennae towers are showing up on
investors' radar.
</P>
<P>
   Falling prices for wireless communications are attracting vast
numbers of consumers, which means that the wireless companies are
expanding their networks for sending and receiving data.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless industry has also turned far more competitive, and
wireless carriers have started improving their efficiency by either
selling their networks _ and then leasing them back _ or
establishing joint ventures with companies that will manage them.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of digital television is also benefiting the
antenna-tower industry, by increasing demand for new towers to
accommodate new digital transmission equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Miller, a broadcasting analyst at Bear, Stearns, which
helped take American Tower public, said the wireless industry
already was using 40,000 to 50,000 transmission towers in the
United States. Demand for towers to accommodate cellular and
personal communications services alone could raise that number
close to 100,000 by 2001, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, like several other analysts, said he expected the tower
industry to keep consolidating. The main reason is that no single
company owns more than 3 percent of the towers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, American Tower owns or operates only about 1,900 towers,
while Crown Castle has 1,219. Specialty Teleconstructors, which
went public in 1994, has 801, and Pinnacle Holdings has 646.
</P>
<P>
   To some investors, so-called tower economics look attractive.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the towers are relatively inexpensive to build,
usually costing no more than $200,000 each. After the towers are
up, they tend to generate steady revenue, much of it from blue-chip
companies that often sign long-term contracts. These pacts usually
require payment in advance and contain built-in rent increases.
</P>
<P>
   Some tower management companies have amassed impressive lists of
customers. Crown Castle's clients, for example, include AT&AMP;T
Wireless, Bell Atlantic Mobile, Motorola, Pagenet and Sprint PCS.
Last year, the company acquired the domestic broadcast transmission
network of the British Broadcasting Corp. It is also pursuing
acquisitions in Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of early foothold in the international wireless market
distinguishes Crown Castle from American Tower, its nearest
competitor. But Crown is also carrying more debt than its rival
because of acquisitions over the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   As of March 31, it had $437 million in debt, more than three
times as much as American Tower, although Crown's planned initial
offering could erase much of that debt.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Roth, an analyst at Renaissance Capital, an
initial-offering research firm in Greenwich, Conn., said Crown
Castle had enough cash flow to service the debt. But he said the
stock carried other risks. Because of the company's rapid
expansion, he said, ``it's hard to determine where their internal
growth ends and where their acquisition growth begins.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the company's ability to generate enough
cash flow will depend on how well it can compete with other bidders
for tower rights _ and on how customers rate the quality and
breadth of the company's network.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to breadth, American Tower may have a two-year
lead on its rivals, analysts said. It also appears to have a more
diversified customer base, with no single customer accounting for
more than 10 percent of the company's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, during the first three months of this year, BBC
accounted for about 46 percent of Crown Castle's revenue, while
Nextel Communications, its second-largest customer, accounted for
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of quick expansion is perhaps best seen in a
strategy change by Specialty Teleconstructors. It has been focused
on building and managing towers for other companies while others
were busy buying. Now the company is racing to catch up but has
found that the price of existing towers has become so expensive
that it is cheaper to build them.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in Specialty's business plan contributed to a 12
percent decline in revenue and a 53 percent decline in profits for
the nine months ended March 31, compared with the period a year
earlier. But the shift from just managing to owning could
eventually mean a stronger revenue stream for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty also expects to derive advantages from its acquisition
in April of another tower company, Omni-America Inc., which has
amassed marketing power with several wireless carriers, like
BellSouth, and which also recently received an investment windfall
from Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, the venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business is a great economic model on paper, but it's
very complex _ it's not as simple as `build a tower and they will
come,' '' said Carl E. Hirsch, the chief executive of OmniAmerica.
``It's about building carrier relationships. It's not just about
real estate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
