<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 9,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLATION-ART (Undated) _ I still recall Gary Hill's
installation at Documenta 9 in Kassel, Germany, with pleasure, even
if it was a little hokey: in the middle of the show, his work was a
sanctuary behind blackout curtains, a long room of videotaped
images of people who seemed to emerge from the darkness like
ghosts, looking out at us, smiling, frowning or whatever, then
retreating as if in a dream. That was six years ago. Since then,
what was no longer uncommon even at that time has become so
commonplace that very often it has passed beyond cliche to parody:
installation art is in the late 90s roughly what Abstract
Expressionism was by the late 50s. By Michael Kimmelman. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROBBINS-FANCY-FREE (subslug) (Undated) _ Jerome Robbins was an
everyday presence in my dancegoing life from early on. I saw his
three sailors on the town in ``Fancy Free'' as a child shortly
after he created this ballet, his first, in 1944. It appealed to
children and grown-ups alike. Ballet had already seduced me with
Act II of ``Swan Lake.'' But ``Fancy Free,'' like all Robbins
works, opened a door. It let me know at a very young age that
ballet had a wide horizon and was not limited to a single type of
theatrical experience. By Anna Kisselgoff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   JEROME-ROBBINS-APPRAISAL (Undated) _ Celebrities from dance and
theater industry offer their assessment and stories of Jerome
Robbins, dancer and choreographer extraordinaire of ballets and
Broadway shows, who died  &QL; 
12 days ago. By Jennifer Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HENSLEY-OKLAHOMA-MUSICAL (London) _ In a New York theater
climate that regularly welcomes Britons, famous or otherwise _
whether Ralph Fiennes or Eddie Izzard _ there is something
particularly gratifying about an American unknown causing a stir in
London. And a Georgia-born baritone named Shuler Hensley most
definitely is doing just that as the menacing Jud Fry in the Royal
National Theater's current revival of ``Oklahoma!'' By Matt Wolf.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER (subslug) (London) _ Any theater historian will
tell you that the 1943 ``Oklahoma!'' was crucial to the evolution
of the Broadway musical and, doing so, leave you wondering if you
honestly wish to see it revived. Trevor Nunn, the Royal National
Theater's director, is staging the Rodgers and Hammerstein's
musical in the Olivier auditorium this summer. By Benedict
Nightingale. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER-DESIGNERS (London) _ Anthony Ward and Mark
Thompson often have designed shows that opened during the same
season, and sometimes _ at the Royal Shakespeare Company in
Stratford-on-Avon, for instance _ even in the same week. But the
two men, who live together, concede that they found themselves in
an unusual situation last month: separately employed on competing
musicals, two of the season's biggest shows, and with back-to-back
opening nights. By Matt Wolf. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AVENGERS-FILM (Undated) _ The great tragedy in the lives of men
of a certain age and outlook is that there is one, and only one,
Emma Peel. As embodied, quite literally and quite luminously, by
Diana Rigg in the arch 1960s spy-fi show ``The Avengers,'' she was
the first and arguably the last woman on television to combine
sensuality with ironic intellect. With the jury already Rigged, Uma
Thurman faces an impossible task portraying Emma Peel in the film
version of ``The Avengers'' opening on Friday. By Franz Lidz.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-CARTOONS (Prague, Czech Republic) _ At the height of the
cold war, hundreds of cartoons distributed in the United States
were actually made in Communist Czechoslovakia. Throughout the
1960s, episodes of ``Tom and Jerry,'' ``Popeye'' and ``Krazy Kat,''
as well as animated versions of classic children's books like
``Madeline'' and ``In the Night Kitchen,'' came into American
theaters, homes, schools and libraries straight from the animation
studios of Prague. By Jen Nessel.
</P>
<P>
   BEVERLY-HILLS-FILM (Los Angeles) _``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' a
film that Ms. Tamara Jenkins wrote and directed, is a 70s-era tale
about the coming of age of 15-year-old Vivian Abramowitz (Natasha
Lyonne). In it, Vivian and her two brothers are being schlepped by
their 60-something father (Alan Arkin) from one thin-walled,
furniture-deprived domicile to the next, each barely within the
90210 ZIP code so as to afford them access to superior public
schools. By Margy Rochlin. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-HEART-FILM (subslug) (Undated) _ When ``Dead Heart'' played
in Australia in 1996, Nicholas Parsons's film, about a highly
charged confrontation between white and aboriginal cultures at Wala
Wala, a remote settlement in the desert 50 miles west of Alice
Springs, was about to fade away from art houses when discussion of
it on a Sydney talk show helped extend its run to 20 weeks. In this
country, ``Dead Heart'' received favorable reviews but disappeared
quickly, in the manner of many good little films. Now it is back on
a videotape from Fox Lorber. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCKAYLE-DANCE (Undated) _ The choreographer Donald McKayle can
be as difficult to locate as he is to classify. Instead of staying
in one place, he shuttles between New York and California. Rather
than create dances for just one medium, he regularly invents them
for Broadway, television, film and the concert stage. By Valerie
Gladstone. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHRYGIAN-GATES-MUSIC (Undated) _ It may disturb the composer
John Adams that his operas have not been revived, as reported in
these pages, but there is a grain of consolation: ``Phrygian
Gates,'' a 20-year-old piano work by Adams, is apparently becoming
a favorite of new-music pianists. By Allan Kozinn. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FUTURISM-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``Russian Futurism,'' five compact
disks in three packages from Arte Nova, appropriates a title to
which it may not be entitled. Futurism had a distinct time, place
and description, and none of the music offered here fits the last
two of these. The visual arts were futurism's focus; the musical
arm survives in accounts of it. Aside from an all but
undecipherable shellac record, this brief, brave movement came and
went, leaving only its ideas behind. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   KARAJAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ In his heyday around 1960, Herbert von
Karajan seemed omnipresent in opera as well as concert, often
dubbed Generalmusikdirektor of Europe. Yet his postwar career
included the artistic direction of only one major opera house: the
Vienna State Opera, from 1957 to 1964. His tenure there became
legendary for artistic high points and equally for contentiousness,
an attribute long native to the institution and to its gossipy home
city. Until now, the sound of Karajan's Vienna performances has
been limited to pirate labels. But to commemorate the conductor's
90th birthday, last April, Deutsche Grammophon recently licensed
and issued four live recordings from those years, available in the
United States as special imports. By David Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   LATE-CENTURY-MUSIC (Undated) _ A short while ago I suggested
that an orchestra could operate for 10 years playing only music
written during the last three decades. That claim was meant to
indicate how much excellent music has been composed during this
time, not to put forward a real proposal for orchestral planning.
For one thing, homogeneous programs are generally less interesting
than mixed ones, which can put a new or recent piece into a useful
perspective. To hear Elliott Carter in the company of Bach, say, or
Steve Reich alongside Stravinsky, will shed light not only on the
newer music but also on the older. By Paul Griffith. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of classical CDs:
Mozart: Piano Works.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-STYLE-MUSIC (New York) _ The expression ``keeping it
real'' has become something of a mantra among the hip-hop set,
intended as an affirmation of one's cultural integrity. But this
notion of authenticity in contemporary popular music is hardly
restricted to hip-hop. Since the late 1980s, reality in music _
whether expressed through lyrical journalism, true-life confession
or strict stylistic adherence to one's heritage _ has become the
standard against which one's artistic integrity is measured. By
Mark Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONICA-MUSIC (Undated) _ Electronica makes use of samplers,
drum machine and synthesizers to make music that have little to do
with dancing and more to do with texture and patterns. Two new
albums, Plastikman's ``Consumed'' and Lithops' ``Uni Umit,'' hew to
electronica's definition. Both are hard to describe but remarkable,
proving that electronica is not as alienating or superficial as its
naysayers claim. By Sasha Frere-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ZAHA-HADID-ARCHITECT (Undated) _ Zaha Hadid's design for the
Contemporary Arts Center in Cincinnati won't be officially unveiled
until this October, but surely I'm not the only one impatient for a
preview. And in fact the design is already far enough along to
praise Cincinnati for giving this remarkable architect her first
commission in the United States. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLATION-ART-COLLECTORS (subslug) (Undated) _ Some
contemporary art collectors are so unfazed by installation-size
works that they would very likely buy Uranus if they could get God
to come and properly install it. But there is one artist still
largely beyond their grasp: Ann Hamilton. Ms. Hamilton, 42, an
Ohioan whose work is perhaps the most elaborate of all, sells her
installations only to museums. By Nancy Hass. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENTS-LOVE-EXHIBIT (Yorba Linda, Calif.) _ The item in the
newspaper appeared in a listing for museum shows. ``Come see
Hillary Rodham Clinton's wedding gown,'' the tiny print said.
``We're just an hour from Los Angeles.'' his was an announcement
from the Richard Nixon Library and Birthplace here in Yorba Linda.
I called to double-check. Was it a prank perpetrated by one of the
old Watergate plumbers? The recording explained everything: the
establishment was presenting the exhibition ``My Dearest Partner,''
all about husbands and wives in the White House. By Deanne
Stillman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL-LIST-TV (Undated) _ Warning! This is (italics)not(end
italics) a list. Nothing will be ordered, ranked or
alphanumerically indexed. There will be no color-coding. No scales
from 1 to 10. There might be an exploded 3-D pie chart or a Venn
diagram somewhere toward the bottom; I haven't decided yet. (As a
concession, however, to those of you suffering from late-millennial
list addiction, here: No. 17 _ Fred Mertz, No. 18 _ The Bay of
Fundy, No. 19 _ Pickled tongue.) The lazybones shorthand of list
making isn't a bad thing. Humankind has always hankered after an
orderly, manageable universe in which the accounting of our stars
and ourselves comes easy. By Jeff MacGregor. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ST.-ELSEWHERE-TV (Undated) _ A new video series is availale that
draws on all seven seasons of the hospital show ``St. Elsewhere''
(1982-88). By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOUIS-TIFFANY-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ For thousands of tourists who
wander into Tiffany &AMP; Co. on Fifth Avenue in New York City this
summer to gape at jewelry designed by Elsa Peretti, Paloma Picasso
and Jean Schlumberger, there is a surprise in store. Interspersed
among the showcases on the second floor are 34 pieces of jewelry
designed by the founder's son, Louis Comfort Tiffany. By Paula
Deitz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AIRLINE-ALLIANCE (Undated) _ Airlines team up, raising
some hackles. By Laurence Zuckerman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ALASKA (Undated) _ A heartening return to Prince William
Sound. By Timothy Egan. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Summer treats onstage and off. By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Picasso works installed at birthplace
in Malaga; Lorikeets, Meerkats and Koalas in St. Louis; Valet
parking introduced at Kennedy; European links to U.S. are focus of
new guide; Blimps and balloons to fill Ottawa skies. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel. This
week: Rembrandt, by Rembrandt; Buenos Aires hotels; Airport
parking; Nevis runway. By Joseph Siano. (Moved).
</P>
</TEXT>
