<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     08-07 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR TO FACE HEARING OVER `SERIOUS AND REPETITIVE' LEAKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge has found enough ``serious and
repetitive'' leaks of secret grand jury information about the White
House sex scandal to warrant a hearing that could lead to penalties
against independent counsel Kenneth Starr or his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers made public Friday, U.S. District Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson cites Starr's own comments in a magazine and in
television interviews, plus dozens of news articles and broadcasts
relying on anonymous sources, as evidence that prosecutors probably
violated grand jury secrecy rules.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were released by a three-judge federal appeals
panel that rejected Starr's effort to block an inquiry by Johnson
into the source of the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Starr and his staff must ``now come forward with evidence ... to
rebut inferences'' that his office was the source of dozens of news
articles and broadcasts containing grand jury information, said the
panel of judges from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   If the prosecutors fail to satisfy Johnson that they were not
the sources of leaked grand jury information, they face penalties
ranging from civil contempt of court to referral to the Justice
Department for possible criminal charges. Federal law prohibits
prosecutors and grand jurors from disclosing matters before grand
juries.
</P>
<P>
   Starr downplayed the significance of Johnson's ruling saying
that leaks might have come from grand jury witnesses or their
lawyers, who are not bound by the secrecy rules that govern
prosecutors. Starr said his office did not violate the rules and
``we welcome the opportunity to demonstrate that fact'' to the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attorney David Kendall, who filed the initial complaint
accusing Starr of leaking information, hailed the appeals court
ruling. ``The endemic and casual disclosures of grand jury
information, which have characterized the past seven months of the
(Starr) investigation, are highly unprofessional and utterly
indefensible,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   While upholding Johnson's decision to investigate the leaks, the
appeals court ruled that she should conduct the review without
Clinton's attorneys present to avoid compromising Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, which included sealed rulings by Johnson in late
June, were made public a day after Monica Lewinsky testified before
Starr's grand jury about a dozen sexual encounters with President
Clinton, many of them in his private office at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's account of an 18-month affair contradicts the
president's sworn denial that he and the former White House intern
ever engaged in sex. Clinton is scheduled to testify before the
grand jury by closed-circuit television Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The president avoided reporters' questions Friday about
Lewinsky's grand jury appearance, and a spokesman declined comment.
``The president, as he said last Friday, is not going to have any
comment on this situation between now and the 17th,'' said White
House spokesman Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the president was asked Friday to delay the
swearing-in of U.N. Ambassador Bill Richardson as Energy Secretary
until the Senate Energy Committee can clear up allegations that he
lied under oath regarding a job he offered Lewinsky a few weeks
before initial reports about the sex-and-perjury scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, wrote Clinton
asking for the delay because of a published report that Richardson
misled committee members when he said during his confirmation
hearing that he was ready to hire Lewinsky for an opening on his
staff in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting documents and unidentified sources, the Washington Times
reported that Richardson did not have an opening in his New York
office in October when he offered Lewinsky the job. The offer was
made following an interview that was arranged at the behest of the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Richardson was trying to accommodate
Lewinsky's desire to move to New York from Washington, where she
was working in a low-level public relations job at the Pentagon.
When the scandal broke in January, Richardson ``panicked,'' the
newspaper said, describing how he then ``scrambled to find a slot
that he could claim existed long before'' the interview with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say whether Ambassador Richardson lied under oath, as
this story asserts, but it is my responsibility to find out,''
Murkowski said in explaining why he wants to delay Richardson
taking the oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has scheduled Richardson's swearing-in for early
September and Friday said there were no plans to delay the
ceremony. ``We know Bill Richardson will be a great Secretary of
Energy and we look forward to his swearing-in,'' said Jim Kennedy,
a spokesman for the White House counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson issued a statement standing by his July 22 testimony
and accused the newspaper of distorting facts. ``The position we
offered her was on the books before I became ambassador,''
Richardson said, adding that the opening was transferred from his
Washington office to New York ``before Ms. Lewinsky came on the
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
