<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA INSTALLS NEW PRESIDENT WHO PLANS TALKS WITH REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Andres Pastrana, a Conservative planning to
begin peace talks with increasingly aggressive rebels, took office
as president Friday, ending the scandal-ridden presidency of
Ernesto Samper by declaring, ``Change begins today.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's inauguration took place in a city fortified to
protect his 4,000 guests by as many police and military guards. He
was sworn in as the 60th president of Colombia 28 years after his
father, Misael Pastrana, now dead, took the same oath.
</P>
<P>
   Obscured by the pomp of the inauguration was the violence that
has been roiling the countryside in recent days, where explosions
and gunfights created a shattering soundtrack to the change of
power.
</P>
<P>
   With the country reeling financially, politically and socially,
the new president's first message pledged a complete turnaround in
government. He is taking over from a leader preoccupied with
holding on to power amid accusations from Washington that drug
dealers had bankrolled his election with $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's swearing in represented a vindication for Pastrana, 43,
who lost the election to Samper four years ago, and also for
Washington. Colombia supplies more than 70 percent of the cocaine
sold in the United States, and most of the heroin along the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana swept into office with the largest margin in his
country's history. A former senator and mayor of Bogota, he will
govern without a majority in Congress for his Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   With the country's finances in tatters, as his predecessor
carved up the government budget to buy allies to stay in office,
Pastrana promised an end to corruption, and said his administration
would be remembered as ``one of the cleanest in the history of
Colombia.'' It was Pastrana who blew the whistle on the Samper
campaign's ties to drug dealers, and on Friday he said, ``We cannot
go on tolerating the systematic theft of goods that belong to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the inauguration, guerrilla offensives
razed the main military and police bases for counter-narcotics
operations at Miraflores, killing and wounding scores of
Colombians, and bringing to 210 the number of security forces that
the rebels claim to hold captive.
</P>
<P>
   Though counter-drug operations out of Miraflores are heavily
financed by Washington, a State Department official said there were
no Americans at the bases. A newspaper report said the damage was
so bad after 13 hours of fighting that bodies were being recovered
by tractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, attacked
the military and police installations with a force estimated at
1,200 men and women, and the smaller National Liberation Army
attacked petroleum installations and other targets this week. In
the city of La Uribe, fighting continued Friday, with bodies
scattered on sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   While not mentioning this week's violence directly, Pastrana
called on Colombians to support the peace efforts. He insisted that
only when the state quells the violence of drug gangs, right-wing
paramilitaries and leftist rebels can society begin to rebuild
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his election in June, Pastrana broke precedent by
meeting with FARC leaders, who represent the country's largest
insurgent group. After the secret encounter, he accepted rebel
demands that security forces temporarily evacuate five cities,
covering an area the size of Switzerland. The rebels had demanded
the evacuation as a condition of peace talks, which Pastrana
promised to begin in the first 90 days of his administration.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though this week's rebel offensive was striking in several ways
_ in coordination, the weapons involved and the casualties _ it did
not prompt Colombians to back away from a prospective dialogue with
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Few Colombians support the rebels, according to polls, and many
have concluded that government forces cannot defeat them. So they
have adopted the view that only a political solution can end the
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Rangel, a former security adviser to Samper, said the
rebels were flexing their muscles to improve their position at the
bargaining table. In an essay in the daily newspaper Tiempo, which
the FARC took the unusual step of putting on the Internet, Rangel
said that the insurgent group planned to grow from 65 to 100 combat
cells in the next five years, with 30,000 combatants, and that the
meeting with Pastrana raised them to a new level of legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not stop their strategic plans because of a talk
with the president,'' Rangel wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC rebels themselves, in a statement to the Columbian
station Radionet, said they had staged the offensive as a parting
shot at Samper. ``The violent and corrupt government of Samper is
responsible for this,'' said Alfonso Cano, a FARC leader.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We reiterate our willingness to begin talks once
areas have been demilitarized in order to reach an accord on
reconciliation and national reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   In his brief, final address as president on Thursday night,
Samper reminded Colombians that he had once said he would leave the
Presidential Palace only with his ``head held high or dead.'' He
said, ``Tomorrow, I will do it in broad daylight with my conscience
calm. Seldom, in the history of this country, have so many
obstacles, internal and external, blocked the job of a president.''
</P>
<P>
   Samper asked forgiveness ``for my mistakes and understanding for
the deficiencies of the government,'' but said he was ``always
inspired by the greater desire to serve my country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
