<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEWINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With one victory in hand, Dewine seeks Clinton signature on
second bill
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With one bill signed by President Clinton and
another waiting in the wings, it's safe to say U.S. Sen. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio, had a good week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Friday signed DeWine's Workforce Investment Act of
1998, a detailed restructuring of the country's job training
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The law lets states, local governments and individuals tailor
programs to fit their needs, and to make one-stop job centers like
Dayton's the gateway to training.
</P>
<P>
   The other bill, awaiting Clinton's signature, would speed the
release of U.S. government records of the Holocaust during World
War II and reveal just how much officials here knew about the Nazi
attempt to exterminate Jews, Gypsies and others.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, DeWine heard Clinton praise his workforce efforts.
``Today, we celebrate a big step forward in making sure every adult
can keep on learning for a lifetime,'' Clinton said at the White
House Rose Garden ceremony
</P>
<P>
   ``To invest in our people, we have to give all of our people
access to world class education and training. We have to do more
than we are already doing.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWine has called the bill a needed companion to the 1996
welfare reform, giving welfare recipients the training they need to
find jobs that pay well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, everyone must be given the competitive skills that
are necessary to prosper in the new global economy,'' DeWine said
at the ceremony. ``This is the crucial second stage of welfare
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, communities and local businesses will
develop a three-year job training strategy. Local governments can
pick programs that train workers for jobs in local industries and
businesses, and use local resources, such as a community college or
vocational school, to provide the training.
</P>
<P>
   A state's governor will review the plan, then send it to the
U.S. Secretary of Labor for final approval. States will get block
grants to pay for their programs.
</P>
<P>
   The new law also lets workers decide which training program they
want to use.
</P>
<P>
   Programs now will have to be accredited by the Labor Department
and give prospective students access to statistics showing how many
of the program's graduates have jobs and how much they earn.
</P>
<P>
   Job training programs will be linked to courses that provide
training for people with disabilities, allowing students to
transfer between the two programs.
</P>
<P>
   Each trainee will have an individual training account to use for
training programs. After the trainee and a job counselor decide on
a program, the trainee will get a voucher to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Harshaw, a spokesman for Montgomery County Department of
Human Services, said Dayton is one step ahead of the new laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, we've been there, done that, bought the tee-shirt,''
Harshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton already has a one-stop job center and began working with
local businesses several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Harshaw said, the county's caseloads dropped and
fewer people are returning for a second or third round of training.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
