<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3982 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-STOTTLEMYRE-TEX     08-07 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STOTTLEMYRE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BROTHER'S DEATH SHAPED TODD STOTTLEMYRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Todd Stottlemyre could pitch the Rangers to a
World Series championship, but he wouldn't consider that his most
fulfilling moment. If he someday won a Cy Young Award, threw a
perfect game, or was voted league most valuable player, those
wouldn't top his list, either.
</P>
<P>
   He will always reserve that spot for a more significant memory.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 18 years ago, Stottlemyre's attitude about life changed
forever when his 11-year-old brother, Jason, died of leukemia in a
Seattle hospital. Eight days before Jason died, Todd, then 15,
attempted to save his brother's life by undergoing a painful
bone-marrow transplant operation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the operation didn't succeed, Stottlemyre for years
partially blamed himself for Jason's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a hurt for a lot of years,'' he said. ``But I got
through that. As I look back on it now, it's my greatest
achievement in life, thinking that I laid it all on the line to try
to save my brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my biggest accomplishment, and it always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who joined the Rangers last week as part of a trade
with St. Louis that sent Darren Oliver and Fernando Tatis to the
Cardinals, has a reputation as a fierce competitor who doesn't know
how to quit. And at least part of that psychological makeup, he
says, is the result of lessons he learned while watching his
brother deal with a terminal illness. Stottlemyre's father, Mel,
won 164 games in a successful career as a pitcher for the New York
Yankees and is now the Yankees' pitching coach. Todd, who has a
career record of 119-106 with a 4.22 earned-run average, is part of
the only father-son combination to record more than 100
major-league victories each.
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, Mel Sr., also was a professional pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Todd says Jason might have been the best natural athlete of all
the Stottlemyres. But shortly after his seventh birthday, Jason
became ill over the holidays at the family home in Yakima, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christmas present we got was that he had leukemia,'' Todd
recalls. ``At the time, none of us knew what the heck leukemia was.
But we knew he was real sick.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next four years, the closely knit Stottlemyre clan
gained an unwelcome insight into the trauma that blood cancer can
cause an innocent child.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Jason went in and out of remission. Each time,
chemotherapy and radiation treatments made him sick and caused his
hair to fall out.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young guy, that was tough, but that was on a much lesser
note,'' Todd said. ``He would seem to be doing good, and all of a
sudden it would hit him again. We all researched it. I think even
Jason knew what was going on. They used to have these leukemia
cards in the restaurants, and he'd never pass one without filling
it up with quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   As the disease advanced, doctors advised that a bone-marrow
transplant would be Jason's only hope for a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were tested, and Todd's blood was found to be
nearly a perfect match. During the operation in February 1981,
surgeons made 500 injections into Todd's hips to remove marrow for
the transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the transplant appeared to be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running around the hospital and everything,'' Todd
said. ``But about seven or eight days after the transplant, he went
into a coma and he never made it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre has replayed one scene thousands of times over in
his mind. He didn't have a driver's license, but with Jason's
heartbeat slowing and the end near, his parents asked him to drive
down the street to pick up his older brother and bring him to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As they hurried together down the hospital corridor toward
Jason's room, they were stopped by a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Did you hear?' And I said, `Yeah, his heartbeat has
slowed down.' And she said, `No, we lost him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, that's tough to think about. I mean, that was it.
That was the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he remembers ``verbally attacking'' the
attending physician, questioning him heatedly about what had gone
wrong with the transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of the loss of Jason, I carried with me for so long
that my blood wasn't good enough to save him. I almost felt
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day or so before he went into a coma, he wanted me to stay
overnight with him at the hospital. It was like he knew it was
coming. And yet he probably took it better than any of us. He just
took it all on. All the spinal taps and everything, his attitude
was, just bring it on. It was like he understood he was dying and
he was trying to make it better for everyone else. Watching an
11-year-old kid understand that is kind of hard to explain. How
could he be so grown up and so accepting of everything? It was
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Todd Stottlemyre has contributed greatly to medical
research seeking a cure for leukemia. He is host to a charity golf
tournament that has raised about $750,000 over six years.
</P>
<P>
   His father also is host to a benefit golf tournament in New
York. His mother, Jean, is active in the cause, as is his wife,
Sheri.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tragedy for a long time,'' Stottlemyre said. ``But
now the whole event is an inspiration on how to lead my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved everything that God gave him, the animals, the
outdoors. Every time I see a butterfly, I think of Jason running
with a net trying to chase it down and going back and looking at
his book to see exactly what kind of butterfly it was. I know it
sounds corny, but every time I see a frog, I think of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so full of life, and yet knowing everything. He never
felt sorry for himself that he had leukemia. He never asked why. He
just battled it. To courageously take on a devastating disease that
is the No. 1 child killer in this country, and to be so positive,
to me that's everything to learn from.
</P>
<P>
   ``For being here such a short time, he was such an inspiration.
My greatest teacher in life has been my little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who was the popular ace of the St. Louis staff and
previously played in Toronto and Oakland, was brought in as a
``hired gun'' of sorts, to help shore up the struggling Texas
pitching rotation for a late-summer playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   He takes baseball and his role seriously, he said, because he is
competitive by nature, but also because he feels a debt to
management and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do everything I can to prepare for the game, and to accept
my role and live up to it,'' he said. ``But when I think about
Jason and I think about baseball and look at it on the grand scope
of events, it's kind of meaningless, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try and teach my daughter (3-year-old Rachel)
those things that I've gone through and learned. That's a huge
responsibility. But I think it's good sometimes that people are
aware there are other things more important than throwing a 3-2
slider out there trying to get somebody out. There are other things
to fight for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
