<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-ART-2T     08-07 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO U.S. EMBASSIES IN EAST AFRICA BOMBED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.) (ART ADV: Three maps, showing locations of U.S. embassies in
Nairobi and Dar es Salaam and distance between the 2 bombing
locations, and two graphics, showing attacks on U.S. installations
overseas and diagrams of embassies bombed, are being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (See related AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-SCENE, AFRICA-SECURITY,
AFRICA-VICTIMS)  
(lb) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Two massive bombs exploded minutes apart
outside the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania late Friday
morning, killing at least 80 people, eight of them American, in
what U.S. officials said were coordinated terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, an enormous explosion ripped through downtown at
about 10:35 a.m., turning the busy Haile Selassie Avenue into a
scene of carnage and destruction that left more than 1,600 people
injured and dozens still missing long after night fell.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which leveled a three-story building containing a
secretarial school and gutted the rear half of the U.S. Embassy
next door, dismembered more than a dozen people passing on foot and
incinerated dozens of others in their seats in three nearby buses.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before, a bomb reportedly planted in a gasoline
tanker detonated near the front entrance of the U.S. Embassy in the
Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam. The blast destroyed the front
of the building and toppled a side wall, throwing charred debris
down the street, setting cars on fire and toppling trees. At least
seven people were killed and 72 injured, none of them American,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they believed the bombings were a terrorist
attack. Although officials did not identify any suspects, the
newspaper Al-Hayat _ based in Cairo, Egypt _ reported in its
Saturday editions that it had received a call claiming
responsibility for the bombings from a previously unknown group
called the Liberation Army of the Islamic Sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton condemned the attacks as
abhorrent and inhuman acts of cowardice. He vowed to bring those
responsible to justice ``no matter what or how long it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombings underscored how vulnerable American officials and
diplomats remain in some Third World capitals in this age of global
terrorism, where borders are porous and security is not as tight as
in the industrialized world. The blasts seemed to be coordinated
attacks against the United States, and appeared unconnected to any
local grievances or political currents in the two capitals, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At least eight Americans and an unknown number of Kenyan embassy
employees died in the explosion in Nairobi, which left embassy
offices a honeycomb of burned-out rubble with bodies buried inside.
``It's going to take a couple of days to find out what's in
there,'' Bill Barr, an embassy spokesman, said. Barr said 15 U.S.
officials were hospitalized and six others were still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the explosion, which shattered windows for
several blocks and blew the roof off a building across the street,
was preceded by a smaller blast, perhaps a grenade. Both appeared
to emanate from a parking lot just behind the embassy, the police
said. Hundreds of people were cut by falling glass and ran bleeding
from the area, flooding local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real national disaster and we highly suspect it is a
terrorist attack,'' Otieno Osur, the director of police operations
in Nairobi, said.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, rescue workers and soldiers in Nairobi toiled
under floodlights with backhoes to extricate dozens of bodies still
buried in the rubble of the Ufundi House behind the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   In Dar es Salaam, embassy officials said they did not know who
was behind the bombing. ``At this point only several hours after
the bombing we have no idea what the motives of the bombers were,''
John Lange, the deputy chief of mission at the embassy, told
Reuters. `` All we know is that an explosion occurred right in
front of our embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been threatened by at least two terrorist
groups in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Egypt's banned Jihad group warned that it
would retaliate against U.S. targets because of Washington's role
in pressing for the extradition of three suspected terrorists from
Albania to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a Saudi Arabian fundamentalist, Osama bin Laden,
identified by the U.S. State Department as a sponsor of terrorism,
also urged his followers to wage an Islamic holy war against the
United States. Bin Laden, who is believed to be in exile in
Afghanistan, is not only a suspect in the 1996 attack at Khobar but
also in the 1995 car bombing in Riyadh that killed five Americans.
He is also believed to have links to the Jihad movement in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   But no firm evidence has yet emerged linking either group to
Friday's bombings, the Kenyan police and U.S. officials said.
Washington has dispatched a special team from the FBI to assist the
local police with the investigation. Kenyan investigators said late
Friday night on state-run television that they suspect that a van
full of explosives was parked behind the embassy in front of the
Ufundi House.
</P>
<P>
   Among the injured in Nairobi was the U.S. ambassador, Prudence
Bushnell, who suffered cuts from falling glass. She was meeting
with a Kenyan minister in a building adjacent to the embassy when
the explosion occurred, Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told of scenes of horror and confusion in the Kenyan
capital after the bomb exploded. A thick plume of smoke rose
hundreds of feet into the air, followed by a rain of glass and
metal, several witnesses said. The blast left a black crater in the
parking lot between the two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Ufundi Co-op House, which houses a secretarial college and
offices, collapsed inward on itself, trapping scores of people. The
reinforced embassy building remained standing and most of the 200
people inside walked out, but its rear offices were devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Three buses on the avenue outside were destroyed and several
cars were left twisted hunks of blackened metal. The dismembered
bodies of at least fifteen people were found on the street near the
blast site. People began crawling over the mountain of cement and
steel that had been the Ufundi House, clawing at the debris to free
people trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, hundreds of office workers poured out of nearby
buildings, many of them lacerated by rubble and glass. More than
1,000 people were treated at local hospitals, hospital officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most witnesses said they heard two explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a small blast and I thought something had just dropped
on the roof,'' said Zachariah Chianda, a 44-year-old banker, who
was next door in the Cooperative Bank Building. ``Then the next
thing we heard was a big blast. Everything was falling down. I
found myself on the floor. People were screaming and some people
were trapped in the elevators. We tried to get people out. There
was glass and metal all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Kiiru, a 31-year-old bank employee, was in a
second-floor computer room of the Cooperative Bank Building when
the explosion rocked the foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw things flying all over the place and computers blowing
up,'' he said. ``We made our way outside. It was horrific. There
was a lot of smoke. It was like a fog. We couldn't see beyond 2
feet. Then we saw there was blood all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   In the emergency room at The Nairobi Hospital, the walking
wounded sat in dazed rows, trying to come to terms with what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Beatrice Ngeru, a 23-year-old secretary, said she had gone to
her window after she heard the first explosion, which sounded like
a gunshot. Her window in the Solar Building looked across the
street at the U.S. Embassy. Seconds later, the window exploded,
raking her arms, face and chest with glass. ``There was a loud bang
and there was smoke all over,'' she said. ``The glass hit me. It
shattered all the glass in our building.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's three main hospitals were overwhelmed with a flood of
patients, the authorities said. Blood was in short supply, and the
authorities issued an urgent appeal for donations.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people in blood-soaked clothes, their faces raked with
cuts, sat in hospital corridors, while overworked physicians tried
to treat the most seriously injured. Nurses and volunteers stitched
wounds of others in hallways and in the open air.
</P>
<P>
   Outside The Nairobi Hospital, crowds of people looking for
friends and relatives gathered around the lists taped to the walls
showing those who had been admitted with serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Vincent Mengo, a 27-year-old street vendor, sat in the
emergency room, his left hand and arm bandaged in bloody gauze. He
had narrowly escaped death, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mengo said he was walking along the avenue near the Ufundi
building when he heard the first explosion in the parking lot
behind the U.S. Embassy. He ducked into the Cooperative Bank
Building, thinking it was a gunshot. Then the world outside
exploded in smoke and fire.
</P>
<P>
   With local hospitals stretched to their limit, the United States
dispatched military cargo planes from Germany with loads of
medicine and hospital equipment, including mobile operating
theaters, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The special FBI team also departed Washington for Africa. The
bureau has been involved for two years with the Saudi Arabian
authorities in the investigation of the June 1996 car-bomb blast
that killed 19 U.S. soldiers in their barracks in the town of
Khobar.
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, rescue workers continued to attack the
mountain of debris with pickaxes, searching for survivors. At 10
p.m., four people were discovered alive in an elevator, but they
had yet to be pulled to safety.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes of finding others alive in the wreckage were dimming.
``It is horrific to hear moaning, sighs and whimpers from under the
rubble when we can do so little to reach victims quickly,'' a Red
Cross spokeswoman, Nina Galbe, told The Associated Press. ``The
longer they're trapped, the less their chances for survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers used backhoes and bulldozers to move the mountain
of debris. Two rescue workers carried out the shredded body of a
young woman on a stretcher and laid her in the back of a pickup.
Stretchers were laid out in rows for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a school here, a college for girls,'' said Paul
Harrison, a 33-year-old Red Cross volunteer who had pulled three
bodies from the rubble. ``It's horrible. I've never seen anything
like it. This reminds me of Beirut, or the Oklahoma bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of the darkened embassy, U.S. marines in full battle
gear stood guard, wide-eyed and battle-bright, guns in combat
position, as night fell. They were guarding a disaster site, but
there were still several bodies of American officials and embassy
employees inside, waiting to be transported to a mortuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two explosions, that's all I know,'' said Gunnery
Sgt. Gary Cross, who was in a stairwell when the bomb went off.
``The whole building started shaking and stuff started falling.''
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant looked above him at the shattered windows of the
embassy. Someone had propped an American flag out of one of them,
presumably to replace the one that usually flies above the
building. The banner hung limp in the dimming light _ forlorn,
soiled, defiant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
