<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3991 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWISH-PHILANTHROPY-A     08-07 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-PHILANTHROPY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH CHARITIES PLAN TO JOIN FORCES, BUT DIVISIONS RUN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass., Ill., Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once the envy of fund-raisers of all faiths, the United Jewish
Appeal and the Council of Jewish Federations were unrivaled
philanthropic powerhouses among American and Canadian Jews, many of
whom viewed them as central to any charitable work done on their
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing about Jewish life is so simple today. Jews are
sharply divided over questions as basic as who can call themselves
Jewish. And these days, Israel, the historic focus of the groups'
charity, is as often a divisive force as a galvanizing one.
</P>
<P>
   So splits have developed in how big donors want their money to
be spent. On a blank check to Israel? On strengthening Jewish
commitment in the United States? Sometimes, it seems that the only
thing the big givers have in common is an intense desire for
hands-on control of their charitable dollars.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means is that while the UJA and the Jewish
federations still raise well over $1 billion each year, they now
struggle to persuade Jews _ younger ones, especially _ that the
organizations are as relevant today as they were during the
Holocaust or Israel's pioneer days.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, leaders of the groups have stumbled in
their efforts to address these challenges. But now they say they
have a plan.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting last month outside Chicago, the UJA and the
federations that make up the council reached an agreement in
principle to merge. The terms of the deal shift power over spending
abroad to the grass roots. Donors in local communities will have
more say over where the dollars sent to Israel should be spent and
whether a bigger share of funds should go to Jewish
community-building at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The groups already have close links and recently combined
offices in New York. But while they still must work out many of the
crucial details and while they have failed to merge in the past,
leaders at both the national and local levels say there is a fresh
commitment to join forces.
</P>
<P>
   Their hope is that the new group will be able to raise more
money and appeal to more donors because it ``will cast a broader
net and engage more people,'' said Carole A. Solomon, the national
volunteer chairwoman of the United Jewish Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the system is owned by these various communities, they
should feel very comfortable at the end of the day,'' Ms. Solomon
added, emphasizing that the merged entity ``will be leaner and
meaner and more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders also say they cannot afford to fail. ``There is
too much at stake for it not to work,'' said Bennett L. Aaron, the
chairman of the United Israel Appeal, which oversees the money that
the United Jewish Appeal raises for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The local federations have been pushing hardest for change.
``The system requires an influx of new energy,'' said Barry Shrage,
the full-time president of the Combined Jewish Philanthropies in
Boston, one of the 187 community organizations in the United States
and Canada that make up the Council of Jewish Federations and that
are responsible for local charity and for raising money to send
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Shrage told his fellow federation leaders in December that he
believed ``our current system is in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving to the groups' combined annual campaign, which raises
funds that are not designated for specific projects, has fallen to
around $800 million in 1996 from a peak of $825 million in 1990. In
that period, Americans' individual charitable donations over all
climbed 26 percent, according to ``Giving USA,'' an annual report
on philanthropy by an arm of the American Association of
Fund-Raising Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to reinvent the North American system of Jewish
philanthropy was reached in early July, at a meeting of more than
140 Jewish leaders in Oakbrook, Ill. The leaders say they intend to
hammer out details of the merger in coming months, with a goal of
creating the new organization by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is considerable. The debate about how Jews should
undertake their religious obligation of tikkun olam, Hebrew for the
repair of the world, has caused big divisions. The new organization
will need to develop a message that resonates broadly enough to
overcome such differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its success will depend not only on its ability to restructure
and streamline and coordinate, but depend on its ability to lead
American Jews to greater consensus,'' said Jack Wertheimer, the
provost of the Jewish Theological Seminary, the Conservative
movement's rabbinical academy in New York, and an expert on Jewish
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, powerful philanthropists with very strong views on
Jewish communal life are dubious that much can be gained by simply
merging the United Jewish Appeal and the federations. ``The problem
is that they are both sick, and bringing them together will not
make them better,'' said Edgar M. Bronfman, the chairman of the
Seagram Co. and a prominent Jewish philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, who as president of the World Jewish Congress has been
a leader in efforts to seek compensation from Switzerland for
Holocaust survivors, said the United Jewish Appeal-federation
system should concentrate more on stopping the ``outflow of Jews''
from Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real agenda of Jewish life is to stop or curb
assimilation,'' Bronfman said.
</P>
<P>
   Created nearly 60 years ago in response to Kristallnacht, the
1938 Nazi rampage, the United Jewish Appeal enjoyed tremendous
support from American Jews, who rallied together to rescue Jews
around the world and to help build a new Jewish state. But as the
number of Jews seeking asylum falls and as Israel celebrates its
50th anniversary as a stronger and more controversial country, many
American Jews find these goals less compelling.
</P>
<P>
   The federation movement, which grew out of the communal needs of
North American Jews in the late 19th century, has traditionally
balanced the desire to give locally with support for overseas
causes. That dual purpose has always been somewhat in conflict with
the aim of the United Jewish Appeal, an advocate for Israel and
Jews abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has sharpened as the federations search for new
ways to persuade their communities to give. It is becoming ``less
meaningful to wrap Jewish philanthropy around certain flag-waving
issues,'' said Stephen H. Hoffman, executive vice president of the
Jewish Community Federation of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, the UJA and the federations conduct a
unified fund-raising campaign for both local and overseas needs.
Indeed, many Jews _ their contact with the groups limited to
receiving fund-raising appeals _ would be surprised to learn that
they were not already a single organization.
</P>
<P>
   The federations have always had complete say over how the local
money is spent and what portion of locally raised funds will go to
programs outside North America. That money is divided under a fixed
formula between the Jewish Agency for Israel, an Israeli group that
has an annual budget of about $350 million, and the American Jewish
Joint Distribution Committee, with a budget of about $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Donors still respond to emergencies. Operation Exodus, for
example, the campaign in the early 1990s to help relocate Jews from
the former Soviet Union, raised roughly $1 billion. But the general
campaign seems less compelling to a new generation of Jewish
philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents and their generation were genetically coded to give
to the United Jewish Appeal and federation,'' said James S. Tisch,
the president of the Loews Corp. ``It was lost in my generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisch now heads the UJA-Federation of New York. His father,
Laurence, Loews's co-chief executive, and his mother, Wilma, have
long been powers in Jewish causes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving to the annual joint campaign, Jews are giving
to competing Jewish charities and their synagogues as well as to
secular causes, which are courting Jewish philanthropists more
aggressively than they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this shift reflects a widespread desire by donors to
give less to umbrella organizations, whether to the United Way or
the UJA. Donors want to be able to follow their gifts more closely
by giving to specific causes or creating their own private
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Money to donor-advised funds and foundations represented about a
third of the $1.6 billion raised by the federations in 1996,
according to the Council of Jewish Federations. The remaining money
was for the federations' own endowments or for special campaigns
like Operation Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline also reflects a growing perception that the UJA
and the federations are not keeping up with the times.
</P>
<P>
   Among liberal Jews, organizations like the New Israel Fund, a
Washington group created in 1979 to focus on issues like religious
pluralism and democracy in Israel, are increasingly popular, though
they are still tiny compared with the Jewish Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Among the tradition-minded, money is flowing to Orthodox
yeshivas and hospitals as well as directly to religious parties in
Israel, according to Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Giving donors more say, through the federations, is at the heart
of the push for change. ``Federations have had to recognize the
pressure they feel from their own donors,'' said Bernard C.
Moscovitz, executive vice president of the UJA. ``They want more
control of the goings-on of the national organization.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the national groups and the local
federations _ which clearly disagree about how much the current
system needs to change _ can reach an agreement. ``I hope the
cynics and optimists can get together,'' said Richard L. Wexler, a
Chicago lawyer who serves as the volunteer president of the United
Jewish Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Central to their disagreement is whether the emphasis on
providing funds for Israel ignores other needs, like Jewish
education in America.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Daniel R. Allen, the executive vice chairman of the United
Israel Appeal, said that if the system did not keep Israel ``front
and center,'' it would be a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. Rukin, the volunteer chairman of the Boston
federation, wants the new group to address issues in North America,
especially the development of Jewish community. ``We need to build
a new set of relationships with Israel,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Others question the role of the Jewish Agency for Israel, which
recently underwent a big reorganization in response to criticisms
that it had a bloated bureaucracy that was addled by cronyism. Some
officials of the federations say the agency is still too
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   To help reach some consensus, the federations and the national
groups will very likely conduct a formal review of the work now
being done overseas. But exactly how much say the federations _ and
their big local givers _ should have in determining the new group's
priorities is also the subject of vigorous debate.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, for one, does not want the system to become ``donor
driven,'' arguing that would not be ``in the best interest of the
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the federations have already refused to guarantee that
they will continue to finance overseas programs at a certain level.
In fact, earlier merger talks ended two years ago because the local
groups would not make that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, some national leaders say they are willing
to move ahead. ``I think it is time we trusted the federations,''
said Wexler of the UJA. ``Let's have the debate and let's see it
play out.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little to lose. Despite the existing system's goal of
having the federations act in concert, many local groups are
already going their own ways because they feel excluded from the
process. They are undertaking overseas projects that they think
will more closely tie their communities to others in Israel or the
former Soviet Union, and many are giving small sums to
organizations like the New Israel Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland federation, for example, last year withheld $3
million of the money it normally sends to the UJA to pursue its own
ideas about how to help Jews around the world, despite vehement
protests from national leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And much of the real work _ convincing Jews that they should
give to help Jews in Prague as well as in Brooklyn _ remains to be
done at the local level.
</P>
<P>
   ``These machinations, among these national organizations, are
the interest of insiders,'' said James Tisch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people say the plan to join forces is an
unparalleled opportunity for American and Canadian Jews to
collaborate on encouraging Judaism to flourish here as well as
abroad. ``The future is going to be created no matter what,'' said
Shrage of Boston, who is fond of telling the Purim story of Queen
Esther, who must decide whether to risk angering the king in order
to save the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have choices to make,'' he said. ``This is a time for
potential renaissance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
