<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-WHYTHERE?-TEX     08-07 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-WHY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSIES MAY HAVE BEEN THE EASIEST TARGETS
</HEADLINE>
 THERE?-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenya and Tanzania are more often the stuff of TV travelogues. A
lure for tourists from around the world, both can boast spectacular
scenery, abundant wildlife and friendly people.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorist attacks are virtually unknown.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted experts on East Africa to suggest Friday that the
U.S. embassies in Nairobi, the Kenyan capital, and Dar es Salaam,
the Tanzanian capital, were attacked because they were easy
targets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. relations with Tanzania are considered excellent, the
specialists noted. U.S.-Kenyan ties have been strained in recent
years because of endemic corruption and a reluctance of President
Daniel arap Moi to ease his tight grip on power. But both the
government and opposition groups curry favor with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can eat my words tomorrow, but I would be willing to predict
with 99 percent certainty that the only association these attacks
have to Kenya and Tanzania is that these embassies were vulnerable
targets,'' said Africa historian Tim Burke of Swarthmore College in
Swarthmore, Pa. Burke visited Nairobi in March.
</P>
<P>
   Cited as factors that would make it easier for terrorists to
carry out attacks in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam:
</P>
<P>
   Direct air links from both capitals with Europe, the Middle
East, South Asia and other major African cities.
</P>
<P>
   Good communications between Nairobi, on a mile-high African
plateau, and Dar es Salaam, a port city on the Indian Ocean, 450
miles to the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The relative ease with which explosives could be smuggled across
borders by bribing customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nairobi and Dar es Salaam are the crossroads of the West and
the Middle East _ just three or four hours by air to Tehran,
Baghdad, or Saudi Arabia,'' said political scientist Michael Chege,
Kenya-born director of the African Studies Center at the University
of Florida at Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenya and Tanzania are the soft underbelly of Western
influence in the region, and that makes them very, very
vulnerable,'' Chege said. When a terrorist can no longer slip
easily into ``Europe, Israel or New York's World Trade Center,
where does he go?''
</P>
<P>
   Kenya is not a country without problems. It has a high crime
rate, is notorious for official corruption and has seen some civil
unrest. Nevertheless, the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, as well as the
one in Dar es Salaam, were considered to be at little risk from the
local populations.
</P>
<P>
   The embassies were less fortified than those in such African
capitals as Lagos, Nigeria, and Harare, Zimbabwe, said Joel Barkan,
a political scientist at the University of Iowa and a senior fellow
at the U.S. Peace Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's blast in Nairobi is the first major bombing in the
Kenyan capital since New Year's Eve 1980, when a bomb exploded in
the landmark Norfolk Hotel, killing 15 and wounding 80. At the
time, Kenyan authorities identified as a suspect a Moroccan aligned
with a Palestinian liberation group, theorizing that he targeted
the hotel because it was owned by a locally prominent Jewish
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, there's never been an incident like this in
Tanzania, and it's been only the second in Nairobi after nearly a
two-decade hiatus,'' Barkan said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive device detonated after Nairobi's morning rush
hour, but the sidewalks were clogged with people lining up for
visas outside the U.S. Embassy and to enter nearby banks, one by
one, because of a bank workers' strike that began Monday, said
Chege, who returned from the Kenyan capital this week.
</P>
<P>
   There were far fewer casualties in the Dar es Salaam blast,
apparently because the embassy is not downtown, but in a less
congested, suburban area called Oyster Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Like other specialists, Barkan said he doubts that the
terrorists came from Kenya or Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   If another country in the region is suspect, he said, Sudan is
the most likely. Sudan, which borders Kenya on the northwest, has
butted heads with the United States by supporting Ugandan rebels,
by launching incursions into Eritrea and Ethiopia, and because of
its human-rights abuses against the southern Sudanese Christian
minority, Barkan said.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are neighbors and were both once ruled by the
British, Tanzania and Kenya had radically different colonial
experiences and took different paths after independence in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   In colonial Kenya, the British encouraged European settlement.
The mainly pastoral, indigenous African population was transformed
into a work force through a ``hut'' tax, loss of ancestral lands
and a lack of educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Mau Mau uprising, dominated by the Kikuyu tribe that lived
in the ``white'' highlands, helped pressure London to relinquish
the colony, although African fatalities far outnumbered those of
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzania was called Tanganyika before a 1964 merger with the
island nation of Zanzibar. The mainland portion was colonized as
German East Africa in the late 19th century but was not
``pacified'' until German troops brutally crushed a grassroots
uprising known as the Maji Maji rebellion. The colony became a
British mandate after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Both neighbors began independent rule with single-party
political systems, which, however, veered in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Kenya charted a capitalist course and aligned itself with the
West. U.S. naval ships were allowed use of Kenya's Indian Ocean
port at Mombasa, and the nation received a considerable amount of
foreign aid in return.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Tanzania embraced what its first leader, Julius
Nyerere, called ``African socialism.'' This entailed nationalizing
industry and large agricultural estates while pursuing a nonaligned
foreign policy. Nyerere's socialist economics led to disaster,
although his social and educational programs are generally seen as
successful.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cold War, the United States began pressuring Moi, the
Kenyan president, to democratize the political system, free
political prisoners, curb corruption and end government connivance
behind ethnic violence. Moi, Kenya's president for 20 years, is
considered one of the continent's most oppressive leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy in Nairobi has become symbolic of Kenyans'
democratic aspirations since a former ambassador, Smith Hempstone,
publicly condemned corruption and human rights abuses by Moi early
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the Kenyan people would be the last to want to see that
building blown up,'' Chege said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past eight years, American aid has dropped by two-thirds,
from roughly $60 million to $20 million. The IMF suspended $200
million in aid a year ago, and other major donors have frozen their
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition sees the United States as a force to pressure
Moi to hold free elections,'' said Thomas R. Gregori, a University
of Houston economist who returned from Africa last week. ``Moi is
not happy with the pressure, but his lifeline is to the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Nyerere's successors, Tanzania has embraced sweeping
economic reforms and encouraged multiparty politics. But experts
fear that the new material successes, however modest at present,
are beginning to fuel corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tanzania's economy is not as large as Kenya's, it has
been growing faster under its new reformist president, Benjamin
Mkapa. Moreover, Tanzania has never experienced the bloody ethnic
clashes that have recently shaken Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Amnesty International called Kenya a ``powder keg
waiting to explode,'' although the description has been used by
others for years. (Editor's note: Star-Telegram writer Barry
Shlachter covered Kenya and Tanzania as an Associated Press
correspondent from 1982 to 1985.}
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
