<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-07 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING RELIGION AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (js) 
 BY PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geoffrey Fieger, the newly selected Democratic standard-bearer
in the Michigan governor's race, is the latest candidate to portray
himself as an ``anti-politician.'' In some respects that claim may
be debatable, but when it comes to his statements about religion,
it is certainly true.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians generally avoid religious controversy. But in his
role as lawyer and champion of Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the advocate and
practitioner of assisted suicide, Fieger has called Adam Cardinal
Maida, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Detroit, a ``nut,''
compared the Council of Orthodox Rabbis of Greater Detroit to
Nazis, described the pope with mocking vulgarities, said that he
would rather take advice from ``Joe the wino,'' and that Jesus was
``just some goofball that got nailed to the cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Are those flip comments from a vigorous advocate or obnoxious
bigotry _ and a serious problem for the Michigan Democrats?
</P>
<P>
   And does it make any difference that Fieger is, in fact, an
equal-opportunity insulter, who has been throwing his
expletive-laden, scorched-earth denunciations in every direction
for years? (He has repeatedly described Gov. John Engler, a
Republican, as ``the product of miscegenation between barnyard
animals and human beings'' and said of the governor's children that
``unless they have corkscrew tails, those kids are not his.'')
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to his office Friday brought a promise to relay
a request for comment to Fieger, who was on a trip to Washington,
and at least a response from an aide. There was no response.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger has said that a report in The Washington Post about the
Jesus remark was ``a lie'' and that Engler used it ``to inspire a
little religious bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   But a tape made by the reporter, Richard Leiby, shows that while
speculating on how religious beliefs emerge, Fieger compared the
belief that Jesus is divine to the cult of Elvis Presley. ``In 2000
years we've probably made somebody who is the equivalent of Elvis
into God, so I see no reason why not to believe that in 2000 years
Elvis will be God'' Fieger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably if we went back 2000 years,'' he continued, ``and
they said, you know, we think Jesus is God, and Jesus is just some
goofball that got nailed to the cross.''
</P>
<P>
   The context includes a Lenny Bruce-like riff on how weird it is
for Christians to wear crosses, preceded by a bitter reflection on
humanity: ``You couldn't develop a virus that kills as many people
as we do and destroys as many things as we do. We're just a
pestilence with appendages.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments about the archbishop came two year ago, when Fieger
was asked why Kevorkian had sought a permit to carry a concealed
weapon. One reason, the lawyer quipped, ``was to protect himself
from nuts like Cardinal Maida.''
</P>
<P>
   Fieger compared the Orthodox rabbis to Nazis in early 1996 when
they issued a statement condemning assisted suicide as a violation
of Jewish teaching. ``They're closer to Nazis than they think they
are,'' he told The Detroit News. ``Orthodox Jews are not different
than the right-wing Christian nuts. If you're a religious nut,
you're a religious nut.''
</P>
<P>
   George Cantor, a columnist and editorial writer at The Detroit
News, responded in a column that confessed personal ambivalence
about the assisted suicide question but not about Fieger's
evocation of Nazism, which Rabbi Elimelech Silberberg, of
Congregation Bais Chabad in West Bloomfield, said this week had
never been retracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Louis Farrakhan or a Pat Buchanan had said something even
approaching this degree of calumny,'' Cantor wrote, ``Jewish
organizations would be hopping up and down in outrage. And
deservedly so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rabbis,'' he wrote, ``were doing what is their right,
their duty, in a pluralistic democracy. They presented their side
of a highly controversial and politicized issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Fieger says he is not a member of any religious group, but is
ready to ``keep all my options open.'' On his Web site, he says ``I
have no difficulty with the unfettered practice of religious
beliefs,'' but do not want them incorporated into law.
</P>
<P>
   He does not explain why he admires the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr.'s religiously based political activity, but calls
Catholic, Episcopal, Presbyterian, Lutheran, Baptist, Muslim and
Jewish opponents of assisted suicide in Michigan ``religious
fanatics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the giants of American politics fell well outside
conventional beliefs. Abraham Lincoln belonged to no church and
held troubled and uncertain religious views that are still debated
by historians, but he has also been called one of the nation's most
profound religious thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson was a deist who deeply distrusted religious
leaders, was denounced as an atheist by his political enemies and
yet attended religious services regularly and treasured his own
rationalist version of Jesus as a sublime ethical teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Mark Brewer, the chairman of the state Democratic
Party, said, ``I don't pretend to be an expert about everything
Fieger has said about religion, but my sense is that voters here
are mainly concerned about bread-and-butter issues of state
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Michigan, Fieger has not usually been described as
``hard-line'' or ``extremist'' _ adjectives generally reserved for
public figures associated with the religious right _ but as
``flamboyant'' and ``populist.'' Of the flamboyance, there can be
no doubt, and if a genius for invective qualifies a
multimillionaire lawyer from one of Detroit's wealthiest suburban
areas as a populist, then that is accurate, also _ as it must be
for Farrakhan and Buchanan as well.
</P>
<P>
   But populism or not, a lot of Democrats who feel that their
religious traditions demand at least a minimum of respect are going
to be pondering Fieger's candidacy long and hard _ and not just in
Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
