<SLUG> BC-BOEING-CONDIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMOR ABOUT CONDIT TAKES ON A LIFE OF ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What started out as a rumor that heads are about to
roll at Boeing _ namely Chairman Phil Condit's _ has taken on a
life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boeing's corporate telephone lines were ringing off the hook
Friday with people from all across the country _ everyone from the
news media to shareholders to factory workers _ asking: Is it true?
</P>
<P>
   _ Some Wall Street analysts even suggested the news contributed
to yesterday's sharp rise in Boeing stock.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boeing factory workers from Wichita, Kan., to Everett were
placing bets on which executive would be first out the door and how
much the stock would rise after they left.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday an e-mail called ``Grape Vine News'' began
circulating throughout Boeing. By Thursday, it had made the rounds
from Boeing factories in Wichita to St. Louis to Renton and landed
on the Internet where analysts and shareholders caught wind of it.
By Friday, it reached the computers of Condit and Boeing President
Harry Stonecipher.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing officials refused to acknowledge the rumors earlier
in the week, Friday they flatly denied them. Stonecipher even sent
his own electronic-mail response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better get yourself a new grapevine because the one you
have is seriously flawed and useless,'' Stonecipher wrote. ``It is
wrong on all counts.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the ``Grape Vine News'' read: ``Phil Condit will be
stepping down and Harry Stonecipher will be taking over the company
... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron Woodard (president of Boeing's commercial division) is
fired and Alan Mulally (head of the company's defense and space
operations) will be coming back from the military division to take
Ron's spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing usually doesn't comment on rumors but the company made an
exception Friday because they had created such a frenzy across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all silliness that started on the Internet,'' Boeing
spokesman Larry McCracken said. ``It is completely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The management shuffle _ which if true, would be among the
biggest corporate shakeups in history _ reportedly is to be
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all should help the stock price,'' the e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching its lowest level in more than two years this
week, Boeing's stock rose $2.19 a share in heavy trading Friday to
close at $39.25. But analysts were split as to whether the Boeing
rumor mill created the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rumor were confirmed, there's a chance the stock would
go up,'' said analyst Paul Nisbet with JSA Research. ``The company
has not performed well and if Stonecipher were to take over, it
would be well received because everywhere he's gone it's been good
for stockholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Campbell with Lehman Brothers in New York said the rumors
could have contributed to the stock rise but said that doesn't
necessarily mean investors want Condit out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said shareholders could have been reacting to what
they think is a proactive Boeing board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much the supposed departure of someone but more
that it would be neat to know they (board of directors) are on the
ball and doing something,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts have been calling for management changes at
Boeing, many say the recent rumors don't appear to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't image the board is upset enough with Condit at this
point to force him out,'' Campbell said. ``It's highly unlikely
that he would step down.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been struggling with commercial aircraft production
problems and has paid the price with more than $3 billion in
writeoffs. In addition, the company reported its first annual
operational loss in 50 years last year and has shown weak quarterly
results since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the senior executives at Boeing have taken their
spears,'' Campbell said. ``The company needs these guys to fix this
stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
