<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RESEARCH-LAB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS RESEARCH LAB MAY BE BUILT IN GALVESTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas, Mexico) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Plans for a laboratory to study some of the
most deadly viruses in the world have been laid at the University
of Texas Medical Branch campus in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the University of Texas Regents in November and
built on schedule, the ultra-secure ``Biosafety Level 4 Facility''
would be one of only about a dozen such laboratories in the world.
Unlike others, however, it would specialize in research on viruses
in the Southern United States, Mexico, the Caribbean basin and
Central and South America, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed laboratory, which scientists say would be similar
to that depicted in the 1995 movie ``Outbreak,'' would be the first
of its kind at a U.S. medical university.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really put us way out in front, not just on the
edge,'' said Dr. Adrian S. Perachio, UTMB's new associate vice
president for basic research. ``We would be the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who expect to work in the lab say they believe the
long-term study of known and yet-to-be discovered viruses will save
many lives and could prevent an epidemic like AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time, maybe around mid-century, that there was
this sort of implicit notion that the age of the plagues was behind
us,'' Perachio said. ``Then came AIDS. We don't want to be behind
the curve like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the laboratory, expected to open in 2002, were
announced Friday by UTMB President Dr. John Stobo. He said a
world-renowned team of tropical-disease research experts has been
recruited since UTMB became home to the World Health Organization's
Center for Tropical Diseases in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for that group to remain on the cutting edge of what
they do, it's necessary for us to build a new facility which allows
them to work with these new and emerging infections in an
environment that is safe and protective for them as well as the
rest of the community,'' Stobo said.
</P>
<P>
   While fewer than a dozen researchers would have direct access to
the laboratory core, where dangerous viruses would be stored,
scientists said work there would open the way for collaborative
work with scientists on campuses throughout Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After only four years in operation, the Center for Tropical
Diseases is bringing $7 million in research money to the campus
annually. Grant money is expected to increase greatly if the
virulent-virus research lab opens.
</P>
<P>
   Among the researchers who would use the facility are Dr. Robert
Tesch and Dr. Robert Shope, who came from Yale University and
brought one of the most extensive collections of virus cultures in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers would study known viruses and look for unknown
ones, mainly in tropical and subtropical environments and in animal
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scope of the project, from the beginning, is to describe
that a bug is there, to decide whether it affects humans, what kind
of disease to expect, and then, obviously, to move into therapy and
prevention,'' said Dr. Charles F. ``Chuck'' Fulhorst, another
virologist who would use the proposed lab.
</P>
<P>
   Cost of the proposed lab is pegged at $5 million to $7.5
million, much of which is expected to come from grants and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for a May 1999 request for construction authorization
from the UT Board of Regents and a July 1999 review of the medical
school's application for construction by the Texas Higher Education
Board.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory would be just blocks from homes in the city's
East End Historical District, an area of restored Victorian-era
homes where Stobo himself lives.
</P>
<P>
   But planners said they believe the facility's virus storage
areas will be as secure as those at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta and in two other Biosafety Level 4
laboratories operated by the Department of Defense and the National
Institutes of Health, in Frederick and Bethesda, Md., respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a submarine locked within a vault,'' Dr. David H.
Walker, UTMB pathology department chairman and Center for Tropical
Diseases director, told several hundred people who attended a
campus ``town meeting'' Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is designed with containment within
containment,'' Perachio said. ``For human entry, there are multiple
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a hurricane threatens,'' he said, ``you're talking about an
hour to an hour and a half in order to be able to shut down the
laboratory and harness everything in there that possibly could be
infectious in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for researchers to see or treat people
suffering from exotic or highly contagious deadly diseases at the
facility, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   UTMB executives also said researchers at the planned laboratory
would not duplicate work at the federal labs.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than conduct long-term research, the CDC spends much of
its resources reacting to emergency situations such as the 1993
outbreak of deadly hantavirus in the southwestern United States,
Fulhorst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't commit to a long-term research program,'' he said.
``They did a great job in identifying the population at risk and
things like that. But, essentially, there have been no advances
made in therapy, and a regional institution like ours can fill in
that gap.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
