<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNEMPLOYMENT RATE STEADY AS CREATION OF JOBS SLOWS
</P>
<P>
   The economy created jobs at a slower but still robust pace last
month, and the unemployment rate held steady at 4.5 percent, the
Labor Department reported. Continued strong employment growth in
service industries more than offset the damage that Asia's woes are
inflicting on manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after a sharp selloff in stocks earlier in the week and
several subsequent days of sweaty palms on Wall Street, the report
reassured investors that the economy remains stable despite the
confusing and sometimes conflicting forces, from Asia's downturn to
the buoyancy of consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   EX-EDS CHIEF TO GET $38.6 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Data Systems in Plano, Texas, said that the
retirement of Lester M. Alberthal Jr. as chairman and chief
executive would cost the company $38.6 million in benefits. Shares
of EDS rose 14 percent. Alberthal announced his retirement after
the stock market closed on Thursday under pressure from board
members and shareholders dismayed by the company's loss of its
former leadership in the computer services industry.
</P>
<P>
   AWARD VS. LOCKHEED SUPPLIERS
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles jury awarded 28 former Lockheed Martin workers
$760 million in punitive damages from five companies that supplied
toxic chemicals used in making Lockheed's Stealth jet fighter
plane.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM EXPECTS MCI CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom expects to take charges of $6 billion to $7 billion in
connection with its $37 billion purchase of MCI Communications, and
other big one-time costs could follow as the company contemplates a
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG WHOLESALERS END DEALS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's four biggest drug wholesalers abandoned plans to
merge into two companies. The collapse of the deals _ Cardinal
Health's $2.8 billion acquisition of Bergen Brunswig and McKesson's
$2.3 billion purchase of Amerisource Health _ had been expected
since regulators opposed the mergers, saying that they would hurt
competition.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-CASINO DEAL CALLED OFF
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Real Estate Equities, the real estate investment trust
controlled by Richard Rainwater, has canceled a planned $1.7
billion acquisition of Station Casinos.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM DEVALUES ITS CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam, as expected, devalued its currency, the third such move
since the Asian financial crisis took hold more than a year ago.
The government has been under pressure to open its markets and to
devalue the currency, the dong, to bolster export-dependent
industries, especially after nine months of bad weather hit crops
especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE WORKERS STAGE BRIEF STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of unionized telephone workers shut down directory
assistance in New York as they staged a two-and-a-half-hour wildcat
walkout aimed at pressuring Bell Atlantic to help avoid a strike at
12:01 a.m. Sunday, when their contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS FLAT FOR UNILEVER
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, the British-Dutch household products conglomerate that
makes Lipton tea, Q-Tips and Wisk laundry detergent, said that its
second-quarter profit was little changed from a year earlier as the
Asia crisis continued to weigh on its business.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY GOOD FOR CABLE BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   For 24-hour cable news programming like MSNBC, CNBC, Fox News
and CNN, the Monica Lewinsky story is big business, meaning more
revenue and higher ratings to shows that mostly struggle at the
margins, looking for _ at best _ the mysterious murder of a beauty
queen.
</P>
</TEXT>
