<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH HIGH SCHOOL GRADUATE CAPTURES AJGA TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By ERIC ZARATE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ Adam Rubinson couldn't look.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Paschal High School graduate was 14 under par
yesterday and had the lead of the AJGA Lucent Technologies Boys
Championship at the Dallas Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, if Nick Manthey of Mesa, Ariz., could make a
20-foot chip shot for birdie on the 18th hole, there would be a
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll hear it'' if Manthey makes the shot, said Rubinson,
sitting at the scorer's table with his back to the green. ``I think
you get more nervous if you watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Manthey's shot rolled five feet past the pin _ he went
on to make bogey _ and Rubinson had his first American Junior Golf
Association victory in one of the organization's major events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Rubinson, whose 72-hole score of 274 on the
DAC's blue course was a stroke better than Russell Wrentz of Cabot,
Ark., and two ahead of Manthey. ``I'm 45-50 minutes from my home.
This feels good, really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Manthey's 9-iron shot on 18 left him five feet short of the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had plenty of club, I just didn't hit it well,'' Manthey
said. ``I normally take the putter out on that chip shot. I didn't
really expect to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Past winners of this tournament include PGA Tour players Tiger
Woods (1992), David Duval (1989) and Jim Furyk (1987).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge for me,'' said Rubinson, who is scheduled to play
in Monday's U.S. Amateur qualifier in Garland. ``Now my name is on
the wall with a lot of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubinson, the 1998 Star-Telegram player of the year who will
play for TCU in the fall, started the day three shots behind the
lead but crafted his second consecutive 6-under 66 to win the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Third-round leaders Patrick Norris of Orlando, Fla., and John
Merrick of Long Beach, Calif., faltered in the final round. Norris'
72 left him at 277 and in a tie for fourth place. Merrick's 74 put
him at 279.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinson's championship also earned him the 17-18 age-division
title. Norris, 16, won the 13-16 division.
</P>
<P>
   Among local golfers, Mansfield's Matt Brost was 4 over for the
day and finished at 284, while Arlington's J.R. Zatarain was at
292.
</P>
<P>
   Staying at the home of some DAC members during the tournament,
Rubinson was told that back-to-back 67s might give him a chance at
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I did better,'' Rubinson said.
</P>
<P>
   His final round was bogey-free, and included a 4-under 32 on the
back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rolled my putter very well on the back nine,'' Rubinson
said. ``I putted very relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the putts were gimme shots. He made a 30-footer to
save par on No. 16, and rolled in a 10-footer in No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing the leaders, ``you have to make the birdies,'' Rubinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Norris had tied Rubinson at 13 under after 15 holes, but bogeyed
16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam was making everything inside 10 feet,'' Norris said. ``He
might have hit every fairway. I never saw him miss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
