<SLUG> BC-GUESTWORKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY, AGRICULTURE PRESSURE CONGRESS TO ADMIT MORE `GUEST
WORKERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sujat Jamil works in a high-tech global village. Together with
co-workers from India, China, Europe, the Middle East and South
America, he designs microprocessors inside Intel's computer chip
factory in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very international and cosmopolitan work environment,''
says the 28-year-old electrical engineer from Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the high-tech industry is relying on the
brainpower of highly trained foreign employees, like Jamil and his
colleagues, to fill what they say is a critical shortage of
qualified American workers.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the employment spectrum, the nation's
farmers say they have a growing need to import field hands for the
harvesting jobs Americans don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Both these powerful industries _ which bring $17 billion to the
Arizona economy annually _ say immigration laws must be changed to
allow greater numbers of foreign workers. If not, they warn, labor
needs could drive their businesses out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns from summer recess in September, votes are
expected on bills that would create a farm guest worker program and
another measure to raise the annual cap on visas for professional,
college-educated workers.
</P>
<P>
   Labor advocates are among the opponents to increasing foreign
hires. They argue that allowing more foreign workers into the labor
poor would displace American workers and drive down wages.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has also threatened to veto a bill increasing
the visas for high-tech workers unless the law provides for
training of Americans for these jobs and companies using the visas
assure they will not lay off American workers to hire lower-paid
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has been bolstered by a General Accounting Office
report and U.S. Department of Labor criticism that disputes claims
of national labor shortfalls for both categories of workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix-area employers and immigration advocates say the
labor needs are very real.
</P>
<P>
   Coeta Chambers, a human resources attorney for Intel, says the
high-tech industry has boomed in recent years, generating thousands
of new jobs each year and strengthening the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Intel alone hired 24,000 employees in 1997 for it's operations
worldwide, she said. Of those, only 500 were foreign nationals.
``It's very few people in this category, but they are for very
critical positions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Each October, 65,000 visas are made available for hiring
high-tech and other college-educated, professionals. Universities,
computer makers and the medical field are among the employers that
compete for this visa pool.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the allotment was used up in 10 months. This year, the
visas ran out in seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the cap many months ago, in May, and we have been
unable to hire any new (foreign high-tech workers) or we've had to
take employees of the payroll... leaving projects unfinished,''
says Jenifer Eisen, a Washington attorney and officer with the
American Business for Legal Immigration group, which represents
many high-tech employers.
</P>
<P>
   At Arizona State University in Tempe, Donald McTaggert, director
of the international programs office, says universities looking to
hire new faculty are caught in the same bind. ``There will be quite
a number of cases of people that won't be eligible to be hired,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, farmers say that without the ability to import more
workers, they'll go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   One of Arizona's largest fruit and vegetable growers, Eagle
Produce owned by the Phoenix-based Martori family for three
generations, has scaled back it's operations due to lack of legal
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had periods this year when we weren't able to get
everything harvested in a timely fashion,'' said Steve Martori. He
didn't lose any of his crops but knows of other farmers who did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to create more jobs if we have trouble filling
the jobs we already have,'' Martori said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation for expanding the foreign professional
guest worker quota, sponsored by Rep. Lamar Smith (R-Texas), would
raise the quota of professional visas to 85,000 this year and add
an additional 10,000 visas each year through 2002. In 2003, the
visa ceiling would drop back down to the current 65,000, to ensure
the increases are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   The farm guest worker program, sponsored by Oregon Sens. Gordon
Smith (R) and Ron Wyden (D), would create a computerized registry
that employers could tap to find legal workers.
</P>
<P>
   If they were unable to meet their labor demands by recruiting
from the registry, farmers would be allowed to import an unlimited
number of temporary foreign farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Boyd of the National Association of Manufacturers, a
national organization representing 14,000 technology companies,
says if employment needs continue to go unmet, companies may have
to move certain operations outside the borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``One solution to this is for employers to move more work to
other places and we don't want to see that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``By providing temporary visas for foreign nationals and
addressing the education and training of American workers, we can
keep American jobs in America.'' &QL; 
Graciela Sevilla can be reached at 444-4783 or by e-mail at
grace.sevilla(at)pni.com via the internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
