</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 7, 1998 -- HOLOCAUST-WISSE, 8-7
-- Ruth Wisse of Harvard University, who argues that
overemphasizing the Holocaust obscures that history and gives
Hitler and his politics too big a place in it. Insuring that this
genocide will not be forgotten is not the same as teaching Judaism
or making the world a safer place,'' she writes. (Michael Quan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- Aug. 7, 1998 -- HOLOCAUST-KATZ, 8-7 -- ``It
seems clear that those who argue that the Holocaust should not be
taught as a specialized field of study in university programs are
out of touch with the feelings of scholars, Jewish and non-Jewish,
around the world,'' writes Steven Katz. ``Still, more important,
they misunderstand the Holocaust's significance not only for Jewish
history but also for the modern era in its totality.'' (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PALM COAST, Fla. -- Aug. 7, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
9 -- SPEND-HOME-REBUILD-2, 8-7 -- Rhon and April Dixon returned to
the rubble of their burned-out house to find a State Farm adjuster
waiting. Many fire victims have collected more than they expected,
and those who have come up short say they have only themselves to
blame because they consciously under-insured their homes, taking
what they thought was a reasonable gamble that disaster was
unlikely. (Joseph B. Treaster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PALM COAST, Fla. -- Aug. 7, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
9 -- SPEND-HOME-REBUILD-1, 8-7 -- The home of James Jones was
insured for $35,000 less than it may cost to rebuild, but he says
he doesn't blame the insurer. Instead of paying whatever it takes
to replace a destroyed home, as had been the case for years, the
leading insurers are now selling policies that limit most payments
to 120 percent of the insured amount.(Joseph B. Treaster/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHICAGO -- Aug. 7, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
