<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLIARDS-BLACK-WIDOW     08-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLIARDS-BLACK-WIDOW-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S LEAGUE CIVILIZES A HUSTLER'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``a'')  
(ART ADV: Photo of Jeanette Lee, the Black Widow, is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 By ADAM GERSHENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was 6:30 already, half an hour after the matches
were supposed to have started, and the fans were getting antsy.
They itched to see behind the blue curtain, into the cordoned-off
area of the Amsterdam Billiard Club, where the Black Widow, the
Duchess of Doom and the rest of the best female pool players in the
world warmed up for the first evening session of the 1998 Brunswick
Billiards New York Classic. Hearing the boom of the break, the
collisions coming like sporadic cannon fire, was almost too much to
take.
</P>
<P>
   At last, the velvet rope was whisked aside, and they scurried
in, beer-bellied men in Harley-Davidson shirts, junior high school
girls with metallic nail polish, Wall Street bankers and senior
citizens, all eager to secure seats where they could watch their
favorites play nine ball for a slice of a $50,000 pie.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at the East 86th Street billiard club Friday evening
showed that women's professional pool has arrived. While the men's
game has recently fallen off fans' radar screens, women's pool has
taken off like a cue ball on the break. Since 1991, the men's tour
has splintered into squabbling factions while the women have
unified, secured corporate sponsors and garnered a television
contract with ESPN. This has left pool in an unusual position among
sports _ its women's league is more widely followed than its men's.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Esposito, a 50-year-old Newark, N.J., police officer who
attended Thursday night's pretournament charity fund-raiser for
literacy at the billiard hall, offered his theory on the women's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring a lot of class to it, elegance,'' Esposito said.
``With guys, you get a lot more rough-edged, hustler style, like
they're still in the pool halls and bars.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's new image is no accident. It has been carefully
cultivated by the Women's Pro Billiard Association. The
organization, formed in 1976, became more important in 1991, when
the women split from the men's tour over marketing and sponsorship
conflicts. At that time, the word ``pool'' often brought to mind
drunken hustlers shooting stick and comparing tattoos in dingy,
smoke-filled bars.
</P>
<P>
   Ewa Mataya Laurance, the former president of the women's
association, said the players decided that if the sport was to
succeed, it needed a makeover. Drinking, smoking and gambling were
outlawed at tournament sites. By the time the New York Classic
started in 1993, the dress code demanded silky gowns and evening
wear for televised matches. Players were counseled to make
themselves accessible to the media and to their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, events like the New York Classic are held in
well-lighted, air-conditioned halls with bleachers for fans and
fine oak tables for the pros.
</P>
<P>
   These pros inspired Bill and Mary Haas to come from the Bronx
and pay $75 for weekend passes to the tournament, even though Haas,
a repairman for Bell Atlantic, may soon be out on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last thing we can afford ...'' began Mrs. Haas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we like to see the best, and these are the major-leaguers
of this sport,'' finished Haas.
</P>
<P>
   These major-leaguers are more than just fancy dresses and
nicknames. Each player has a story, and Friday night, the fans
spoke about them as if they were close friends.
</P>
<P>
   They marveled at Alison Fisher, the Duchess of Doom, who came to
America from England in 1995 as a snooker champion and has used
careful strategy and superior shooting to dominate the American
game, which is similar.
</P>
<P>
   They praised Mary Guarino, who returned to the table after
undergoing neurosurgery in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And naturally, they gushed about Jeanette Lee, the Black Widow,
whose dramatic play and elegant style have made her the most
recognizable player in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans know that Ms. Lee, a 27-year-old native of Bayside,
Queens, went from being a waitress at the Amsterdam Billiard Club
in 1993 to the No. 1 female player in the world in 1994. They know
that she likes to dress all in black, and they know that she has
run afoul of the dress code more than once with her sleeveless
gowns.
</P>
<P>
   But few of them know that Ms. Lee, who now lives in
Indianapolis, was born with scoliosis and has a 28-inch rod
supporting her spine. When she started shooting pool at 14, doctors
warned her not to play, because she would have to bend excessively.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lee ignored that warning. Hooked on pool, she wrapped her
hand in electrical tape at night and slept with it bound in the
bridge position. On the subway she drew stares as she practiced her
follow-through with an imaginary cue. She played marathon matches,
often hustling unwitting men who could not imagine that a woman
could beat them. ``I got caught up in the beauty of the game,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Die-hard fans have enabled the women's tour to become a staple
of ESPN and ESPN2's programming. According to ESPN, the telecasts
consistently draw more than 740,000 viewers, regardless of what
time they are aired or what sports they are up against.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, fans mingled with the players, collected
autographs and asked for tips on how to sink long shots against the
rail. They watched Ms. Lee execute a trick shot in which she used
two cues like chopsticks and still sank a ball into the corner
pocket. Some of them ponied up $50 to play against the pros.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Goryeb, chief executive officer of Champion Mortgage of
Manhattan, went head-to-head against the real champion, Alison
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Goryeb has been playing pool for 53 years. He owns 12 cues.
Still, Ms. Fisher beat him with a flurry of shots to close out the
match.
</P>
<P>
   As Goryeb slipped his stick back into its velvet case, he shook
his head and smiled. ``It was worth it,'' he said. ``It's like
playing golf with Jack Nicklaus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
