<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, AUGUST 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CONSUMER-CODE-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 19,
about problems consumers face when seeking to determine if food has
been genetically modified misstated the practices of one
supermarket chain, Whole Foods Market Inc. of Austin, Tex. It does
not require suppliers to guarantee that products they sell to the
company are free of gene-altered ingredients. The chain asked
suppliers for such a restriction, but the suppliers said they were
unable to comply.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MINNEAPOLIS-ARTS (moved on Tuesday, August 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 4,
about a museum exhibition in Minneapolis devoted to the visual and
performing arts misstated the names of the museum and the
exhibition. It is the Walker Art Center, not Arts, and the
exhibition is called ``Art Performs Life,'' not ``Life Performs
Art.'' The article also misstated the date of a Merce Cunningham
Dance Company performance at the Walker in the 10th-anniversary
celebration of the museum's sculpture garden. It will be on Sept.
12, not Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-ROBBINS (moved on Wednesday, July 29)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of the director and choreographer Jerome Robbins,
sent by the New York Times News Service on Wednesday, July 29,
misstated the authorship of the 1948 Broadway musical ``Look Ma,
I'm Dancin'!'' It was written by Jerome Lawrence and Robert E. Lee,
not by Mr. Robbins, who is credited with having conceived the idea
for the show.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-LEWIS (moved on Monday, August 3)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of the ventriloquist and puppeteer Shari Lewis sent
by the New York Times News Service on Monday, August 3, misstated
the name of her first show for NBC television, in 1957. It was
``Shariland,'' not ``The Shari Show.'' From 1960 to 1963, her
program was called ``The Shari Lewis Show.'' ``The Shari Show,'' a
syndicated program, began in 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
