<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-ADOPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES ANOTHER ANTI-GAY MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Va.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In one of its last acts before recessing for an
August vacation, the House on Friday approved a measure that would
bar adoptions by gay couples in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the measure was an unacceptable intrusion
into local control by the district, and senior advisers have
recommended that he veto any bill that includes it. There is little
prospect that the Senate will go along with the House anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But passage of the provision was another demonstration of House
Republicans' effort, particularly in recent weeks as the election
season nears, to adopt a number of policies circumscribing the
rights of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said this measure, an amendment to a $491 million
bill financing district operations in the coming fiscal year, was
needed because it would help ensure that adopted children had
stable lives. The amendment would prohibit adoptions in the
district by ``individuals who are not related by blood or
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla., who introduced the measure, said it
would not bar single people, whether homosexual or heterosexual,
from adopting. But he did say he was opposed to homosexuals'
adopting children, because he believed they were using adoption as
one way of acting like married heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might give some gay-rights activist a warm feeling to see
gay couples treated just as if they were married,'' he said in an
emotional floor debate that ran past midnight into Friday morning.
But, Largent said, adoptees have already had a rough start in life,
and ``it is simply wrong to turn them into trophies from the
culture war, to exploit them in order to make some political
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Moran, D-Va., called the measure mean-spirited and
said House Republicans wanted to have ``one last bash before we go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Others complained that the measure would deny good homes to some
of the 3,600 children in foster care in the district and would also
have additional unintended consequences, for instance preventing
two nuns from adopting a child but allowing married alcoholics to
do so. Current law in the district allows local judges to determine
adoptions on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Largent was supported by Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., who is the
father of two adopted children. He said that unless parents had a
marriage contract, an adopted child had no legal protection. If an
unmarried couple decide to part, ``what happens to the child?'' he
said. ``What rights does the child have?''
</P>
<P>
   Largent's measure passed by a vote of 227-192, with the support
of 190 Republicans and 37 Democrats. Thirty Republicans voted
against it, as did 161 Democrats and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   The broader district financing bill, which passed on a vote of
214-206, also includes a provision that would provide vouchers to
low-income parents in the district to help pay for sending their
children to private or parochial schools, another provision opposed
by the president.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have frequently used the spending bill for the
district, which has no vote in Congress, to make social points.
They passed a similar measure providing for school vouchers last
year, but the efforts to bar gay adoptions and prevent the use of
local money for needle-exchange programs, which was also attached
to the district spending bill, are new.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
