<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDGE ORDERS A RWANDAN TO SURRENDER FOR TRIAL ON GENOCIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A U.S. District Court judge in Texas this week
ordered a Rwandan who has been indicted for genocide in Africa but
who is living in the United States to surrender to an international
war crimes tribunal for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan, Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former Seventh-day
Adventist pastor who was accused of encouraging the massacre of
ethnic Tutsi in Rwanda in 1994, has been living in Texas with a
son.
</P>
<P>
   He has 30 days to appeal the order.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling had been sought by the State Department, which
supports international tribunals and was embarrassed by the release
of Ntakirutimana by a Texas magistrate late in December 1996. While
some African nations were turning suspects over to the tribunal,
which is based in Arusha, Tanzania, the United States in effect had
freed the only suspect in U.S. custody.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana, 73, was living with his son Eliel, a well-known
anesthesiologist in Laredo, when he was arrested in September 1996.
Another son has been charged with war crimes and is in custody in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ntakirutimana was accused of leading an ethnic Hutu
militia to his church and hospital compound in Mugonero, where
frightened Tutsi had fled for safety. Hundreds were reportedly
killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Tanzania, the registrar of the Rwanda war crimes tribunal,
Agwu Ukiwe Okali, welcomed the new judicial order, handed down on
Wednesday in Laredo by Judge John Rainey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribunal hopes that this decision will accelerate the
process of bringing Ntakirutimana, accused of genocide and crimes
against humanity, to face trial before the tribunal,'' Okali said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Stefanie Grant, program and policy director for the
Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, applauded the judge's ruling,
saying, ``We welcome the lead which the U.S. is giving to other
countries in this decision in cooperating with international
criminal justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana is expected to appeal. His lawyer, Ramsey Clark, a
former U.S. attorney general, has argued that the International War
Crimes Tribunal for Rwanda has no legal standing as a U.N. body.
</P>
<P>
   The international tribunals cannot ask for extradition, only the
voluntary handover of people indicted for crimes under its
jurisdiction. The harshest sentence the tribunals can impose is
life imprisonment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
