u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     08-07 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMASHING SUCCESS AT SIMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry was a 15-year-old schoolboy in Los Angeles in
1977 when Reggie Jackson joined the Yankees and announced: ``I'm
the straw that stirs the drink.'' He was oblivious then to being a
pro player, much less a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing ball, basketball, football and I was enjoying
being a kid, and I wasn't thinking about anything important,''
Strawberry said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years later, the name Strawberry is one of the most
recognized and resilient in baseball _ as much for the dazzling
heights as for the desperate lows and, finally, for the
exhilarating comeback that his name represents. Now, at age 36,
Strawberry has not so much matured as he has evolved. He is one of
several straws that stir the drink.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his 21st home run Friday in an 8-2 romp over the Kansas
City Royals in the first game of a day-night doubleheader. Three
nights earlier, in Oakland, Strawberry's dramatic ninth-inning,
pinch-hit grand slam catapulted the Yankees to one of their most
enthralling victories in an enthralling season.
</P>
<P>
   He simply grabbed the bat off the rack, walked to the plate and
hit the ball. Not a lot of warm-up swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more simple now,'' he said. ``About playing, whatever I do
as far as helping the team, it's a simple thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge for Strawberry is answering questions about
his surgically repaired left knee. Chili Davis is expected to
return from ankle surgery this month, and manager Joe Torre plans
to use him as the designated hitter, in place of Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, if he wants to play regularly during this period,
will have to compete for playing time in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave it all up to Joe, let him make the decision,''
Strawberry said. ``I've been able to live with just about
everything. Everybody wants to be on the same page. In '96 and '97
we had bad apples griping about playing time. We haven't had that
this year. There's no need for it.'' Few of Strawberry's teammates
can appreciate the Yankees' success more than he can. Few have as
keen a perspective about the fragility of success, the thin line
that separates success from failure. Strawberry was left for dead
last year in the baseball sense. He has far exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I'm alive, I'm healthy,'' Strawberry said. ``I'm
back with the ball club. They gave me another opportunity and
that's all that really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In a day when so many professional athletes have been coddled
and catered to since their teen-age years, few actually have known
struggle beyond the confines of the court or field: making the
team, not making the team, suffering injury, coming back from
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Few know the feeling of actually having a life turned inside
out, upside down, having the feeling of being lost, in a
wilderness. Strawberry knows.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted by the Mets in 1980, he was signed to a $210,000
contract by Frank Cashen, who initially vowed not to bring the
young player to New York. Bowing to pressure, the Mets called up
Strawberry in 1983 at the age of 21. There was adulation, and a
World Series championship in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But after a glorious season, there would be domestic violence,
tax problems, drug and alcohol abuse. A career and a life seemed in
ruin. He has come full circle, back to the same city, but a
different team, again in the limelight but neither seeking it nor
reveling in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth is a combination of everything; what you've been
through,'' Strawberry said. ``Everything's not going to be as good
as you'd like for it to be. Things happen in people's lives. I was
one of those people and I learned to deal with it. Didn't blame
anyone for what I did. I've accepted who I am and what I've done
and I'm trying to make the best out of who I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is after a third World Series championship, the
culminating accomplishment of a 15-year career. He leads the team
in home runs; he leads the team. Not the way Paul O'Neill leads.
Strawberry shakes it up.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years after he first heard Reggie make the claim, he
is a different sort of straw, and the Yankees are a different kind
of drink. But Strawberry stirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys around here know that I know how to play the
game, I understand the game, and that's basically what it's all
about,'' he said. ``And going out and having a winning attitude and
understanding what winning is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about numbers; this is not a numbers game. It's about
what we do together, how far we go.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
