A4032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-DROUGHT-COX     08-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-DROUGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lawmakers dispute economists' drought views
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Comptroller John Sharp told lawmakers
Friday that the state should call out the National Guard to deliver
hay to bail out Texas farmers suffering through a crippling
drought.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. George W. Bush and Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry
said they may have a better, cheaper way. Bush and Perry said
private companies might be willing to deliver hay for free.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas were offered up as the House Appropriations and Senate
Finance committees met in joint session to hear what the drought
has done to the state and what the state can do to help.
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread agreement that economists who say the
drought is something less than a big, statewide crisis are
clueless.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Pete Laney, Senate Finance Chairman Bill Ratliff
and other legislators with agricultural interests in their
districts said the economists' assessments don't add up.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp agreed, noting that the $1.8 billion in lost agriculture
income has the same impact as shutting down the state's $1.4
billion hotel-motel industry and putting all of its employees out
of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economists aren't talking to families,'' said Sharp. ``They
are not talking to bankers that lost huge loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Texas economists, noting that agriculture accounts for
only 1 percent of the state's gross product, said last week that
the drought will not have significant statewide impact unless it
drags on for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said they are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this drought ripples through the economy it is serious,
and you cannot look at it just from a point of view of what the
gross state product is,'' said Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Perry agreed, telling the committees that urban Texans may see
short-term benefits but will see long-term problems as a result of
hard times down on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Beef prices will come down as a result of forced liquidation of
herds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at this time next year, if, God forbid, this continues on,
your constituents can expect to see increased prices at
supermarkets for beef'' and other farm products, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp pitched his hay idea as a result of a similar plan that
has worked well in Oklahoma, another state hit by the summer
drought. About 80 percent of Texas' ranges and pastures are rated
poor or very poor this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Perry, Sharp's GOP opponent in this year's lieutenant
governor's race, said his ``Hay Hotline,'' which began as a way to
match up people selling hay with people needing it, is now getting
calls from people offering free hay and free transportation of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard times like these that can bring out the best in
people,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, ranchers Jack and Leslie Hale heard about the Texas
woes and organized a drive that, so far, has collected nine
truckloads of hay. The Kansas National Guard will haul the hay to
Texas on Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the governor believes the
use of National Guard troops to deliver hay in Texas is feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But private companies are starting to express interest in the
transportation of hay, and we want to see first if that will
provide the solution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
