<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASSMASTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brauer vaults into lead in Classic
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Denny Brauer was sounding more like a rookie
than one of the greatest bass tournament anglers of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   After he turned in the heaviest catch and biggest bass of the
tournament Friday, Brauer, a member of the sport's exclusive
millionaire's club, seemed to be holding back the giggles as he
tried to explain how he vaulted into first place with one round to
go in the 28th BASS Masters Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer caught five bass weighing 17 pounds, 14 ounces _ the
largest one 7-6 _ to take a 14-ounce lead over first-round leader
George Cochran. Brauer has a two-day total weight of 29-15, placing
him in the pole position to win his first Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big fish was my first bite,'' said Brauer, adding the fish
was in his live well inside the first 10 minutes. ``When a day
starts out like that you know it's going to be a magical day.''
</P>
<P>
   And considering that many in the 46-competitor field were still
struggling to find keepable fish (14 inches is the minimum) willing
to bite, the Camdenton, Mo., angler's day was almost miraculous. He
caught his limit of five bass by 8:25 a.m. and ended up tossing
back four others that were keepers and three more that weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer's bass-fishing resume is impressive no matter what
happens today. He was the BASS Angler of the Year in 1987, has won
10 BASS events, and is one of the top moneywinners on the
Wal-Mart/FLW Tour, considered by some the biggest competitor BASS
has.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he lacks a Classic title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the chance to win three Classics and this one is no
exception,'' he said. ``I don't even know if I will catch anything
(today). But I can promise you that I'll do my best ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Despite falling out of the lead, Cochran, from Hot Springs,
Ark., still had a productive Day 2. He had four fish weighing 11-14
to give him a 29-1 total. In third at 26-11 is Mike Reynolds of
Modesto, Calif., a Classic first-timer who had 15-12 total Friday
to moved up from 12th place. Zell Rowland of Montgomery, Texas, was
fourth with 25-2, moving up from eighth with a 13-10 performance,
and Tom Biffle of Wagoner, Okla., fell from fourth to fifth, but
was still within striking distance at 24-4. Randall Romig of Barto,
Penn., and Randy Blaukat of Joplin, Mo., were tied for sixth at
23-11.
</P>
<P>
   The two Georgians _ Stanley Mitchell of Fitzgerald and Danny
Kirk of Jasper _ look out of contention. Mitchell, who caught
Thursday's big bass, was 13th with a 16-3 total, while Kirk was
25th at 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell managed only three fish that weighed 6-6 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so tough out there, but that's the way the fishing
is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk caught three weighing 6-15, but was less than an inch away
from a five-fish limit after throwing back two fish that were each
within about a quarter-inch of being keepers. If they had been
keepers, he likely would have been in the top 20 entering the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
