<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HR hype tougher than fastballs
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Mark McGwire didn't get a hit in three games here yet
was the story of the weekend. Mark McGwire didn't play Wednesday in
Milwaukee yet was the story of the night. And it is barely August.
</P>
<P>
   The Maris Record should _ as opposed to could _ fall soon. Guys
are bigger and stronger and have creatine to sustain them. There
are more bad pitchers than ever. Add McGwire's May to Sammy Sosa's
June to Albert Belle's July and you've 52 home runs in the span of
three months. The problem isn't so much hitting the ball. The
problem is everything that accrues from hitting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   There's a picture of Maris standing in his locker briefing the
media after he hit No. 61 on Oct. 1, 1961. (Sal Durante, the truck
driver who caught the historic ball, stands behind Maris, looking
bemused.) Eight reporters are seen in the photo, all of them
placidly taking notes. (Meaning: No jostling.) There's not a TV
camera visible, and therein is your difference.
</P>
<P>
   Maris hit 61 in the days before ESPN and live cut-ins. Maris hit
61 at a time when print coverage meant the hometown papers _ no USA
Today, no national baseball writers, no columnists jetting in to
hop on the next big story. Even as the weight was pressing down on
Maris, whose hair infamously fell out in clumps, we look upon the
media crush of '61 and say, ``You call that a crush?''
</P>
<P>
   Already McGwire's routine has been so stretched that he has
none. He has mass press conferences _ plenty of TV cameras on hand
_ on the first day of every road series. (This weekend he's home,
but Sosa comes calling. Hype-o-rama!) In them, he has been mostly
agreeable but has shown the occasional sign of irritability. And
remember, it's barely August. The longer this goes, the less
patient he'll be. Human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Maris caught some breaks in '61. For the season's first half it
was Mickey Mantle who seemed most apt to catch Babe Ruth. (Mantle
finished with 54 homers.) The Yankees were their imperial selves,
headed toward the AL pennant. McGwire has none of that. He was the
designated record-smasher from spring training on, and to his
credit he has put himself in position to do it. But his team is
going nowhere, meaning that he's the only reason to watch the
Cardinals. (Indeed, when John Mabry started in McGwire's stead
Wednesday, the Milwaukee crowd booed.)
</P>
<P>
   Strength isn't the issue. Temperament is. The man who catches
Maris must do as Michael Jordan has done this entire decade, must
absorb the attention and then put it aside long enough to do his
job. He must be able to stand above his team, above his entire
sport, and not be distracted. Trouble is, Jordan wasn't much good
at hitting baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   That McGwire went a week without a homer has been described as a
colossal failure. (A week? Rafael Belliard went a decade without
one.) From coast to coast, nobody asks who won last night, only if
McGwire got his. When he does, it's a headline. When he doesn't,
that's a headline, too. And remember, it's barely August. Imagine
how September will be. Me, I'm betting the Maris record holds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
