A4038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK08     08-07 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Butler learned from failures
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adam Butler is getting a second chance. As bad
as it was, he never wants to forget the first one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have been a little overwhelmed the first time up
here,'' he said before Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Butler arrived from the Class AAA Richmond Braves _ from Buffalo
through Pittsburgh _ nearly four months after Atlanta sent him
down. A spring training sensation (0.93 ERA and 10 strikeouts in 9
2/3 innings), Butler had been a disaster come April (0-1, 33.75
ERA, four hits two walks in 1 2/3 innings). He has often thought
about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was pitching inside like I needed to,'' said
Butler, who takes Russ Springer's spot on the roster (15-day
disabled list with bone spurs in his right elbow). ``I don't
remember shaking off Javy (Lopez) one time. Not to say he wasn't
calling a good game but if I'd disagree with something, I might
have just thrown it anyway. He's been in the major leagues, what,
five years?''
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky start once he returned to the minors, Butler was
3-7 with 12 saves and a 3.31 ERA (83 hits and 79 strikeouts in 89
2/3 innings) while sharing closing duties. It is not inconceivable
he could make a place for himself in Atlanta the second time
around. John Rocker did and the Braves are still looking for a
second left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get him in there,'' said manager Bobby Cox, ``as quick
as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I learned to pace myself a lot better,'' Butler said.
``I was up 12 times in the 14 games I was up here. I was getting
worn out. So I'm going to take it easy when I'm warming up and not
leaving it all down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Door No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cather might have rejoined the club instead of Butler, if
his elbow was sound. Optioned to Richmond July 16 to make a place
for Mark Wohlers when he returned from his first optional
assignment, Cather has encountered a tendon problem in his right
elbow. He had accumulated a 6.14 ERA in his six appearances before
his elbow flared up. A product of Cal-Berkeley (Cather appeared for
the Bears in the 1992 College World Series), he was actually a
drawing card here this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have called him right back,'' said Cox. ``I just ran
into about 50 of his friends outside. They all bought their tickets
way in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire one
</P>
<P>
   Cox was incredulous over a report circulating in Detroit that
the Braves were close to dealing center fielder Andruw Jones. A
Detroit newspaper reported Atlanta general manager John Schuerholz
had agreed with Tigers GM Randy Smith to swap Jones for Tigers
closer Todd Jones and center fielder Brian Hunter, until Cox shot
down the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made that up,'' Cox said. ``That's stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Orange power
</P>
<P>
   With three home runs within 10 at-bats entering Friday night,
Andruw Jones declined that his power surge is a result of his new _
and vacillating _ hair color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' said Jones, ``just good luck against Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   His double-HR performance against the Reds Thursday night meant
12 of his 42 career homers have come against the Reds. He is on
pace to reach 27 homers this year, the most by Braves center
fielder since Ron Gant hit 32 in 1991. For the record, the hair
tone Friday remained a shade of gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's prematurely orange,'' said broadcaster Don Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
