<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-COX     08-07 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fight night fright night for local investors
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The ring will be surrounded by more than 40,000 seats
and seemingly as many questions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one: Which Atlanta carries more weight _ the one that can
claim participation in one of the most noteworthy nights in boxing
history, Muhammad Ali's return to the ring in 1970 at the old City
Auditorium? Or the one that consistently has failed to support not
only local club shows but a resident who happens to be the greatest
heavyweight of this era?
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks from today, Evander Holyfield will defend his
heavyweight title against Vaughn Bean in the Georgia Dome. The
Sept. 19 fight, which will be announced officially in a Tuesday
news conference, will be only the third heavyweight title fight
held in the city and the fourth bout for Holyfield in his hometown.
It also represents perhaps the greatest test for the city's
affection for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the Georgia Boxing Commission, Thomas
Mishou, views the fight as ``an excellent opportunity for Atlanta
to recognize the economic potential boxing can bring to the city
and state.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Morrison believes he already has a fix on the
economics. Morrison, who has funded four successful monthly shows
at the Roxy Theater in Buckhead, was approached by Holyfield
attorney Jim Thomas about bankrolling a $3 million site fee for the
September show. He declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that Evander wants to fight here, and I feel the
city really should support him,'' Morrison said. ``But he's never
been able to sell tickets. Why, I don't know. ... They wanted to
give me the honor of underwriting this fight. But there's no honor
in losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as he has disproved people in the ring, Holyfield aims to
disprove Morrison and others who are convinced that Atlanta is not
a boxing town. Holyfield will take the majority of the financial
risk, in effect drawing his purse from the gate. But he says a
combination of factors will fill the Dome:
</P>
<P>
   Moderately priced tickets, expected to start at about $25.
</P>
<P>
   Belated corporate participation; Holyfield and Thomas are trying
to persuadecompanies to buy blocks of tickets to distribute to
schools.
</P>
<P>
   And the rare opportunity to see a heavyweight title fight here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the only chance a lot of people get to see me
fight in person before I retire,'' said Holyfield, who would follow
a win with bouts against Henry Akinwande in Las Vegas or Atlantic
City and Lennox Lewis in Las Vegas. ``Think of all the kids who
would have the chance to tell their kids, 'I saw Holyfield fight.'
I'm doing this for Atlanta. I think the support will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The promotional push will be strong. Promoter Don King is fresh
off being cleared of insurance fraud charges and already has
described the fight as ``a celebration of freedom.'' Holyfield
plans to train in Atlanta rather than Houston for the four weeks
leading up to the fight and probably will hold some open workouts
and speak to a number of youth groups.
</P>
<P>
   Bean's promoter, Butch Lewis, he of the bow tie without the
shirt, is one of the sport's more colorful figures and also will be
visible.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta's boxing history is mixed: Ali's return against
Jerry Quarry in 1970 sold out, albeit in a weathered 5,000-seat
auditorium. Tim Witherspoon vs. Tony Tubbs, the first heavyweight
title fight in Atlanta, in 1986, drew 6,500 in the Omni. A
gathering of 7,500 was announced for Holyfield's cruiserweight
championship against Dwight Muhammad Qawi in the Omni the same
year, but 4,000 seemed more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In Holyfield's most recent Atlanta appearance, a 1991
heavyweight defense against Bert Cooper, also in the Omni, 12,996
were announced. That was well short of a sellout but not bad
considering that Cooper was a last-minute replacement for Francesco
Damiani, who had been a replacement for Mike Tyson, who had backed
out of a November fight after suffering a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Boorman is a spokesman for Main Events, Holyfield's
promoter at the time of the Cooper fight. ``We thought the response
was pretty good, especially considering all the changes,'' Boorman
said. ``The strange thing was we actually had to give some people
refunds when Damiani backed out. We tried to explain to everyone
that Cooper actually was a tougher fighter, but nobody believed us.
That's the problem with being a promoter. When you tell the truth,
nobody believes you. It's like the boy who cried wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper nearly stunned Holyfield in his homecoming, knocking the
champion into the ropes in the third round. Referee Mills Lane
called it a knockdown, the first of Holyfield's career. Cooper
finally fell to a series of punches in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman expects the Holyfield-Bean fight to draw more than
20,000. ``Remember, the Holyfield who fought Cooper hadn't beaten
up Tyson yet,'' he said. ``Because of who Evander is and what he
does to promote Atlanta, he should sell the place out. But I'm just
naturally a pessimist.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty about the turnout could affect broadcast decisions
by the Showtime cable network, which has not staged a boxing show
in Atlanta. Executive Jay Larkin said the company generally does
not black out fights in the host city but is considering doing so
for this one. ``We want to have a full house for Evander's sake,''
Larkin said. ``All I have to go on is the adage in our business
that Atlanta is not a good boxing town,'' Larkin said. ``I'd like
to disprove that Sept. 19 with Evander. The guy has a highway named
after him. He's a local hero. I watched him carry the torch into
the stadium during the Olympics, and the crowd went nuts. I have to
believe that will translate into ticket sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Mishou, who has seen increased interest in club shows around the
state in recent months, agrees. ``There is no reason why Atlanta
can't become a significant market for pro boxing,'' he said. ``We
have the infrastructure and the right demographics. I understand
the conditions to get a Holyfield fight or one like that have to be
incredibly favorable. But for this fight, they are. The ticket
prices will be low.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Atlanta hasn't developed into a strong boxing town,
despite Holyfield's presence, Mishou said, ``Part of it is the
image of the sport itself. That's not just a problem here; that's
all over the country. Also, Atlanta is a major-league sports town,
but it hasn't gotten there easily. Every sport has had to struggle
before it succeeded. I'm convinced boxing can do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
