<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals seek turnaround for defense
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Ky. _ The Cincinnati Bengals coaching staff is
documenting and deliberating every move in the much-ballyhooed
quarterback battle here between struggling incumbent Jeff Blake and
challenger Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bengals defense, which ranked 28th in 1997, might be
under even closer scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the playmakers we have (on offense), it almost seems
like we're going to put up points no matter who's playing
(quarterback),'' strong safety Sam Shade said. ``But if we don't
hold up our end of the deal. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Blake suffered through a 1997 season so miserable that coach
Bruce Coslet played aging Boomer Esiason for the final month. But
Cincinnati still managed to rank 10th in the NFL in both scoring
and total yards, because wide receivers Carl Pickens and Darnay
Scott are among the league's most talented and tailback Corey
Dillon is an emerging star.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bengals are to challenge Pittsburgh and Jacksonville in
the AFC Central, however, they must master defensive coordinator
Dick LeBeau's exotic zone-blitz scheme. The excitement about
LeBeau's return last year to Cincinnati, where he was coordinator
from 1984-91, did not match the results. Never before had a unit
led by LeBeau, 60, ranked so low _ the Bengals surrendered the most
first downs in the league (351) and the fourth-most points (405).
</P>
<P>
   A defense designed to pressure from unusual angles generated
only 35 sacks, 13 interceptions and 23 takeaways, while allowing
opponents a gaudy third-down conversion rate of 44.9 percent. The
7-9 Bengals lost three games in which their offense scored 20
points or more, including a 44-42 defeat at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply had too many players who didn't understand the
defense early on,'' LeBeau said. ``There was a painful transition
period, and it wasn't until the second half of the year when we
really started playing on the same page. We have to come together a
lot quicker this time around.''
</P>
<P>
   That feat could be difficult for a defense that figures to start
as many as eight players with four years or less of NFL experience.
The zone-blitz scheme, debuted by LeBeau in the late '80s and
originally designed to take advantage of the hybrid abilities of
strong safety David Fulcher, has evolved into a linebacker-driven
defense. At some point this year, LeBeau probably will be starting
three linebackers selected in the first round of the past two
drafts _ Reinard Wilson in 1997 and Takeo Spikes and Brian Simmons
in '98.
</P>
<P>
   That Spikes, the former Auburn and Washington County High School
star, will start in tonight's preseason opener against the New York
Giants is almost as significant as the fact Blake will open the
game at quarterback. As was the case with Wilson a year ago, Spikes
already has been somewhat overwhelmed by the complexities of the
zone-blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you learn everything, this defense is a linebacker's
dream, because it puts you in position to make a ton of big
plays,'' said Spikes, who will replace injured veteran Jerry
Olsavsky (dislocated wrist). ``But there's a lot of responsibility.
There are nights where you're studying the playbook and end up
giving yourself a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsavsky, an unheralded backup for the Steelers last year, was
injured during a Saturday scrimmage and will not play for eight
weeks. He is expected to be a steadying influence for the younger
linebackers. The annual battle of the bulge for James Francis, an
eight-year pro, might end in a pink slip and force LeBeau to play
natural inside linebacker Steve Tovar at an outside spot in the
Bengals' 3-4 front. Journeyman Gerald Dixon, who notched a
team-best 8 1/2 sacks, departed in free-agency.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month before the regular season begins, third-year
inside linebacker Tom Tumulty appears to be the only established
starter. Still, there is optimism that the influx of athletic
defenders and the continuing growth of young veterans such as
Shade, Wilson, free safety Greg Myers and corner Ashley Ambrose
will bring improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more talent and definitely more understanding than
last year,'' said Wilson, a former Florida State defensive end who
collected three sacks in '97. ``Now we've got to turn that into
more results.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
