<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inmates denied cooling water, fans, group says
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A prisoner-advocacy group charged Friday that
some convicts in Texas' sweltering prisons are being denied water
and fans and others have been shackled on uncooled buses for as
long as 44 hours without adequate water or restroom breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials immediately rejected the allegations as untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lois Robison, chairwoman of Texas Citizens United
for Rehabilitation of Errants, said the group believes complaints
from convicts, guards and former prison workers about what she
called ``a growing problem'' with the way convicts are treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical, mental and medical abuses have been a constant
problem,'' Robison said at a Capitol news conference. ``This
summer's extreme heat combined with those ongoing abuses have
subjected prisoners to even more inhumane conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The group charged that water has been withheld from convicts at
some prisons on 100-degree days, that small fans have been
confiscated from convicts for rules infractions and that guards at
some prisons have closed doors and windows _ making it even hotter
inside convicts' cells.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Robison said prisoners with medical conditions or
who are on medications that impair the body's ability to cope with
the extreme heat have ``been forced into working or living
conditions that are injurious to their health.''
</P>
<P>
   Other convicts have reported being prevented from lying on the
concrete floors of their cells to stay cool, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are prisoners just now at this late date getting fans?''
Robison said. ``Why are physically and mentally ill prisoners, many
of whom are on medications, subjected to torturous bus rides? Why
is (the prison agency) unable to control the behavior of its
staff?''
</P>
<P>
   Robison provided few details to bolster the group's allegations,
which she said are partly based on complaints from convicts or
guards who fear retaliation from prison officials if their
identities are made public.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Castlebury, a spokesman for the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice who sat in on the news conference, criticized the
allegations. ``It's not happening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Convicts are bused between prisons only during the coolest hours
of the day, he said, and for no more than nine-hour trips at a
time. Although the prisoners ``are expected to use the restroom
facilities prior to leaving,'' Castlebury said, ``a stop may be
made at another (prison) unit or county jail if facilities are
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   He also challenged the group's suggestion that temperatures in
some death row areas had reached 130 degrees. Robison said one of
her sons, Larry, is on death row. A second son, Steve, is serving a
17-year sentence at the Beto prison unit in northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are problems, we certainly want to deal with them,''
Castlebury said. ``But there's nothing to these.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
