<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR ready with rain tires
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watkins Glen, N.Y. -- If the rain that is forecast to hang
around for Sunday's Bud at the Glen materializes, NASCAR is ready
to roll with a tire developed for wet pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear unloaded 1,200 wet-weather tires Friday at Watkins Glen
International. They're stacked in the back of the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   The tire has been in development for three years and was tested
in practice during qualifying last year in Japan. Usually, NASCAR
stops its races when rain falls and tracks get wet. Some rain
delays to dry the surface have lasted more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   But the new tire, unlike the normal slick racing tire, has a
slightly raised tread (6/32nds of an inch) separated by a mid-tire
groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have some rain, we'll make the decision then,'' NASCAR
spokesman Tim Sullivan said. In case of rain, NASCAR will call all
the cars into the pits under caution to switch to the wet-weather
tires.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup teams have been instructed to arrive here with
quick-mount windshield wipers, defoggers and tail-light assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a monsoon, we'll get everybody off the track, of
course,'' Sullivan said. ``But we're prepared to go under some
moderate rain conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of racing in the rain has met with mixed reactions
from drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not have the rain tires at Watkins Glen?'' Dale Earnhardt
asked. ``We used them in Japan for qualifying, and the Goodyear
engineers did a great job with them. We need to have a rain plan.
The fans deserve every effort to make sure we race when they have
it scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit I do have some reservations with racing in the
rain,'' Terry Labonte said. ``My biggest concern is the lack of
visibility. It might be interesting, but I prefer to race under dry
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin shares Labonte's concern. ``I think it will be
difficult to actually race in the rain, due to the spray of 43 cars
on the road course at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew swaps
</P>
<P>
   Charley Pressley, one of the more experienced crew chiefs in
Winston Cup racing, has been named crew chief for Morgan-McClure
Motorsports, which runs the No. 4 Chevrolet. He has been with
Larrry Hedrick Motorsports and takes over for interim crew chief
Robert Larkins.
</P>
<P>
   At Hedrick, Tim Brewer was hired as crew chief of the No. 41
Chevrolet. Brewer has been in racing 29 years, 13 of those under
the legendary Junior Johnson. He has helped prepare cars that have
won 53 times and 54 pole positions.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett reflects
</P>
<P>
   Barely a week after running out of gas and losing any chance at
the Brickyard 400, Dale Jarrett was still emotional on Friday when
asked about the controversial point in the race when Ward Burton's
car was disabled on pit road and drivers expected a caution flag
that didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I didn't even want to come here (to the
media-center press conference) today, because it's over and done
with,'' Jarrett said. ``The PR department said we needed to come
and do this. I can honestly say I didn't think about that race all
week, except when I was awake.''
</P>
<P>
   He voiced frustration at NASCAR's inconsistent calls. ``We're
told in drivers' meetings that if you have a problem with your
race, get off the racing surface, we'll get you taken care of, just
don't create a bigger problem. Ward Burton did exactly what he's
instructed to do, and when I was out of fuel, I did the same thing,
too. But you can bet the next time my butt is stopping on that race
track, I'll get a caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
