<SLUG> BC-RAC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fellows, Said surprise qualifiers at the Glen
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ We interrupt The Jeff Gordon Show to
present two giddy Winston Cup drivers who are happy just to be in a
Winston Cup, forget about starting second and fifth in Sunday's Bud
at the Glen.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon rolled along Friday, taking the pole at Watkins Glen
International with a best qualifying time of 120.331 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But it was two substitute drivers, Ron Fellows and Boris Said,
with surprising finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows, a Busch driver, qualified second in the No. 96
Chevrolet with a lap of 120.002 mph. On Sunday, he'll run in his
second career Winston Cup race. He finished 35th here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shaking a little bit,'' Fellows said.
</P>
<P>
   Said, who drives in the NASCAR truck series, qualified the No.
23 Ford fifth at 119.780 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a little kid at Christmas,'' he said. ``It's just
hard to believe I'm out here driving with these heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Between these no-names, Ricky Rudd (119.914) qualified third and
Jeff Burton (119.910) fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is on another of those little successful streaks that
have marked his brief, but very profitable, stock-car driving
career.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent pole was four races ago at Sears Point, but the
Bud pole is Gordon's sixth this season. He has started on the front
row in nine of the last 11 races.
</P>
<P>
   He has won three of the last four Winston Cup races to sprint
out to a 72-point advantage over Mark Martin in the championship
points race.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough, he's back to defend his victory here
last year, and he recalled Friday that this is the track that gave
him the comfort level he now has on road courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race last year did a lot for me, confidence-wise, on the
road courses,'' Gordon said. ``I didn't know if I was capable of
winning on a road course until we won here. I think that
transferred to winning at California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning at California has definitely brought some momentum
into this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's comfort level was obvious on a day when a number of
drivers had trouble staying on the course because of high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad we didn't hit anything,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott never finished his lap after losing control and
getting into some gravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got in a little too hard and hit that inside curb,'' he
said. ``When it did, it just launched me straight across.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way my year has been going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kenny Irwin, in the No. 28 Ford, hit some oil in turn
seven, spun around and then took the car back around in the wrong
direction before actually qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of weeks, I think I've gained 10 years in
qualifying,'' Irwin said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bobby Labonte, who did not qualify, had to go to a backup
car after destroying the sheet metal on the rear of his No. 18
Pontiac after hitting a wall in the last five minutes of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
