<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO--WORLD-CHAMPIONSH     08-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO--WORLD-CHAMPIONSHIPS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. sole men deploy 
defense to edge Italy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Some teams have the heart of a champion. Others,
like this U.S. squad that sometimes seems destined for gold, have
the soul of a winner. The sole of a winner, too, as it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Hawkins proving it really is the shoes that make
the difference, he and fellow point guard Kiwane Garris led the
U.S. team to a gutsy, hard-fought 80-77 victory over Italy on
Friday at Olympic Stadium and a spot in the medal round today
against Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins scored 12 of his team-high 16 points in the second half,
when he was wearing teammate Trajan Langdon's left shoe after
Hawkins' rubber sole ripped while he was making a cut late in the
first half. The problem: Langdon wears a 12{. Hawkins is a size 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole sole was completely torn on the bottom of my shoe
from all the cutting,'' Hawkins said. ``So I had to go to one of
Trajan's shoes, which was a half-size small. It was really tight.
But I had to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Size didn't matter in this job. Once in a while, Cinderella has
to slip into a slightly tighter slipper.
</P>
<P>
   Snug shoe and all, Hawkins was the guiding force _ and he had a
lot of help from Garris and the rest of the strong-willed Americans
as the United States assured itself of a top-four finish in the
FIBA World Championship of Basketball. Not bad for replacement
players thrown together in less than a month. They played Italy
close virtually the entire game, with the momentum alternating.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the United States held Italy without a field goal
for the final 7:22 and kept the Italians scoreless on six of their
final seven possessions to outscore them 11-2 in the final 4:50.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a relief,'' said Garris, who had 11 points, all
in the final 6:36. ``Back home, people were talking that we weren't
going to do this and we weren't going to do that. We're happy and
relieved to be in the medal round. But now that we're there, we
have to take advantage of it and go for the gold. We don't want to
just settle for a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Added center Gerard King: ``Some people said we wouldn't get
there, so there's a sigh of relief. But we're not quite there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They could get there by Sunday. After the way the Americans
played Friday, it's looking as if they are capable of overcoming
any obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   They were ahead 59-53 after a 12-0 sprint, then let the Italians
come off the floor with an 11-0 run that put the United States in a
66-61 hole with just less than six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Garris scored for the first time with a 3-pointer, and with the
Americans down 75-69, Garris hit a driving bank shot with 3:30 to
go. The defense dug in and forced a turnover from Gregor Fucka.
Jimmy Oliver was fouled on the ensuing fast break and hit two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Myers, Italy's best scorer who lived at the free-throw
line all game but was only 7-for-21 from the field, would miss
three jumpers in the final 2:30, tarnishing his 32-point effort.
</P>
<P>
   When Garris hit two free throws with 1:28 left, the game was
tied at 75. Brad Miller grabbed a Myers miss, and Hawkins then was
isolated against his defender and converted it into a drive down
the lane and a 10-foot bank shot for the lead with 41 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy (Tomjanovich, the U.S. coach) opened the court for me
because he knew I could take the guy,'' Hawkins said. ``I crossed
him over and got into the heart of the defense and waited to see
what the big guy was going to do. He stayed under the basket, so I
shot the jumper. And I did mean for it to go off the backboard. The
guys were kidding me about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy tied the game when Myers hit two of his 15 free throws
with 27.2 seconds left. It was the only points for Italy in the
final 3:43.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Alexis, who had 14 points, was fouled quickly and hit
two free throws with 25.7 seconds to go. When Myers missed a
3-pointer with Alexis' hand in his face, Garris rebounded and made
one of two free throws with 2.9 seconds left for the final score.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans felt the pressure that the quarterfinal round can
produce earlier. They were chasing the Italians throughout most of
the first half after squandering an early 11-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is money time. This is crunch time,'' Tomjanovich said.
``We lose this one, and it's: `Hey, we heard you guys were pretty
good. How was it over there?' And all the work these guys had done
(would have been lost).
</P>
<P>
   ``These are a bunch of hard-working guys. But it's a struggle
out there. We had times when we didn't look too damn good out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And a loss meant no chance at a medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
