<HEADER>
A4049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFINGS-N     08-07 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZ., CALIF., DEL., IOWA, KAN., MD., N.H., N.Y., ORE., PA., WASH.
AND SOUTHERN STATES: FOR CAMPAIGN 2000, A MONTH OF TUESDAYS  
 ARIZONA: NO. 9, NO. 9, NO. 9? NOT IN THIS STATE   
 MISSOURI: DESEGREGATION DIVIDES SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the spring of 1984, some Southern states got together
and created the first regional ``Super Tuesday'' by scheduling
their presidential primaries for the same early date in the
nominating season. Their aim was to increase the South's clout in
the presidential picking process by weighing in with a big bag of
votes while the process was still young enough to be influenced.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, other regions have also toyed with the concept,
setting off a wild quadrennial scramble to be in the forefront of
primary and caucus voting. Adding to the freneticism, some big
individual states, like California, have also joined the scramble.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, when the National Association of Secretaries of
State held its annual convention in Salt Lake City _ the
secretaries enforce election laws in most states _ there was a lot
of talk about bringing some order and calm to the nominating
process, possibly by establishing a series of five regional
primaries to be held one month after another, with the order of
voting to be rotated every four years. Iowa, which traditionally
has held the first caucuses, and New Hampshire, which traditionally
has held the first primary, would be excepted from the new
approach.
</P>
<P>
   By fall, the secretaries hope to be ready to present a detailed
regional primaries plan to the nation's state legislators and
governors. But where that will all come out is at best a guess and,
in any event, not much is likely to be acted upon before the 2004
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the scramble is on for primary and caucus
position in the 2000 presidential election, with March 7 shaping up
as the mother of all blockbuster Super Tuesdays if some states and
regions don't back off.
</P>
<P>
   California is talking to Oregon and Washington about setting
that date for a Pacific Coast Super Tuesday. Arizona and a
half-dozen other Southwestern and mountain states may also set
aside that day _ or maybe an earlier day _ for a Western Super
Tuesday .
</P>
<P>
   The New England states, other than New Hampshire, are talking
about a May 7 Yankee Super Tuesday, with maybe New York joining in.
Likewise, Maryland is thinking about holding a Mid-Atlantic Super
Tuesday that day, if it can persuade Pennsylvania and Delaware to
go along.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas wants to hold a Prairie Super Tuesday, providing it can
persuade other farm belt states to join in _ at an early date. The
Southern states, though they started the regional Super Tuesday
trend, have said little about their schedule for 2000, but they
almost surely will opt again for an early date, maybe even March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is getting to be a bigger mess than ever, a political and
civic crisis,'' William Galvin, the Massachusetts secretary of
state, commented the other day after the Salt Lake City meeting.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9, No. 9, No. 9? Not in Arizona
</P>
<P>
   The lottery was a form of gambling found in only a few states
until a quarter of a century ago. The others were too straitlaced
to permit it.
</P>
<P>
   But lottery fever has since swept the country and now 37 states
and the District of Columbia have lotteries. The players love the
whopping multi-million-dollar jackpots _ the latest Powerball prize
was almost $300 million _ and state legislators love to use what is
left over to finance new government goodies like schools, roads and
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lottery is not everybody's game. Just as opposition
is beginning to build in some parts of the country to spreading
numbers of electronic poker parlors and riverboat and Indian
reservation casinos, in Arizona opposition to the lottery is
building.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful group of social conservatives in the state
legislature has succeeded in forcing a statewide vote this fall on
whether to keep or kill the lottery, which has been a sanctioned
Arizona money game since 1981. The group argues that the
get-rich-quick tease of the lottery is ultimately destructive, not
just depleting paychecks and emptying bank accounts but, worse,
destroying families.
</P>
<P>
   No other state has scrapped a lottery, not once its citizens and
legislators got hooked on the big jackpots and extra revenue for
schooling, transportation and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Most Arizonans want to keep their lottery, polls indicate. But
its opponents are not without a case. Besides their argument that
the lottery is socially destructive _ a powerful argument in a
state as conservative as Arizona _ they also have the results from
a recent state audit of the lottery operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery sales have been flat for several years, the auditors
found, mainly because of inept management. How inept?
</P>
<P>
   A new computerized bingo game that was designed to increase
sales turned out to be a bust. Even more embarrassing, a computer
program designed to run the Pick 3 game could never find the number
nine.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery director was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Desegregation Divides Missouri Senate Race
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Jay Nixon of Missouri had no trouble winning
the Democratic nomination in last Tuesday's U.S. Senate primary.
But a major political problem he faced before the primary is still
with him as he heads into an uphill general election battle with
the Republican incumbent, Christopher Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the primary campaign, Nixon was severely criticized
by many of Missouri's top black leaders for calling for an end to
state aid for school desegregation programs. And no sooner was the
primary over than those critics resumed the attack, with the St.
Louis office of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People warning top national Democrats that they would be
confronted by pickets if they showed up at any Nixon fund-raising
events in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked to choose between a flawed candidate like Nixon and
respecting an NAACP picket line,'' the NAACP chapter president,
Charles Mischeaux, wrote in a letter sent to such leading national
Democrats as Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, as well as to the Democratic National Committee, ``I
am hopeful you will choose the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, now trailing in a race the experts originally predicted
would be closer all the way, needs every bit of campaign money he
can raise and _ every bit as serious _ he can ill afford to be at
odds with Missouri blacks, a significant part of the Democratic
base in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general contends that the Mischeaux letter is
nothing more than a recycling of an old complaint. He contends that
in the primary, he ran well in black precincts all over the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bond sees the letter as proof of great disarray in the Nixon
campaign. He says he, by contrast, is having good success drawing
blacks to his campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan, the state's top elected Democrat, is holding
talks with black leaders in an effort to heal the racial rift
within the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
