<HEADER>
A4050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CABLE-TV-1STL     08-07 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CABLE-TV-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL IS GOOD NEWS TO ALL-NEWS NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to identify and give full name of Larry Gerbrandt in graf
7.)  
(lh) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The images hardly make for compelling television: mostly Monica
Lewinsky getting out of cars and Kenneth Starr getting into them.
The talking heads make up a largely over-exposed collection of
former prosecutors, defense attorneys and pundits. And often there
hasn't been a whole lot of hard news to headline.
</P>
<P>
   But for 24-hour cable news networks like MSNBC, CNBC, Fox News
and CNN, all that does not seem to matter. The questions that would
dominate dinner party conversation these days are apparently enough
to sustain what some have come to call ``All Monica All the Time'':
Will the dress test positive? Will the president submit his saliva?
What is Ms. Lewinsky's state of mind?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the talk show clatter, the Monica Lewinsky story is big
business, meaning more revenue and higher ratings to shows that
mostly struggle at the margins, looking for, at best, the
mysterious murder of a beauty queen.
</P>
<P>
   Where initially this kind of round-the-clock coverage, ushered
in by the Gulf War, appeared to be dictated by news developments,
now it seems largely fueled by the bottom line. All-news channels
depend on events like the O.J. Simpson trial, the death of Princess
Diana and now the trials and tribulations of President Clinton for
their very survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs live or die on issues of this sort,'' said
Marvin Kalb, director of the Shorenstein Center on the Press,
Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University. ``Because talk is
the cheapest form of entertainment, it can fill hours of air time
at the lowest possible cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable news executives say they are simply responding to the
demands of the marketplace. ``Do I think we're crisis-driven now?
No,'' said John Moody, vice president of news editorial at Fox
News. ``The nation's viewing habits are changing. There's always
someone who wants to find out what's going on. This is not a
country that's all at home at 6:30 to watch Dan or Peter or Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   But media experts say cable news networks are not yet
established enough to eat into the networks in the absence of a big
breaking story. ``The worst thing that can happen to a CNN is for
there not to be a Monica Lewinsky or an O.J. Simpson or a war,
because you don't get any of these peaks and surges in viewing,''
said Larry Gerbrandt of Paul Kagan Associates, a media research and
consulting firm based in Carmel, Calif. ``No news is bad news for
these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the cable universe is so much smaller than the broadcast
universe, media experts say _ 66 million households vs. 100
million, according to one estimate _ a little lift goes a long way.
A story like this one, for example, can boost a program's rating
from a 0.1 or 0.3 to a 0.3 or a 0.6. ``In broadcast terms, that's
nothing,'' said John P. Ellis, a marketing and advertising
consultant who has advised CNBC. ``But in cable terms, it's called
doubling your audience. To cable news people, Monica is a huge
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a story like the Lewinsky scandal not only helps
fledgling all-news cable shows build ratings and get noticed,
television experts say, it goes straight to the bottom line,
particularly because these programs have fixed costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A case like this, for cable news shows over the coming year,
is probably worth in the tens of millions of dollars,'' said Larry
Gerbrandt, a senior analyst with Paul Kagan Associates Inc. a
Carmel, Calif.-based media research and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how long it drags out, maybe even in the
hundreds,'' Gerbrandt continued, ``because future ad time is based
on historic viewing patterns. So the benefit really comes over the
next year to 18 months.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For what are called spot advertising buys _ time that has not
been purchased in advance _ for example, cable news channels can
adjust their prices upwards depending on the daily Nielsen ratings
data, Ellis explained. ``Cable news is very spot market heavy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the cable shows may reach a relatively small audience
compared with the networks, media experts say, their influence is
considerably broader. Networks and print organizations, cable news
executives note, are fueled by the constant scandal updates
available from their cable competitors. ``When the soap opera on
the news channels is better than the soap opera on the networks,
then I think it does provide a certain amount of pressure,'' Moody
said. ``Despite protestations that we're saturating America's
living rooms with tawdry detail, that same detail is exactly what's
being demanded by our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this means people like Geraldo Rivera are having a very
good time. Prime time ratings for his program, ``Rivera Live'' on
CNBC, which has devoted its hour to the Lewinsky-Clinton story
night after night, are up nearly 30 percent for the month of July
compared with the same period last year, from 438,000 households to
567,000.
</P>
<P>
   ```Rivera Live' has clearly found its niche,'' Rivera said.
``It's by seeking the nuance and promising your audience that
you'll report every significant development that you build an
expectation that, when push comes to shove, there's only one show
to turn to.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``Hardball With Chris Matthews,'' which started a
year and a half ago and appears just before Rivera's program on
CNBC, saw its prime-time ratings increase 57 percent for July
compared with last year and 147 percent in the program's midnight
time slot, when it is rebroadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cable news anchors are quite so proud. Keith Olbermann,
whose program ``White House in Crisis'' on MSNBC was started in
February in response to the Lewinsky story, has done some public
chest-thumping about his own coverage. In a May 23 speech to his
alma mater, Cornell University, he said: ``There are days now when
my line of work makes me ashamed, makes me depressed, makes me cry
... . About three weeks ago, I awakened from my stupor on this
subject and told my employers that I simply could not continue
doing this show about the endless investigation and the
investigation of the investigation, and the investigation of the
investigation of the investigation. I had to choose what I felt in
my heart was right, over what I felt in my wallet was smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Olbermann, who declined to comment, is still on the air
every night, discussing the latest Lewinsky speculation on MSNBC's
``The Big Show.'' Erik Sorensen, the executive vice president in
charge of programming at MSNBC who only started at the network last
week, said this kind of ambivalence comes with the territory.
``There is a lot about this story that a lot of us covering it
aren't particularly crazy about,'' he said. ``But that's what we do
for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable news shows have been criticized on the Lewinsky story,
along with the mainstream press, for vamping without substance and
for vague attribution. Indeed, Gerbrandt suggested that the report
about nerve gas in Vietnam, which got CNN into trouble recently,
was an example of an ill-fated effort to generate excitement in a
slow news period. ``That story on nerve gas is the result of a CNN
trying to make sure they have an ongoing series of reports that can
attract viewers,'' Gerbrandt said, ``realizing that you can't count
on a scandal or a disaster or a trial of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, correspondents say their information is no less
reliable because they have so much time to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, for example, made a point of saying on the air last week
that he stood by his report of Aug. 4 alleging that the infamous
dress had tested positive for ``human genetic material,'' which he
attributed to ``one source very close to the president.'' NBC last
week sent out a message warning its other reporters not to pick up
Rivera's report and saying the network had not confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been wrong yet,'' Rivera said. ``In that sense, I'm
still living as queen for a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is viewing newscasters like Rivera as
royalty. ``For me, I am finding _ as there is this explosion of
talk, talk, talk _ that I cannot listen to the din,'' said Kalb of
Harvard. ``I'm not learning anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton story shows few signs of receding, cable
news executives acknowledge that there will come a time when Ms.
Lewinsky will be old news. ``I'm already losing sleep over it,''
said Sorensen of MSNBC. ``Inevitably, this story is going to end
and, as an all-news channel, we rely on reality _ and we need
reality to cooperate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4052 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NANULA-STARWOOD-HOTEL     08-07 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANULA-STARWOOD-HOTELS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 38, HE RUNS A HOTEL GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Colo., Conn., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9)  
 (af)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard D. Nanula is not in the middle of changing jobs and
moving, he likes to unwind by watching five television sets at
once, using a customized touch pad to change channels quickly and
adjust the sound. Oh, and he sometimes reads at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a multiprocessor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And listening to Nanula, 38, talk about his life is also like
watching several channels at once.
</P>
<P>
   There he is at the Walt Disney Co., which hired him out of
Harvard Business School 12 years ago and named him chief financial
officer at the age of 31. He quickly made his mark, negotiating
long and hard to get the troubled Euro Disney theme park on firmer
financial footing, handling more than $1 billion of financing for
Disney films and issuing rare 100-year bonds.
</P>
<P>
   And there he is pursuing his second career as one of the world's
greatest sports fans. He once moved intensive business negotiations
to the Super Bowl so he wouldn't miss the game.
</P>
<P>
   When he learned that Shaquille O'Neal, the Los Angeles Lakers
center, had moved into his Beverly Hills neighborhood last summer,
Nanula got his wish for a pick-up game with him.
</P>
<P>
   And there he is again, in a T-shirt, sunglasses and a baseball
cap, on the back cover of the menu at the recently opened ESPN Zone
restaurant in Baltimore. The restaurant is a Disney property, and
executives who knew of Nanula's passion for sports agreed that he
should be the poster boy for serious fandom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my favorite things I've ever done,'' Nanula said
of the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nanula (pronounced na-NOO-lah) faces perhaps the hardest
thing he's ever done, taking over as chief executive of Starwood
Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, the world's largest hotel company.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his challenge. By acquiring Westin Hotels and ITT,
Starwood has become, in a way, a $16 billion start-up. And Nanula,
who became its chief on June 1, must now assemble a team to run
Starwood's many distinct parts _ including the Caesars World
casinos and the company's Sheraton and luxury hotels _ and assemble
three companies into one at its new headquarters in White Plains,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   To cut costs, he is using the company's size to renegotiate
contracts for its 650 hotels on everything from mattresses to
shrimp to long-distance service. He hopes to raise revenues by,
among other things, stitching together reservation systems and
frequent-guest programs.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Starwood is growing, with 125,000 employees and
$1 billion of projects in the pipeline, and it is starting a new
brand, W Hotels, to compete in the so-called boutique hotel market.
</P>
<P>
   Lest Nanula's job grow too dull, he must also develop a new
corporate structure for Starwood, which recently lost a battle with
Congress and the White House to extend the tax advantages of its
unusual corporate structure.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock price, meanwhile, has sagged, along with
others in the lodging industry; Starwood shares have fallen 5.7
percent over the last year, better than the 6.4 percent drop in the
Chicago Board Options Exchange index of real estate investment
trusts but well below the 16.7 percent gain in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure anyone has tried to pull off what we're doing
here,'' Nanula said during three hours of interviews squeezed into
his schedule. ``It is a big and interesting challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at stake is the reputation of Barry S. Sternlicht, a
longtime friend of Nanula. Sternlicht, who is 37, built Starwood at
breakneck speed and is now its chairman, but he acknowledges that
he lacks the operational skills to make it all work. Nanula's
efforts will go a long way toward determining whether Sternlicht
will be regarded in coming years as a savvy deal maker or as
someone who paid too much to create an unwieldy corporate giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see today is a company operating on 2 of its 12
cylinders,'' Sternlicht said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people on Wall Street are betting that Nanula can make
Starwood hum, though no one minimizes the enormity of his task.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Richard Nanula to have left his job at Disney says a lot
about what he believes is the potential for Starwood,'' said Jason
N. Ader, an analyst at Bear, Stearns. ``But he's got to focus to
manage the assimilation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanula's route to Starwood can be traced, in part, to his
penchant for juggling several tasks.
</P>
<P>
   On his first day at Harvard, in 1984, he took a seat in the
lecture hall at the end of the last row _ or ``skydeck,'' as the
students called it _ so he could read newspapers and magazines or
do course work when class discussions bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   Two seats away sat Sternlicht, another multitasker. ``I'm really
good at doodling and listening at the same time, which drives
people crazy because they don't think I'm listening,'' he explained
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The two had pursued different academic interests. Sternlicht was
a liberal arts major at Brown University in a program called Law
and Society (or ``Lost in Society,'' as he called it). Nanula
studied economics at the University of California at Santa Barbara
and was a certified public accountant.
</P>
<P>
   But the men soon found common ground. They spent many Sunday
afternoons watching football together. During intramural basketball
games, Sternlicht played point guard, often setting up Nanula, who
is said to have a pretty good outside shot.
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht also helped Nanula land his first job. In their
second year, Sternlicht organized a field study project at Disney,
in part because he had a good contact there, but also because
Disney was far away from the chilly Northeast. He recruited four
classmates, including Nanula, to study the feasibility of a new
theme-park attraction of mini-factories showing how things like
bread and cheese are made.
</P>
<P>
   Nanula made a quick impression on Disney executives and was
hired into the strategic planning department even before the
students made their final presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht was not jealous, he said, because he preferred to
work in a smaller company. ``I didn't like hierarchy,'' he said.
``My goal was to do deals, to learn to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nanula, though, was drawn to the breadth and complexity of a
large corporation. He was also following in the footsteps of his
father, who had run companies that made products ranging from
cooling towers to automatic sprinkler systems (and, on occasion,
was known to read a book in front of the TV).
</P>
<P>
   Though fast friends, Nanula and Sternlicht assumed that they
would never work together. But they soon found themselves sitting
across from each other at a negotiating table. Sternlicht landed a
job at JMB Realty in Chicago, and he and Nanula haggled over the
sale to JMB of the real estate assets of Disney's Arvida
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   They stayed in touch _ Nanula sometimes called Sternlicht to
needle him about the California weather _ and they often went on
vacations and attended the NCAA Final Four together. But their
career paths were very different.
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht's trajectory dipped sharply early on. He led a team
that analyzed the finances of Randsworth Trust PLC, a British real
estate company, before JMB and some American pension funds bought
it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Randsworth collapsed two years later, for a loss of more than
$425 million. Sternlicht has said he was made the scapegoat for the
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   But failure, he said, ``teaches you intellectual discipline and
humility.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after he left JMB, Sternlicht started Starwood Capital
with investments from the Ziff publishing family and others.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Starwood, named for the community near Aspen, Colo.,
where it was assembled, bought its first hotels. The company took
off in 1995, when it acquired Hotel Investors Trust, a real estate
investment trust and standard operating company that traded as a
single stock _ a so-called paired-share or stapled REIT.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with its special structure, Starwood stormed the industry,
acquiring properties and companies that today give it hotels or
casinos in 70 countries. For most of that time, Starwood's stock
has performed well, far surpassing the average for hotel companies
and REITs. It has risen 284 percent in the last three and a half
years, despite its recent drop.
</P>
<P>
   At Disney, meanwhile, Nanula rose quickly. As chief financial
officer, he not only handled the negotiations over Euro Disney, now
known as Disneyland Paris, but also revamped the way Disney
financed its films, making the terms not quite so favorable to
outside investors. He learned Disney's businesses, from theme parks
to films to retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Nanula also picked up a few things that would come in handy at
Starwood. For one thing, Disney has about 25,000 hotel rooms. And
Nanula has some familiarity with casinos, having made regular trips
with friends to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   As chief financial officer, Nanula was known to push colleagues
time and again for more analysis to back up recommendations to
invest in new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very good in a company where risk is part of the
culture, but where you have to manage risk in a conservative
fashion,'' Michael D. Eisner, Disney's chairman, said in a recent
interview. ``He has pretty good antennae for spotting problems in
advance of everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner made Nanula president of the company's Disney Store
Worldwide unit in November 1994 to give him operating experience.
Without it, Eisner said, ``he wouldn't have been able to go all the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nanula's replacement as chief financial officer, Stephen P.
Bollenbach, left in early 1996 to become chief executive of the
Hilton Hotels Corp., Eisner named Nanula to the job again, to help
integrate Disney's $19 billion acquisition of Capital Cities/ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Nanula's accounting for the purchase was questioned in a lengthy
article in Barron's in March of this year; it said Disney had
created an undisclosed reserve of as much as $2.5 billion to absorb
expenses related to the merger without reducing its reported
earnings. When asked about this, Nanula said, ``Nobody who was up
on accounting standards ever questioned the accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, Nanula immersed himself in the life of a Disney
executive. He stared down the difficult decision of which
character's costume to wear for a stroll through Disney World as
part of a theme-park orientation. (He chose Tigger,
Winnie-the-Pooh's sidekick). He met his future wife at Disney _
Tracey Hart, an executive assistant in strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   And his wealth rose. The 1997 Disney proxy said Nanula was paid
a salary of $632,692, plus a $1.3 million bonus. His exercisable
options had gained about $15 million in value. Options that he lost
upon leaving the company were worth an additional $30 million or
so.
</P>
<P>
   (Starwood has not released details of Nanula's pay package,
including the degree to which he was compensated for what he gave
up, though he has invested about $500,000 in Starwood stock.
Besides nurturing his own holdings, Nanula will now play an
important role in sustaining his friend's wealth; Sternlicht owns
Starwood stock worth about $400 million, plus options worth $80
million at the end of last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives grew to rely on Nanula to add levity to
meetings. If someone proposed an idea that no one liked, Nanula
might break the silence by saying: ``That's a great idea. It would
put us out of business in three days. But that's a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the CFO, or the CEO, you've got to say `no' a lot
without having everybody hate your guts,'' Nanula said. ``You want
them to keep coming up with good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanula built a collection of 50 Disney neckties and appeared to
be settling in for the long haul. He was often mentioned as an
eventual successor to Eisner. ``I never thought a minute about
leaving Disney,'' Nanula said.
</P>
<P>
   But, ever multitasking, Nanula often offered Sternlicht advice _
on everything from takeover tactics to dismissing executives. ``I'm
not good at firing people,'' Sternlicht said. ``When I had to let
somebody go, Richard and I would rehearse what I was going to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   They also helped each other through difficult personal times.
Last year, Sternlicht learned that his youngest son had juvenile
diabetes, and Nanula's twin daughter and son were born 15 weeks
early, weighing only one and a quarter pounds each. (Nanula's
children are now fine, and Sternlicht has joined the board of the
Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.)
</P>
<P>
   As Starwood grew, Sternlicht mentioned the possibility of
turning his friendship with Nanula into a business partnership. But
Nanula politely waved off the idea. When Sternlicht closed in on
the $13.3 billion deal to acquire ITT, however, he raised the issue
again. This time, Nanula had a different answer: He would consider
it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht was certain that his friend would be the best
candidate, even though working so closely together would put their
friendship at risk. But the decision to hire a chief executive
would have to be made by Starwood's directors.
</P>
<P>
   There were other candidates. Buying some of them out of
option-laden contracts, however, would have been too costly. One
even demanded that he be given the chairman's title after a year.
``That's a little overreaching, I'm afraid,'' Sternlicht told him.
</P>
<P>
   The board settled on Nanula, in part because of his skills,
which complemented Sternlicht's, and in part because of the
chemistry between them.
</P>
<P>
   Though they walk into each other's offices at least a dozen
times a day to run through decisions, in the kind of shorthand that
develops between friends, Nanula and Sternlicht are still
adjusting. ``It's just very different having him next to me,''
Sternlicht said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nanula is often on the road, flying in a Gulfstream IV jet
to visit the company's many operations, refining goals for managers
and setting a tone for the company.
</P>
<P>
   He likes meetings with free-wheeling discussions, like those he
had at Harvard and Disney. ``There's no teacher,'' he said, ``just
a bunch of us in the room figuring out what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nanula has little patience for people who are unprepared,
and he will direct a manager to do more homework before setting up
another meeting or phone call with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Wells was that way,'' he said, speaking of Disney's late
president. ``He would simply say, `Go get the answers, and we'll
make the decision when you get them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Nanula calls managers far down the ladder to get
front-line perspective. And he often sends managers handwritten
notes with a simple happy face or frowning face sketched in the
corner, for a quick take on his mood.
</P>
<P>
   This approach, he said, ``takes the edge off a little bit'' _ an
edge that is likely to exist when older executives find themselves
reporting to a thirtysomething boss. But former ITT executives who
are the resident graybeards at Starwood say that, after the first
few weeks, they like working for Nanula.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell by the way he asks questions that he wants to
gather all the facts,'' said Daniel P. Weadock, 59, a special
assistant to the chairman after working for ITT, in one stint as
president of its hotels, for all but one of the years that Nanula
has been alive. ``They do take the input I give them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanula grew up in Pasadena and Santa Rosa, Calif. He held a
number of jobs as a teen-ager, waiting on tables many a summer _
``good, general people training,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His parents said they were at times concerned that Richard had
too many irons in the fire, his schoolwork competing with jobs,
sports and dating.
</P>
<P>
   But Nanula grew into a serious student at Santa Barbara. With
many fellow students pursuing majors in partying, Nanula saw an
opportunity. ``If I was the only one studying,'' he said, ``I could
probably get A-pluses and get into any business school I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he did, though Harvard deferred his acceptance, so he
went to Deloitte, Haskins &AMP; Sells in Atlanta for two years,
becoming a CPA.
</P>
<P>
   Nanula, whose father is white and mother black, said he rarely
encountered racism growing up in mainly white neighborhoods,
perhaps in part because his light skin color made many people think
he was Hawaiian or Egyptian. ``Thankfully, nobody really cared,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   And today, he said, he does not often think about being one of
the few blacks in the highest ranks of corporate America. ``I do
believe in being a good role model,'' he said. ``But I've generally
just operated on doing my job, and race and age and background has
never really played into it very much, so I've just not focused on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, as he waits for his new house in Greenwich, Conn.,
to be renovated, he is focusing on Starwood during long workdays,
though he tries to be at home to help put his children to bed and
spend time with his wife, as well as to see his two golden
retrievers. He generally brings home a briefcase of work for the
weekend. There is not much time to watch even one television set.
</P>
<P>
   He and Sternlicht have talked about working out together again,
playing basketball or taking a ``spinning'' class _ Nanula said he
is a ``gigantic fanatic'' about riding an exercise bike to pounding
music for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't found time to do either one of them yet,'' he said.
``But we'll do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
