<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-GORE-COX     08-07 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore unites Florida Democratic Party
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ In a closed-door meeting Friday with
Vice President Al Gore sitting between them, an emotional Buddy
MacKay finally got the endorsement he so dearly wanted from U.S.
Rep. Alcee Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, whose campaign for governor has been damaged by
bickering among black and white leaders in the Democratic Party,
said the endorsement from Hastings is a major step toward bringing
the party back together and moving his campaign forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings agreed, but he also said Democrats still will have to
prove that they are taking blacks seriously. Hastings, a three-term
congressman and powerful voice in the black community, said more
blacks must be appointed to top party positions and made a part of
campaigns throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   During the hour-long meeting, Lt. Gov. MacKay became emotional
as he talked to a group of about 25 people that included
representatives from the NAACP, seven state House members and
Democratic Party chairman Mitch Ceasar.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay talked about the difficulties the party has faced ever
since the ouster eight months ago of state Rep. Willie Logan of
Opalocka as the first black Democratic House leader. The ouster,
done with little warning, was orchestrated by 31 white House
Democrats and caused a firestorm in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was touched by the fact that many of those in the room
were close friends, MacKay became emotional because, ``I respected
the difficulty of the situation. They were there and I appreciated
it and it was emotional for me, yes. They were doing something that
was hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the meeting ended, Hastings, D-Miramar, said, ``I
don't think the Democratic Party will ever take black people for
granted again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Gore, MacKay, his running mate Rick Dantzler, Hastings,
Gov. Lawton Chiles and other top Democratic leaders spoke at a
``united for victory'' rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no great need for high drama, there is no great need
for looking into the past, we're all here to do one thing and one
thing only, and I'm certainly going to make it clear that I'm
supporting Buddy MacKay and Rick Dantzler,'' Hastings shouted to a
cheering crowd of about 200 at the Fort Lauderdale Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, divisions remain. Some black state lawmakers are angered
by Hastings' attempt to step into the middle of the selection of a
new Democratic House leader to replace Logan. They say the
congressman has no business interfering with state House business.
</P>
<P>
   Since Logan's ouster, Hastings has been one of the loudest
voices of protest. He said the issue ``is not about personality but
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   As the issue festered, Logan began working closely with
Republicans and Democrats began to fear that significant numbers of
black voters would abandon the party. Hastings, in meetings at the
White House with Gore, warned that Democrats risked not only losing
the governor's race but also possibly losing the state in the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   In a front page letter in Friday's edition of the Broward Times,
a widely read black newspaper, state Rep. Josephus Eggelletion Jr.,
who hopes to replace Logan as House leader, sharply criticized
Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged Hastings for attempting to be the sole voice of
black leadership and said he resented Hastings' implication that
Eggelletion and other black leaders ``need your personal permission
and approval regarding the decisions we make in the representation
of our constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the crowd at the rally that he came to Florida to help
unite the party at the urging of Hastings. But whether Hastings can
bring all of the squabbling black Democrats together remained in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gore attended a hurricane preparedness
meeting. He also attended a private money-raising reception that
collected an estimated $200,000 for the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
