<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-INQUIRER-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER SUED BY OWN REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Cipriano, a reporter for The Philadelphia Inquirer, sued
his editor and his newspaper for defamation Friday after the
editor, Robert Rosenthal, was quoted as saying the reporter ``has a
very strong personal point of view and an agenda. ... There were
things that Ralph wrote that we didn't think were truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal's comments came in a June 13 article in The Washington
Post about Cipriano's decision to publish in The National Catholic
Reporter an article about the business practices of the
archdiocese. The article included unpublished reporting that
Cipriano said he had done for The Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which also names the paper's owner, Knight Ridder
Newspapers Inc., as a defendant, chronicles the history of
Cipriano's difficulties with his editors _ in particular the
disagreements over his coverage of the Philadelphia archdiocese and
Anthony Cardinal Bevilacqua.
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, Cipriano, who currently covers neighborhoods in
South Philadelphia, said his editors, under pressure from the
archdiocese and concerned about falling circulation, ``watered
down'' his copy. Later, he said, his city editor told colleagues
``that Cipriano was `biased' and `had an ax to grind,''' the suit
documents said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to Rosenthal was returned by Pamela Browner, the paper's
vice president for business and community relations, who said: ``We
disagree with Ralph because we believe our coverage of the
archdiocese of Philadelphia has been fair, accurate and relevant.
We regret that Ralph has chosen a lawsuit as his means of
addressing the matter of how the Inquirer covers a topic of great
interest to our readers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
