<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Picking the Beasts, Not the Beauties, of the World Wide Web  
   
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The world is full of contests to pick the best. Movies, plays,
books, even Web sites vie for the winners' laurels.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But now the losers of the World Wide Web will have a chance at
their 15 minutes of fame _ or is that infamy _ thanks to the Mud
Brick, a new award dedicated to singling out the world's ugliest
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all being done tongue-in-cheek,'' said Manish Vij,
25-year-old chief executive of NetStudio Corp. ``We're not after
personal pages, but the sites of businesses that should know
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Mud Brick is not so much an independent contest as
a shameless publicity stunt. NetStudio sells software to create
attractive Web graphics. The Berkeley startup hopes to raise its
profile by getting people to name the stinkers of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   To nominate a site for a Mud Brick, e-mail its address to
 &LR; mudbrick &LR; netstudio.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The contest will be judged by NetStudio's staff. The results
will be announced in September, when the Seybold printing and
graphics show comes to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Winners _ or is that losers? _ will get a copy of the $149
NetStudio software, an hour of design consulting time and a
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Feedback loop &LR; : Many Web sites invite visitors to e-mail their
comments to some sort of general address, like
 &LR; feedback &LR; company.com. &LR;  Handling the responses may not be difficult
when you're a startup like NetStudio trying to get attention.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, many Fortune 1000 companies post these general mail
boxes _ then find themselves unprepared for the volume and variety
of the responses they get.
</P>
<P>
   And that means they're missing a huge bet, said Mark Gainey,
president of Kana Communications, a Palo Alto startup that sells
software to sort, route and reply to general delivery e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is raw, unfiltered opinion from customers,'' Gainey said.
``This is what companies pay millions to get from market research
organizations, and here customers are giving it to them, free.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey stumbled into the e-mail response market after he quit
his venture capital job in 1995 to start his own company.
</P>
<P>
   He had intended to sell sporting goods over the Internet, but in
talking to equipment manufacturers, he discovered how they were
handling their general delivery e-mails. ``The president of one
name-brand company would give the feedback e-mails to his
teenaged-daughter, who would mail out replies through her AOL
account,'' he said. ``That's when the light bulb went off.''
</P>
<P>
   He founded Kana in 1996 to help automate the process of replying
to unsolicited e-mail. Several other companies are aimed at the
same niche, including General Interactive in Cambridge, Mass.,
Brightware Inc. in Novato, and Mustang Software in Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Heart of silicon? &LR;  Two weeks ago I reported how venture
capitalists Gib Myers and Bud Colligan are trying to reverse the
valley's skin-flint reputation and stimulate philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, a recent survey done by the Field Research organization,
for the Community Foundation Silicon Valley, indicates they'll have
their hands full, especially when it comes to converting valley
millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   The Field survey looked at the giving habits of 730 individuals
selected at random in Silicon Valley _ an area defined as
stretching from San Jose north to Highway 92 on the Peninsula, and
up to Fremont in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to this scientific survey, Field zeroed in on 160
people in Silicon Valley identified as having more than $1 million
in liquid assets _ net worth minus real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The random sample, which represented the general population,
gave about 2.1 percent of their income to charity. That's on par
with national averages.
</P>
<P>
   The picture wasn't so bright for the 160 millionaires. Nearly
half of that batch gave $2,000 or less to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at another way, if a family with $50,000 in liquid assets
was as tight as some valley millionaires, they'd only donate $100
to charity in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Jay, president of Field Research, cautioned against
drawing too many conclusions from the 160-person sample. She said
it wasn't a scientific sample.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Chu, vice president of the foundation that sponsored the
survey, said diplomatically, ``What it says to us is that,
relatively speaking, we're a more affluent area, but we're not
giving up to our potential.''
</P>
<P>
   She also found a key difference between giving in the valley and
giving in other parts of the country, which suggests that high-tech
stinginess is cureable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elsewhere the church is the center of life, especially
charity,'' she said. ``In Silicon Valley, the workplace is
central.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that changes in CEO behavior could set the example
for all those future stock-option millionaires _ which is exactly
what Myers is trying to do with his Entrepreneurs' Foundation (see &LR; 
www.the-ef.org &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650) 961-2689, fax (650) 961-5023 or e-mail ( &LR; abate &LR; sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
