<SLUG> BC-ANG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Newspapers, Union OK Pact   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
After 11 years of on-again, off-again bargaining, ANG Newspapers
Inc. has struck a tentative labor agreement with the Northern
California Media Workers Guild, which represents editorial staff
such as reporters, photographers and copy editors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The salary terms of the three-year agreement are meager, even by
newspaper standards, but union representatives said reaching any
accord after 11 years is a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ANG Newspapers publishes five dailies in the Bay Area including
the Oakland Tribune, Hayward Daily Review, Tri-Valley Herald, San
Mateo Times and Fremont Argus. It also owns six weeklies on the
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which will be voted on next week by the
220-member ANG bargaining unit, sets mandatory minimum average
salaries that are lower than in the industry as a whole, despite
the high cost of living in Alameda and San Mateo counties.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory pay raises, which will be based on merit, will average
just 1 percent in each of the first two years of the agreement and
2 percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   Managers may opt to pay more, but there is no requirement for
them to do so. Discretionary pay increases by managers have
averaged 3 percent in each of the last two years, but future
increases will depend on the financial health of the business, said
Scott McKibben, ANG's president and publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by no stretch of the imagination an economic incentive
to stick around,'' said Stacey Wells, bargaining unit chair and
city hall reporter for the Oakland Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing most people will be happy with is that it will
bring this (11-year) ennui to a close,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   The guild and ANG have been debating terms of an agreement since
1987, shortly after the company, then called the Alameda Newspaper
Group, was bought by William Dean Singleton's MediaNews Group of
Denver, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The company had not been organized under its previous owner.
</P>
<P>
   When the talks began, ANG offered a contract with $400 per week
minimum salaries. In 1996 it raised that offer to $425 and on
Monday, after several months of work with a federal mediator, the
company went up to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's contract offer was initially rejected by the guild over
another issue, but the differences were resolved and a tentative
deal was struck yesterday, said Erin Tyson Poh, a guild organizer.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the contractual minimum salary will have
little impact, said McKibben. ``There were no people affected by
this agreement that were making as little as that to begin with, so
we felt we might as well move it up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, editorial staff who have worked at the
paper less than six years would receive a minimum salary of $500,
or $26,000 annually, while veterans would be guaranteed at least
$580, or $30,160 per year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ANG agreed that median salaries would hit at least
$550 per week for the first group and $720 for the second. That
translates into annual salaries of $28,600 and $37,440
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the average guild salary for top-scale workers
around the country is $784, or $40,768 per year.
</P>
<P>
   If the contract is ratified, ANG reporters will make about the
same amount as reporters at the Peoria (Ill.) Journal Star.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed contract allows workers to earn time-and-a-half pay
when they work more than eight hours in a day or more than 40 hours
in a week. Some small improvements were made to employees' benefits
package.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the salary, the most important term of the contract
is the requirement for an annual evaluation of each employee to
give the worker a chance to discuss his or her compensation. ``This
will at least give them a foot in the door,'' said Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Some ANG workers have not received a raise in 10 years, said
Poh.
</P>
<P>
   ANG promised to increase its $5.5 million salary pool for
covered employees by 1 percent for each of the next two years and 2
percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its five dailies, ANG owns six free weeklies in
San Mateo County with a combined circulation of 200,000. McKibben
said it will announce an expansion on the Peninsula in about 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   ANG's daily newspapers have a combined paid circulation of
215,000, McKibben said.
</P>
<P>
   ANG's contract with the Bay Area Typographical Union is slated
to expire at the end of this year. McKibben said discussions with
that group ``are moving along nicely.'' None of the company's other
780 employees are subject to outstanding labor contracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
