<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCENE-LEWINSKY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA FRENZY GREETS LEWINSKY'S ARRIVAL AT GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the time Monica Lewinsky arrived at the E.
Barrett Perryman Federal Court House Thursday, the media mob was in
a full froth-at-the-mouth frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   At least 250 journalists, 19 satellite trucks and a
four-story-high cherry-picker carrying a CNN camera surrounded the
building on Pennsylvania Avenue, in the shadow of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The political paparazzi _ many of whom have spent the past 28
weeks chronicling the scandal _ stood guard outside each of five
courthouse entrances, and they snapped into action when a black
sport utility vehicle approached at 8:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in Washington when the House approved the most sweeping
campaign reforms in a quarter-century, when a congressional
committee voted to hold the attorney general in contempt for the
first time in history, and the nation inched closer to a
confrontation with Iraq _ the media's attention, and so the
nation's, was focused on the secret testimony of the president's
alleged paramour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're turning onto 14th!'' ``Looks like she'll go in the
Pennsylvania Avenue side.'' ``No, they're headed for the Third
Street entrance,'' came the cackling over scores of walkie-talkies.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, wearing a blue pantsuit, ignored the press horde that
was kept 100 feet away by police, gave a hug to Sydney Hoffman, a
member of her legal team, shrugged her shoulders and went inside
for a day of private testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Her public appearance in the courthouse driveway lasted less
than 20 seconds. Nevertheless, the crowd outside spent much of the
next 81/2 hours discussing it _ much of it on live television.
Several networks carried live coverage of a man sitting in his
Toyota sport utility vehicle, waiting to take Lewinsky away from
the courthouse once she finally emerged shortly after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It is . . . something stupid,'' said Maryse Burgot, a French
television reporter who had arrived this week from Paris to cover
the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   In her thick accent, Burgot recalled how she had been dispatched
to Oklahoma City after the horrific bombing three years ago and was
stunned by the number of reporters and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the same thing,'' she said. ``I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther down Pennsylvania Avenue at the White House, officials
tried hard to appear uninterested. As Lewinsky's testimony began,
President Clinton was in the Rose Garden celebrating the fifth
anniversary of the gun-control measure known as the Brady Bill.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to taunt the media when he looked up from his notes
and said: ``There has been another development today that because
of this opportunity, I feel I have to comment on.'' He went on to
criticize House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., over proposed tax
cuts, to the disappointment of reporters, who shouted questions the
instant he stopped speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, are you concerned about Lewinsky testifying
today? Are you sticking with your story, your denials?'' they
yelled.
</P>
<P>
   But the president ignored the questions, and a military band
began playing ``The Stars and Stripes Forever'' at top volume,
drowning out &UR;  &LR; even the most persistent interrogators.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a briefing, deputy press secretary Barry Toiv said he
was not aware that the president was paying any attention to the
testimony, which reportedly included graphic details of sexual acts
between Clinton and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has not expressed any views to us on this,
except we know that he does agree with us, and probably all
Americans, that if this means ... we're coming to the end of this
four-year, over $40 million investigation, then that would be a
good thing,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers preparing for their August recess could not avoid the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sick of hearing about it,'' House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., said when asked at a news conference. ``I think
most people are. I think we've had an overdose.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif, complained that the focus on
Clinton's alleged indiscretions distracts from important policy
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try very hard for it not to, but it clearly does,''
Tauscher said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the courthouse _ which some reporters dubbed ``Monica
Beach'' _ tourists and publicity seekers marveled at the scene
before becoming part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   George Hancock, a 32-year old from Bowling Green, Ky., carried a
sign reading ``Good Luck Monica.'' He told dozens of reporters the
story of how he was on his way to Niagara Falls when he heard
Lewinsky would be testifying and stopped by ``to let her know that
at least one person wishes her well.''
</P>
<P>
   With little hard news to report, the media focused on details.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a rumor spread that Lewinsky's spokeswoman, Judy
Smith, had gone to the courthouse cafeteria for two jelly
doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said they were both for her,'' one reporter explained.
</P>
<P>
   When a former federal prosecutor descended the courthouse steps,
she was mobbed by reporters who thought perhaps she had some inside
information. She didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to do an interview with Inside Edition,'' said
Cynthia Alksne.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on and the sun grew warm, one technician fell
asleep in a chair with a book on his lap. He was immediately
surrounded by photographers, who sought out angles to capture the
sleeping journalist with the courthouse in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The book on his lap was entitled: ``No Safe Place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
