<SLUG> BC-TENN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RURAL TENNESSEE RACE, YOUTH PREVAILS OVER AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Youth prevailed in Coffee County, Tenn., on Thursday as
18-year-old Nathan Cunningham defeated 81-year-old Fayna Walker in
an election for the county commission that gained national
attention because of the 63-year gap between the candidates' ages.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, a Republican who graduated from high school this
spring, said he was thrilled by his 282-187 victory over Mrs.
Walker, a Democrat who has served on the commission for 23 years.
``It feels great,'' he said. ``I believe people were ready for a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Mrs. Walker, Cunningham attributed his success to
opposing property-tax increases in Coffee County, a farming
community of about 40,000 some 65 miles southeast of Nashville. But
Mrs. Walker said that other factors might have played a part,
including her age and the size of Cunningham's large family.
</P>
</TEXT>
