<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDS-CEO-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDS SAYS CHIEF IS DEPARTING WITH $38.6 MILLION IN BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, N.J., Texas)  (js) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Electronic Data Systems said Friday that the retirement
of Lester Alberthal Jr. as chairman and chief executive would cost
the company $38.6 million in benefits _ a cost the company defended
by citing his 30-year career at EDS and his agreement to never join
any competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, shares of EDS rose $5.125, or nearly 14 percent, to
$41.8125, in heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Alberthal announced his retirement after the stock market closed
on Thursday under pressure from board members and major
shareholders dismayed by the company's loss of its former
leadership in the computer services industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with company managers Friday morning,
Alberthal said the decision to retire was his own. But the board
signaled its desire for change by announcing that the next chief
would come from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Alberthal's retirement package _ costing a nickel a share after
taxes _ brought a protest from the California Public Employees
Retirement System, among the company's loudest shareholder critics.
``You'd have to question the wisdom of offering this retirement
arrangement when his leadership has not created a lot of value for
shareholders,'' said Brad Pacheco, a fund spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   EDS refused to break down the expense other than to say that it
included the vesting of stock benefits, a five-year consulting
arrangement and pension payments. Last year, Alberthal was paid
$850,000, but received more than $12.9 million in stock benefits
based on the company's 1996 performance. Under current formulas,
company documents say, Alberthal is eligible for retirement
benefits of about $700,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Stubbs Norwood, a company spokeswoman, noted that at age
54, Alberthal was still in his peak earning years. ``This,'' she
said, referring to the retirement agreement, ``precludes him from
engaging in a wide range of opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts welcomed the news of Alberthal's retirement while
adding that finding a prominent, qualified successor will be no
easy job. ``I'm not saying they should promote someone
internally,'' said Susan Scrupski, a partner in ARC Consulting of
Tinton Falls, N.J. ``I'm saying they should look for someone who
has knowledge of information services. It's a very special
executive, and they're in short supply.''
</P>
<P>
   EDS needs someone able to reassure employees and investors
alike, analysts said. ``They need a Lou Gerstner,'' said one
substantial shareholder, referring to IBM's chief executive and the
turnaround he achieved. ``But he's got a job.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp.'s pension fund, EDS' largest shareholder by
far with a 25.7 percent stake, said Friday that it would sell as
much as 8 percent of those holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would capitalize both on Friday's gains and on the lift
from news that at the close of trading Monday it will be included
in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
