<SLUG> BC-NY-PHONE-STRIKE-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE WORKERS IN NEW YORK STAGE WALKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Va.)  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of unionized telephone workers shut down
directory assistance in New York on Friday as they staged a
two-and-a-half-hour wildcat walkout aimed at pressuring Bell
Atlantic to help avoid a strike at 12:01 a.m. Sunday, when their
contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   Walking off the job Friday afternoon, the workers gave millions
of consumers a taste of the inconveniences that would be suffered
in a full-fledged strike. The workers held raucous demonstrations
at phone company buildings in Manhattan, the Bronx and upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Workers shouted ``No contract, no work,'' and some occasionally
engaged in pushing matches with police officers, who tried to keep
them behind barricades to prevent them from impeding traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting a strike, Jose Navarro, a telephone service worker
from Brooklyn, said, ``We have to use all means necessary to
protect our job security.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he felt threatened because Bell Atlantic had moved
work once done by union employees to nonunion subsidiaries, a
practice known as double-breasting.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said that double-breasting was the main issue in
the talks between Bell Atlantic and two unions representing 85,000
workers. The two sides continued their talks Friday in New York
City and Washington in an effort to avert a strike that would
affect phone service from Virginia to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working hard to reach an agreement before the current
contract expires,'' said John Bonomo, a phone company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the two unions _ the Communications Workers of
America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers _
said there had been progress in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been progress in concept, but there are still
specifics to work out,'' said Jeffrey Miller, a spokesman for the
communications union workers. ``We want to see the exact contract
language proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   While the strike would not interrupt normal phone service, it
could create serious delays for consumers who want to use directory
assistance, make collect calls or talk with business
representatives. It would also cause delays in repairing telephone
service and installing new lines. A strike would not eliminate all
such service, however, because managers would do some of the work
now done by union members.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Friday's work stoppage, many callers who sought
directory assistance were greeted with busy signals. There were
also major delays for callers who sought to make operator-assisted
calls in the Bell Atlantic area. The work stoppage ran from 2:30
p.m. to 5 p.m., and directory assistance was again working smoothly
when the workers returned.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued during the stoppage, the company said,
``We are doing everything possible to minimize the impact on our
customers.'' Bell Atlantic added, ``This action will not impact
contract negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   While demonstrating in front of the Bell Atlantic building at
42nd Street and Avenue of the Americas, Kareemah Abdullah, a
service technician, said: ``We have to stick together. We're
worried about Bell Atlantic subcontracting out work to nonunion
places. Bell Atlantic has a lot of money and doesn't want to share
it with us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In separate negotiations, the communications union reached a
tentative agreement with Southern New England Telecommunications,
which provides phone service to almost all of Connecticut. The
union had threatened a strike against that company beginning Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 6,300 SNET workers, applauded the
agreement, under which employees would no longer have to pay for
health insurance and would receive an 11 percent wage increase over
the 32-month contract.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Miglio, SNET's chairman, said in a statement: ``We're
very pleased that we have a tentative agreement. We have good,
hard-working people who deserve a contract that recognizes their
significant contribution to the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The communications union workers faulted Bell Atlantic for
moving work long done by unionized business representatives to a
nonunion subsidiary in Norfolk, Va., called Bell Atlantic Plus. In
addition, union officials complained that the company had set up
another nonunion arm to install sophisticated lines that give
business customers high-speed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do here is smash double-breasting in its
infancy,'' one union official, who insisted on anonymity. ``If we
do that, this will be an important, trend-setting contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials have defended using the nonunion
subsidiaries, saying that they enable the company to increase
profits by using a work force that has lower wages and is not
hamstrung by union work rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
