<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CUBAN-CIGARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ILLEGAL SMOKE FOR THE '90S, FROM CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Friday night, on day three of the great federal
crackdown against Manhattan's outlaw Cuban-cigar aficionados, a
cigar bar seemed just the place to puff awhile and wait for the
smoke to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dragging those people off just for smoking Cubans, it's
absurd,'' said John McFadden, an investment banker who was savoring
an Astral cigar and gesturing in the general direction of his
companion, Joseph Avantario.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole Cuban thing was topic one at lunch today,'' said
Avantario, lighting up another of McFadden's Astrals. ``Just about
every U.S. senator smokes Cuban cigars. So why not go after them?''
</P>
<P>
   They were enjoying a predinner puff Friday night with a friend,
Janine Johnson, in the Cigar Bar at Carnegie Bar and Books at 156
West 56th St., a cynosure of the smokily comfortable, clubby little
world of the upscale Manhattan cigar worshipper.
</P>
<P>
   True, it was the Friday night kickoff to a summer weekend, and
many high-end cigarophiles had already headed for the Hamptons or
were firing up entirely legal Cuban Cohibas in the hills of
Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, 35 diehards were breathing cigar smoke, sipping
cocktails and listening to light jazz in the mahogany-and-maroon
bar, with its bronze chandeliers and showcases filled with
Partagas, H. Upmann and Dunhill cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Subi Gurge, a financial consultant, was puffing a Honduran
Padron as he sat with 11 colleagues under the bar's ornate
stairway. He was ruminating annoyedly about ``that ridiculous
embargo against Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the world doesn't support it,'' he said, ``and it
isn't effective anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, most of the smokers said they were well aware
of the news that on Wednesday, federal officials charged the
operators of an upscale restaurant and a private club in Manhattan
with illicitly selling Cuban cigars to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents with search warrants seized hundreds of boxes of
cigars from the humidors of the Patroon restaurant on East 46th
Street and the Racquet and Tennis Club on Park Avenue. On Thursday,
prosecutors charged four investors and businessmen, including two
chief executives, with buying contraband Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, two more cigar smokers were drawn into the federal
investigation, bringing to nine those arrested. Michael Dana, 38, a
managing director in the investment banking division at Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, and Jeffrey Kelter, 44, president of a
real-estate investment company in suburban Philadelphia, were
arraigned in federal court in Manhattan and released on their own
recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enforcement seems so selective,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``Why
single these people out from all the people who have Cuban
cigars?''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
high-profile Cuban cigar prosecutions were a deterrent that not
only responded to violations of federal law (since owning them is a
felony) but also supported U.S. foreign policy and helped to deny
economic benefits to Cuba, since the state manages cigar
production.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gurge's colleagues, who gave his name only as Eric, said:
``Americans shouldn't smoke Cubans, because that's supporting the
Cuban government,'' he said. ``And they're evading paying taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Avantario, an investment banker who lives in Chappaqua, said
Cuban Cohibas, Montecristos and Romeo y Julietas are ubiquitous.
``If you want them, you can get them,'' he said. ``They even hide
them under the ribbons of Dominican cigars.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few in the bar would admit to having gone Cuban. ``I did
have one Cuban cigar,'' said Peter Genet, a real-estate consultant,
``but I didn't inhale.''
</P>
<P>
   His companions in the book nook near the door, Robert and Marie
Guarnieri, rolled their eyes as they laughed. ``I had my first and
only Cuban cigar on my wedding night in Sweden,'' said Guarnieri, a
technology consultant who lives in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was legal!'' Mrs. Guarnieri said.
</P>
<P>
   At the ornate mahogany bar, Eric Lightner, the manager,
explained to a visitor that ``people ask all the time for Cubans,''
he said. ``What we tell them is the truth. We don't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``many customers come in with their own Cubans to smoke
them here,'' said Tara Oniki, the cocktail waitress. ``They aren't
worried by all this. They don't take this seriously. In fact, the
only reason they smoke Cubans is for show. You know why I think
they smoke them? Because they're illegal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
