<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RENT-IMPACT-440&AMP;AD     08-07 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RENT-IMPACT-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 1997 CHANGE IN RENT LAWS PRODUCES A BOOM IN APARTMENT
DEREGULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since New York lawmakers scaled back rent regulations
last summer, at least three times the number of apartments in New
York City have been deregulated under the new laws as under the old
ones, a new study has determined.
</P>
<P>
   The rise _ from about 1,000 a year to more than 3,500 _ has
occurred almost exclusively in Manhattan, the study found, and is
higher than either landlords or tenant groups predicted during the
wrenching battle over rent laws.
</P>
<P>
   And it indicates that with the economy booming and real estate
prices soaring, landlords in prime neighborhoods have taken full
advantage of measures they won in Albany to bring about
deregulation by increasing rents sharply when some apartments turn
over.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new laws, a rent-stabilized apartment becomes
deregulated _ meaning the landlord can charge whatever the market
will bear _ when its rent under the stabilization rules reaches
$2,000 after a vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey by the city's Rent Guidelines Board, the first
detailed look at the city's housing market since the new laws were
passed, also found that while rents had risen steeply for newly
occupied apartments south of 96th Street in Manhattan, the new laws
appeared to have had only a small impact elsewhere, as many
economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a tale of two cities,'' said Edward Hochman,
chairman of the rent board. ``What it shows is that in many parts
of the city, regulated rents already may be at or approaching
market levels.''
</P>
<P>
   From June 1997 to last March, when the study was conducted, the
median increase for newly rented apartments protected by rent laws
in so-called core Manhattan was 21 percent, far outstripping an
estimated 12 percent rise the year before the changes. Citywide,
the increase was 12 percent, after an 8 percent increase the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an average renter south of 96th Street whose old
rent was $1,500, paid $1,815 after moving.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, by comparison, such rents rose by an average of 5
percent, the same as the year before; in Queens, rents rose 8
percent, after a 5 percent increase the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But the study warns that even though increases remained
relatively stable outside Manhattan, working-class and poor
families appear to be having a harder time finding apartments they
can afford.
</P>
<P>
   For those earning the median income for families in
rent-stabilized housing _ $26,797 _ about 39 percent of newly
occupied apartments were considered affordable. A year ago, half
the newly occupied apartments were considered affordable, which,
according to the government, means that the family paid 30 percent
of its income or less for the apartment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And advocates for tenants warn that the problem will grow more
severe more quickly as a result of less stringent rent protections.
``Even though you may not be seeing bigger increases immediately in
those neighborhoods, it is going to happen,'' said Michael McKee,
policy director for the New York State Tenants and Neighbors
Coalition, ``because people will be priced out of part of the city
and pressures will grow in other neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   But some landlords contend that the survey is the first clear
demonstration that only Manhattan is truly affected by rent
protections. In most other neighborhoods, they say, market forces
already prevail and rents will rise at slow, predictable rates
while landlords will continue to be burdened with the bureaucracy
of rent regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that the whole angry debate last year was a
waste of time,'' said Dan Margulies, executive director of the
Community Housing Improvement Program, a trade association for
apartment building owners. ``Things have changed very little for
most owners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
