<HEADER>
A4075 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     08-07 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHISTICATED TERRORIST GROUPS SUSPECTED IN EMBASSY ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to reorganize, trim, reword lede and mention Albania
specifically in graf 8.)  
 (See also AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-SCENE, AFRICA-SECURITY,
AFRICA-VICTIMS)  
(lh) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Administration officials said the attacks on two
U.S. embassies in East Africa only minutes apart Friday probably
were carried out by one of a small number of sophisticated
terrorist groups presumed to have attacked U.S. installations in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ordered teams of FBI agents, medical military
specialists and explosives experts to leave immediately for Africa
to track down the bombers and aid the victims. Although few
terrorism investigations overseas have ever borne fruit, Clinton
vowed to bring the bombers to justice.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the State Department, Under Secretary
Thomas Pickering said it was too early to single out suspects in
the bombing or to speculate about why they had chosen to carry out
the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find them, we'll ask them,'' he said. ``I don't
believe at this stage that we are reading anything special into the
choice of these until we get further down the investigative
process. I don't have an answer. Terrorists tend to be
unpredictable, and there may be some of that in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was reported to be rushing
home from Italy, where she was to have attended the weekend wedding
of her chief spokesman, James Rubin. She said in a statement that
the administration ``will spare no effort to use all means at our
disposal to track down and punish the perpetrators of these
outrageous acts.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. intelligence official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that based on early circumstantial evidence, the
investigators were focusing on followers of Osama bin Laden, a
multimillionaire Saudi-born financier who has sworn to wage a holy
war on the United States and its interests abroad. The U.S.
official declined to describe the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Laden and a group of extremist Muslim clerics
called on their followers to kill Americans. He is considered a
prime suspect in a 1996 terrorist bombing of an American apartment
complex in Saudi Arabia in which 19 U.S. airmen were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said there were also suspicions that
the attacks in East Africa may have been carried out by the Holy
War organization in Egypt, an Islamic extremist group that warned
earlier this week of reprisals against the United States over its
purported involvement in the extradition to Egypt of three of its
members who were arrested in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the early hours of this, and it's too early to finger
anybody,'' said another senior administration official, cautioning
against speculation about the identity of the bombers. ``We're
looking at the usual suspects. And this time, the usual suspects
may be to blame.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States said that within hours of the bombings Friday,
two teams made up of agents from the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and other government anti-terrorist experts had been
been gathered in Washington and ordered to fly from Andrews Air
Force Base to East Africa: one team bound for Nairobi, the Kenyan
capital, the other for Dar es Salaam, the Tanzanian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon sent a C-141 cargo plane with a surgical team and
medical supplies from Ramstein Air Base in Germany to Nairobi. A
separate anti-terrorism squad of 40 marines was being flown to
Nairobi from Saudi Arabia, where they are temporarily based.
</P>
<P>
   As the first teams of U.S. investigators were leaving for East
Africa, President Clinton, who was awakened at 5:30 a.m. with news
of the bombings, condemned them as ``cowardly acts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These acts of terrorist violence are abhorrent, they are
inhuman,'' the president said, interrupting a bill-signing ceremony
in the Rose Garden to comment on the bombings. ``We will use all
the means at our disposal to bring those responsible to justice no
matter what or how long it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ordered a tightening of security at U.S.
embassies and other diplomatic installations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Police hurriedly erected barricades in front of several U.S.
embassies elsewhere in Africa, out of fear that terrorists might
strike again on the continent. The Ugandan government ordered
traffic police in Kampala, the capital, to move vehicles from the
street in front of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said that there was no specific threat to
the embassies in Kenya or Tanzania immediately before the bombings.
``There was no telephone call to the embassies minutes before,
saying something was going to happen, no,'' said Patrick Kennedy,
assistant secretary of state for administration.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said suspicion was falling on Laden in
part because of the location of the terrorist attacks Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Laden, who has been described by the State Department as ``one
of the most significant financial sponsors of Islamic extremist
activities in the world,'' has close ties to Muslim extremist
groups in Sudan, which borders Kenya to the north, and lived in
Sudan before relocating to Afghanistan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long had strained ties with the Sudanese
government, which it has accused of harboring terrorist groups, and
has moved most of its embassy employees out of Sudan to Nairobi,
where they work out of the embassy building that was bombed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say that Laden sends tens of millions of dollars
through Islamic banks and charities to terrorist organizations,
militant groups and extremist political movements based in Sudan,
Algeria, Egypt, Lebanon and the Philippines, as well as providing
support for Jihad, which is also suspected of involvement in the
attacks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a newspaper in Kuwait quoted Ayman al-Zawahri, a
physician and leader of Holy War, as renewing his call for attacks
against American interests. The newspaper said Zawahri was then
living in Afghanistan with Laden, who has been stripped of his
Saudi citizenship by the government in Riyadh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
