<SLUG> BC-WILDWOOD-CASINO-CHAOS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSTACLES LOOM FOR PROPOSED INDIAN CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(af) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 20 years, the New Jersey beach resort of Wildwood has been a
town seething with envy. As hotels and shops along its boardwalk
have tried to survive on the income they made three months out of
the year, its more famous neighbor to the north _ Atlantic City _
has used its neon-splashed casinos to become a year-round mecca for
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wildwood is fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Wildwood's city commissioners voted 2 to 1 to
approve the transfer of a 2.5-acre municipal parking lot to the
Delaware Tribe of western Oklahoma. In return, the Delawares would
operate an Indian casino on the lot.
</P>
<P>
   But this plan would run afoul of federal laws that give the
state a deciding voice in the creation of new Indian land, a
federal Indian Affairs spokesman said Friday. And Gov. Christine
Todd Whitman's administration has been opposed to the city's
gambling plan for years.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Mayor Fred Wager of Wildwood said Friday that he
believed the city could skirt the governor's opposition by limiting
the gambling to so-called Class II gaming, which includes bingo
and, he said, keno poker and off-track betting.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he hoped that the low-level gambling casino would
eventually grow into a full-fledged Class III casino, of the type
operated by the Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation in Ledyard, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for all of it, but we're willing to start out
with a Class II casino, where you have bingo and keno poker and
horse racing, and move to a Class III casino later,'' Wager said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city could do this without federal approval because
Class II gambling was not regulated by the federal Indian Gaming
Regulatory Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as our checking into it, we don't need the state or the
federal government's permission to do that,'' the mayor went on.
``I don't know if there's a way they can stop us, but the
information we have is that we don't need their permission.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Rex Hackler, a spokesman for the Interior Department's
Bureau of Indian Affairs, said that federal rules governing the
tribal ownership of land, and not the type of gambling the city
envisions, stand in the way of an Indian Casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Indian gaming has to take place on Indian land, and just
because the town of Wildwood gave this land to the Delawares does
not make it Indian land,'' Hackler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Class II gaming cannot take place until the Indians have
taken the land in trust, which basically means that the governor
must give her blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delawares, who were compelled to move to Oklahoma in the
last century, signed an agreement with Wildwood in 1995 to operate
the casino. Larry Snake, the tribal chairman, said at the time that
the tribe had had no plans to operate a casino until Wildwood
merchants got in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe filed suit for the land in state court in March,
citing archeological evidence of Indian habitation near Wildwood.
Jeffrey April, the tribe's New Jersey lawyer, said in the spring
that the litigation was intended to expedite a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the parking lot over to the Delawares would settle the
tribe's claim to all of Wildwood as its ancestral lands. The tribe
has not formally agreed to the settlement under which they would
get the casino lot and the city's backing for a casino, Wager said.
But, the mayor noted, the council still had to take the legal steps
authorizing the transfer before a deal could be made. April could
not be reached by phone Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the Wildwood casino would not serve alcohol, or
offer any dining more lavish than a food court, so that local
businesses would benefit directly from the crowds they expect the
casino would draw.
</P>
<P>
   Wildwood expects to earn more than $8 million a year in new
revenues from the casino, as well as employment for 600 to 1,000
residents _ a lot of jobs for a town of 5,000. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're not looking to compete with Atlantic City. We're not
looking to put 12 casinos in here, and we're not looking for the
high rollers,'' Wager said. ``We're looking for a family
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the New Jersey Constitution, casino gambling is legal only
in Atlantic City. The attorney general, Peter G. Verniero, repeated
through a spokesman on Thursday that the state was opposed to the
creation of an Indian tribal casino at Wildwood.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials were not clear Friday which state agency, if
any, would govern Class II gambling in New Jersey. Bingo and
similar games of chance are regulated by the Department of Consumer
Affairs, but a consumer affairs spokeswoman said her department
oversees only charity games.
</P>
<P>
   Several municipalities and developers across the country have in
the past tried to create Indian reservations out of private or
municipal land for the purposes of creating a casino, but without
success, and the federal government has never approved a grant of
land to a tribe outside its home state, said Stephanie Hanna, a
spokeswoman for Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would have to happen is that they would have to establish
reservation land in New Jersey and then enter into a compact with
the state of New Jersey for Class III casino gambling,'' Ms. Hanna
said. ``There has to be some established legal record that gave
them that land.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Hackler of the Bureau of Indian Affairs, approval
to take land in trust in order to create an Indian casino is a rare
occurrence, even with full state backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the entire history of the BIA we have taken only one piece
of land into trust for gaming purposes,'' Hackler said, ``and that
was in Duluth, Minn., and that came with the blessing of virtually
everybody involved, including the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackler said, ``We wish the town of Wildwood the best in
developing its economy, but it isn't going to happen this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
