<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-N     08-07 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR INTENSIFIES CRITICISM OF PLANNED YOUTH MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said in a radio interview
Thursday night that the public should know that the organizers of
the planned Million Youth March have said they plan to bring
violent gangs into the city during the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not talking about a million kids,'' Giuliani said in an
interview on WCBS' ``Ask the Mayor'' program, referring to the
march's primary organizer, Khalid Abdul Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, a former senior aide to Louis Farrakhan, minister of
the Nation of Islam, wants to hold the rally in Harlem on Sept. 5.
Organizers are billing it as a show of strength and unity among
black teen-agers from across the United States. It is patterned
after the 1995 Million Man March in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the city has denied Muhammad a permit to hold the march on
that date or on Harlem's Malcolm X Boulevard, citing traffic
concerns. City officials offered two locations they said could
accommodate large crowds: Randalls Island and Van Cortlandt Park in
the Bronx. They also said that Sept. 19 would be a more appropriate
date for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad has called that later date and the locations the city
has offered ``totally unacceptable.'' He has also vowed to hold the
event on Sept. 5 in Harlem or in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, as a
``direct confrontation with the Jews of that area.''
</P>
<P>
   In his radio remarks Thursday night, Giuliani called it ``a
shame'' that the news media had not reported what he considered the
most vicious of Muhammad's threats: to bring gang members from
across the country to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference last week, Muhammad told reporters that
``if cooler heads don't prevail, there are obviously two forces
that are going to clash here on Saturday, Sept. 5.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We are prepared to bring the youth here. We are
prepared on that day, with angry youth, some who are gang members,
Crips, Bloods, Vice Lords, gangster disciples, some who are from
the gangsta rap culture and the hip-hop culture in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Malik Zulu Shabazz, a lawyer representing march organizers, said
that Muhammad, who was on a plane en route to Africa Friday, had
invited ``the gang members, along with the best and the brightest
in young black America'' to help forge a truce among the gangs.
Shabazz said the mayor's lack of sensitivity toward Muhammad's plan
had ``proven that he cares little about the concerns of the black
community of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   On the radio program, Giuliani also assailed other comments by
Muhammad. He said it was silly to believe _ as Muhammad had
asserted _ that Jews and other whites working for the mayor were
secretly responsible for the difficulties march organizers were
having with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the city's rationale, the mayor said: ``It's not
going to be a million people, but they are talking about a million
people. You can't go into a residential community in the city with
a million people and have a march. You're going to destroy the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor added that Muhammad was ``filled with hatred, anger,
viciousness about the Jews, about Catholics, about the pope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
