A4175 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     08-07 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
McIVER TO MISS COWBOYS-RAIDERS PRESEASON GAME 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The strange details surrounding the
dorm-room episode involving the Cowboys' Everett McIver might never
be made public. But Michael Irvin, one of the players in this
mystery, said yesterday that he and McIver should have no problems
peacefully coexisting this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no animosity between us,'' Irvin said. ``Y'all cut
that out, the rumors of us not getting along. Me and Everett are
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing between Michael and Everett in the past and
candidly, there is nothing between them today,'' Jones said. ``They
have a lot of respect for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the case. Yet whatever happened during the July 29
``horseplay'' incident, in which McIver sustained a deep cut on his
neck, has kept him from being in game shape. He is expected to miss
tonight's preseason game against the Oakland Raiders at Texas
Stadium, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   McIver ran laps with strength coach Joe Juraszek yesterday and
left before the afternoon practice was over without comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been given a clean bill of health,'' Jones said. ``But
we don't want to take any risks that might involve him pulling (a
muscle), or him not being in shape. This has nothing to do with his
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver's absence will let coach Chan Gailey give Flozell Adams a
long look at right guard. Adams has been the club's most impressive
rookie this summer, and yesterday Gailey said Adams is already good
enough to be a starter in this league at either guard or tackle.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently, Adams' development will not cost McIver his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that Everett has played well enough, and he
shouldn't be penalized because he has lost time,'' Jones said. ``He
is one of our smartest players. Of all our guys who might miss some
time, he's probably one who could make it up better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   There are others, however, who are fighting for starting jobs
tonight. Gailey will get a second look at the players in several
training-camp battles. Ernie Mills and Billy Davis are the primary
contenders for the No. 2 wide receiver spot. Omar Stoutmire, Kenny
Wheaton, and George Teague are battling for the starting free
safety job.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey might also get his first look at cornerback Deion
Sanders, who missed the last preseason game and the contact portion
of Thursday's scrimmage with the Raiders because he was not fully
recovered from off-season ankle surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Gailey would like to build cohesiveness among
his starters, who dominated the scrimmage against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased, but we've got a long way to go,'' Gailey said.
``We need every bit of the remaining opportunities we have to
practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
