<HEADLINE>
COMING CHANGES TO ALUMINUM BATS ALARM A MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., Kan.)   (af)  
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the NCAA apparently on the verge of ordering significant
changes in the way aluminum bats are constructed, a major bat
manufacturer announced Friday that it had filed a $267 million
pre-emptive lawsuit against the collegiate governing body.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges an unlawful restraint of trade by the National
Collegiate Athletic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Easton Sports, which has headquarters in Van
Nuys, Calif., came one day after the NCAA's baseball rules
committee, citing safety concerns and mushrooming scores,
recommended that the size and weight specifications of aluminum
bats be altered to reduce their potency.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the committee recommended that the batted-ball
exit velocity of aluminum bats be reduced from 113 miles per hour
to 93. To do so, it wants the maximum diameter of the barrel of
aluminum bats reduced by one-eighth of an inch and the weight in
the length-to-weight ratios of the bats increased.
</P>
<P>
   If the recommendation is approved by the NCAA's executive
committee at a meeting next Wednesday in Chicago, the next question
would be when it would take effect. The baseball rules committee
wants the change to be enacted on Jan. 1, 1999, in time for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is that timing that has raised alarm at Easton and led to
the filing of the suit in the U.S. District Court in Kansas City,
Kan., near NCAA headquarters in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes the legal action will keep any rules change
from taking effect that quickly. The company estimated it would
lose $267 million if the rules change takes place in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to let them know that this is a serious change,'' said
Jim Easton, the chairman of Easton Sports, which is one of the two
biggest manufacturers of aluminum bats. The other is Louisville
Slugger, and together the two companies produce about 40 percent of
the 500,000 aluminum bats manufactured annually in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA wants the bats to be different, so be it, Easton
said. But the timing, he said, has to be realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Easton, whose company also makes hockey sticks and bicycle
tubing, said half of next year's bat orders had already been
shipped to colleges or are ready to be shipped. He said if the bat
specifications were changed next week, his company would face the
difficult task of retooling all of its bat orders at the same time
that the other bats were rendered obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA first approved use of aluminum bats in 1974, and their
attractiveness is their relative durability _ two to three years
for the average bat _ in comparison to wooden bats.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA is concerned that balls are coming off aluminum
bats too fast and that serious injuries could occur. It is also
concerned about out-of-control offensive rampages, such as the
record 35 runs in the championship game of this year's College
World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
