A4195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TREASURY-BILLS-N     08-07 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TREASURY-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BITE-SIZE TREASURY BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   There is no safer investment than a Treasury bill. But for
nearly three decades, the government has refused to make such safe
investments available to those with less than $10,000 to invest. It
is good that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has decided to end
that practice.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for discriminating against small investors were
never very good, but they vanished years ago. The policy was
adopted in 1970 out of fear that small savers would seek the higher
yields then available from the government rather than the lower
rates paid by banks and savings and loan associations. The Federal
Reserve's infamous Regulation Q in those days limited the rates
banks could pay, a move that supposedly kept mortgages affordable
but in reality assured that mortgage money would dry up when market
interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with next Monday's auction of three- and six-month
Treasury bills, the minimum investment in Treasury bills will be
returned to $1,000, where it was before the 1970 change. The
minimum for two- and three-year Treasury notes is being reduced
from $5,000 to $1,000, which had always been the limit for
longer-term Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury also announced improvements in its Treasury Direct
program, which lets investors buy securities directly from the
government, avoiding commissions. Beginning next month, investors
will be able to buy such securities through the Internet. Telephone
purchases will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Once those improvements are up and running, the Treasury should
consider reducing the minimum investments for Treasury securities
even further, at least to $500 and perhaps lower. There is no
reason that such safe investments should be denied to people with
relatively little to invest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
