McCULLOUGH IS CLEARED TO JOIN TROJANS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC football recruit Sultan McCullough was granted
his academic eligibility by the NCAA Clearinghouse on Friday and
expected to join the Trojans' training camp today.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, a tailback from Muir High School, was forced to take
a summer class to meet NCAA eligibility requirements. He is
expected to compete with returning players Chad Morton and Malaefou
MacKenzie for playing time at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes likely to join team: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes is
expected to be available for Thursday's practice after striking a
plea bargain arrangement with the Lodi district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes will appear in court Wednesday and plead guilty to a
reduced misdemeanor count for writing bad checks. Hayes is expected
to pay about $8,500 in damages and receive probation.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes had originally faced three felony counts. USC's official
position has been that Hayes could be admitted to the university as
long as he was not guilty of felony charges.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot, 200-pound wide receiver, Hayes is considered one of
USC's impact recruits. He started two years at San Jose State,
leading the Spartans in receiving both seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback added to roster: USC has added Chad Pierson, a 6-2,
220-pound fullback from Oxnard High. Pierson was recruited by many
Pac-10 schools last year, but only recently passed his Scholastic
Assessment Test. He will be on a full scholarship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT &LR;      08-07 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA LOOKS LIKE LAST ANGRY MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Mike Piazza is not saying much these days. He does not
need to. The body language says it all, especially the scowl.
</P>
<P>
   Scowl and all, Piazza was in the starting lineup Friday night as
the Mets opened a nine-game trip with a weekend series against the
Colorado Rockies at Coors Field. Asked before the game if he was
having any fun at all, Piazza simply said, ``I'm having a blast,''
and walked away, bat in hand, to take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident that seems to have dampened Piazza's
enthusiasm for New York occurred at Shea Stadium Thursday
afternoon, after he was removed from behind the plate in the eighth
inning during a game in which the Mets led the San Francisco Giants
by a run.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine replaced Piazza as part of a double
switch when he sent for Greg McMichael from the bullpen, Valentine
later said the move was a hunch _ and it did work out an inning
later when Matt Franco delivered a key pinch-hit single in what
would have been Piazza's spot in the order as the Mets rallied for
a 9-8 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said Friday he had made the move with the bottom of
the eighth in mind, reasoning that with a hitter in the pitcher's
spot, the Mets would have a better chance to pad their lead in that
inning before San Francisco's outstanding closer, Robb Nen, got a
chance to enter the game.
</P>
<P>
   What Valentine had not planned on, he said, was McMichael
blowing the Mets' lead and Nen going into the game in the eighth
inning to protect a Giants' lead.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, the move required Piazza, an All-Star catcher, to
leave the field during an inning and be replaced by Todd Pratt,
just up from the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   As he took a seat on the Mets bench, Piazza did not look
particularly happy. But as one member of the Mets organization said
Friday, echoing the observations of others, Piazza always seems
upset of late.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the booing at Shea has been bothering Piazza, even
though it has subsided. Or maybe recent suggestions in the news
media that he will not be with the Mets next season have also had
an effect. Much has been made of Piazza's unproductive batting
average with runners in scoring position: entering Friday night's
game, he was hitting only .224 with two home runs and 15 runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza also was batting .326 before Friday night in the 62
games since the Mets acquired him from Florida on May 22. And no
one is harder on Piazza than Piazza himself. Publicly, he will not
criticize the fans for booing. Privately, teammates are beginning
to wonder why a player making $8 million in the final year of a
two-year, $15 million deal should be so unhappy at the park.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Todd Hundley. For someone struggling as much as
Hundley was at the plate before he went 3-for-3 on Thursday, it
would have been easy to understand why if his head were hanging in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley's response has been exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to sound like an announcer, but Todd's attitude
has been so fabulous,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said Friday. ``When
you're hitting .300, it's very easy. But when you're hitting .150,
it is harder to have a very positive outlook. But Todd's presence
has been wonderful. We're starting to see him produce. And it is
starting to be recognized in the box score as well as in the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not getting down on himself. It was a tough situation
that he was thrown into. And he's had a positive attitude through
it all. For a baseball player, a missed fly ball or a strikeout is
a personal thing. He's been through a lot really. And he's held up
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The three hits against the Giants could not have come at a
better time for Hundley, who lifted his batting average to .200 in
the 25 games since returning from elbow surgery. Hundley made some
adjustments to his approach at the plate after reviewing videotapes
of his swing into the wee hours of Thursday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
