<HEADLINE>
FASSEL, LESS TENSE, BEGINS THE SEASON NO LESS INTENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, New York Giants Coach Jim Fassel said he faced his
team's first preseason game with this thought: ``Boy, I'd like to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel was then a rookie head coach. And he knew what that
meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just know people are wondering if you can coach at all,''
Fassel said this week, recalling the mix of nervousness and
anticipation that gripped him on the eve of that first game a year
ago. ``So you feel like you have something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, asked what he wished for as his Giants prepared for
their first preseason game Saturday night against the Cincinnati
Bengals, Fassel didn't hesitate with his answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No injuries,'' the coach said. ``That's it, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, as the coach of the defending division champion,
as the National Football League's 1997 coach of the year, and as
the coach of a team that doesn't have a single starting job up for
grabs, Fassel is more relaxed in his role.
</P>
<P>
   He is no less the taskmaster _ he has been just as vocal
scolding his players in training camp as he was last summer _ it's
just that Fassel is more confident approaching what is still the
formative part of the pro football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told the team that every time we put on that uniform, I
want them to play hard and play smart,'' Fassel said. ``But yes, we
can see the bigger picture now. Other priorities creep in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel won that first preseason game in 1997. Then he lost the
next three, and three of the next four games in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be 1-3 again in the preseason, and it wouldn't worry
me too much,'' Fassel said. ``So long as we were playing hard. I
truly believe that we're a much better team now than we were a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, I want to win. But I've got a lot of guys
from the second and third teams that I have to see and evaluate.
You can't lose sight of the overall goal.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Fassel plans to play his reserves for about
three-quarters of Saturday's game. And while the Giants,
technically, have no starting roles unsettled, there will be a few
players auditioning for expanded roles.
</P>
<P>
   At running back, for example, expect Tyrone Wheatley to get the
bulk of the carries. Wheatley, with a strong preseason, could still
run his way right into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel won't want to expose Tiki Barber, who is his current
starter, for too long in the exhibition season. Barber, who had a
series of injuries last season, will be protected _ although he is
going to see considerable time as the team's new featured punt
returner.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Brown, the other candidate for the starting job at running
back, has displayed the power-running, between-the-tackles style
the Giants expected of him. The Giants know what Brown can do for
them.
</P>
<P>
   It is Wheatley, as always, about whom the team remains
uncertain. When healthy in training camp, Wheatley has looked in
better shape and more energetic. Fassel and offensive coordinator
Jim Skipper would like nothing better than to see Wheatley have a
strong, consistently productive preseason.
</P>
<P>
   This would allow them to rotate Wheatley, Brown and fullback
Charles Way _ who they would like to use more often as a halfback
this year _ on the early downs in a series and feature Barber in
the third-down packages.
</P>
<P>
   This is Wheatley's best chance to prove his worth yet. And he
seems eager to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the field, wide receiver Ike Hilliard could receive
that first jarring hit since his neck surgery last September. How
Hilliard will react to a testing collision _ there hasn't been one
in training camp _ has been a continuing topic of conversation at
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to see me take the lick, get up and run back
to the huddle with a smile on my face,'' Hilliard said. ``I want to
get it over with, too.''
</P>
<P>
   With starting strong safety Sam Garnes out with a sore shoulder,
Giants fans will also get their first look at this year's
first-round draft pick, Shaun Williams. Veteran Rodney Young will
start the game in Garnes' place, but Williams, who has been
impressive at times in camp, will probably play most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Sehorn, who has been practicing with the first-string
kickoff return unit, won't return any kickoffs Saturday night.
Sehorn will get a few kickoff-return attempts before the regular
season begins, but Fassel doesn't want to risk Sehorn to injury any
more often than is prudent.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is the battle for the backup fullback
spot. So far, it seems apparent that the coaches believe rookie
Greg Comella of Stanford is winning that competition with Eric
Lane, the second-year player who was Way's backup last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
