<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-FOUNTAIN-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK'S FOUNTAIN OF WHIMSY FLOWS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cherry Hill in Central Park was conceived in the
1860s as a scenic concourse where people on horseback and in
carriages could stop, admire the view of the shimmering lake and
tangled Ramble, and then perhaps take a short walk amid chirping
crickets to nearby Bethesda Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   At Cherry Hill's center was a considerably smaller fountain,
intended as a watering place for horses. When horses faded from the
scene, the area became a parking lot for cars. The fountain has not
been operating for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, after a painstaking restoration, the fountain was
turned on again, much to the delight of regular park goers. ``I
stopped each day, and they told me today would be the day,'' said
Tim Carroll, a police officer on a motorcycle whose beat is the
park.
</P>
<P>
   The fountain is a piece of Victorian whimsy. At the top of the
intricate 14-foot-high tower, water flows out of eight little
flowers, falling into goblet-shaped bowls. Each bowl spills water
onto a granite dome and the water sheets down, ultimately dripping
like light rain into the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised at how delicate it was, how gentle a fountain
it was,'' said Peter Champe, director of conservation and sculpture
for the Central Park Conservancy, which earlier this year took over
management of the park from the city.
</P>
<P>
   To turn on the fountain, Champe descended into the steaming-hot
underground pumphouse, which has been outfitted with brand-new
electrical and plumbing gear.
</P>
<P>
   He turned on a big valve. He then had to adjust eight small
valves, as a colleague outside told him one or another of the eight
goblets needed water or was getting too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little more on No. 8, a little less on No. 3,'' the
conversation went. Ever so slowly, at a rate one-hundredth that of
Bethesda Fountain, water trickled forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now has life again,'' said Vallessa Monk, a monuments
restoration technician.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the fountain is a strange, almost surreal
object, located as it is in the middle of a traffic circle with no
traffic, just north of the 72nd Street drive through the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ever a design were ornamental, this is it,'' said Karen
Putnam, president of the Conservancy. ``It is testimony to a
different kind of taste in a different era.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Champe sees the fountain's initial creation in the 1800s
as something of a lark. He imagines the architect Calvert Vaux, one
of the designers of Central Park, going to his associate Jacob Wrey
Mould and saying: ``Jacob, why don't you go out and design a horse
trough. Make it look nice.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, the effort fell short. Bob Garber, a retired architect
who jogs by the fountain daily, said it is out of scale with its
surroundings. Pointing to the granite base, he said: ``It could be
bigger. This base requires a larger statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Putnam says people can like it or not, but all should
understand that it represents an exact reproduction of the High
Victorian aesthetic that prevailed in early years of the park. She
called the fountain ``a decorative arts destination,'' one of the
park's most dramatic. She said it is important to restore such
small, sometimes quirky artistic touches, even as the park's huge
landscape improvements occupy center stage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The restoration of Cherry Hill fountain cost $20,000, which came
from a gift from Elizabeth and Clement Moore through the Indian
Point Foundation. Since 1980, the Conservancy has spent $170
million on restorations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the gilding, so to speak,'' Champe said, ``restoring
the smaller, less noticed corners of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors seemed to love the new fountain. ``I could jump
in,'' said John Pierce, a Manhattan recording engineer. Jeanne
Mutti, a tourist from Switzerland, said, ``It's like an oasis
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gruber, a retired retailer wearing just shorts and
sandals, said he walks by Cherry Hill every day and is pleased the
fountain is finally back. Pointing to the view of the glimmering
lake and the verdant Ramble, he said: ``You dwell on life here.
Look at that picture postcard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clip-clopping around the fountain throughout the brilliantly
sunny day were horse-drawn carriages. Some hansom cab drivers said
Cherry Hill is a popular spot for couples to get engaged. The
leisurely equestrian parade scene suggested, just maybe, that not
much has changed since those long-ago days when New York City's
great park opened.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, though, has changed: Horses are no longer permitted
to drink from what was once their own fountain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
