<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CORMORANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., CANADA)  
 EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE DEAD CORMORANTS OF LITTLE GALLOO ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been trying for several days now to imagine the person or
persons who pulled ashore last week at Little Galloo Island in
eastern Lake Ontario and began firing at the double-crested
cormorants that nest there, killing nearly 900 of them. It isn't
the heat of the act that interests me but its coldness, the fact
that it was an economic crime, in all likelihood, rather than an
act of murderous insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Cormorants feed mainly on non-game fish, yet many anglers
believe, falsely, that the cormorants in the Great Lakes have
sharply reduced the numbers of game fish, like trout and bass.
Someone apparently believed it strongly enough to act upon it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a fisherman, and I've often heard other fishermen cursing
cormorants or pelicans or herons, though never with much passion.
What those anglers were glibly cursing, I think, was their own
inadequacy, their inability to be as stealthy and patient as a
great blue heron. Things would be different if a sport-fisherman's
life depended on stealth and patience, as a heron's does. Imagine
two predators of different species competing for the same prey. If
it's only a game to one of them _ i.e., not a matter of survival _
then the Darwinian rules are suspended. Or so it would seem.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter last week occurred because both sides were playing
in earnest. By 1973, cormorants in the Great Lakes had declined to
only 125 nesting pairs, largely the result of hunting and DDT. But
when the shooting began last week, there were some 8,400 active
nests on Little Galloo Island alone. The birds there fed in the
same waters where local charter-boat captains and fishing guides
take their clients.
</P>
<P>
   If we liked, humans could fish Lake Ontario with devastating
efficiency, the way we do the world's oceans _ so efficiently, in
fact, that it would doom cormorants and all other fish-feeding
birds almost as an afterthought. But sport fishing is intentionally
inefficient. That's one of the things that makes it a sport, one
sharing the same ethic, I believe, with naturalists and
bird-watchers who welcome the return of double-crested cormorants
from near-extirpation in the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   But a game fish becomes an economic force in its own right, its
value inflated by the money anglers spend on travel, gear and
guides just to catch it. And it is the high indirect-dollar value
of game fish that appears to bring cormorants and the sport-fishing
industry into competition, even though the competition is illusory.
Scientific evidence suggests that cormorants take only a tiny
fraction of the fish that game fish themselves, being cannibals,
take when they prey on their own kind. Still, birds make good
scapegoats when the fishing is bad.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this slaughter notable isn't just its savagery or its
magnitude. It's the fact that it reveals in sharp relief the
results of direct human competition with other species, something
we like to pretend no longer exists now that so few of us live in
nature. In fact, the consequences of our competition are merely
forgotten in the past or hidden at the far end of a long chain of
events for which we like to pretend we can disclaim responsibility.
When humans compete with other species, other species always lose.
It's one of the tragic, cardinal facts of our history, which is
filled with scenes like the one on Little Galloo Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980807.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4212 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-LADN     08-07 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYNE'S WORTH LINGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wherever he is in the middle of his summer vacation, Wayne
Gretzky undoubtedly will pause for a moment Sunday to mark an
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at the federal prison in Lompoc, where Bruce McNall is
serving a 70-month sentence for committing $236 million in bank
fraud, the former Kings owner will pause, too, and ponder the
difference a decade makes.
</P>
<P>
   And avid hockey fans with a keen sense of history should take
the time this weekend to consider that 10 years ago Sunday, the
sport they love was irrevocably altered for better and worse by the
news that a frail, pale demigod on skates was changing his address.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, 1998, the sports world was stunned to learn that
Gretzky, hockey's greatest scorer, then 27 years old and at the
height of his powers, had been traded to the Kings by the Edmonton
Oilers in a multi-player deal that also sent a $15-million direct
deposit north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, McNall's blockbuster put hockey on the front
page in mid-summer, remarkable given that the sport traditionally
had struggled to gain attention in Southern California even during
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, and especially in Edmonton, the swap was met with
outrage, and then-Oilers owner Peter Pocklington gained instant
leper status. Today, Pocklington refers to the deal as ``strictly a
business decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But 10 years ago, a Canadian politician said, ``Wayne Gretzky is
a national symbol like the beaver. ... The Edmonton Oilers without
Wayne Gretzky is like apple pie without ice cream, like winter
without snow, like the ``Wheel of Fortune' without Vanna White.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, Canada and Edmonton survived, though hardly a
year has passed since the deal without a rumor that the Oilers are
about to pick up and move to a sunny home in the southern United
States. Quebec and Winnipeg already have lost their NHL of the six
remaining Canadian teams in the league periodically are reported to
be in peril, in no small part a backhanded tribute to the big-money
era spawned by the Gretzky trade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it hasn't all been bleak in Edmonton. The Oilers managed
to win a fifth Stanley Cup after Gretzky left, and Gretzky has not
won a Cup since two months before the trade, when Edmonton captured
its fourth championship in five years.
</P>
<P>
   How to assess the impact of this deal, given a decade's
hindsight?
</P>
<P>
   It has been good. And it has been bad. But it has not been
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, other factors have had significant roles in hockey's
evolution over the past decade. In analyzing hockey's altered
landscape, one cannot ignore the ever-escalating power of
television in sports and the increased militancy of the National
Hockey League Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   But would any of the changes have occurred or been so dramatic
had hockey's finest ambassador not been wrested from a mid-sized
Western Canadian city and dropped smack in the middle of the United
States' second-largest media market?
</P>
<P>
   As mentioned earlier, it's been good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the NHL's only Sun Belt team was the Kings.
Today, there are nine. Ten years ago, there was no U.S.
minor-league team west of Salt Lake City. Today, there are 11,
including the Ice Dogs in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But for those wishing to attend an NHL game in person, proximity
does not necessarily equal accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   The year before Gretzky came to the Kings, the average paid
ticket for a Kings game at the Forum cost $11.50. In Gretzky's
first year as a King, that figure rose to $16.50. By last season,
it had skyrocketed to $40.34. And for the coming season, Kings fans
have been treated to an 11-percent hike in ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring ticket costs in Los Angeles and around the NHL have
gone hand-in-hand with the rise in player salaries, another
development that can be linked closely to the Gretzky deal.
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky joined the Kings, he was coming off a season in
which he'd earned $1.1 million Canadian about $700,000 in U.S.
currency. With McNall freely spending money it would turn out he
should not have been spending, Gretzky's income rapidly increased.
This season, Gretzky will be paid $6 million by the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's fellow players should kiss the ice he skates on.
Salaries only began to rise so rapidly because there was someone of
Gretzky's mass appeal to set new standards. Since the NHLPA started
tracking such figures, the average NHL player's salary has jumped
from $271,000 in 1990-91 to $1.167 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone believe any of this would have happened so quickly
if Gretzky had not hit the Los Angeles scene and opened the NHL's
doors to puck-ignorant places such as Anaheim, San Jose, Miami,
Tampa and Nashville, to name a few?
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone believe sales of NHL licensed merchandise, as
reported by the league, would have increased 10-fold over the past
decade, to $1.2 billion in 1997-98, if Gretzky had not pulled that
silver and black Kings jersey over his head in 1988 while standing
on a stage in the packed ballroom of a hotel situated a few breaths
of carbon monoxide from Los Angeles International Airport?
</P>
<P>
   But there was only so much Gretzky could do.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he could not win a Stanley Cup in Los Angeles,
though he probably came within a Marty McSorley curved stick of
doing so in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And Gretzky did not transform Los Angeles forevermore into
anything resembling a hockey town. When the Kings began their
decline on the ice, the big crowds disappeared, even before Gretzky
was traded to St. Louis in 1996. Average attendance last season
(13,019) was closer to that of the Kings' final pre-Gretzky year
(11,667) than it was to the first season with Gretzky (14,875) or
the sold-out season of 1991-92, when there wasn't an officially
empty seat in the Forum all year.
</P>
<P>
   On a national scale, there is similar and plentiful evidence
that in most places in the United States, a losing NHL team leads
to instant fan indifference. The bright light Gretzky brought with
his move to the U.S. doesn't fill seats in the arenas of most
losers. And it doesn't impel fans to sit in front of their big
screens, either, as evidenced by national television ratings that
were in a free fall last season. Simply put, Gretzky's appeal was
never enough to spare us the glowing puck.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the participant level, hockey never has been more
popular in the U.S. Today, nearly one-half million players are
registered with the sport's umbrella agency, USA Hockey, more than
double the number from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   And of all those kids, how many took their first strides
dreaming of being the next Mario Lemieux, Pavel Bure, Dominik Hasek
or Cammi Granato? Chances are, more of them have dreams of being
No. 99 than all the others combined.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Gretzky's on-ice legacy, awe-inspiring as it is,
almost certainly would have been even greater had he simply stayed
put.
</P>
<P>
   Playing from 1979-88 with an Edmonton lineup dotted with Hall of
Famers, Gretzky produced 2.4 points a game, and his teams were 192
games above .500.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with inconsistently-talented teams ever since, Gretzky
has averaged 1.56 points a game and his teams have been 16 games
below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Age and injuries have played into the decline of Gretzky's
still-impressive post-Edmonton statistics. But how stratospheric
would his numbers have been and how many more Stanley Cups would
the Oilers have won if Gretzky had spent the last 10 years skating
alongside all his old Edmonton buddies, instead of just some of
them?
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know, of course, and the reason we won't is the
trade that happened 10 years ago Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, its impact on hockey has been greater than
anyone could have predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
