<SLUG> BC-CT-COMPTROLLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS AGAIN SEEK CANDIDATE FOR COMPTROLLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ A day after Ramon Antonio Serbia withdrew from
the state comptroller's race, in part because of his involvement in
a bank fraud case in Puerto Rico, Republican leaders began talking
Friday about how to best round out their ticket with a new
candidate for comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. John Rowland's Democratic challenger, U.S. Rep.
Barbara Kennelly, criticized the governor for a ``cavalier
attitude'' in choosing a statewide candidate without a more
extensive background check.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders said they did not know that Serbia was acquitted
of bank fraud charges in 1986 in Puerto Rico, and saw no need for
an extensive background check because they knew him personally and
he had been a state employee and a party worker.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia had also claimed on his campaign biography that he held
two academic degrees, which was not true. At one point on Thursday,
the Republican Party chairman, Chris DePino, said they did not
check Serbia's educational background in part because he was 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``For heaven's sake,'' Mrs. Kennelly said at a news conference
Friday in Wethersfield. ``Fifty-eight? What, is there a statute of
limitations? That is what we're talking about. A very cavalier
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they did know that Serbia had filed his federal
income tax late, but did not think that was a problem, because he
was paying the taxes he owed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Mrs. Kennelly admitted Friday that she did not expect
the case to become a major issue, and Republican leaders began
mentioning names of possible replacements for Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Facing criticism by Democrats that the controversy over Serbia
resulted from Rowland's being too eager to put another minority
candidate on the ticket, Republicans on Friday stressed they would
choose the best candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   But DePino said that if candidates were equally qualified, he
would like to see someone from Fairfield County or New London
County, and two names were mentioned on Friday: state Rep. Marilyn
Hess of Greenwich and Andrew Norton, a former state representative
from Colchester who ran for the Republican nomination for Congress
in the 2nd District and who recently said publicly that he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   DePino said other people being considered included state Rep.
Christopher Scalzo of Ridgefield, and Susan Townsley, first
selectwoman of Old Saybrook.
</P>
<P>
   DePino said that he would discuss candidates with Rowland and
other party leaders early next week, and expected to name a
replacement by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Fergus Cullen, Rowland's deputy campaign manager, said that
while there were several candidates to choose from, it was still
too early to decide who would fill the slot. ``It's not as though
we had a bullpen of backup catchers here in case someone was
injured,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
