<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLD HANDS AND THE NEW SHARE A FEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some of the Yankees showed up early enough Friday to
make sure the long day of baseball in the Bronx would stretch even
longer. That's what happens when players on the finest club in the
major leagues are trying to be remembered as one of the best teams
ever. That is why it made sense for the players, destined to spend
at least 13 hours at Yankee Stadium, to gulp that first cup of
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees and Royals playing games at 1:05 p.m. and at
7:35 p.m., with a separate admission for each one, the whole scene
was similar to an American Legion tournament rather than an
American League doubleheader _ play a game, devour a meal, wait a
few hours and play another game.
</P>
<P>
   This wrinkle in the schedule, caused by a rainout in May, did
not affect the Yankees, who pummeled the Royals, 8-2 and 14-2. They
did so in the first game behind the pitching of David Cone, the
offense of Darryl Strawberry, Tino Martinez and Bernie Williams,
and Pat Rapp's shabby imitation of a pitcher _ all before a crowd
of 14,425, the team's lowest attendance figure of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance swelled to 37,988 in the second game and the
Yankees' record swelled to 82-29 as David Wells outdid Cone with
his fourth complete game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer outdid everyone in going 5-for-5 and powering the
Yankees to the victory. The rookie, filling in for Paul O'Neill in
right field, slugged the first two home runs of his career, and hit
two doubles and a single while scoring four runs and driving in
three.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch lined his ninth homer since the All-Star Game
break and Williams had a two-run shot that traveled 416 feet. Luis
Sojo had three hits and three RBIs as New York moved 53 games over
.500, a season high, and ensured a winning record for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' pitching was as impressive as the offense. Jermaine
Allensworth's run-scoring double in the third ended Wells' streak
of 25 straight at-bats without allowing a hit with runners in
scoring position, but that was the only serious dent the Royals
made.
</P>
<P>
   Neatly spotting his fastball, slider and changeup, Wells (14-3)
walked none, struck out four and allowed only six hits in winning
his sixth straight decision to creep closer to winning 20 for the
first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ready to play,'' Manager Joe Torre said. ``That
becomes a habit after a while. Now we're into August and we're used
to doing it all year.''
</P>
<P>
   With each day the Yankees pull on the pinstripes, they overwhelm
inferior teams such as the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (16-4) became the first 16-game winner in the majors and
strengthened his candidacy for the Cy Young Award by halting the
Royals on two runs and six hits in the opener, striking out five
and walking none in six and two-thirds innings. Martinez drove in
three runs, Williams knocked in two, and Strawberry had another
mammoth homer.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's last six hits have been home runs, giving him 21,
and he has nine homers in his last 29 at-bats. Arthritic knee and
all, Strawberry was intentionally walked in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such an imposing figure,'' Torre said. ``Every time he
swings the bat, it's a home run. At least it's been that way the
last few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry simply said, ``I feel a great confidence when I come
to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like Cone on the mound. After permitting a run in the
first on a double by Johnny Damon and a single by Jose Offerman,
Cone watched the Yankees score four runs off Rapp and then helped
his team run away. He retired 15 of 17 batters through six innings
as the Yankees pushed the lead to 6-2 and then 8-2. Cone's control
was precise and stingy with men on base as the Royals went 1 for 9.
Once again, Cone won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixteen wins is amazing to me,'' said Cone, who might
challenge the 20-3 record he had with the Mets in 1988. ``Again,
it's a byproduct of a great record. I've had great run support.''
</P>
<P>
   That started early as the Yankees scored four runs during a
first inning walkathon in which Rapp made 38 pitches. Williams
singled in the first run, and Martinez doubled in the second,
putting Yankees on second and third with one out. After Rapp fell
behind Strawberry, 2-0, the Yankee was walked intentionally.
``That's respect,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said, ``I was thinking, well, maybe they want to get
a double play.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget that. Rapp inexplicably walked Tim Raines on five pitches
to force in the third run, and Martinez slid over the plate and
then reached back to touch it before Mike Sweeney tagged him while
scoring the fourth run on Scott Brosius' sacrifice fly. Williams
singled in another in the second to make the score 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry gave them a splashy show in the third by
rocketing Rapp's high 1-2 fastball into the fourth row of the
right-field upper deck. He jogged stiff-legged around the bases, a
sight that has become more familiar lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the game begins, I'm thinking about hitting, not about
hitting homers,'' Strawberry said. ``The homers are just coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as quickly as victories.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Because David Cone has now pitched 149 innings and is scheduled
to make 10 more starts, he is almost guaranteed to eclipse 200
innings and trigger a $5.5 million option for 1999. While the
Yankees must offer the option if he hits 200, Cone can accept it or
become a free agent. Cone has reiterated that he wants to remain
with the Yankees. ``If I pitch the way I can, everything will work
itself out,'' said Cone, who is 10-0 at Yankee Stadium this season
and 25-3 as a Yankee in the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
